 SENATE OKS RATE CUT FOR SAN DIEGO  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state Senate approved a plan Thursday to roll back San Diego
power rates to pre-deregulation levels as legislators held their
first hearings on California's soaring electricity bills.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dede Alpert, D-Coronado (San Diego County), introduced
legislation to return San Diego's utility rates to July 1999 levels
until lawmakers can decide whether to repeal or revise the state's
deregulation blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Average power bills in the Southern California city _ the first
to feel the full effects of deregulation _ have more than doubled
over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted 28 to 0 to send the bill to the Assembly next
week. If it passes there, it would then go to Gov. Gray Davis for
his signature before being enacted as law.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let San Diegans suffer while we sort this whole
thing out,'' Alpert said.
</P>
<P>
   Her bill would be retroactive to June, when San Diego ratepayers
first saw their electricity bills jump as San Diego Gas and
Electric passed along surging wholesale power prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation is vague about how San Diego Gas and
Electric would recoup its costs if a rate limit is reimposed.
Alpert said this is a matter that would be taken up down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably this isn't the utility's favorite bill of the
year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her bill also would require the California Public Utilities
Commission to investigate why electricity prices are going through
the roof and present its findings to federal regulators as part of
a petition to officially determine that the state lacks a
competitive energy market.
</P>
<P>
   The governor already has called on the PUC to make such a
request to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which can
mandate ``just and reasonable'' rates when a market is deemed
uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Davis asked the PUC to require so-called level
pricing for San Diego Gas and Electric customers, which would
stabilize electricity bills by spreading wholesale costs over
longer periods.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, this would reduce bills during the summer but raise
them at other times of the year when usage is comparatively low.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC is scheduled to act on the proposal at a special meeting
August 21.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's legislative hearing, more than a dozen energy
industry insiders, experts and concerned citizens appeared before a
joint meeting of the Senate and Assembly utilities committees to
discuss how deregulation had taken a wrong turn.
</P>
<P>
   Most matters discussed were technical in nature and offered no
clues as to what, if anything, the Legislature may do to effect a
long-term remedy for the state's electricity woes.
</P>
<P>
   Nettie Hoge, executive director of the Utility Reform Network, a
San Francisco consumer group, offered a mixed review of the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, she said, legislators appeared to be
showboating to convey to constituents that they take deregulation
seriously. On the other, Hoge said, a number of legislators seem to
genuinely comprehend the complex issues involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very acute understanding that deregulation is not
working,'' she said. ``But there's a great deal of confusion about
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous questions centered on how California got into this mess
and why San Diego ratepayers have been socked so badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an experiment, and San Diegans were the guinea
pigs,'' PUC President Loretta Lynch told the legislators.
</P>
<P>
   A number of questions focused on whether those in the business
of generating power have been manipulating prices on the state's
wholesale electricity market. Although there is widespread belief
that this is indeed the case, it remained unclear whether such
actions are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the tone of the hearings was subdued and generally
monotonous. An unexpected highlight came when legislators paused
midway through their discussion of electricity for a warning that
their microphones might not be operating properly.
</P>
<P>
   There was a short in the system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
