 NORTHERN CALIFORNIA RACE KEY TO HOUSE CONTROL  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ Underscoring the national significance of the
campaign to replace Republican Tom Campbell, R-Calif., Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt and two dozen House members rallied for fellow
Democrat Mike Honda Thursday in downtown San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give us Mike Honda, you give us a majority _ and we will
change this country,'' said Gephardt, the Missouri Democrat who is
expected to become House Speaker if Democrats pick up the seven
seats they need to win a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The South Bay district, which stretches from Great America's
roller coasters to Santa Cruz's wooded mountains, has become ground
zero in each party's efforts to win control of the House. Evenly
split between Democratic and Republican voters, it is currently
represented by Campbell who is leaving the House in an effort to
unseat Sen. Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very tough race'' said Commerce Secretary Norm
Mineta, who represented the district for 20 years and joined
Democrats Thursday for a lunch with technology leaders sponsored by
Visa. The lunch and rally were held in the congressional district
represented by Rep. Zoe Lofgren, a couple of miles from the 15th
Congressional District that Honda is seeking to represent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 435 House seats subject to election this November, only
several dozen are considered up for grabs, including half a dozen
in California. The huge stakes and the GOP's narrow House majority
has prompted party leaders to spend considerable time in the state
in districts where the outcome is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert was in the South Bay on Wednesday
on behalf of Assemblyman Jim Cunneen, the GOP's candidate. Arizona
Sen. John McCain has made appearances for Cunneen, and is expected
to return in the fall. Virginia Rep. Jim Davis, the head of the
Republican's House Campaign Committee has already made three
visits.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gephardt has made the trip to the
district three times, noting Thursday the potential for Democrats
to have a monopoly on the three Silicon Valley seats (Lofgren and
Rep. Anna Eshoo, both Democrats, represent other portions of the
region.)
</P>
<P>
   ``These are historic choices,'' Gephardt said. ``What we try to
get the voters to understand is the national consequences'' of
their vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both Honda and Cunneen serve in the state Assembly. Both &LR;   &LR; They
are regarded as likable moderates, with similar records on issues
such as abortion, guns and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue that regardless of Cunneen's moderate record, it
is critical to elect a Democrat to break up the GOP majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no moderate Republican,'' insisted Rep. Patrick
Kennedy, D-R.I., who is the head of Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee. ``The majority controls the agenda. From day
one (Cunneen) signs his soul away with the Republican right wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunneen, in a phone interview on his way back from Sacramento,
called Kennedy's position ``naive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, people are going to vote on who is
going to best represent Silicon Valley,'' Cunneen said.
</P>
<P>
   The throng of Democrats were in the Bay Area at the invitation
of Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-San Francisco, who arranged a three-day
tour of the area's hottest high-tech sights. The gathering was part
educational, part fund-raising, and part a rally for Pelosi's quest
to become the Majority Whip if Democrats win control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the tour has been a fantastic learning experience
for members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day (technology) changes. That's why I wanted people
here. It doesn't matter what anyone knew yesterday, it's about what
you know for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats figure there are five California seats now held by
Republicans which could easily go their way in November _ providing
them most of what they need to win back the House. Republicans
concede they will be lucky to hold their ground in California, but
are hopeful they can contain their losses to just a seat or two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
