 HEAD AND SHOULDERS ABOVE THE REST  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No suspense at the Democratic Convention?
</P>
<P>
   How about this: Who dyes?
</P>
<P>
   With all the hard-hitting journalists swarming Los Angeles,
someone is sure to blow the lid off the coverup coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore dyes his hair, it would appear, but how, who and why? We
want details. And one reader swears that Joe Lieberman dyes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Are we ready for a Democratic ticket that isn't comfortable with
its collective natural hair color?
</P>
<P>
   Gore reportedly tries to keep his bald spot out of view as much
as possible. One rumor is that he tabbed Lieberman as VP so he
(Gore) could have an excuse to wear a yarmulke.
</P>
<P>
   Don't smirk, GOPs. Remember President Reagan, whose hair was
once described as ``prematurely orange?''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, by the way: Natural hair, but he colors his
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   CHUMP CHANGE: Zia Kahn sends an ad that appeared in The
Chronicle's New Homes section.
</P>
<P>
   The ad is for Bridle Creek in Pleasanton, which boasts of homes
``From the low $1,000,000s.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, that would have been an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   PANSY POACHERS and assorted flower filchers, beware:
</P>
<P>
   Flower theft is epidemic. The thieves rob parks and yards and
gardens and sell for big bucks at the Flower Market.
</P>
<P>
   The news is that the cops have come up with a plan that should
result in arrests.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, eventually this will make an exciting episode
of ``Nash Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   PARKERS WALK: At the Pan Pacific Hotel near Union Square, the
``Motor Court'' crew of about 28 _ valet parkers, bellmen,
chauffeurs _ has been on strike for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Many gripes. The strikers claim the Pan charges an arm and a leg
to park your car, but gives the guys who park it the finger.
</P>
<P>
   RE: REDUNDANCIES returning redux:
</P>
<P>
   Don Fogg writes, ``Redundancies are a very American literary
form,'' and cites: ``(I)n order to form a more perfect union ...''
</P>
<P>
   And: Old adage (Ken Lesher) ... Reflecting back, consensus of
opinion (Sarah Morse) ... Very unique (Tracy Bates) ... ``Have you
risen up or entered into anything lately?'' (Matthew Downing) ...
Traffic jam (Q) ... Future prospects, old traditions (Marvin
Chandler).
</P>
<P>
   And today's educational corner: Do you know what a pleonasm is?
Scott Summerville does. It's ``the use of more words than are
necessary to express an idea.'' Like free gift or fully nude.
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. also notes that near Phoenix there is a flat-topped
mountain (the bottom is probably flat, too) named Table Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't ask what is the diff between a pleonasm and a
redundancy.
</P>
<P>
   NEW SCAM? Customer sits down, but there's food on the seat and
he stains his nice pants. He writes a letter to the restaurant's
management, complimenting the place but asking that they pay his
cleaning bill of $13.85.
</P>
<P>
   Most restaurants would shrug and send a check.
</P>
<P>
   Only trouble is, this ``accident'' took place in mid-July at the
Gramercy Grill, which has been closed down all year for remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wren, provider of this item, suggests that if the
stained-pants man was unlucky enough to have 1,000 similar
accidents, he could rake in $13,850.
</P>
<P>
   The receipt submitted with the man's letter is from Privilege
Cleaners in Beverly Hills _ such an exclusive establishment that it
has no phone listing.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, at least Pants Man isn't out stealing flowers.
</P>
<P>
   DANCERS GET BOOT: What's happening in the Mission is being
called a cultural clear-cutting. Everything old and artsy must go.
The latest casualties: Two long-time dance studios.
</P>
<P>
   Dance Mission had its rent jacked up from $5,500 a month to
$20,000. Dancers' Group Footwork, same deal, from $3,000 per to
$15,500. Both are likely to fade away after decades of dance.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, city of homeless hoofers.
</P>
<P>
   To see what you'll sooner or later be missing, take a guided
hike Saturday (11 a.m., corner Mission and 24th), through the 'hood
of endangered species _ artists, small businesses, nonprofs.
</P>
<P>
   FROM THE Carmel Pine Cone's ``Police and Sheriff's Log'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Woman reported someone yelled obscenities at her when she
failed to allow a squirrel to cross the street in front of her.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is: In Carmel, which of those two crimes is the
more dastardly?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
