<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CLINTON-REFLECTIONS-1     08-11 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REFLECTIONS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPENTANT CLINTON REVIEWS HIS PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new 6th and 7th grafs; subs 12th graf starting Aides to
Gore, etc., for rewriting)   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BARRINGTON, Ill. _ Four thousand church members bowed
their heads Thursday and prayed for a sinner in their midst _ a man
who, like them, was struggling in his life with right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guide his path,'' intoned Bill Hybels, senior pastor at the
Willow Creek Community Church. ``Fill him with your wisdom and
cause him to keep growing personally and maturing.''
</P>
<P>
   The man before them was President Clinton, and he had just
described how his life had spun out of control after an adulterous
affair, how his job sometimes overwhelmed him, how the past seven
and a half years had had low moments and wonderful ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not careful when you have this kind of job, it can
overtake you,'' the president said wistfully, sitting on a swivel
chair on a stage in an enormous church. ``You can believe it's even
more important than it is. You can let it take up even more time
than it should. It can crowd out all that other stuff that keeps
you centered and growing and whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has reflected on impeachment before, and he has
discussed his religious beliefs throughout his presidency. But his
reflections Thursday amounted to a live public interview on the
personal travails of his presidency, conducted by a pastor who has
counseled him regularly since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   And he went out of his way to give credit to Vice President Al
Gore for the administration's successes and to insist that Gore
should not be blamed for Clinton's personal failings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't get enough credit for what we did together that is
good and, surely, no fair-minded person would blame him for any
mistake that I made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now in the second year of a process of trying to totally
rebuild my life from a terrible mistake I made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can say, `Hey, the state of my spiritual
life is great, it's constant and it's never going to change.' I
think I've learned enough now to know that's not true, that it's
always a work in progress and you just hope you're getting better
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not getting better,'' he said, ``chances are you're
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   His appearance at the church came at a delicate time, just days
before the Democrats are to open their political convention in Los
Angeles, and shift the spotlight from Clinton to Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Gore have expressed their annoyance that Clinton and
his wife, Hillary, plan such a high profile role at the convention,
and the president's headline-grabbing remarks here on the eve of
the convention could add to their annoyance, even if they are
grateful to Clinton for his praise on Thursday for the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Gore campaign continued to express frustration over
the repeated dredging up of Clinton's affair _ already back in the
news because Gore's vice presidential pick, Sen. Joseph Lieberman
of Connecticut, had criticized Clinton so openly about it.
</P>
<P>
   One Gore adviser observed drily, ``We're trying to keep the
focus on the future and on the issues that matter to the voters,
and this isn't in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Gore aide said the campaign hoped that the selection of
Lieberman, the first Democratic senator to chastise the president
openly, would underscore that the ticket was separate from the
president and also that the president's comments clearly reflected
that his affair had been his own problem.
</P>
<P>
   But White House aides said there had been no political
calculation in sandwiching the president's confessional between an
educational event in Chicago and an evening in New York City for
Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had promised Hybels _ who described himself as the
president's ``behind the scenes spiritual adviser'' _ that before
he left office he would appear at one of Hybels' leadership
summits, which draw pastors and other church leaders from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at the religious retreat had been
contentious. Some conservative pastors had opposed the visit and
had insisted that Hybels not go easy in his questioning of Clinton
in his missteps. And Hybels, in a sympathetic way, obliged.
</P>
<P>
   He asked about the president's dog, Buddy. He asked about the
issues the president cares most about and how he wants to be
remembered. But he asked as well about Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's face appeared on two large screens in the church
auditorium, the kind of close up that the television networks use
to show the awkward, perspiration-inducing moments of an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have given evidence that I need to be in church,''
Clinton said at one point, referring to the fallout from what he
called ``my personal crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he continues to rebuild his life after his affair
with a White House intern, and he said he continues to grapple with
the state of his character and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he had also found a silver lining in the whole
uncomfortable public airing of his missteps. ``In a funny way, when
you realize there's nothing left to hide, it sort of frees you up
to do what you ought to do anyway,'' the president said of his
ongoing counseling sessions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the embarrassing episode had humbled him, and he
encouraged other politicians to seek spiritual advisers to guide
them throughout the pressures of public office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that even presidents must realize that they were
flawed, both as politicians and policymakers. ``I am quite sure
that some of my positions are wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment episode aside, Clinton said the lowest moment of
his presidency came when he learned that 18 U.S. soldiers had been
killed in a military action he had ordered in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the sickest I have been since I have been here,'' he
said, adding that all military actions were a strain on him. ``You
know the chances are some of them are going to die.'' And even if
U.S. soldiers do not die, they are likely to kill someone else, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton rattled off far more positive recollections from his
presidency _ legislation that had passed, foreign-policy successes,
standing with Nelson Mandela in the prison cell where he had spent
so much of his life. And Clinton said he would miss the ups _ and
even the downs _ of being president.
</P>
<P>
   More than riding on Air Force One or hearing ``Hail to the
Chief'' when he walks into a room, or waking up every morning in
the White House, Clinton said, ``what I will miss more than
anything else is the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
