<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-MARS-NASA-SFCHRON &LR;      08-11 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-NASA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA TO SEND TWIN ROBOTS TO MARS IN '03
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a year after two Mars-bound missions vanished in
space, NASA officials announced they will send two powerful roving
robots to the Red Planet in 2003 to search for evidence of water _
the key ingredient for life.
</P>
<P>
   The twin 300-pound rovers, scheduled to land on Mars within
three weeks of each other in January 2004, will each carry two
cameras, five instruments and a ``abrasion tool'' designed to
scrape away weathered rock surfaces and reveal the chemical
composition of the ancient rocks, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Images transmitted to Earth last June by Mars Global Surveyor,
the orbiting spacecraft, showed the planet to have dramatic
features. According to scientists, they could only have been made
by gullies, channels, trenches and fan-shaped rocky regions where
surging water would have dumped debris the way flashfloods on Earth
fling boulders as big as cars downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Such features were all located in a region near the south pole
of Mars. But the planet and Earth will be in a different alignment
when the twin rovers land, so they will only have access to areas
nearer the Martian equator, Mars Program Manager Firouz Naderi said
Thursday, speaking from NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just think of a human geologist examining rocks on Earth,''
Naderi said, unable to conceal his excitement over the new project:
``Our Martian rovers will each have eyes to seek out promising
rocks from four feet above the ground, a tool to grind the rock
surfaces, a camera just like a hand lens to examine the fine grains
within the rocks, and five instruments to analyze the chemistry of
the rocks and nearby soil in detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of the NASA decision came at a Washington press
conference where Edward Weiler, the agency's chief of space
science, said: ``To have two rovers driving over dramatically
different regions of Mars at the same time, to be able to drive
over and see what's on the other side of the hill _ it's an
incredibly exciting idea.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA's schedule for increasingly sophisticated Mars missions had
called for only one landing on the planet in 2004, but the
two-pronged approach ``adds resiliency and robustness to our
exploration program,'' said Scott Hubbard, Mars program director at
NASA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of both rovers will be to learn about ancient weather
and climate on Mars,'' said Steven Squyres, the Cornell planetary
geologist who is chief scientist for the new rover missions. ``You
can think of each rover as a robotic field geologist, equipped to
reach the geologic record at its landing site and to learn what the
conditions were like back when the rocks and soils were formed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two Mars-bound spacecraft are scheduled to be launched from
Cape Kennedy aboard Delta II rockets in 2003 _ the first on May 22
and the second on June 4. They will follow identical paths through
space and land on Mars 71/2 months later and 18 days apart.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists will not chose specific landing sites for another two
years. First they must do an intensive study of images taken by the
Mars Global Surveyor, which has been orbiting the planet for more
than three years. Additional images are expected to come from a new
orbiting Mars Surveyor craft due to be launched next April.
</P>
<P>
   Both landing sites will lie in an area between five degrees
north of the Martian equator and 15 degrees south, Naderi said, and
both will be within broad regions offering tantalizing glimpses of
what seem to be ancient lakebeds and river channels.
</P>
<P>
   The two rovers will each run on six wheels powered by solar
batteries. Each will be capable of transmitting images and
chemistry findings directly to Earth, where mission controllers can
direct the vehicles toward promising features for direct
examination and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The rovers will be able to travel more than 300 feet in a single
solar day, and will cover at least a half-mile of terrain during
the scheduled 90-day mission, Naderi said. If all goes well and the
rovers are in good shape, the mission could be extended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a disastrous one for NASA's Mars exploration
efforts. In September a $125 million orbiter vanished as it was
nearing the planet, and in December a $165 million lander
disappeared only minutes before it was supposed to reach the
Martian surface. No one yet knows what caused the two failures.
</P>
<P>
   Cost figures have not been firmly set for the two new Mars
landing missions, but according to Hubbard the first rover is
expected to cost between $350 million and $400 million, while its
twin should benefit from economies in testing and development and
cost about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Even at those prices the Mars ventures are relatively cheap
compared to some other missions. The cost of a Galileo mission to
Jupiter or a Cassini to Saturn can run a billion dollars or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a chance to double our science and do it for far less
than twice the cost,'' Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plan, the images the rovers send back to Earth
will be immediately relayed to a new site on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Facts on the new Mars rover mission are on the Web at:
 &UR; www.jpl.nasa.gov/facts/mars03rover.pdf &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
