r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RIO-GRAND     08-11 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RIO-GRANDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIO GRANDE OFFICIALS VISIT, HOPE TO NAB COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Six representatives from a group trying
to lure the Cowboys to the Rio Grande Valley for training camps
paid a visit to the team's Midwestern State University facilities
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a negotiating trip. We're up here strictly to
observe and learn ... to see how it's done,'' said Randy
Whittington, Rio Grande Valley Regional Sports Authority chairman,
adding with a laugh, ``And to see what we've gotten ourselves into,
if it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys break camp one week from today, completing their
third year on a year-to-year lease arrangement with Midwestern
State.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones said he has spent as much as $1 million per
year on training camp, although the cost at Midwestern State has
been estimated at closer to $400,000 _ including food, housing and
security.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio Grande Valley proposal, approved by the McAllen and
Mission city councils last week, would pay Jones $350,000 per year
for three years, and Jones admitted that ``breaking even'' would be
good business. The proposal also includes a promise to have a
state-of-the-art training site in place at Sharyland Plantation's
Pepsi Park by July 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Jones acknowledged yesterday that the Cowboys have hired a
representative to check two California sites, but Jones declined to
identify either site.
</P>
<P>
   It might be moot because Jones has made it known that he is
extremely interested in the Rio Grande Valley effort, which
coincides with his fondness for tapping into Mexico as an NFL
market. The proposed site is 10 miles from Reynosa, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A source in camp close to the situation has said that Jones'
``instincts are that it's going to work out'' for the Cowboys to
relocate to the Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   However, a deal has not been struck and no timetable has been
set for a decision, according to people on all sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been optimistic since the first time I ever talked to
\RJones\S about coming to the Valley,'' Whittington said. ``There's
still a ways to go ... but I'm still optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharyland Plantation is a 6,500-acre combination community
living/business park created by Dallas oilman Ray Hunt of Hunt
Valley Development. Pepsi Park already is being used by amateur
softball and baseball leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of \Rthe developing\S they're doing, they're going to do
anyway, whether the Cowboys come or not,'' said Whittington,
adding, ``They may be laying the sod for the \Rpractice\S fields as
we speak.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, always complimentary toward Midwestern State and Wichita
Falls as a training site, isn't expected to make his decision known
until after camp breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Midwestern State officials were hoping to keep the Cowboys
``three to five years'' when Jones relocated from Austin in 1998,
according to Howard Farrell, the school's vice president of
student/administrative services.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said yesterday that he has not ruled out returning to
Midwestern State. He did say that the ``McAllen people are further
down the road'' than any site in California.
</P>
<P>
   Whittington and his group ate lunch in the Midwestern State
dining hall yesterday and were taken on a tour of the campus
facilities by Cowboys director of sales and marketing John Hickman.
</P>
<P>
   Whittington was joined by Hidalgo County Judge Eloy Pulido,
Steve Ahlenius and Nancy Millar from the McAllen Chamber of
Commerce, Viola Espinosa of the Mission Chamber of Commerce, and
Tony Aguirre, vice chairman of the Rio Grande Valley Regional
Sports Authority.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
