<HEADER>
A8533 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHAVEZ- &LR;      08-11 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS UPSTAGE BUSH WITH CHAVEZ HOLIDAY LEGISLATION
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALINAS, Calif. _ Democratic lawmakers upstaged Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's attempts to woo Central Valley Latino voters
Thursday by voting to make farmworker leader Cesar Chavez's
birthday a state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush chugged by train through the Central Coast saying he
was proud of his family's ``sangre latino'' _ Latino blood _ the
Democratic-majority Legislature fast-tracked a long-dormant bill
declaring Chavez's March 31 birthday a holiday, at least for some
employees.
</P>
<P>
   At a cost of $52.5 million, state workers would get a paid day
off while schools could choose to hold a half-day of instruction,
including an hour about Chavez's life.
</P>
<P>
   Students would be encouraged to spend the rest of the day
performing some community service.
</P>
<P>
   Although backers of the bill say its passage at nearly the same
time Bush whistle-stopped through Salinas was just coincidence, the
vote came at an opportune moment.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it overshadow the Republican nominee's effort to
court Central Valley Latinos, it also underscored the Democrats'
long-standing commitment to farmworkers rights _ on the eve of the
party's national convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say I was that smart,'' said Richie Ross, a
political consultant for the United Farm Workers Union, referring
to the timing of the bill's passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided three or four weeks ago to push the bill out
yesterday to create an opportunity for the governor to sign it
around the convention,'' Ross said. ``Bush was not a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Gov. Gray Davis announced he would ``proudly'' sign
the Chavez holiday bill, but probably not at the Democratic
convention, which is designed to be a showcase for Vice President
Al Gore. Davis' office said he could delay the signing until Gore's
first swing through California after his nomination, then sign it
with the vice president at his side.
</P>
<P>
   On his campaign trip up the central coast of California from
Santa Maria to Salinas _ where Chavez fought for decades to
organize farm laborers in the lettuce fields _ Bush often
encountered the late farm labor leader's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   And he was met by some sharp criticism from UFW President Arturo
S. Rodriguez, Chavez's son-in-law, who charged that Bush's
treatment of laborers in Texas undercuts the GOP candidate's
efforts to attract farmworker votes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to see a Republican candidate for high office reach
out to Latinos and farmworkers and speak to them in Spanish,'' said
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our people are sophisticated enough to look beyond
(Bush's) rhetoric to the policies he has supported as governor of
Texas,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, traveling from Santa Maria to Lodi and Stockton Thursday,
was accompanied by Arizona Sen. John McCain on the second day of
his train trek.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's trip _ his seventh to the state since the March primary _
has been carefully shaped to highlight his outreach to
traditionally independent and Democratic voters, particularly
Latinos, and farmworkers.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's bunting-draped train has provided the campaign
with rich photo opportunities, including stops in small coastal
farm towns, many populated by farmworkers.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Bush addressed thousands in both Spanish and English
at a railway station in Salinas. Asked by reporters his opinion of
Chavez, Bush said the labor leader ``certainly broke new ground
when it came to fighting for individual rights. I have respect for
people standing for what they believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had signed a Texas proclamation honoring Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at the Republican National Convention, Bush's
24-year-old bilingual nephew George P. Bush appeared to compare
Chavez's leadership to that of his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled how, upon the death of Chavez, his Mexican-born
mother urged him to find a leader ``who represents our people, who
represents our culture. That person ... is my uncle.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats vehemently disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Cesar Chavez. I worked with Cesar Chavez. And Gov. Bush
is not, and never will be, Cesar Chavez,'' said Art Torres, who
heads the state's Democratic Party. ``Here's a guy who didn't come
out against Proposition 187, and he comes to Salinas and acts like
he cares about farmworkers,'' Torres said. ``The photo op and the
rhetoric just don't match his deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Grossman, the former spokesman for Chavez and current
spokesman for the UFW, called the comparison of Bush to Chavez
``not credible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice that he's reaching out to Latinos ... but what's
more important are the policies,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, he said, small farmers are exempted from the Fair
Labor Standards Act, with the result that ``the minimum wage for
thousands of farmworkers in Texas is $3.35 an hour _ $2.00 below
the federal minimum wage guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, farmworkers receive the federal $5.75 an hour
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said Bush, contrary to his expressed concern for
Latinos, has never expressed support for a wage increase for such
workers, and their salary hasn't risen in Texas since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in an impromptu press conference aboard his Amtrak
campaign train, argued that the exemption to the federal minimum
wage in Texas applies only to ``a small number of people'' _ those
who work on small farms that don't export products outside the
state.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed that more than 96 percent of all Texas workers are
paid minimum wage, and insisted he was committed to helping them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of people that come to our state and have been
for generations,'' he told reporters. `Our fundamental question is
how to help the next generation.''
</P>
<P>
   And Karen Hughes, Bush's spokeswoman, said it was unfair to
compare the higher salaries of California farm workers to those in
Texas. ``The cost of living is far less in the rural areas where
this mostly applies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Grossman was unimpressed by Bush's defense. ``How can a
civilized society expect any worker to survive on $3.35 an hour?,''
he asked. ``Is that compassionate conservatism?`
</P>
<P>
   Even as Bush faced questions about his comparisons to Chavez and
his outreach to Latinos, Democrats were already preparing to
counter with the governor's signing of the Chavez bill.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Davis had tried to speed passage of the bill
so he could sign it on Chavez's birthday. Lawmakers didn't oblige
him. The bill remained bottled up in the Assembly Appropriations
Committee until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed the Senate unanimously Thursday with two
Republican votes. Other GOP senators were present but did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of the Assembly's 79 members voted against the bill,
including a GOP lawmaker from Fresno who appeared to part ways with
Governor Bush over the memory of Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never has there been a figure in human history who will
receive the attention Cesar Chavez will under this bill,'' said
Assemblyman Mike Briggs, in expressing his opposition. ``This bill
gives state workers a day off, not farmworkers. If you want to
honor the farmworker movement, there has to be a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Abel Maldonado, R-Santa Maria, accompanying Bush
on his tour, defended the Texas Governor even as he touted his own
upbringing as the son of Mexican farmworkers.
</P>
<P>
   Maldonado also defended the comparisons between Bush and Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cesar Chavez was a man who wanted to leave no child behind.
Governor Bush talks about that. Cesar Chavez wanted to help the
voiceless and the vulnerable. So does Governor Bush,'' he said.
`Obviously, he's been getting elected with huge Hispanic votes in
Texas -- 50 percent of that vote...and I think he's done a lot for
Hispanics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
