<HEADER>
A8534 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIM     08-11 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIMMING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRES' SPARKLING RETURN HOPEFULLY IS REAL DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Four years ago, at the doddering age of 29, Dara
Torres was roundly convinced that she had put the notion of
swimming in the Olympics behind her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's how far it was from my mind,'' Torres said last night.
``I went to the '96 Games as a spectator, and I went to all the
other events ``except'' for swimming. I didn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``During those seven years off, no, I never thought about
getting back in the water again.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a confession that echoed of achievement, but likely will
soon ring with accusation. Torres innocently offered the anecdote
as a way of showing how far she has come, from the comfortable
couch of a seven-year retirement to yet-another place on the U.S.
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials here last night, Torres'
battle with Jenny Thompson in the final of the women's 100-meter
butterfly showed itself to be the arresting head-to-head duel that
everyone hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   The two swimmers _ teammates, only in the broadest sense of the
term _ were never more than an arm's length apart. They finished,
as expected, one-two, with Thompson touching the wall first in
57.78 seconds and Torres reaching for the other Olympic spot in
57.86.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made of their rivalry, a cat fight that both
continue to publicly deny, but while still in the water last night
they hugged. They slapped fives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all just one big happy team now _ USA,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   The roomful of interviewers seemed to smirk as one. I don't
think anyone was buying it.
</P>
<P>
   They asked Torres the same thing a few minutes later, and she
shot back, sarcastically, ``No, it was totally fake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, yes, it was real. I was psyched. I was psyched for
myself and for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The race lacked only the regal trimmings of a record, something
Torres had done in Wednesday's first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Both tried to offer explanations, which sounded more like
apologies. Thompson, whose last Olympic Trials in 1996 had been a
personal disaster _ expected to make the team in four individual
events, she made it in none _ said that she became so emotional
last night at the thought of finally winning the trials, she slowed
down over the final 25 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torres: ``We got to the 75-meter mark. I looked to see
where she was, and I started to rush my stroke and tightened up.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Quick, the ex-Texas and now Palo Alto, Calif., coach
whose attention they vie for, called it an important learning
experience for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got caught up in the race with themselves,'' Quick said.
``I think it's worth reminding that Dara swam her best time in the
prelims \Ran American record 57.58\S when she was just swimming
with rhythm, and Jenny did the same in the semis (57.59). Today,
they tried to do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   They share the same coach, but also the same dream. Both have
been to the Olympics and won gold medals, but only in relays, not
in the individual events. Both were also expected to be long since
retired by now.
</P>
<P>
   In Thompson's case, however, the pedigree was there. She went
into the previous Olympic Trials ranked as a legitimate medal
contender in Atlanta in three separate events. Torres, on the other
hand, disappeared from the world swimming scene in 1992, ranked
seventh in the 100 fly, sixth in the 100 freestyle and 15th in what
might now be her best event, the 50-meter free.
</P>
<P>
   She has returned to the global scene not only with new purpose,
but sporting a conspicuous new body. Her arms and shoulders, in
particular, ripple with muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Given swimming's dark headlines over the past eight years, she
can expect to come under more than passing scrutiny in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Richard could pretty much tell you the work I've
done,'' Torres countered last night. ``It's been done through hard
work, dedication and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, this is supposed to happen, and I'm just
enjoying the ride. And I feel great knowing I've done it the right
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Thompson nor Torres is wont to talk about her new
training regimen, one that reportedly includes a veritable buffet
of pills and natural supplements under the administration of Austin
nutritionist Glen Luepnitz. Everything that the two have put into
their body, Luepnitz has said, is natural.
</P>
<P>
   Natural, however, in recent years has taken on a variety of
meanings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you something,'' Quick interrupted. ``If I ever
thought that any athlete of mine was cheating, I wouldn't coach
them one more second.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard work and commitment, Quick contends, can produce
``steroid-like performance.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a regretful commentary on the state of Olympic swimming
that Quick finds himself having to defend his two once and future
Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   The hug, Torres said, was not fake. Let's hope her and Thompson
aren't, either.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0009 </DOCNO>
