<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CATHOLIC-CHARITIES-SF     08-11 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-CHARITIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CEO OF CATHOLIC CHARITIES RESIGNS OVER EXPENSES  &HT;     By TOM ZOELLNER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Frank Hudson resigned as the chief executive
officer of Catholic Charities of San Francisco Thursday after the
charity's board condemned his ``lavish and extravagant'' spending
on restaurant meals and cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A Board of Directors investigation into Hudson's spending habits
concluded that he ``melded his professional and personal
lifestyles'' by spending $73,000 of charity money over two years on
gourmet meals at top-tier restaurants such as Stars and Zuni Cafe
and on anti-wrinkle treatments and laser hair removal.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson had said he was dining with politicians and business
leaders in an attempt to boost the charity's visibility. But the
report found that in some cases, he had listed on receipts the
names of people who were not present at the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the receipts were approved not by the board finance
chairman but by Hudson's personal assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have had a wake-up call,'' said San Francisco
Archbishop William Levada, who met privately with Hudson several
times earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sorry for the impact this has had on agency and for the
impact that it has had on donors and the city at large,'' said
Levada, who is head of the charity's board. ``I think he felt that
very keenly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, who had been in his job eight years, could not be
reached for comment at his Petaluma home last night.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities, in existence since 1907, is one of the
largest providers of social services in the Bay Area, running 37
programs that serve 100,000 clients. It also has $10 million a year
in contracts with the city of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson was replaced by Brian Cahill, the former head of the San
Francisco Department of Social Services and the current executive
director of the Catholic Youth Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people are angry and upset and feel deceived,'' Cahill
said last night. ``I acknowledge credibility has been lost. But I
believe we can restore trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop's spokesman Maurice Healy said Hudson's resignation
is effective immediately, but that he will continue to be paid
through the end of October. He will be given no severance package,
but was not asked to reimburse any of the money he spent on meals.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson was asked to return his company car, a 1998 Chevrolet
Suburban, leased by Catholic Charities from a Santa Rosa dealership
for $579.75 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Hudson's spending habits were first reported in The
Chronicle on June 22, but Hudson remained on the job for seven
weeks in the belief he could survive the criticism, said some
employees close to him. He repaid $3,158 on cosmetic treatments and
apologized for ``not being sensitive enough'' to public
perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   But Hudson's fate became apparent last week when Levada called
Cahill to inquire of his availability.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Harry Johnson, who attended Thursday's closed-door
meeting at St. Mary's Cathedral, said there was little question
that Levada had had enough of the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hudson had not tendered his resignation, he would have been
fired,'' Johnson said. ``He told half-truths to the board and
squandered agency money.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Brian Swift said, ``People have to understand this
is not like a normal board of directors. In this board of
directors, only one person (the archbishop) makes the decision. The
Catholic Church is not a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added the board should have been paying closer attention to
Hudson's spending. ``We really need to tighten our controls,'' he
said. ``There's a certain mea culpa attitude about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In an awkward footnote to the affair, the board accepted
Hudson's resignation the day of a long-scheduled party at the
archbishop's residence to honor the top 25 donors to Catholic
Charities. Hudson had been invited, but neither he nor Cahill was
there, attendees said.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said they hoped Cahill's appointment would quickly
restore public trust in San Francisco Catholic Charities, whose
finances suffered from the revelations about Hudson's spending.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Redevelopment Agency, calling Hudson's
spending ``unconscionable,'' reduced a contract with Catholic
Charities to run residential treatment centers for HIV patients to
$1 million from $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Charity staffers said the nonprofit also stood to lose another
$1 million in donations from corporations and Catholic
parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fund-raisers are sort of embarrassed to be promoting the
organization right now, so activity is kind of slowed,'' said one
high-ranking staff member who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill is a native San Franciscan who attended St. Patrick's
Seminary in Menlo Park in the 1960s with hopes of becoming a
priest. But he switched careers before ordination, earned a
master's in social work from San Francisco State University and
became head of the San Francisco Boys home.
</P>
<P>
   After working as the executive director of the California
Association of Services for Children, he served as then-Mayor Frank
Jordan's head of the Department of Social Services from 1992 to
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill said one of his first moves would be to change Catholic
Charities' leadership structure from corporate-based to one more
typical of a nonprofit agency. The leader will no longer be a
``CEO'' but an ''executive director'' and will work under more
scrutiny from the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Under Hudson, Catholic Charities's budget grew from $7 million
to $23.5 million. But critics inside the charity complained the
organization was too focused on winning lucrative government
contracts and too quick to close programs that seemed to be
financial losers.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the controversy surrounding Hudson's spending is
the continued operation of Guerrero House, a home for young
homeless people in the Mission District, which had been slated for
closure. Board members say they will try to find alternative
funding for the center's $480,000 annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we need to be good stewards of
people's money and if we're not, then we're betraying a trust,''
Cahill said. ``We're supposed to be doing what's in the Gospel. The
principle of stewardship has slipped a little and it need to be set
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
