<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUCHANAN MOVES HIS REFORM PARTY FACTION TO THE FAR RIGHT  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As the Reform Party shattered into two
warring conventions Thursday, Pat Buchanan moved his faction
solidly to the right with a three-page manifesto that laid out his
solidly conservative beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The statement compares abortion to Adolf Hitler's euthanasia
program, describes homosexuality as ``a sign of cultural decadence
and moral decline'' and calls for a ban on women in combat, saying
``a country that sends its women out to defend it is a country not
worth defending.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan acknowledged that the Reform Party platform is silent
on the social, cultural and moral issues that were the basis of his
two campaigns for the Republican presidential nomination. But he
said, ``I do not believe presidential candidates can remain
silent.''
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon news conference, Buchanan said the statement
``will be binding only on me and the vice presidential candidate''
he is scheduled to name this morning. But he left little doubt that
his campaign as a Reform Party nominee would be the same type of
moral crusade that he and his backers ran in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one political leader can reverse ... moral decline,'' he
said in his statement. ``But a president can put himself in the
vanguard of those who wish to make America God's Country again.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan pledged to use the moral authority of the presidency
``to support a rule of law based on a moral order that is rooted in
Biblical truth and the laws written by God on the human heart.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Reform Party Divided
</P>
<P>
   The former television commentator's conservative beliefs, along
with his hardball political tactics, have helped split the Reform
Party into battling factions that are holding separate conventions
less than a mile apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Buchanan has attempted to corrupt the presidential
process,'' said Jim Mangia, a longtime supporter of party founder
Ross Perot and head of the breakaway group. ``He is the worst
example of politics as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Mangia and physicist John Hagelin, who is challenging Buchanan
for the Reform Party nomination, led about 200 supporters on a
morning march to the Long Beach Convention Center; where  &LR; they were
turned away when they tried to get into the hall where the
delegates were slated to meet.
</P>
<P>
   After some shouting, fist-waving and a couple of choruses of
``We Shall Overcome,'' the dissidents marched to the nearby
performing arts center, which they had already rented for their
rump convention.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said official convention delegates were welcomed,
regardless of who they supported, but that security people turned
away protesters who weren't on the list of delegates. The
opponents, he suggested, are merely sore losers who aren't willing
to admit they don't have the delegates to swing the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played by the rules everywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way Mangia sees it. To him, Buchanan and his
backers have hijacked the Reform Party and are changing it to
mirror their own conservative beliefs at the expense of the party's
top issues, such as campaign finance reform and nuts and bolts
changes in the way the country is run.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the Reform Party nomination also gets $12.5 million
in federal election funds, money that goes to parties that pull
over 5 percent of the vote in the previous presidential election.
Mangia filed a formal complaint Thursday with the Federal Election
Commission, asking them to bar Buchanan from receiving the money
because of alleged vote fraud in the Reform Party's mail-in
balloting. He said he would rather see the party shut out
completely than have any of the money go to Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pat Buchanan wins the nomination, it's the end of the
Reform Party, because he won't get the 5 percent needed to keep us
as a national party,'' Mangia said. ``Hagelin has a better shot,
because at least he's not the most hated political figure in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he was confident he would win the nomination,
survive any legal challenges and run a full-blown campaign in the
fall. He also  &LR; ridiculed the little-known Hagelin, who is also the
three-time presidential candidate of the tiny Natural Law Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Hagelin is a log thrown on the railroad tracks, and it
will not even slow our express,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin spoke last night at the rump convention, but Buchanan
was not in the hall when he was nominated by the main body of the
party. He plans to stay away from the convention until he gives
what he says will be his acceptance speech Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
