<SLUG> BC-TEN-ESTYLE-CLASSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS INCONSISTANT, BUT WINS ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif _ Serena Williams wows the crowd with her
100 mph serves, forceful forehands and ability to run down
virtually every ball. Her power is evident, but it's sometimes raw,
and it might be important to remember that for all of her success _
including the U.S. Open title and the Wimbledon semifinal _ she's
just 18 years old.
</P>
<P>
   However, 18 is a veteran age in women's tennis and it was the
veteran in Williams who overcame her inconsistencies and Conchita
Martinez to post a 6-2, 4-6, 6-2 victory Thursday in an estyle.com
Classic quarterfinal at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the defending champion and No.5 seed, played the day's
only quarterfinal. In second-round matches, second-seeded Lindsay
Davenport defeated Anne-Gaelle Sidot of France 7-6 (7-0), 6-7
(7-4), 6-2, Amy Frazier upset seventh-seeded Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario 6-3, 3-6, 6-3 and Lisa Raymond swept 17-year-old
qualifier Daja Bedanova 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had her way in the first set, winning the last four
games. But she ran into trouble in the second set, when her
overzealous play led to too many unforced errors. Her approach game
also failed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm strong mentally. I'm staying in there,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   That she did, offsetting a poor service game (just 47 percent of
her first serves landed in) with a solid receiving game. She broke
Martinez seven times, including the final game.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Williams has followed a five-week layoff with a
38-minute breeze and a slightly longer and more difficult match.
Now, she has beaten a ranked player and will face either top-seeded
Martina Hingis or Frazier in Saturday's semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good I had a test,'' Williams said. ``It's good I played
a top player.''
</P>
<P>
   Another top player who struggled yet won was Davenport. She has
faced Sidot twice _ though not since 1997 and won easily both
times. But Davenport is in a mental funk right now, making every
match a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going through a cycle where I'm not playing well,''
Davenport said. ``I've got to fight my way through it. I fought my
way out of it in Wimbledon, but I don't feel like I'm hitting the
shots I want.''
</P>
<P>
   She can't take time off because the U.S. Open is in three weeks,
followed by the Olympics. So she has to remember what led to her
previous success.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport also should have remembered Sidot's serve, which kept
the Frenchwoman in the match. Davenport and Sidot held serve
through the first set, but in the tiebreaker Sidot's serve left
her. She double-faulted on the first two and fifth points.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport reciprocated in the second-set tiebreaker with two
double-faults of her own. Otherwise, ``the only reason I won was
holding serve. I only got broken once.''
</P>
<P>
   Frazier can't recall a better two weeks in her 10-year pro
career. She beat Martina Hingis in the quarterfinals last week in
Carlsbad en route to her second semifinal berth in 14 tournaments,
and knocked off Sanchez-Vicario to reach today's quarterfinal
matchup (rematch?) with Hingis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really nice to be playing good tennis,'' Frazier said,
``and it's so much fun to play so many matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Frazier has beaten Sanchez-Vicario the last three
times they have played, although the two hadn't met since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez-Vicario trailed 5-1 and faced being broken for the match
in the third set before rallying and closing to 5-3. But Frazier
broke her to win.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond took advantage of Bedanova's weak second serve to win
points with a crafty drop shot. Bedanova appeared to expect either
a deep slice or a powerful forehand, only to watch helplessly as
Raymond dropped balls into the frontcourt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
