<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-GENTRY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS INTRODUCE GENTRY AS NEW COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Alvin Gentry wasn't the first offered the vacant
Clipper coaching position. A long list of names emerged before
Gentry reach frontrunner status.
</P>
<P>
   But after a tortuous six-month search, the former Piston and
Heat coach was happy to be the one saying, ``I do'' on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I the first person, I don't know,'' Gentry said after being
introduced as the new Clipper coach at the Marina Del Ray Mariott.
``I probably wasn't the first choice of my wife either. We've been
together 10 years and she kinda likes me. ... That doesn't bother
me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry was given a four-year contract, but the dollar amount or
how many years were guaranteed were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching search led Clippers brass from Mike Fratello to
John Lucas to Bob Huggins and finally to Gentry.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, who first met with the Clippers at the pre-draft camp in
Chicago, was excited about the young Clippers team, which includes
a roster that in places is younger than some college teams.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry, who was an assistant for the Clippers under Mike Schuler
in the 1990-91 season, said he wasn't worried about the negatives
that surround the Clipper organization and often scare coaches and
players away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned what this organization is going to do from
this day forward,'' Gentry said. ``I think as you look, I think
this is a golden opportunity for this franchise. The young players
that we have going for us here. And we have a chance to make this
special over the next couple of years and something that can last
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, Clippers vice president of basketball operations,
watched Gentry since he arrived as a Clippers assistant. Baylor
said Gentry's style fits the young team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Alvin, Alvin has patience,'' Baylor said.
``When he has to get tough he can do that. With young players you
have to be careful because you can kill their confidence right
away. I think Alvin is going to relate very well to the players. I
think he is the kind of coach that is going to be able to motivate
players.''
</P>
<P>
   This despite Gentry being fired in Detroit in part because his
players had reportedly tuned him out. Joe Dumars, one of those who
decided to let Gentry go with 24 games left last season, was one of
the people the recommended Gentry to Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations had been set the year before as far as making the
playoffs and getting things rolling,'' Dumars said. ``When it
didn't happen _ the NBA is a long season _ he got caught in
tailspin, guys weren't playing up to their ability. The decision
was made to make a change right now. By no means did anyone say
that Alvin Gentry is a terrible coach and can't get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry took over in Detroit for Doug Collins in February 1998.
In the lockout-shorted 1999 season he took Detroit to the playoffs,
losing in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the team lost seven of 10 and 11 straight on the
road before Gentry was let go. Gentry in part blamed the skid on
Grant Hill missing a number of games with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You struggle without Grant Hill out there and they made a move
and you are entitled to do that,' Gentry said.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry finished with a 73-72 record with the Pistons. He was
also coach of the Miami head for 34 games in 1995, going 15-21 and
bringing his overall coaching record to 88-93.
</P>
<P>
   Despite firing him five months ago, Dumars felt that Gentry
would be able to relate well to oung players because Gentry is the
type of coach players can easily talk to.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know will Alvin the teaching is fundamentally right,'
Dumars said. ``It didn't work out in Detroit. You know what give
him a chance with a young team and high energy guys and this may be
the right fit for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry also had the strong pull of Philadelphia 76ers coach
Larry Brown, who is the only coach to take the Clippers to the
playoffs twice. Brown had lunch with Clippers owner Donald Sterling
this month and when presented with a list of possible coaches,
pushed for Gentry.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry was an assistant for Brown at Kansas from 1985-88 _ the
Jayhawks won the national championship in 1988. When Brown moved on
to San Antonio, Gentry moved with him and spent two seasons as an
assistant before joining the Clippers as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Brown recommended Gentry for two reasons: He can teach young
players and he wanted the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he would be great with young kids,'' Brown said. ``I
think he would work well with Elgin and (Sterling). I believe he is
a young coach that can teach with the experience he had in college
and the opportunity he had in our league.
</P>
<P>
   Brown added, ``He really wanted the job and I thought that was
very important. A lot of people look down on the Clippers. He's a
very decent guy that loves to teach and coach. I thought with young
kids they would be receptive to that. Not everybody gives us a
chance to teach on our level and I think he enjoys that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of teaching to do with high schooler Miles, who
would be a freshman in college. Keyon Dooling, Quentin Richardson
and Corey Maggette would all be college juniors this season.
</P>
<P>
   Miles, Dooling and Richardson worked out with Gentry before he
was introduced in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Miles and Richardson's agent, David Falk, had openly pushed for
Lucas for the job. But the two said they were happy with the choice
of Gentry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him a thumbs up,'' Miles said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson added, ``I was pretty happy with it. He seemed to
work well with us being young guys and trying to improve on our
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   While Lamar Odom wasn't at the news conference, Clippers center
Michael Olowokandi met Gentry for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Last year) there wasn't any defense,'' Olowokandi said. ``He
said we are going to be playing defense ... to me that is
definitely a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of teaching the young players, Gentry said he won't
stand for players being late for meetings or the team bus. Gentry
said he wants the young players to understand that they have the
responsibilities of a job.
</P>
<P>
   On the court next season, two keys for Gentry are defense and
making it clear that Odom is the focus of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Grant Hill and I see Lamar and I see the same talent,''
Gentry said. ``I think he is a great basketball player. I'm not
afraid to tell the other guys that this is Lamar's team. It will be
his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentry said that he will likely retain Dennis Johnson and Rex
Kalamian as assistants and hire a third coach. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
