<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING CLOSE AT U.S. SWIM TRIALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Ed Moses won the 100-meter breaststroke by 0.65
seconds Thursday at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials. On this day,
that qualified as a rout.
</P>
<P>
   Every final was so tight and the atmosphere so airless, it was
as if the IUPUI Natatorium had been turned into a giant Tupperware
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100-meter butterfly, Stanford's mismatched pair of Jenny
Thompson and Dara Torres were expected to be separated by little
more than static cling and they didn't disappoint. Thompson edged
her teammate, 57.78 to Torres' 57.86, to avenge the loss of her
American record to Torres the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   The width of an eyelash was what separated Diana Munz from 1996
Olympian Brooke Bennett after 400 meters of freestyle. Munz was
declared the winner by 0.05 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   And the only things racing faster than USC sophomore Erik Vendt
and Tom Dolan in the 400 individual medley were the hearts of the
4,500 spectators. Vendt and Dolan were within spearing range of
Dolan's six-year-old world record before settling for a photo
finish, Dolan touching in 4:13.72 to Vendt's 4:13.89.
</P>
<P>
   As if the crowd's collective knuckles weren't white enough,
Vendt's Trojan Swim Club teammate Lenny Krayzelburg came within
0.07 seconds of his own world record in the semifinals of the
100-meter backstroke. Krayzelburg's global mark of 53.60 ought to
be put on the endangered-species list immediately. It could be gone
today, when the final is contested.
</P>
<P>
   Other impressive swims were turned in by Kevin Clements of
Industry Hills, who finished fourth in the I.M., and ex-UCLA
standout Richelle Fox and USC's Karen Campbell, who finished fourth
and fifth, respectively, in the 100 butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of his USC teammates, who see how hard Vendt works day
in and day out, not too many people expected the Massachusetts
native to be a handful for Dolan or Wilkens.
</P>
<P>
   Vendt wasn't even convinced he could stay close to the
front-runners. Vendt's best event, after all _ at least in his mind
_ is the 1,500 freestyle. The 19-year-old looked at the 400 I.M. as
a really grinding warmup for next week's mile.
</P>
<P>
   It turned into a war when Vendt allowed himself a sidelong
glance during the breaststroke leg and saw that he was not only
near Dolan and Wilkens, he was practically even with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pushed off the wall (after the breaststroke leg) and I
was right there with them, I was more excited than anyone on the
pool deck,'' Vendt said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe everyone but Krayzelburg, who was roused from his
warmdown swim by the roar of the crowd. When he glanced at the
scoreboard and saw Vendt's splits, he hopped out of the water and
added his voice to the chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost lost my voice,'' Krayzelburg said. ``I couldn't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vendt, at 5-foot-10, gives up eight inches to the wiry Dolan,
but he didn't give up an inch when Dolan found another gear to slip
into with 50 meters to go. Krayzelburg wasn't surprised. ``Erik's
got a heart of a lion,'' he said. ``He's a feisty little guy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Vendt finished and saw the ``2'' next to his lane, he
pumped a fist at his parents in the stands _ just as he imagined
he'd do after making the Olympic team in the 1,500 _ and then tried
hard not to wake up from this wonderful dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to swim that fast,'' said Vendt, who took a
five-second chunk out of his previous personal best. ``I really
thought it was out of my reach. I thought I could sneak in if I had
a great race.''
</P>
<P>
   Today it's Krayzelburg's turn. ``Hopefully,'' Krayzelburg said,
``I can do something special.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
