A8553 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PARTIES-DNC-2ndtake-L     08-11 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTIES-DNC-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: people signed on.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, even in a party town like L.A., next week will seem
excessive. You could literally skip the convention and spend the
entire week attending brunches, lunches, receptions, dinners,
concerts and after-hours events scheduled from one morning to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Micucci, founder/owner of Along Came Mary Productions of
Los Angeles, said the DNC is great for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I embrace the opportunities -- and these special event
marathons,'' says the gourmet caterer, who has been part of the
L.A. party experience for the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Along Came Mary is catering and orchestrating 14 parties,
including numerous events sponsored by UAW/General Motors and a
sit-down luncheon for 250, sponsored by Sony Pictures and
California Gov. Gray Davis for the Democratic governors Monday at
Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   Trendy L.A. restaurants will be dishing up extra chow, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Patina Group, which owns Patina restaurant on Melrose
Avenue, is preparing the food for Saturday evening's LA Convention
2000 Media Event, Faces of Los Angeles. It's one of the largest
parties, with 20,000 journalists and media representatives expected
to attend at the Performing Arts Center of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a challenge to feed 20,000 people and produce
that much food,'' says Stephanie Edens, the company's director of
catering and special events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took the event and broke it into four separate parties of
5,000 each, with each operating with its own chef.''
</P>
<P>
   Latin-American, Asian-American, Southern and Melting Pot are
among the themes featuring such foods as corn tamales with chicken,
beef taquitos, assorted sushi, spicy buttermilk fried chicken,
country coleslaw, black olive focaccia, spicy shrimp with couscous
and cool mint yogurt sauce, vegetable empanadas, Chinese beef salad
and 10 different desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Organization, say party planners, is the key to pulling off six
successive days of parties.
</P>
<P>
   At Someone's In The Kitchen, Roth-Oseary has been working on the
battle plans -- as she calls them -- for months. The firm is
catering 11 events sponsored by UAW/DaimlerChrysler at the Peterson
Automotive Museum from Sunday through Thursday in addition to a
Blue Dogs party Sunday at the Santa Monica Pier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've drawn on each and every year of my 20 years of experience
to bring off this feat, which involves close to 400 people in the
production,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be preparing 640 racks of lamb, 550 herb-crusted
roasted sea bass, 600 pounds of filet mignon and 450 pounds of
orzo. We will also be serving 54,000 individual hors d'oeuvres. We
also expect to go through 40 gallons of half-and-half and will
ultimately consume a 14-foot-long truckload each of fresh fruits
and fresh vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   So how do you decide which parties to attend? Maybe you don't
have to narrow it down.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some smaller private dinners being held at restaurants
such as Spago, many of the parties are receptions designed to
encourage people to stop by as they are party-hopping all over
town. In some cases, different-size tables will be sprinkled around
the emptied-out restaurants and venues to allow for plenty of
standing room -- and schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients want people to come to their parties but realize
they have other places to go,'' said Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   When the party is over, what happens to the leftovers?
</P>
<P>
   The windfall of prepared foods that never came near the buffet
tables will be picked up by the Los Angeles Regional Foodbank and
distributed to soup kitchens, homeless shelters and other charities
that feed the hungry.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
