<SLUG> BC-PARTIES-DNC-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE DNC PARTIES BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From chic restaurants like Patina, which plans to
serve 20,000 meals, to hip caterers like Along Came Mary, with 14
parties booked, the Democratic National Convention has taxed Los
Angeles' seasoned catering corps like never before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having the Oscars four nights in a row because these
people will be party-hopping all over town,'' said Jondel
Goldsmith, director of special events for Spago Beverly Hills,
which is catering at least a dozen parties.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC is providing such a bonanza to the catering industry
that just about every full-time and part-time waiter, waitress,
bartender, dishwasher, table, chair, fork and knife in Los Angeles
have been called on, with frantic calls sent to other cities and
states for backup equipment.
</P>
<P>
   With many of the 15,000 reporters, photographers and other media
workers already in town and the Democratic delegates arriving en
masse Saturday for a week of partying, it's show time in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Today's arrival of President Clinton and his Senate candidate
wife, Hillary, for a weekend of fund-raising and party boostering
will kick off the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   Literally hundreds of parties are scheduled all over town, from
exclusive affairs in the mansions of Bel-Air and the Riviera
Country Club to massive open bashes at the Music Center Pavilion
and the Paramount Studios lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the DNC, we are sold out every day from now through
Aug. 19 -- and I have in excess of 600 active and on-call field
staff,'' said Tracy Adams, general manager of The Party Staff Inc.,
a Los Angeles company providing staffing for caterers and corporate
clients for some 100 events in a 13-day period.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who's nearly spent even before the festivities begin, has
drawn on the company's outlets in Orange County and San Diego to
fill the requests. ``I'm considering early retirement,'' Adams
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the poor bride and groom trying to get married next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to turn away a lot of nonDNC-related business from
regular clients, like dinner parties, barbecues and anniversary
parties, for months,'' said Joann Roth-Oseary, president of
Tarzana-based Someone's In the Kitchen. ``I even turned down one
wedding eight months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some clients were able to shift their parties to the weekend
of Aug. 19, and we're catering seven parties that weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The party marathon has also been a bonanza for the equipment
rental business.
</P>
<P>
   Stand-up bar tables (1,000 needed), buffet tables and smaller
round tables have been sent in from Orange County, Arizona and New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several large events that have used up quite a bit
of equipment -- and then there are various home parties for
delegations -- and various fund-raisers that have compounded the
problem,'' said Jeffrey Williams, vice president of Regal Rents
Inc. in Los Angeles. ``On the larger events, we had two to three
months' notice, but the smaller ones came in later. We are in good
shape now.''
</P>
<P>
   As all party organizers know, they must expect the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   United Jewish Communities expected some 2,000 people at its
party at the Sony Pictures Studio in Culver City. But after Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut was selected as the Democratic
running mate for Vice President Al Gore, an additional 1,000 people
signed on.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
