A8557 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-JEWISH-FEDERATION-LAD     08-11 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-FEDERATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH GROUP EVENT JOINS A-LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Up until last week, the United Jewish Communities
organization's plans for a celebration on Sunday were going well,
with some 2,000 people planning to attend the event at the Sony
Pictures Studio in Culver City.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Tuesday's announcement that Sen. Joe Lieberman of
Connecticut was being selected as the Democratic running mate for
Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even begin to count the number of calls we got,'' said
Diana Aziz, director of the Washington office of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had originally intended to keep it at 2,000. But now it's
over 3,000 people and counting. We're trying to accommodate
everyone, and we're telling them just wear short sleeves, because
it will be crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   That's even without Lieberman confirming an appearance. Still,
the group had a pretty good draw already with President Clinton and
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is the first Jewish American to run on a major
presidential party ticket and is seen not only as boosting
enthusiasm in the Jewish community but in other minority
communities as well for breaking a barrier to high public office.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many Jewish activists believe it will have an impact on
the Republican ticket of George W. Bush and Dick Cheney as they
attempt to broaden their reach into minority communities as well as
keep GOP Jewish voters in their party.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of the event for the United Jewish Committee is an
example of the role ethnic politics plays in both parties, but
especially for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Separate events have been scheduled for various groups of
activists, including Armenian-Americans, African-Americans,
American Indians, Italian-Americans and Irish-Americans, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic diversity is so prominent that next Wednesday, the
party is holding one luncheon of all the different groups called
Ethnic America 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both parties do this, but the Democrats do it more and
better,'' said Democratic political consultant Joe Cerrell, who is
hosting a luncheon for Italian-American office holders on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats have an ethnic coordinator, and it's important
for these different groups to get recognition that they wouldn't
get otherwise if they just attended the convention. It
reinvigorates them to know that the party has to respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it makes the party aware that different groups want
special attention and have their own concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Aziz agreed with that assessment but said her experience has
been that the United Jewish Communities -- created by the merger of
the United Jewish Appeal, the Council of Jewish Federations and the
United Israel Appeal -- draws from a wider audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see people who have similar concerns as we do coming to our
events,'' Aziz said. ``They feel they are connected through an
affinity group.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe said the various ethnic
groupings play a more practical role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that a lot of money will be raised,'' Jeffe said.
``This is the big enchilada as far as Democrats are concerned. If
you consider the party one big pie, they are slicing it as many
ways as they can to get the biggest bang.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans do it differently because the party is not as
diverse, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call it corporate constituencies,'' Jeffe said. ``That's
what you saw in Philly, where it was the lawmakers who were
invisible, but were raising lots behind the scenes.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
