r a BC-MEDIA-PERCEPTION-LADN     08-11 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-PERCEPTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S REPORTERS TAKE WHACK AT DEFINING L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Democrats' coronation bash doesn't commence
until Monday. But the East Coast media, long suspected of a bias
against the Left Coast, already kicked sand in the host's face.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal, the gray business bible, said in a
front-page story this week that Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan
``melds brains and bumbling'' and nicknamed His Honor the ``City
Slipper'' for his inclination to sometimes mangle people's names.
</P>
<P>
   The angle taken by the Journal is not a surprise, though,
because here in Los Angeles the horizon separating reality from
perception is often blurred.
</P>
<P>
   With 15,000 journalists hitting town -- outnumbering delegates
almost 4 to 1 and turning the convention center into the world's
biggest press room -- that horizon will be stared at more than
ever. The city will be scrutinized as much as the Democratic
platform.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the paper noted that Riordan is a brilliant
businessman and rich enough to basically run the city for free. But
the paper also said the Republican mayor is ``not poised and
polished ... and basic etiquette sometimes eludes him.''
</P>
<P>
   Journal spokesman Dick Tofel said the paper did not take a
similar whack at Philadelphia -- or its mayor -- before the
Republican love fest two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the thousands of other journalists covering the
convention are still working on their L.A. scene stories, to run in
papers across the world in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Barnes, a reporter for the National Journal, a Washington,
D.C.-based political magazine, is comparing the personalities of
L.A. and D.C., saying the two cities are woven from different
cultural fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is a more formal place with a more clearly defined
power structure. Los Angeles is, well, not.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is certainly seen ... as this exotic spot on the Left
Coast,'' he said. ``Los Angeles has a very different society to it.
We're Brooks Brothers, and L.A. is more Armani.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes was also surprised by the city's new subway system.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest things that made an impression on me was
the subway and not going through a turnstile. The honor system was
pretty interesting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Readers of the Houston Chronicle might also get a surprise this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The paper sent Washington-based reporter Patty Reinert into the
neighborhoods around downtown on Thursday to assess what Los
Angeles is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out L.A and Houston are a lot alike, she's writing.
They're both sprawling, culturally diverse metropolises with bad
air.
</P>
<P>
   Reinert notes that lots of people outside of Los Angeles are
familiar with the city's tawdry resume, which includes the Rodney
King beating, riots, earthquakes and the O.J. Simpson trial, as
well as the glitzier Hollywood stuff.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour sponsored by the Convention and Visitors Bureau, she
saw a resurgent downtown and much more.
</P>
<P>
   She saw a city that looked like a lot of other cities that
people call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was diverse in every way,'' Reinert said after visiting
neighborhoods like Little Toyko and Boyle Heights. ``I guess I saw
more harmony than we have seen in recent years. Today what I saw
was much more of an integrated culture, a lot of groups of people
coexisting very close together.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
