L.A. BOOSTERS' EFFORT ARE AN UNDERWHELMING SUCCESS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With 15,000 journalists hitting town for the
Democratic National Convention, civic boosters saw a prime
opportunity Thursday to turn the spotlight on the city's leading
industry -- entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   A press tour called for a free lunch, behind-the-scenes access
to Universal Studios and the ear of some Hollywood insiders, so
space was limited to a manageable 100 people.
</P>
<P>
   Six showed up, another four straggled in later.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers, whose staff and handlers nearly outnumbered the
guests, were somewhat disappointed with the turnout but said the
effort was worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get a positive message about Los Angeles out
to the world, so if it's just two people who write good stories,
that's better than 100 journalists who weren't impressed,'' said
John Duel, media relations manager of one sponsor, the Los Angeles
Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the attending journalists had the opportunity to
carry L.A.'s message far -- Germany, China and Japan, among others
from their bureaus in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Milker, bureau chief of German television production
company GTP-MEDIA, said the convention would provide a good reason
to turn his cameras on Los Angeles in general, to show the side his
countrymen may not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already have a very good opinion of L.A., even though I
interview German tourists who are very disappointed with Hollywood
because it's kind of dirty and not as nice as they see in the
movies,'' Milker said.
</P>
<P>
   The revitalization of Hollywood was a theme in Thursday's tour,
which concluded with a hard hat tour of the TrizecHahn project at
Hollywood Boulevard and Highland Avenue -- the future home of the
Academy Awards and a focus of the area's renewal.
</P>
<P>
   The tour started in North Hollywood with a round-table
discussion at the Academy of Television Arts &AMP; Sciences featuring
executives from Technicolor Inc. and other production and Internet
entertainment companies.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed by lunch at CityWalk and a VIP tour of
Universal Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Other tours in the weeklong L.A. Industry Showcase fared only
slightly better in terms of attendance.
</P>
<P>
   A science tour Monday with stops at NASA's Jet Propulsion Lab
and the California Institute of Technology drew about 20 members of
the press corps, about the same as Wednesday's focus on new media
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers with LA TradeMark, a consortium of the visitors
bureau, Los Angeles Area Chamber of Commerce and Mayor Riordan's
Business Team, said the low attendance was understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Many journalists were not expected to arrive until today, and
those that are already here have time constraints, deadline
pressures and political angles to cover, said tour organizer
Jennifer Zabriskie.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
