<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-SATURN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURN REGAINS RANKING IN CUSTOMER SALES SATISFACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGOURA HILLS, Calif. _ Saturn has regained its top position on
the latest J.D. Power and Associates customer sales satisfaction
index, recovering from a slip to sixth place in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus and Cadillac tied for second place this year.
</P>
<P>
   The study showed Saturn was particularly strong in the purchase
transaction area.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Denove, a partner at J.D. Power, said most buyers surveyed
felt they were treated honestly and fairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people will be surprised to hear the great
majority of buyers were satisfied with the process of buying a
car,'' Denove said.
</P>
<P>
   When people felt they were treated unfairly, dealerships failing
to live up to commitments made during the sales process was the
most serious complaint.
</P>
<P>
   An unhappy purchaser translates to loss of service business and
loss of potential sales through recommendations to friends, Denove
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealers need to understand that they might be able to pressure
the customer into spending a few extra dollars on a vehicle today,
but they're probably going to be hurt in the long run because
they'll lose business in the future,'' Denove said.
</P>
<P>
   It costs a small fortune in advertising to acquire new
customers, so it's critical to keep customers coming back, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Nitowski was at Saturn of Thousand Oaks on Thursday getting
one of his family's two Saturns serviced.
</P>
<P>
   Nitowski said he bought one in 1995 and had no problems with it,
so he got another one in 1998. The cars were for his college-age
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them stuck on the freeway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nitowski liked the no-haggling policy at Saturn. When he bought
a previous car, he said he couldn't sleep that night for worrying
that he had been cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Bohn, partner and sales manager at Saturn of Thousand
Oaks, said his dealership ``never, ever'' pressures a customer and
makes sure any problems that arise are resolved to the customer's
satisfaction as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically treat people the way they want to be treated,''
Bohn said. ``We respect their time, their budget and their
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The J.D. Powers study showed auto companies raking in the most
sales had declines in customer satisfaction. Denove attributed that
drop to delays in delivering cars to customers and a decrease in
some dealers' willingness to negotiate when demand for their cars
is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Customer satisfaction with the sales process also decreased when
the time required to complete the sales transaction increased.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the respondents said knowing the dealer invoice
price was important. When they learned it from their dealer rather
than through their own efforts, they were more likely to be
satisfied with the sales process.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn led or tied for the sales satisfaction index from 1995 to
1998, then slipped to sixth place. This year, it edged out Cadillac
and Lexus to regain the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Cadillac, Volvo and Jaguar were tied for the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the 23 nameplates that placed above the
industry average in 2000, in order of ranking, were: Infiniti,
Buick, Land Rover, Mercedes-Benz, Volvo, Jaguar, Oldsmobile, BMW,
Lincoln, Porsche, Saab, DaimlerChrysler, GMC, Mercury, Jeep,
Pontiac, Audi, Chevrolet, Acura and Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Powers has produced the Sales Satisfaction Index for 13
years. This year's survey was a random sample of 41,358
respondents.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, the survey separated car and truck satisfaction and
sometimes added other categories. In the early to mid-1990s, Lexus,
Cadillac, Mercedes-Benz and Infiniti showed up frequently in the
new car sales satisfaction category. In the truck category,
Pontiac, Ford, Chevrolet, Oldsmobile and Land Rover were winners.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
