<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-CHEERLEADER-AZR &LR;      08-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADER-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-CHEERLEADER-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `BUT I'M A CHEERLEADER' NOT MUCH TO CHEER ABOUT(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your story goes here.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)But I'm a Cheerleader (enditalic)is a confused
movie about a confused young woman.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, you can understand the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the movie plays as broad satire, lampooning
intolerance against homosexuality. In other places, it seems to
lash out at gay males, portraying them as mincing stereotypes.
Embossed atop the whole thing is a love story that seems more
suited to a John Hughes movie, if he ever made a film about
same-sex relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a movie that tries to be about something but will
probably just offend everyone. That's a shame, because director
Jamie Babbit had some good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts out in amusing fashion, as we meet Megan
(Natasha Lyonne), a cheerleader who's confused about her sexuality.
Her boyfriend loves to make out, but she couldn't be more bored
with him. In fact, she's more interested in her fellow
cheerleaders, but she's not quite sure why.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Megan's ultraconservative parents, who immediately arrange
an intervention (a hilarious scene by itself) and ship Megan off to
a homosexual deprogramming camp. There she meets counselor Mike
(RuPaul, out of drag and wearing a ``straight is great'' T-shirt)
and Mary (Cathy Moriarty), who runs the home while trying to
deprogram her own hunky son (Eddie Cibrian).
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a ``message'' movie, the counselors are portrayed
as unsympathetic, tin-plated ideologues who spout ridiculous
theories on sexuality. Much of this is played for laughs, though it
often flies way over the top.
</P>
<P>
   The sets are fun, done in bright colors with a sort of Kmart
chic. The house where the camp is held is even surrounded by a pink
picket fence. The costumes (blue for the boys, pink for the girls)
add a few laughs as well.
</P>
<P>
   Those touches give the movie an unconventional tone, somewhat
akin to John Waters' (beginitalic)Hairspray(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   For the first half-hour, (beginitalic)But I'm a Cheerleader
(enditalic)is mostly a farce, as Moriarty tries silly methods to
make her charges behave ``normally.'' There are plenty of sight
gags and double entendre, all aimed at showing that the treatment
isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's almost having the opposite effect as Megan strikes
up a friendship with Graham (Clea DuVall), a girl who doesn't buy
the brainwashing but pretends to go along. At this point, the film
starts to unravel, lurching from satire to a serious love story.
</P>
<P>
   We also have to endure Babbit's strident, off-putting depiction
of heterosexual sex, as the students try to simulate guy-girl
relationships. This is Babbit telling us that society has no
business trying to force homosexuals to be hetero, and it has all
the subtlety of an anvil dropped from a great height.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the trouble with much of the movie. By the end of it,
we're not so much enlightened as we are sore from being beaten over
the head.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
