<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-BLESSCHILD-AZR &LR;      08-11 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLESSCHILD-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-BLESSTHECHILD-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `BLESS THE CHILD' POSSESSED BY FORCES OF DOPINESS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some notes on battling Satan in the movies, for the producers of
(beginitalic)Bless (enditalic)(beginitalic)the Child:(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the Prince of Darkness cannot be defeated with
conventional weapons. Pistols and tear gas are no good. You need
some sort of ancient dagger or book of runes.
</P>
<P>
   When arriving at Satan's residence to serve an arrest warrant,
do not enter the premises without backup, especially if said backup
disappears into some sort of evil mist.
</P>
<P>
   Do not, under any circumstances, sneak into a house full of
devil worshipers armed only with a kitchen knife and a winning
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid the room with the big altar in it. Bad things happen
there.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Satan plays poorly with a lead. As soon as he gets the
upper hand, his imps start strutting around and talking trash. This
is the time to act.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the makers of (beginitalic)Bless the Child
(enditalic)didn't remember many of these important guidelines and
ended up with a pretty dopey movie, which is watchable just the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Basinger stars as Maggie, a nurse who raises her infant
niece, Cody (Holliston Coleman), after the girl is dumped on
Maggie's doorstep by her druggie sister (Angela Bettis). By age 6,
we learn, Cody is ``special,'' that is, she can make objects spin,
reanimate dead animals, simple stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Cody is also the target of evil Eric Stark (Rufus
Sewell), a cult leader with a direct line to Lucifer. Stark wants
to kidnap Maggie and turn her to evil, much like Darth Vader tried
with Luke Skywalker, except with less stuff blowing up.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie gets some help from handsome FBI agent John Travis (Jimmy
Smits, who apparently never turned in his (beginitalic)NYPD Blue
(enditalic)trench coat). Travis is trying to solve a series of
child murders, and - well, you can see where all this is going.
</P>
<P>
   That's sort of the fun of (beginitalic)Bless the
Child(enditalic). Hokey and contrived, yes. But it holds your
attention, in that Saturday-matinee sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   Like dozens of Satan-battling movies before it,
(beginitalic)Bless the Child (enditalic)comes with the
(beginitalic)Exorcist (enditalic)starter set: crying statues,
self-lighting candles, sinister ancient symbols and the handy
all-knowing priest. The dialogue is uniformly weak, when it's not
simply lifted from other films.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the internal logic makes no sense. The devil worshipers
constantly capture Maggie but never finish her off. Maggie meets a
street urchin (Christina Ricci) who knows everything but hasn't
bothered to tell the cops. Satan can conjure hundreds of demons but
is easily thwarted by the closing door of a subway car.
</P>
<P>
   While Basinger thrives in certain roles (case in point, her
Oscar for (beginitalic)L.A. Confidential(enditalic)), she doesn't
really have the range to carry a whole movie. Smits is serviceable
as the FBI agent but tends to fade into the woodwork on the big
screen.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the movie gets a lift from Sewell
((beginitalic)Dark City(enditalic)), who plays a pretty good imp.
And Coleman, who is only 7 years old, does a splendid job as Cody.
</P>
<P>
   All told, (beginitalic)Bless the Child (enditalic)is a pretty
mindless movie. But it has some thrills and chills, and doesn't
descend into quite the gorefest of films such as (beginitalic)End
of Days(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   If only they knew the rules.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
