<SLUG> BC-MINE-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MINE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    HEFTY FINE HITS MINE OPERATOR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By CRAIG HARRIS(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Federal mining regulators Thursday fined an Asarco
copper mine near Tucson nearly $250,000 for safety violations
discovered after a Jan.31 accident that killed one miner and
severely injured two others.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Mine Safety and Health Administration also will issue
further fines for eight more alleged safety violations at the mine,
MSHA attorney Tom Mascolino said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition Thursday, the mine was cited for 24 more MSHA
violations after a surprise inspection this week in the wake of
(beginitalic)Arizona Republic(enditalic) reports about the January
death of Jose Villanueva.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had a chance to review the reported new MSHA
citations issued at our Mission mine,'' Asarco said in a written
statement. ``But given the political pressure generated by
(beginitalic)The Arizona Republic's(enditalic) recent biased
articles, we aren't surprised that they were issued. MSHA has been
under heavy pressure to `do something' to `atone' for its supposed
earlier laxity.''
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)The Republic (enditalic)reported that the January
accident occurred after Villanueva and others repeatedly complained
about unsafe conditions, complaints they said were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Mascolino said the newspaper's stories had nothing to do with
this week's citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspectors write citations when there is a need to do it,'' he
said. ``Our job is to protect people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Citations pile up for Asarco.  &UR; A14 &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 0801EDT &QL; 
