u f BC-BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC-BOS     08-11 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCIENTIFIC IN TALKS TO BUY ISRAELI STENT MAKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Scientific Corp., which has lost market share in the
fast-growing cardiovascular stent market due to difficulties with
Medinol Ltd., its major supplier, has quietly begun talks to
acquire the Israel-based business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that has happened in the last three weeks,''
James Tobin, the president and chief executive of Boston
Scientific, said of the negotiations. ``We both engaged bankers and
those bankers are dealing with each other. The process is moving
forward as quickly as anything like this can. But it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Medinol, a five-year-old privately held company based in Tel
Aviv, supplies Boston Scientific with the NIR line, its
top-of-the-line cardiovascular stents. These stents _ small tubes
used to prop open once-clogged arteries _ are used to treat
diseases of the cardiovascular system, which affects 7.2 million
Americans. About 350,000 new cases of coronary artery disease are
diagnosed each year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boston Scientific received $410 million in revenues
from selling Medinol stents, according to the Wall Street
investment firm ABN AMRO Inc. That accounted for about 14 percent
of the Natick, Mass. firm's worldwide revenues and about 27 percent
of its SciMed division revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this year, however, its cardiovascular
stent revenues slipped because of shortfalls in sales, competitive
pressures, and delays in getting new stents from Medinol. ``It's
been no secret that the two companies have had a somewhat
tumultuous relationship,'' Daniel T. Lemaitre, first vice president
at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., wrote in a report to investors. ``The
channels of communication between the two have been spotty in the
past, which had resulted in longer than expected development cycles
and suboptimal inventory management.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Boston Scientific's three major rivals _ Guidant
Corp. of Indianapolis, Medtronics Inc. of Minneapolis, and Johnson
&AMP; Johnson, the world's biggest medical device maker _ manufacture
their own stents and thus receive higher profit margins. By not
owning Medinol, Boston Scientific can't be as competitive because
its 60 percent profit margin is about 10 to 15 percent lower than
its competitors on stents that command $1,300 to $1,800 each.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific officials acknowledge that the fast growth of
the cardiovascular stent market has surprised them. So when a
best-selling NIR stent was recalled in 1998 by the company and the
US Food and Drug Administration, the company not only lost market
share, but also had to delay the introduction of new stents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We underestimated the size of the market,'' said Peter
Nicholas, the Boston Scientific cofounder and chairman, noting the
cardiovascular stent market is about $2 billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 13 months ago, the Israeli newspaper Ha'aretz reported
that Boston Scientific, which owns about 22 percent of Medinol, was
trying to buy the entire company. Boston Scientific officials said
the report was untrue but did not rule out the possibility of
eventually acquiring Medinol.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said the ``rocky partnership'' in the past has changed
recently. Medinol's founders, Israelis Kobi and Judith Richter,
have agreed to sell ``because the time was right,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what had changed since last summer, Tobin said Kobi
Richter considered a new NIR stent under development a breakthrough
device that will give both firms a leadership position. Tobin said
Richter believes the device, the subject of much industry buzz,
could enable Boston Scientific to regain its lead in sales and
market share when it gains FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so the time to start the (acquisition) discussions is
now,'' Tobin said of Richter's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Owning Medinol would also solve a major problem for Boston
Scientific, permitting them to boost profit margins on stents by
eliminating the markup. Last month, the company announced a
manufacturing reorganization that would save it $250 million a year
and consolidate production. Over the next 17 months, Boston
Scientific will close its manufacturing operations in Watertown,
Mass., Plymouth, Minn., and Redmond, Wash., which together employ
1,900 workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
