<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8676 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-BUSH-CHARACTER-NEWHOU     08-11 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHARACTER-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
  
 BUSH HITS THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL ARMED WITH THE `CHARACTER ISSUE'
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, AUGUST 10, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By BILL WALSH. 
 C.2000 Newhouse News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (WASHINGTON) -- George W. Bush rides the Republican presidential
campaign trail packing the ``character issue'' at his side like a
trusty six-shooter.
</P>
<P>
   His stump speeches are chock full of words like ``honor,''
``dignity'' and ``values,'' and while the word ``Clinton'' never
comes up, it would be difficult for anyone to miss the references
to the president's moral lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush insists that he is not criticizing Clinton. Instead,
Bush said, he is just giving voters a preview of his own moral
conduct inside the Oval Office -- a claim critics say is so
disengenuous it calls Bush's own honesty into question.
</P>
<P>
   While it might seem a foolproof campaign strategy to impugn the
integrity of the only impeached president of the 20th century,
political experts say Bush needs to be careful. Despite Clinton's
troubles, he remains popular and voters are in no mood to recall
the dark days of the impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, experts say, Bush could appear heavy-handed if he tries
to tar his rival, Vice President Gore, with Clinton's personal
problems. The risk, the experts say, is that Bush could become the
target of a character campaign himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that character is the subtext of this
election,'' said Robert Denton, a professor of political
communication at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State
University. ``The question is, how hard can he push it? He knows
it's a very fine line and he damned near crossed it. No one likes
to see you hit a dog when he's down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has certainly given his opponents plenty of ammunition.
Even before he took office in 1992, questions swirled about his
marital fidelity and political shenanigans while governor of
Arkansas. His White House administration was dogged by allegations
of fund-raising improprieties as Democratic donors swarmed to
private coffees with the president or spent the night in the
Lincoln bedroom. Clinton's reputation for moral rectitude hit
bottom in 1998 when he admitted having an affair with a White House
intern and was impeached by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore's selection Tuesday of Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman as a running mate was widely seen as an effort
partly to shield himself from broad character attacks on the
Clinton administration that could stain his own candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was never connected to the scandal, but his Achilles' heel
may be the way he reacted to it. At the height of the scandal, Gore
defended Clinton as ``one of the best presidents.'' Lieberman,
meanwhile, was denouncing the president's behavior from the floor
of the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Having Lieberman at his side isn't likely to innoculate Gore
from questions about his own ethical problems, which mostly involve
dubious fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bush's character campaign has been waged with a wink and
a nod. He has barely mentioned Clinton or Gore by name. His
acceptance speech last week contained more than two dozen
references to character issues, but only two explicit mentions of
the ``Clinton/Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nobody missed the point. When Bush called for a new ``era
of responsibility,'' the partisan Republican crowd roared. They did
the same when Bush said, ``Times of plenty, like times of crisis,
are tests of American character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one thing that has dominated the news about the
presidency since 1998, it was that whole matter of the personal
behavior of President Clinton,'' said Charles Jones, a presidential
scholar with the Brookings Institution. ``People do not have to be
reminded of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say that Bush is courting trouble if he is too coy.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week with The Washington Post, Bush
insisted that his promise to bring ``honor and dignity'' to the
White House was not aimed at the president, an assertion that
elicited guffaws in some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost insulting,'' said Denton, the political scholar
from Virginia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't speak well for Bush's own candor and honesty,''
added Bill Benoit, a professor of communication at the University
of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush can't be too explicit, either. Focus groups listening
to Bush's acceptance speech responded favorably when he sketched a
broad vision of strong leadership and morals in the White House.
But as soon as the comments appeared to stray too close to a
personal attack, voters tuned out.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   It's likely, the experts say, that Bush will continue to make
glancing references to character, but leave the more stinging
attacks to his lieutenants. Among the candidates: Vice Presidential
nominee Dick Cheney,the Republican governors and congressional
Republican leaders like Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi and Rep. Tom
DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, experts say, that the Bush character campaign may
dodge the impeachment altogether. Even though it was championed by
his own party and was the final chapter in the sordid sex scandal
Bush continues to hint at, pollsters and political scientists say
that voters don't want to be reminded of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are pretty much tired of all that. They want to
put it behind them,'' said David Allen, a political science
professor at Colorado State University.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a Republican, believes that Bush's character campaign is
targeted at those who already have a low opinion of Clinton and
Gore: The Republican constituent base. He said the comments are
intended to energize the core believers to get them involved in the
campaign and to vote in November.
</P>
<P>
   But, Allen also said it could backfire, especially if Bush is
seen as unfairly attacking Gore. Despite the fund-raising
questions, Allen said that no one has ever questioned Gore's
morality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people recognize that it is Lieberman and Gore and not
Clinton-Gore,'' Allen said. ``Bush can use that to drum up the
faithful, but I don't think it will garner them votes.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some believe it could open the door to Bush's own,
admittedly, dark past.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has acknowledged that in college and in the years before
being elected to public office, he was a heavy drinker. He has
studiously avoided saying whether he experimented with drugs,
saying he hasn't used any since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   His ``frat boy'' image has been muted somewhat by a religious
awakening that saw him embrace Christianity and eschew alcohol.
But, experts say, in the heat of a campaign that already seems to
be turning negative, anything is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be above moral reproach today, but it wasn't always
so,'' said Judith Trent, a political scientist at the University of
Cincinnati. ``While most people aren't that concerned about his
past, he risks being seen as a hypocrite. He has to tread very
carefully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
