<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Saturday, August 12 and Sunday, August
13, 2000 are moving today to clients of the New York Times News
Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ ``Unless we take action now, our
nation may confront a situation similar to the Great Depression _
and maybe even worse.'' The presidential candidate who made this
frightening prediction is lying low. His political party, however,
currently has a high profile. It is being torn apart from within.
It turns out that Ross Perot's leadership was not needed to save
America from another Great Depression. But Perot may be needed to
keep his Reform Party from crumbling to pieces. (Rowland Nethaway
is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ As a born and
bred Southsider I can't help but get a chuckle out of the Great
Pink Flamingo Controversy north of here. In case you haven't been
following major news events lately, here's the story. Doug and
Ellen Henry bought a home in what I take to be a subdivision.
Hoping to spruce up their front yard, which likely had been left
bare of trees by greedy developers, they paid $15 each for a pair
of pink flamingos. They described the colorful birds as ``lawn
decoration.'' Their neighbors, certainly not Southern-born, thought
the colorful birds were tacky eyesores. (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Texas _ When Al Gore introduced his new
running mate Tuesday _ Joseph Lieberman, America's first Jewish
vice-presidential candidate _ the mood in Nashville was jubilant.
The theme of the party: ``Isn't it great that we live in America,
where such a thing can happen?'' Meanwhile, in the months and weeks
leading up to the election, as the two major parties moved
inexorably to the nomination of yet another daring combination of
Four White Guys, I've found myself asking a different question:
``This is America! Why can't we get some semblance of diversity on
the ticket?''(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Before I made that dash
from the air-conditioned office to the air-conditioned car, I
checked my finances. I had 65 cents to my name. I could buy a cold
drink to sip on the way home, or be 65 cents ahead tomorrow. I
decided I needed the change more than the soda. As I pulled out of
the newspaper parking lot, cranked up the AC and headed to the
intersection, I saw her, looking like a frightened rabbit. (Ernest
Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Undermined by votes in the Knesset and betrayed
by a one-time coalition partner in filling the nation's figurehead
presidency, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has been left holding an
empty political bag. The question now is whether Barak, after a
series of political defections, can cobble together a functioning
coalition before the Knesset, on a three-month recess, reconvenes
in October and makes a final decision on its preliminary vote to
call early elections. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ``Is America ready for a Jewish vice
president, only a heartbeat away from the presidency?'' The answer
needs to be a typical Jewish one, a return question: ``Why not?''
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Foreign policy issues rarely decide elections.
Although they can be a factor in whether a candidate ``appears
presidential,'' most voters look elsewhere in choosing whom to
support. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the
Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN - THE BALLPARK IN ARLINGTON _ This is the house
that George W. Bush helped build. Politics aside, it's such an
improvement over its ugly predecessor as to not be in the same
ballpark, so to speak. Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel. MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
