<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A-flutter over flamingos
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a born and bred Southsider I can't help but get a
chuckle out of the Great Pink Flamingo Controversy north of here.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't been following major news events lately,
here's the story.
</P>
<P>
   Doug and Ellen Henry bought a home in what I take to be a
subdivision. Hoping to spruce up their front yard, which likely had
been left bare of trees by greedy developers, they paid $15 each
for a pair of pink flamingos.
</P>
<P>
   They described the colorful birds as ``lawn decoration.'' Their
neighbors, certainly not Southern-born, thought the colorful birds
were tacky eyesores.
</P>
<P>
   The Towne Park Homeowners Association, although not mentioned in
the U.S. Constitution or appointed by Gov. Roy Barnes, has a lot of
power. It started fining the Henrys $25 a day for every day the
flamingos stayed on their lawn. Pretty soon, according to news
reports, they owed $3,400 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   I don't blame the Henrys for being angry, although they brought
a lot of their trouble on themselves by their lack of judgment. I
would never join a homeowners association, or any other association
that spelled ``town'' with an ``e.'' Being a born and bred
Southsider, I would immediately sniff a dose of ersatz elitism.
</P>
<P>
   The Henrys got their fines reduced to $1,100, but they had
enough of Towne folks. They moved, taking the flamingos along. When
a new baby boy arrived, their neighbors, instead of complaining
about tacky yard decorations, draped blue ribbon over the birds.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy the Henrys are happy, but I wish they had moved to my
county, just to see if we still have our values intact. Lately we
tend to get a little highhanded ourselves about who can put what
where. We should not throw rocks at people who have special
prejudices. We have our own. Being as David wears no pants, my
hometown certainly wouldn't permit Michelangelo's statue of him on
the courthouse lawn, or anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brooks is a longtime county resident, proprietor of the
highly respected Whitewater Country Club, a generous contributor to
civic causes. He also is a good-old-boy graduate of Clemson
University who eats breakfast at the Waffle House.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bob wanted to open one of his Hooters restaurants, a
crowd of protesters showed up at a downtown rally. Something about
waitresses wearing skirts so short they could be cheerleaders for
the high school football team.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters is out, but I think pink flamingos are OK. I'm no
lawyer, but my lay opinion is that while plastic varieties might
not be constitutional in some parts south they are perfectly legal
in other parts of the county _ at least until the commissioners
meet again.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, flamingos would be fine if they were made of terra
cotta and cost more than $15.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic flamingos at $15 would be well received in the
semi-rural part of the county where we live. We aren't many years
away from old automobile tires painted white with tulip beds
inside. Rocks washed with white mud dug out of creek banks made
fine borders for whatever flowers our grandmothers had blooming.
</P>
<P>
   We decorated a lot in the old days. Even a sophisticated city
like Fayetteville boasted streets with oak trees painted white
three-quarters of the way up the trunk. I remember going to town
with my daddy on Saturday afternoons and wishing we lived in a big
city with white-tailed oak trees like Fayetteville.
</P>
<P>
   We haven't gone back to whitewashed automobile tires, but pink
flamingos for decorative purposes have been in resurgence for some
time. They often are rented for festive occasions like weddings and
birthday parties. They are especially popular for birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   Since he is in New York on temporary duty and won't read this, I
can confide that we are planning to help our semi-city son
celebrate his 40th by placing several rent-a-birds on his front
lawn. His boss in Atlanta has been invited down to dinner and we're
sure he wants to make a good impression.
</P>
<P>
   I hope we come out better than well-meaning friends of Bobby
Mobley, my fellow traveler to the Australian Outback and other
exotic vacation spots most Americans visit only when ordered to go
in time of war.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark of night, when Bobby was about to celebrate a
significant birthday, Carolyn Croft and other devoted friends
placed 60 rented pink flamingos in his front yard.
</P>
<P>
   When Bobby woke up, he loaded the flamingos into his pickup
truck and headed for Alabama, where such yard decorations sell for
a premium. I understand he wrote nice notes, thanking his friends
for their thoughtful birthday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
