<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0812-C     08-11 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reformers in desperate need of Ross Perot now more than ever
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ ``Unless we take action now, our nation may
confront a situation similar to the Great Depression _ and maybe
even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential candidate who made this frightening prediction
is lying low.
</P>
<P>
   His political party, however, currently has a high profile. It
is being torn apart from within.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Ross Perot's leadership was not needed to save
America from another Great Depression. But Perot may be needed to
keep his Reform Party from crumbling to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Perot was a surprisingly strong candidate for the
presidency, he told American voters that the nation's economy was
``perched on the edge of a cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Americans, Perot was heading up a ``Straight Talk
Express'' eight years before Sen. John McCain gave that name to the
bus that carried his own maverick presidential campaign message.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans once thought Perot actually had a good chance to
win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   BUTTER OFF BISCUIT
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the campaign was long enough for voters to figure
out that most of the butter had slipped off the Texas billionaire's
biscuit.
</P>
<P>
   Perot received 19 percent of the vote in the 1992 presidential
election even after he unexpectedly quit the race and spouted off
about several conspiracy theories worthy of the aluminum-foil hat
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Perot said was well received.
</P>
<P>
   Perot talked about the need to balance the budget, get out of
debt, kick the lobbyists out of Washington, provide Americans with
quality health care and give American children the best education
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years before McCain used campaign finance reform to
torment his Republican primary opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
Perot called for the elimination of all political action
committees. He supported passage of laws ``eliminating all
possibilities for special interests to give large sums of money to
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain showed that idea remains popular today. Who could doubt
it as Americans continue to watch Republicans and Democrats rake in
mountains of cash from special interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Perot was far ahead of McCain when he called for laws requiring
the return of all excess political campaign funds to the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Perot also sought laws reducing the time for federal election
campaigns, reducing the cost of federal campaigns and creating
equal opportunity for all new candidates by providing equal
television time.
</P>
<P>
   Short campaigns are appealing to Americans who grow weary, bored
or angry with this nation's lengthy political selection process.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Perot may have won the 1992 election had the
campaign process been shortened to only a couple of months. It took
time to discover that this fast-talking quipster with a lot of good
ideas actually was a bit balmy.
</P>
<P>
   Balmy may be fine for entertainers, but not so fine for
commanders in chief.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's appeal, money and organizational skill quickly got him
on the ballot in nearly every state. He showed there are a lot of
Americans frustrated with both major political parties, Washington
gridlock, finger pointing, red ink, political name-calling,
bureaucracy and neglect of important domestic issues.
</P>
<P>
   By virtue of Perot's success, his Reform Party now qualifies for
more than $12 million, which is being fought over by two Reform
Party factions.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan, who must be the famous crazy aunt living in
Perot's basement, is trying to make off with the Reform Party and
millions in federal campaign funds so he can spread his narrow
message of cultural warfare, isolation and division.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Perot looks like a solemn statesman. Where is
Perot when we need him?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
