<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8684 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0812-CO     08-11 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Helping solve a problem is satisfying work
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There are very few things in this line of work more
rewarding than actually being able to help somebody. I hand out
advice in this space every week and almost never know whether it
did anyone any good.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, I received this e-mail from a local woodworker
named Johnny Herron:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am having trouble with something that is supposed to be easy
to do _ a simple jig for a router table to make a circle cut.
Directions call for a piece of 1/4-inch plywood with a small nail
through it, then into my wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'm supposed to slowly turn the blank to cut a circle. My
problem is that I can't seem to keep the nail steady. It gives and
I have a flat spot or router chatter and small nicks in the wood.
How do I keep the nail from moving?
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, in cutting an inside circle, do I need to drill a hole
for the blade to rise through or do I just raise the blade and push
down on the blank. This seems to jerk the wood in the wrong way. I
then have to stop the kickback and go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   We would have gotten it worked out sooner if I had not gotten
hung up on the question about drilling a hole in the workpiece.
</P>
<P>
   My reply:
</P>
<P>
   You don't say what sort of router, or what bit and shank size
you're using, or how thick the workpiece is. However, it sounds as
though you're trying to make the cut in a single pass. A cut of 1/4
inch is the deepest I'd ever consider making with any size router
and a 1/2-inch shank bit. One-eighth inch at a time would be a lot
easier on the machine, the bit and you. If you do it that way,
there should be no need to drill a starter hole.
</P>
<P>
   Further, I don't quite understand how this jig works. How small
is the nail? I wouldn't use a very small nail for this. I can't
hold nail sizes in my head, so I can't be exact, but I'd use a nail
with a shank about 1/8-inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Herron replied that his was a small router running a 1/4-inch
shank, but that he knew well enough to take the cut in small
increments. The project, he said, came from a very popular magzine
devoted entirely to projects, but only specified a ``small nail.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there appeared to be nothing wrong with my correspondent's
technique, then the problem had to lie with the jig. It is very
surprising that the project plans did not specify a size for the
nail; after all, ``small'' depends on who is making the definition.
</P>
<P>
   I replied:
</P>
<P>
   I'd say the problem lies primarily with the small nail. The
smaller the nail, the more likely it is to begin wiggling; the more
it wiggles, the more it enlarges the hole in the plywood, and
everything gets worse exponentially. From your description of the
project, a bigger nail isn't going to deface anything.
</P>
<P>
   Herron took the suggestion to the next level, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reading your response about using a larger nail I
thought about it and came up with using a short piece of dowel for
the pivot point. Since the middle would be scrap, I drilled a
5/16-inch hole to match a piece of scrap dowel. I cut it to 1
1/4-inch long and epoxyed it to the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``WORKS WELL!!''
</P>
<P>
   Upon reflection, this was a very wise move. Even a stout nail
might be subject to vibration and movement when held in something
as thin as 1/4-inch ply.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
