<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8690 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GENOME-SALES-NEWHOUSE     08-11 1784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-SALES-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETIC MAP LEADS WAY TO COMMERCIAL TREASURE
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, AUGUST 10, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With a graphic showing map and impact of the Big Burn, and
four photos, of Forest Service archeologist Cort Sims and tanker
plane (NNS1), smoke jumpers bording a transport plane (NNS2),
wildfire blazes in Montana (NNS3) and timberman Bill Mulligan
(NNS4) 
 By JOHN MANGELS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) As unlikely as it may seem, genetics researchers and
young Harry Potter fans share a dilemma when it comes to satisfying
their interests.
</P>
<P>
   Mad-about-Harry readers itching for the new Potter book ``The
Goblet of Fire'' can peruse it for free at the public library but
may have to wait months for a copy to become available. Or they can
get the 734-page tome immediately by forking over $25.95 at the
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, scientists who want to pore over the just-completed
map of all human genetic material can wait until the government's
Human Genome Project is made available at no cost on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can pay thousands of dollars to get it from the maverick
Rockville, Md., biotech firm Celera Genomics.
</P>
<P>
   Many academic researchers had criticized Celera for its plans to
restrict access to the genetic blueprint for life that is present
in all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, they are beginning to sign on with the company,
wooed by its ability to analyze and display the massive amounts of
data rapidly or worried that without immediate access, they'll lose
an advantage to competing researchers. In some cases, scientists
will be paying for repackaged genetic information their own labs
helped compile.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State University and the University of Cincinnati reached
agreements with Celera two weeks ago, paying $150,000 apiece for a
three-year subscription to the company's computer database. Each
university signed up 10 researchers at an individual subscription
cost of $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and Vanderbilt universities and Texas' state colleges
have signed up, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celera has made itself almost the sole supplier of information
that everyone else wants,'' said Thomas H. Murray, president of the
Hastings Center, which studies ethical issues in medicine and
society. ``It's a very clever plan.''
</P>
<P>
   If a certain similarity to Microsoft comes to mind -- an
arrogantly brilliant business plan, scorched-earth market tactics,
a Fort Knox-sized budget and the ability to trump competitors by
bettering their original idea -- Celera wouldn't discourage it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to become the definitive portal'' for genetics
information, said Daniel Clutter, a Celera regional account
manager. ``No matter what the Human Genome Project does, we'll be a
year or two ahead of them. They're so far behind, it's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   To a nonscientist, the material at the heart of this dust-up
doesn't look like much to fight over. Accessed by computer, it's a
bewildering mix of jargon -- ``blasts,'' ``contigs,'' ``snips'' --
and screenfuls of the same four abbreviated chemical letters, A, C,
T and G, repeated in endless, eye-glazing columns: gatctcggct
cactgcaacc tctgcctcct ...
</P>
<P>
   What it represents, though, is a coming revolution in the
diagnosis and treatment of disease, the formulation of personally
tailored drugs and the understanding of how a dizzying array of
life forms evolved on Earth. The secrets are in our genes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, a group of government and academic scientists led by
the National Institutes of Health began the biological equivalent
of the moon-landing program. They started trying to decipher the
makeup of the genetic material that carries instructions for
assembling and operating all living creatures, from simple bacteria
to human beings.
</P>
<P>
   For the next eight years, the Human Genome Project moved at a
methodical pace, aiming to finish in 2005 and make its findings
available to anyone who wanted them. The researchers picked a
slow-but-sure technique for teasing out the secrets locked inside
the twisted coils of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one of their own had rebelled. J. Craig Venter, an
NIH scientist who had developed a much faster but less thorough way
of decoding DNA, became frustrated with the Human Genome Project's
gene-mining.
</P>
<P>
   He started a for-profit company, Celera (a form of the Latin
word for ``quick''), intending to beat the Human Genome Project at
its own game. With tens of millions of dollars in investment money
and the most powerful computers available, Celera would use its
shortcut approach to crack the human genetic code within three
years, Venter declared at the company's 1998 launch.
</P>
<P>
   Many scientists fretted about the potential for Celera to horde
the treasures it might unearth in human DNA, either by patenting
unique genes linked to disease or behavior or by restricting access
to the entire decoded genetic sequence. The Human Genome Project
ramped up its effort and moved up its timetable to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides declared a tie in June when they simultaneously
announced completion of a ``rough draft'' of the full complement of
human genetic material. But the information is in fragments that
still have to be assembled, checked for errors and sorted to
determine which portions of DNA are nonfunctioning ``junk'' and
which are genes.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project has finished 22 percent of that final
draft and says it will be done by 2003. Celera claims it will have
the completed human sequence available for its paying customers
this fall, as well as details about gene products and genetic
variations between people. Later, the company intends to add the
decoded genetic blueprint for mice, rats, cats, dogs and other
higher animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're paying for a time advantage. You're paying for what you
could get for free in a year or two,'' said Gerald M. Rubin, vice
president for biomedical research at the Howard Hughes Medical
Institute, a major nonprofit medical research organization.
``People have to make a decision whether it's worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, some scientists and the company itself contend,
the product Celera is selling isn't much different from a
subscription to a stock market service that provides almost
immediate access to trading results and prepares market information
suited to a customer's interests.
</P>
<P>
   But Celera likely wouldn't have had a database to sell -- at
least not as quickly -- without using information from the
taxpayer-funded $300 million Human Genome Project to fill the gaps
caused by its shortcut decoding method. So, in essence, academic
researchers are paying for an encyclopedia containing chapters
they've written, although Celera has assembled the material and
devised ways of searching and analyzing it.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting issue,'' said Richard P. Lifton, chairman
of the genetics department at Yale University School of Medicine
and an adviser to the Human Genome Project. ``There certainly are
scientists who will say, `Over my dead body' -- it would be
anathema to subscribe. My personal perception is that Celera has
every right to package the data and try to sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifton, however, said that as an individual scientist, he
``would see it as a sign of disloyalty to sign with Celera.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My dean would say $50,000 is a small price to pay if you can
get a million-dollar grant from it,'' said Huntington F. Willard,
chairman of Case Western Reserve University Medical School's
genetics department and director of University Hospitals' Research
Institute in Cleveland. CWRU is considering signing up with Celera.
``If there's value added -- and that's a big `if' at this point --
I have no objection to taking sequence information from my lab,
turning around and paying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``value-added'' part is a sore point with some academic
scientists. Much of what they're being asked to buy, using scarce
research dollars -- the human and mouse blueprints, the specifics
of genetic variation -- isn't ready yet. There's no pre-purchase
test drive of the data, but Celera isn't shy about reminding
potential customers of the consequences of not signing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research is a competitive business,'' said the company's
Clutter, a biochemist turned salesman. ``There's limited grant
money out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have a legitimate fear that they'll be left behind,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of Celera's pitch is intrinsically clever -- fear of the
unknown,'' Lifton said. ``You won't know what's in it until you buy
it. (But) gosh, all of your competitors will be light-years ahead
because they have access.''
</P>
<P>
   In a mix of altruism and savvy advertising, Celera partnered
with academic researchers in March to decode and make available
without charge the genetic blueprint of the fruit fly. It was a
valuable contribution to science because of the fly's genetic
similarity to humans. It also boosted Celera's credibility and
whetted appetites by proving its shortcut approach works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a bad marketing technique,'' Clutter said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   The company eventually will provide free access to the ``raw,''
unanalyzed human genetic blueprint but probably never will give
away more specialized data, Clutter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a business aspect,'' he said. ``We do have to make a
profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some researchers can accept paying for Celera's
information, they worry about the effect it might have on the
publicly funded gene-mapping effort. The Human Genome Project
intends to do much of the same analysis as Celera. It doesn't
object to commercial firms repackaging the genetic information but
wants to ensure the data is freely available, said project
spokeswoman Cathy Yarbrough.
</P>
<P>
   But if Congress, the project's ultimate financial overseer,
decides that duplication is unnecessary -- that genetic information
already is available, albeit at a price -- will it scale back or
shut down the project?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unfortunate if the government pulled the plug on
the public effort,'' said Dr. Sanford Markowitz, a CWRU cancer
genetics researcher and Howard Hughes Medical Institute scientist.
``You want this to be available to the assistant professor just
starting a lab and to whom $15,000 (for a Celera subscription) is
not a doable number.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
