<P>
   Arm your readers with the latest thinking and best ideas for
creating, leading and transforming business.
</P>
<P>
   That's possible through the new affiliation of Harvard Business
School Publishing with The New York Times Syndicate. HBSP is the
publishing arm of the world leader in business and management
education.
</P>
<P>
   Building on nearly 80 years of tradition, HBSP provides
authoritative, researched-backed insights into how to manage
today's business _ and tomorrow's.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are the articles that make up this week's
transmission of HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, the first of two news
services that will carry content from Harvard Business School
Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The other service will follow in the coming months, so watch
your news wire for information. In addition, stories from HBSP
publications will be offered on a ``separate-buy'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers to HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING will receive two
articles per week, edited for length, from HBSP's three
newsletters: Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
</P>
<P>
   The following articles have been sent to the ``f'' (financial)
category code. Take a look.
</P>
<P>
   ASSERTING YOURSELF: HOW TO SAY `NO' AND MEAN IT
</P>
<P>
   BC-JUST-SAY-NO-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF _ Are you
uncomfortable when you have to assert yourself in a tricky
emotional situation? Do you sometimes say ``yes'' when you mean
``no'' to avoid an ugly confrontation in the workplace? Many people
find it difficult to be assertive in one-on-one or group
situations. Here are some steps experts recommend to become more
assertive _ from developing an action plan to sticking to standing
your ground when others don't like your answer. 800 words.
Excerpted from the Harvard Management Communication Letter.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW USES OF INTRANETS
</P>
<P>
   BC-USES-OF-INTRANET-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF _ Y2K has
come and gone, and corporate information technology departments are
turning their attention to that perennial technological stepchild,
the intranet. Their findings? A company's internal Web site can be
a powerful tool for sharing and managing information of all sorts.
The most efficient intranet systems help to not only keep people in
touch, but also automate routine tasks, provide easy access to
information, cut overhead costs and much more. 800 words. Excerpted
from Harvard Management Update.
</P>
