<HEADER>
A8714 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-JUST-SAY-NO-HARVARD-B     08-11 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUST-SAY-NO-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSERTING YOURSELF: HOW TO SAY `NO' AND MEAN IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: THE HARVARD MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION LETTER  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Are you uncomfortable when you have to assert yourself in a
tricky emotional situation? Do you sometimes say ``yes'' when you
mean ``no'' to avoid an ugly confrontation in the workplace?
</P>
<P>
   Many executives find it difficult to be assertive in one-on-one
or group situations. Instead, they'll ignore the poor performance
of a senior staff member, say ``yes'' to an impractical team
decision and even do their own clerical work rather than delegate
it to a hot-tempered assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some steps experts recommend to become more assertive:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMIT TO CHANGING YOUR BEHAVIOR. &LR;  If you think you have a
problem, don't just promise yourself you'll try to change; do
something about it, says Mildred 0. Saunders of Milsaun &AMP; Co., a
New York-based management consulting firm. Otherwise, it's no
different from saying you'll go on a diet next week while gorging
yourself on a six-course meal.
</P>
<P>
   Judith C. Tingley, president of Performance Improvement Pros in
Phoenix and author of ``Say What You Mean, Get What You Want''
(AMACOM, 1996), suggests you advise your management team about your
plan to change. Letting others know ensures a sincere effort at
change. Besides, it may be wise to let them know what's coming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEARN TO VALUE YOURSELF. &LR;  Do an inventory of your strengths to
rebuild your self-confidence. If you can't turn off the negative
voice in your head, seek out people whose judgment you trust to
give you a more positive assessment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEVELOP AN ACTION PLAN. &LR;  This should not focus on addressing
your weaknesses but on providing you with more opportunities to
shine by playing to your strengths, according to Jeff Davidson, a
conference and convention speaker based in Chapel Hill, N.C. The
purpose is to create a foundation on which you can build feelings
of assurance, competency and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't shine, say, when you're discussing a problem in a
large crowd, you can work on that from now until the end of your
days yet never feel totally at ease,'' he says. ``If you're more
effective on a one-to-one or small-group basis, create those
circumstances to deal with awkward or unpleasant communications.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS ON THE BUSINESS IMPLICATIONS OF YOUR ANSWER. &LR;  Don't fill
your mind with thoughts that have nothing to do with the decision,
like fears of retaliation and rejection. You can't please everyone,
and sometimes making the right decision won't please anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The higher you move in an organization, the more isolated you
may feel. ``But senior managers need to remember that saying 'yes'
won't end that isolation,'' Tingley says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SAY `NO' IF IT'S THE BETTER ANSWER. &LR;  Follow your response with
a single explanation. Multiple reasons, a longwinded explanation or
the word ``no'' followed by an apology can weaken the response and
encourage a plea for a change of mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T GET PRESSURED INTO SAYING `YES.' &LR;  If you are asked for an
immediate reply but you don't have enough information to make a
``yes'' or ``no'' decision, say ``no.'' Later, if you decide that
``yes'' is a more suitable reply, it will be better accepted than
if you say ``no'' after having said ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T ALWAYS WAIT TO BE ASKED SOMETHING TO SAY `NO.' &LR;  Take the
initiative if you sense a request coming. Phrase your ``no'' as a
directive or observation. This way you increase the likelihood that
work will be done to your specifications without creating
disappointment or ill will, Tingley says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T LET SOMEONE PUSH YOU INTO CHANGING YOUR MESSAGE. &LR;  When a
``no'' with a single explanation isn't enough, use what Tingley
calls the ``broken record'' technique by repeating your response.
In short, the person is trying to wear you down. Worst-case
scenario: the other person will be disappointed or angry with you,
Tingley says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REHEARSE DIFFICULT CONVERSATIONS. &LR;  For instance, if you have
avoided discussing an employee's poor performance, open the
conversation by admitting your failure, then assertively set the
agenda: to agree to a timetable for performance improvement.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the script, Saunders says, anticipate how you will
respond to a variety of reactions, from put-offs to ``poor me'' sob
stories. Have crib notes with you if you are worried that you might
forget some key point when caught up in the emotion of the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BE CONSCIOUS OF YOUR BODY LANGUAGE. &LR;  Eliminate nonassertive
behaviors, such as looking away from the person, covering your
mouth or wetting your lips. Also, consider voice pitch and speed.
For example, if you're too loud, you may sound angry; speak too
quickly, and you may seem impatient.
</P>
<P>
   A passive stance or timid voice may encourage a more aggressive
reaction from the other party, thereby putting greater pressure on
you.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be passive, or nonassertive, to be uneasy
delivering bad news or rejecting someone's idea or request. Both
the stress in today's organizations and movement toward a more
collaborative workforce make it harder, as a leader, to stand apart
from the group and say ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognize that others have the right to ask, but you have the
responsibility to say, `No,''' Tingley says.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on HARVARD
BUSINESS PUBLISHING and other features. &QL;
</P>
