r f BC-USES-OF-INTRANET-HARV     08-11 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USES-OF-INTRANET-HARVARD-BUSINESS-PUBLISHING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW USES OF INTRANETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For immediate release.)  
 &HT;    
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: The following story is for use by clients of
HARVARD BUSINESS PUBLISHING, a new service from The New York Times
Syndicate that is composed of two articles per week _ edited for
length _ from the Harvard Management Update newsletter, Harvard
Management Communication Letter and Balanced Scorecard Report.
These articles will guide your readers to the ideas, trends and
solutions that are changing the business world _ and are a perfect
fit for your business section.) 
 &HT;    
 (For information about purchasing this article as a
``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a client of HARVARD BUSINESS
PUBLISHING _ contact one of the New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 &HT;    
 FROM: HARVARD MANAGEMENT UPDATE  
 c.2000 Harvard Business School Publishing  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Y2K has come and gone, and corporate information technology
departments are turning their attention to that perennial
technological stepchild, the intranet. Their findings? A company's
internal Web site can be a powerful tool for sharing and managing
information of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intranet is the communications platform for group work _
the `electronic brain' that employees tap into,'' says Steve
McCormick, a consultant with Watson Wyatt Worldwide's Washington,
D.C., office.
</P>
<P>
   What's new here isn't groupware, which Lotus Notes broke ground
on a decade ago. The novelty is putting everything on the same
Web-based system.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some examples of well-designed intranets at major
companies and the features that make them special.
</P>
<P>
   KEEP PEOPLE IN TOUCH
</P>
<P>
   At MadeToOrder.com, a Redwood City, Calif.-based seller of
corporate logo apparel, the intranet is the key to efficient
functioning of the company's newly created _ and widely distributed
_ work force.
</P>
<P>
   The intranet allows ``remote employees to feel part of the
company,'' says Weston Rose, president and CEO of MadeToOrder.com.
</P>
<P>
   Intranets hardly remove the need for face-to-face interaction,
but _ paradoxically _ they can improve on-site gatherings. ``The
meetings you do have are more meaningful,'' Rose says. ``You don't
have to spend a lot of time catching up.''
</P>
<P>
   A favorite intranet site of J.C. Penney managers is the
company's Knowledge Management System. After signing in, each
manager views a desktop customized by his or her function and
level. The desktops contain training programs and management tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't publish or mail training materials any longer,'' says
Deborah Masten, director of human resources communications and
development at J.C. Penney's corporate headquarters in Plano,
Texas. That's a huge savings for a far-flung retailer that hires
between 400 and 700 management trainees a year.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful feature: asynchronous discussion. J.C. Penney
managers can ask questions of their peer group, and other managers
can answer when they log in.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMATE ROUTINE TASKS
</P>
<P>
   ``At Microsoft, we're doing everything on the intranet,'' says
Mary Lee Kennedy, director of information services at the software
company's headquarters in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's intranet contains about 1,000 sites, more than 2
million pages and dozens of applications and functionalities. Every
day, roughly a third of the company's 30,000 employees log on to
MSWeb, the most general-purpose site.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite: MSMarket, an intranet where employees can buy
office supplies and book travel tickets. The site is a time-saver
for employees and a purchasing department's dream, seamlessly
integrating vendors.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDE EASY ACCESS TO INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, managers at Kraft Foods saw a need to coordinate
Web usage among different divisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the groups were developing Web pages at the same time. We
wanted to make sure that not all of them were reinventing the
wheel,'' recalls Karen Isaacson, director of human resources
information and technology at the company's Northfield, Ill.,
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft set up an intranet committee composed of representatives
from corporate affairs, human resources, legal and IT. The result:
the Kraft Intranet Cafe, a striking Web site that is the default
home page for every Kraft employee. The cafe provides access to the
rest of the company's intranet sites, such as HR Online.
</P>
<P>
   CUT OVERHEAD COSTS
</P>
<P>
   Veritas, a storage-management software maker based in Mountain
View, Calif., uses the intranet to reduce administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we in HR are overhead. We have to think of
ways of doing things better and reducing the percentage of overall
costs that HR accounts for,'' says Elizabeth Grover, vice president
of human resources.
</P>
<P>
   She began by putting basic HR information on the intranet, then
added a Web application that managers use to figure merit raises.
The intranet version of the merit calculations contains several
improvements over the spreadsheets Grover formerly sent to
managers, and at the same time streamlines HR's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANIZE _ AND COMMUNICATE _ DATA
</P>
<P>
   For many industries, the need to manage data goes beyond a
nicety. Intranets linked to several databases can organize the
voluminous material.
</P>
<P>
   For example, J.C. Penney managers can look at sales reports
through the company's Infovision intranet site and can share
information (such as reports on slow sellers) with peer groups
through the Knowledge Management System.
</P>
<P>
   WIN-WIN MARKETING
</P>
<P>
   MadeToOrder.com creates intranet sites for its clients free of
charge, allowing the clients' employees to order corporate-logo
shirts, hats and more with a few clicks.
</P>
<P>
   MadeToOrder gets the orders; clients get control over the use of
their logo, which for many companies is a nagging problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a service that most corporations spend millions of
dollars on,'' says Rose, the CEO. Several clients, including
Symantec and the national YMCA organization, use the service.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
