<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-MANAGEMENT (San Francisco) _ Martha Steffens and Robert
McCray, the editor and general manager who have been hired to take
over the San Francisco Examiner under its new ownership, believe
they have some innovative answers. The two executives, whose
appointments were announced this week, will be key leaders in the
remaking of The Examiner under local publisher Ted Fang. By ERIN
McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOMOZA-RESTAURANT (San Antonio) _ In another investment that
signals this city's downtown revival, descendants of the Somoza
family that ruled Nicaragua for more than 40 years plan to open a
restaurant next summer. By DAVID HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-CHEVY-IMPALA (Undated) _ The Impala is back. Well, sort of.
Chevrolet reintroduced the Impala nameplate for model year 2000 in
a
</P>
<P>
   modified and extended version of the midsize Lumina sedan that
is roomy
</P>
<P>
   enough to be classified as a full-size car by EPA standards. But
the new Impala isn't anything like its predecessors. By CHAMBERS
WILLIAMS III
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-PONTIAC-AZTEK (undated) _ Some love it, some hate it. But
General Motors is betting that those who love the design of the new
Pontiac Aztek will make the car a hit, something that GM really
needs after going out on a limb to build a vehicle that some
critics have called
</P>
<P>
   ``just plain ugly.'' By CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-MAZDA-SUV (undated) _ Mazda, a longtime holdout, joins the
SUV ranks with the Tribute, a compact with an attitude. The Tribute
has some heady competition, however. And it's not just from Mazda's
usual Japanese competitors, Toyota and Honda, both of whom have
small sport-utilities, the Toyota RAV4 and the Honda CR-V, already
well
</P>
<P>
   entrenched in the U.S. marketplace. By CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-HOUSE (San Francisco) _ It is the oldest house in San
Francisco and it sits on top of what is arguably this city's most
expensive three-car garage. It was originally built in 1853 with
subsequent additions designed by architect Willis Polk at the turn
of the last century. The
</P>
<P>
   painstakingly restored home will go on sale next week. The
asking price is $4,995,000. By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-LATIFAH (Undated) _ Changes are ahead for ``Queen Latifah.''
Big Brother kind of changes. ``We're going to stay current, stay
with the times,'' says Latifah, who is barnstorming the country to
promote her talk show's second season. ``We're going to try some
experiments this time around with some reality-based TV, in the
`Big Brother,' Survivor' sort of sense.'' By MIKE MCDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CHILD (Undated) _ The most entertaining thing about ``Bless
the Child'' is that Satan's last stand takes place in a creepy
mansion off Route 17 ``just outside Albany.'' It's a rare and
unintentionally hilarious moment in an otherwise hollow and
familiar film. Never mind that the real Route 17 is closer to New
York City than the Capital Region. Bad geography is the least of
this film's problems. By KRIS WORRELL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REPLACEMENTS (Undated) _ The fear of being tagged stupid
has gone to Keanu Reeves' head. ``The Replacements'' has him
playing the smartest guy in the locker room - and the distinction
is the only nuance in the film. The way-mellow one has surrounded
himself with the dumbest people ever assembled for a sports movie.
Reeves plays quarterback to the police-lineup of stereotypes and
grotesques who've been hired to play football in the midst of a
midseason players' walkout. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FUNCTIONAL-FOOD (Undated) _ This is the breakfast of the near
future: Everything is good for you, even food that used to be bad.
You treat your high cholesterol with a bagel and cream cheese. The
cream cheese lowers your cholesterol, thanks to an ingredient from
pine trees. Wash down the bagel with juice. The juice lowers
cholesterol, too, and it has an ingredient to prevent deteriorating
eyesight. It doesn't have any parts from a pine tree in it, just
soybean extracts. Welcome to the world of functional foods, where
groceries and pharmaceuticals meet. By SCOTT SIMONSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: FUNCTIONAL-SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (Indianapolis) _ Jenny Thompson has marbled arms, a
back of steel and, judging by a new photo in Sports Illustrated,
abs made of hard metal, too. This is a strong woman. She's headed
for medical school at Columbia University in another year, and
headed to Sydney for her third Olympic Games next month. By GWEN
KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-AURILIA (New York) _ Rich Aurilia doesn't hide the fact he'd
welcome playing in New York one day. It was his childhood dream to
be a Met, to play baseball at Shea Stadium, to catch a subway to
work, to play before friends and family and all the crazies in
Gotham. He still thinks about doing that. Just not yet. Not now. By
JOHN SHEA.
</P>
