<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LATIFAH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEEN LATIFAH PRACTICES TV SURVIVAL SKILLS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Changes are ahead for ``Queen Latifah.'' ``Big Brother'' kind of
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to stay current, stay with the times,'' said
Latifah, who is barnstorming the country to promote her talk show's
second season. ``We're going to try some experiments this time
around with some reality-based TV, in the `Big Brother,' `Survivor'
sort of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the show to sometimes devote one or more of its
segments to video of an ongoing or upcoming story _ using footage
obtained from wiring houses with microphones and cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have an issue, we'll go in and wire a person's house for
a period of time, just let them be in their own environment and let
them go about life as they ordinarily go about it,'' Latifah said.
``We'll check up on them maybe once or twice a week, and until the
time comes when it's time for them to come to the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say it's spanking the kids _ should you or not _ and some guy
says, `Oh, I spank my kid all the time.' Well, we want to see it.
We want to see how you do behave with your son or daughter. And
that gives us a better base from which to speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Latifah is an unabashed admirer of reality programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like `Survivor.' I haven't really watched `Big Brother.' I
watch `The Real World.' This is kind of a `Real World' thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those who watches `World's Scariest Police
Chases,''' she said. ``I'm fascinated by stuff like that. I watch
`Trauma: Life in the ER.' I watch Discovery and TLC all day. I like
to learn about other things. Human behavior is very interesting
because it's never what you expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're going to try this and see what happens. I mean, we're
still a talk show. We're not a `Big Brother.' So we'll only use it
in the way we feel is necessary for the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which begins a new season Sept. 11, also will adopt a
documentary style from time to time. But Latifah plans to keep it
as fun, irreverent and dotted with celebrities as ever.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, ``Queen Latifah'' could indeed be classified as a
``Survivor'' type of show. Though only a marginal success in the
ratings in its first year, it's around for another season _ a fate
such shows as ``Roseanne,'' ``The Martin Short Show'' and ``Later
Today'' cannot claim.
</P>
<P>
   Latifah, 30, has been reaping headlines for her work. Most
famously, she stood firmly by an overweight girl who dropped out of
school after being mercilessly teased. She offered the student
suggestions on dieting and food preparation, and told her she would
escort her back to school when she was ready to go back. And she
did.
</P>
<P>
   Another show was devoted to a black Houston woman who treated
her two dark-skinned daughters like Cinderella, while a lighter
daughter was treated like a queen. Latifah urged the woman to seek
counseling, and out of that she learned that the woman had been
treated the same way growing up; the woman's lighter-skinned
brother could do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Her shows have helped get girls out of gangs, and prostitutes
and drug addicts off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself a regular person with an extraordinary
job,'' Latifah said.
</P>
<P>
   She can call herself a regular person, but not many people can
match her versatility. She's made a name for herself in films
(``Set It Off,'' ``The Bone Collector''), TV series (``Living
Single'') and TV movies (``Mama Flora's Family,'' the upcoming
miniseries ``The O.Z.'').
</P>
<P>
   Her greatest love, she said, is music. Her latest rap album,
tentatively titled ``Elevation,'' will be released in November _
and she's proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tight,'' she said. ``All the beats are hot, all the words
are hot, the hooks. It's real melodic.''
</P>
<P>
   She hopes to tour with that next spring.
</P>
<P>
   And she's still got her eyes peeled for any TV or movie projects
that might come along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born to perform,'' said the Newark, N.J., native, born
Dana Elaine Owens. ``I watched a lot of TV as a kid and was just
fascinated by it. I would get in the mirror sometimes and make up
these dramatic stories, and my imagination would go so far with it,
I would make myself cry. I'd do it just to see if I could do it. I
was always into it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
