<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FUNCTIONALFOOD-HNS &LR;      08-11 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNCTIONALFOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS HOPE BUILDING A BETTER BUTTER WILL IMPROVE HEART
HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (With optional trims, photo and functional-sidebar) 
By SCOTT SIMONSON &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the breakfast of the near future: Everything is good for
you, even food that used to be bad. You treat your high cholesterol
with a bagel and cream cheese. The cream cheese lowers your
cholesterol, thanks to an ingredient from pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   Wash down the bagel with juice. The juice lowers cholesterol,
too, and it has an ingredient to prevent deteriorating eyesight. It
doesn't have any parts from a pine tree in it, just soybean
extracts. Finish with yogurt that helps control ulcers and a bowl
of cereal that contains weight-loss supplements.
</P>
<P>
   With the cereal, have some milk. There's nothing special about
the milk _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the world of functional foods, where groceries and
pharmaceuticals meet. Instead of taking a pill with your meal, the
pill can be (begin ital) in (end ital) the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Functional food is regular food that has been engineered to
address health problems. Functional food used to mean breakfast
cereal fortified with vitamins and minerals. Now, that same cereal
might contain ingredients that help people lower cholesterol or
lose weight. These products can be found in Europe, and they're
starting to appear here.
</P>
<P>
   Functional foods arrive as a growing number of consumers are
practicing what food trends expert Elizabeth Sloan calls ``self
care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are actively treating themselves first before seeking
medical help,'' said Sloan, whose Florida marketing and consulting
firm, Sloan Trends &AMP; Solutions, Inc., tracks what's new in food,
pharmaceuticals and supplements. ``There's a backlash, and people
are trying to avoid prescription drugs or the over-the-counter
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan put it another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't seem to be a society that likes a lot of pills,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And functional foods are supposed to taste better than pills.
Viactiv ``candy'' delivers the same benefits as calcium tablets.
One chocolate or mochachino candy chew provides half of the
recommended daily intake of calcium.
</P>
<P>
   At the Institute for Preventative Medicine at Houston's
Methodist Hospital, medical director Dr. Peter H. Jones recommends
that patients use margarine substitutes and salad dressings that
actually reduce cholesterol. The brands are Benecol (made by
Johnson &AMP; Johnson) and Take Control (made by Lipton). Both can be
found in grocery stores here.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (begin optional trim) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jones not only recommends Benecol products, he's a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salad dressing clearly tastes better than the no-fat
alternatives, and the Benecol margarine tastes great as well,''
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (end optional trim) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Using these products regularly can lower LDL cholesterol (the
bad cholesterol) by 10 percent to 15 percent, ``which is pretty
good, considering it's a natural substance,'' said Jones, a
physician and associate professor at Baylor College of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The key ingredient in Benecol is an extract from pine trees. In
Take Control, it comes from soybeans. Scientific evidence indicates
that Benecol and Take Control work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those contain ingredients that have been tested for 40 or 50
years,'' said David Schardt, associate nutritionist for the Center
for Science in the Public Interest. ``There's a lot of research in
them. They may be beneficial for people, depending on their
(health) situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and colleagues at Baylor conducted a study in 1998 and
1999 that found a 12-percent reduction in participants' LDL
cholesterol levels after using Benecol spread instead of corn-oil
margarine. All of the subjects had high cholesterol levels but no
other health problems and adhered to a low-fat diet.
</P>
<P>
   As margarine substitutes, Benecol and Take Control seem to pass
the taste test, but two problems are hard to miss.
</P>
<P>
   One is price. They cost four to six times more per ounce than
light margarine. Take Control costs as much as $3.99 for 10 ounces.
Benecol costs $4.99 for 8 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The second problem is serving size. To lower cholesterol, a
person must consume at least 2 tablespoons per day _ more than
twice the average amount of margarine an American eats daily,
according to the National Association of Margarine Manufacturers.
And they should spread it out to eat it three times a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the issue a lot of my patients ask is, `Gee whiz, I
don't think I'll do it three times a day, every day,''' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Is the product still worthwhile? ``I think the answer is yes,''
he said. ``Because if you're going to use this instead of butter or
margarine, you're adding something useful and taking away something
detrimental.''
</P>
<P>
   If patients reach for Benecol or Take Control instead of
margarine, Jones said, they'll be eating healthier, even if it's
only once a day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (begin optional trim) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Quan saw his cholesterol level drop from 320 to 260 after
two months of eating Benecol. Quan, a 36-year-old resident of the
Dallas suburb of Rowlett, started eating Benecol as part of a study
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't much of a butter person,'' he said. ``I'm now in the
habit of eating wheat toast every morning. I spread it on there.''
</P>
<P>
   He takes his daily three servings of Benecol on two slices of
wheat toast. Quan, who has used Benecol now for more than a year,
said his cholesterol level now is about 230.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (end optional trim) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some view Benecol more cautiously. Dr. James M. Wilson, a
physician at the Texas Heart Institute, emphasized that Benecol is
a high-fat food _ something he would prefer that his
high-cholesterol patients avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Three servings of Benecol contain 27 grams of fat. That's 42
percent of the recommended daily fat intake in a 2,000-calorie
diet. (Take Control suggests eating two serving per day with a
total of 12 grams of fat.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no long-term data that shows that it makes anybody any
healthier or lowers heart attacks,'' said Wilson, a clinical
researcher and assistant professor with Baylor College of Medicine.
``It is a logical conclusion, but there's no proof. Once it can be
proved, I'll recommend it, but right now, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions also linger about Benecol's marketability. Benecol and
competitor Take Control each started with a common goal: Build a
better butter substitute, and hope the $1.2 billion margarine
market beat a path to their door. The American Heart Association
says that 40 million American adults (roughly 1 in 5) have high
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol and Take Control launched last year with fanfare from
publicity campaigns. Benecol came from Finland, where it reportedly
sold so fast stores couldn't keep it on their shelves.
</P>
<P>
   In their first year in the United States, Benecol and Take
Control accounted for a combined 4.5 percent of total sales of
margarines, spreads and butter blends, according to Information
Resources, Inc., a market research firm. Neither was close to
becoming one of the Top 10-selling brands.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies also introduced cholesterol-lowering salad
dressings. Slow sales have resulted in the dressings being ``phased
out,'' meaning they might still be available in stores, but they
aren't being manufactured any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Benecol snack bars also have been phased out. Benecol cream
cheeses and yogurt, available in England and Ireland, haven't been
introduced here.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the first functional foods to meet resistance.
Kellogg's withdrew its Ensemble line last year because of weak
sales. Ensemble products included breakfast cereals and frozen
entrees, all containing soluble fiber from the grain psyllium,
which also reduces cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   The problem may be that functional foods sound too good to be
true, said Robert L. Heath, professor of communications at the
University of Houston. Heath has researched corporate communication
strategies, including how organizations communicate with the
public.
</P>
<P>
   People are becoming more suspicious of ads for ``healthy''
foods, Heath said, especially since the debate over genetically
modified crops. Opponents of so-called ``Frankenstein foods''
believe that tampering with nature carries dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Heath said, people tend to worry about long-term
side effects and avoid new, unproven products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to be incredibly complicated,'' Heath said.
``It's almost like we're asked to be quasi-medical types and
quasi-pharmacist types. So what do we do? We're very skeptical
about product advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the skepticism is justified, said nutritionist Schardt,
because not all functional foods are backed by years of research.
Messages on product labels also can be suspect. If a label says
``fights heart disease,'' the product's health claim must be
approved by the FDA. If a label says ``maintains a healthy heart,''
no FDA approval is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Bencol and Take Control declined to talk about
future functional-food products from their companies, citing a need
to protect that information from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Food trends researcher Sloan has some guesses. The diet market
is as big as it's ever been, she said, and companies will try to
sell other foods that can lower cholesterol or help people lose
weight.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan predicted the children's market will be big as companies
search for ways to make medicine and nutrition taste better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making lollipops that aid sore throats,'' she said.
``It's happening with fun foods. (Kids) don't want to go out and
eat soy milk; they want something familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan also said that foods will be developed to replace
over-the-counter products. She pointed to Europe, where people can
buy yogurt that does the job of an antacid.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, scientists at the Boyce Thompson Institute
for Plant Research at Cornell University are working on ways to
deliver vaccines by putting them in foods like potatoes and
bananas.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge remains: Does health food have to taste so
healthy? Big companies hope the answer will be no. Instead of a
spoonful of sugar to make the medicine go down, maybe a spoonful of
yogurt contains all the medicine people need.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
