<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PONTIAC-AZTEK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GM HAS HIGH HOPES FOR `UGLY' AZTEK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some love it, some hate it.
</P>
<P>
   But General Motors is betting that those who love the design of
the new Pontiac Aztek will make the car a hit, something that GM
really needs after going out on a limb to build a vehicle that some
critics have called ``just plain ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aztek, which is based on the chassis of the Montana minivan
but looks more like a small wagon or hatchback, is aimed at young
people with active lifestyles who like the great outdoors. Pontiac
calls it a sport-recreation vehicle; the fusion of ``the driving
excitement of a sport sedan, the rugged capability of a
sport-utility vehicle, and the people/cargo flexibility of a van.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Aztek is specifically designed for
outdoor activities, and even comes with an optional camping
package: a tent that attaches to the rear hatch and a mattress that
fits into the cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac unveiled the Aztek at the North American International
Auto Show in Detroit in January with a stage presentation that
included black-clad ninjas rappelling onto the stage from high
above, and a horde of young people oohing and aahing over the cars.
</P>
<P>
   It went on sale in mid-July as a 2001 model, and in some areas,
sales have been steady if not brisk, Pontiac dealers say.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the vehicles were shipped to dealers in Texas and
the Southwest, as well as in California, which are expected to be
among the hottest markets for such a car.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nissan made a big splash with the introduction of the
Xterra sport-utility, also aimed at a 20- or 30-something age group
with active lifestyles, and one of its most popular options was a
first-aid kit built into the rear hatch. The Aztek's built-in
camping gear just seems to take that theme a lot farther, adding
functionality to a vehicle to make it into something different,
something special.
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen had its popular bus camper package in the '70s and
'80s, but the Aztek has better styling and performance for today's
active generation.
</P>
<P>
   The Aztek comes with a 185-horsepower, 3.4-liter V-6 engine and
four-speed automatic transmission. An all-wheel-drive system is
optional.
</P>
<P>
   In fuel economy, Aztek is expected to top practically every
six-cylinder SUV on the market. And its 26 miles per gallon highway
fuel economy equals that of the four-cylinder, 150-horsepower PT
Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Though young people are its target, there are others interested
in the car, dealers say. In Mesa, Ariz., a woman in her 70s bought
an Aztek with the camping package, and even in San Antonio, older
couples with motor homes are looking at the Aztek as a vehicle to
tow, dealers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're selling ours at $500 off sticker,'' said Mike Hennigan,
the sales manager at Gunn Pontiac in San Antonio. He said the
dealership has fixed prices on all of its vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A fully equipped model runs about $25,000, while the base prices
for the Aztek begin at $21,995 plus $550 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   JETTA WAGON DUE EARLY IN 20001
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen will begin selling a wagon version of its popular
Jetta compact in North America in February or March as a 2001
model, and it will be similar in design to the VW Bora Variant
small wagon now on sale in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Jetta wagon will help dealers satisfy customers who need a
more versatile vehicle than a sedan or hatchback. VW doesn't have a
sport-utility or a minivan, which puts dealers at a disadvantage in
today's SUV- and minivan-crazy market. Volkswagen does offer the
larger Passat wagon and the Eurovan, a mid-size, front-engine van.
But prices for the van begin at just over $30,000 and sales have
been sparse. And prices of a fully equipped Passat wagon are near
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Jetta wagon will give consumers a lower-priced alternative.
Jetta sedan prices begin under $17,000. VW says the Jetta wagon
would cost about $500 more than a Jetta sedan, which is the
company's most-popular car in the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO S80 GETS HIGH CRASH RATING
</P>
<P>
   Volvo has modified the air-bag system on its flagship S80 so the
2001 models of the sedan were able to earn the top crash-safety
rating and be designated a ``best pick'' by the Insurance Institute
for Highway Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The institute earlier had dinged the S80 on its safety ratings
because air bags in test vehicles had deployed at speeds of 5 mph
during a simple bumper test, even though the car had done very well
on the higher-speed concrete-barrier crash tests.
</P>
<P>
   Although the institute's safety ratings are primarily based on
the 40-mph barrier test, the ``best pick'' designation was withheld
from the S80 because of the low-speed air-bag deployments. The
institute said deployment of the air bags would cause about $4,000
damage to the vehicle. In addition, there have been reports of
deaths or serious injuries to children or small adults in some cars
that had inadvertent air-bag deployment at low speeds (although not
specifically in the S80).
</P>
<P>
   There also were concerns about the high temperature of the air
bag gas as it escaped near the hands of the dummy in the 40-mph
test. Volvo has redesigned the air-bag system to address those
concerns, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, funded by the auto insurance industry, operates a
state-of-the-art crash-test facility near Charlottesville, Va.
</P>
