<SLUG> BC-AUTO-MAZDA-SUV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAZDA PAYS `TRIBUTE' TO SUV CRAZE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, Mazda officials counted themselves among the
small group of people predicting the impending end of the
sport-utility-vehicle craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SUV is just a fad,'' these people have been saying for the
past couple of years. They insist that the runaway popularity of
sport-utilities soon will be a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   These vehicles, they believe, will return to their former niche
status or even eventually be relegated to the annals of automotive
history along with the big station wagons of the '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, they say, will soon tire of these car-truck hybrids
that now appear in almost every suburban driveway and will again
embrace the traditional family sedan as the most practical choice
for everyday needs.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Mazda had a sport-utility to put on its
dealers' lots.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the Navajo, which was a two-door version of the Ford
Explorer that Mazda sold in the mid-90s, the only truck product the
company has offered is the MPV minivan.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Mazda finally has a sport-utility of its own, the
compact 2001 Tribute.
</P>
<P>
   And with that comes the prediction from Mazda that the SUV is
here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that those most likely to proclaim the impending
doom of the sport-utility are automakers who haven't yet jumped on
the bandwagon, Steve Odell, vice president of marketing and sales
for Mazda North American Operations, said the Tribute and Mazda's
all-new 2000 MPV minivan are expected to fuel a 10 percent annual
increase in Mazda's North American sales over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 48 SUV models on the market now, and there will be
63 within the next couple of years,'' Odell said last week as the
automaker rolled out the Tribute, which goes on sale this month at
U.S. dealerships. ``There is no sign of a slowdown in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tribute has some heady competition, however. And it's not
just from Mazda's usual Japanese competitors, Toyota and Honda _
both of whom have small sport-utilities, the Toyota RAV4 and the
Honda CR-V, already well entrenched in the U.S. marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co., which owns controlling interest in Mazda, has
its own new compact SUV this summer _ the Escape _ and it is a
virtual clone of the Tribute (or vice versa).
</P>
<P>
   The two companies collaborated on the vehicles, which are the
same underneath, but which have slightly different external styling
and different options packages.
</P>
<P>
   And even though the Tributes destined for the U.S. market will
be built on the same assembly line with the Ford Escape in Kansas
City, Mazda is building Tributes in Japan for its home market as
well as for other worldwide markets, including Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, Mazda hopes to differentiate the Tribute from
the Escape _ and other competitors as well _ by focusing on its
unique styling and Mazda's brand image, which emphasizes fun and
sportiness.
</P>
<P>
   The Escape, therefore, is for average folks who want just
another sport-utility, while the Tribute is for people who might
rather have a Miata sports car, but who need the practicality of an
SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Introduction of the Tribute coincides with a new national ad
campaign designed to help Mazda build on that sporty image.
</P>
<P>
   With a recurrent theme using the words ``zoom, zoom,'' Mazda
will attempt to strengthen its position as the sporty, fun import
brand, a continuation of the company's long-running ``Get in, be
moved'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribute could benefit the most from this push, with TV ads
such as one that shows the new SUV in the middle of a pack of Mazda
sports cars, with the question being asked: ``What would happen if
an SUV were raised by a family of sports cars? Zoom, zoom.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``zoom'' theme doesn't signify speed as much as it means a
car that embodies amusement, Odell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the Tribute is a Japanese import, and that's good,'' he
said. ``But it's almost got a twinkle in its eye. It doesn't
conform to other Japanese imports.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazda's own research with consumer focus groups showed that the
Tribute was perceived ``to have a sportier feel in the way it
drives'' than the Escape, Odell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has SUV capability with sophisticated, refined style like
an RX7 or Miata,'' he said. The RX7, which isn't sold in the United
States now, is Mazda's rotary-engine sports car that dates to the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, Tribute is going to appeal to compact-SUV buyers
who want an import rather than a domestic model _ people who still
don't trust U.S. automakers to build quality, dependable products.
Those who don't automatically gravitate toward imports, or who
insist on ``buying American,'' probably will choose the Ford model.
</P>
<P>
   But even up against the Japanese competition, the Tribute should
easily score lots of conquests _ if consumers give it a close
enough look.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from a base of $17,005 for an entry-level
two-wheel-drive DX model with a 2.0-liter four-cylinder engine and
manual transmission to $23,025 for the top-of-the-line ES
four-wheel-drive version with a 3.0-liter V-6 and automatic
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   A fully equipped high-end model will top out at about $25,000.
That's a bargain when compared with high-end models of popular
midsize SUVs such as the Ford Explorer, which can run more than
$36,000.
</P>
<P>
   That puts the Tribute right in the game with the CR-V, RAV4,
Jeep Cherokee, Isuzu Rodeo, Nissan Xterra, Hyundai Santa Fe and
Suzuki Grand Vitara/Chevrolet Tracker.
</P>
<P>
   But the best-selling imports from Honda and Toyota don't even
offer a V-6 option; they come only with four-cylinder engines.
Mazda predicts that 80 percent of its Tribute sales will beV-6
models, because American consumers are hungry for the extra power.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Tribute's engines come from Ford. The four-cylinder
cranks out 130 horsepower and 135 foot-pounds of torque, which is
about par for the mini-SUV class, while the V-6 turns out 200
horsepower and 200 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed manual transmission, available only with the
four-cylinder engine, is made by Mazda, while the four-speed
automatic _ optional with the four cylinder and standard with the
V-6 _ is a Ford product.
</P>
<P>
   That extra power from the V-6, plus the Tribute's ample
dimensions, push it up into the compact class with the Rodeo,
Xterra and Cherokee, rather than the mini-SUV group that includes
the RAV4, Vitara/Tracker, CR-V and the Kia Sportage. (The Vitara
and Tracker are the only ones in that group that have an available
V-6 engine, but their interior dimensions keep them in the mini-SUV
class.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Tribute is six inches longer than the Jeep Cherokee
and has more front and rear leg room than the $35,000-plus Lexus RX
300. It seats five full-size adults in comfort, and a
four-by-eight-foot piece of plywood will fit through the rear
liftglass.
</P>
<P>
   To help maximize interior space, the Tribute's
automatic-transmission shifter is on the steering column instead of
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The engines are transverse mounted to accommodate the Tribute's
normal driving mode, which is front-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   The optional four-wheel-drive system works automatically to send
up to 50 percent of the power to the rear wheels if the front
wheels begin to lose traction. A dash-mounted switch allows the
driver to lock the vehicle into four-wheel drive for special
situations, such as mud, sand or snow driving.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the viscous couplings that most others in this class
have, the Tribute's four-wheel-drive operates from a specially
designed mechanical ``rotary blade'' coupling.
</P>
<P>
   With the V-6 engine and towing package (which includes hitch and
heavy-duty oil cooler), the Tribute can tow trailers of up to 3,500
pounds. That's enough capacity to pull a trailer carrying two
personal watercraft, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda expects to sell at least 35,000 of the Tribute in the
United States annually, not an overly ambitious goal considering
that Honda sells 120,000 CR-Vs, all with just four-cylinder
engines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think our vehicle looks nicer, too,'' said Gary Roudebush,
Mazda's assistant program manager for the Tribute.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
