<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8807 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-CHEVY-IMPALA-HNS     08-11 1366
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CHEVY-IMPALA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ONCE-STAID IMPALA GETS A SPORTIER MAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Impala is back.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet reintroduced the Impala nameplate for model year 2000
in a modified and extended version of the midsize Lumina sedan that
is roomy enough to be classified as a full-size car by EPA
standards.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Impala isn't anything like its predecessors: It's
not a huge boat and it doesn't have rear-wheel drive, a V-8 engine
or a four-on-the-floor transmission.
</P>
<P>
   What it offers is a favorite nameplate from the childhoods of
today's aging baby-boomers, in a modern, front-wheel-drive package
that incorporates engineering features of the best-selling Japanese
sedans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's just about the only formula that makes sense
for today's automotive marketplace, in which Toyota and Honda
sedans rule.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy tried selling big cars well into the '90s with the
Caprice, the upside-down bathtub that, although it was a fine
automobile, was soundly snubbed by boomers. The big Caprices ended
up primarily in police and taxi fleets; the few that were sold to
consumers primarily went to golden-agers who refused to cram
themselves into today's smaller, sleeker cars.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced in 1958 on an up-level coupe and convertible variant
of the Bel Air, then in 1959 on a sedan and wagon, the Impala name
was last used on a souped-up SS version of the Caprice that ran for
three model years _ 1994-96 _ and was produced in Texas at the
Arlington plant. Production of these Impalas was limited and they
already have become something of a collector's item.
</P>
<P>
   Impala purists _ especially those who liked the Super Sport
models of the '60s _ won't be excited by the new model, but the
2000 Impala does give Chevrolet a family sedan that can compete
well against the popular Ford Taurus and even, perhaps, the Toyota
Camry and Honda Accord. The somewhat plain-looking Lumina has never
been a major player in the midsize segment, so Chevrolet
desperately needs the Impala to make some headway against these
formidable competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 model, which goes on sale this fall, is identical to
the 2000 model except that some new colors have been added, and the
General Motors OnStar live navigation and information system has
been included as standard equipment on the up-level LS model. That
system, which allows the driver to talk with an OnStar operator 24
hours a day, seven days a week, uses GPS satellites to tell the
operator exactly where the car is. The system will be optional on
base models.
</P>
<P>
   Also for 2001, Chevrolet is selling a police version of the
Impala _ GM's first police car since the Caprice went away (and the
first police vehicle since an attempt a couple of years ago to sell
Tahoe sport-utilities with a police package). It remains to be seen
as to whether the Impala will catch on as a cop car, considering
that it has only a V-6 and front-wheel drive, compared with the V-8
and rear-wheel drive in the competing Ford Crown Victoria police
car.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 122 cubic feet of interior space, the Impala is
roomier than any of its midsize competition. Along with all of that
space, it brings a combination of styling, performance and value
that today's new-car buyers crave.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not exactly an exciting car _ the kind that inspires
Beach Boys songs like ``409,'' which glamorized the 409-cubic-inch
engine in the first Impala Super Sport. But it's a car that will
give families the option of a sedan that can carry as many people
and nearly as much stuff as a midsize sport-utility, yet maintain
good handling, sporty looks and much better fuel economy than an
SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Overall length is almost 200 inches _ an inch shorter than the
Lumina. But the wheelbase is three inches longer, and very
efficient use of space has created a roomier interior than that of
the Lumina.
</P>
<P>
   With a bench seat up front, the new Impala seats six adults
rather comfortably, but its turning radius is the same as that of
the smaller Taurus. The trunk is huge _ 17.6 cubic feet (vs. 15.5
cubic feet for the Lumina and 15.8 for the Taurus). The interior is
as roomy as that of the larger Buick Park Avenue, except that the
Park Avenue has slightly more rear-seat leg room.
</P>
<P>
   Exterior styling is more reminiscent of the Chevy Malibu of the
early '70s than the early Impalas. Still, there are some design
cues taken from the Impalas of the past, including the round tail
lights, chrome center bar and Chevy bow tie emblem in the grill, as
well as the muscular exterior lines.
</P>
<P>
   Value is stressed by Chevrolet in all of its literature about
the Impala.
</P>
<P>
   This is a full-size car that carries a base price under $20,000
_ fairly well-equipped.
</P>
<P>
   For a list price of $19,265 (including transportation), the base
Impala comes with a 3.4-liter, 180- horsepower V-6 engine (the same
one used in the Venture minivan), four-speed automatic
transmission, power windows and door locks, six-passenger seating,
air-conditioning, power steering, cruise control, four-wheel power
disc brakes, and an AM/FM radio. The LS model lists for $22,365
plus $560 transportation
</P>
<P>
   For $22,925, the up-level LS model _ our test car _ comes with a
bigger engine, the 3.8-liter, 200-horsepower V-6 also used in the
Park Avenue, as well as traction control, antilock brakes,
dual-zone temperature controls, a side air bag for the driver,
bucket seats up front (with power adjustments for the driver's
side), and a firmer ``touring'' suspension that helps the vehicle
hold the road better during cornering.
</P>
<P>
   The interior isn't as luxurious as those of some competitors,
and the instrument-panel materials are rather plain. But Chevy had
to cut corners somewhere to keep the price down, and this was the
most likely place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the cabin is very quiet at highway speeds, the seats are
as comfortable as any in this class, if not more so, and the ride
in our LS was cushy, but not overly so.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't tested the base model, but the 180-horsepower engine
should provide plenty of power for most people's needs. The bigger
engine in our LS is quite a capable performer, however, adding some
measure of excitement to the driving experience. The transmission
shifts smoothly and almost seamlessly, and with the touring
suspension, the Impala LS corners much better than most of its
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is impressive, and will be one of the top selling
points for the Impala. The base engine is EPA rated at 20 miles per
gallon in the city and 32 on the highway. The bigger engine is
rated at 20 mpg city/29 highway. The average sport-utility vehicle
has fuel economy ranging from about 14 to 18 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Other standard equipment on our LS model included the Passlock
theft-deterrent system, daytime running lights, 16-inch aluminum
wheels, power trunk opener, variable intermittent wipers, fog
lamps, rear spoiler, body side moldings, tilt steering wheel,
remote keyless entry, heated electrically remote-controlled outside
mirrors, rear-window defogger, and split-folding rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   LS models come with cloth-trimmed front bucket seats, but ours
had the optional leather-trimmed seats ($625), which adds leather
to the front seating surfaces only. An AM/FM/cassette six-speaker
stereo is standard, but ours came with the optional audio system
with cassette and compact-disc players and eight speakers ($223).
</P>
<P>
   Other options on our test car included an electric sun roof
($700); a comfort seating package ($425), including heated front
seats and a six-way power front passenger seat; and the LS
preferred-equipment group ($517), which added an electronic
driver-information system that monitors 17 items, including tire
pressures, an alarm system, an automatic-dimming rearview mirror,
and steering-wheel radio controls.
</P>
<P>
   Total price for our fully-equipped LS test car was $25,415,
including $560 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The new Impala is built at Oshawa, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
