<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-     08-11 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOE MAKERS SEEK FOOTHOLD IN TOUGH MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Two makers of sensible shoes have new ad campaigns. One wryly
romances the clog and the chukka; the other seems poised to focus
as much on beefcake as on leather.
</P>
<P>
   Ads from the Dexter Shoe Co. of Dexter, Maine, are all shoe and
no people. A new ad from the Rockport Co. of Marlborough, Mass. is
all people and no shoe.
</P>
<P>
   In magazines, a Dexter ad shows a photo of a big shoebox.
Inside, there's a shoe and a hammock. ``Comfort in every box,''
says a headline created by Mullen of Wenham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Rockport, a division of Reebok International Ltd. of Canton,
Mass., also has a new campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A billboard ad features a photo of a young man cuddling a
woman's foot to his face. How do motorists know this isn't an ad
for a bath gel or a condom? The only tipoff is Rockport's new
modernized logo.
</P>
<P>
   Created by AG Worldwide of New York, the new campaign is about
adding a ``sensuous and emotional'' component to a brand long
associated with comfort, said Stefanie Lucas, Rockport's vice
president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   New ads, she says, are ``about loving your feet.''
</P>
<P>
   A reader of the business pages might think these would be great
days for casual-shoe companies. The economy is booming, and dress
codes are relaxing. Wingtips and pumps are out, and what's
fashionable are brown shoes that look good with khakis.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, casual-shoe sales are barely growing, said Steve
Lunder, Dexter's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In borrowing ideas from sneakers, casual shoes have become more
durable. Partly because these shoes last longer, and partly because
consumers no longer feel the need to own a pair of shoes for every
occasion, annual sales in the casual-shoe category have been
increasing by only 1 or 2 percent, Lunder said.
</P>
<P>
   One of several shoe companies owned by Berkshire Hathaway Inc.,
the holding company run by investment guru Warren Buffett, Dexter
does not break out its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Employing large numbers of US workers to make many of its
products, Dexter faces pressure from rivals that rely on cheap
foreign labor. As Dexter tries to improve sales, ads look to
lionize Dexter shoes as ``icons of comfort,'' Lunder said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Edward Boches, Mullen's chief creative officer,
many rival shoe campaigns are fond of building ads around
inspirational themes. Dexter slyly spoofs that approach with ``ads
that are likable and make people smile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dexter and Rockport count middle-aged consumers as some of
their best customers. And once again, Rockport seems to be
attempting to increase disappointing sales by convincing young
folks its shoes are as trendy as they are comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   With sales off about 7 percent for the most recent quarter,
Rockport's cobblers have again taken up the tough challenge of
transforming a comfort shoe into an essential accessory for a hip
lifestyle, all while staying true to Rockport's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   In wooing the young, ads consciously strive for unisex appeal.
Some previous ad campaigns, Lucas said, resonated more with men
than with women, and they failed to make an ``emotional
connection'' with the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Future ads will unveil the theme ``Don't just walk,'' and they
may exhibit more sightly young people not wearing much.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes themselves should make a cameo appearance in the next
round of ads.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking to portray its stores as a safe haven from the daily
grind, Dunkin' Donuts USA of Randolph, Mass. will introduce a new
$60 million ad campaign around Labor Day with the theme ``Loosen up
a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is being developed by Dunkin Donuts' ad agency,
Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new ads are a reflection of how our customers feel about
us and how we fit into their lives,'' Dunkin Donuts' director of
advertising, Maura Reardon, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Since the company retired Fred the Baker as its pitchman in
1997, many Dunkin' Donuts ads have run without a tagline in recent
years, said Hill Holliday group creative director Marty Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Loosen up a little'' will be a ``rallying cry'' for the
brand, he said. It tells consumers: ``Don't take life so seriously.
Come on out and have a doughnut or a bagel.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chris Reidy is a member of the Globe staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
