<HEADER>
A8813 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-11 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST WAS A WORTHY MODEL _ ON AND OFF THE COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not exactly privileged information that the silhouette of
a player comprising the official NBA logo is that of Jerry West, a
man who resides in the inner sanctum where only the truly great
players in NBA history can claim a spot.
</P>
<P>
   But were there an official scout's logo (a guy taking notes at a
college game?) or general manager's logo (someone making a deal
over the phone?), Jerry West could have been the most likely model
for those, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure I can think of anyone with his range of
credentials,'' confirms Jan Volk, the former general manager of the
Celtics. ``There is no one else who was an extraordinary player and
also an extraordinary executive.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, I don't like this past tense business, the need
to say ``was,'' rather than ``is.'' Jerry West is only 62. He is
far too young, with too much more to give, to be retiring from the
Los Angeles Lakers after 40 years of consecutive service.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not any one of the next 100,000 people you might see
walking down the street. He is Jerry West. His noted teammate Elgin
Baylor once told Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist Jim Murray that
Jerry needs to go to a movie seven times in order to see it,
because ``he can't sit still more than a few minutes.'' That was 35
years ago. West's restlessness grew more acute with time.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was the team's general manager, he would never
accompany the Lakers east during those memorable series with the
Celtics in 1984, 1985, and 1987. Watching his team on the road in
those kind of big games was too much for his system. I begged him
to come, and I'm sure I was not the only one. I wanted Jerry West
to come to Boston in order to find out how beloved he was in this
town. He was then, and still remains, the single most revered
Celtic opponent of all time. No Celtic opponent has ever had more
fans wishing he would switch uniforms, and that includes Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noble'' doesn't begin to describe the level and style of his
performances against the Celtics in the '60s. His LA teams lost
Finals series to Boston in '62, '63, '65, '66, '68, and '69. His
scoring averages in those six series were 31, 29, 34, 35, 32, and
38. Young-uns, do I now have your attention?
</P>
<P>
   It gets better. During those six series, the Lakers won 13
games. In those victories, West's average was 38. The fewest points
he scored in victory was 26. His totals in the other 12 victorious
Laker efforts ranged from 32 to 53. And that's without even
discussing such losing efforts as 40, 42, and 45 (twice). That 42,
incidentally, was part of a triple-double (42 points, 13 rebounds,
12 assists) in Game 7 of the 1969 series.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he did this to everybody, not just the Boston
Celtics. He retired in 1974 with career averages of 27.0 points in
the regular season and 29.1 points in the playoffs. After averaging
17.6 points his rookie season, he never again fell under 20. He was
over 25 a game 11 times and over 30 four times. In the 54-year
history of the NBA, only two men have retired following seasons in
which they averaged 20 or more points. Those men are Michael Jordan
and Jerry West. Oh, and the only reason he was first-team
All-Defense only four times was that they didn't invent the award
until he was 30 and had been in the league eight years.
</P>
<P>
   It probably smacks of redundancy to point out that there is no
guard in the league today as good as Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   And now there will be no one running an NBA team on his level,
either.
</P>
<P>
   He is getting out, I can only assume, because he feels he has
enough money and he simply doesn't need it any more. The guy who
needed seven movie screenings 35 years ago and who couldn't bear
the thought of traveling to Boston to see his team play 15 years
ago had become so overwrought that he couldn't even attend the home
games during the final two rounds of the 2000 playoffs. Frankly,
that scares me, and if things are that bad for him, then he
probably should get out.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves on top. The current Lakers are his creation. He
created the salary cap space to get Shaquille O'Neal. He identified
the latent greatness in Kobe Bryant and worked the trade with
Charlotte that made Jellybean Bryant's gifted son a Laker. He
scouted or drafted or traded for everyone on the roster. He has
rebuilt a team that as recently as the 1993-94 season was a
complete non-factor (33-49, and no playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   It has long been publicly acknowledged that Jerry West was a
great judge of talent. But the general public only knew half the
story. They didn't know how much the insiders respected his
tenacity and his willingness to do the same kind of scouting grunt
work some low-paid scout was doing for another team. You think some
of those guys didn't go back to the bar or their hotel rooms after
watching a college game and say, ``Good Lord, was I really just
hanging out with Jerry West?''
</P>
<P>
   But there was yet another Jerry West persona. This was the Jerry
West who went to league meetings and assorted league gatherings,
representing the Los Angeles Lakers by wearing his GM's hat. ``He
has a grace and a style that was almost regal,'' recalls Volk. ``At
league meetings, he wouldn't talk much, but when he did, everybody
listened. He was so subtle and laid-back. It was a style that was
easy to take and easy to listen to. And this was, of course, Jerry
West, who had established his credibility as a player. That was
built-in. Now you combine that with his style and he had total
credibility. And it never appeared to be ego-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ego-driven? The man didn't even appear at his own retirement
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   He had no Farewell Tour as a player and they don't have Farewell
Tours for executives. But somebody's got to do something. The logo
has just walked out the door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
