u e BC-MOVIE-DEMENTED-BOS &LR;      08-11 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DEMENTED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DEMENTED' ISN'T AS CRAZY AS IT WANTS TO BE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
CECIL B. DEMENTED 
Written and directed by: John Waters 
Starring: Melanie Griffith, Stephen Dorff, Alicia Witt, Adrian
Grenier, Erika Lynn Rupli, Zenzelle Uzoma, Larry Gilliard, Jr.,
Eric M. Barry, Maggie Gyllenhaal, Jack Noseworthy, Harriet Dodge,
Mike Shannon, Mink Stole, Ricki Lake, Patricia Hearst, Kevin
Nealon 
Running time: 89 minutes 
Rated: R (strong crude sexual content, violence, language and drug
use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Waters' new ``Cecil B. DeMented'' has fun with both ends of
the moviemaking spectrum _ megabore mainstream and sanctimonious
indie. It also ought to earn Melanie Griffith a good-sport award as
a Hollywood star kidnapped by self-proclaimed guerrilla filmmakers.
She starts out with a cliche movie star hissy fit in Baltimore,
when a white limo is sent to pick her up instead of a black one.
``Do I look like Liberace's boyfriend? Do I look like a coke
dealer?'' she harrumphs, only to be kidnapped minutes later and
hustled off to a crumbling theater by underground filmmakers who
live in a heavy-metal goth dream world. They take a thumbs-down
attitude toward mainstream culture _ thumbs and other assorted body
parts being tattooed with the names of Fassbinder, Otto Preminger,
David Lynch, Spike Lee, Herschel Gordon Walker, Sam Fuller, and
other cinema gods.
</P>
<P>
   Don't arrive too late for the funny opening credit montage, a
series of theater marquees boasting such divertissements as a Pauly
Shore festival and the English-dubbed version of ``Les Enfants du
Paradis.'' One plot bit involves the guerrillas crashing a strip
mall multiplex showing the director's cut of ``Patch Adams.'' Even
without being reminded that John Waters regular Patty Hearst
appears as the straight mom of one of the film guerrillas,
cognoscenti will have picked up on the fact that the film's plot
loosely echoes the real-life kidnapping of Hearst by the Symbionese
Liberation Army, and her subsequent temporary conversion to their
cause. It's fun to watch Griffith segue from a sensible survivor
mode to something like sympathy for the group because the diva side
of her realizes that she not only looks good in the guerrilla
project, but looks younger than she has looked in her last few
Hollywood features.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Dorff is a nonstop caricature of Mansonesque energy in
the title role, a man who can say with a straight face that
technique is nothing more than failed style. But the very nature of
his character hints at the film's shortcoming. Essentially, it's
Waters looking back at his younger self affectionately, but also
with a mature sense of how silly he was in his rebellious youth.
The film's heart is in the right place, and the cast is sunnily
engaging. But the film can't sustain its initial high attack, and
ends up seeming a bit of a fizzle, mischievous rather than
genuinely wild.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``Cecil B. DeMented'' suffers from a split
personality. It admires the energies of guerrilla filmmaking, but
can no longer recapture them. And it's fully aware of the emptiness
of Hollywood spectacles, but doesn't try to conceal a sneaking
fondness for them, expressed at a sharply campy level. Even the
music over those not-to-be-missed opening credits is a sonic
montage of inspired cheesiness. But ``Cecil B. DeMented'' deals in
affection, not firepower. It's the cinematic equivalent of one of
those prop guns where you pull the trigger and a little flag comes
out of the barrel, waving gaily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     08-11 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED'S SOFT LANDING ASIDE, CAUTION NOW PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news for investors could hardly be better.
</P>
<P>
   The hope for a soft landing seems to have arrived. The economy
is slowing, inflation is under control, and the Fed probably won't
raise interest rates later this month. Earnings in the second
quarter were terrific, especially in the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   So how has the stock market reacted to all this good fortune?
</P>
<P>
   With a yawn. You'd think investors were watching the Republican
convention. The market averages have barely moved for weeks and all
remain slightly negative for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Are we in the August doldrums or is there a reason to think we
may be stuck here for a while? ``You have to ask: Is this as good
as it gets?'' said William Braman, chief investment officer for
John Hancock Funds.
</P>
<P>
   First the news.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Wednesday reported that the economy is
slowing. Consumer spending, manufacturing, and construction are all
losing steam, the Fed reported in its ``beige book.'' Wages are
still rising, but thanks to a combination of competition and
productivity gains, prices are holding steady.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the government Tuesday reported that productivity is
rising at the fastest pace in 17 years. Strong productivity growth
means the economy can grow without triggering inflation. On a scale
of 1 to 100, the productivity report was a 96.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has been looking for moderation in growth and stability
in prices. With evidence of both in hand, the central bank likely
will do nothing at its Aug. 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   On the earnings side, profits in the second quarter grew
slightly more than 20 percent, ahead of estimates. The performance
of some key technology companies was truly eye-popping. Cisco
Systems this week said its sales grew 61 percent in the quarter.
Applied Materials, a key supplier to the semiconductor industry,
had a revenue gain of 83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So why the ho-hum reaction?
</P>
<P>
   Lauriann Kloppenburg, director of equity research at Loomis
Sayles, has one answer. ``People are cautious,'' she said. ``Some
of this news is almost too good to be true. People aren't sure it
can last.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed may be on hold for the moment, say money managers, but
there is no guarantee there won't be more rate hikes down the road.
The economy, like the stock market, might just be taking a
breather.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain amount of caution about earnings as well.
Sure they are wonderful today, but can they stay wonderful?
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks a few technology giants, including
wireless leaders Nokia and Ericsson, have warned of slowing sales
in the second half of the year. A handful of analysts also have
predicted some easing in demand for semiconductors, another
mainstay of the technology business.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting disaster, but it wouldn't take a disaster,
just a mild slowdown, to knock technology stocks off their lofty
perches.
</P>
<P>
   ``These stocks are already priced with the expectation of some
very good numbers,'' said Hancock's Braman, who notes that the top
tech stocks still sell for stratospheric multiples. Cisco, for
instance, trades at 87 times earnings. EMC, another high-flier,
sells for 117 times earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Blow-out-the-doors sales and profits don't push these stocks
higher because it takes terrific performance just to keep them
where they are. Said Braman, ``We have a battle between earnings
and valuation.''
</P>
<P>
   The implications going forward aren't inspiring. As Rodgers and
Hammerstein once said of Kansas City, stock prices may ``have gone
about as far as they can go.'' The tremendous runup in the markets
over the past five years was predicated on a world of strong
growth, low inflation and good earnings.
</P>
<P>
   We've got that world, but what do we do for an encore?
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisors, suggests that the current pause may be a good thing.
``This is healthy,'' Riley said. ``In the tech area especially,
expectations got way out of line with reality. Now we are getting a
narrowing of the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, earnings can catch up with stock prices and the
market can make another move forward.
</P>
<P>
   How long could this consolidation period last? A month? Six
months? A year? No one has a clue. But in the meantime, get used to
boring. You can practice by watching the Democratic convention next
week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
