<P>
   KIPP-EDUC (Berkeley, Calif.) _ With the national political
debate increasingly focused on education, perhaps the most divisive
question has been how to raise achievement among poor and minority
children. One experiment has drawn keen attention from both
liberals and conservatives. KIPP Academy, a pair of remarkably
successful middle schools in the ghettoes of Houston and New York
City's South Bronx, was highlighted at this month's Republican
National Convention by Laura Bush and earlier rewarded by the
Children's Defense Fund, an organization close to the heart of
Hillary Clinton. The question is whether it can be replicated. Now,
in an unprecedented effort to build hundreds of KIPP clones around
the country, Donald G. and Doris Fisher, the owners of The Gap
clothing stores _ who know something about building a franchise _
have given $15 million to create the KIPP Foundation. Their aim is
not only to create a chain of like-minded schools, but to shift
American education more broadly. By Jodi Wilgoren.
