</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RATES (Tokyo) _ The Bank of Japan ends its policy of zero
interest rates, defying government calls for a delay in a rate
increase in what has been the biggest public fight over Japanese
economic policy this century. After 17 months of near-zero rates,
the central bank raises its target for overnight lending to 0.25
percent _ the first rate increase in a decade. While ruling party
leaders have inveighed against a rate increase, calling it
irresponsible at a time when the economy is undergoing a fragile
recovery, many economists say that the move will have little
impact. The decision, however, is a significant show of
independence by the central bank, two years after it won autonomy
from the Ministry of Finance. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
