<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-WOMEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WOMEN WILL FACE THE IRON IN THEIR QUEST FOR THE GOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States women's national team is receiving little
respect and no sympathy from Olympic soccer organizers. The US will
meet Norway and China _ the runners-up in the 1995 and '99 Women's
World Cups and 1996 Olympics _ in its first two games.
</P>
<P>
   But the US apparently is anticipating the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the single most difficult and challenging draw FIFA
has ever put out to a team that was ranked No. 1 in the world,''
coach April Heinrichs said after announcing the team members during
a conference call Thursday. ``FIFA has provided us the greatest
challenge and the most hurdles and we love it. Every time something
or somebody says that this team can't do something they prove them
wrong and we hope that trend continues.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few changes from the '99 Women's World Cup team that
defeated China on penalty kicks in the final, with all the starters
returning and only reserve Tisha Venturini excluded. Every starter
from the '96 Olympic final team remains. And six starters from the
'91 Women's World Cup final team remain, including Michelle Akers,
who scored both goals in a 2-1 win over Norway in Guangzhou, China,
and Heinrichs, who was named coach in January.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the holdovers _ Akers (shoulder) and Carla Overbeck
(knee) _ were questionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having Michelle Akers and Carla Overbeck on this team was a
decision that I made in my mind two or three months ago because of
Carla's leadership,'' Heinrichs said. ``Carla's knee might be about
70 percent but her will and power among these players, along with
her leadership, makes her the glue of this team and every team has
a glue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michelle is a world-class player. I think what we will see
over the next couple of weeks is that she will get better and
better every time she steps out on the field. What I know about
Michelle is that she always overcomes adversity and I think she
will again.''
</P>
<P>
   The US will meet Norway Sept. 13, the first of a possible five
games in 15 days. The 18-player roster limits options.
</P>
<P>
   Siri Mullinix, an active and aggressive goalkeeper, will likely
be the starter ahead of Briana Scurry. Goalkeeper Jenni Branam was
named an alternate and will travel with the team along with
midfielder Michelle French, 23. The other alternates are defender
Nandi Pryce, 18, and forward Christie Welsh, 19.
</P>
<P>
   The most important transitional players will be Mullinix, 22;
midfielder Nikki Serlenga, 22; and defender Danielle Slaton, 20,
the active roster's youngest player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have more than two or three younger players we've made
too much of a jump, we were too quick to change, and we were
careless,'' Heinrichs said.
</P>
<P>
   The US will meet Russia in Annapolis Sunday; Canada in Kansas
City, Mo., Aug. 20; and Brazil in San Jose, Calif., Sept. 1 before
traveling to Melbourne Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the final tournament for many of the veteran
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's over we will be kind of sad because I don't know how
many of us will be around,'' Overbeck said. ``But the younger kids
are very athletic, very driven, and they've learned something from
residency camp. They've learned about dedication and what it takes
to make it. This team will keep rolling on. April is one of the
best motivators and she knows what it takes to win and I am
confident the younger players will be prepared for the next few
years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
