<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8829 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-THREATENING-BOYFRIEND     08-11 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREATENING-BOYFRIEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWAITING TRIAL OF EX-BOYFRIEND, WOMAN GOES INTO HIDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The police were searching for Angelique Uhlmann's body
when she arrived, trembling, at her Beacon Hill apartment last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was 4:30 Saturday morning, shortly after Uhlmann says she was
awakened by the voice of her ex-boyfriend, who had called the home
of her new boyfriend to say that he was in her apartment and
planned to kill him, her, and himself.
</P>
<P>
   She rushed across town to her home, where she was met by police
who'd arrived minutes earlier to find a blood-soaked scene so
disturbing that they believed a particularly horrible murder,
perhaps a mutilation, had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   A trail of blood led up a stairwell to Uhlmann's shattered
apartment door, ripped off its hinges so forcefully that two
deadbolts dangled inside, according to a police report. The
apartment had been ransacked, its floors strewn with shards of
glass and plastic left from a smashed telephone and wine glasses. A
garbage bag had been ripped open, its contents dumped on a deck.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the blood, smeared on every conceivable
surface: walls, furniture, appliances, framed photographs, even
receipts and credit cards pulled from Uhlmann's wallet, according
to police.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting shirtless and blood-splattered on the apartment's front
steps was Uhlmann's ex-boyfriend, Vincent J. Froio Jr., a former
competitive bodybuilder who, according to a police report, was in
an ``agitated and uncooperative state'' when officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested and appeared in Boston Municipal Court Monday
morning, charged with breaking into Uhlmann's apartment, trashing
it, and threatening to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors asked the judge to hold Froio, 33, without bail,
arguing that he was too dangerous to release. But Judge Mark
Summerville did just that, also refusing a request that Froio be
tethered to an electronic bracelet before trial. Bail was set at
$30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Froio, a lawyer with the downtown law firm of Foley, Hoag &AMP;
Eliot, made bail and was freed later that day after promising to
check himself into a New Hampshire psychiatric hospital _ something
he didn't do for 27 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Now a terrified Uhlmann, a fourth-year medical student at Tufts
University, is in hiding, frantic that Froio will make good on his
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only goal now is to keep myself safe and to be able to live
until my medical school graduation without him killing me,'' said
Uhlmann, 32, who has temporarily dropped out of her surgery
rotation. ``He showed that he had the rage, the ability, the
temper, and the loss of control to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Froio's defense attorney, Desmond Fitzgerald, insisted that
Summerville's decision to release Froio on bail was appropriate,
noting that Uhlmann was not harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Even James Borghesani, a spokesman for the Suffolk district
attorney's office, called the $30,000 bail ``very high'' when
considering the nature of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to minimize the nature of this crime,''
Borghesani said. But Froio has no criminal record and no history of
not appearing in court, he said, two main considerations in setting
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Uhlmann's charge that Froio threatened to kill her is
``unsubstantiated,'' Fitzgerald said, adding that he believes she
lied to police about the threat because she was distraught over
their breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole thing is about a girl whose boyfriend was
cheating on her, or who thinks her boyfriend was cheating on her,
and she's upset,'' Fitzgerald said. ``And sometimes when people
feel jilted they will say things that aren't necessarily true, and
I think that's what happened here.
</P>
<P>
   But Uhlmann says she was the one who ended their 2 1/2-year
relationship six weeks ago. About two weeks after the breakup,
Uhlmann said, Froio began to call her repeatedly, prompting her to
call one of his friends and ask him to tell Froio to stop
contacting her. He also sent a threatening e-mail, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the calls continued, including one in which Uhlmann says
Froio told her, ``I know you're dating another guy,'' identifying
the man by his first name.
</P>
<P>
   Uhlmann believes Froio got the man's name by gaining access to
her phone messages.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening before Froio allegedly broke into her apartment,
Uhlmann had dinner with her sister and the man she was dating.
</P>
<P>
   The three later returned to his apartment and, when her sister
fell asleep, Uhlmann says she decided to spend the night rather
than return to her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 4 the next morning the phone in her new boyfriend's
apartment rang repeatedly. Uhlmann said she answered it and heard
Froio's voice, screaming racial slurs, obscenities, and threatening
to kill her, the new boyfriend, and himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone in his voice was just rage,'' Uhlmann recalled.
</P>
<P>
   When Uhlmann called police and returned to her apartment, ``It
was like a scene from a horror movie,'' she said. ``I have never
seen that kind of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Froio was arrested and taken to jail, where he called her, she
said, and pleaded, ``Please come down and get me. You're the only
one who can do this. You know how much I love you'' _ this despite
orders from police not to telephone her.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald said that Froio had fallen while walking to Uhlmann's
house and cut his finger. Noting that Uhlmann is training to be a
surgeon, Fitzgerald said it is ``quite possible he was going there
for assistance with his injury.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the blood had been intentionally smeared on
Uhlmann's possessions. ``I would say that when I walk upstairs, I
put my hand on the railing and wall to balance myself, so if my
finger's bleeding, there's going to be blood on the wall,''
Fitzgerald said. ``And if I touch a photo or a couch, the blood is
going to mark that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Uhlmann had no reason to fear for her safety.
</P>
<P>
   But Gerald Stewart, the supervising assistant district attorney
for Boston Municipal Court, thought otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed that in order to ensure the safety of the victim,
holding him without bail was appropriate,'' said Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot, where Froio has worked as an associate
since April, referred questions on the case to Gerri Denterlein
Worldwide, a public relations firm. Denterlein called the charges
against Froio ``serious'' and said the case is ``under review at
the highest levels of the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after learning that Froio had not been admitted to
a psychiatric hospital until 27 hours after his release on bail
because of problems finding a bed, Summerville held a hearing to
amend the conditions of Froio's release. He ordered that Fitzgerald
provide additional information about the psychiatric facility where
Froio was admitted, Elliot Hospital in Manchester, N.H. Summerville
said he will review that information to determine if the facility
provides adequate security.
</P>
<P>
   If he determines that it does not, he may revoke Froio's bail
and order him jailed before trial.
</P>
<P>
   Uhlmann said she fears she'll be emotionally imprisoned for much
longer than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will forever have to look over my shoulder because of this
guy, because nothing he can tell me will convince me that he won't
snap like that again at some point,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
