<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-RUIZ-ART-BOS &LR;      08-11 1708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 `QUIET MAN' STAYS IN THE SHADOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The biggest thing to happen all week for Johnny Ruiz
is that he got sued by an old promoter. In boxing, getting sued is
one sign you've hit the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to see your name on a huge billboard near the
McCarren Airport when you finally land in the Nevada desert and
head to the Strip at three in the morning, as Ruiz did last Sunday
after he arrived in town bleary-eyed following nearly three hours
of flight delays.
</P>
<P>
   Or to keep running into pictures of yourself at a Las Vegas
casino, pictures of you right next to three-time heavyweight
champion Evander Holyfield. Ruiz sees this every time he walks
around the Paris Hilton or the adjacent Bally's casino. The posters
are like postcards to himself that carry home one message. He's in
the big time this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ten times a day, 20 times a day, however many times a day John
Ruiz leaves his room, the pictures tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign, and in Ruiz's case the most important one, will
come Saturday night when he finally hits Holyfield in the face for
the first time or vice versa. At that moment, a kid from Chelsea,
Mass. who had a dream all his life will have officially grown into
a challenger for the heavyweight title. He will have officially
earned $1.5 million regardless of what follows that first punch. He
will have officially begun fighting with a legend for the World
Boxing Association heavyweight championship.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, little has changed for The Quiet Man except that
Panos Eliades, a former promoter, is suing him for $10,000, which
he claims he's owed from a past fight against Jerry Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz never looked at the papers when they were served on his
manager. It's not a problem he thinks about, just like the lights
of Las Vegas are not something he thinks about. Ruiz may be living
on the Strip this week, but he could just as easily be in Lunenberg
for all the difference it's made to him. This week, like all weeks,
The Quiet Man has stayed quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly I play gin in my room with Stoney (manager Norman
Stone) and Gabe (trainer Gabe Mari) or I watch TV,'' Ruiz said when
asked about his big week in the big time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't gamble. I don't go to shows. I go for a couple of
walks after I eat with Stoney and Gabe. I sleep a lot. That's about
it. This fight could be anywhere as long as I have a room.''
</P>
<P>
   A room with a view. A view of Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm alone I focus on the fight,'' Ruiz said. ``That's
really all I do. I think about the fight and what to do. What I've
been surprised about is I haven't been nervous. I haven't been
nervous for the last few fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a guy who would sit wracking his brain all day
before a fight, thinking about this and that and what if. Then all
of a sudden, three fights ago, it was like I suddenly felt
comfortable. That's why I think this fight came at the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   If it did, Ruiz is well rested for it. Unlike Peter McNeeley
when he swept through Las Vegas a few years ago before he fought
Mike Tyson and was everywhere, including the ``Tonight'' show, Ruiz
has been seldom visible.
</P>
<P>
   On walks people recognize him as ``the guy who's fighting
Holyfield.'' They ask for his autograph, but unless they're from
New England they ask who he is after he walks off. To them, he is
the bull's-eye Holyfield will be hitting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   That is what it means to be a challenger facing arguably the
greatest heavyweight of his time. Ruiz understands that and thinks
nothing of it. He takes a picture when asked, he signs autographs
when asked, he smiles always, he says little to anyone but
``Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We taught him to play gin at Logan,'' Stone said. ``We boxed
Saturday night and were supposed to leave at around 9 but the plane
was delayed forever so we taught him how to play. We never should
have. He's up about 40 bucks and we're only playing for $2 a game.
He doesn't say much then, either. Just takes the money. It's just
five of us. There's no entourage, no family.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but Holyfield and the effort to prepare for him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Each morning since his arrival, Ruiz has gotten up to run, then
found some place to work out each evening. Between the morning run
and the 7 p.m. workouts, he sits in a room at Bally's and thinks of
Holyfield, or he goes for a meal and an hour walk and he thinks of
Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, Holyfield. Holyfield is his constant companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who else is there to think about?'' Ruiz jokes. ``Lennox
Lewis?''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is the reigning World Boxing Council and International
Boxing Federation champion, a former stablemate of Ruiz who refused
to give him a shot at the unified title after beating Holyfield
even though he was contractually obligated to do so. Since then,
Lewis has repeatedly referred to his former sparring partner as
``Johnny Louise,'' a fact not lost on The Quiet Man.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't often talk about that, but he does talk . . . and
think . . . about all that has been said about him since this fight
was announced. Little of it has been good. Probably the kindest
thing is that he is a hard-working journeyman. The rest has
centered on claims that he didn't deserve a title shot (as if Frans
Botha, who Lewis just cold-cocked in one round, did?). They say he
got a title shot only because his powerful promoter, Don King, got
him the No. 1 ranking through careful maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz may be quiet but he's not deaf and he has been answering
these charges the best he can both at the final press conference
Wednesday and during phone interviews (in his room, of course)
arranged by the promoters. He's talked with a half-dozen Spanish
language TV and radio stations that are here because Ruiz could
become the first Hispanic fighter to win the heavyweight
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Usually Ruiz softly accepts praise and just as softly defends
himself against his critics, saying we'll soon see if he deserves
to be here.
</P>
<P>
   But underneath, as he sits in his room alone, a fire burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff is on my mind,'' Ruiz admitted. ``The only thing it
does is fuel the fire. I've been fighting professionally for eight
years. I'm 36-3. I knocked out 27 guys. I've fought three ranked
fighters and beat them, but I know I've got a lot more to prove
this fight than Evander does.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stuff just makes me more determined to go out and win
this fight. It does make me angry but I've been the underdog since
the day I was born, so any other way would be uncomfortable for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is why his routine has varied little since arriving
in Las Vegas. Walks in the desert, walks in the casino, the
occasional autograph to sign or interview to be done, jogs at a
city park at sunset, meals with his five-man entourage that
includes no family. Other than that, TV, sleep, gin, and thoughts
of Evander Holyfield occupy his time.
</P>
<P>
   That was John Ruiz's big week until Thursday's weigh-in at the
showroom at the Paris Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz tipped the scales at 224, four pounds lighter than he was
when he left Boston. For some, this was a sign that nerves were
eating away at him. To Stone, it was what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be faster,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz said nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing until after Holyfield weighed in at 221. Then Ruiz
surprisingly hung around the stage to do interview after interview.
Al Bernstein from ESPN. Local and national TV. Print media. Spanish
media. British media. Surrounded by microphones, The Quiet Man
suddenly had a lot to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what he's thinking but I hope he's ready because
I know I'm ready,'' Ruiz told a group of reporters. ``I'll try and
set the pace and work him as much as I can to see what he has left
in his tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Is that any way for The Quiet Man to talk? As he does, Stone
turns to a friend and says, ``This is great. Johnny is ready to
fight this guy. I've never seen him this confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Not once does Ruiz disparage Holyfield. That he will not do. But
he mentions that he's 28 and Holyfield is nearly 38 and that
everyone has their time. What he implies without saying it is that
this is no longer Holyfield's time, which means, it stands to
reason, it is his.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect The Quiet Man to say it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Ruiz talks, Stone's ear is constantly glued to a cell phone.
Calls from home. Calls from King's representatives. Calls from the
media looking for Johnny.
</P>
<P>
   Calls, calls, calls. Few get through to Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   That will continue even Saturday when Stone says he will be ``in
constant cellular contact'' with his wife. The reason is she's
hiding a gift for Ruiz that he will not get until this fight is
over.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is the presence of his wife, Sahara. As far as Ruiz
knows, his wife and children are not coming to Las Vegas. He is
against the kids seeing him fight and his wife hates to watch,
although at times she has.
</P>
<P>
   A family decision was made to avoid the pressures and problems
of bringing his family on this business trip, so Ruiz expects to
talk to them sometime after he becomes heavyweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   He will. But it will be face-to-face with his wife, although he
doesn't know it yet. All he knows is that his prefight routine will
not change, just as little else has all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll stay up later the night before the fight so I can get
some good sleep during the day,'' Ruiz said. ``On the day of a
fight, that's what I do. I sleep until they call us to go to the
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   On the biggest day of his professional life, that is what The
Quiet Man plans to do. He'll sleep until it's time to punch Evander
Holyfield in the face.
</P>
<P>
   When the punching stops, the outcome will be known and Ruiz will
return to his life. It will be changed forever if he wins because
it would mean more title fights and bigger purses. Millions upon
millions.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, things may change for John Ruiz but the changes
will come like everything else has this week.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
