<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-11 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTCOM NOTHING BUT A `CLASSIC' SALES JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Douglas Warshaw is a pretty smart guy. Oh, he graduated from
Princeton and worked as a producer for ABC Sports for years, but
that is not why he is smart guy.
</P>
<P>
   He knows things. Cool things. Like the time Elvin Hayes played
in a game and touched the ball 41 times. Hayes shot it 40 times and
lost it out of bounds on the 41st. Or the time Caldwell Jones,
starting center for the great Philadelphia 76ers teams of the
1970s, told a reporter that the highlight of his life was when the
Flintstones went from 30 minutes to an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get him started. Warshaw can go on for hours. In fact, his
lasting legacy is ``Classic Sports,'' the Old School paradise. Two
of his friends, Steve Greenberg and Brian Bedol, called him in 1995
and told him about their plan for the cable network. Warshaw was so
excited he immediately told his wife he finally had a place for all
the useless information in his head.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN bought Classic in 1997, reportedly for $175 million. As one
of the founding partners, Warshaw had some cash but no job. Two
years ago, he installed a cable modem at his home, and that sparked
what would become a new career. ``I got up around 11:05 p.m. and
woke up my wife,'' Warshaw said. ``I told her it was 1939 and
someone had invented the television and we still had a radio.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife rolled over with nothing but thoughts of her husband
working at another start-up business. Six months later, in July
1999, Warshaw found another job as executive vice president of
content strategy and production with a New York-based Internet
video company, Softcom.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Softcom was a start-up company. Warshaw was the 15th
employee. And yes, it's a gem. The company already has attracted
$30 million in investments, and just last month Softcom merged with
Los Angeles-based Interactive Video Technologies and now goes under
its name.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind all the corporate ties, what Softcom does is put meat
on the bare bones of television. It also gives viewers the ability
to get what they want when they want it.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is complicated, but the result is quite simple.
For example, ``The Sopranos'' is a hit series on HBO. Unless a
viewer has watched the show from the beginning, it's a little hard
to follow all the relationships within the mob families. Softcom
produced the ``Sopranos Family Tree'' to enable viewers to follow
the show better. Traffic increased four to five times on HBO.com,
in part because of that interactive video.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to replicate what's already on television,''
Warshaw said. ``We use our technology and applications to create
the most complementary and compelling programming.''
</P>
<P>
   E! Online's Enhanced Oscars hired Softcom to produce an
interactive component for its coverage of the Academy Awards. Lew
Harris, E! Online editor in chief, said in a published report that
about 5,000 users took part in the Oscarcast chat, about two to
three times the traffic of a regular chat site.
</P>
<P>
   Next Saturday, HBO.com will unveil its latest product with
Softcom for the Prince Naseem Hamed-Augie Sanchez fight. HBO.com
will offer prefight information with fighter stats, profiles, and
interviews as well as weigh-in footage the day of the fight. During
the bout, the site will offer round-by-round scoring and chats and
clips from past fights. And while the site will not have live
video, it will have audio of the trainers of both fighters between
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to just have cool stuff on our clients' Web
sites,'' said Warshaw. ``We want stuff that makes viewers smile and
say, `I want to use that' or `I need that.' We understand better
than anybody the relationship between technology and content. It's
not 1939 anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The interactive programming enables networks to extend the life
of their programming. Instead of a show appearing only for 30
minutes or two hours, the programming now has another life on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sports TV on steroids,'' said Warshaw. ``The parade is
about to take off. You don't want to be too far in front. But as
the pipes get fatter and the technology gets thinner, and the
people that control content get smarter and more visionary, we will
see this explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not sorry he missed you
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Anthony Munoz told ``One on One Sports'' that he
was glad O.J. Simpson did not participate in the recent Hall of
Fame ceremonies. ``That was a relief,'' Munoz told radio host Chet
Coppock. ``It was such a great weekend, I don't think I would have
been the only one who would have been uncomfortable. I think it
would have put a damper on things, and you hate to say that about
someone, but that's just the way I feel. And a lot of guys feel
this way, and I'm just glad that we didn't have to deal with
that.'' . . . A new college football pregame show makes its FSNE
debut Aug. 26 with host Kevin Frazier and analyst Kellen Winslow .
. . ABC Sports's college football season starts Aug. 26 at 8 p.m.
with defending national champion Florida State facing Brigham Young
and follows the next day at 2:30 with Penn State-USC. The network
has hired former Boston College radio voice Sean Grande to do
play-by-play. Grande also is the TV voice of the NBA's Minnesota
Timberwolves . . . NBC Sports has hired Kevin Johnson to work as a
NBA studio analyst, replacing Isiah Thomas, who has become head
coach of the Indiana Pacers. Johnson will work with host Hannah
Storm and Peter Vescey . . . Ken Murrah, a multiple Emmy
Award-winning producer, is joining CNBC to handle the Senior PGA
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
