<SLUG> BC-SOMOZA-RESTAURANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SOUTH FLORIDA RESTAURANT PLANS EXPANSION TO SAN ANTONIO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Descendants of the Somoza family that ruled
Nicaragua for more than 40 years plan to open a restaurant on San
Antonio's popular River Walk.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, Los Ranchos restaurant, is to be the first built
outside of South Florida. There, brothers Julio and Carlos Somoza
operate six of the award-winning South American steak restaurants
in the Miami area.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Ranchos restaurant announcement completes a four-year
dream by the Somoza brothers, who are nephews of the Anastasio
Somoza Debayle, the last in the line of Somoza family members who
ruled Nicaragua for most of the period between 1936 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Anastasio Somoza was assassinated in 1980, a year after he left
Nicaragua in exile. Jose Somoza, the father of the U.S.-educated
Somoza brothers, was a military general during Anastasio Somoza's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Somoza said he has harbored a desire to open a River Walk
restaurant since 1986, when he visited the city as a tourist. The
River Walk is a mainstay of San Antonio's tourist trade, lined with
restaurants, clubs, shops and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Julio, 49, and Carlos, 48, own 50 percent of the six Los Ranchos
restaurants in the Miami area, but they have secured a licensing
agreement from their partners to operate the San Antonio restaurant
under their name.
</P>
<P>
   Los Ranchos was named by Gourmet magazine as the best restaurant
for families in a 1999 readers' survey for the Miami/Fort
Lauderdale area.
</P>
<P>
   The moderately priced restaurant chain is known for its
tenderloin steak cuts marinated in chimichurri sauce, as well as
for its cheeses and sweet milk-drenched cake desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Another Los Ranchos restaurant also is planned for a 2001
opening in Coconut Grove, Fla., but the San Antonio restaurant is
the first outside of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Julio Somoza said he favored San Antonio for its ambiance and
its Latin culture and population. Another plus, he said, is that
the city draws a large number of Hispanic tourists, while the
Convention Center expansion is expected to help San Antonio become
one of the top 10 U.S. convention cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 7 million River Walk visitors a year,'' Julio Somoza
said. ``We are very enthusiastic (that) we will be very successful.
We have been patient because (the Peterson Building) is an
outstanding location.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
