u s BC-FBC-PATRIOTS-FRIESZ-B     08-11 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PATRIOTS-FRIESZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S BACK TO BASIC TRAINING FOR FRIESZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ After spending the last 10 summers in NFL
training camps, John Friesz has gotten used to a routine.
</P>
<P>
   Wake up every morning, head to the field, stretch, practice,
watch some film, and go to sleep. The sites may change (the
Patriots are Friesz's fourth team), but the routine always remained
the same.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, the routine changed.
</P>
<P>
   Friesz was lost.
</P>
<P>
   In every other camp, Friesz had plenty of conversations with the
head coach and offensive coordinators, letting Friesz know how
things were progressing, what they liked and disliked, and what was
expected of him during camp.
</P>
<P>
   It was never anything complicated or enlightening, but these
brief talks helped put the veteran quarterback at ease _ a sign
that he was once again in familiar surroundings working through his
familiar football custom. This year, however, new head coach Bill
Belichick and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis remained silent
for the first week.
</P>
<P>
   Friesz's comfort level dropped, and the mind games began.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't being informed of how things were going, so you kind
of start thinking to yourself,'' Friesz said. ``You start thinking,
`This scenario, that scenario. This is what they are thinking.' And
it is just nice to know what the news is. Good, bad, or indifferent
_ be honest with me. Just tell me what the news is.''
</P>
<P>
   While his teammates went through drills when camp opened in
Foxborough, Friesz was isolated. Instead of strapping on a helmet,
Friesz pumped his legs on an exercise bike and was forced to run
the perimeter of the field over and over in front of hundreds of
fans after he failed to meet Belichick's desired time in the
50-yard dash.
</P>
<P>
   That was Friesz's first sign that things were not going well.
But still he was never told so, leaving him time to do two things _
get in shape and think.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the mind games, Friesz engaged in his own brand
of mental warfare and it helped tremendously when Weis finally
broke the news that Friesz would not be getting any playing time
for the first two exhibition games.
</P>
<P>
   As the Patriots' only experienced backup to Drew Bledsoe, Friesz
knew his time would eventually come. And when it did, he was
determined to make sure his mind games kept him on top of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the situation right now, with the limited amount of reps
I have received in the last two weeks, and I guess, really
nonexistent reps, I have had to try harder than ever to stay into
it mentally . . . to get mental reps,'' Friesz said. ``I have had
to spend extra time in the playbook because I have not been able to
do it on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monday) felt like the first day of training camp because it
was the first time in 16 days that I got in the huddle and actually
called plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Friesz shared the majority of snaps with Bledsoe in practice
and, despite his lack of time under center, looked relatively
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to spend extra time studying. You have to spend extra
time, literally, visualizing what you are going to do on the
plays,'' Friesz said. ``Sometimes it is the simple stuff like
running plays. You tend to forget about running plays but we have
different footwork. Sometimes you are opening to the hole, away
from the hole, reverse pivoting, whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the sudden, when you are back under center, you catch
yourself going, `Hold it, here.' You forget the most basic things
just because you have not physically done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night against a revamped Washington Redskins defense,
Friesz will get his chance to combine the physical and mental
preparations. He will most likely relieve Bledsoe to start the
second half. Friesz should see playing time in the final exhibition
games against Tampa Bay and Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the physical action will cease and X's and O's will
fill Friesz's thoughts once more.
</P>
<P>
   In seven seasons, Bledsoe has played in 106 of 112 possible
regular-season games. Friesz appeared in only one game last year
and didn't attempt a pass.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves these exhibition games as Friesz's best chance to
compete and make amends for the problems a couple of tenths of a
second caused for him when camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this could be Friesz's best chance to get out of
the doghouse.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what Friesz is thinking.
</P>
<P>
   It's simply football. A chance to forget the games Belichick,
Weis, and even Friesz himself waged in July in his own head and
continue playing the real games on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an opportunity to go play football again,'' Friesz said.
``It is fun. I enjoy the game and I am not going to make a big deal
out of this. I am going to go out there and try and be 100 percent
on getting the play called correctly and going about my read
correctly. The physical part has always taken care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, so has the mental.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0086 </DOCNO>
