<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8839 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-TAO-BOS &LR;      08-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TAO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES OF COOL GET A WARM COMEUPPANCE IN `TAO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE TAO OF STEVE 
Directed by: Jenniphr(cq) Goodman 
Screenplay by: Duncan North, Jenniphr &AMP; Greer Goodman 
Starring: Donal Logue, Greer Goodman, Kimo Wills, Ayelet Kaznelson,
David Aaron Baker, Nina Jaroslaw, John Hines, Selby Craig, Craig
Lafayette 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great thing about ``The Tao of Steve,'' Jenniphr Goodman's
smart, sparkling, convention-defying romantic comedy, is the way it
flies in the face of genre expectations. Actually, it may be a
stretch to use the word ``flies'' in the case of the film's
protagonist, Donal Logue's Dex. He shows up at his 10th-anniversary
high school reunion in Santa Fe in a scruffy beard and a Hawaiian
flowered shirt that barely covers the sizable beer gut he has
acquired since his glory days as the school's babe magnet. As one
fellow alum puts it upon sighting the new Dex: ``You used to be
Elvis, man! What happened?''
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing is not that a few of the women at the reunion
admit to having slept with Dex when they all were in school, but
that Dex is still pulling women into his orbit. As his
ex-classmates momentarily interrupt their palaver about their
start-ups and IPOs, they look on in disbelief as Dex puts some
moves on the cute student bartender and obviously seems to be
getting somewhere. How does he do it? That's where the film's title
comes in, or at least Dex thinks it does. His sex life is as active
as it is, he's convinced, because he plays it cool.
</P>
<P>
   The Tao part has to do with never trying too hard, at least not
overtly. Steve is Steve McQueen, Dex's god. The way to seem sexy,
Dex repeatedly instructs his roommate, Kimo Wills's good-natured
but hopelessly dim Dave, is never to push things, or even appear to
try at all. Instead, he explains to Dave, whose nonstop
incomprehension is one of the film's ongoing sources of mirth, do
something excellent to demonstrate your sexual worthiness. Dex is
clever, charming, witty, and smart enough to come on
self-deprecatingly. But, of course, there's a gap between what he
says and what he does.
</P>
<P>
   He's actually interested in Greer Goodman's Syd, the snazzy
blond playing drums at the reunion, and his attentions to her are
filled with virtuosic indirection. Things all but blow up in his
face when she informs him that they slept together in high school,
after it's obvious that he doesn't remember. Then the film moves
from clever to really interesting, as Dex is really challenged to
impress Syd, who's too aware to be scammed by the glib verbiage of
the glib, potbellied one-man love boat. He does have a few
qualities that are more than redeeming. Some he doesn't even know
about. Or is it just that he's shrewd enough to exploit them? His
clumsiness and physical limitations, for instance, which bring out
Syd's maternal side after a disastrous camping trip.
</P>
<P>
   Dex can be captivating and disarming. What he has to learn is to
trust to his innate appeal and not think he has to scam his way to
love. Just how smart and insightful the film is about what really
counts, and how accurate it is about women's patience in waiting
for men to catch up to them emotionally, is proof that it can only
have been written from a woman's perspective (or at least clarified
by such, since it was based on the experiences of the Goodman
sisters' friend, Duncan North). Logue's Dex reminds us that the
ability to make someone laugh can be sexier than any bicep.
</P>
<P>
   You'll care whether he can work his way past his own cleverness
and become the most improbable romantic hero of the season if he
can prove himself worthy of a woman's mercy and desire to bet on
heart, not slickness. Logue and the Goodman sisters reinvigorate
the genre, not because they're avant-garde, but because they
convince us they're of the here and now, while the rest of the
genre has become derriere-garde. One of the year's most winning
performances, Logue's Dex will grow on you as he stumbles toward
emotional fullness. Greer Goodman is a dynamite combination _
savvy, sexy, and kind _ and Jenniphr Goodman reminds us, as too few
filmmakers do, that sentient can be sexy, too. Maybe this really is
a new millennium. Already this year we've had three terrific
romantic comedies: ``Wonder Boys,'' ``High Fidelity,'' and now
``The Tao of Steve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
