<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WONDERLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTIMISM WINS IN `WONDERLAND' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WONDERLAND 
Directed by: Michael Winterbottom 
Screenplay by: Laurence Coriat 
Starring: Shirley Henderson, Gina McKee, Molly Parker, Ian Hart,
John Simm, Stuart Townsend, Kika Markham, Jack Shepherd, Enzo
Cilenti, Sarah-Jane Potts, David Fahm, Ellen Thomas 
Running time: 108 minutes 
Rated: R (some strong sexuality, and for language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since Mike Leigh's camera regularly prowled the streets of
Margaret Thatcher's England has a film so convincingly plunged into
bleak urban life with the ensemble zest of Michael Winterbottom's
``Wonderland.'' It's not as different as you might suppose from
Winterbottom's best-known film, ``Welcome to Sarajevo.'' There, the
bombings and cannonings were literal. Here, they're emotional and
psychic. The wonder in ``Wonderland'' is that the characters
flailing around in it haven't slashed their wrists. But then the
film isn't really about the misery in which they're all sloshing
around. It's about the less immediately apparent resilience with
which they strive to surmount it.
</P>
<P>
   The great paradox of postwar English drama is the gusto with
which it pursues its theme of national devitalization.
``Wonderland'' is very much of this hardy ilk. It's carried by a
raw, documentary flavor _ this is one of the few films in which
hand-held camera technique doesn't seem an irritant. Instead, it
propels the multi-track efforts of a dozen or so characters as they
try to fill some yawning emotional gaps in their lives. In the
hands of a less engaged director, a less artful screenplay and a
less energized ensemble that obviously takes to the sometimes
spiky, sometimes despairing, always prickly emotions they're given,
``Wonderland'' could easily crash and burn. Instead, it keeps
going, all the way to something that could almost be called an
optimistic ending.
</P>
<P>
   At its core are three women whose relationship is clarified as
the film progresses. Shirley Henderson's single-mom hairdresser,
Debbie, would seem to be facing the longest odds. Her ex, an angry
lout played by Ian Hart, is unreliable about spending time with
their 11-year-old son on weekends, which complicates Debbie's
spirited efforts to sleep with whomever she fancies and leaves
their son on his own more than he wants to be. She's all too aware
that whatever she's making in bed with this bloke or that, it isn't
love. Yet she's not resentful of Molly Parker's sweet, pregnant
newlywed (also named Molly) whose husband has a steady job and
whose future seems, if not golden, at least stable.
</P>
<P>
   But Molly's husband hates his job and feels the walls closing
in, and is ready to bolt. Although both women have men, they're no
better off than Gina McKee's Nadia, whose Olive Oyl body language
and Raggedy Ann hairstyles emphasize her gawkiness as she tries not
to let her desperation show each time she follows up a personal ad.
McKee, who will be remembered as the hostess to Hugh Grant's
friends in ``Notting Hill,'' reinforces the strong impression she
made in that film. Then there's an older couple, Kika Markham's
Eileen and Jack Shepherd's Bill, draining the life out of one
another in a marital standoff of years' standing in a dreary
council flat. There's also a sketchily drawn young couple, Enzo
Cilenti and Sarah-Jane Potts, who check into a hotel under veiled
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   You can small the symbolism when you learn that the film's
chilly November action takes place on the eve of Guy Fawkes Day,
when bonfires are traditionally lit to commemorate an aborted
17th-century anarchist plot to blow up Parliament. More to the
point, you'll care what blows up here and what doesn't and which
fires can be put out, and why. ``Wonderland'' is not a work of
existential resonance; it's soap opera shot in unvarnished verite
style. But it's lively soap opera, ratcheting up the intensity with
freshness and immediacy. Give it a chance and you'll probably share
the cast's collective impulse to dive in and embrace it, even if
the it in question turns out to be what Langston Hughes once called
the sweet flypaper of life, and even if that flypaper is just as
sticky in Tony Blair's London as it was in Margaret Thatcher's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-BLESS-BOS &LR;      08-11 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLESS THE CHILD' CURSED BY HOLLOW SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
BLESS THE CHILD 
Directed by: Chuck Russell 
Screenplay by: Tom Rickman, Clifford &AMP; Ellen Green 
Starring: Kim Basinger, Jimmy Smits, Rufus Sewell, Ian Holm, Angela
Bettis, Holliston Coleman, Dimitra Arlys, Lumi Cavazos, Christina
Ricci 
Running time: 110 minutes 
Rated: R (violence, drug content and brief language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you absolutely cannot wait until next month's ``Exorcist''
reissue, there's always ``Bless the Child,'' latest in a long and
apparently unending line of ``Exorcist'' and ``Omen'' knockoffs.
The computer graphics-assisted differences here are that the forces
of good are more apparent than usual and that Kim Basinger's
madonna figure does most of the work of taking on Rufus Sewell's
devil's disciple, who more than meets his monthly overhead by
fronting a self-empowerment cult. Holliston Coleman manages to look
both adorable and empathetic as the child with special powers
they're both fighting over. But the air pretty quickly goes out of
an initial attempt at characterization and what follows is more
hollow than scary.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a much more secure grip on dark, sleek urban
visuals, starting with a lingering pan around a stone gargoyle,
shiny with rain, looming high over the streets of New York at
night. Cut to the doorway of the shabby Brooklyn apartment house
where Basinger's nurse, Maggie O'Connor, lives. When she sees a
stranger huddled in her doorway, she draws back, only to recognize
her drug-addicted younger sister bearing a baby wrapped in a
blanket. This promising twist on an urban nativity scene quickly
becomes ordinary as the sister departs. The childless Maggie raises
the girl, who turns out to be slightly autistic, but can do things
like telekinetically make plates spin. Cut to six years later, when
the sister returns on the arm of Sewell's well-to-do empowerment
guru.
</P>
<P>
   They remove the child by force, and a tug-of-war ensues, with
Maggie enlisting the aid of Jimmy Smits' FBI agent attached to New
York's finest to help solve the serial killings of children with
the same birth date as Maggie's young niece. The FBI man
understands all possible supernatural dimensions of the situation,
having conveniently been provided with a background as a
seminarian. So it's them and the police, augmented by a few angelic
interventions, against the forces of darkness, predictably togged
out as a black-clad heavy metal group with a suburban goth look.
</P>
<P>
   A few killings, car chases, and conflagrations later, it all
comes down to a confrontation in a neo-medieval chapel following
episodes squandering Ian Holm and Christina Ricci in minor roles.
Smits is pretty monochromatic, but he'd have to be a miracle worker
to do much more than he does with the perfunctorily written role of
the lawman. A bravely deglamorized Basinger's heart seems to be in
the right place, but the pedestrian script locks her into an
unvaryingly mundane mode. The deflatingly ordinary ``Bless the
Child'' causes one to wish, not for the first time, that movies
about the supernatural could make contact with supernatural script
doctors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS &LR;      08-11 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRING CHEESE GETS MILEAGE OUT OF VARIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the start, members of the String Cheese Incident knew what
they wanted. The idea was to build a fan base through live shows
rather than hustling after radio airplay or making videos. In
short, they set out to follow the same jam-band tradition that has
held true from the Grateful Dead to Phish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot in common with the Dead, actually,'' says String
Cheese Incident bassist Keith Moseley. ``We play long shows and we
have people following us on the road. They know that we're more
interested in the shows than in jumping through record-company
hoops.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed seven years ago in Colorado, where band members first
went to pursue recreational lifestyles in skiing and bicycling, the
Incident has played up to 230 shows a year. It is now down to about
125 (``A couple of us are married now and are trying to spend some
time at home,'' says Moseley).
</P>
<P>
   What separates the String Cheese Incident from the pack,
however, is its musical variety. How many bands can cover songs by
bluegrass pioneer Bill Monroe and jazz god Miles Davis? The
Incident can. The band can also branch into Latin jazz, world beat,
classic rock (it opened with an Afro-spiced version of Bob Dylan's
``Tom Thumb's Blues'' at the Newport Folk Festival last weekend),
plus who knows what else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might do a loping, 6/8 Afro-pop tune _ you don't hear that
from most jam bands,'' Moseley says. ``Then we might go into
something with a Cajun or Latin feel. We spend a lot of time on our
set lists, and we like to have everybody in the band singing every
night. Also, there are songs with jams built in every night. We
might say, `Let's jam on a particular chord progression' or `Let's
do something that sounds like Pink Floyd here.' The jam part of the
night is really hit or miss.''
</P>
<P>
   He's being modest, because the jams usually hit more often than
miss. Just ask anyone who has seen the String Cheese Incident
lately, because the group has improved vastly since just a couple
of years ago. And it has come eons from its first gig at a talent
show at the Crested Butte Center for the Arts in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really liked our music right away, but we couldn't
figure out why at first,'' says guitarist Bill Nershi with a laugh.
``When we started, it was more acoustic-based. We were doing
Newgrass and David Grisman-style jazz and swing. Then we added a
drum kit and electric mandolin and some rock-based stuff with
vocals. And when Kyle Hollingsworth (the keyboardist) joined in
1996, he brought in the Latin and Afro styles.''
</P>
<P>
   The band really started to pick up with the addition of
Hollingsworth. ``He has a degree in jazz piano, so that has really
helped,'' says Moseley.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the group's Web site, at www.stringcheeseincident.com
generates 1 million hits a month. The band also has its own label
(Sci Fidelity Records) and its own ticketing service and travel
agency. Call it grass roots with a capital G.
</P>
<P>
   The group is presently pooling tracks for a double live album
due this fall _ and has hired Steve Berlin (saxophonist for Los
Lobos) to produce the next studio album. These are exciting times
for the Incident _ and definitely not bad for a band that started
as a side project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Counting Crows come aLive: The Counting Crows are skilled at
choosing compatible bands to bring on tour. Their last summer tour
found them paired with the Wallflowers. This time it's with the
band Live, whose singer, Ed Kowalczyk, has become a good friend of
Crows vocalist Adam Duritz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I first met Ed years ago at a festival in Holland,'' says
Duritz. ``I was at his show with a video camera, shooting up at him
from the pit. He looked down and recognized me. At first he said,
`Who is the (expletive) guy with the video camera?' Then he said,
`Oh, I know you from TV.' Then we ran into each other back in Los
Angeles and we've since become friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Counting Crows and Live play the Tweeter Center on Wednesday
(with a third act, Galactic, a New Orleans band also friendly with
Duritz). The tour so far has been highlighted by Duritz joining
Live on their song ``Dolphins Cry,'' and Kowalczyk joining the
Crows on ``Hanginaround.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed and I thought our bands would be a good fit, but it's been
even better than we expected,'' says Duritz. ``And I get inspired
by watching Live's set. Halfway through it, I'm completely feverish
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Audiences are responding too. The Crows/Live tour has been
averaging 12,000 to 15,000 people per night. ``It's been great,
especially because neither of us has a record in the Top 100 right
now,'' says Duritz.
</P>
<P>
   It's further evidence of how the Crows continue to do things
their way _ and get away with it. As Duritz says, ``I don't want to
shill for MTV. I don't want to go to (MTV's) beach parties or award
shows just to make it. I'm thinking of this in the long term. I
don't want to burn out. A lot of the music scene can be
soul-killing, but I'm still pleased and proud to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Duritz admits, however, that in the media the Crows are
``probably more respected than liked. I think a lot of journalists
and radio and TV people feel that way. But we know we're loved by
our fans and by a lot of other musicians. That keeps us going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
