<HEADLINE>
PERFECT CIRCLE TAKES A RIGHT-BRAIN APPROACH 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trends suggest that bands have to be loud, angry, and
belligerent to gain success in rock today, but, thankfully, that's
not always true. Artistic merit can still count for something, as
shown by A Perfect Circle, an alluringly mysterious Los Angeles
group that has become one of the breakthrough acts of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Deemed an ``art-rock'' or ``art-metal'' band, terms not heard
much anymore, A Perfect Circle features an unlikely teaming of
singer Maynard Keenan (best known as the singer of Tool) and
guitarist Billy Howerdel, a former guitar tech for Nine Inch Nails,
Fishbone, and Smashing Pumpkins.
</P>
<P>
   The band opens a national headlining tour with a sold-out date
at Avalon in Boston next Friday. This follows a sumptuous album,
``Mer de Noms'' (translation: ``Sea of Names''), which improves
with repeated listens and stands freshly apart from the relentless,
often calculated anger that dominates rock radio.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's surprised to be doing so well and to have received
such a boost from the group's hit, ``Judith,'' Keenan says, ``No,
not really, considering the current state of music. There's nothing
out there right now. It's all posturing. A lot of these bands are
like businessmen. There's less focus on art, and more on
business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the name A Perfect Circle connotes a natural resolution,
the band actually came together by accident. Howerdel, who had also
worked as a guitar tech for Tool, wrote some instrumental songs
that Keenan chanced to hear and really liked. The pairing proved
fateful, for Howerdel was ready to pursue his dream of rock
songwriting (``I wasn't a frustrated guitar tech who wanted to get
onstage, but I was a frustrated writer who wanted to get back to
the hotel and write some more'') and it enabled Keenan to take a
break from being Tool's frontman. Keenan is a less central force in
A Perfect Circle, adding lyrics and layered vocal harmonies to
music Howerdel has already written.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing is being more interpretive rather than being
the centerpiece,'' says Keenan. ``It's the role I'm comfortable
with. I'm not comfortable with being the frontman, but I like using
my voice as an instrument. I can't play guitar or flute or anything
of that stuff. I'm a klutz with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare A Perfect Circle with Tool, Keenan hems and
haws, then answers, ``Every band has a different personality and
approach. If I have to be cornered into commenting, I'd say that A
Perfect Circle has more of a right-brain feminine approach. It's
more emotional and intuitive. And Tool is more mechanical and more
left-brain masculine, with an esoteric edge.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no timetable for another Tool album, but Keenan dispels
rumors that it's because of writer's block. ``We (Tool) have over
40 songs, so we have too many options. But I'm really not here to
talk about Tool right now,'' he says during a phone interview from
Winnipeg, where A Perfect Circle is wrapping up the Canadian
``Summersault'' tour opening for Smashing Pumpkins and the Foo
Fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The versatile Howerdel is also a sound engineer who recently
finished two years of computer programming for the long-awaited and
still-delayed Guns N' Roses album. There he met ex-Vandals drummer
Josh Freese, who was auditioning for Guns but ended up in A Perfect
Circle. Freese had also played drums with Devo when the latter was
on the Lollapalooza tour. The other Perfect Circle members are
bassist Paz Lenchantin (who also plays violin) and guitarist Troy
Van Leeuwen.
</P>
<P>
   The group's evocative music is not always easy to grasp _
Keenan's vocals are often submerged in the mix, making it hard to
understand the words _ but, as Keenan says, the music is all about
``feeling'' and about ``the beauty and originality of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The words are an afterthought,'' he says. ``It's really about
getting the five of us in a room, reacting to sound.''
</P>
<P>
   The sounds are an atmospheric melange, ranging from the
old-school art-rock of ``Renholder'' (with guitar arpeggios
enhanced by violin) and the screeching guitars of ``Magdalena,'' to
the modern, drum-machine-spiked ``Thinking of You,'' a hopeful love
song that has Keenan singing ``Taking time to look into your eyes .
. . sweet revelation, sweet surrender.'' Many tracks have a hopeful
tone, especially compared with the disaffected nature of many Tool
songs.
</P>
<P>
   Like the earlier art-rock of bands such as Yes and Emerson, Lake
&AMP; Palmer, some songs have a mythological bent, including
``Orestes'' and ``Sleeping Beauty.'' It figures that Keenan is a
big student of author Joseph Campbell, an expert on mythology.
</P>
<P>
   The band's main attribute, however, is the dramatic, sweeping
guitar lines of Howerdel, who says his chief influences are the
Cure and Ozzy Osbourne, specifically Ozzy's early guitarist, Randy
Rhoades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the biggest Randy Rhoades fan you could find,'' says
Howerdel, who grew up in New Jersey. ``I literally locked myself in
the basement for two years to learn every note he played. I was
also a big Blue Oyster Cult fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated now to presenting its songs on the road, A Perfect
Circle is looking forward to starting its headlining tour at the
sold-out Avalon, the smallest venue on its ever-increasing
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled and surprised at how quickly we've gotten the
band to this point,'' says Howerdel. ``I hope that people don't
burn out on us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
