<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GRAVESEND-BOS &LR;      08-11 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GRAVESEND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMAN ISSUES, NESTLED IN A FISHING TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
GRAVESEND LIGHT 
By David Payne. 
Doubleday, 382pp. $$24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Payne is a writer whom readers take personally, a novelist
who speaks to their lives, whose books become part of their
experience. He began with a flourish in 1984 with the publication
of an exuberant fabulation, ``Confessions of a Taoist on Wall
Street.'' This was followed by another large novel, ``Early from
the Dance'' and, in 1993, a shorter country cousin, ``Ruin Creek,''
which was announced as the opening volume of a projected trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gravesend Light,'' another wonderful book, now appears without
reference to a trilogy, and it can certainly be read independently,
although it picks up many of the principal characters and issues of
``Ruin Creek,'' while advancing the time 17 years, to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The setting again is the Outer Banks of North Carolina, to which
Joe Madden, now 28 and an anthropologist by profession, has
returned with personal and professional objectives. He wants to
study the isolated fishing community in Little Roanake before its
individuality and identity disappear in the common culture; he is
also on a journey of self-discovery, although he would probably
deny this, because he has closed off his emotional life. His
temperament and experiences have taught him to examine both sides
of every question _ except for those he's made his mind up about,
and in them there is no room for controversy. In a way he's like
Little Roanoke, although the community seems eager to accept the
benefits of progress while ignoring some of its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Joe's experiences on a fishing boat and in the town, and a love
affair with a feisty feminist doctor, draw him out of his shell and
into the community of humanity. There are several stages in this
journey, and many key players. Some of them, like Joe's parents and
younger brother, return from ``Ruin Creek,'' altered but still
recognizeable as the figures in the old photographs that play a
role in the story. Some of them are new, like Ray Bristow, an
ex-con fisherman. Ray awkwardly tries to befriend Joe, who finds it
so hard to read the code of male friendship that there's no
possibility the the two will connect.
</P>
<P>
   What Ray wants, and fears, is to be seen for who he is, and to
be accepted; this, of course, is what Joe wants, and fears _ just
like his father, Jimmy, his mother, May, the woman he loves, Day
Shaughnessy, and just about everyone else in the book. Ultimately
nearly everyone comes to a new level of self-understanding and
therefore compassion for others. A violent storm, more terrifying
than anything the summer screen has provided, is the catalyst.
</P>
<P>
   Payne tells the story in alternating chapters, some from an
omniscient narrator tracking Joe, some in Day's buoyant but
anchored voice. Here she is at a community meeting. ``As we sat
down on the left, I saw . . . several men I'd dated _ mostly blind
and seldom twice. With their gold signet rings and graphite golf
clubs rattling in the Beamer's trunk, they tended to blur into a
single image: Topsiders without socks, a starched madras shirt, a
belt with yachting flags, a haircut like a twelve-year-old's, that
Tefloned, ultra-Southern, almost military-style politeness, so
friendly on the surface, to a true and searching intimacy so
opposed.``
</P>
<P>
   Joe and Day find themselves strongly drawn to each other,
despite conflicting views on just about everything. ``To him,
Little Roanoke was like a rare and precious ecosystem in a state of
fragile balance that had taken generations to create. When he
looked, that was what he saw: simplicity and character, old
folk-ways, seafaring traditions dating back to Devonshire in Walter
Raleigh's time; Joe saw the villagers' originality and ferocious
independence, their unwavering certainty as to who they were. When
I looked, I saw patriarchalism, religious dogma, bigotry toward
blacks and women. Our difference as lovers and human beings somehow
boiled down to our different views about this town . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Both views, of course, are accurately observed, and complement
each other, as Day and Joe must learn from a series of conflicts
over community issues and personalities, pregnancies past and
present, and a family Christmas as emotionally charged as the
earlier one depicted in ``Ruin Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Early from the Dance'' was an overpowering experience because
it was full of loose ends, like life. ``Ruin Creek'' and
``Gravesend Light'' are more schematic, like a movie script or a
``well-made'' play. But this characteristic isn't the liability it
often proves in popular fiction because Payne sees and hears the
human reality in every situation he has so painstakingly set up;
the book is certainly the captivating summer read promised in some
of the early publicity, but it is also something different from,
and more than, that.
</P>
<P>
   Payne pegs all of his characters as adroitly as a casting
director, but then they surprise us with things that don't
``belong'' there; he hears the variety and music of different kinds
of speech; he knows what things look like and how they feel in the
hand; he has learned how a fishing boat works and how complicated
the human heart is. His words are like stones, polished smooth,
then dropped into great depths, leaving every-widening ripples of
implication.
</P>
<P>
   Or, to make another comparison, his words are like fundamentals
in a musical bass, releasing many overtones, some of them
dissonant, but affecting the character of the harmony. The book
demonstrates the value of instinct, the virtue of thinking twice.
Payne sees his characters for who they are, accepts them, loves
them, and joins their voices in a hymn of life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
