<P>
   CELL-PHONE-PRIVACY (Washington) _ In what privacy rights
advocates say is a significant threat to civil liberties in the
digital age, the FBI may soon be able to turn the cellular phone
into a ready-made tool for nosing around in private lives. If a
federal rule stands up to a court challenge here, f ederal and
state law enforcement agencies will be allowed to track a cell
phone user's location while monitoring bank and data transactions
made with the device _ all without the need for a court-ordered
wiretap. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
