<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   CLONE _ Send in the clones. The only privately owned cloned
animal in the country (maybe the world) is celebrating its first
birthday. And owner/rancher/jester Ralph Fisher of La Grange is
hosting a birthday party with 300 guests on Sat. Aug. 12 for
``Second Chance,'' the clone of Fisher's favorite old dead Brahman
Bull, ``Chance.'' It's all so eerie. Second Chance acts and looks
just like Chance, even down to finding the one perfect little nap
spot on a 50-acre spread. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-POLICY _ Smokey Bear's done his job. Perhaps too well in
the tinder-dry West. The U.S. Forest Service mascot who cheers the
notion of preventing forest fires succeeded in instilling fear of
fire into generations of Americans. But he may also have cast a
stigma on a land management tool that maybe could have diminished
the fuels - overgrown brush and trees that have grown unchecked for
decades - that have fed this summer's burns. ``We have been in the
mode to suppress,'' said Martha Ketelle, supervisor of the White
River National Forest. ``We have seen a buildup of fuels on most
national forests as a result of the policy.'' (Grand Junction)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-DISEASE _ JERUSALEM _ The cliche is that diseases don't
know borders. As a result, medicine is one of the prime areas of
cooperation between Arabs and Jews. A Palm Beach, Fla. infectious
disease specialist Sandford Kuvin has been exploiting that fact to
try to stamp out a widespread, and often fatal, parasitic disease,
Leishmaniasis. At the Jerusalem-based Kuvin Centre for the Study of
Infectious and Tropical Diseases, several Arab students work under
Israeli professors in researching the disease throughout Israel and
the West Bank. The students are among the Palestinians first
home-grown class of doctors. The center, recognized by the United
Nations, has projects from Israel to Tunisia and has been able to
navigate around the region's politics. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
