<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8891 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-OLD-HOUSE-HNS &LR;      08-11 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-HOUSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENTREPRENEUR RESTORES HOME THAT SURVIVED QUAKE, FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD PAOLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is the oldest house in San Francisco and it
sits on top of what is arguably the city's most expensive three-car
garage.
</P>
<P>
   It is 1032 Broadway, a home on the saddle of Nob Hill originally
built in 1853 with subsequent additions designed by architect
Willis Polk at the turn of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   It earned a nickname as the ``Flag House'' in the fiery
aftermath of the 1906 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this piece of Bay Area history has become the latest
sample of Mitch Menaged's love affair with San Francisco's old
houses. The painstakingly restored home will go on sale next week.
The asking price is $4,995,000.
</P>
<P>
   To the highest bidder will go a four-bedroom, four-bath,
five-fireplace home with sweeping views of the San Francisco Bay
and downtown.
</P>
<P>
   There also is a three-car garage cut into the hillside and an
elevator to whisk homeowners to and from their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two years to do this project,'' said Menaged, leaning
back against the granite kitchen counter top. ``It's one of best
I've worked on and one of the most challenging,'' said a man who
views his work with a mixture of enthusiasm and modesty.
</P>
<P>
   Menaged's company, Historic San Francisco Homes, has an
established reputation for restoring older homes _ and for
providing surprising entertainment at the openings. This event will
be no exception. When asked what it will be, Menaged grinned and
simply said: ``It will be the best we've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   A preview for invited guests will be held at the house on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent tour of the older part of the house, Menaged
pointed excitedly to the brass plaque near the front door bearing
the 1853 date; to the hand-carved pillars at the foot of the
interior staircase; and to the original flooring.
</P>
<P>
   Beams from a ship's cabin brace the dining room ceiling. The
wood has been carefully cleaned and covered with a protective
stain.
</P>
<P>
   On the upper floor of the original section of the home, Menaged
led a visitor to the master bathroom. ``You really have to see
this,'' he said. And there stood a corner bathtub with a view of
the Bay on one side and of the Financial District on the other, a
clear glass-enclosed double shower, separate sinks and smooth stone
floors.
</P>
<P>
   While the restoration work below breathed history back into the
building, the upper floors glowed with luxury. The high ceilings
and tall doors have been kept; hardwood floors and fireplace
mantles have been stripped and cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   It is not merely love of art and history of the old house that
has made Menaged take such pains with the restoration. ``This is a
registered historic landmark and the landmark preservation people
had access during the work here,'' he said. ``It also means that
there is an oversight provided to assure we maintain the historical
integrity of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   The house was originally built for Joseph H. Atkins, a brick
contractor. After the 1906 earthquake and during the ensuing fire,
the army was ordered to dynamite the house on Nob Hill. But Aktins'
descendants raised the U.S. flag over the house and the soldiers
refused to destroy the home.
</P>
<P>
   It was Atkins' daughter, Catherine, who hired Willis Polk to
expand the house at the turn of the last century.
</P>
<P>
   For Menaged, this project now ends, but others he is working on
continue around San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 2,500 of these historic homes in San Francisco. In
the past several years, my company has done 100 restorations. There
are still lots to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
