<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CHILD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EVEN THE KID CAN'T SAVE `BLESS THIS CHILD' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRIS WORRELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The most entertaining thing about ``Bless the
Child'' is that Satan's last stand takes place in a creepy mansion
off Route 17 ``just outside Albany.'' It's a rare and
unintentionally hilarious moment in an otherwise hollow and
familiar film. Never mind that the real Route 17 is closer to New
York City than the state capital. Bad geography is the least of
this film's problems.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of ``Bless the Child'' seems more like a haunted house
at an amusement park than a genuinely scary good-vs.-evil movie.
It's as if the filmmakers went down a checklist of things generally
found in horror and supernatural films and then crammed them all
into one movie. Rats? Check. Rolling heads? Check. Flying demons,
bats and gargoyles? Check, check, check.
</P>
<P>
   The story revolves around Maggie O'Connors (Kim Basinger), a
nurse in a New York hospital whose stringy-haired, strung-out kid
sister, Jenna (Angela Bettis), shows up on her doorstep one rainy
Christmas Eve and saddles Maggie with an autistic newborn named
Cody.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie mothers the abandoned baby until six years later, when
Jenna suddenly reappears and, with her mysterious new husband, Eric
Stark (Rufus Sewell), abducts Cody (Holliston Coleman). Despite the
fact that Maggie has no legal rights to Cody, FBI agent John Travis
(Jimmy Smits), an expert in ritual homicide and occult-related
crime, takes up her cause when he realizes that Cody shares the
same birth date as several other recently missing children.
</P>
<P>
   But Cody is different. She revives dead birds. She makes plates
spin. She hugs people. She is obviously mankind's last hope. Sound
familiar? Screenwriters Clifford and Ellen Green also wrote ``The
Seventh Sign,'' a 1988 movie starring Demi Moore as the mother of
mankind's other last hope.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key elements of bad horror movies is that they must
feature a completely idiotic heroine, someone so empty-headed that
she trusts the wrong people, walks into abandoned alleys and opens
doors that any fool knows should be left closed. Hmmm, should she
confront Satan's foot soldiers alone, in the dark (gasp!) woods?
Why of course! What could happen? Everybody loves a blonde!
</P>
<P>
   Basinger does her best Stepford-wife imitation here. Without
even a hint of personality, Basinger sleepwalks her way through
encounters with some of horror's greatest hits: Druid symbols,
Satanic teenagers, creepy cults.
</P>
<P>
   The considerable talents of Ian Holm (``The Sweet Hereafter'')
are wasted in his role as Rev. Grissom, a wheelchair-bound
ex-priest who is meant to lend moral heft to the movie but instead
merely delivers more hocus-pocus.
</P>
<P>
   And poor Jimmy Smits. The talented actor left his role as a
strong but caring detective on television's ``NYPD Blue'' only to
be cast in this movie as a strong but caring detective who isn't as
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Director Chuck Russell, who also directed the fast-paced films
``The Mask'' and ``Eraser,'' takes the opposite approach here,
slowing down the action to a painful crawl. He even filmed some
segments in slow motion, perhaps to detract from the robotic
Basinger.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 7-year-old Holliston Coleman, who plays Cody, delivers
the best performance of the film. She's cute, and you can tell she
really wants to save the world. She just couldn't save this movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
