<HEADLINE>
HILLARY REVISITED
</HEADLINE>
  Time for a second look at first lady 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Rob LowmanJust in time for the this week's Democratic Convention in
Los Angeles is the release of the paperback version of Gail
Sheehy's look at the first lady, ``Hillary's Choice'' ($16;
Ballantine).
</P>
<P>
   The book brought mixed reviews when it was released last year,
but Sheehy has made some revisions and has added a chapter now that
the first lady is running for a U.S. Senate from New York State.
</P>
<P>
   In the new material, Sheehy discusses: why Hillary is running;
whether the withdrawal of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from the
race over health and marital woes has helped or hurt her cause;
what the president feels now that the roles are being reversed;
what professional women in New York think about her; and what she
has learned now that she's out in the spotlight instead of being
behind the scenes managing Bill's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The book also dives into the Clinton marriage, which has been
rocked more than once by the president's affairs, and why Hillary
has stayed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is in many ways the classic philanderer, like a
little boy who comes back after being bad and looks for Mother's
forgiveness. Hillary provides it,'' Sheehy writes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you buy that or not is up to you, but with Bill and
Hillary running around town this week, it makes for interesting
reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
