<HEADER>
A8905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COSTARICA-CHILDSEX-$A     08-11 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-CHILDSEX-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COSTA RICA CLAMPING DOWN ON SEXUAL EXPLOITATION OF CHILDREN
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With COSTARICA-CRIME-$ADV13.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ The girls giggle in their classroom. They
laugh and joke with each other as they mop the floors and clean the
bathrooms of the large, comfortable house where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita, who is 14, arranges her teddy bears on her bunk bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here,'' she says of the shelter for homeless girls
run by the Salvation Army on the outskirts of this capital city.
``It's much prettier than the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Just six months ago, Juanita was a troubled runaway, standing on
a darkened corner in San Jose's tourist district, offering to have
sex with foreign men for money.
</P>
<P>
   Children's' advocates say Central America has become a Mecca for
the sex tourism industry, fed by graphic sites on the Internet that
advertise an anything-goes atmosphere, cheap travel costs and
crackdowns in more well-known sex tourism centers like Thailand and
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Exploitation of children _ both boys and girls _ is the seamier
underside of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   As Central America's most prosperous, stable nation and its top
tourist destination, Costa Rica has been at the center of an
international spotlight on the problem. Prostitution is legal and
regulated by the government here _ but only for women 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedophiles look for three things _ anonymity, poverty and
impunity,'' said Bruce Harris, director of Latin American
operations for Covenant House, a private group that works with
troubled teens in several U.S. cities, as well as in Central
America. ``They find them here. These children are desperate and
vulnerable, and the government has not assumed its responsibility
for taking care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris cites a U.S. State Department report that estimates as
many as 3,000 underage children may be sexually exploited in Costa
Rica, as well as a United Nations committee that expressed concern
over the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rican officials say the numbers are a gross exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To give that type of number is irresponsible,'' said Lilliam
Gomez(CQ Both), the country's top prosecutor for sex crimes. ``It's
clear the problem exists, but not in that dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of their country's reputation as a family-oriented
tourism gem, government officials have taken steps to combat the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   New laws have been passed outlawing sex with children, and
perpetrators face prison terms of up to 10 years. Gomez has been
promised that her understaffed division will be beefed up, although
she has yet to see any increase in resources.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also funded a national ``Save Our Children''
advertising campaign, featuring television and print ads reminding
the public that children are the nation's most valuable resource.
Brochures will be printed for distribution to arriving visitors,
warning that sex with children is unlawful, while government
Internet sites pushing Costa Rican tourism will do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want those kinds of people coming here, and we don't
want our country known for that type of activity,'' said Costa
Rica's Tourism Minister, Walter Niehaus. ``We take this very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have also cracked down on San Jose's red-light district.
While visitors can still find legal prostitutes in a number of bars
and casinos that cater to tourists, the bands of underage boys and
girls who only a few months ago roamed the district and brazenly
propositioned foreign men are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Several well-publicized raids have swept them from the streets
and also hampered the operation of private homes that serve as
brothels.
</P>
<P>
   But under-age prostitutes are still available. Visitors need
only ask a taxi driver outside any of the downtown bars, and they
will be taken to a private home where girls clearly under the age
of 18 make themselves available, sometimes for as little as US$16.
</P>
<P>
   Niehaus says he'll soon start a program in which taxi drivers
will display stickers warning their passengers not to ask for help
in finding young girls for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says the government efforts are inadequate, aimed more at
spiffing up Costa Rica's image than helping the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' he said. ``Until we see a big sign at
the airport showing the pictures of foreigners behind bars instead
of this dancing around to protect the country's image, nothing will
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Vargas, director of children's' programs for the Salvation
Army and a former governor of San Jose province, says the problem
is part of a wider crisis of delinquency and drug-use among Costa
Rica's youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society has lost its values,'' he said. ``We need a change
in attitude by the public. This problem can't be solved by the
police alone. Society must understand that if we don't help these
children, they will only grow up into lives of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In rural Costa Rica, girls have traditionally married at a young
age, and while there are no hard statistics, there are reports that
sexual abuse of children within families is not infrequent.
Nationwide, a quarter of Costa Rican mothers have their first child
between the ages of 15 and 18, and 41 percent of children are born
to single mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita _ a fictitious name, since Costa Rican law protects the
identity of minors _ began her prostitution career at age 12.
Living in a rural province, she rebelled against her parents,
sleeping with boys for fun and for pay. She ran away, lived with
the family of a friend, and then was turned over to the child
welfare agency when she got caught having sex with that family's
15-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   She was sent to the Salvation Army shelter in San Jose, but ran
away for about a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy to be a prostitute,'' she said. ``I went to a park
and asked around and they told me where to go. I would stand on a
corner. All my clients were foreigners. I made about 30,000 colones
(US$100) a night.''
</P>
<P>
   Her money went for clothes and drugs for her friends. But she
gave it up after growing tired of the hard life on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly and cold,'' she said. ``I like it better here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maricela Barboza, a psychologist at the shelter, said most of
the girls come from broken families, where many were sexually
abused by relatives. Some, like Juanita, stay for months at the
shelter and seem ready to turn their lives around.
</P>
<P>
   But others stay only a few days to rest, clean up and eat well,
before running away again to lives of drugs and exploitation on the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard for us to keep them here,'' she said. ``These
girls can make as much in one night as they would earn in one month
in a regular job.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams may be contacted at: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.tourism-costarica.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.casa-alianza.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
