<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-THIN-BLUE_LIE-REVIEW-     08-11 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIN-BLUE_LIE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIN BLUE LIE' NEEDS A THICK RED PENCIL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sun., Aug. 13.) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
``The Thin Blue Lie'' _ a cunning take on ``The Thin Blue Line,'' a
phrase once used to describe the difficult position police find
themselves in, separating us from anarchy and also on the '80s film
of that name _ is an almost stirring yet all too familiar story
about a renegade journalist bucking the odds and effecting social
change.
</P>
<P>
   This film opens with a montage essaying recent examples of
police brutality and corruption, L.A. and New York obviously
earning the most screen time. The point is to imply that the story
herein _ set in 1976 in Philadelphia _ is the granddaddy of all
these cases, as if corruption didn't exist until then. Indeed, many
of the journalists depicted here are clueless dunderheads trying to
maintain the status quo until the heroes of this film venture onto
the scene and put things right.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Morrow (``Northern Exposure'') stars as Pulitzer
Prize-winning social advocate Jonathan Neumann, who single-handedly
busts open a scandal involving cops beating suspect confessions out
of sometimes innocent suspects. No one, naturally, is interested in
his theories _ in fact, other journalists dump threats on his head
as unambiguous as those of the corrupt cops themselves _ yet he
perseveres and ultimately triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the film's veracity, it all plays as awfully
self-serving and programmatic. Neumann seems to operate in a
bizarre vacuum in which his uniquely selfless deeds protect him
from both horribly violent cop threats and his own editors'
involvement, or lack thereof. Every other reporter in town _ even
Phil Chadway (Randy Quaid), who joined forces with him on his quest
for truth and shared his Pulitzer _ is depicted as a clueless
moron.
</P>
<P>
   Only Paul Sorvino's eccentric turn as psycho-mayor Frank Rizzo
offers any color to a story perfunctorily rendered. Neumann is even
allowed a vaguely romantic encounter with a vapid blond who comes
to realize the purity of his mission. Journalists, of course,
fantasize about such nonsense; only middling TV movies allow them
such luxuries. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``The Thin Blue Lie.'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama about corruption among Philadelphia homicide
detectives in the '70s. &QL; 
The stars: Rob Morrow, Randy Quaid, Paul Sorvino, Cynthia Preston. &QL; 
Where: Showtime. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1444EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
