u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      08-11 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
CLINTON WILL TELL CONVENTION OF HUGE DIFFERENCES WITH BUSH &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)
 &HT;    By HELEN THOMAS
 &HT;    c.2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will use his farewell address to
the Democratic National Convention on Monday night to lay out his
accomplishments of the last few years and speak out on what he
believes are the ``profound philosophical differences'' between the
two political parties.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton believes
Americans have ``a clear and very distinct choice this year''
between building on the economic and social success of his years in
office, or making ``U-turn back to policies that have failed in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect any more apologies from Clinton for the Monica
Lewinsky affair as a couple of close friends have suggested,
Lockhart said, adding ``and 600 others in the White House think
would be crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Give him a break. What can you say after you've said you are
sorry?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton probably also is counting on ``Monica fatigue'' by
Americans who believe enough is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, didn't Vice President Al Gore, who hopes to succeed
Clinton, take a giant step to remove himself from Clinton baggage
when he named Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his running mate?
Lieberman's one claim to national fame is that he denounced
Clinton's behavior as ``immoral'' in stunning speech on the Senate
floor which was a curtain raiser to Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's devastating lecture was widely interpreted as a slap
at Clinton. The president responded by turning the other cheek and
praising Lieberman's selection, calling him a ``good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   In his sentimental valedictory, Clinton will be stressing the
``huge differences'' with the Republican ticket, headed by Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, in terms of economic, crime, health and
education policies. He also plans to sound a warning that ``the
next president will make two to four appointments to the Supreme
Court'' which he said would assure a conservative majority on the
high bench.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Gore camp seems less than gracious in seeking to
dissociate the Democratic presidential hopeful from the president,
Clinton is taking it all in stride, knowing the exigencies of
politics, not to mention the opposition attempts to make him the
issue in the election.
</P>
<P>
   Aides say that Clinton will be lavish in his praise of Gore and
toss him many bouquets when he walks on the convention stage in Los
Angeles Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   That is more generous than the parting shots of some of his
predecessors. Clinton aides have been gleaning the farewell
convention speeches of some other presidents. They found it notable
that outgoing President Dwight D. Eisenhower's lengthy address to
the GOP convention on July 26, 1960, failed to mention Vice
President Richard Nixon who hoped to succeed him in the fall
election that year.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not surprising in view of one of his last news
conferences as president, Eisenhower was asked what Nixon had
contributed to his administration as vice president. Eisenhower's
famous reply: ``If you give me a week, I'll think of something.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 15, 1988, President Ronald Reagan strongly supported
Vice President George Bush as his successor in the White House and
told the convention that Bush had helped him to overcome ``liberal
opposition to put our programs in place.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added ``without George Bush to build on those policies,
everything we've achieved will be at risk. All the work, sacrifice
and effort of the American people could end in the very same
disaster that we inherited in 1981.''
</P>
<P>
   For President Clinton, it's payback time. He is sparing nothing
to try to help his wife Hillary win a Senate seat in New York,
particularly in the fund-raising department.
</P>
<P>
   It's a turnabout since she has devoted most of her married life
pitching in to promote her husband's political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seems particularly anxious to cut off at the pass her
critics who claim she has not done anything on her own.
</P>
<P>
   He told a recent New York fund-raising dinner that he and his
wife had been looking forward to relaxing ``a little bit'' during
his last months in the White House but when a group of New York
Democrats asked her to run, ``she understood it was important to
carry on the work that we have been about these last eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this,'' he said, ``for 30 years all he ever did
was help everybody else and I'm kind of proud of her for sort of
venturing out on her own now and trying to do something for
herself.''
</P>
<P>
   He then proceeded to tick off all of the work the first lady had
done to promote the Family Medical Leave Act, the Children's
Insurance program, as well as her efforts to promote adoption of
children with disabilities and foster care for needy kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people that are trying to beat her will spare no
effort or no expense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also told the potential donors that his wife ``won't let you
down, and she'll be great in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart is taking his
predecessor Mike McCurry's word for it: ``There is life after the
White House.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry is now running a lucrative consulting business, hitting
the lecture circuit and getting with it in the dot-com world.
</P>
<P>
   What's more he also gets to see his children now, a difficult
feat when he was at the beck and call of a president and the
Washington press corps.
</P>
<P>
   So Lockhart is sorting out several offers, mostly in the
communications field and looking forward to quitting his
high-profile position in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It is always a glorious occasion for the nation to see that all
of our heroes are not from battlefields. True humanity and
sacrifice are on display when a president hands out the Medal of
Freedom, the nation's highest civilian award, at White House
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, humor is injected in the solemn occasion.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton presented the medal to famed economist
John Kenneth Galbraith, he said: ``It is ironic that John Kenneth
Galbraith actually coined the term 'conventional wisdom,' since he
spent his entire life challenging it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also evoked laughter when he said it was suspected
that President John F. Kennedy sent Galbraith to India as the U.S.
Ambassador ``to be free of his political advice and policy ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
