<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-NICAR-STREETKIDS-NEWH     08-11 2230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICAR-STREETKIDS-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NICARAGUA, AN EXPLOSION OF STREET KIDS
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, AUGUST 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ART ADV: With three photos, of Ivan (NNS1), Freddie (NNS2) and
Roberto (NNS3)
 By JAMES HODGE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANADA, Nicaragua -- Like a starving dog, a small boy steals
into the trendy restaurant at dusk, slinking across the floor
toward the nearest table. His eyes dart around the room before he
reaches up to touch the arm of a tourist tasting filete jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   The startled American looks down, and the Nicaraguan boy
flinches as if expecting to be struck. ``Comida?'' he whispers,
cocking his head to one side. ``Comida?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wants something to eat,'' says a woman at the
table. The man starts to break off a piece of bread, but another
customer, loosening his belt, interjects, ``No, don't. You'll just
encourage them.'' With a wave of his hand, he shoos the small
beggar away.
</P>
<P>
   As he heads toward the door, the boy looks back at the bread and
then disappears into the night, his hunger compounded by
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, who looks about 8, is part of a growing army of
school-age children who roam the streets each day, begging,
performing menial tasks and selling trinkets or themselves. Hordes
pick through garbage cans, sometimes fighting with dogs or other
youths for scraps of rotting food.
</P>
<P>
   Many sniff cobbler's glue, kept in baby food jars. The vapors
ward off hunger pangs and give them a feeling of euphoria, an
escape, at least for a few hours, from the harsh reality of the
street.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to spot them: They pull their T-shirts over their
faces when inhaling the deadly vapors. Soon their eyes become
vacant, glazed over. They lie down in doorways or on sidewalks,
flies buzzing around their faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terribly disturbing,'' said Dr. Frank Incaprera, a
retired New Orleans internist who has treated Granada street
children during medical missions sponsored by the Archdiocese of
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The future for these children is grim. ``Most already suffer
from malnutrition and intestinal parasites,'' he said. ``The glue
causes liver and irreversible brain damage. Their life spans are
not long.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a shabby bunch of kids,'' he said, ``yet all lovable,
with delightful smiles. They really tug at your heartstrings.''
</P>
<P>
   According to UNICEF, 40 million children live or work on the
streets of Latin America, more than half of whom sniff glue. The
explosion of street children has been called the dark side of
globalization, paralleling the rise in unemployment and poverty
levels in many Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Nicaragua, where half of the country's 5 million people are
under 17, the per capita income is little more than $1 a day, and
unemployment has soared as high as 60 percent in the decade since
the Sandinistas were defeated, ending an 11-year effort to build a
socialist state.
</P>
<P>
   Crippling foreign debt coupled with the ravages of Hurricane
Mitch have kept Nicaragua the second-poorest country in the Western
Hemisphere, after Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to implement austerity programs to obtain loans through
the International Monetary Fund, the government has drastically
slashed social programs, leaving the fate of the poor largely in
the hands of charities.
</P>
<P>
   In Granada, one of the few refuges for street children is Cristo
Sana-Los Ninos, a center established by the New Orleans
Archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   The program is a spinoff of the archdiocese's Nicaraguan medical
mission launched in the early 1990s by Bishop Gregory Aymond and
Marianite Sister Mary Bertilla McNeely, a nurse who had worked in
famine-ravaged Somalia as well as at health clinics in poor New
Orleans neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   When the medical teams returned increasingly disturbed by the
street children, Aymond sent a social worker to do a needs
assessment and then recruited Sister Renee Daigle to set up Los
Ninos for boys ages 6 to 15. The nun, now the vocational director
for the Marianites, contacted Granada's wealthier women for
donations and obtained a rundown building that New Orleans
seminarians helped renovate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center gives them some safe space, adults they can
trust,'' Sister Daigle said. ``The ultimate goal is to get them
back home, in drug rehab or in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds, she realizes, are not auspicious. Many of the boys
fled abuse at home, the rehab facilities are few, and most cannot
afford the school book and registration fees the government charges
to cut public spending. Although the constitution guarantees every
child a free education, hundreds of thousands of Nicaraguan
children are not in school, child welfare agencies say.
</P>
<P>
   Los Ninos provides some educational instruction, but because of
limited money, the center is open only from 8:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m.
During that time, dozens of boys are given breakfast and lunch,
take showers, and receive lessons in personal hygiene, social
skills and crafts.
</P>
<P>
   The center, located on a busy street not far from the town
square, is run by a Salvadoran nun, Sister Ana Rosa. She is helped
by Adela Lacayo, a former New Orleans resident who heads the
archdiocese's Cristo Sana board in Granada and helps coordinate its
medical missions.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, boys, hungry and happy to have survived another
night on the street, wander over to the brown and white stucco
building with its high arched doorway and wait for the nun to open
the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Those reeking of glue aren't allowed in, but can stay in the
entrance hall where they are fed. Those who are glue-free are
greeted with a large welcoming banner reading ``Bienvenidos'' and
the warm friendliness of Sister Ana Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   Among the regulars these days is 7-year-old Manuel. Sitting at a
table in an open room with tile floors and padded benches, he's
eagerly attempting the schoolwork the nun has given him. He boasts
he can write his name and proudly holds up his paper, but it's
filled only with a string of OOOOOs.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Ana Rosa said he's one of nine children in his family.
Six of his brothers live on the street. One of them is languishing
on the floor of the entrance hall with the other glue-sniffers
behind a red iron gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mother has no husband. She's desperate and sends her
kids out to beg. Manuel sometimes sleeps at a park,'' she said,
voicing her wish that Los Ninos could provide sleeping
accommodations. Every afternoon, she said, ``it breaks my heart to
turn them back out onto the street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One day that may change,'' said Lacayo, the granddaughter of a
former Nicaraguan president, who promised Sister McNeely before her
death last year that she would help the street children. ``The land
has been purchased, but we are still trying to raise money to
build'' a residential facility, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For now, we do what we can,'' Sister Ana Rosa said, walking
down a hall to a small room where some boys are making a Winnie the
Pooh pinata to sell. Outside on a patio under a tin roof, other
boys make hemp wall hangings by wrapping pieces of colorful rope
around nails hammered in various designs on plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Learning to make crafts not only adds to the family income, but
can lower the level of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many poor women can't find jobs,'' the nun said. ``They can't
afford to feed their children and send them out to beg.'' When they
come home empty-handed, the mothers sometimes abuse them, she said.
</P>
<P>
   One Los Ninos boy, now 14, is a case in point. ``When he was 5,
he came home with nothing to show for the day,'' she said. ``His
mother strung him over firewood, built a fire and burned his feet.
He still has the scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the horrible poverty that is the root of the abuse,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   James Wright, a sociologist at Tulane University in New Orleans,
agreed: ``Conditions of extreme poverty and deprivation lead to
desperate behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The brutal reality for many Nicaraguan youths is that their
childhood ends at the age American children begin kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children in Latin America can be an economic asset by the time
they're 5,'' said Wright, co-author of a study on street children
in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason, he said, ``you see them swarming everywhere:
in the street, in the markets, at the airport, hanging around
churches. They come up to carry your bag, to sell you chewing gum,
to sell you candy. Everywhere you go, there's just these swarms of
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   A child's meager earnings can make a significant difference to a
family. School becomes secondary to survival.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by the twisted logic of the streets, children, the
younger and cuter the better, are the most effective beggars. When
they get older, they're seen as a nuisance, even a threat. And with
little education and little opportunity to earn money, they often
resort to petty theft or prostitution to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Wright sees little chance of an economic turnaround in Nicaragua
any time soon. ``Everyone understands that as long as poor nations
are saddled with the kind of foreign debt that they're saddled
with, they're never going to get anywhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the economic changes undertaken to reduce that debt --
slashing of publicly financed social services and privatization of
state-run industries -- tend to drive up unemployment, at least in
the short term.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the number of street children grows, especially
as land reform efforts fail and rural migrants keep flowing into
cities looking for work.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   While severe poverty may be the underlying factor, for many
children the more immediate reason for living on the street is to
flee physical, emotional or sexual abuse at home, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the abuse doesn't end when they leave home. Out
on the street, they fall easy prey to sexual predators. And they're
frequently targeted by police whom merchants hire to clear the
streets in front of their shops, human rights groups say. In one
high-profile incident in 1993, eight homeless children were shot to
death by off-duty policemen in Brazil as they slept across the
street from a church that was a prominent tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   In Nicaragua, politicians have recently scapegoated street
children for an increase in serious crime, said Bruce Harris,
executive director of Casa Alianza, the Latin America arm of
Covenant House, the largest privately-funded childcare agency in
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   More than 95 percent of serious crime in Nicaragua is committed
by adults, Harris said, and if officials want a crackdown, it
should be aimed at poverty and unemployment, the roots of the
growing violence.
</P>
<P>
   Brutal as police can be, a lack of law enforcement can do
violence of another kind, some child advocates say, especially when
it comes to the sale of glue.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Tabor, a former Peace Corps volunteer who works with
street children and helps Sister Ana Rosa at Los Ninos, said:
``I've watched police in Granada's central park turn a blind eye to
these children and to the street vendors who sell the glue to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some in the community who have the power to curb this,
death by glue seems more of a solution to a problem than a
tragedy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Covenant House and other child welfare agencies have tried for
years to cut off the sources of the glue that Latin American
children consume at a rate of about 20 million gallons a month.
</P>
<P>
   Their main target has been H.B. Fuller Co., a $1.3 billion
corporation in Minnesota that supplies 70 percent of the
solvent-based glue used in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller has steadfastly refused to add a noxious oil to its glue
to discourage abuse, but in January, it quietly announced that it
had stopped its sales of addictive shoe glues in Latin America as
of November.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, for one, isn't holding his breath. After years of
lobbying, he said he welcomes the announcement but cautions that
the company made similar statements in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   In its recent statement, the company said it won't recall its
products and estimated it would take three to five months to
exhaust current inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Tabor said she has seen no drop-off in the availability of glue
in Granada. ``Actually, I think it's increased.''
</P>
<P>
   Tabor knows that the children's dirty clothes, skin rashes and
pesky persistence alienate people, but she can't understand the
cold indifference they are accorded by the more fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   She's heard people refer to them as vermin. ``They would rather
throw away their leftovers than give them to a hungry child, always
with an excuse -- let's not encourage begging or make them
dependent on us. They never look them in the eyes, leaving the
children to feel subhuman,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   -------- (James Hodge is a staff writer for The Times-Picayune
of New Orleans)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
