<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-CRIME-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMAGE IS EVERYTHING: COSTA RICA REASSURING TOURISTS FOLLOWING
RECENT CRIMES
 &HT;    EDs: photos available for Cox Newspapers only.
 &HT;    With COSTARICA-CHILDSEX-$ADV13.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Costa Rica - With no national army, a prosperous
economy and an enviable record of free, fair elections, Costa Rica
has been a beacon of peace and stability in a region beset by
military coups, civil wars and corrupt dictatorships.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months this tranquil oasis and beloved tourist
destination has been shaken by a crimewave against residents and
visitors, triggering worries that some of the outside world's
problems may finally be catching up to once-isolated, idyllic Costa
Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Local newspapers have been filled with stories of a few
sensational crimes, including a July kidnapping that resulted in a
shoot-out that left one hostage dead and three police officers
wounded. The country also saw a flurry of unflattering
international stories following the murders of two American college
students on the Caribbean coast in March.
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile cases have sparked a round of national
soul-searching in this country of 3.5 million residents, which
prides itself on being known as the ``Switzerland of Central
America'' because of its long tradition of neutrality and peace.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, a national debate over the causes and proposed
solutions to the crimewave has swirled through this capital city,
with some leaders calling for more police, more prosecutors and
stiffer penalties for criminals. Others say what is needed is a
return to traditional values.
</P>
<P>
   Even an annual religious festival in early August drew attention
to the problem, as Costa Rica's top Catholic cleric prayed for the
country to find a way to end the violence that has upset so many.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception of the citizens about the problem of insecurity
is very high,'' said Rogelio Ramos, Minister of Public Security.
``It's because we have such a long tradition of peace that a small
number of incidents can leave the country shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos is quick to point out that even with the recent spate of
crimes, Costa Rica is still one of the safest countries in the
hemisphere, with an enviable record of catching and convicting
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the lowest index of murders in the hemisphere, less
than six for every 100,000 residents,'' he said. ``Besides that,
the judicial police solve more than 90 percent of the murders,
which means that if you commit murder here, you have a 90 percent
chance of going to jail for it. And more than 70 percent of all
crime here are property crimes that don't involve violence,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Those facts seem lost in the wave of public concern, however.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, one of the country's top law-enforcement officials
told reporters her agency doesn't have the resources to meet the
growing crime problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is worrying,'' said Lineth Saborio, head of the
Costa Rican Office of Judicial Investigations, the country's
equivalent of the FBI. ``The level of violence is beyond the
ability of the police to cope with.''
</P>
<P>
   Her plea for more resources came just as the government is
discussing budgets for next year. While there have been reports
that the agency might suffer some funding cuts, Ramos insisted that
the resources would be found to deal with the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a new investigative team is being formed to fight
kidnappers, he said. The group will receive special training from
the Colombian police, who have lots of experience as their country
suffers the highest rate of kidnapping in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rican leaders say the increase in crime is due to several
factors, many of which plague other countries, including the United
States. The list includes poverty, a loss of traditional values of
respect for others, the influence of violent television and movies,
violent games and sites on the Internet, and an influx of mostly
poor immigrants from other countries _ some of whom turn to crime
out of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly worrisome is the fear that juvenile delinquency _
among both boys and girls _ is on the rise. While no hard
statistics are available, news accounts paint portraits of boys
involved in petty theft and even armed crimes, while girls as young
as 12 and 13 have become part of the sex trade. Many of the
customers are foreign visitors attracted to Costa Rica because
prostitution is legal for women 18 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Vargas, former governor of the province that includes San
Jose and now director of youth programs for the Salvation Army,
says the problems stem from broken homes and dysfunctional
families. He worries that the nation is already facing a generation
of lost kids who are growing up to lives of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're seeing those that 10 years ago were delinquents are
20 years old and involved in serious crime,'' he said. ``In the
last 10 years the problem with drugs has become more acute, but
unfortunately neither the state or society gave it the proper
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major worry for many in Costa Rica is that the growing
crime rate will hurt tourism, which has become one of the nation's
top industries along with agriculture and light manufacturing. Last
year, more than 1 million visitors came to Costa Rica, spending
nearly $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The March murders of Emily Howell of Lexington, Ky. and Emily
Eagen of Ann Arbor, Mich., both of whom had attended Antioch
College in Yellow springs, Ohio, stunned Costa Rica and triggered a
torrent of international publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested two young men for the crime, one of whom was
recently convicted and sentenced to 15 years in jail _ the maximum
allowed in Costa Rica for a juvenile. The other youth, who is an
adult, faces trial soon. Police are still seeking another man, a
Nicaraguan, in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The two 19-year-old women were staying near the Caribbean resort
of Puerto Viejo when the crime occurred. The area is popular with
college students and young tourists seeking the exotic rhythms and
Caribbean flavor there, but it is also known to be more
crime-ridden than the rest of Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Niehaus, head of the Costa Rican Institute for Tourism, a
Cabinet-level agency, said tourist bookings dropped by about 1
percent in the months immediately following the killings but have
since recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of Costa Rica was shocked by the killings, and we gave our
true feelings to the families,'' he said. ``But it was an isolated
incident. The police acted immediately and two men are now in
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Niehaus and other top officials reacted aggressively to reassure
would-be travelers that Costa Rica is still a safe destination.
Responding to an invitation from former Florida Gov. Kenneth H.
``Buddy'' MacKay Jr., who is now President Clinton's special envoy
for Latin America, Niehaus headed a delegation of officials to
Miami-Dade County in June. There they studied South Florida's
response to a rash of tourist killings and crimes in the early
1990s that triggered a similar round of negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very helpful,'' Niehaus said, noting that Miami had set
up special signs to help guide tourists around the city. ``We are
going to have security brochures printed for visitors to advise
them about how to travel safely, along with information on the
Internet. We're also using more bicycle police, and will have a
special branch of tourist police stationed at the most popular
destinations in Costa Rica.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials have also cracked down on the exploitation of
under-age girls for sex, making several street sweeps and raiding
brothels where the girls were available. Visitors will also soon be
given brochures at the San Jose airport _ the primary gateway for
international tourists _ warning that having sex with under-age
girls is a crime and that if caught they will be punished, Niehaus
said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the publicity and public debate, officials insist that
seasoned travelers recognize that Costa Rica's reputation as a
safe, easygoing place is still deserved. While tourists have always
been warned to watch out for pick-pockets and petty thieves, the
government seems serious about taking firm steps against the more
serious crimes that could turn their tourist-rich paradise into a
less-than-desirable destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as bad as it has been made to sound,'' Niehaus said.
``But we are taking action. Because of our peaceful reputation, if
we have one high-profile crime, it gets a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams may be contacted at: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.tourism-costarica.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.tourism.co.cr/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
