<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GLUE WILL HOLD CHAIR JOINT FOR LONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August   13, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am fixing dowel joints in a chair. Is there a better glue
than white or yellow glue to hold those legs? They are always
working loose.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE SWIFT, Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those joints will always work loose because of their design.
You could try two-part epoxy, which might keep them tight for a bit
longer. Recorsinol glue, a two-part glue but not an epoxy, will
also work better, but not much. There is just too much stress from
sitting in these chairs (and leaning back on the back legs) for
them to stay tight for long.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you add wire supports, which keep the leg assembly tight,
the joints will work loose no matter what you do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I got cedar bleed (brown stains) on my cedar siding with
Benjamin Moore's solid oil stain, it washed off OK with detergent
and water. Then when it rained it came back. How can I keep it
away?
</P>
<P>
   LEO COFFEY, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cedar bleed does come off easily enough, usually, but it will
come back, particularly when it rains. The stains are the pigment
(the tannins, really) of the cedar being leached out by water, and
deposited on the siding. As long as you have moisture, particularly
behind the shingles or siding, you will have cedar bleed.
</P>
<P>
   But you can do this: Prepare the surface by sanding and washing,
then apply an exterior primer. This will seal the cedar against
bleeding, just as shellac seals a water stain on a plaster ceiling
to keep it from bleeding through the ceiling paint. Then apply two
thin coats of the Benjamin Moore solid oil stain. The primer
defeats the purpose of the solid stain, because it can peel. It
might not, but it can. It cannot be helped, unless you install
white cedar shingles and let them weather to that Cape Cod silver.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house has gas-fired heat and gas-fired hot water. My flue
pipes keep rusting out. I was told that there are too many trees
around the house, which restrict the chimney draft, and that I
should cut a few down. Another said the moisture causing the rust
is coming through the concrete floor in the basement. I had a
makeup air pipe installed to increase the draft, and a chimney cap,
but neither did much good. An aluminum flue liner failed in one
season. Now What?
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL ALBERT, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Whew! You mentioned the aluminum flue liner failing in a
season. What were the other pipes that failed? I must assume they
were galvanized steel. The problem is not a bad draft, so keep the
trees, unless some are leaning over the house. The problem is
moisture, but it is not the moisture coming from the basement
floor. The aluminum flue liner failed because it was the wrong
kind. The moisture is coming from the fuel. Burning gas creates two
cubic feet of water vapor for each cubic foot of gas burned. That's
a lot of water vapor, and it condenses as it goes up the chimney,
rusting out the flue liners.
</P>
<P>
   Install a stainless steel flue liner, or a special aluminum type
that is recommended by the gas company. In fact, either type of
liner is required when gas is burned.
</P>
<P>
   That has to work. But if it doesn't consider converting your two
heaters into power-vented ones. Power-vented heaters exhaust
low-temperature gases out a PVC pipe through the wall, eliminating
the need for a chimney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is on a concrete slab. I would like to put down a
border of hardwood on the floor, with a rug in the middle. There
are 10-inch vinyl tiles there now, over a layer of 9-inch asphalt
tiles. Can I take off those tiles along the border and substitute a
hardwood floor as a border?
</P>
<P>
   H.K., Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can, but it's a lot of work, can involve checking
for asbestos in both types of tiles and possibly very expensive
removal, if those tiles contain asbestos. Besides, putting hardwood
on the concrete is not a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   So, why not try this: Buy Pergo, the laminated plastic flooring
that looks pretty much like wood but is only about 1/4-inch thick,
and glue it down as a border. Then put the rug in the middle, over
the tiles. The rug and pad are about the same thickness as the
Pergo, so you won't trip over the border.
</P>
<P>
   This way you will avoid lots of headaches. Not only is removal
of the tiles and adhesive difficult, but both the vinyl and asphalt
tiles may contain asbestos. To determine this, you'd have to take
or send a sample of the tiles to an asbestos abatement company or
certified testing laboratory for analysis. Abatement companies are
in the Yellow Pages under Asbestos Abatement, labs under
Laboratories _ Testing.
</P>
<P>
   You can avoid all this by installing wall-to-wall indoor-outdoor
carpet. The tiles are safe as long as they are undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail
hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
