<SLUG> BC-FOUR-HEADED-GORE-ECONOMIST-575&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL THE REAL AL GORE PLEASE STAND UP?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 2 trims, 150 words; 1,100 uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: TWO OPTIONAL TRIMS, TOTALING 150 WORDS, AT 575 AND
775. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,100.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   With the Democrats gathering in Los Angeles for their convention
next week, America's voters will have before them four men bidding
to lead their country. Should they choose the pragmatic politician,
the co-chief executive of their country, who has supervised eight
years of staggering prosperity?
</P>
<P>
   Or what about the dreamy idealist, the policy wonk absorbed by
technology and the environment? Or perhaps the sour, partisan
reactionary _ a brutal attack dog who specializes in ripping apart
the ``risky'' dreams of others?
</P>
<P>
   Or then again, there is the panicky panderer, who changes his
mind about a small Cuban boy's future just to win a few votes in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be too difficult, but for one thing: all four of
these men are Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, consistency is hardly the political profession's main
speciality; the vice president's Republican opponent, George W.
Bush, to name but one, has courted and dropped the religious right
at least twice during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But, given his prominence in public life, the level of doubt not
just about the vice president's basic beliefs but also his
character is remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are not just four Gores to choose from. The whole
tribe could form a queue around the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than providing the usual opportunity to help cull their
number, the campaign so far has merely added more Gores, some of
them (class-warrior Gore, outsider Gore) indecently farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   Even within his personal heartland _ the environment _ there is
a chasm between the eco-zealotry of his recently reissued book,
``Earth in the Balance,'' and the mild measures the vice president
says he wants to enact.
</P>
<P>
   This ambiguity, particularly the sour side of it, is one reason
why many people seem more comfortable with the easier-to-follow
Bush. Fresh from his own convention in Philadelphia, some opinion
polls have put the Texan governor as much as 17 percentage points
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Gore can expect to get a post-convention bounce in the polls as
well, especially given his bold and tactically shrewd choice as his
running-mate of Senator Joseph Lieberman, Bill Clinton's most
prominent Democratic critic over Monica and morals.
</P>
<P>
   But will that be enough? Although Nov. 7 is still a long way
off, no candidate in recent history has rebounded to win having
been behind at the start of September.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is formidable. Yet one thing is clear: Gore should
be an impressive candidate _ and could still become one. After all,
Gore has no need to prove his competence.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Republican National Convention, The Economist asked,
``Is Mr. Bush ready?'' No such doubts exist about a man who already
runs much of the White House's business.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, probably the most involved vice president in history, has
spent a lifetime preparing for the presidency. On wonkish issues
like missile defense, Gore has probably forgotten more than Bush
will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   Second, some of the main issues of the election _ medical care
and Social Security _ are ones where voters have traditionally
preferred Democrats. Gore's incremental approach may be less daring
and prove ultimately less effective than Bush's; but it may be more
in line with voters' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally Gore, as the inheritor of the Clinton economy, has an
impressive record to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Each time the Republicans ask Americans to turn their backs on
the 1990s, they sound like those spoilsport Democrats did during
the Reaganite 1980s. Most Americans have never had it so good. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 575) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gore has already been snarling at Bush's ``risky'' schemes to
endanger that prosperity (not to mention all his other risky plans
for education and Social Security).
</P>
<P>
   A negative campaign can go a long way _ as Gore proved in the
primaries when he ripped apart Bill Bradley's health-care reforms,
whilst offering precious few new ideas of his own. Yet attack can
also backfire. After all, Americans currently give the credit for
their economic good fortune more to the Federal Reserve than the
White House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   There is also the issue of Clinton fatigue: ``change, versus
more of the same,'' as the great man's own campaigners once put it.
And the more Gore snarls, the more he risks emphasizing one of his
weaknesses _ that unlike Clinton and, it seems, Bush, voters do not
find him likeable.
</P>
<P>
   In short, at the upcoming convention, Gore has to speak
convincingly about himself _ and about what he actually believes
in. One advantage of his current predicament is that he now has a
relatively blank slate on which to draw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 75 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 775) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This newspaper's hopes for what he might actually say range from
sadly unrealistic fantasies (he deserts the teachers' unions and
promises structural reform in America's schools) to unlikely hopes
(he revokes his waffle about ``fair trade''), to reasonable
expectations (he expands his measures for gun control).
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gore's general instincts seem creditable _ his
internationalism, for instance; others, particularly his faith in
government intervention, less so. No matter: Bush also has his
faults. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,100) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is to give more indication of what a Gore
presidency might be like. Two people might serve as role models.
The first, bizarrely, is Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, the then-vice president seemed sour and
unfocused and was also at one point 17 points behind a successful
governor, Michael Dukakis. His eventual victory owed much to a very
nasty campaign, which traduced his rival's record.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the lesson, Gore's team, partly staffed by former
Dukakis people, would have no qualms about copying.
</P>
<P>
   But, in 1988, the older Bush also offered a little more. At his
convention, the man derided as ``every woman's first husband''
emerged as an independent character _ and stepped out from
President Ronald Reagan's shadow. Gore now similarly needs to shrug
off Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The second is Lieberman. Not only does the Connecticut senator
convey a much firmer moral compass than Gore; the very act of
choosing him has already shown a bolder side to the vice president
on which he now needs to build.
</P>
<P>
   Some spinmasters argued against putting a Jew, extraordinarily
for the first time ever, on a national ticket; now nobody can
understand what all the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore goes on to win, Lieberman may prove to have been the
turning point. But that will surely only happen if Gore presents
the American people with a coherent account of what his presidency
would be like.
</P>
<P>
   His last chance to start doing that will come in Los Angeles
next week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
