<HEADER>
A8949 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-KASHMIR-GOADS-ECONOMI     08-11 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR-GOADS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KASHMIR PEACE PROCESS: BACK TO GROUND ZERO  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 950-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   After barely a fortnight of frail life, the peace process in
Jammu &AMP; Kashmir is officially dead.
</P>
<P>
   Hizbul Mujahideen, one of the main groups fighting India's rule
in its only Muslim-majority state, had on July 24 called a
cease-fire and said it would like to talk to the Indian government.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it imposed an ultimatum: the talks would have to include
Pakistan, which controls a third of Kashmir and regards India's
portion as its rightful inheritance, or the cease-fire would be
called off.
</P>
<P>
   India ignored the ultimatum, and on Aug. 8 Hizbul Mujahideen
said it would fight on.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict seems to be back to the same hopeless state in
which it has languished for 53 years _ except that nowadays, on a
whim of either India or Pakistan, it could turn nuclear.
</P>
<P>
   According to some rumors, Pakistan and India have, despite
appearances, already struck a secret deal on the future of Kashmir,
making the end of the truce nothing more than a tactical maneuver.
That seems unlikely, though nothing can be ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the past hopeful fortnight's events turn out to be no
more than a feint in the direction of peace, though, they have
revealed the contours of how a peace process might evolve.
</P>
<P>
   First, it should be understood that the stated obstacles to
peace are not the real ones.
</P>
<P>
   India's prime minister, Atal Behari Vajpayee, dispensed quickly
with the main Indian objection to talks with the rebels, who want
either independence for Kashmir or union with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Though India could not transgress its own constitution, Vajpayee
dropped his insistence that the rebels had to accept it as a
condition for talks. India should deal with them on the basis of
insaniyat (humanity), he said.
</P>
<P>
   The speed and flexibility of his response to the cease-fire gave
the rebels little excuse for backing out. Nonetheless, Hizbul
Mujahideen found one, in the form of a demand that Pakistan had to
be party to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   India rejected that for two reasons. First, it regards Pakistan
as the author of violence in Kashmir, whether it was last year's
harebrained attempt to grab territory on India's side of the line
of control or last week's horrible series of massacres in which
over 100 people died.
</P>
<P>
   More profoundly, India regards Kashmir as its territory and the
discontent of the Kashmiris as an internal matter. Even so, dual
talks could have been embarked upon, perhaps by treating them as
separate processes.
</P>
<P>
   The real hurdles to peace are, first, India's bumbling and
brutal treatment of a people who have never been certain whether
they belonged with India, Pakistan or on their own; and, second,
Pakistan's stake in their discontent.
</P>
<P>
   While it lasted, the cease-fire offered a glimpse of a way over
the first hurdle. India would have started by talking to Hizbul
Mujahideen, which, unlike most of the other militant groups, is
dominated by Kashmiris rather than outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The talks would have gradually been extended to take in other
separatist groups, including at least some of the 23 members of the
All-Party Hurriyat Conference. Eventually, they would have
encompassed all shades of opinion in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Such talks would get nowhere, however, without tangible
improvements in India's administration of Kashmir. Each stretch of
the track would add strain.
</P>
<P>
   The state's ruling party, despised by most Kashmiri Muslims, has
no wish to make way for pacified militants. Vajpayee's own party,
the Hindu-nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, is ideologically
disinclined to make the sort of concessions that might pacify them.
Sooner or later, these issues must be faced.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre and the ultimatum suggest that Pakistan, or groups
over which Pakistan's government has some influence, can veto any
move towards peace and has strong reason to. But India has, in
essence, everything else it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Though India formally claims all of Kashmir, including the areas
now controlled by Pakistan and China, it would probably settle for
the status quo, turning the present line of control into the
international border.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan thinks, probably wrongly, that violence can force India
to grant Kashmir ``self-determination.'' Pakistan's incentive to
disrupt any truce is like that of a gunslinger in a poker game who
knows he holds low cards.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders can help blunt that incentive. In March Bill Clinton,
stopping briefly in Pakistan on his way home from India, declared
that ``this era does not reward people who struggle in vain to
redraw borders with blood.''
</P>
<P>
   It is widely believed that behind the scenes America has been
cajoling Pakistan to restrain the militants. It had been hoping
that the country's military ruler, General Pervez Musharraf, was
desperate enough for economic aid to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Hizbul Mujahideen's cease-fire proposal looked like the fruit of
that pressure. Although the truce has broken down, progress need
not come to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   India should continue with its peace offensive, preaching and
practicing insaniyat. That means talking to willing Kashmiris,
restoring democratic decency to the state and allowing its citizens
to be architects of their own future.
</P>
<P>
   India will not be chided for refusing tripartite talks at the
point of a gun, but it cannot forever dodge talking to Pakistan
about Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   At some stage, Vajpayee and General Musharraf will have to meet.
Pakistan and Hizbul Mujahideen will have to return to the
negotiating table, leaving their guns at the door. They may not win
back the rest of Kashmir. But a durable peace that ended the threat
of nuclear war would be quite a consolation prize. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
