<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8951 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-MATES-SPI &LR;      08-11 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MATES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNLIKELY PLOT WEAKENS TNT'S CAMPAIGN FOR `RUNNING MATE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The beauty of a show like ``The West Wing'' is that no matter
how make-believe it is, it still seems impossibly real. The problem
with ``Running Mates,'' a politically charged movie airing on the
eve of the Democratic National Convention Sunday night, is that
it's not ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the acclaimed NBC series, which has former Oval Office
insiders on its production staff, ``Running Mates'' can boast a
political pedigree: One of its executive producers is Gerald
Rafshoon, White House communications director during the Carter
administration. But unlike ``The West Wing,'' whose scripts fairly
crackle with vitality, Sunday's TNT movie looks like someone's
untutored impression of behind-the-scenes presidential politics.
More like a botched campaign appearance, it looks staged and dated.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem: The film is described as a comedy/drama,
possibly to explain away the hysterical, though not particularly
funny, performances of Faye Dunaway and Teri Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   It's really a polemic against campaign-finance abuse, though.
Nothing wrong with that: Movies with messages are good for the
soul. But once the audience understands the ground rules, the
ending of ``Running Mates'' is about as surprising as the outcome
of modern political conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Selleck (with upper lip completely naked because no one with
facial hair has been elected president since Taft) plays the main
character, Michigan Gov. James Reynolds Pryce, a liberal Democrat
with his party's presidential nomination in the bag. His big
decision now is to choose between a running mate who makes the high
rollers happy or one who's good for the country.
</P>
<P>
   The former is the obvious choice because it comes with a
guarantee of serious funding from big business. The alternative,
like raisin bran, is good for the constitution but not necessarily
a boon to one's economic well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name, Pryce likes to think he's not for sale, that
opportunism practiced with an eye toward the greater good is OK, or
at least convenient salve for the conscience. Pryce weighs his
options with input from four women who have made an impression in
his life, or at least in his mattress. First, but not always
foremost, is his patient wife, Jenny (Nancy Travis). More crucial
to the campaign is his loyal, driven and brilliant campaign
manager, Lauren Hartman (Laura Linney). Also in this odd bridge mix
are Meg Gable (Dunaway), the booze-fogged wife of Pryce's political
mentor, and Shawna Morgan (Hatcher), a wacko Hollywood fund-raiser
who wants to be Pryce's White House social secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Dunaway and Hatcher emoting over the top, the film
has solid performances from Selleck, Travis and the
underappreciated Linney. Bob Gunton, Bruce McGill and Rober Culp
also shine in small roles, but ``Running Mates'' ultimately lacks
the very imagination that Gov. Pryce and his campaign staff boast
will take them to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it injects stilted humor and contrived situations,
notably an implausible powder-room scene involving all four women,
in an effort to spark interest in a story that's all too familiar,
even to us political outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING MATES
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: Two-hour TV movie about a
</P>
<P>
   presidential candidate's choice
</P>
<P>
   of a vice presidential nominee
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Tom Selleck, Laura Linney, Nancy Travis, Faye Dunaway,
Teri Hatcher, Bruce McGill, Bob Gunton and Robert Culp
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Sunday at 8 p.m., 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   and midnight
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: TNT cable
</P>
<P>
   RATING: TV-14
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1531EDT &QL; 
