<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV13-B     08-11 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-GUN TEXAN NEEDS TO START USING HIS HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August   13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I have no notion of whether Vice President Al Gore
will make missile defense a major issue when he makes his big
speech here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But he's almost a lap behind Governor George W. Bush, if you
measure laps by double-digit polling margins. And arguing that Bush
is reckless and immature by vowing to bust up the 28-year-old
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty is probably not good politics.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans don't understand that there's really no way to
protect this country from sneak A-bomb attacks, missiles, or
otherwise. A pickup truck sneaking across from Canada, or a
sailboat coming ashore at night in the Gulf, or a freighter carting
bananas into New York Harbor can do the trick. But politicians
can't win any votes by telling you that.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor earned high marks for his big speech in
Philadelphia, mentioning ``character'' 10 times, and stressing how
red-white-and-blue he is, and sincere in helping minorities. He
tells us daily he wants us to know ``what's in my heart.'' Excuse
me: I want to know what's in his head.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's well-delivered and well-received acceptance speech
contained just 79 words about what may be his greatest challenge as
president: ``When America uses force in the world, the cause must
be just, the goal must be clear, and the victory must be
overwhelming. I will work to reduce nuclear weapons and nuclear
tension in the world _ to turn these years of influence into
decades of peace. And, at the earliest possible date, my
administration will deploy missile defenses to guard against attack
and blackmail. Now is the time, not to defend outdated treaties,
but to defend the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   You can draw a number of inferences from this. He won't send
troops to put down riots, rebellions, or massacres in Africa or
Indonesia or the Balkans or the Middle East. Where he does send
troops, the outcome will be ``overwhelming,'' which was certainly
not the case in his father's Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But the vow to deploy a new missile defense scheme ASAP is his
most breathtakingly reckless promise. It is potentially more
destabilizing than his
whoopee-I'll-give-everybody-a-great-big-fat-tax-cut promise, a
hollow bribe reprising his daddy's infamous ``read my lips _ no new
taxes!'' ploy.
</P>
<P>
   The dirty little secret of arms control is that there is no
system you can build to realistically protect American cities from
weapons of mass destruction. Any bright college sophomore can
download formulas for making atomic weapons. The Clinton
administration is weighing committing the United States to building
new radar bases in Alaska to detect missile strikes from China or
North Korea. Scientists who think the scheme cannot tell decoys
from the real thing are embroiled in bitter disputes with defense
bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   I buy the technical argument that this costly system won't work.
</P>
<P>
   The same day Bush vowed to bust up the ``outdated''
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty that has been the basic blueprint of
disarmament since 1972, Britain's Financial Times editorialized
that a US missile scheme in violation of the ABM treaty would be a
colossal mistake for us: ``Russia and China are both adamant in
their opposition to the US plan, which they see as a first step
toward a much more comprehensive ABM system aimed not at rogue
states but at themselves.'' All our European allies are aghast. The
Chinese, already helping North Korea, Pakistan, Iran, and Libya
with long-range missile development, are deeply suspicious of our
intent.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joe Lieberman's record of collecting defense contractor
contributions for his support of missile defense systems makes it
even less likely Gore will make a big deal of this. And
anti-Clinton blather about the Democrats' political machine selling
out America to Chinese money makes the Chinese even more wary of
Bush's saber-rattling and Gore's tiptoeing around the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Most American voters don't care what the rest of the world, the
94 percent who are not American, thinks about our fears about
hostile missiles aimed at our cities. Bush, a callow figure when it
comes to knowledge of the planet's peoples and cultures, brags of
his Midland, Texas, background and its bumptious ``The sky's the
limit!'' mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to missile defense, ``the sky's the limit!''
is a dangerous and misleading motto. The CIA just warned the White
House China will accelerate its missile-building even more if we
break the ABM Treaty. The Europeans will go ballistic, to employ a
missile term rhetorically. Against us. We are on the verge of
pitching over the precipice into another arms race. With hardly any
debate or thought.
</P>
<P>
   My hunch is that Gore will try to finesse the issue, letting
Clinton and Defense Secretary Bill Cohen decide whether to go ahead
with Alaska base preparation. If they do that, the British will
start getting sniffy about allowing us to upgrade the US radar
capability at Flyingdales in Yorkshire.
</P>
<P>
   My suspicion is that the average American voter is indifferent
or even hostile to what leaders of other countries think about our
missile schemes. But our leaders have to be smarter and more wary
than our voters. That's why we call them ``leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Every time I hear that ``sky's the limit'' talk, I envision
missile silos yawning open, across China, Russia, the North Korean
peninsula, to Iran and Iraq and Israel, perhaps even to the Arab
oil states, and maybe the restless archipelago islands of the
Pacific. The sky is the limit, unless we grow up and recognize that
the rest of the world is not going to let us try to dominate the
planet with missile schemes that will provoke our friends as well
as our foes to build up their own weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Surely a man wise enough to be president should understand this.
Can't someone explain it to this two-gun Texan? Look, Governor:
It's like handguns in Texas; the other guy has one, you want one,
right? You must believe that, because you signed that
right-to-carry law to let Texans carry concealed handguns. So,
think of a nuclear missile like your favorite six-shooter. If
you've got one, your neighbor wants to be packing his own, right?
</P>
<P>
   Now that you've got that, go one more step: When every
so-inclined nation, right or rogue, is packing its own nukes, does
that make the neighborhood safer? Or a more dangerous place? We
need a president whose head overrules his heart. There's a lot
riding on this. Like the planet's future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
