<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8959 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-RACE-GETS-RACY-ECONOM     08-11 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-GETS-RACY-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, CAMPAIGN 2000 GETS INTERESTING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE story stands in 900; 1,000
uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This story can stand alone in 900 words; total uncut
is 1,000.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``There's a lot at stake in this election and real
differences between the two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Lieberman said that at the war memorial in Nashville
just after Al Gore had formally picked him as the Democratic
running mate, it sounded like the sort of remark _ simultaneously
bland and exaggerated _ that politicians perpetrate when they have
nothing much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was both surprising and true. It was surprising
because for most Americans, and almost all foreigners, this is one
of the least gripping elections on record.
</P>
<P>
   Many still think of it as the Gush versus Bore contest _ between
two cautious scions of America's political aristocracy rushing
towards the electoral center offering undistinguished and
indistinguishable policy platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comment is also true because for the first time in
decades almost any electoral result is conceivable, ranging from a
clean sweep of the presidency, Senate and House of Representatives
by the Republicans, to a clean sweep by the Democrats _ or any
combination in between.
</P>
<P>
   That means the winner could end up with a degree of control not
seen since the Eisenhower administration and would be able to
influence policy for years afterwards through its control of the
many appointments to the Supreme Court and the Federal Reserve
Board that fall due during the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between what people seem to think about this
election and what is actually at stake is becoming more striking
during the current convention season _ ``the most critical period
of the campaign,'' claims Tom Mann of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   There may still be few clear signs that America's apathetic
voters are aware what their decision in November could do to their
country. But something is beginning to click. The gravitas of the
candidates and the sharpness of their policy differences have both
increased over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has never been accused of lacking seriousness, but Bush has
and the display of party unity at the Republican Convention in
Philadelphia last week, in addition to his well-received final
speech, suggests that, at the least, he has become a formidable
party manager and campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   These two have now been joined by two of the more respected
politicians in the country _ Dick Cheney, the secretary of defense
during the Gulf war, and Lieberman, the nearest thing the Senate
has to a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The policy differences between the two sides have also begun to
sharpen. On Social Security (the pensions system), Bush has
proposed letting people take a share of their payroll taxes _
probably two percentage points out of the current 12.4 percent _
and invest it in personal retirement accounts. This is the
so-called ``partial privatization of Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also wants to encourage private saving for retirement. But
he does so by proposing a federal savings subsidy, directed at
poorer savers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Bush would change the structure of the system
up front, while Gore would erode people's dependence on Social
Security by encouraging additional savings and, possibly, make
structural changes later.
</P>
<P>
   There is a comparable difference in education and health care.
Gore wants to increase spending on public education by up to four
times as much as Bush does. But Bush would try to transform the
system itself by allowing some parents to divert the money that now
goes into their children's public education towards private
schools, providing a measure of competition.
</P>
<P>
   On health, Gore wants to expand Medicaid (the system for poor
Americans) to some who do not now get it, and expand Medicare (for
the elderly) to cover the cost of more prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to reform Medicare by allowing people to buy
different levels of health care, and would provide the prescription
drug benefit through private insurers, not the government.
</P>
<P>
   None of this compares with the sort of ideological choice that
Ronald Reagan presented to Americans in 1980. But the differences
are sharp enough, and if you add in the tax cuts the two are
proposing ($1.3 trillion over ten years for Bush, $500 billion for
Gore, including the savings subsidy), it is hard to argue that it
would make little difference whom the voters decide to pick.
</P>
<P>
   Despite which, the attitudes of those voters have not changed
much. Influenced partly by satisfaction with the economy and partly
by a sense that politicians have had little to do with their
prosperity, voters remain unmoved by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The number of hours of television watched and broadcast for the
Republican Convention was the lowest since TV became a mass medium.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of voters who say they are not following the
campaign continues to rise (44 percent now compared with 37 percent
in July 1996). Still, the twists and turns of the election do seem
to be having an impact on those who are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in the polls leapt after last week's Republican
Convention in Philadelphia by an average of six points to around
14. That lead immediately shrank to within the margin of error in
one poll taken the day Gore chose his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The moral may be not that voters are entirely indifferent, but
that their involvement is mild and changeable. This in turn is
determining campaign strategy. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 900, OR CONTINUE TO 1,000) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No one could fairly accuse the Republicans of offering a vacuous
set of policies. But politically, the main impact of their
proposals has not been to focus voters' attention on the issues but
rather to minimize the perception (which still exists) that Bush is
a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican interest lies in keeping attention away from
policy matters and on to the contrast of personality, where Bush
outscores Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, of course, have the opposite interest. And that
is where the election now stands _ with voters roughly evenly
divided between an unfocused satisfaction which probably favors
Bush and a fitful interest in the issues which Democrats believe
favors Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It is a start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-RACE-GETS-RACY-ECONOM     08-11 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-GETS-RACY-ECONOMIST-900&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINALLY, CAMPAIGN 2000 GETS INTERESTING  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE story stands in 900; 1,000
uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This story can stand alone in 900 words; total uncut
is 1,000.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``There's a lot at stake in this election and real
differences between the two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Lieberman said that at the war memorial in Nashville
just after Al Gore had formally picked him as the Democratic
running mate, it sounded like the sort of remark _ simultaneously
bland and exaggerated _ that politicians perpetrate when they have
nothing much to say.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was both surprising and true. It was surprising
because for most Americans, and almost all foreigners, this is one
of the least gripping elections on record.
</P>
<P>
   Many still think of it as the Gush versus Bore contest _ between
two cautious scions of America's political aristocracy rushing
towards the electoral center offering undistinguished and
indistinguishable policy platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comment is also true because for the first time in
decades almost any electoral result is conceivable, ranging from a
clean sweep of the presidency, Senate and House of Representatives
by the Republicans, to a clean sweep by the Democrats _ or any
combination in between.
</P>
<P>
   That means the winner could end up with a degree of control not
seen since the Eisenhower administration and would be able to
influence policy for years afterwards through its control of the
many appointments to the Supreme Court and the Federal Reserve
Board that fall due during the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancy between what people seem to think about this
election and what is actually at stake is becoming more striking
during the current convention season _ ``the most critical period
of the campaign,'' claims Tom Mann of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   There may still be few clear signs that America's apathetic
voters are aware what their decision in November could do to their
country. But something is beginning to click. The gravitas of the
candidates and the sharpness of their policy differences have both
increased over the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has never been accused of lacking seriousness, but Bush has
and the display of party unity at the Republican Convention in
Philadelphia last week, in addition to his well-received final
speech, suggests that, at the least, he has become a formidable
party manager and campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   These two have now been joined by two of the more respected
politicians in the country _ Dick Cheney, the secretary of defense
during the Gulf war, and Lieberman, the nearest thing the Senate
has to a conscience.
</P>
<P>
   The policy differences between the two sides have also begun to
sharpen. On Social Security (the pensions system), Bush has
proposed letting people take a share of their payroll taxes _
probably two percentage points out of the current 12.4 percent _
and invest it in personal retirement accounts. This is the
so-called ``partial privatization of Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also wants to encourage private saving for retirement. But
he does so by proposing a federal savings subsidy, directed at
poorer savers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that Bush would change the structure of the system
up front, while Gore would erode people's dependence on Social
Security by encouraging additional savings and, possibly, make
structural changes later.
</P>
<P>
   There is a comparable difference in education and health care.
Gore wants to increase spending on public education by up to four
times as much as Bush does. But Bush would try to transform the
system itself by allowing some parents to divert the money that now
goes into their children's public education towards private
schools, providing a measure of competition.
</P>
<P>
   On health, Gore wants to expand Medicaid (the system for poor
Americans) to some who do not now get it, and expand Medicare (for
the elderly) to cover the cost of more prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to reform Medicare by allowing people to buy
different levels of health care, and would provide the prescription
drug benefit through private insurers, not the government.
</P>
<P>
   None of this compares with the sort of ideological choice that
Ronald Reagan presented to Americans in 1980. But the differences
are sharp enough, and if you add in the tax cuts the two are
proposing ($1.3 trillion over ten years for Bush, $500 billion for
Gore, including the savings subsidy), it is hard to argue that it
would make little difference whom the voters decide to pick.
</P>
<P>
   Despite which, the attitudes of those voters have not changed
much. Influenced partly by satisfaction with the economy and partly
by a sense that politicians have had little to do with their
prosperity, voters remain unmoved by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The number of hours of television watched and broadcast for the
Republican Convention was the lowest since TV became a mass medium.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of voters who say they are not following the
campaign continues to rise (44 percent now compared with 37 percent
in July 1996). Still, the twists and turns of the election do seem
to be having an impact on those who are paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead in the polls leapt after last week's Republican
Convention in Philadelphia by an average of six points to around
14. That lead immediately shrank to within the margin of error in
one poll taken the day Gore chose his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The moral may be not that voters are entirely indifferent, but
that their involvement is mild and changeable. This in turn is
determining campaign strategy. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 900, OR CONTINUE TO 1,000) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No one could fairly accuse the Republicans of offering a vacuous
set of policies. But politically, the main impact of their
proposals has not been to focus voters' attention on the issues but
rather to minimize the perception (which still exists) that Bush is
a lightweight.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican interest lies in keeping attention away from
policy matters and on to the contrast of personality, where Bush
outscores Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, of course, have the opposite interest. And that
is where the election now stands _ with voters roughly evenly
divided between an unfocused satisfaction which probably favors
Bush and a fitful interest in the issues which Democrats believe
favors Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It is a start. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
