<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8972 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-TRAVELOCITY-TEX     08-11 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVELOCITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED ITINERARY TO REVERSE A STOCK SKID, TRAVELOCITY RE-MAPS ITS
PLAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREA AHLES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Travelocity.com joined the tech stock market
craze a little too late.
</P>
<P>
   When the Fort Worth online travel site became publicly traded
March 8, it opened at $47 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of skyrocketing and creating multimillionaires,
Travelocity shares have dropped steadily in the past six months to
$12, even though the company added new features and launched a
travel site for America Online users.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity, one of the largest e-commerce sites on the Web
behind Amazon.com and eBay, outperformed analysts' expectations for
its first and second quarters. But the stock has remained depressed
along with the shares of other online retail sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their weak stock performance is more indicative of a sector
that has been under pressure for quite a while than anything
happening with the company,'' said Steve Weinstein, vice president
at the Pacific Crest Securities investment firm in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity continues to increase revenues and attract new
customers, compared with other online travel sites like
Expedia.com, Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   And in an attempt to generate more interest in its stock by
institutional investors, Travelocity will convert 33 million shares
of preferred stock held by its parent company, Sabre, into Class A
common stock, chief executive Terry Jones said last week. That move
will triple the company's market capitalization to $780 million,
making it more attractive to banks, insurers and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had high hopes for Travelocity's market debut when it
announced in October that it would merge with publicly traded
Preview Travel. Shares of Preview Travel rose 160 percent from
about $17 a share in October to $47 a share in March when the
merger was completed.
</P>
<P>
   But when the public shares of Preview Travel converted to the
Travelocity ticker symbol on March 8, the stock began to skid.
</P>
<P>
   The deal created a travel Web site with 21 million customers and
more vacation and cruise packages than the old Travelocity site.
Sabre continues to own a 70 percent stake in Travelocity.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity says it took some of the best features from the
Preview Travel site, such as all-inclusive vacation packages, and
added them to its site. The site added a ``ski map'' for those
looking for ski trips and a ``dream map'' showing customers various
destinations available for a specific dollar price.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the company launches a magazine offering travel tips
and features about exotic locales. The bimonthly magazine will
initially be sent to 250,000 Travelocity members and will be
available on newsstands for $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the Preview Travel deal, Travelocity became a partner
with America Online, providing the online community with a travel
site. The AOL site was launched in April.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other portal deals that Travelocity has with Yahoo,
Lycos and Excite, the AOL partnership gives Travelocity up to $200
million over the next five years and a share of the advertising
revenue generated on the site, Jones said. AOL also gets a portion
of the earnings from each sale on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked hard on our brand, our customer service and new
features to get customers to use our site,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity has grown to almost 1,000 employees and is moving
from its headquarters at 4200 Buckingham Blvd. in the Centreport
development to a building nearby on 15100 Trinity Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently reported a second-quarter net loss of $13.5
million, compared with a net loss of $12.78 million in the same
quarter last year. Revenues rose to $46.79 million from $19.2
million. Wall Street had expected the company to lose 34 cents per
share, before one-time items; it lost 26 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Travelocity has built itself to be the premium
leisure travelers' site in the growing online travel market, and
they expect the company to become profitable in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of Travelocity is you can book a round-trip
ticket and the hotel and rental car in under 10 minutes,'' said
Henry Harteveldt, a senior analyst at Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester predicts that the online travel market will grow to
$29 billion in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Travelocity is facing more Internet
competition as two new entrants get ready to launch this fall.
Orbitz and Hotwire, both backed by airlines, are hoping to capture
a portion of the online market with cheaper airfares and search
functions that are intended to be easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   The online travel market is crowded with sites like Expedia.com,
backed by Microsoft, and the name-your-own-price Priceline.com.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity needs to expand its presence, particularly in the
business travel market, said Joshua Friedman, a senior research
analyst at IDC Corp. Only 30 percent of Travelocity's customers are
business travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future is definitely not in standard published air, car
and hotel fares, and Expedia has understood that better than
Travelocity,'' Friedman said, pointing to Expedia's recent purchase
of Travelscape, a wholesale travel site.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said Travelocity will continue to add new features and
work toward profitability, with the hope that the stock price will
follow.
</P>
<P>
   Travelocity stock ``is a long-term play,'' Jones said. ``Over
the long term, we believe the market will reward us.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
