<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSED-ARGENTINES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWN AND OUT IN NOT-SO-BUENOS AIRES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 575-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ Not for nothing does Buenos Aires claim to have
more psychoanalysts per square kilometer than any other city in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   For Argentines are a mercurial people: notoriously immodest
about their country's virtues, they can as easily switch to
exaggerated excoriation of its faults.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the national mood is one of deep depression,
manifested in recent days in an outpouring of anguished
self-analysis over the suicide of a well-known surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Favaloro pioneered heart-bypass surgery when working in the
United States in the 1960s. Back in Buenos Aires, he set up a
medical research center and became one of Argentina's most
respected public figures.
</P>
<P>
   On July 29th, Dr. Favaloro shot himself, seemingly because of
his medical institute's financial problems. That struck a
particular chord with Argentina's middle classes, who seem to see
in the doctor's suicide an echo of their own frustration over the
country's depressed economy.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of despair goes wider: a million or more flocked this
week to the shrine of San Cayetano, patron saint of labor, praying
for his help to find work.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is suffering some of the textbook symptoms of
deflation. The economy went into recession almost two years ago,
battered by emerging-market blues and the problems of Brazil, its
main trading partner.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Brazil, whose economy is now growing strongly again,
Argentina cannot shake off recession by devaluing its currency: its
peso is fixed by law at parity with the dollar under its rigid
currency-board scheme.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando de la Rua's government has instead tried to
woo the financial markets by trimming the fiscal deficit it
inherited when taking office in December, through tax rises and
spending cuts, including a cut in civil servants' wages.
</P>
<P>
   But the recovery has been sluggish. Growth is confined to
exports; consumer spending continues to fall, in part because of
the tax rises and wage cuts for civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   Though lower than its peak in the last recession in 1995,
unemployment is still rising. It stood at 15.4 percent in May, up
from 13.8 percent last October. Officials still claim doggedly that
the economy will grow by 3 percent this year, but most
private-sector economists think 1-2 percent more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Tax revenues in July were disappointing, after the previous
month's bumper take had temporarily improved confidence. Investors
have started to worry that the government may not manage to meet
the fiscal targets for the rest of the year that it has negotiated
with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an economic team that makes such a big deal out of country
risk and investors' expectations, that would be a tremendous
setback,'' says Pedro Lacoste of Alfa, an economic think-tank.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of several economists who argue that de la Rua's team
should have taken even tougher action when it came to office in
December, cutting instead of raising taxes and forcing privatized
utility operators to slash their tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the public-sector wage cuts, that would have added
up to ``a once-off deflationary shock,'' of equivalent effect to a
devaluation, says Lacoste.
</P>
<P>
   Officials counter that the worst is over, and that patience will
be rewarded. Few Argentines are prepared to contemplate abandoning
their currency board: many retain traumatic memories of the
hyperinflation that preceded it. But deflation carries
psychological scars too.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Argentina's psychoanalysts should face no problems
finding work in the coming months. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
