<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8977 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EARTH-MOTHER-WONK-ECO     08-11 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARTH-MOTHER-WONK-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EILEEN CLAUSSEN: MOTHER EARTH VS. GLOBAL-WARMING SKEPTICS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 925-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Dear Tony,'' begins the earnest memo from one
policy wonk to another. ``Knowing our shared interest in global
climate change, I have enclosed a report on the benefits of
greenhouse gas emissions trading...
</P>
<P>
   ``This new report by the nonprofit Pew Center on Global Climate
Change supports the view that a flexible, well-designed trading
system will significantly reduce the costs of climate change
mitigation...With best regards, Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The casual snoop might pass over this epistle as merely the
unremarkable ramblings of an academic or bureaucrat. Inspect more
closely, though, and two surprises emerge.
</P>
<P>
   First, this letter, penned recently by one Bill Clinton to one
Tony Blair, Britain's prime minister, is about an issue both take
seriously: global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the letter reveals just how influential Eileen Claussen,
the head of the Pew Center, has now become. Why does she have the
ear of the world's most powerful man? The answer is that she knows
how to dance circles around the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three years ago, in the run-up to the signing of
the U.N.'s Kyoto Protocol on global warming, the debate in America
on climate change was dominated by skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   The Kyoto pact was seen in many countries as a courageous if
imperfect attempt to come to grips with an impossibly complex and
uncertain threat. In the United States, however, it was regarded
with scorn by those who sought to portray it as the handiwork of
wild-eyed greens such as the vice president, Al Gore, who had
helped to broker the Kyoto deal.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the opposition was the Global Climate Coalition (GCC),
an umbrella group representing heavy industry. Through television
campaigns and intense lobbying, company executives sought not
merely to sink the Kyoto treaty, but to trash the very notion of
climate change.
</P>
<P>
   Such hostility was a sharp contrast with the more open attitudes
of big business in Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Even when faced with new scientific evidence of the human role
in climate change, the GCC remained combative.
</P>
<P>
   The picture has changed dramatically in the past two years.
Giant firms such as United Technologies, Intel, American Electric
Power (AEP), DuPont and BP now openly accept that the evidence for
climate change is sufficient to take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them, as a new report issued last week by the Pew Center
points out, are conducting audits of the amount of greenhouse gases
emitted by their plants and are taking on voluntary targets for
emissions cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms even think reducing emissions could be profitable.
Frank Loy, America's top negotiator on climate change, says that
big firms have ``shifted from being climate skeptics to climate
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   He gives much of the credit for this volte face to Claussen.
Until the Pew Center began to challenge its line roughly two years
ago, the GCC had a virtual monopoly as the public face of corporate
America in the climate debate.
</P>
<P>
   Claussen, a longtime bureaucrat who had often dealt with
corporations during international environmental talks, suspected
that attitudes in big business were not quite so uniform.
</P>
<P>
   After she resigned from government in mid-1997, she crafted a
set of principles that reflected a more progressive approach to
climate change, but which ``danced a fine line on Kyoto,'' as one
person on the receiving end of her pitch describes it.
</P>
<P>
   With some trepidation, she approached a handful of leading
American industrial firms that she thought might be open-minded.
She was right. A number of companies agreed to band together under
the Pew Center's umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy for the early joiners: some, such as AEP, a big
coal-fired utility, and BP, a giant oil firm, were berated by their
peers for breaking ranks. However, the Pew's media skills meant
that they soon found strength in numbers and a powerful voice.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the GCC is a spent force, while the Pew's blue-chip
member companies have annual sales of more than $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It is no suprise, then, that Claussen has detractors. One charge
is that the Pew Center is a front for the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Claussen insists this is nonsense. She points out that she has
been highly critical of the administration, both for its lack of
domestic action and for its ``dangerous'' efforts overseas to
dilute the Kyoto pact.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she notes, she served under Presidents George Bush and
Ronald Reagan with distinction, and counts leading Republicans as
fans. She even chides Gore for ``lacking courage'' to push ahead
with the issue of which he was an early champion.
</P>
<P>
   Another, more substantive, grouse is that Claussen is a
shameless publicity hound. The boss of a respected think-tank
points to the huge sums that the Pew Center spends on full-color
advertisements and glossy brochures, and mutters that he could have
used that money for serious research projects.
</P>
<P>
   On this count, Claussen is probably guilty as charged. But do
not expect any remorse, as her use of the media has been by far her
most powerful weapon.
</P>
<P>
   By spending pots of money on ads, brochures, independent reports
and high-profile conferences, the Pew Center has managed to earn
credibility as an honest broker. Where moderate firms once kept
silent, they now have a forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, only the bad guys were out there in the media,''
says Claussen. ``We raised the ante by being so public.'' That is
the sort of spin of which both Tony and Bill would surely be
proud. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0146 </DOCNO>
