<SLUG> BC-PHONE.COM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY LINE: PHONE.COM AND SOFTWARE.COM MERGE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 850-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The search for the next Microsoft is an
understandable obsession. But although this week's $6.4-billion
merger between two of Silicon Valley's highest-flying software
communications firms, Phone.com and Software.com, inevitably
prompted such talk, the reality is that Phone.com already looks
rather more like the next Netscape _ Microsoft's erstwhile victim.
</P>
<P>
   Although the deal was predictably described by the participants
as the creation of a new ``global powerhouse,'' the combined annual
revenues of the two companies are only around $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   And though Software.com is a solid business, and is even making
a small profit, Phone.com has faced a sufficiently uncertain future
to be regarded by most analysts as a takeover candidate. It must
hope that throwing in its lot with a firm of similar size will
change that.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best news for shareholders was that the merging
firms have lured a top manager from the mighty Cisco Systems, Don
Listwin, to run the business.
</P>
<P>
   To walk away from the possibility of succeeding John Chambers,
Cisco's boss, in five years' time, not to mention a bundle of Cisco
options, is quite a declaration of faith.
</P>
<P>
   As a linchpin of the mobile Internet, Phone.com was one of the
past year's hottest stocks, rising by 1,200 percent from its IPO in
June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to agree that the mobile phone will quickly
overtake the personal computer as the means by which most people
gain access to online services. And as the pioneer of much of the
software infrastructure that is making all this happen, Phone.com
seemed to be sitting pretty.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's founder, Alain Rossmann, a veteran of Apple, had been
determined not to repeat the mistakes made by his former company.
</P>
<P>
   When Phone.com (then called Unwired Planet) came up with the
technology for a mobile browser, Rossmann, rather than go it alone,
approached the mobile-phone-making giants _ Nokia, Ericsson and
Motorola _ in 1997 to persuade them that it should become the
standard for wireless Internet communication.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, and the technology became known as WAP (wireless
application protocol). It was the breakthrough that Rossmann's
fledgling company needed, but it came at a price.
</P>
<P>
   Although Unwired Planet had a technological lead over
mobile-phone firms and software rivals, WAP was to be an open
standard rather than a proprietary one (like Microsoft's Windows).
</P>
<P>
   Today, around 80 percent of all WAP telephones have Phone.com
browsers, but Nokia is already using a version of its own and
Ericsson plans to offer a mobile edition of Microsoft's Internet
Explorer next year.
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com is probably resigned to seeing its share of the WAP
browser market decline. But, as it more or less gives its browsers
away, it could live with that as long as there is strong demand
from big telecoms firms for its server software for the mobile
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft, Oracle and others are greedily contemplating
that market. Phone.com will need to take full advantage of its
superior focus and nimbleness if it is to stay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Software.com is less glamorous than Phone.com, but has been just
as much a leader in its field.
</P>
<P>
   By selling Internet messaging infrastructure to telephone
companies and Internet service providers, it has quickly built up a
base of around 120 million users. Its software brings together
e-mail, voice mail, messaging and even video into one unified
Web-based service.
</P>
<P>
   Software.com faces stiff competition too, but has looked less
vulnerable than its new partner.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Internet mailbox companies offer similar products
aimed at consumers and small businesses, while Microsoft will
defend its dominant Exchange program from insurgents by
incorporating it into its .NET web-services strategy.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Software.com's range of products can expand and
still remain competitive, the big communications companies it
serves are unlikely to desert it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the merger will create a ``powerhouse'' is debatable,
but it should bring some benefits. It will stop both firms from
competing expensively against one another, as they did within a few
weeks of each other earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Phone.com paid $850 million for a unified messaging start-up
called Onebox.com and Software.com bought (at) &LR; mobile.com, a
wireless-application service provider, for over $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   With customers and product lines that are complementary, there
should also be plenty of scope for cross-selling. And, by creating
a single platform across both the fixed-line and wireless Internet,
the new entity should be better placed to fend off rivals that have
only one part of the jigsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Much, though, will depend on Listwin. He will bring with him
from Cisco both a high level of credibility with large telephone
companies and an unrelenting focus on customer satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   If he can also pull together two talented but very different
developer teams, he may succeed in forging a company that is at
least capable of competing with Microsoft, if not rivalling it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
