<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Before the current stage of the presidential
campaign began, conventional wisdom (excuse the term) held that
George W. Bush's choice of running mate would define his candidacy
but the Republican shindig in Philadelphia would not. Conversely,
it was thought that Al Gore's running mate would hardly matter
(because the options were all so dismal) but his speech to the
Democratic National Convention would be decisive. So far, every
part of this wisdom has turned out to be wrong. &QL;
</P>
