<P>
   &UR; DOWN AND OUT IN NOT-SO-BUENOS AIRES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEPRESSED-ARGENTINES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ Not for nothing does Buenos Aires claim to have
more psychoanalysts per square mile than any other city in the
world. Good thing, too, for at the moment the national mood in
Argentina is one of deep depression, manifested in recent days by
an outpouring of anguished self-analysis over the suicide of a
well-known surgeon. And the sense of despair goes wider still: a
million or more Argentines flocked this week to the shrine of San
Cayetano, patron saint of labor, praying for his help to find work.
At least Argentina's psychoanalysts should face no problems finding
work in the coming months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ECONOMICS &AMP; FINANCE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITAIN'S LAGGING ONLINE INVESTORS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITS-E-TRADERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Following the explosive growth of Internet
stockbroking in American in 1996-99, it was natural that American
online brokers would start expanding into Europe. Natural, too,
that their eyes should alight first on good old Britain:
English-speaking, Internet-hip and, since the privatizations of the
1980s, home to a broad-based ``shareholder culture.'' Yet Britain
is proving slower to embrace online investing than are continental
countries, supposedly so much more leery of the American way of
capitalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EILEEN CLAUSSEN: MOTHER EARTH VS. GLOBAL-WARMING SKEPTICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EARTH-MOTHER-WONK-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ ``Dear Tony,'' begins the earnest memo from one
policy wonk to another. ``Knowing ouir shared interest in global
climate change, I have enclosed a report on the benefits of
greenhouse gas emissions trading... With best regards, Bill.'' The
casual snoop might pass over this epistle as merely the
unremarkable ramblings of an academic or bureaucrat. Inspect more
closely, though, and two surprises emerge. First, this letter,
penned recently by U.S. President Bill Clinton to British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, is about an issue both take seriously: global
warming. Second, the letter reveals just how influential Eileen
Claussen, the head of the nonprofit Pew Center on Global Climate
Change, has now become. Why does Claussen _ the scourge of
global-warming skeptics _ have the ear of the world's most powerful
man? The answer is that she knows how to dance circles around the
big boys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (925 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARTY LINE: PHONE.COM AND SOFTWARE.COM MERGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHONE.COM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The search for the next Microsoft is an
understandable obsession. But, although this week's $6.4 billion
merger between two of Silicon Valley's highest-flying software
communications firms, Phone.com and Software.com, inevitably
prompted such talk, the reality is that Phone.com already looks
rather more like the next Netscape _ Microsoft's erstwhile victim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAGGY FIT: U.S. RETAILERS OVER-EXPAND &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BLUE-RETAILERS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ America is in the ninth year of its longest-ever
peacetime expansion, but somebody has forgotten to tell its
retailers. While department stores such as Nordstrom, J.C. Penney
and Federated have been fighting decline for years, and the woes of
``category killers' such as Toys ``R'' Us are well-known, the
country's hugely successful specialty retailers _ such as Gap,
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, American Eagle Outfitters and Office Depot _
are only now hitting trouble. There are many reasons, but above
all, the fat years of the recent past have tempted store groups
into over-ambitious expansion plans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `LIGHTS, CAMERA...BOMBAY!': INDIA'S FILM INDUSTRY GROWS UP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `BOLLYWOOD'-BOMBAY-BIZ-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUMBAI _ Subhash Ghai is all smiles these days _ and with good
reason. Mukta Arts, his movie production company, has just closed
the first-ever public offering of shares by a big firm from
Bollywood, the name for the Hindi movie industry located around
Mumbai (Bombay). As investors pore over the volatile cash flows of
his firm, Ghai is jazzed by the idea of building a Hollywood-style
studio that hires and trains Indian movie directors, writers and
technicians. Some optimists even see India as a low-cost producer
for the global movie industry. Film City, a newly expanded
2,000-acre complex on the outskirts of Hyderabad, offers 40 studio
floors and sophisticated post-production facilities; it has already
attracted a handful of movie-makers from Hollywood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SET A BUG TO CATCH A BUG: PROTECTING CALIFORNIA'S VINEYARDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASTY-BUGS-VINEYARDS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Grapevines, being clones (they are propagated as
cuttings), are extremely susceptible to disease. That is why
California's viticulturists are so worried about Pierce's disease.
It has ravaged the state's vineyards twice in the past and now, to
the horror of wine lovers everywhere, it is threatening to do so
again. It has already been recorded in 11 of California's
grape-growing counties. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
