<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-MANAGEMENT-1     08-11 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-MANAGEMENT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW OWNER NAMES EDITOR, MANAGER FOR SAN FRANCISCO DAILY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Subs 23rdgraf, At the Binghampton, to add first reference
to Schaffer)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIN McCORMICK  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Martha ``Marty'' Steffens and Robert McCray have
been named the editor and general manager of the San Francisco
Examiner under its new ownership.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives, whose appointments were announced Thursday,
will be key leaders in the remaking of the Examiner under Ted Fang,
the publisher of a three-times-a-week newspaper in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst Corp., which recently bought the San Francisco
Chronicle for $660 million, is transferring the Examiner to Fang
and his family _ along with a $66 million subsidy for three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle and Examiner have operated under a joint operating
agreement since 1965, combining business operations and splitting
profits while maintaining separate editorial staffs. The agreement
was to run through 2005 but was terminated by the sale, which
formally occurred last month after a bitter court fight over
whether the deal violated anti-trust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens and McCray hint at ambitious plans for reshaping the
newspaper in a competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at places like New York, Chicago and Los Angeles,
these are major metropolitan cities that support multiple daily
newspapers,'' said McCray, 42, who will take over the Examiner's
business operations in November. ``I think San Francisco is the
kind of city that can support more than one newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   McCray is currently general manager of the Blade in Toledo,
Ohio. He has also worked at the Los Angeles Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens, 47, the former editor of the Binghamton (N.Y.) Press &AMP;
Sun-Bulletin, will take charge of the Examiner's editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   Both acknowledge they face a huge challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be very, very busy,'' Steffens said.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner was acquired by Fang and his politically prominent
family as part of Hearst's purchase of the Chronicle. To avoid
anti-trust problems with the U.S. Justice Department, Hearst
transferred the smaller Examiner to the Fangs. Hearst is running
the newspaper during a four-month transition period.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs have said they intend to convert the Examiner from an
afternoon newspaper to morning publication focusing on San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the newspaper will start its new life with a big
influx of cash from its former owner, journalism experts say it has
some major hurdles to overcome to survive in the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a very tough road ahead of it,'' said Ben Bagdikian,
former dean of the journalism school at the University of
California at Berkeley and the author of ``Media Monopoly.'' ``It's
going to be up against a very big newspaper, owned by a very rich
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bagdikian said it is encouraging to see the Fangs hiring
people who are nationally established in journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are serious about putting out a paper, this is the
first step,'' he said. ``You bring in a general manager who has
some experience and an editor who has some experience, and you
begin remaking the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Both managers said they would conduct national searches to build
a quality staff.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Examiner employees can join the
Chronicle, which has the same union contract _ an opportunity most
are expected to take. The Fang family, which currently runs the
free community paper, the Independent, is not expected to have a
unionized staff.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless Steffens invited current Examiner staff members to
apply for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think money will be a problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While she would not be specific for ``proprietary reasons,''
Steffens said her goal will be to find ways for the newspaper to
reach new audiences in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens, who has worked at the Orange County Register and the
Los Angeles Times, has long been a supporter of civic journalism,
which advocates that newspapers work to improve the cities they
serve.
</P>
<P>
   At the Binghamton paper, Steffens created a local forum and
related newspaper series focusing on what could be done to prevent
the community from being hurt by economic downsizing, said Jan
Schaffer, executive director of the Pew Center for Civic
Journalism. Steffens serves on the center's board.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is doing journalism that is being used for text books,''
Schaffer said.
</P>
<P>
   McCray became general manager of the Toledo Blade just eight
months ago, after working at its sister paper, the Pittsburgh
Post-Gazette. McCray was praised by those who had worked with him
in the past, as being one of the rarest types of business managers:
one who understands newspapering.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Leader, a current Los Angeles Times editor and former
Examiner staffer, praised McCray's work at the Blade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sensed that he very much recognized the importance of
journalism,'' Leader said. ``This is a high-energy guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
