<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9018 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLONE0812-COX     08-11 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONE0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lone clone doesn't mind leaving life to Chance
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SWISS ALP, Texas _ Ralph Fisher's house comes with a deja view.
</P>
<P>
   Peek out the calico kitchen curtains and you'll see a baby
Brahman bull napping on the front lawn under a hackberry tree.
Nothing odd about that, unless you know that this bull wallowed out
that sweet spot in another lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   So when Fisher looks out the farmhouse window, he sees not only
the reality of the new bull calf but also a remembered landscape
with his favorite bull (now dead) dozing in the grass.
</P>
<P>
   The young bull is a clone of the old bull, a TV and movie star
named Chance who lived to be 22.
</P>
<P>
   And today it's time to sing ``Happy Birthday'' to Second Chance,
who is either 1 year old or 23 years old, depending on whether you
think clones are new animals or the same old familiars rewrapped in
fresh hide.
</P>
<P>
   A clone needs a clown to throw a party, so that's exactly what
will happen tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, a sometimes rodeo clown, invited 300 guests to his
52-acre ranch in Swiss Alp, a hamlet between La Grange and
Schulenburg about 65 miles southeast of Austin. Fisher invited so
many people because he wanted to include ``everyone who knew him in
his former life.'' And, the Texas A&AMP;M scientists who cloned Second
Chance are scheduled to come and announce new findings about the
bull's longevity and health.
</P>
<P>
   It will be good news, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most press since they shut down the Chicken
Ranch,'' said Fisher, referring to the legendary La Grange
whorehouse that inspired a Broadway musical. ``I invited the
governor. I doubt he's going to show, but we might get a letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's private party includes armadillo races, hayrides,
horseshoes, pony rides and free photos with Second Chance, whom
Fisher is grooming to join his herd of Longhorns and other animals
that attend parties and conventions for photo opportunities.
(Fisher is the man who brings his Longhorns to the corner of
highways 620 and 2222 near Lake Travis on weekends for tourist
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves recognition,'' he said. ``Most people don't even
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Second Chance is believed to be the lone clone living with
private owners. He was created by Texas A&AMP;M University experts who
scraped skin cells from Chance before he died in 1998. Second
Chance was born Aug. 9, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher asked A&AMP;M scientists to clone Chance because he had been
the beloved family pet for 17 years, and he thought Chance could
help further genetic research. The university paid for the cloning
with a research donation, and Fisher got to take Second Chance home
after he was weaned from his surrogate mother.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day Second Chance really spooked Fisher and his
wife, Sandra Reddell.
</P>
<P>
   With 52 acres of farmland beckoning in all directions, Second
Chance did exactly what Chance used to do. He walked over to a
special spot in Fisher's front yard, just 15 feet from the kitchen
window, and laid down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, uh-oh.'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wondered if it was all accidental or coincidental,''
he said. ``In my heart, (I think) if his physical appearance
regenerates material, why can't his memory functions be the same or
develop into the same?''
</P>
<P>
   Second Chance also likes to be scratched in the same spots as
Chance and has the same peculiar eating manners of Chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes the same things he liked the first time,'' Fisher
said.
</P>
<P>
   All the other farm animals put their mouths in the feed buckets
and don't come up for air until the food's gone. But Second Chance
eats with bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He puts his head down and fills his mouth up like a child with
no manners and lifts his head and just chews and chews,'' Fisher
said. ``I've raised at least 20-30 Longhorns and Brahmans and I've
never seen another one eat like that,'' except for Chance.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher is ecstatic to have his favorite animal back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thank God he gave him back to us,'' said Fisher, who
doesn't support the cloning of humans. ``We're Christians, and we
stand proud of the fact that technology is such that we can get him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've stopped telling Aggie jokes,'' said Fisher, who holds two
degrees from Sam Houston State University in Huntsville, Texas,
including a master's in special education. ``If I had another life
myself, I'd be a doggone Aggie.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Fisher's friends wants Second Chance to attend the Texas
delegation's presidential ball in Washington D.C. in 2001_ whether
George W. wins or not.
</P>
<P>
   Since this presidential race is giving the Bush family a second
chance at the White House, Fisher figures Second Chance would be
the perfect party animal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
