<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU COULD CALL IT SOMEWHAT UNCONVENTIONAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that's a convention.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about the Republicans and their Philadelphia love-in.
Never mind the Democrats and their upcoming Al &AMP; Joe Show in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   You want action? You want drama? You want heart-stopping,
bare-knuckled political street-fighting? The Reform Party is
dishing up all that and more at its second quadrennial nominating
bash in Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Who woulda figured?
</P>
<P>
   Ross Perot founded the Reform Party in 1995 solely for the
purpose of rubber-stamping his run for president in 1996. When some
would-be usurper misread Perot's intentions and decided to campaign
for the party's '96 presidential nomination, Perot squashed him
like a bug.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, a far more determined and resourceful
interloper set his sights not merely on grabbing the Reform Party
nomination but on seizing control of the party _ lock, stock and
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears that ex-Republican Pat Buchanan has achieved more
or less what he set out to achieve by snatching the Reform Party
right out from under the devoted Perotistas who thought they
controlled it.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``more or less'' because it's not entirely clear whether
Buchanan intended to irreparably alienate the many Perot
aficionados who saw _ still see _ themselves as the lifeblood of
the party. Maybe Buchanan truly believed that the Perotistas would
readily see the wisdom of handing him the keys to the Reform
machinery _ or maybe he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, it doesn't much matter. Buchanan seems rather
pleased to be the focal point of so much anger and resentment; he
seems energized by the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   It figures. Buchanan is a former newspaper columnist and TV
commentator, which means that he has spent much of his adult life
fending off the indignation of those who have no use for anything
he says or does.
</P>
<P>
   After years of co-hosting ``Crossfire,'' the shout-and-snarl
discussion program on CNN, Buchanan could hardly be expected to
come unglued over the sniping of a mild-mannered Reform Party
mainstay such as Russ Verney.
</P>
<P>
   Verney, in fact, couldn't even get under the skin of Pat's
sister as the two discussed their differences in several joint TV
appearances. Bay Buchanan, who serves as her brother's campaign
manager and chief spokesperson, laughed her way through a
``Crossfire'' confrontation with Verney even as the Verney and
Buchanan forces faced off like rival gangs gearing up for a
ferocious battle over some disputed piece of turf.
</P>
<P>
   There is much more at stake, of course, than just the top spot
on the Reform Party ticket _ which by itself would appear to be
worth considerably less than Ralph Nader's Green Party nomination,
at least as far as the presidential preference polls are concerned.
The prize that really has the Buchanan brigades and the Perotistas
clawing at one another's throats is the $12.6 million in federal
campaign cash awaiting the survivor of the Reform Party blood feud.
</P>
<P>
   Verney says that Buchanan is not entitled to the money because
he stuffed the ballot box in the party's mail-in primary election.
Bay Buchanan says her brother locked up the nomination fair and
square _ and she seems confident that the money will be safely
delivered into Buchanan campaign coffers faster than you can say,
``Ross who?''
</P>
<P>
   At last report, the Perotistas had abandoned the
Buchanan-sanctioned convention site and set up their own convention
for the purpose of nominating a nuclear physicist named John
Hagelin, who is also the nominee of some outfit called the Natural
Law Party.
</P>
<P>
   Could this deal get any weirder? Surely not, but at least it's
interesting, which is more than we say for some of the major
parties' recent conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. It could get weirder. Isn't there still a chance that the
Great One, Ross Perot _ aka the Scheming Weasel _ could come
swooping into Long Beach at the last possible moment and demand the
Reform Party nomination for himself?
</P>
<P>
   It's far-fetched, I know. But then, just about everything Perot
does is far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9024 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-REVIEW-JETTA0812-COX     08-11 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-JETTA0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volkswagen's 2000 Jetta GLS 1.8T has plenty of va-voom
 &HT;    By Pete Szilagyi
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - These are horsepower-crazy times. My family
drives a perfectly stock minivan with nearly the power of some '60s
muscle cars, and any contemporary luxury sedan needs at least 225
horsepower to even be considered by shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   BMW's M5, a sedan comfortable enough to take grandparents to
Sunday brunch, has nearly enough power to launch the space shuttle.
Even your neighbor's new pickup, which may never do a lick of work,
probably generates close to 300 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer a modest, four-cylinder, 1.8-liter engine available in
several Volkswagen and Audi models. It's tiny but as thrilling as
many of the huge engines. The VW-Audi 1.8T _ the 3T2 is for
turbocharged _ transforms the New Beetle, Jetta and Golf into
absolute delights, with a rush of acceleration that no competitor
less than $20,000 can match.
</P>
<P>
   It's an efficient, durable and punchy engine, developed for a
European market snobby about performance and driving aesthetics. VW
models have other excellent four- and six-cylinder engine options,
including a lively turbo-diesel, but the 150-horsepower 1.8 turbo
provides the most performance for the price.
</P>
<P>
   This week's test model, a firehouse-red 2000 Jetta GLS 1.8T,
costs $21,500, which could have been pared to a more reasonable
$19,500 with the elimination of the optional Monsoon sound system
and leather seats. The base Jetta, the 115-horse GL, is $17,000 to
$19,000. Top market GLX, with the 174-horsepower VR6 V-6, can reach
to the mid-$20,000s.
</P>
<P>
   Most disappointing is the Jetta's cramped rear seat and higher
prices than same-size competitors, although all Jettas include as
standard 15-inch wheels, height-adjustable front seats, anti-lock
brakes, floor mats, air conditioning, upgraded audio and side
airbags.
</P>
<P>
   VW's Golf, also the recipient of the 1.8T for 2000, is
essentially a hatchback Jetta but sportier looking and more useful
for hauling large objects. Golf models are about $1,300 less than
comparable Jettas.
</P>
<P>
   The first impression you'll have of the Jetta (and Golf) is of
sophistication and quality for the price range. The interior, quiet
and tasteful, is finished in attractive materials and patterns,
with a border of chrome here and there. Exterior panels are
assembled carefully to close tolerances, and the paint is deep and
rich.
</P>
<P>
   Ample space is provided for front-seat occupants, unless they
are more than 6 feet tall, but rear legroom and headroom are
lacking. At 6-foot-2, I couldn't sit in the rear without banging my
head on the headliner. My knees were in my face. The trunk is
roomier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Instrumentation is minimalist, functional and generally easy to
use, although symbols on the climate-control system are tiny and
inscrutable. The cruise-control switch is awkwardly located atop
the turn-signal stalk. Sufficient interior storage space for maps,
sunglasses and the like is provided.
</P>
<P>
   Under way, the Jetta's chassis dynamics and harmony between the
steering, suspension and brakes are impressive. Although not as
stiffly suspended as a sports sedan, the Jetta can be driven
adventurously without undue tire screeching and body swaying.
Steering is precise for a vehicle the Jetta's price, and the car
stops quickly. The body is rigid and solid, rattle- and
squeak-free.
</P>
<P>
   The four-speed automatic transmission, an $875 option in the
1.8T, takes the edge off the turbo's whoosh slightly but makes the
Jetta easier to drive. Unlike some Swedish turbos, VW's 1.8T still
has some turbo lag and hesitation at lower engine speeds. With the
manual five-speed transmission, the driver can get caught in a gear
too high, then have to quickly downshift to regain steam.
</P>
<P>
   The automatic is more intuitive about maintaining proper engine
speed than a daydreaming driver with a five-speed. Of course,
driving enthusiasts will buy nothing but the five-speed, and I'm
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
