<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaner, meaner flagship sedan can run with best
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ General Motors may be axing its performance-oriented
Chevrolet Camaro and Pontiac Firebird in the next couple of years,
but that doesn't mean there's nothing left to offer buyers looking
for something with power. Just check out the second-generation
Oldsmobile Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   For 2001, the Aurora is leaner and meaner, with a 250-horsepower
V-8 out in front of the creature comforts expected in an Olds. GM
calls the Aurora an ``entry-level luxury'' sedan, but it could just
as easily be a ``sports sedan.'' It doesn't take long behind the
wheel to realize the Aurora is a car that can go.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 Auroras have been sold since the model debuted
in 1995; other numbers that really please Olds division execs are
from the racetrack. The Aurora V-8 has won four straight
Indianapolis 500 races, with nine of this year's top 10 finishers,
including winner Juan Montoya, using racing versions of the motor.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what consumers really make of this, but the
win-on-Sunday, sell-on-Monday dictum so often heard in years past
in Southern stock-car racing circles clearly resonates today in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more than power to the Aurora. Opt for the 215-hp
V-6 version and, for a base price of $30,000, a generous helping of
amenities. Move up to the $34,305 Aurora with the V-8, and the
standard fittings will include power leather seats, real wood trim,
power equipment and safety features that include front and side air
bags, traction control and anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Give the design/engineering people some credit for legible
instrumentation and controls where you want them. This year's
Aurora is 6 inches shorter (overall length is about 200 inches)
than last year's model and a couple hundred pounds lighter (3,800
pounds). That's enough heft to give it a stable feel even without
the Aurora's self-leveling independent suspension and traction
control.
</P>
<P>
   Five adults can ride in the Aurora with adequate head and leg
room _ this is a car 56.7 inches tall with almost 38 inches of rear
headroom _ and they'll find little reason to carp. The driver
benefits from stereo/AC controls on the steering wheel, which is a
responsive 2.6 turns lock-to-lock, and the Aurora has enough drink
holders and storage spaces to prevent nitpicking in those areas.
</P>
<P>
   It does have some body lean, and the Aurora cabin isn't as
hushed at speed as some of its competitors, which include the
5-Series BMWs, Lincoln LS, Lexus ES300 and comparably priced
Acuras. But the fact that Olds has a sedan that can be seriously
measured against the German and Japanese cars says a lot for
Oldsmobile and what has been done with its flagship sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
