<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMERCE-MINETA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COMMERCE CHIEF HAS BIG PLANS FOR BRIEF TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Just after being confirmed as President
Clinton's new Commerce secretary, Norman Mineta called the chief
executive of a major Silicon Valley technology company and
introduced himself as ``Secretary Mineta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're secretary to whom?'' a somewhat bewildered assistant to
the executive asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess, technically, I'm secretary to President Clinton,''
Mineta replied.
</P>
<P>
   The former San Jose mayor and longtime U.S. representative is
still getting used to the title _ and his new place in history as
the first Asian-American appointed to the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta returned Thursday to San Jose, where he grew up, in his
first official trip to the region since he was named June 26 to
replace William M. Daley, who resigned to become chairman of Vice
President Al Gore's presidential campaign. The Senate confirmed
Mineta on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has only six months until a new president is in
office, Mineta expects to play a key role in helping the Clinton
White House win Senate approval of normalized trade relations with
China. He also plans to be an advocate for the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta, a delegate at next week's Democratic National
Convention, was skeptical of efforts at the Republican convention
last week to present itself as the party of diversity. But he
conceded the furor over the 1996 fund-raising scandals, including
Vice President Al Gore's appearance at a Buddhist Temple, hurt
Democrats among Asian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta, who is of Japanese descent, insists it is his resume,
not his ethnic background, that got him the job as head of the
Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think it was because of my qualifications,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His resume includes: Army intelligence officer in Korea, San
Jose city councilman and mayor, member of Congress for 21 years
and, since 1995, a senior vice president at Lockheed Martin.
Clinton was interested in tapping him as secretary of
Transportation in 1992, but Mineta chose to stay in Congress and
become chairman of the House Public Works and Transportation
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, he spent three years with his family in a World War II
internment camp in Wyoming. He later fought successfully in
Congress to get reparations for the tens of thousands of
Japanese-Americans forced into the camps out of suspicion that they
would spy for the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta hints that if Gore is elected in November, he may stay in
a Cabinet post, most likely at Commerce or the Department of
Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta said he has a clear focus for the next six months:
keeping the economic boom going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a very fortunate person,'' he said. ``I'm coming into this
job as secretary of Commerce at a time when the economy is booming.
. . . To me, the important thing that I have to do is make sure
this expanding economy continues to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes the outlook for the economy remains sunny. The
Commerce Department reported July 28 the gross domestic product
grew at 5 percent last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of his agenda is securing China's entry into the
World Trade Organization. The House voted in May to approve
permanent normal trade relations with China and the country's entry
into the WTO. The Senate is expected to approve the measure this
fall, but it must clear stiff opposition from, among others, Sen.
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the chairman of
the Foreign Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say normalizing trade relations undermines Congress'
ability to pressure China to improve its human rights record. For
years, Congress has had to vote annually to extend trade relations
with China while the bill before the Senate would make the ties
permanent.
</P>
<P>
   Mineta disagrees with the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's human rights or trade violations or anything
else, it seems to me you're better off having them at the table,
rather than be outside the tent,'' he said. ``If you're at the
table and inside the tent, at least you're able to talk about and
negotiate these items with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Mineta said spurring the growth of electronic commerce is
another major priority. He believes the Commerce Department should
help set privacy rules to protect Internet users, and uniform
standards to make sure different technologies are easy to use for
consumers. Generally, the government should have a ``minimalist
role'' in regulating trade over the Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Calif., praised Mineta for his focus on
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm represented the epicenter of the area that created the
new economy,'' Eshoo said, referring to California's Silicon
Valley. ``He understands how to use the extraordinary powers of his
office to do great things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
