<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-AURILIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RICH AURILIA LONGS FOR THE BIG APPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN SHEA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rich Aurilia doesn't hide the fact he'd welcome
playing in New York one day. It was his childhood dream to be a
Met, to play baseball at Shea Stadium, to catch a subway to work,
to play before friends and family and all the crazies in Gotham.
</P>
<P>
   He still thinks about doing that. Just not yet. Not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to play in New York, but maybe some time down the
road,`` Aurilia said. ``I'm happy in San Francisco. I love the
team, the stadium and my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia was born and raised in Brooklyn, where his father (also
Rich) followed the Brooklyn Dodgers and watched his kid develop
into an All-Big East shortstop at St. John's University and
eventually hook on with Brooklyn's old enemy, the dreaded Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of playing in New York surfaced in June, when
the Mets called the Giants' front office to inquire about Aurilia's
availability.
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia was targeted as a possible replacement for injured Rey
Ordoez, even though Aurilia struggled in the first half with his
glove and bat.
</P>
<P>
   Aurilia also heard that Boston had made inquiries. But if
manager Dusty Baker was going to stick with Aurilia, so would the
front office. Aurilia stayed, and a funny thing happened on the way
to a mediocre season. Just as the trade report surfaced, Aurilia's
game took off.
</P>
<P>
   He regained his batting stroke and fielding prowess, and the
numbers tell it all - he's batting .359 since July 1 while playing
errorless ball in 43 of his last 44 games, including the last 25 in
a row. He also tops National League shortstops with 12 homers and
51 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   And now he is returning to New York, albeit as a Giant, for an
important weekend series and possible playoff preview. The first of
four games is Friday night, and Aurilia expects his parents making
the drive from their new home in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with my game now,'' Aurilia said. ``I finally feel
I'm playing to my capabilities. It's a satisfying feeling after my
rough start.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wild-card standings, the Giants are 11/2 games behind the
Mets. In the first meeting between the teams, the Giants pulled off
a four-game sweep at Pac Bell Park in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of Aurilia, and instead of Barry Larkin, who vetoed a
trade to New York, the Mets acquired shortstop Mike Bordick from
Baltimore and now think they've got enough to win the wild card, if
not overtake Atlanta in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips said he sees ``good balance.
No
</P>
<P>
   gaping holes or weaknesses anywhere. We're not perfect, but
we're pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the pitching staff, which offers a 1-2 punch of Mike
Hampton (11-7, 3.59 ERA) and Al Leiter (12-5, 3.28), who'll pitch
Saturday and Sunday, respectively, against the Giants' top starters
- Shawn Estes (11-3, 3.81) and Livan Hernandez (11-8, 4.00).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really big series, especially because we didn't play
the Mets real well last year,`` said Aurilia, recalling that the
Giants lost seven of nine in the 1999 season series. ``We've got to
beat those teams to get to the playoffs, and they know they've got
to beat us. It'll be an intense series.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not Ebbets Field or the Polo Grounds, but it's the next
best thing for Aurilia, who caught the Giants a few times at Shea
as a kid. He remembers Jack Clark getting beaned and Terry
Mulholland tossing his glove to first base when a comebacker got
stuck in his web.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my favorites to this day is Mookie Wilson. I loved
watching Mookie run the bases,'' Aurilia said. ``I liked Hubie
Brooks and later Keith Hernandez and Wally Backman.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a great place for baseball, but I guess it's
nothing like it was. Growing up in Brooklyn, I felt the sentiment a
lot of people still had for the Dodgers. My dad would tell me about
going to Ebbets Field and all the kids trying to sneak in.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Giants, Dodgers and Yankees all playing within 45
minutes of
</P>
<P>
   each other, that was the golden age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
