<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-11 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JENNY THOMPSON: A SWIMMER TO WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Jenny Thompson has marbled arms, a back of steel
and, judging by a new photo in Sports Illustrated, abs made of hard
metal, too.
</P>
<P>
   This is a strong woman. She's headed for medical school at
Columbia University in another year, and headed to Sydney for her
third Olympic Games next month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow, she has become a sympathetic figure, the poor kid
</P>
<P>
   from New Hampshire whose father bailed out when she was a
toddler and whose spectacular swimming career has been foiled at
the most critical moments.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday should have put an end to all of that. Two snapshots of
Thompson emerged. In one, she was winning the 100-meter butterfly
at the U.S. Olympic Swimming trials, then pumping her fist to the
cheering crowd as she marched off the deck. In the other, she was
wearing skimpy shorts, boots and nothing else. She posed like a
pinup for Sports Illustrated, placing her hands strategically
across her chest to keep things provocative rather than
pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   But even the story accompanying the brash display of flesh
portrays Thompson as thwarted, shortchanged. Only one thing will
</P>
<P>
   stop the pity party that the media insist on throwing in her
honor: a gold medal in an individual Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has five golds now, all in relays. She also has a
silver,
</P>
<P>
   from the 100-meter freestyle in Barcelona. That medal is the
most
</P>
<P>
   controversial, and the most misrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson dived into the pool as the world record-holder in the
100
</P>
<P>
   free. A Chinese woman, Yong Zhuang, won the 1992 gold, beating
Thompson by two-tenths of a second. Zhuang, through a bizarre set
of regulations since abandoned, was not tested for drugs after the
race.
</P>
<P>
   But when dozens of Chinese swimmers started testing positive for
steroids a few years years later, the conventional wisdom said that
Thompson had been cheated out of her rightful place in swimming
history.
</P>
<P>
   There's a problem with that theory. Zhuang did not break
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's world record. She won the Olympic final in 54.64
seconds _ 0.18 of a second slower than Thompson had swum at the
U.S. trials five months earlier. If Zhuang was doping, she still
wasn't unbeatable. Thompson had already proved that she could go
faster than the new champion. She just didn't do it on the day they
were handing out Olympic gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has always had superior times and lamentable timing.
She
</P>
<P>
   was America's premier swimmer in 1996, but she faltered badly at
the Olympic trials. She became an emotional mess before the meet,
unable to sleep, focus or relax. She didn't have the swagger of a
great champion.
</P>
<P>
   She qualified for the U.S. team only on the relays. She was
becoming Dan Jansen Lite, one of those athletes who dominates
events for three years and then shrinks in the Olympic spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been unfathomable, except that Thompson
</P>
<P>
   does not act like a dominant athlete. She swims like one, but in
every other arena, her vulnerability shows.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, she punctuates almost every sentence with a
nervous
</P>
<P>
   laugh. She seems uncomfortable in front of a microphone, almost
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, she has learned how to be a public figure, to say the
right things with poise and a smile. ``I can't tell you how
thrilled I am - and how relieved,'' she said Thursday night, after
her butterfly win. ``I think a lot of people think of it as a
cakewalk, but it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   She admitted to anxiety, to letting her emotions cramp her
</P>
<P>
   style in the last 25 meters of the race. She won in 57.78,
slower than in the semifinals the night before. At the end, she
visibly tightened up, as did runner-up Dara Torres, in the lane
next to her.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them were watching each other, looking side to side
</P>
<P>
   rather than at the finish. Their coach, Richard Quick of
Stanford, scolded them for losing their concentration, their
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   At her age, in her position, Thompson should know better. But if
</P>
<P>
   She gets a little insecure, it's understandable. Whenever she
thinks she's out in front, all alone, somebody always catches up.
</P>
<P>
   At this time last year, everything had locked back into place
for
</P>
<P>
   Thompson. She broke Mary T. Meagher's world record in the 100
butterfly, making herself the undisputed favorite for Sydney. That
record had stood for 18 years, and among active swimmers, only
Thompson had ever seriously challenged it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Thompson's record is gone, shattered twice by Inge
</P>
<P>
   de Bruijn of Holland. She doesn't even have the American record
anymore. Torres took that on Wednesday in the preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Torres came back to swimming last summer, after a seven-year
</P>
<P>
   layoff. She joined Thompson's team, swam Thompson's events,
commanded attention from Thompson's coach. Pretty soon, the two had
to be separated, Thompson in one workout session, Torres in
another.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been only human for Thompson to resent Torres.
</P>
<P>
   The interloper is not just a threat in the pool. She is a former
model, a beautiful, gregarious extrovert whom the media would
adore.
</P>
<P>
   In sports, these things shouldn't matter. But for female
athletes, as Anna Kournikova's disproportionate fame demonstrates,
they matter far too much.
</P>
<P>
   The picture in SI shows that Thompson, too, can play ball
</P>
<P>
   in the pulchritude league. But most of all, she can swim.
</P>
<P>
   Torres was gaining on her all the way down the stretch, but
</P>
<P>
   Thompson never yielded. At the finish, the two embraced in a
full bear hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no, it was totally fake,'' Torres deadpanned at her news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   She was a total ham. She showed up in the press room while
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was still talking and plopped down amid reporters, a
conspicuous presence in the audience, with a red, white and blue
bandanna wrapped around her head.
</P>
<P>
   Torres is a natural scene-stealer. But Thompson has owned this
</P>
<P>
   stage for a long time, too long to step aside now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
