 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Aug. 12. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EGYPTAIR-CRASH (Washington) _ The National Transportation Safety
Board Friday strongly indicated that Egyptair 990 crashed last Oct.
31 because of a deliberate act by the relief co-pilot, releasing
nearly 1,700 pages of documents, as the chairman of the board
declared that there were ``no unresolved safety issues'' that would
require a hearing. But American experts representing Egyptair,
including a former chairman of the Safety Board, said that the
documents contained extensive evidence that argued against the
crash as being a deliberate act. The plane went down about 60 miles
from Nantucket on a flight from Kennedy airport to Cairo, killing
all 217 people aboard. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Undated) _ With the worst wildfires in a generation
still burning out of control across a dozen Western states, a
fierce debate, tinged with politics, is also under way over who is
to blame. Fire experts had warned for years that a buildup of
combustible material in Western forests had reached vast and
dangerous proportions. But federal agencies did not address the
problem in earnest until 1995, and even since, conservative critics
including the Republican governor of Montana said angrily Friday,
the administration did not move with appropriate dispatch. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Long Beach, Calif.) _ Developments at the Reform
Party gatherings. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CLINTON (Dateline to kum) _ A look at the continuing role of
President Clinton in Democratic politics. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-RATES (Tokyo) _ Reflecting its belief that the world's
second largest economy is firmly on the road to recovery, Japan's
central bank raised key interest rates Friday for the first time in
a decade, despite strong pressure from government officials to keep
borrowing costs close to zero as an economic stimulus. The central
bank said it would steer the overnight call rate _ the interest
rate that private banks charge one another _ to 0.25 percent from
virtually zero. The official discount rate, the rate on loans to
private banks, was left unchanged at 0.5 percent, a record low. But
the central bank's decision drew sharp criticism from government
officials, political leaders, and many economists who have argued
that Japan's economy is still too delicate to sustain an increase
in interest rates, no matter how small. Many critics of the rate
hike view it more as an statement of independence on the part of
the central bank than sound economic policy. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWIM (Indianapolis) _ Lenny Krayzelburg, possibly the United
States' best hope for a swimming gold medal in Sydney, swims the
100-meter backstroke Friday night in the Olympic trials. He is the
world record holder in the event, and could well break it here. By
Jere Longman.
</P>
