<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NEWHO     08-11 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS GEARING UP FOR CRISIS-FREE CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, AUGUST 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Sunday.) 
 By JAMES HODGE  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The last preliminary event of what is expected to
be one of the closest presidential races in recent history will
begin Monday when Democrats gather in Los Angeles to nominate Vice
President Al Gore and rally the faithful for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's challenge will be to articulate his vision for the
future, highlight his party's differences with Republican nominee
George W. Bush and tout the administration's record over the past
eight years while stepping out of the political and personal shadow
of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And, as the GOP did two weeks ago, Democrats also hope to mount
a four-day, tightly scripted, televised lovefest without
controversy, conflict or crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But some pre-convention skirmishes may hamper the Democrats'
effort to display that kind of unity and provide some news for the
15,000 journalists expected to be on hand for the event.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons have already arrived in Los Angeles, with a full
schedule of fund-raising activities that has some Gore supporters
angry they will siphon money away from the presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And the Gore folks continue to press Rep. Loretta Sanchez,
D-Calif., a general co-chairwoman of the Democratic National
Convention, to cancel a scheduled fund-raiser at the Los Angeles
Playboy mansion, an icon of Hugh Hefner's adult entertainment
company. It's a potential embarrassment for the party and Gore's
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, who has taken
high-profile stands against the sexual and violent content of
entertainment produced in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides predict these conflicts will be resolved by the time
the convention opens, and the White House predicts that any
animosity toward the Clintons will ease after the president's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will begin the process of passing the torch with his
speech to the convention Monday, a night that will also feature New
York Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton. Tuesday will feature
former candidate Bill Bradley, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and
Massachusetts Sen. Ted Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Convention organizers said President Clinton will offer not only
a recitation of the Clinton-Gore accomplishments, but also a
rousing endorsement of Gore as his successor.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman will accept the party's nomination for vice president
Wednesday night, sharing the stage with Gore's daughter Karenna
Gore Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   Before he steps onto the 5-foot-high, 3,700-square-foot stage at
Los Angeles' Staples Center to accept the nomination Thursday
night, Gore will see his life presented in what aides describe as a
``warm and fuzzy'' biographical video. It will chronicle his tour
in Vietnam, his ``scoops'' as a reporter in Nashville, Tenn., and
his long love affair with his wife, Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to soften aggressive images on the campaign trail, Gore
promised last week that ``I will not say a single unkind word about
Gov. Bush or Dick Cheney,'' but Democratic supporters still expect
him to methodically go down the list of issues that separate the
two presidential campaigns -- from Social Security to tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will hammer on the differences between the two
major party candidates on a variety of issues important to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are big differences in economic policy, in crime policy,
in health care policy, in education policy, environmental policy,
right down the line,'' Clinton told a gathering of Democratic
faithful last week. ``And in our policy on building one America,
whether we should have a minimum wage, hate crimes legislation,
employment nondiscrimination legislation, whether we should
preserve or get rid of a woman's right to choose -- all these
things are at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The president and other speakers are likely to mention House
Republicans more often than speakers at the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Jefferson, D-La., said that ``voters need to know
that with Bush you get the whole package, including the
right-wing-dominated House GOP leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson repeated the Gore campaign's description of the GOP
convention as a masquerade ball, with party leaders keeping top
House GOP leaders mostly out of sight from prime-time TV viewers.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they won't be quiet during the convention,
promising, as Democrats did at the Republican convention, to
provide a daily ``truth quotient'' that won't end until well after
the traditional balloon drop at the convention's close to Tina
Turner's ``Simply the Best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has already provided its pre-convention spin,
predicting that Gore will get a convention bounce and narrow the
gap with Bush, but that he will ultimately fail even with a lot of
production help from Hollywood friends to convince voters he's
capable of working constructively with both Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now does anyone think, after the kind of `risky scheme'
language and `masquerade ball' and `whose planet are they on' type
rhetoric, that Al Gore would truly be able to change the tone in
Washington?'' Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9043 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NEWHO     08-11 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS GEARING UP FOR CRISIS-FREE CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Friday, AUGUST 11, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: Embargoed against use before Sunday.) 
