<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FISHING-DRUGFREE0812-     08-11 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHING-DRUGFREE0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Fish &AMP; Small Fries
 &HT;    By Sofia Villalobos
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CARROLLTON, Ohio _ The crowd was awed as 7-year-old Travis
Dwire proudly displayed the carp on the fishing line.
</P>
<P>
   After gently returning the carp to the water, Travis flashed a
smile and remembered the biggest fish he ever caught. ``It was a
really heavy 16-inch bass and I reeled it in all by myself!''
</P>
<P>
   Travis and his sisters Casey and Lindsay were among 175 children
and parents who were kept occupied with earthworms, rods and
bobbers at Hooked on Fishing, Not Drugs 2000. For the second
summer, the Ohio Division of Wildlife and Five Rivers MetroParks
teamed up to offer a free nine-week program that educates
youngsters about the dangers of drugs while they are kept busy
enjoying nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to teach the children to respect each other and to
respect wildlife,'' said Tina Weaver, a MetroParks wildlife
officer. ``Every week we collect litter around the area.''
</P>
<P>
   During every Wednesday morning session, Tina Weaver and her
husband Trent, who also is a wildlife officer, kick off the day
with an hour of safety tips about biking, hiking, fishing and the
dangers of alcohol and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most importantly, we encourage the parents and guardians to
come with their children so they can appreciate outdoor activities
together,'' Tina Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Hooked on Fishing participants ranged from 5 to 18 years old and
those younger than 15 are required to attend in the presence of a
parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   The Weavers introduce a new fishing topic each week. The lessons
began with introductory information on casting. Children were then
put to the test as they aimed to place their casts inside a hula
hoop floating in Possum Creek Pond. The next step dealt with
baiting the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them it's better and less expensive to use live bait
like night crawlers and crawdads,'' the wildlife officer explained.
</P>
<P>
   For backup bait, the group made dough ball baits of bran flakes,
dried corn, vanilla and water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catfish and carp just love them,'' Tina Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   After learning to properly tie knots to attach to the hooks, the
children were instructed to be aware of the habitat before
attempting to fish. While a pond's water is still and easier to
fish in, the river's current may cause more difficulty because the
bait is likely to get snagged in the greenery.
</P>
<P>
   Week four took on a creative spin and each child had the
opportunity to draw a picture of a freshwater aquatic animal.
Winning artists were supplied with reels and rods. It doesn't stop
there, the children have many chances of acquiring their own
equipment. ``If the kids are on time they win a T-shirt and if they
attend at least six sessions of the nine-week program they get
their own rod and reel along with hooks and bait,'' Tina Weaver
said.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers and fishing experts like 73-year-old Ermon Brown take
part in the workshop by offering guidance and helpful fishing tips.
``The important this is camaraderie,'' he said. ``I'm just an old
guy that loves kids _ they're exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowded under a shelter during a thunderstorm last week, the
children gathered for the final session: learning to fillet their
catch. Each session began with a pledge to resist using harmful
substances followed by a series of safety questions. The children
eagerly raised their hands to answer in exchange for informational
cards about several types of fish.
</P>
<P>
   The storm cleared as the youngsters gathered to watch Brown's
fillet demonstration. Before piercing the catfish, the volunteer
informed everyone that the fillet blade is much sharper than any
household knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to hold his sharp spines down and start cutting the
tough skin behind the whiskers,'' he said as the youngest
participants ones shrieked with excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bibby, an intern at the Division of Wildlife and a Wright
State University student, offered tips on examining the fish before
cooking it. ``The gills have to be red and make sure that the
fish's eyes are clear, or else the fish is not safe to eat,'' she
warned.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing program concluded with an hour of fishing followed
by a fish fry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a lot of fun for these kids and for me, too,''
Tina Weaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
