<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WEATHER-Q&AMP;A-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BAD WEATHER IS GOOD BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Ravi Nathan, the weather is not kindling for small talk.
Sunshine does not necessarily lift his spirits, nor does rain
always sour his mood.
</P>
<P>
   As the portfolio manager of weather derivatives at Aquila
Energy, Nathan is more concerned about how heat waves lingering
over California, hurricanes gathering in the Gulf of Mexico and
cold fronts drifting into the Northeast will affect his clients,
companies whose businesses are vulnerable to the vicissitudes of
the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   This summer has been especially unruly, with droughts and high
heat in parts of the South and West, but rain and relatively cool
weather (so far) in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot day in Kansas City, Mo., where Aquila _ a unit of
Utilicorp United, an energy company and utility _ is based, Nathan
talked of his complicated relationship with the shifting skies.
Following are excerpts from the conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ NEELA BANERJEE
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does it mean to hedge against the weather?
</P>
<P>
   A. We use various weather measures, such as temperature and
precipitation, to come up with various averages for a city, a
region. And we can create an index from those averages that we base
our contracts on.
</P>
<P>
   So for example, if you see from the index that there will be
several days over 100 degrees in New York this summer, then you
enter into a contract that says, for every degree over 100, you get
$10,000. But for that protection, you pay a premium ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Who are most of your clients?
</P>
<P>
   A. Technically, any business impacted by the weather is a
candidate. But mainly it's energy companies, utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But we also get soft-drink companies, too. Beverage companies
hedge by setting up contracts in case there aren't enough hot days.
If the temperature gets above 90, people drink more soda. The
contract will be set up, say you have 50 days in the summer under
90 degrees, and for each day you get paid depending on how much in
prospective sales you lose.
</P>
<P>
   The average risk exposure on the contracts is about $2 million.
But the biggest single contract I've had is $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So how are your clients faring? Did they guess right about
the weather this summer?
</P>
<P>
   A. The weather market in California originally thought summer
would be cool there, because the last three summers have been cool
and power prices didn't do much, and they expected it to be the
same. But weather being weather, it will surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know the meteorological pattern that's caused it, but
a ridge of heat has stayed over the whole West for most of July,
which is strange because weather usually moves around and lets a
region cool off.
</P>
<P>
   But utilities also hedge against cool summers, against people
not turning on their air-conditioners, if you want to put it
simply.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has the summer's unexpected weather _ the lasting heat and
droughts in the West, the cool, rainy weather in the Northeast _
been good or bad for business? And do you react to the weather
differently from other people?
</P>
<P>
   A. What's good for business is when risks go up. When there's so
much volatility, the prospects for making money are good. At the
same time, it is so important for me to balance my exposure out _
all over the country, all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   This summer in America has been absolutely good for business.
We're doing quite well.
</P>
<P>
   But it's bad being a weather trader, because I just can't enjoy
the weather. You walk out of the house and you think the weather
will be a kiss on the cheek, but it ends up being a punch in the
nose. I'll go to New York, say, and I may have a contract there,
and if the weather isn't going the way we planned, I think, ``Oh,
God, I'm losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can individuals use weather derivatives, to, say, hedge their
barbecues?
</P>
<P>
   A. We're prevented by our regulators from dealing with mom and
pop. If people want to bet on the weather, maybe they should try
Vegas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
