<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9046 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-KPMG-ART-$ADV1     08-11 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-KPMG-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KPMG CONSULTING ARM LOOKS READY TO FLY SOLO 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the busy market for initial public offerings _ especially for
volatile Internet-related companies _ analysts tend to be wary,
which makes their enthusiasm for a planned $2.83 billion stock sale
announced last week by KPMG Consulting Inc. all the more
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Through an alliance with Cisco Systems, which invested $1
billion in KPMG Consulting a year ago, the consulting group has
specialized in what it calls ``e-business services'' to a client
list that includes blue-chip companies, the Pentagon, the State
Department and Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the largest technology services IPO in history,''
said Karl Keirstead, vice president for equity research at Lehman
Brothers. ``I think Wall Street will find it quite attractive,'' he
added, in comparison with its competition. Two other big
information-technology services companies, Electronic Data Services
and Computer Science Corp., ``have been going through tough
transitions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think KPMG will be the first of the Big Five accounting
firms'' to sell part of its consulting business to the public, said
Moshe Katri, managing director at SG Cowen Securities, who follows
Sapient Corp., a KPMG competitor. ``We expect the others to
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, federal regulators are hammering out tough new limits on
accounting firms' ability to perform lucrative consulting work for
their audit clients. Last Monday, an arbitrator separated Andersen
Consulting from Arthur Andersen, the tax and auditing firm. Earlier
this year, Ernst &AMP; Young sold its consulting unit to Cap Gemini for
roughly $11 billion, and PricewaterhouseCoopers is considering
divesting itself of its consulting unit by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   In January, KPMG LLP incorporated its consulting unit as a
separate entity, 80.1 percent owned by KPMG and its partners and
19.9 percent by Cisco. KPMG Consulting announced plans in May for a
$1 billion initial public offering, but in an amended prospectus
filed last week with the Securities and Exchange Commission, it
raised the offering to 324.2 million shares to be priced at $6.75
to $8.75 each. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is to be the underwriter.
After the sale, the public would own 55 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Within five years, the accounting firm KPMG LLP and its partners
are to divest themselves of any common shares in the consulting
company, which has applied to trade on Nasdaq under the symbol
KCIN.
</P>
<P>
   Katri is positive about the new offering. ``In general, spending
on information technology services is growing about 14 percent a
year,'' he said. ``The biggest attraction of computer services is
that investors don't bet on the technology itself, which may not
work out. You're betting on consultants that use the best-of-breed
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   KPMG is particularly well positioned, Keirstead added. ``All the
Big Five firms are struggling to transition their business models
and employee skill sets to capitalize on the demand for Internet
consulting services,'' he said. ``In my view, KPMG has done the
best job of making the transition, given that half of its revenues
derive from Web consulting projects. That's what Wall Street wants
to own today.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew T. Burns, senior vice president at PaineWebber in San
Francisco, said: ``It's a reasonable valuation. It's a discount to
pure Internet professional services companies and a slight premium
over the mainstay outsourcing companies like Electronic Data
Services.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The stock seems to be priced unusually low, compared with
similar, $20-a-share offerings at the beginning of the year, said
Gail Bronson, a consultant in Palo Alto, Calif., who also provides
market commentary for IPO Monitor, a news and data Web site. ``What
does that say,'' she asked, ``about the overall enthusiasm of the
investment houses'' to which they made advance presentations?
</P>
<P>
   Even investors who are bullish on KPMG Consulting long term
should steer clear of the initial offering, Bronson advised. ``No
one should buy an IPO in the first day that it trades, or even the
first couple of weeks, until you see where the price settles out
to,'' she said. ``Invariably, if it's a popular offering,'' she
added, ``it will shoot up'' at first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
