<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     08-11 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN'S CANDIDACY WILL TELL MUCH ABOUT AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JIM JONES 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Thank you. God bless you. God bless America,'' Sen. Joseph
Lieberman said this week in Nashville after the history-making
announcement that he would be the first Jewish-American
vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It was an apt beginning for the ``moral crusade'' Lieberman will
carry out in the months ahead as running mate of Democratic
presidential hopeful Al Gore, a Southern Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is a devout Orthodox Jew who prays three times a day
and walks to Sabbath services because of his religion's
prohibitions against driving or working on the Sabbath. He doesn't
even turn on lights or punch elevator buttons on the Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't attend the political convention nominating him as
senator in Connecticut because it fell on Saturday. However,
Lieberman said his religion allows some public service work on the
Sabbath, such as crucial votes in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent book, ``In Praise of Public Life,'' co-authored
with Michael D'Orso (Simon and Schuster. $21), Lieberman says
America is tired of its moral backsliding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clear signs of a beginning of a new American
\Rspiritual\S awakening around our country today,'' he writes.
``Today's awakening is appropriately multidenominational and
broadly spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans are alarmed by what they see as ``a crumbling moral
framework,'' reflected by rising divorce rates and such recent
history as the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, the high school shootings
at Littleton, Colo., and similar disastrous events.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman tells about his own divorce 16 years ago, calling it
one of his most painful decisions. Today, he is happily remarried
to Haddasah Freilich Lieberman, whose parents were Holocaust
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked with prominent Christians, such as former
Education Secretary William Bennett, in denouncing what he calls
violent and immoral programming in movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   This presidential campaign will be a time of testing for
America. Will citizens in a predominantly Christian nation show
respect for the first Jewish vice-presidential candidate? Or will
some revert to name-calling and bigotry?
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup Poll indicates a large majority of Americans
would not reject a presidential candidate simply because he is
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rev. Welton Gaddy, director of the Interfaith
Alliance, a multidenominational organization that counters
political efforts by religious conservatives, said pockets of
prejudice linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is some people will continue to apply a religious
litmus test to candidates, and that's sad,'' Gaddy said.
</P>
<P>
   While admiring Lieberman's moral stands, Gaddy said the
vice-presidential nominee and all other candidates should be judged
on their political merits, not their faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not electing holy man of the year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Land, president of the conservative Southern Baptist
Religious Ethics &AMP; Religious Liberty Commission in Nashville,
Tenn., said most Baptists won't reject Lieberman simply because he
is Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Land said controversial campaigns by Baptists aimed at
conversion of Jews to Christianity were misinterpreted and were
examples of a biblical command to evangelize all people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Baptist voters respect Senator Lieberman's faith and
commitment; they see it as a positive, not a negative,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Land said, many Baptists will be turned off by
Lieberman's pro-choice stand on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Lieberman praises America's strides in showing
tolerance to minority races and religions. But he said a skewed
view of tolerance has caused an erosion of moral values in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We confused tolerance and respect for all people with
tolerance and respect for all behavior,'' he writes. ``This moral
timidity in the name of tolerance deprived us of the common
vocabulary of values and the shared moral assumptions that
traditionally have been at the heart of the American experience
...''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's faith commitment again accentuates the major role
religion is playing in this year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush, a United
Methodist, has called Jesus of Nazareth his philosophical hero. He
candidly speaks about his own spiritual rebirth, influenced by
private conversations with Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a moderate Southern Baptist, has said that part of his
decision-making is based on asking the question, ``What would Jesus
do?''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a political decision on the part of Gore to name
a Jewish running mate, it was a stunning reaffirmation of America's
unique brand of religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In Lieberman's own words, ``Miracles do happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The true miracle could blossom in the months ahead as Americans
set aside age-old bigotries and choose a candidate on his morality,
integrity and governing skills, not his religion.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0182 </DOCNO>
