A9048 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-FOLIAGE-IFYOUGO-TEX     08-11 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOLIAGE-IFYOUGO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME TIPS IF YOU DECIDE TO GO
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Accompanies FALL FOLIAGE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the beauties of enjoying fall foliage is that you can
just pick up and go _ self-led driving tours are a popular way to
enjoy the colors. But if you prefer to leave the driving to someone
else, or need advice choosing an area, here's some help:
</P>
<P>
   Great Train Escapes offers combination train/bus foliage tours
through New England, with stops in Boston, Cape Cod, Mystic, Conn.,
and more. Eight-day trips in September and October start at about
$2,000. (888) 544-RAIL; www.greattrainescapes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Tauck World Discovery has several fall foliage itineraries,
covering New England, the Canadian Rockies, Midwestern states and
Colorado. An 11-day New England tour, stopping in Lake Placid,
N.Y., Stowe, Vt., and more, starts at about $2,600; (800) 214-5158;
www.tauck.com.
</P>
<P>
   Globus Tours offers several fall foliage itineraries, hitting
such high spots as the Adirondack and White mountains; an eight-day
bus tour starts at about $1,300. Contact a travel agent or visit
www.globusandcosmos.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foliologist'' Scotty Johnston of Tauck World Discovery
regularly updates his color prediction hot line through the end of
autumn; call (800) 214-8209.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a number of hot lines, tourism departments and Web
sites offer fall-color guidance. However, as the season starts
later here, some of the following will not have updated information
for another few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For an overall view, try the Texas Parks and Wildlife
Department, www.tpwd.state.tx.us or (800) 792-1112. The state
tourism department _ (800) 452-9292; www.traveltex.com _ is also
helpful.
</P>
<P>
   For information on East Texas sites, contact the East Texas
Tourism Association, (903) 757-4444; www.easttexasguide.com.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Maples State Natural Area fills quickly, especially with
campers; the park's main number is (830) 966-3413.
www.tpwd.state.tx.us/parks/index.html
</P>
<P>
   Guadalupe Mountains National Park updates foliage information
regularly starting in October; (915) 828-3251.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Canadian sites, call (806) 323-6234;
www.canadiantx.com
</P>
<P>
   The Texas State Railroad runs a fall foliage route between
Palestine and Rusk in east Texas; (800) 442-8951.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
