<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD REASONS NOT TO FORWARD THAT HEART-WRENCHING E-MAIL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By J.R. LABBE 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Humans are the most gullible creatures on the face of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not talking your dog kind of gullible _ you know, you
pretend to throw the ball and then hide it behind your back while
Rambo searches the backyard for something that isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   No, I'm talking the ``I believe everything I see in print''
gullible that prompts otherwise intelligent people to believe some
of the garbage that gets circulated on the Internet as truth.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since I first wrote about the Postal Service e-mail
tax and the ``Janet Reno thinks Christians are cultists'' Net
hoaxes, people who profess to be die-hard daily readers of the
paper continue to forward both e-mails to me, with attached
messages that express their outrage at the disdain that the federal
government shows for the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh.
</P>
<P>
   But there have also been the readers who provided solid reasons
why it is a terrible idea to pass along any of the e-chain types of
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mazy of Florida, a veteran who served with the 2nd Battalion
4th Marines, suggests that Net hoaxes and dozens of other ``please
forward to as many people as you can'' e-mails start as a scam by
people who collect active e-mail addresses so ``they can compile
page after countless page of addresses to sell to the mailing list
companies so that they in turn can flood your mailbox with all of
their unwanted mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you respond to a `Remove' from an e-mail, all you're
doing is assuring the fact that you will be receiving even more
junk mail. The sender will stop sending you his'' _ er, remember,
Jim's a Marine, so I must judiciously edit the adjective inserted
here _ ``mail, but he also takes the address (the one you just
proved to him is current) and sells it to other junk e-mailers. The
cycle continues over and over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Tow from Richland, Wash., cautions about the sob stories
that call for folks to forward chain letters to countless friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most ask only that the recipient forward them to `all your
friends' or `at least ten friends.' They seem to circulate forever,
even though most of these heart-rending stories are not true. The
one about the little girl in the wheelchair, alone in the park,
with the sad look on her face, is full of logical flaws, but used
to cycle through my inbox every other month.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the harm in this, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   ``The damage they do is to fill the e-mail servers and inboxes
with e-junk and, because most people use `Forward,' they create
huge lists of valid e-mail addresses that can be misused by the
unscrupulous,'' Tow wrote. ``I believe chain letters are money in
the pockets of those who gather and sell lists of valid e-mail
addresses to spammers and others who send unsolicited commercial
e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil Unsel, a local buddy of mine, suggested that folks should
add the ``Urban Legend Combat Kit'' Web site to their handy list of
electronic bookmarks if they have any doubts about the validity of
an e-mail claim.
</P>
<P>
   The site is terrific fun. It breaks down the hoaxes by category:
new legends (Are people putting HIV-infected needles in gas pump
handles?); old urban legends and myths (our old Postal Service
friend Bill 602P is here, along with Madalyn Murray O'Hair trying
to ban religious programming on TV and the lapse of
African-American voting rights in 2007); and a ``Forward an Email
to All of Your Friends and Something Great Will Happen'' list.
</P>
<P>
   You can find 'em all at www.netsquirrel.com/combatkit _ the
promises of free beer, candy, computers, cars, CDs, soda and gift
certificates, all for the click of that Forward button.
</P>
<P>
   Tow advises that the best way to stop spam is to just erase it
as it comes in.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person doesn't respond within two or three e-mails, the
spammer usually removes your address for you. He figures he's just
wasting his time e-mailing you and moves on to an even fresher set
of addresses that he just purchased from the guy that everyone
responded to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullible has its dark side, Mazy cautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are too ready to fill out every line of every form they
receive on the Internet, giving out valuable private information as
to who they are and their lifestyle; then they sit back and
complain about the spam they are deluged with daily.''
</P>
<P>
   You may be signing away something that's worth a lot more than a
free case of M&AMP;M candy.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
