<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSTANDING CROP OF CONVERTIBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you live in the Northeast or Upper Midwest, you may be
shopping for an ark. Who can think of convertibles when gray skies
seem to bring showers almost daily?
</P>
<P>
   But the long-range forecast calls for sunshine _ someday _ and
when it comes, a drop-top car will seem all the sweeter. And when
it comes to convertibles, the choices have rarely been better, with
several new cars out now. Here are models from major manufacturers
priced at $150,000 or less:
</P>
<P>
   ASTON MARTIN DB7 VANTAGE VOLANTE
</P>
<P>
   $150,000; 420-horsepower V-12; rear drive; 4 seats; power top;
glass rear window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The styling is beautiful and the V-12 power is impressive, but
the DB7's real draw is the Aston Martin nameplate, which guarantees
exclusivity almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ACURA NSX-T
</P>
<P>
   $88,745; V-6 (252 or 290 h.p.) rear drive; 2 seats; removable
roof panels.
</P>
<P>
   An exotic, distinctively styled supercar with Honda quality and
durability, this midengine, race-inspired rocket is unlikely to
leave you stranded.
</P>
<P>
   AUDI TT ROADSTER
</P>
<P>
   $33,750, 180-h.p. 4, front drive and manual top; $39,450,
225-h.p. turbo 4, all-wheel drive, power top, glass window. Four
seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is there a cooler-looking car on the road than the TT coupe?
Well, there's the 2001 TT roadster. Truly an all-season car, it is
the only medium-priced convertible available with all-wheel drive
for winter snows.
</P>
<P>
   BMW 323Ci
</P>
<P>
   $35,560; 170-h.p. 6; rear drive; 4 seats; manual top; plastic
window; power top optional. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, the 3-Series sedans were remade, then the coupes. This
year, the convertible got a new platform, but it kept its great
road manners. Other engines are coming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW Z3
</P>
<P>
   $31,870 with 170 h.p. 6; $37,470 with 193-h.p. 6; rear drive; 2
seats; manual top; plastic window (power top optional).
</P>
<P>
   BMW M ROADSTER
</P>
<P>
   $43,270; 240-h.p. 6; rear drive; 2 seats; power top; plastic
window.
</P>
<P>
   A high-performance version of the sporty Z3, this pocket rocket
can be highly entertaining in the hands of a skilled driver.
</P>
<P>
   BMW Z8
</P>
<P>
   $128,700 with 94-h.p. V-8; rear drive; 2 seats; power top; glass
window.
</P>
<P>
   James Bond already had a turn at the wheel of this
limited-production roadster with 50's overtones, but it will be an
unattainable dream for most people.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CAMARO
</P>
<P>
   $24,915, 200-h.p. V-6; $29,290, 305-h.p. V-8; rear drive; 4
seats; power top; rear glass.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC FIREBIRD
</P>
<P>
   $25,785, 200-h.p. V-6; $31,525, 305-h.p. V-8.
</P>
<P>
   Camaro and Firebird fans should get 'em while they can. After 33
years in GM's lineup, they are likely to disappear, in their
current form, in 2002. They're still relative bargains, though
insurance can be costly.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CAVALIER Z24
</P>
<P>
   $20,350; 150-h.p. 4; front drive; 4 seats; power top; glass
window.
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC SUNFIRE GT
</P>
<P>
   $22,265; 150-h.p. 4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most affordable softtops around, the Cavalier and
Sunfire come with a long list of standard equipment, including
antilock brakes and traction control.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CORVETTE
</P>
<P>
   $46,350; 345-h.p. V-8; rear drive; 2 seats; power top; glass
window.
</P>
<P>
   The latest version of the Corvette, an American icon since 1953,
keeps the character of past classics but improves on their
weaknesses. It is now easy to climb in and out, and the trunk can
carry two sets of golf clubs. For 2001, horsepower rises to 350.
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER SEBRING
</P>
<P>
   2000 model: $25,070; 168-h.p. V-6; front drive; 4 seats; power
top; glass window.
</P>
<P>
   Practical and relatively affordable, with a back seat that
adults can actually use, the Sebring has been the nation's
best-selling convertible for good reason. For 2001, an all-new
Sebring comes with a 200-horse V-6.
</P>
<P>
   DODGE VIPER R/T10 ROADSTER  &QL; 
$67,950; 450-h.p. V-10; rear drive; 2 seats; manual top. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Viper as a raucous street-legal race car. A new
sport package for weekend warriors trades amenities and weight for
10 more horsepower. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORD MUSTANG
</P>
<P>
   $22,135 (190-h.p. V-6); GT $26,035 (260-h.p. V-8); Cobra $32,370
(385-h.p. V-8); rear drive; 4 seats; power top; glass window.
</P>
<P>
   Ford celebrated the Mustang's 35th anniversary in 1999 with a
redesign that gave the pony car sharper lines and some retro
styling touches. A total remake is due in 2002, with a shift to the
Lincoln LS platform.
</P>
<P>
   HONDA S2000
</P>
<P>
   $32,440; 240-h.p. 4; rear drive; 2 seats; power top; plastic
window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You'll feel like Mario Andretti as you goose the high-revving
engine and quickly run through the short throws of the six-speed
manual transmission. But the purity of the racecar design also
results in a stiff ride, lots of noise and few amenities.
</P>
<P>
   JAGUAR XK SERIES
</P>
<P>
   $71,795 (XK8, 290-h.p. V8); $82,395 (XKR, 370-h.p. supercharged
V-8); rear drive; 4 seats; power top; glass window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Already a raving beauty with sumptuous accommodations and
powerful engines, a Silverstone edition due later this year will
give the XK even more power. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAZDA MIATA
</P>
<P>
   $20,995; 140-h.p. 4; rear drive; 2 seats; manual top; glass
window.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda started the roadster revival a decade ago with this car.
Despite an onslaught of new rivals, the perky Miata still delivers
the most smiles for the money.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ CLK-CLASS
</P>
<P>
   $48,745, 215-h.p. V-6; $56,245, 275-h.p. V-8; rear drive; 4
seats; power top; rear glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though the trunk space is skimpy for a car of this size, the CLK
offers solid, classy, luxurious open-air motoring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ SL-CLASS  &QL; 
$83,245, 302-h.p. V-8; $129,595, 389-h.p. V-12; rear drive; 2
seats; power top; plastic window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The SL, competing in the stratosphere of luxury roadsters, has
worn the same basic body since 1990. A new one is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   MITSUBISHI ECLIPSE SPYDER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $23,842, 154-h.p. 4; $25,732, 205-h.p. V-6; front drive; 4
seats; power top; plastic window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``geo-mechanical'' styling of the Spyder, introduced as an
'01 model last spring, has arcing lines, hard edges and ribbed
panels. There is no longer an all-wheel-drive option. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH PROWLER
</P>
<P>
   $43,725; 253-h.p. V-6; rear drive; 2 seats; manual top; glass
window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the Plymouth brand doomed, this caricature of a 1950's hot
rod will become the Chrysler Prowler in a couple of years. The
car's cartoonish appearance is a lot more fun than its
performance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE BOXSTER
</P>
<P>
   $42,195, 217-h.p. 6 6; $50,695, 250-h.p. 6 rear drive; 2 seats;
power top; plastic window.
</P>
<P>
   New this year, an S model adds a more powerful engine to the
many charms of this midengine sports car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE 911 CARRERA  &QL; 
$75,735; $81,165 with all-wheel drive; 300-h.p. 6; 4 seats: power
top; plastic window.
</P>
<P>
   Many enthusiasts consider the 911 the epitome of sports cars.
The classic look remains even afte a total redesign.
</P>
<P>
   SAAB 9-3  &QL; 
$40,300, 185-h.p. turbo 4; $43,825 SE, 205-h.p. turbo 4; $45,570
Viggen, 230-h.p. turbo 4; 4 seats; power top; glass window. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The name has changed from the 900 to the 9-3 in recent years,
and engines were updated. Yet the basic structure is the same, and
it feels dated.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA CAMRY SOLARA  &QL; 
$25,523; 135-h.p. 4; front drive; 4 seats; power top; glass window.
</P>
<P>
   Based on America's best-selling sedan, the Solara convertible is
quiet, smooth and nicely finished, but don't expect sports car
handling on curvy roads.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA MR2 SPYDER
</P>
<P>
   $23,553; 138-h.p. 4; rear drive; 2 seats; manual top; glass
window.
</P>
<P>
   A midengine design makes the new MR2 a great-handling roadster,
but results in a near-total lack of storage. Unless you travel
solo, the Miata is more practical.
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN CABRIO  &QL; 
$20,515 (GL, manual top), $23,825 (GLS, power top with glass
window); 115-h.p. 4; front drive; 4 seats.
</P>
<P>
   If you want an affordable convertible with European handling,
this is your only choice.
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO C70
</P>
<P>
   $44,075, 190-h.p. 5; $46,075, 236-h.p. 5; front drive; 4 seats;
power top; glass window.
</P>
<P>
   The first Volvo to break out of the company's styling box, the
C70 looks more impressive than it drives. Compared with rock-solid
convertibles from some European manufacturers, the C70's structure
can be shaky and its drivetrain feels coarse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
