<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV13-B     08-11 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV13-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HONORS LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 13, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know it is August when the lead story in the news _ not the
business page but the morning radio news _ is a tire recall.
</P>
<P>
   Granted that Ford and Firestone should have known there was a
problem with sport utility vehicle tires that sometimes
disintegrated at highway speeds. Some 46 deaths may have resulted
in the 10 years since the Ford Explorer was introduced. The anatomy
of industrial error is always interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the second-biggest tire recall in history (at 6.5 million
tires, it is fewer than half the 14.5 Firestone radials replaced in
1978) is the kind of story that usually dominates the headlines in
August, along with ``Eli Lilly Suffers Prozac Blow,'' not to
mention ``War in Chad, Not Many Killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, political and technological tides run deep even in
the still of summer. Their effects were to be glimpsed momentarily
last week when the Clinton administration called John Kenneth
Galbraith to Washington to receive the Medal of Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith, 91, was the oldest of the 15 people honored Wednesday
at the White House for their ``devotion to freedom and its
expansion.'' The presidential medal dates from the administration
of John F. Kennedy. It is the nation's highest civilian award.
</P>
<P>
   The composition was about what you would expect in Bill
Clinton's last honors list _ a wholehearted salute to the social
activist movement in which the president grew up. Included were
George McGovern (Food for Peace), Jesse Jackson (Project Share),
and Marian Wright Edelman (Children's Defense Fund).
</P>
<P>
   Also honored were women's labor activist Mildred McWilliams
Jeffrey, worker advocate Monsignor George G. Higgins of Washington,
immigrant rights advocate Cruz Reynoso of California, and the Rev.
Gardner Calvin Taylor of New York. Others were retired General
Wesley K. Clark, retired Admiral William Crowe, retired Johnson &AMP;
Johnson chief executive and antidrug activist Jim Burke, and AIDS
researcher and educator Mathilde Krim.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the list were Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan of
New York, the late Senator John Chafee of Rhode Island (whose widow
accepted the award) and Nazi hunter Simon Wiesenthal (who did not
attend). None of them can ordinarily expect to be celebrated in the
business pages. Yet all of them are properly understood as being
entrepreneurs, and all have contributed directly to economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Galbraith was the only one of the 15 of whom it can be said
confidently that his influence will continue long into the 21st
century. The reasons are simple. He is a writer and he has filled
an important gap. He has been the chief critic of the dominant
tendencies of modern economics.
</P>
<P>
   In the 62 years since his first book _ ``Modern Competition and
Business Policy,'' with H. S. Dennison _ a steady flow of essays,
novels, histories, criticism, journals, tracts, letters, and
autobiographical writings have issued from his writing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In steadiness of output he resembles one of his heroes, the
novelist Anthony Trollope, of whom it was said that, if he
completed a book during a morning writing session, he would place a
blank sheet of paper before him on the writing desk and begin the
next novel, continuing to write until the allotted time was up.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes speaking for a variety of other economists who for one
reason or another could no longer speak for themselves, other times
speaking for those who had no voice, the world's poor, Galbraith
wove a coherent and complete vision of the great evolving apparatus
of global production and consumption. Often his account was quite
at odds with the version being taught in the principles of
economics course across the way at Harvard, where he was professor
for 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   John Maynard Keynes, Joseph Schumpeter, and Allyn Young had
died. Edward Chamberlin and Joan Robinson were caught up in a vain
attempt to persuade other economists of the significance of
imperfect competition. Thorstein Veblen was all but forgotten. It
was Galbraith who, in books like the ``The Great Crash'' and ``The
New Industrial State,'' depicted an economic order in which
powerful forces contended for dominance and ``consumer
sovereignty'' was more a metaphor than a fact.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one book more than any other for which
Galbraith will be remembered. ``The Affluent Society'' was
published first in 1958, and received new editions in 1969, 1976,
1984, and 1998. ``To furnish a barren room is one thing,'' it
concludes. ``To continue to crowd in furniture until the foundation
buckles is quite another.'' The book is an eloquent brief for more
public investment: in education, the amelioration of poverty and
inequality, environmental quality, preservation, and other
significant human capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to mock the wrong predictions _ although
generalizations that may have seemed wrong in one decade have a
mysterious way of seeming right again the next. In general,
Galbraith greatly underestimated the scope and scale and durability
of the market revival. He overestimated the capacity of a
bureaucratic elite to smoothly administer economic affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is impossible to mistake his deep insight into the
militarily-driven, technologically-hyperactive economy that has
emerged in the years since World War II. Businessmen always were
among his fans. If he couldn't keep up with all the willy-nilly
changes of the '80s and '90s, he nevertheless provided a durable
map of where to look to find the really important stories of the
day: the burgeoning consumerism, the increasing inequalities among
the labor force, and even the patent disputes and the tire recalls
that are the stuff of news in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many economists have enlisted in an effort to
``get Galbraith right'' _ or Schumpeter, or Veblen, or Chamberlin.
And, indeed, new tools are being forged all the time with which to
discuss the frictions, assymetries and inequalities which Galbraith
insisted were the essence of the process. Instead of ``The Great
Crash,'' we get behavioral finance. More power to the scientists in
their quest.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is worth remembering that Galbraith all along has been
not a scientist but a humanist. He is committed as few others to
seeing things whole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
