<HEADLINE>
$ADV16 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For release WED., AUG. 16, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: All times are Eastern Time unless otherwise specified.
Please check local listings for time and channel.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the next-to-the last week of the most popular TV show of
the millennium so far. ``Survivor,'' airing at 8 on CBS, has blown
ABC's ``Millionaire'' out of the top spot in the ratings and become
a true phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Only five castaways are left on the island as tonight's
installment begins: Sean, Kelly, Rudy, Richard and Susan. Since the
last four have voted as a bloc almost straight through, you might
expect Sean to be the next to go. But Kelly's loyalty to the
alliance has come under doubt, so she may be targeted.
</P>
<P>
   And if the million-dollar pot of gold at the end of this twisted
rainbow isn't enough, the prize in tonight's reward challenge is
some cold beer, which sounds pretty enticing after 30-odd days on
the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is followed at 9 on CBS by the execrable ``Big
Brother.'' Unless you're really a connoisseur of awful television,
you might want to skip that and switch to Fox for ``American
High,'' which is a cinema verite documentary set in a suburban
Chicago high school. Real kids, real problems, and some compelling
video _ this may be Fox's way of jumping on the reality-TV
bandwagon, but it's an honorable effort, which is more than we can
say for the appalling ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democratic convention: Vice presidential nominee designate
Joseph Lieberman should speak tonight. You can watch on PBS from
7:00 p.m.-closing, or on ABC, CBS or NBC from 10:00-11:00 p.m.
Cable networks CNN, C-SPAN, MSNBC and Fox News will air hours of
coverage and pundit blathering. And Comedy Central will have
``Indecision 2000'' coverage at 11 on ``The Daily Show.'' From Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``King of the Hill,'' Fox at 8: A father and son shooting
contest threatens to expose Hank's poor marksmanship, while Bobby
turns out to be an ace. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing,'' NBC at 9: Honored by Viewers for Quality
Television and the Family TV Awards, as well as 18 Emmy
nominations, this might be broadcast TV's best drama, even if ``The
Sopranos'' would win in head-to-head competition. Tonight, staffers
have to bail the president's Supreme Court nominee (guest star
Edward James Olmos) out of jail in Los Angeles after a DWI arrest.
Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew Carey Show,'' ABC at 9: Drew wants a promotion and may
have to step on someone else to get it. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Crocodile Hunter,'' Animal Planet at 9: Traveling the Dingo
Fence, which is a sort of Berlin Wall put up to protect Australia's
sheep from the doglike wild dingo. But more important, wouldn't
Dingo Fence be a great name for a rock band?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At Any Cost,'' VH1 at 9: A cautionary tale about the predatory
nature of the music business, as three young rockers form a band
and then find out what they have to do to succeed. Glenn Quinn
(formerly ``Angel's'' sidekick) has a nice turn as the band's shark
of a manager. Eddie Mills is the lead singer. Made-for-cable movie
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truth About Jane,'' Lifetime at 9: Another airing of last
week's original movie debut about a mother (Stockard Channing) who
has a hard time when her teen-age daughter (Ellen Muth) comes out
as a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' Carrie's in a mess _ Aidan finally says
those three little words, which means her fling with Mr. Big is a
real complication. Plus the usual sophisticated problems for the
other gals, this time involving prenups and phone sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos,'' HBO at 10: Attention from the Feds forces Tony
to relocate his operations to Barone Sanitation, and Richie causes
him much aggravation by continuing to run coke on garbage routes.
Meanwhile, under house arrest, Junior seems to have found a
girlfriend. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park,'' Comedy Central at 10: Another viewer-chosen
rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATE NIGHT TALK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman,'' CBS at 11:35: Ellen
Degeneres, Sheryl Crow. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno,'' NBC at 11:35: Tipper Gore. Hey,
she's in town. And Willie Nelson is the musical guest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically Incorrect with Bill Maher,'' ABC at 12:05: Holland
Taylor and White House press secretary Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late, Late Show with Craig Kilborn,'' CBS at 12:35 a.m.: Al
Franken, Sinead O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Night with Conan O'Brien,'' NBC at 12:35: Chris Rock. &QL; 
