<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-COLLECTOR-PROFILE-     08-11 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLLECTOR-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 ON THE PATH TO CREATE A SCHOOL OF THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gregory Javan Mills is talking about the collection
he has spent 20 years assembling: 5,000 films starring black actors
or made by black producers and directors. There is ``Tamango,''
with Dorothy Dandridge as a slave who has a love affair with her
master. There is ``Joe's Bed-Stuy Barbershop: We Cut Heads,'' an
early film by Spike Lee. There is ``Harlem Rides the Range,'' an
all-black western from the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   So what are the prized possessions in Mills' collection at the
New York State Black Film Archive?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call them possessions,'' he stammers, then begs,
``You have to phrase it another way.''
</P>
<P>
   He is sitting in a film and video classroom in the Adam Clayton
Powell State Office Building on 125th Street in Harlem. A Bell &AMP;
Howell projector so old that it looks like an antique refrigerator,
with a door that flaps open if it is not latched, sits on a coffee
table. The machine was built for the military, it turns out. But it
is not his prized possession. Finally, Mills decides that his
prized possession is ``the ability to steer this organization on
the right path.''
</P>
<P>
   And there it is: Unreconstituted art-speak, or rather, arts
administrator-speak, that falls so easily from the tongues of the
type of executive director whose job includes running the projector
and making the popcorn. Mills talks as if he is writing a grant, or
perhaps has written too many: Careful, measured and heavy on what
some might call truisms. ``There's always room for improvement,''
he says after being asked if things are better for black artists
now than in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   At the Harlem Week 2000 Black Film Festival, which ends on
Sunday, Mills is showing films that have not been screened in half
a century or more. They are drawn from his archive, which he
describes as the largest collection of black films. Mills' films
are stored in the basement of the office building and in other
places, including his apartment, the studio in Harlem where he has
lived, alone, since he moved to Manhattan in the 1970s. ``I'm like
Duke Ellington: This is what I do, this is my family. Duke
Ellington said, `Music is my mistress.'''
</P>
<P>
   But collecting movies was an ordeal at first. In the early
1980s, Mills would set up a table outside the New York Public
Library, offering information about his organization. The idea was,
once people came up to the table, they would slip some change into
the donation jar. He ended up with more than money. He met film
collectors from Brooklyn, who provided the reels for the first
Black Film Festival, in 1985. The collaboration was, in Mills'
terms, ``an opportunity to bring Manhattan and Brooklyn together.''
</P>
<P>
   But the collectors did not volunteer to help him build a
collection. ``I would say, `How do you get this stuff?' They would
say, `We got the connections.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, 48, did not start off with much of an interest in film,
although as a child in Winston-Salem, N.C., he loved Bette Davis.
And he remembers overhearing his mother, a public-school dietitian,
talk about Dorothy Dandridge's death (in 1965, at 42, of an
overdose of prescription drugs). His father worked on cars. ``I
don't think I wanted to work in the cafeteria or be a mechanic,''
he says, ``so I became an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   A painter, to be specific. He spent a few years in the Air Force
(his ``Peter Max period,'' he calls it; he painted a psychedelic
mural for the noncommissioned officers' club at Ellsworth Air Force
Base in South Dakota). Then, thanks to the GI Bill, he moved to New
York and enrolled at the School of Visual Arts. He still quotes
Oscar Wilde and Jimi Hendrix like an ardent student.
</P>
<P>
   Here is something he says the professors did not teach him at
the school: In the 1970s, New York galleries would not show ``black
art,'' and that included abstract paintings by a black artist,
namely, him. Here is something they did teach him there: Artists
start schools of thought, like Bauhaus, the Ash Can School and
Dada. So, at school, he decided to start a ``school of thought for
artists of color.'' One of his first projects was to help a fellow
student whose photographs of children playing in Harlem had been
declared ``unaesthetic'' at Visual Arts. His letters of protest led
the administration to reconsider, and the student got the degree
that had been hanging in the balance. A panel discussion on race
and the arts, the first of many, followed.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '80s, Mills saw a public television segment on
Oscar Micheaux, who made films in the early '20s and '30s about
black life and who was nicknamed the Midnight Rambler because he
often rented white movie theaters after midnight to show his films.
Mills knew nothing about the man.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way of things. Know nothing, start a film festival.
Fortunately, Mills and Ernest Steele, who became the archivist,
found _ without the help of the Brooklyn collectors _ the Donnell
Library Center in Midtown Manhattan, which houses the city's film
archives. They spent days researching distributors and collectors
and building a network of people who would alert them when rare
prints came on the market.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, worried that the recession was hurting support of
the arts in Harlem, he considered quitting. ``I thought, `Let's
have an auction, sell off everything, everyone go back to their
first love.''' Then another grant came through, and changed his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
