<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9092 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CLEANING-CHIC-$ADV13-     08-11 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEANING-CHIC-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGING THE FARM FOR A MOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stacey Lavender isn't a cleaning fanatic, but she plays one at
work. Lavender is the assistant buyer in charge of housewares at
Restoration Hardware, the nostalgia-driven national chain, so she
is responsible for the 38 cleaning products and tools the company
now carries, like Italian-made squeegees in two sizes, Johnson
flannel dust cloths, Seeds' Wood Dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Lavender said that the buzz in cleaning right now is microfiber
and that Restoration Hardware will be doing a microfiber ``story,''
as the store calls its displays, in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microfiber creates static electricity,'' Lavender explained,
``which means that it literally attracts dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very cool. We'll have a mop, a mitt and a set of three
towels. I'm pretty excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Also coming in January: an 8-foot telescoping cleaning tool with
a flood-bulb changer, a cobweb brush and a wool duster.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration Hardware sells its cleaning products with the same
chatty fervor and folksy nostalgia it uses to sell the rest of its
wares. For example: ``When I was a kid,'' the squeegee caption on
the company's Web site begins, ``there was a guy named Pete who
yearly took down and washed our storm windows. ...'' The Pete story
won't win the Booker Prize, but you get the point, that squeegees
are iconic objects vibrating with Proustian memories, that
squeegees are something worth thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   On her Web site, Martha Stewart hawks Homekeeping Brushes,
``from a family-run business in Germany that uses only the finest
natural materials, including real goat hair, ostrich feathers and
solid woods.'' They come in odd and wonderful shapes, like enormous
surgical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Williams-Sonoma's current catalogs boast an even more impressive
and seductive array of cleaning tools, including a gleaming,
stainless-steel, hotel-quality, standing dustpan and broom for $95;
a beechwood and horsehair extendable broom set for $16 _ ``For
sheer luxury as well as utility, natural horsehair is a winner''
the caption reads _ and three Miele vacuum cleaners (the Platinum,
at $999, is the best seller).
</P>
<P>
   ``People are spending an enormous amount of money on their
homes, and they want to take care of them,'' Richard Harvey, the
vice president of merchandising for the Williams-Sonoma catalog,
said. ``What we bring to the table is a selection of the absolute
best products. A lot of what we carry you can find in restaurants
and hotels like that upright dustpan. It's $95, but it will last
forever. And you know what? It sells great. And it looks cool. You
can't underestimate how something looks. So part of what we're
doing is making housewares attractive and not so mundane.''
</P>
<P>
   Perish the thought! David Brooks, in his book, ``Bobos in
Paradise, the New Upper Class and How They Got There'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $25), writes, ``Educated elites are expected to spend
huge amounts of money on things that used to be cheap.'' So the
best Bobos, Brooks' term for a group he defines as Bohemian
bourgeois, find the best microfiber mops, Australian lamb's wool
ceiling dusters and professional vacuum cleaners to care for their
restaurant-quality kitchens, recycled teak floors and slate-slab
bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaning has come out of the broom closet. A home magazine,
Dwell, makes its debut this month with a cover line that reads,
``The Most Beautiful Vacuum Cleaners on Earth.'' And aren't they
just? From the pink Hello Kitty Sanyo, $89.95, to the Filter Queen
Majestic, a ringer for the robot on ``Lost in Space,'' about
$1,800. Cleaning has gone all high-tech and looks gender-neutral.
You might call it indoor gardening.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
