<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0812-COX     08-11 2224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Buchanan's choice: black woman teacher
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan today introduced Ezola
Foster, a black Los Angeles teacher and conservative political
activist, as his running mate. Foster, a teacher and administrator
for 33 years, was a supporter of California Proposition 187, which
sought to deny most forms of state aid to illegal immigrants. It
passed, but was invalidated by the courts. Buchanan made his
announcement outside the convention hall in Long Beach, Calif.,
site of an intraparty battle between Buchanan and supporters of
party founder Ross Perot, who is staying out of the fray this year.
Buchanan opponents are holding their own parallel convention
nearby, supporting nuclear physicist John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGNING BEFORE SUNDOWN
</P>
<P>
   Courting key constituencies in battleground states, Al Gore
sought today to boost support from union workers at stops in
Philadelphia and Detroit. Gore is getting the endorsement of the
United Auto Workers despite labor opposition to his views on trade
issues. Appearing with running mate Joe Lieberman at a doll factory
in Philadelphia run by women and known for hiring the disabled and
homeless, Gore also touted proposals for ``unprecedented tax cuts
for working families.'' Afterward, Lieberman was heading home to
Washington to observe the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE LINKAGE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush said today that Al Gore needs to do more to
criticize President Clinton's misconduct in office. Bush told
reporters that Clinton had ``embarrassed the nation'' _ and that
Gore should be saying more about it. ``If Al Gore has differences
with the president, he ought to say loud and clear what they are,''
Bush said. Americans ``have felt let down'' by Clinton's behavior,
Bush said on the plane from California to Oregon as he campaigned
for a second day with his former rival, John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE SEPARATION
</P>
<P>
   Only days before the opening of the Democratic convention,
President Clinton urged Americans to throw no political stones at
Al Gore for the Oval Office affair that Republicans have been using
to link the vice president with Clinton's behavior. ``Surely no
fair-minded person would blame him for the mistakes I've made,''
Clinton volunteered at the end of a 75-minute question-and-answer
session before an audience of 4,500 in Willow Creek Community
Church in South Barrington, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   TWO-PARTY SYSTEM: SEEING DOUBLE
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1995, the Reform Party was founded as an alternative to
the two-party system. Now, the Reform Party is a two-party system.
This year, the party finds itself organized like Noah's Ark. There
are two of everything: two Reform Parties holding two separate
conventions led by two different party chairmen. And by Saturday,
there will be two ``official'' Reform Party presidential
candidates. It'll take the Federal Election Commission, and likely
a federal court, to decide which one is the real Reform Party _
which can be defined as the party that gets the $12.5 million in
federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   DELEGATES TAKING A BACK SEAT
</P>
<P>
   The six members of the Federal Election Commission, rather than
the hundreds of Reform Party delegates, will decide the outcome of
the battle between Pat Buchanan and John Hagelin for $12.5 million
in federal funds that go to the party's presidential nominee. Under
federal election law, the Reform candidate must certify that he's
on the ballot in at least 10 states and then formally ask the FEC
for the federal funds. The commission then votes whether to release
the money. Four votes are needed.
</P>
<P>
   BUT . . . THEIR MONEY IS GOOD
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Leadership Council, the tax-exempt group led by
Joe Lieberman for the last five years, has raised millions from
corporations, including some oil and tobacco companies criticized
by ticket-mate Al Gore. The DLC raised about $4 million last year,
most from companies and executives who gave anywhere from $10,000
to a half-million dollars to support the group's pro-business,
centrist agenda. The donors include communications, high-tech and
pharmaceutical giants. But it also has attracted financial support
from corporations that traditionally support the Republican Party _
like Texaco and Koch Oil and tobacco giants Philip Morris, U.S.
Tobacco and R.J. Reynolds. The DLC provided the donor list to the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   BUT . . . THE PAST IS HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years ago, Congress held televised hearings into
whether the Reagan administration improperly arranged for military
assistance to the Contra rebels battling communism in Nicaragua at
a time when U.S. aid to the rebels had been banned by Congress.
Dick Cheney, then a Wyoming congressman, helped lead the defense of
the administration and Oliver North, countering Democratic
accusations of lying and covering-up by highlighting North's
tireless efforts on behalf of the communist-fighting guerrillas.
Now, Cheney is declining to discuss that role. Said his spokesman,
Dirk Vande Beek: ``This race is about the future and . . . not on a
resolved situation from the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ARMS LENGTH ON PLAYBOY . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California said today she'd be willing
to move her upcoming fund-raiser from the Playboy Mansion after
fellow Democrats blasted the planned gala and removed her as a
convention speaker. ``It's never been about the Playboy Mansion;
it's been about putting on a good event and raising money,'' she
said today. Besides dropping Sanchez from the speakers roster,
party officials plan to meet Aug. 18 to determine whether to take
any additional action against her.
</P>
<P>
   . . . BUT NOT FROM THE MONEY
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said his acceptance of campaign money from Playboy
magazine executives doesn't compare to the poor symbolism of a
Democratic Party official holding a fund-raiser at the Playboy
Mansion. ``It's apples and oranges,'' Gore said today, supporting
the party's decision to separate itself from the event and from
Rep. Loretta Sanchez for her role as organizer. But Gore said he
hoped the dispute could be worked out by moving the fund-raiser to
another location.
</P>
<P>
   FRIST NEW SENATE LIAISON
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential campaign named Sen. Bill Frist of
Tennessee as its liaison with the Senate. Frist played a key role
in last week's Republican convention, delivering a health care
speech on the same night that George W. Bush accepted his
nomination as the party's presidential candidate. Frist was a
co-chairman of the committee that wrote the party platform and
played a key role in retaining Bush's education initiatives. Bush's
previous liaison was Georgia Sen. Paul Coverdell, who died July 18
of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGENCY: GET HILLARY!
</P>
<P>
   A newly formed group wants to raise $9 million to boost Rick
Lazio's Senate chances with a negative advertising blitz in the
campaign's final two months, according to a fund-raising letter
being sent to many New Yorkers. The plans of the Emergency
Committee to Stop Hillary Rodham Clinton are outlined in the
letter. The Lazio campaign disavowed any connection to the group,
based in Washington. Founders of the group, according to the
letterhead, include ex-Reagan aide Lyn Nofziger, ex-Attorney
General Edwin Meese, ex-Rep. Bob Dornan of California and
unsuccessful presidential candidate Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK-CHANGE ARTIST
</P>
<P>
   Blending her unique roles as first lady and Senate candidate,
Hillary Clinton plans several high-profile appearances through the
opening stages of the Democratic convention. She'll attend glitzy
fund- raisers and receptions and then deliver a prime-time address
to the convention Monday night, just before President Clinton takes
the podium. The hoopla began for her today as she and her husband
flew to Los Angeles aboard Air Force One. She was whisked off to a
taping with Jay Leno for his late-night NBC show.
</P>
<P>
   OLD ENOUGH TO BE INDEPENDENT
</P>
<P>
   The only Kentucky Democrat in Congress, Rep. Ken Lucas, says he
won't vote for Al Gore's presidential nomination next week because
of deep differences over tobacco, abortion and gun control. ``I'm
pro-life and he's pro-choice,'' said Lucas. ``I'm for the tobacco
farmer and the tobacco industry here in Kentucky and he is not. I'm
for Second Amendment rights. So we just have some major
differences.'' Consequently, Lucas, a 66-year-old first-termer,
said he'll abstain when fellow delegates vote for Gore's nomination
at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   EVER THE SUPPORTIVE HUSBAND
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton lavished praise on his wife for pursuing a
Senate seat and promised that if she's elected, doubtful New
Yorkers ``will never have another question'' about her
qualifications. At a $25,000-a-plate dinner in Manhattan's Upper
East Side that brought in $500,000 for Hillary Clinton's campaign,
the president said he regrets that they had to abandon plans to
spend his last year in office traveling together. But he doesn't
mind, he said, because his wife is pursuing her dream.
</P>
<P>
   WHO WANTS TO BE A CABINET MEMBER?
</P>
<P>
   If George W. Bush wins the presidency, it's a cinch that quite a
few of his friends, political allies and business associates will
share in the patronage. And Texas Republican _ with discretion and
humility of course _ are engaged in a parlor game, trying to guess
who'll get what. The Dallas Morning News says that so many Texans
fancy themselves in top administration jobs that, if fantasy comes
true, the state might suffer a brain drain. No problem, said Texas
GOP chief Susan Weddington: ``Republicans have so many brains, they
could send a bunch to Washington without a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   JEWISH ROOTS STRESSED
</P>
<P>
   Hadassah Lieberman made her first campaign trip apart from her
husband, taking Tipper Gore to her hometown, where she underscored
her Jewish faith and the diversity of the Democratic ticket. She
saluted Gardner, Mass., where her father was a rabbi, as a place
``that respected others that were not exactly like them.'' Her late
father, Samuel Freilich, brought his family to the central
Massachusetts industrial town after the Holocuast because it had an
opening for a rabbi. Hadassah Lieberman had been born in Prague,
Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AHEAD IN BATTLEGROUND BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing Al Gore in the battle to win states, and
electoral votes, was underscored this week as George W. Bush
campaigned in California. The powerhouse state, where Gore once led
comfortably, now appears competitive. And Bush is showing strength
in the polls in many other key battleground states. In 20 states
where both campaigns are focusing their energy and advertising,
Bush has a lead or an edge in more than half, including some states
Democrats should be able to count on. He was even with Gore in
seven of those states, while Gore was ahead in only two.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE USUAL TOUR BUSES DON'T GO
</P>
<P>
   The air-conditioned bus stopped in front of the local landmark
in Huntington Park, and would-be convention protesters got out to
gawk and snap photos of a block-long mountain of concrete rubble.
As Southern California puts on its best face for next week's
Democratic convention, community activists showcased its seedier
side with a ``reality tour.'' The sweep through downtown and the
industrial suburbs of Los Angeles included stops at a half-built
high school sitting on a toxic site and an oil refinery that
critics fear could spread a poison cloud in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING HIS DAY JOB
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lieberman will still seek a third term in the Senate, even
as he pursues the vice presidency as Al Gore's running mate.
Spokesman Dan Gerstein said Thursday that Lieberman considered
dropping out, but decided it ``would cause a lot of instability and
potentially hurt the party if he took his name off the ballot.''
But Democrats worry that the decision might show a lack of faith in
Gore's prospects. Also, if Lieberman wins the vice presidency,
Connecticut's Republican governor would appoint a Republican
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   GIVE HIM A UNION CARD
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader walked the picket
line Thursday with Communication Workers of America employees
striking Verizon, the largest Baby Bell, unconcerned that the
strikers' union already has endorsed Al Gore. He said Democrats and
Republicans are both to blame for putting corporate interests above
public interest. Nader has made federal labor law and corporate
influence on public policy centerpieces of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A CLAY FAMILY TRADITION
</P>
<P>
   In a five-way race to succeed retiring Rep. William Clay
(D-Mo.), the congressman's 44-year-old son, state Sen. William Clay
Jr., won the Democratic primary this week in the 1st Congressional
District. The election had been expected to be close, but Clay won
handily, sweeping St. Louis and elsewhere running slightly ahead of
his main rival, Charlie Dooley, a member of the St. Louis County
Council.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
