<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9095 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-CLEANING-CHIC-$ADV13-     08-11 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEANING-CHIC-$ADV13-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: indoor gardening.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now, you can brandish your Miele Red Star, $699 (with a
telescoping wand for hard-to-reach places), as proudly as you once
did your forged-steel Smith &AMP; Hawken trowel; debate the attributes
of Orange Glo versus Murphy's Oil Soap, as you once debated compost
mixes; and deploy with aplomb your Williams-Sonoma Parsley
Countertop Scrub ($9.50) on your soapstone counter.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book, ``Sex and Real Estate: Why We Love Houses''
(Pantheon, $23), Marjorie Garber proposes that many people view
houses as objects of sexual and romantic desire. ``By providing not
only love objects but love stories, love scenarios,'' writes
Garber, a Harvard University professor, who clearly delights in
cultural metaphor, ``the house and its furnishings are doing our
living for us.'' In Garber's world view, spring cleaning is a Roman
orgy. What fun!
</P>
<P>
   A good manual helps. Cheryl Mendelson is a lawyer, a philosophy
professor and the author of ``Home Comforts: The Art and Science of
Keeping House,'' (Scribner, $35), a hugely comprehensive manual for
matters domestic, from mildew removal to accident liability at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Where Martha Stewart, still the benchmark for domestic activity,
is Vreelandesque and hortatory _ ``Why don't you clean your
silverware drawer?'' _ Mendelson is academic, encyclopedic and
sometimes very funny, a Beeton with a Ph.D. There are now 200,000
copies of ``Home Comforts'' in print. ``It's popped on and off the
best-seller lists,'' Beth Wareham, the director of publicity at
Simon &AMP; Schuster, said. ``The response has sort of blown us away.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though cleaning house represents only part of the book's
scope, ``it is always referred to as `that cleaning book,'''
Mendelson said. ``Clearly, that's the part that has touched a
nerve,'' she continued. ``I have a friend who is a psychiatrist,
and she said, `Hmm, clean and dirty, that's 2-year-old stuff.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mendelson, who speaks as vigorously and precisely as she writes,
continued: ``I do think the job situation has strained the
connection to the home. People are working very long hours, and
they're living as transients in their own houses. People are
literally homesick. Maybe one of the ways they respond is to go and
buy all this stuff, to feel rooted and cared for, by caring for
their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Elitism, sex, homesickness _ these are big concepts to swirl
around the mop bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Margaret Horsfield, a BBC journalist who lives
in British Columbia, published a book called ``Biting the Dust: The
Joys of Housework'' (St. Martins Press). It's a discursive social
history of cleaning in this country, a tale of germ warfare and
societal pressures, strewn with weird and wonderful personal
anecdotes, of looking for Mr. Clean and never finding him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing was how much ink the book got,'' Horsfield
said. ``Not many people bought it, but everyone wanted to write
about it, because, it turned out, every reviewer wanted to confess
his or her cleaning practices. There's a lot of emotion around the
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Before too long, I found myself confessing to Horsfield. I told
her about how the skirting boards in my house dominate my thoughts,
and how I find myself stopping work every hour or so to run an old
T-shirt over the notched surfaces. I told her about the Miele
vacuum cleaner I bought last month, the entry-level model purchased
for $319 at the Reliance Vacuum Cleaner Co. in Middletown, R.I. It
doesn't have a telescoping wand, but it does have a swiveling head.
In any case, it is awfully pretty.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, Ramona, who washes her floors every night and likes
to call me after the deed (``It's done!'' she'll breathe into the
phone), had sent me to Reliance for Crush, the store's own citrusy
wood-floor cleaner, which trumps Murphy's. Five hundred dollars
later, I had my new Miele, the Crush, a mop ``system,'' stainless
steel polish, hospital-grade tile cleaner and three empty spray
bottles. I told Horsfield I had never been happier.
</P>
</TEXT>
