 ART ADV.: A photo with BOX-RUIZ is being transmitted to NYT Photo
Service subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, please contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta
 &LR; at the Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of
graphics or photos please call  &UR; 888-346-9867  &LR; or  &UR; 888-603-1036 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-CONVENTION (Los Angeles) _ Monday, the Democrats begin
their presidential convention, hoping to erase the nation's
memories of the recently ended festivities in Philadelphia, where
George W. Bush received his party's coronation. By Wil Haygood. (2
takes)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATION (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THREATENING-BOYFRIEND (Boston) _ For Angelique Uhlmann, the
nightmare began at 4:30 a.m. last Sunday morning, when her
ex-boyfriend, an intellectual property lawyer, phoned her at her
new boyfriend's house to say that he planned to kill him, her and
himself. A terrified Uhlmann is now in hiding in a hotel, bitter at
a court system that she thinks went easy on one of its own and
frantic that her abuser will make good on his threat. By Sacha
Pfeiffer. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VENNOCHI-COLUMN (Undated) _ The People's Republic of
Massachusetts is left out again. By Joan Vennochi.
</P>
<P>
   NYHAN-COLUMN (Philadelphia) -- Good old Gerry Ford left Philly
under his own steam, reminding us that the doughty ex-president
keeps having these near-miss experiences at Republican national
conventions. By David Nyhan.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds.: Derrick Jackson and Alex Beam are not writing today.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-DEMENTED (Undated) _ John Waters' new ``Cecil B.
DeMented'' has fun with both ends of the moviemaking spectrum _
megabore mainstream and sanctimonious indie. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TAO (Undated) -- The great thing about ``The Tao of
Steve,'' Jenniphr Goodman's smart, sparkling, convention-defying
romantic comedy, is the way it flies in the face of genre
expectations. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-WONDERLAND (Undated) _ Not since Mike Leigh's camera
regularly prowled the streets of Margaret Thatcher's England has a
film so convincingly plunged into bleak urban life with the
ensemble zest of Michael Winterbottom's ``Wonderland.'' By Jay
Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-BLESS (Undated) _ If you absolutely cannot wait until next
month's ``Exorcist'' reissue, there's always ``Bless the Child,''
latest in a long and apparently unending line of ``Exorcist'' and
``Omen'' knockoffs. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-REPLACEMENTS (Undated) -- Movies don't get more
shamelessly manipulative than ``The Replacements.'' By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-OPPORTUNISTS (Undated) _ When Victor Kelly's landlord
sneers at him and calls him a loser in ``The Opportunists,'' the
label is not easy to refute. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-PERFECT (Undated) _ Artistic merit can still count for
something, as shown by A Perfect Circle, an alluringly mysterious
Los Angeles group that has become one of the breakthrough acts of
the summer. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ From the start, members of the String
Cheese Incident knew what they wanted. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-GRAVESEND (Undated) _ ``Gravesend Light'' appears without
reference to ``Ruin Creek'' or a trilogy, but it can certainly be
read independently. By Richard Dyer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
