<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TXOUT-GEAR0812-COX     08-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-GEAR0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Admit it _ you've got to have new gear
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It would be interesting to be a billionaire for
a day, just to see how long I could shop f/w new stuff without
getting tired.
</P>
<P>
   I expect the World Bank might have to be called in to assess the
damage, though, because if there's anything better than buying new
gear for hunting season, it's buying new gear and not having to
worry about how much it costs or if there's a warehouse that can
hold it.
</P>
<P>
   And the great thing is marketers know that no hunter can resist
buying something before he heads out to hunt for the first time
each fall, especially if it represents a new twist on an old item.
After all, how many camouflage mesh tops do we really need? Several
apparently, since they now come in versions that are insect proof
and in different colors for different conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But, we have to choose, don't we? Therefore, this seemed like a
good time to review some of the new stuff on the market, as well as
look at some new versions of items you might already have. Here we
go:
</P>
<P>
   _ Chairs: A place to sit during hot, dove season afternoons is
important. You can get a director's chair that holds two people for
about $50 or you can get seats and buckets with built-in ice chests
and storage compartments for shells and other gear. This year I
bought a folding tripod stool in Mossy Oak camo for about $10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clothes: You need a hat for dove hunting to keep the sun off
your face and maybe provide a little camouflage for the birds
coming in. Any cap will do, of course, but there are models that
have mesh crowns to allow for some cooling air to move through. You
can buy them for less than $20. Light cotton or mesh shirts in
every camo pattern on earth are available, usually for less than
$30.
</P>
<P>
   Shorts are nice if you're not hunting in really bad thorn
country. Look for camo or tan or green khakis, $15-50 depending on
brands and how fancy they are.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shells: Most sporting goods stores will offer some kind of
special on dove loads before the season opens. If you hunt much at
all, you might want to consider a case of 10 boxes. These should be
priced anywhere from $40 to $75, depending on the amount of shot
and the promotion at your store.
</P>
<P>
   _ Knives and shears: A good pair of kitchen shears is one of the
best investments you can make for dove and duck seasons. They can
cost $15 or more than $100 if you get into the surgical stainless
steel variety. Most knife manufacturers make them, though, and sell
them for not a lot of money. They do a better job of cutting
through leg and wing bones than a knife and you don't have to
sharpen them as often.
</P>
<P>
   _ Radios: There are all kinds on the market today, and they just
keep getting cheaper as electronics get better. They can be useful
around a dove field for setting hunters and letting people know who
might need shells, drinks or who has a limit and is about to vacate
a hot shooting spot.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is the standard, and the company is selling its
Talkabout models from around $50 up to more than $200 for the most
powerful models. You can even get them in camouflage colors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hearing protection: Those of us going deaf wish we'd known
more about how to protect our ears before it was too late. But it's
never too late to start, no matter how old or young. Anything you
do now is saving hearing for later on.
</P>
<P>
   I have custom ones fitted to my ears that cost $50, and you can
get those at outdoor shows and such. Or you can buy simple ones
that cost a few dollars. There are electronic models with
directional hearing that can cost a couple of hundred and more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
