<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-$ADV14-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GETS UGLY IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Aug. 14)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ It is almost enough to make one have a kind
thought about Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the blue, Al Gore has decided to make a humiliating
example of a woman for the choice she has made of a location for a
fund-raising reception.
</P>
<P>
   This imbroglio involves, curse me for mentioning it in a family
newspaper, the Playboy Mansion. It is also supposed to involve, in
some tortured way that escapes me, sex _ a topic from which
Republicans and Democrats alike recoil with the same horror.
</P>
<P>
   And the allegedly offending person, the Hester Prynne of this
latest tale of morality politics gone nuts, is a congressman
rightly regarded in the Democratic Party as a bit of a hero simply
for the fact that four years ago she dethroned Representative Bob
Dornan of Orange County, who in addition to his other sins had
raised the politics of misogyny to an art.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore invested his time on behalf of Loretta Sanchez when she
ran for reelection against Dornan two years ago, showing up for a
fund-raiser in an apparently politically correct location as well
as two rallies in the county that has been a symbolic capital for
California conservatism but is gradually becoming a symbol of
dynamic diversity. It also turns out that Sanchez is developing
into one fine congressman, increasingly effective on national
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But now, because she had the alleged temerity to arrange a
reception for 650 of her donors at Hugh Hefner's mammary monument
(a smart marketing move and nothing more), consider what is about
to happen to her. At Gore's behest, with the guys who run the
Democratic National Committee and its congressional campaign
affiliate being the agents, she is to be dropped from her
ceremonial honor as a cochairman of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez is also to be denied her few moments of face and
speaking time from the podium of this self-sanctified convention.
And now, if cooler heads do not prevail, she is being threatened
with dismissal from her other ceremonial position as a vice
chairman of the party and official disavowal of her reelection
campaign in what is still a potentially competitive district is
even on the table. These latest threats were conveyed last week
directly to Sanchez by no less than Bill Daley, the Gore campaign's
boss, who should know better, being of the Chicago Daleys, in whose
town the Hefner empire was born.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez's sins consist of the choice of the mansion in stylish
Holmby Hills for an event, sold out at $5,000 a person, for the
benefit of her political action committee (Hispanic Unity USA) that
registers new Latino voters. It will be held under a tent on the
lawn, not inside the sin palace. There will be no Bunnies around,
as is typical at the many such receptions held there that have
benefited causes from cancer research to arms control. The National
Women's Political Caucus has raised money there, as the Hollywood
Women's Political Committee used to, and as Rock the Vote has on
behalf of young voters. Like, big deal.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Gore reaction of disapproval a few weeks ago was
ridiculous enough, but the move to squish Sanchez like a bug
gathered steam last week in the wake of Gore's bold decision to
make Senator Joe Lieberman his running mate. Gore and Lieberman are
apparently set on being the Cotton and Increase Mather of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   The hypocrisy quotient is gigantic. Al Gore has already
collected $1,500 for his own campaign from Hefner and daughter
Christie. Since 1992, the Democratic Party has received at least
$100,000 in Playboy money.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just on the surface. All over town this week,
Democrats are taking money in the homes of people who make dirty
movies, really dirty movies, movies and TV shows that market
violence and sex, toys that glorify gory (pardon the pun) violence,
records that celebrate hatred of women, cop-killing, and rape, not
to mention garden variety polluters, price-gougers, and gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's choice of victim for his symbolism crusade (a slick
marketing effort that in fact destroys the very values it purports
to support) is instructive _ a two-term congressman who is female.
Does anyone think he would land like a ton of bricks on a male
congressman with real seniority?
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez has been magnificent in her refusal to get drawn into
this farce. Under absurd pressure, she is willing to find a
different location if she can hold her crowd and its money, which
will go for something worthwhile. All campaigns end up asking
forbearance of their supporters during the inevitable rush to the
center, and sometimes the last straw is itself symbolic, but it is
no less real.
</P>
<P>
   It may be too late for an outcry to work. But it wouldn't
surprise me if some serious and high-minded money types in the
Democratic Party started writing checks to Hispanic Unity USA and
telling the big-shot guy Democrats that the dough is coming out of
their hides.
</P>
<P>
   Until last week, what Gore was up to was merely dumb. Now,
however things turn out, it's both wrong and revealing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
