<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9103 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JUDAISM-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      08-11 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDAISM-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDAISM: A PRIMER (TWO TAKES)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Al Gore's selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as his
Democratic vice presidential running mate puts the national
spotlight on Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   It is attention that many in the Jewish community welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more positive exposure Jews get and the more awareness the
rest of the world gets about Judaism, the better off we all are,''
said Rabbi Eve Ben-Ora, director of Jewish education for Houston's
Jewish Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   And while Rabbi Shaul Osadchey of Congregation Or Hadash says
the Connecticut senator's nomination brings some concern about
anti-Semitism emanating from misperceptions or misunderstandings of
Judaism, it also ``gives us an opportunity to educate people on
Jewish life.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy learning. Modern Judaism is not a monolithic
religion but one marked by a variety of beliefs and ideas with
varying degrees of observances of rituals and traditions. But there
are some basics on which all three major American branches _
Orthodox, Conservative and Reform _ agree.
</P>
<P>
   Religious Jews worldwide believe in one God.
</P>
<P>
   The world's 14.5 million Jews, including nearly 6 million in the
United States and 3.5 million in Israel, trace their religious
history nearly 4,000 years to the Patriarch Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   Ancient Judaic writers characterize God as a passionate deity
who controls and intercedes in the affairs of his creatures. It was
God who called Abraham to ``leave your country, your kindred and
your father's house for a country which I shall show you; and I
shall make you a great nation'' (Genesis 12:1-2). It is this
promise that allows religious Jews to characterize themselves as a
chosen people who have a divinely selected home: Israel.
</P>
<P>
   God again interceded when the Jewish people were in Egyptian
bondage and called Moses to lead the Jews to freedom. It was to
Moses that God entrusted the Ten Commandments in a personal
encounter on Mount Sinai. Moses is traditionally considered the
author of the Torah, which is the basis of Jewish law and the first
five books of what Christians know as the Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   Over several millennia, the religious observances of Jewish
people revolved around the laws, holy days such as Rosh Hashana and
Yom Kippur, and life cycle events such as weddings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, Judaism faced serious challenges as Jews
found growing acceptance in what once were hostile, discriminatory
societies. But acceptance often came at the price of abandoning
religious observances and distinctive garb. In addition, science
and rationalism of the period called into question the supernatural
and the divine.
</P>
<P>
   The responses to modernity shaped the face of modern Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ORTHODOX
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews are a minority in the United States but are
dominant in Israel, Europe and other areas, according to Rabbi
Joseph Radinsky of United Orthodox Synagogues, Houston's largest
Orthodox congregation with 500 families.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is one of about 1 million Orthodox Jews. Although the
branch is the smallest and most observant of the three, it is
gaining new adherents among younger, tradition-minded Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here in 1976, (the synagogue) was mainly old
people,'' Radinsky said. ``Now it is all young, highly educated
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews interpret the Torah and its divine revelations as
literal events. The Torah, with its traditional regulations, is
regarded as written law. But equally authoritative is Halakha, a
body of oral law, rabbinical commentaries and traditions that the
Orthodox believe are based on the divine revelations at Mount
Sinai.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews believe the Torah and its codes are eternally
binding and unchanging. For example, keeping the Sabbath (from
sunset Friday to sunset Saturday) means no work and a day set aside
to worship God. That is why Lieberman does not campaign or attend
political events on the Sabbath. He also cannot travel except by
foot, which means he walks from his home to the capitol when he
needs to cast a Senate vote on Friday nights or Saturdays. What
constitutes work on the Sabbath can bring forth often detailed
definitions from rabbis and even contradictory opinions.
</P>
<P>
   But rabbis have long held that work that saves lives _ such as
that done by physicians and firefighters _ is exempt from the law.
Lieberman's own rabbi and others have said this also applies to the
senator's work as a public servant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt that _ and the rabbis have encouraged me in
this and Jewish tradition does _ when you have a responsibility to
the people that can protect or advance their well-being or their
lives, then you've got to do it (work),'' Lieberman has said.
</P>
<P>
   By observing the biblical commandments, known as mitzoh,
Orthodox Jews attain personal holiness. Among the commandments are
the dietary laws known as kosher, which, for example, bans the
eating of pork.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews maintain gender traditions such as separating men
and women in the synagogue. Orthodox women still adhere to head
coverings at worship. The Orthodox do not accept women as ordained
rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox men often wear a yarmulka (skull cap) and are required
to pray three times daily.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox also emphasize Hebrew in their services and in
learning, although sermons in the United States are in English.
</P>
<P>
   The Orthodox response to modernity was to keep the Torah
interpretations intact, including oral laws and traditions.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Reform Jewry, while following many Jewish laws and traditions of
old, take a more progressive or liberal view of the Torah and
Halakha.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteenth-century Jewish scholars in Germany, notably Abraham
Geiger, established two basic principles that have guided Reform
Judaism. One is that Judaism is evolving and is not based on a
once-and-forever divine revelation that was likely the product of
human inspiration rather than a supernatural event. Revelation can
continue through great teachers and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The second principle is that Judaism is subject to modern
knowledge and individual critical analysis. The two principles,
coupled with desires to blend in with more open and modern
societies, led Reform leaders to reject many traditions such as
wearing yarmulkas. They modernized worship, introducing the local
language instead of Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   X X X MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest strength of Reform Judaism is that it encourages
people to make informed choices and informed decisions,'' said the
JCC's Ben-Ora. ``What that means is that people have to learn and
to know and then apply that knowledge to their lives. They have the
ability to decide what they are going to do or what they are not
going to do as a result of their leaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Reform Judaism took deep root in the United States through such
leaders as Isaac Mayer Wise (1819-1900). Wise established the Union
of American Hebrew Congregations, Hebrew Union College and the
Central Conference of American Rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Judaism accepts the ordination of women as rabbis and
allows men and women to sit together in the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   American Reform rabbis shocked the Orthodox in 1983 when they
voted to automatically accept as Jewish those who had Jewish
fathers and were raised exclusively Jewish. This changed the
2,000-year-old law that Jewish identity flowed through mothers to
their children.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, along with Reform's more relaxed requirements for
conversion, have created tension with Orthodox leaders, especially
those in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, American Jews have largely supported the Reform
movement. The two largest synagogues in Houston, Beth Israel and
Emanu El, are Reform. There are 1.5 million Reform Jews in 895
congregations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a movement toward more tradition and ritual in
Reform Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in its history (the Reform movement) is turning
back a lot more to traditions which at one point it rejected,''
Ben-Ora said.
</P>
<P>
   Hebrew is being reintroduced in many synagogues, and many rabbis
and laity are returning to the use of the yarmulka.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE
</P>
<P>
   The radical changes introduced by Reform Judaism in the 19th
century led to the development of Conservative Judaism in the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding the need for modern thinking and updating, such
scholars as Solomon Schechter (1850-1915) insisted on the
observance of religious traditions and laws. Schechter was
president of the Jewish Theological Seminary in New York and
organized Conservative congregations into the United Synagogue of
America.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Judaism rejected the personal autonomy that Reform
Judaism espoused, Osadchey said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Jews, along with Reform members, do not take the
Torah revelations as literal but as the product of human
inspiration influenced by God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though (Jewish law) was created by human beings, it has a
divine element to it and (Conservative Jews) accept as a community
this law as binding upon us,'' Osadchey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual does not have the right or prerogative to
determine how, for example, they observe the Sabbath or kosher,''
Osadchey said. ``These are established by the Conservative movement
for its members.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Conservative movement accepted the ordination of
women, it rejected patrilineal descent.
</P>
<P>
   With a foot in both the Reform and the Orthodox worlds,
Conservative congregations can range from very traditional to
liberal. About 1.5 million Jews in 800 congregations are
Conservative movement members.
</P>
<P>
   Other branches
</P>
<P>
   While about 4 million Jews are members of the three major
branches, many American Jews are not affiliated with a specific
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Small numbers are associated with other groups such as
Reconstructionist Judaism, the newest movement among American
Judaism. It is a growing arm of liberal thought and observance that
focuses on social and personal improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Hasidic Jews, with their distinctive wear such as black hats and
long black coats, are a minority of Orthodox Jewry. There are
numerous subdivisions among the Hasidic, who are characterized by a
positive, joyous attitude toward observance and embrace the
mystical dimensions of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
