<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-RUIZ-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S UNDERDOG VS. OLD DOG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Holyfield career text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ There is only one question on the mind of everyone
who has ever known John Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Can he do it?
</P>
<P>
   Can a relatively unknown heavyweight from Massachusetts find a
way to beat the greatest heavyweight of his era Saturday at the
Paris Hilton to win the World Boxing Association title? Can a guy
who was knocked out in 19 seconds six years ago by David Tua
survive the onslaughts of Evander Holyfield and conjure up some way
to defeat him?
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics, of which there are many, answer that with another
question. Can elephants fly?
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the skeptics are right because many of
those same experts said barely four years ago that matching
Holyfield against Mike Tyson was a felony. They said Holyfield's
entrance music that night should have been ``The Executioner's
Song'' because he was walking into a fistic electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven rounds later, Tyson was bloody, beaten, and half
unconscious and suddenly many of the same wiseguys were saying they
knew it all along.
</P>
<P>
   So can John Ruiz beat Evander Holyfield? Yes, he can.
</P>
<P>
   Will he? That's up to him and, to a lesser extent, Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the best Ruiz could not beat the best Holyfield _ but
that Holyfield no longer exists. He is nearly 38 years old and has
been through two hard nights with Lennox Lewis and a similarly
difficult one with Michael Moorer before he finally stopped him
nearly three years ago. That's not to mention his three wars with
Riddick Bowe, fights that changed both men for the worse.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ruiz's battle plan, which is to test Holyfield by
working at a fast pace from the outset and hitting him wherever he
can whenever he can, regardless of the location of the punches, is
a sound one. It is based on a simple question: What does Holyfield
have left?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make Holyfield fight Johnny's fight,'' said Gabe
Mari, Ruiz's trainer. ``Punch and move. Make him work more than he
wants to. Don't let him set the pace. Don't let him get
comfortable. Hopefully, Johnny'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the real question with Ruiz (36-3, 27 KOs), of course.
Will he do it? He can, but will he?
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz is a skilled journeyman, what I call a professional. In
boxing, being called a professional is being spoken of with great
respect. It doesn't mean you are the most skilled fighter in
history or that you are a legend in the making. What it does mean
is you know your trade and how to ply it.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz has learned his the hard way, in small arenas for small
money until his chance finally came. But he has learned, reaching a
point several years ago that shocked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``About three or four fights ago I really started feeling
comfortable,'' Ruiz said. ``That's why I think this fight came at
the right time for me.''
</P>
<P>
   If it did, it will be because Holyfield (36-3-1, 25 KOs) is no
longer what people think he is and Ruiz is more than they think he
is. If Ruiz is that, he can win because he comes to the ring with a
hard jab, the ability to move and box, and enough cumulative power
to wear down an opponent and take him out.
</P>
<P>
   He is not a one-punch knockout artist, but neither is Holyfield.
Both are boxers more than fighters, with Holyfield the consummate
counterpuncher, which means Ruiz must be careful when he presses
the attack not to get caught by a counter left hook as he jabs. He
must keep his right hand up to protect himself at those moments.
But that jab and the movement that is supposed to follow is what he
must use to bother Holyfield and drag him into the deep water of
the fight's late rounds, when Ruiz's youth (28) becomes a benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will beat Holyfield's jab,'' Mari warned. ``Even Lewis
didn't beat him with his jab. But the difference between Johnny's
jab and Lewis's is Lewis throws pillows. There's night and day
difference between them. Johnny's jab does damage. We need to use
it and avoid fighting Holyfield's fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to walk out and knock Johnny out and go home. So we
have to start fast, too. We got youth on our side, so who benefits
if they go to war a little bit?''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis is on the words ``a little bit.'' If a brawl breaks
out early, Holyfield probably wins it. But if a fight breaks out
with punches and counterpunches and a fast pace it could take more
out of Holyfield than it does Ruiz. There are several small things
pointing to Holyfield not being as ready as he should be.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield weighed in Thursday at 221 pounds. It is the heaviest
he has ever weighed for a fight. Combined with the fact he already
had the match postponed once when he claimed a rib injury makes you
wonder how seriously he has taken the 224-pound man in front of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Holyfield has fought down to the level of his
opponent. He rose up in the big fights with Bowe, Tyson, and, to a
lesser extent, the Lewis rematch, but struggled against Moorer
twice, Bobby Czyz, Alex Stewart, and Vaughn Bean. If that pattern
persists Saturday, the three-time champion may find it far more
difficult to become the four-time champion than he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   That Holyfield has little respect for Ruiz was clear when he
stood up at the final press conference and said, ```I'm preparing
for a better person that I see.''
</P>
<P>
   For a longtime Holyfield watcher that meant he doesn't see much,
if he's even bothered to look. He felt the same way about Czyz and
trained three weeks for the fight. He won, but looked so bad Tyson
decided that night to fight him.
</P>
<P>
   The other issue is, who will Ruiz really have in front of him?
He will have an old champion who has not looked like himself since
the second Tyson fight (June 28, 1997). He will have an old
champion who is coming off two straight big fights with Lewis,
neither of which he did well in. He will have an old champion
asking himself to get up mentally for a guy he says doesn't look
like much as a ``person.'' He will have an old champion whose
greatest fights have always been as much mental exercises as
physical ones, nights in which his will overwhelmed bigger,
stronger, and more heavily favored opponents.
</P>
<P>
   As he has aged, Holyfield has begun to face what most athletes
do. Good as his body looks, he admits to having more bad days than
good ones. More days when his shoulder is stiff, or his legs cramp,
or his back is sore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure that's happened,'' said Jim Thomas, Holyfield's advisor.
``But Evander is as well-conditioned an athlete as I've ever seen
at 37.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so but can he be in better shape than he was for the two
Lewis fights? What will he feel like when he leaves for the arena?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe like the old Evander Holyfield. Or maybe just like an old
Evander Holyfield. If the latter happens, and Ruiz remains mentally
strong and follows Mari's plan, it may become clear finally why
Ruiz is only a 4-1 underdog, not 6-1 or 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny has a shot,'' veteran fight trainer Lou Duva said last
week. ``I know this guy (Holyfield, who Duva once trained and
managed). Evander isn't Evander anymore and Johnny can fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the reticent Ruiz acknowledged this week that he is not the
only one with questions about himself when the bell tolls around 11
p.m. Holyfield does too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he comes in,'' Ruiz said. ``I'm ready for that. Making
him work hard is my main goal. From the first round I have to
fight. I'm the underdog. I got more questions to answer than he
does. I have to change people's minds from the beginning to the
end. But I want to see what he still has in the tank after a couple
of rounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect Ruiz to use his jab and his right hand behind it to score
early. But also look for a lot of movement that forces Holyfield to
pursue him, using his energy to get into position to punch.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to see Ruiz loading up, however. Rather he will
look to hit Holyfield anywhere, including on the arms and elbows,
as often as he can while carefully trying to avoid the counterpunch
and uppercut that have turned so many nights Holyfield's way.
</P>
<P>
   If Ruiz's plan is successful, he will make Holyfield work late
into the night, into rounds he never thought he'd be facing. What
happens if they get there will tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield is a great fighter, but he's an old fighter,'' Mari
said. ``I've watched him a lot on tape. I don't think he can see
the punches anymore. I don't think he can get out of the way of a
punch anymore. That's why Lewis hit him so often.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he does have is experience. John doesn't. You have to
rise to the occasion. He has. Now John has to. Everybody has bad
days on the job. But if you're a fighter, you can't have a bad day
on a night like this or you won't be a champion.''
</P>
<P>
   No you won't. But that applies not just to Ruiz. It also applies
to an old warrior who may not be ready for the young brave who is
waiting for him with more arrows in his quiver than Holyfield
thinks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
