<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 13, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   GORE-IMAGE-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ No matter whether you think Al
Gore should be the next president, give him this much: He has
transformed the vice presidency, the subject of generations of
ridicule and derision, into more than the butt of jokes. So it is
remarkable that Gore's political coming-out here next week has been
designed not merely as the usual four-day paean to the party's new
standard bearer but also as a production that will obscure, neglect
and even expunge his time in what he calls the ``Square Office,''
only 18 steps down the blue-carpeted corridor to the Oval Office.
By Richard L. Berke. (Moving in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ron Wyden, a Jew whose parents fled
Nazi Germany, is now the Democratic senator from Oregon, a state in
which Jews account for less than 1 percent of the population.
Oregon is also home to not a few militia members and
black-helicopter conspiracy buffs. And yet Wyden says he has
encountered only a ``small hard core'' of anti-Semitic haters. The
tale of Wyden in Oregon bears retelling for those who reacted to
the news of Sen. Joseph Lieberman's annointing with the queasy
suspicion that this just cannot be good for the Jews. Although
bigotry thrives and shouts rather loud, Jews in this country have
never before had so little reason to worry. The reason is that Jews
are no longer considered ``the other'' in America. By Laurie
Goodstein. (Moving in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS-CREATIONISM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Darwin is back in Kansas.
In the state school board primary this month, Kansas voters
defeated those candidates who last year supported removing any
mention of evolution from the state science curriculum. Now,
whoever wins in November is expected to restore evolution to the
curriculum and reverse a significant victory for advocates of
creationism. By Pam Belluck. (Moving in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-HASSLES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Business travelers have been
grousing for years about flights that fail to take off on time (or
at all), lost bags, arrogant customer service, overcrowded planes
and a tote board full of other indignities and inconveniences. Air
travel, once considered pleasant and even glamorous, is now
routinely derided as something akin to riding a Greyhound with
wings, except the bus has more comfortable seats and usually gets
there on time. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-GAP-REVIEW (Undated) _ Once it was the great taboo. Now,
most American schools and policy-makers are talking about it: the
achievement gap between black and Hispanic students on the one hand
and whites and Asians on the other, which persists even among the
ranks of the most well off and well educated. Fourteen racially
diverse suburbs in different parts of the country have joined to
share successful strategies for closing the gap. As a way of
forcing them to deal with it, states are beginning to require
school districts to break out their test score data by race. By
Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   SINATRA-WWII-REVIEW (New York) _ Some in Times Square aren't
thrilled by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's plan to erect a statue of
Frank Sinatra on the traffic island at 44th Street and Broadway.
Critics say the Crossroads of the World are too congested for the
bronze likeness of a singer with little connection to Broadway. The
most historically significant aspect of this proposal, however, has
been overlooked: The monument in front of the armed forces' busiest
recruiting station would honor a man who avoided the World War II
draft and spent much of his life trying to live it down. By Tom
Kuntz.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LAWS-REVIEW (Boston) _ ``We must help protect our children,
in our schools and streets, by finally and strictly enforcing our
nation's gun laws,'' Gov. George W. Bush of Texas declared in his
acceptance speech at the Republican convention in Philadelphia. In
other words, Bush was saying, we don't need more laws to do the
job. This is one side of the long-running debate on how to control
the terrible toll guns exact on the country. It is the side long
supported by the Republican leadership in Congress and the National
Rifle Association, who see new gun laws as a threat to American
freedom. But is this true? In 1998 alone, 30,708 people were killed
by guns in America, including murders, suicides and accidents, at a
cost estimated as high as $100 billion. Are current laws adequate
to to fight this scourge? By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   THEATERS-ORNATE-REVIEW (Undated) _ Marcus Loew, who founded
Loews Theaters in the early 1900s, once said: ``We sell tickets to
theaters, not movies.'' That was certainly the case when the grand
movie palaces of the teens and twenties lit up America's big cities
and small towns. For the most part, the theaters were baroque,
showy grand dames. Some flaunted crystal chandeliers, marble
floors, and architectural ornamentation worthy of the Sun King.
Now, a new grandiosity is back, inflating cinemas into
Brobdingnagian multiplexes that house as many as 30 screens. Many
theaters now compete with their film selections in terms of
theatricality. By Monte Williams.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-MILITARY-REVIEW (Santiago, Chile) _ A look at the waning
political influence of Chile's once all-powerful military, which is
all the more noteworthy because old authoritarinan habits are
returning in neighboring Peru and several other South American
countries. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   PRAGUE-IMF-TEXT-REVIEW (Prague, Czech Republic) _ Some
translations from the Web site of the Czech Ministry of Interior,
giving advice to Prague residents on how to behave during the
annual IMF/World Bank meeting in September. Prague expects as many
as 30,000 anti-globalization protesters, and international
organizations have expressed worries that that the Czech police
might not be able to handle the protests.
</P>
