<HEADER>
A9113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-NYT &LR;      08-11 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET CAMPAIGNS TO AVERT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ Since being stripped of his senatorial
immunity on Tuesday, Gen. Augusto Pinochet and supporters have
started a campaign to gain support to help him avert a trial on
charges of kidnapping, murder and torture.
</P>
<P>
   The approach represents a shift from what had been a quiet,
strictly legalistic defense before the Supreme Court, with lawyers
arguing that the former dictator was too frail to instruct his
lawyers adequately in a long trial.
</P>
<P>
   The effort, which appears to be orchestrated with conservative
politicians, retired military officers and executives, is an
attempt to galvanize the support of an estimated 30 percent of the
country that still considers Pinochet a hero whose coup in 1973
overthrew President Salvador Allende Gossens, a socialist, and
saved the country from Communism.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, 60 politicians and other supporters gathered
around the general at his house to offer their support in an event
that was carefully choreographed for Chilean television cameras.
The general, smiling and carefully balancing himself with a cane,
spoke for 10 minutes and promised a vigorous defense of his
innocence and honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate obligation that I will assume before my
conscience and my family,'' he said. ``I don't ask for anyone to
accompany me. But those who want to help me can help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet had kept a low profile since returning here in early
March, not voting in the Senate, where he is a member for life
under a constitution written during his 17-year rule, or otherwise
involving himself overtly in politics. He has stayed home, played
with his grandchildren and consulted his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says he is preparing ``a letter to the Chilean people''
that will justify his role in history. It is bound to be a polemic
that may galvanize the right and surely outrage the left.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published this week by the Center of Studies on
Contemporary Reality, a research center, indicates that 52 percent
of Chileans support the Supreme Court decision to strip his
immunity, with 35 percent opposed and the rest giving no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean society has been deeply divided on the case since
Pinochet was arrested two years ago in London on a Spanish warrant
that sought to try him for a variety of serious criminal charges.
Demonstrations have gradually decreased in size and emotion. But
Chileans still express concerns that the case could upset the
country's stability.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's new gestures have been accompanied by a more public
role in recent days by his wife, Lucia Hiriart, the grand dame of
the Chilean right. At a public dinner on Thursday night, Pinochet's
wife criticized the judicial investigation into her husband's
involvement in human rights violations as ``entirely political,
unjust and cowardly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't they judge him immediately after he left the
presidency?'' she asked. ``They waited until now when he is sick,
old and without power. Is that just?''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the new campaign, Francisco Javier Cuadra,
Pinochet's chief of staff from 1984 to 1987 and a lawyer, said:
``Until now, the defense has been strictly juridical and in the
hands of lawyers. I think from now on his defense will be more
political.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative business leaders have become more vocal on
Pinochet's behalf, suggesting that the legal proceedings are having
negative effects on investment. ``The ruling will not alter Chile's
political stability or social peace,'' said Hermann Von
Muhlenbrock, president of the Metal Industries Association. ``But
it will have an impact on future economic activities and in the
decisions of certain investment groups.''
</P>
<P>
   President Ricardo Lagos, a socialist who is moderate on economic
affairs, has tried to encourage businesses to pump up investment as
part of an effort to lift the country from a lingering recession.
He has argued that the Pinochet case should have no economic
repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman, the prosecuting judge in the case, is
preparing a list of questions to interrogate Pinochet. The judge is
widely expected to draw up an indictment in October and then order
a medical examination to test the general's mental state before a
possible trial can begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
