<HEADER>
A9125 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-DENEUVE-DIAMONDS-$ADV     08-11 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENEUVE-DIAMONDS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE KIND OF BEAUTY, COOLLY MEASURING ANOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By GUY TREBAY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The red diamond is worth half a million. It's just
half a carat and looks like a piece of faceted beach glass. ``It's
minuscule,'' Catherine Deneuve says. ``I blow, and it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve is paying a call on Yves Ringler, a diamond merchant who
often sells stones to her friend Marcial Berro, the Argentine
jeweler. Ringler's firm, the Cora Diamond Corp., is well known in
the trade for dealing in colored gems of exceptional rarity and, of
course, cost.
</P>
<P>
   Gems are a subject for which Deneuve has what you might
understate as an affinity. It's an interest put to good use in
``Place Vendome,'' opening here this week. The film stars Deneuve
as the alcoholic widow of a prestigious Parisian diamond dealer
driven to suicide by debt. The plot, such as it is, revolves around
her discovery of, and attempts to unload, a cache of precious and
undoubtedly stolen diamonds. ``I like very much stones,'' the
actress says. ``I've always collected them, rocks at first and then
heart-shaped stones and then precious stones and then ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me show you something rather special,'' Ringler says.
</P>
<P>
   It is a simmering midweek afternoon, but the atmosphere in
Ringler's Midtown office is cool and hushed. The Cora Diamond Corp.
is on a street called Diamond and Jewelry Way, in a nondescript
building with an OshKosh B'Gosh store on the ground floor and the
elite Diamond Dealers Club above. It is here on 47th Street that an
extraordinary percentage of all the gem diamonds on the world
market are faceted, bought and sold; that lobby clocks are set to
times in the diamond capitals of the world (New York, London,
Antwerp); that merchants bustle around carrying million-dollar gems
in cloth wallets beneath their trousers; that security is so tight
that even Catherine Deneuve is stopped for an ID.
</P>
<P>
   Can that be? The star of ``Belle de Jour''? The favorite not
only of Bunuel but Truffaut, Aldrich, Polanski and Agnes Varda? The
onetime face of Marianne, emblem of France? It seems strange to say
so, but casually dressed in a black linen shift, an orange cashmere
cardigan, beige fishnet stockings and tiger-printed linen
sling-backs with pointy toes, Deneuve might pass along New York's
streets almost unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   Her hair is tawny. She wears sunglasses with strong prescription
lenses. Her eyes are slightly puffy, but otherwise she appears to
be a typical Parisian woman of indefinite age, the type once
referred to as BCBG (bon chic, bon genre) by the French. Some
biographies put Deneuve in her mid-50s; some say she's a decade
older. Whatever the truth, she retains the slightly frigid demeanor
that earned her the nickname ``ice queen,'' a description she used
to detest but now says she thinks is ``right on.''
</P>
<P>
   Deneuve has a brother-in-law, a niece and two nephews in the gem
trade. She is a collector of jewels. She can diagram a diamond _
table, girdle and culet _ and talk not only with expertise, but
with experience, about the great jewelers like Harry Winston,
Chaumet and JAR; about the diamond bourse in Antwerp, Belgium;
about the ancient universal method for carrying loose gems, which
is to fold them into a paper pouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to learn this folding,'' she says, for ``Place
Vendome.'' ``You couldn't fake it. And once you fold the paper,
there is no way the stone can go out of the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   Ringler places a tray on the table. ``Most diamond dealers trade
in half carats,'' he remarks. ``One carat and up, it's considered
large diamonds.'' He brings out an intense blue diamond that, by
anyone's standards, is large: 22 carats. ``I like very much this
blue,'' Deneuve says. ``But really, you are going to sell that to
... who? To an Arab? And she can only go out with two bodyguards?''
</P>
<P>
   Ringler palms the stone and then replaces it with a rose one the
size of a pigeon's egg. ``Pretty,'' Deneuve says coolly. ``And how
do you call this color?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bazooka pink,'' he says. ``The rough was African and was over
30-something carats to start.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cannes last year, Deneuve explains, she wore a necklace from
Harry Winston. It had three very large diamonds and was copied from
an original belonging to Marilyn Monroe. ``But hers,'' she says,
``was fake.'' Harry Winston was famous in the trade for two things,
Ringler remarks: He never allowed his face to appear in pictures,
and he always carried a rock in his pocket. ``He liked to have the
feel of a diamond around him,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' Deneuve says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, with her own gems Deneuve is casual to the point of seeming
heedless. Once, she explains, she cleaned a diamond ring in a pot
of boiling water and forgot it was on the stove. The ring was a
loss, but the gem survived. She once dropped a stone in the dirt
while gardening with her grandson. She continues: ``For me ... what
can you do? It was a little diamond. These things happen. But for
him it was wonderful, like a fairy tale, digging, looking for this
treasure in the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The actress lifts an enormous blue stone, and then a yellow and
then a pink, the aggregate value of the three probably $20 million
or more. She examines each as casually as though it were a lump of
sugar and then replaces it with ostentatious care.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tastes,'' she says, ``don't go to such large pieces. It's
disturbing. It's distracting.'' When a woman wears a piece of
jewelry like that, she adds, cocking her beautiful face slightly,
to calculated effect, ``you don't see the woman.'' There is a
pause. A certain kind of answer is obviously called for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another woman, perhaps,'' Ringler replies. And Catherine
Deneuve permits herself a faint smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
