<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     08-11 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET WATCH: WALL ST. AND THE POLITICS OF THE STATUS QUO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miami)   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wall Street's political views are usually summed up
with the simple logic that is a staple of junior high math. If all
wealthy people are Republicans, and all bankers and traders are
wealthy, then all bankers and traders are. ...
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are plenty of exceptions, most notably Robert
E. Rubin, who jumped from running Goldman Sachs to become President
Clinton's Treasury secretary and is now chairman of Citigroup's
executive committee. But for both personal reasons (cut my taxes)
and ideological ones (competition is good, except on investment
banking fees), most financial professionals prefer the Republican
mantra of smaller government programs, less regulation and, of
course, lower taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This year would seem to be no exception. The Republican
candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is offering enough treats
to warm even Gordon Gekko's heart. Bush wants to end the estate
tax, cut income taxes and give people a chance to invest some of
their Social Security taxes in the stock market. Vice President Al
Gore, on the other side of the aisle, prefers tough environmental
regulations and adding a prescription drug benefit to Medicare, a
step that the drug industry opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wall Street remains strangely tepid about Bush. What gives?
</P>
<P>
   Just this: The last five years have been the best in the history
of the U.S. capital markets. Since the end of 1994, the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index has more than tripled, and the value of
United States stocks has risen by more than $10 trillion, to $16
trillion. The Street may be too conservative to thank Bill Clinton
explicitly for its good fortune, but it is well aware that the
federal budget surplus has played an integral role in powering the
market higher.
</P>
<P>
   To finance deficits, the government must sell bonds to
investors, competing for capital that could otherwise be used to
invest in stocks or corporate bonds. Government borrowings raise
long-term interest rates, stifling economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last five years, thanks to tax increases in 1990 and
1993 and relatively restrained government spending, the federal
budget has gone from deficit to surplus. As a result, long-term
interest rates have fallen from 8 percent to less than 6 percent,
after dipping as low as 5 percent in late 1998. With lower interest
rates and lots of capital available, companies of all sizes have
been able to raise the money they need to grow. In turn, strong
economic growth has stimulated consumer spending, raised tax
revenue and increased the government's surplus, making even more
capital available for private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the surplus is not the only reason that the economy has
performed so well lately. Information technology and the explosion
of the Internet have probably been even more important. But
investors are not interested in a return to deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street likes it just as it is and doesn't want to see any
big policy changes,'' said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer
of First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But both Gore and Bush are eager to get their hands on the
surplus for new spending programs and tax cuts. Either move would
be a mistake, said Byron Wien, chief U.S. investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. In fact, if the new president is able
to spend the surplus, the Federal Reserve will probably raise
short-term interest rates, Wien said. That's because the Fed is
already worried that the United States economy is growing too fast
and increasing the risk of inflation, and that deficits (or lower
surpluses) will further stimulate the economy in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want either party's program to pass,'' Wien said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed. While the Street has a slight preference for
Bush, it would be happiest if neither party controls both the White
House and Congress next year, he said. ``I'd like to see a
Republican president neutralized by a Democratic Congress,'' he
said. ``Give us policy gridlock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
