<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GREIG-FILES0812-COX     08-11 1896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-FILES0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GREIG FILES: Back to school
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As the school buses rumble though Central Texas,
bevies of backpacks, reams of ruled paper and coveys of crayons
will be on board.
</P>
<P>
   Back to school means the end of campouts and lazy mornings. It
also signals the end of juvenile ennui as parents breathe a
collective sigh of relief. Goodbye, ``I am bored.'' Hello, ``Do we
have any graph paper?''
</P>
<P>
   Like Pavlov's dog, these students will salivate at the feel of
clean, crisp notebooks under their tanned palms and
chlorine-wrinkled fingers and become intoxicated by the aroma of
newly sharpened pencils.
</P>
<P>
   But back to school also signals back to routines and pressures
and late-night wails of ``Mom, I need four empty juice cans in the
morning and a diorama of the Alamo on Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   On this last free, albeit frantic, Saturday, let the Greig Files
entertain and inform you. After all, this time next week students
and parents alike will be knee-deep in essays on Eastern Europe and
refrigerated science experiments.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder what the signs of stress in school-age children
really are? Or just how that pencil came to be? Even if you do not
have a child in the impending melee, you just may learn something
for that sought-after appearance on the ``Millionaire'' show. So if
you do not know why pencils are yellow or what the original eight
colors were in the first Crayola box, read on and enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a test.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IF YOU HATED YOUR JOB AND HAD TO STAY IN IT FOR 12 YEARS?
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly how some children feel about school, says Lake
Travis psychologist Melanie Horn who specializes in treating
families with school problems.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a daily work environment without much privacy, new tasks
to learn every day and
</P>
<P>
   almost daily reviews from the boss. Yikes! No wonder the school
venue breeds tension in children.
</P>
<P>
   NEED MORE SOURCES FOR STRESS AT BACK-TO-SCHOOL TIME?
</P>
<P>
   Peer pressure, academic pressure and that old bugaboo, parental
expectations, Horn says.
</P>
<P>
   Past social problems with everything from bullying to
persnickety little girls may resurrect like the ghosts of school
years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Children want to be liked and accepted (who doesn't?), but
unfortunately, only a few believe that they are. Moving to a new
school (elementary to middle or middle to high) or even a new
school district may trigger homesickness for the last set of
friends and teachers. As children progress throughout the school
system, campuses grow larger; peer groups, more varied.
</P>
<P>
   Academic challenges of the past year may loom large as rumors of
increased work load and no-nonsense teachers gain credibility.
Parental expectations, including the litany of things a child needs
to do to get into a good college, add to internal pressure. Horn's
advice? Love 'em and hug 'em.
</P>
<P>
   MOM, WHY ARE FROGS BORN WITH EXTRA LIMBS?
</P>
<P>
   Stumped by your child's homework? Keep this site for yourself,
mom and dad, kids.infoplease.lycos.com, where the answer to the
frog question can be found. (Scientists believe these
disfigurements are caused by parasitic flatworms and not chemical
pollution or thinning ozone layers.)
</P>
<P>
   The site also includes odd bits to spice up that dry history
essay on the White House, such as the fact that Teddy Roosevelt's
dog, Pete, once pulled the pants off the French ambassador. (It's
always the French ambassador.)
</P>
<P>
   READY FOR SOME NUMBERS? The uproar in your family as the
children head back to school is shared by others. The National
Center for Education Statistics reports there are almost 90,000
public K-12 schools in the United States. In 1998, 46.7 million
students were enrolled in public schools (33.5 million in
pre-kindergarten through eighth grade; 13.2 million in grades 9-12;
the remainder in schools without designated grade levels). In
addition, more than 27,000 private K-12 schools dot the nation with
an enrollment of almost 6 million students.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S A FERRULE?
</P>
<P>
   The little crimped metal on the end of the pencil that holds the
eraser. Thank Philadelphian Hyman Lipman for attaching erasers to
pencils in 1858. According to the Incense Cedar Institute, erasers
were originally called rubbers since they rubbed out marks made by
a pencil. Erasers are made from vinyl or rubber and, to their
manufacturers, are known as plugs when they sit on the end of a
pencil.
</P>
<P>
   WHY ARE 95 PERCENT OF THE PENCILS SOLD IN THE UNITED STATES
YELLOW?
</P>
<P>
   In the 1800s, the best graphite came from China. Since yellow is
associated in China with respect, American pencil manufacturers
decided to use yellow to let the world know its pencils were filled
with regal Chinese graphite.
</P>
<P>
   IS THERE LEAD IN THAT LEAD PENCIL?
</P>
<P>
   Nope.
</P>
<P>
   It is graphite and clay. Graphite came into widespread use as a
writing tool in the 16th century. This soft yet brittle substance
was first wrapped in string to make pencils. Eventually it was
slipped into a hand-bored tube inside wooden sticks. Talk about
labor intensive!
</P>
<P>
   So how are pencils made? Wood, usually cedar, is cut into block
and then slats. The slats are stained and grooves are cut into one
surface (see illustration at right). Prepared leads (OK, they are
graphite and clay but are still called leads) are placed in the
grooves. A second slat is placed on the top and bonded with the
first. This pencil sandwich is milled and separated into individual
pencils. Finishing touches (paint, erasers, etc.) are added.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the wonderful world of pencils, visit
the Incense Cedar Institute's www.
</P>
<P>
   pencilpages.com.
</P>
<P>
   WHENCE COMETH CRAYOLA CRAYONS?
</P>
<P>
   Cousins Edwin Binney and C. Harold Smith were at the helm of
Peekskill Chemical in New York when teachers clamored for better
materials _ especially a chalk that would not crumble and create
clouds of dust.
</P>
<P>
   Having just developed a new wax crayon to mark crates and
barrels, the cousins were poised to corner the student market. In
1903, the 5-cent box of crayons (non toxic and encased in
hand-rolled labels) hit the market.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WAS ALICE THINKING?
</P>
<P>
   You mean Alice Binney, wife of a founder of Binney &AMP; Smith,
makers of the schoolroom staple?
</P>
<P>
   She combined the French word craie (chalk) with ola (oleaginous
because the crayons were made from petroleum-based paraffin) to
coin the name crayon.
</P>
<P>
   WHO THE HECK IS ELMER? Elsie (the Borden symbol) the cow's
husband and the name of glue that has graced school desks since
1947.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at that time the white glue was called Cascorez Glue
and was packaged in glass bottles with ``ice cream pop'' type
wooden sticks attached with a rubber band. It did not take long for
the makers to figure out Cascorez was not a catchy brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Elmer, spokesbull, and Elmer's Glue All.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE BOX _ CRAYOLA FACTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Crayolas are available in 120 colors, including 20 blues, 19
greens, 15 oranges and 13 purples. _ If all the Crayolas made in
one year (3 billion) were laid end to end on the equator, they
would circle the Earth six times (just before melting). _ The
average child will wear down 730 crayons by his 10th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 24-count box is the best seller, although box sizes
include 8, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 96 and 120.
</P>
<P>
   JOT THIS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   _ One pencil can write 45,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pencil comes from the Latin ``penicillum,'' a paintbrush.
</P>
<P>
   _ Approximately 110 million gross of pencils are manufactured
every year in the world (a gross equals 144 _ math majors, start
multiplying).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Grapes of Wrath'' author John Steinbeck used as many as 60
cedar pencils every day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thomas Edison kept a 3-inch pencil in his vest pocket to jot
down ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pencils made from tropical rain forest wood have a brownish
color with little red or dark brown flecks.
</P>
<P>
   _ A typical pencil can draw a line 35 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   AND DON'T EVER RUN WITH THEM . . .
</P>
<P>
   Scissors, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Scissors are a step up from cutting things with stones like
prehistoric man did. Scissors have been found in ancient Egypt and
Italy. Shepherds cut wool; craftsmen adorned them with metal
inlays. Englishman Benjamin Hustler of Sheffield produced quality
shears of steel in the 1740s. The word is derived from the Middle
English sisoures.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF STRESS IN CHILDREN
</P>
<P>
   _ The mantra: ``I hate school. I do not want to go to school.''
_ Crying frequently before school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Physical complaints such as stomachaches and headaches. _
Irritability or snapping at people _ Loss of interest in things
that used to be fun. _ Changes in eating, sleeping and energy
level, general lethargy. _ Look of sadness or worry. _ Change in
sleeping patterns (including increased number of nightmares,
inability to sleep).
</P>
<P>
   HELPING KIDS COPE
</P>
<P>
   _ Be cognizant of a child's strengths and weaknesses. _ Listen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not downplay or dismiss the child's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not jump in immediately with a lecture. _ Listen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investigate what is going on at school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to understand the child's point of view. _ Listen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have your child evaluated for academic or physical problems.
</P>
<P>
   _ Acknowledge the child's progress and comment on successes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Listen.
</P>
<P>
   READ MY LIPS: NO NEW HOMEWORK EXCUSES
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, librarians and coaches have heard every excuse under
the sun for why books are not returned, homework is not handed in
or equipment is missing. To save students time this year, here are
a few excuses Zilker Librarian Jackie Kraal and fifth-grade teacher
Rebecca Lang have heard that have been used already.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is always the truth: ``My (your pet here) ate
it'' as well as the bizarre ``My sister could not find her same
assignment from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ It's in my aunt's boyfriend's truck.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's in my aunt's boyfriend's truck, and he just sold it.
</P>
<P>
   _ The family printer did not work.
</P>
<P>
   _ My mom's computer is not compatible with my dad's computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ I pushed ``save,'' but the computer did not save it.
</P>
<P>
   _ I gave it to (person's name here) to hand in, and he did not
do it.
</P>
<P>
   _ I had it in my hand, but I left it in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   _ My mom is reading the book.
</P>
<P>
   _ My parents did not put it in my backpack. I switched
backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   _ My dad tore it up because it did not look important.
</P>
<P>
   _ It fell out of my binder.
</P>
<P>
   _ I left it in the car, at home, at a friend's house, in the
other backpack, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _ We had to go out to eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ I took the wrong books home.
</P>
<P>
   _ I did not have a pencil at home.
</P>
<P>
   _ It has been recycled.
</P>
<P>
   _ My (dad, mom) took it to work.
</P>
<P>
   _ We had to go shopping, and I got home late.
</P>
<P>
   _ It blew away.
</P>
<P>
   STICK WITH ME: ELMER'S FACTS
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 47 million elementary school students use Elmer's
Glue on a weekly basis. _ Elmer's Glue is white because of the
natural reaction of the raw materials used to make the glue. _
Elmer's Glue was used to build a pasta bridge supporting 2,350
pounds. The bridge was built by a high school student and was the
winning entry in a pasta-bridge building contest held in Rhode
Island. _ The strength of the glue bond is due to the attachment of
the polymer adhesive to the surface of the piece to be glued.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
