   CVN-MEDIA _ WASHINGTON _ Story on convention media preparations.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, Politics
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-MONEY _ When it comes to raising cash at their convention,
the Democrats give no ground to the the GOP, though they perform
the money dance a little differently. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-TERRY _ When Democratic convention planners ran into money
and organizational problems, they called in Clinton friend and
prodigious money-raiser, Terry McAuliffe. We spend a few days with
the man said to have raised more money than any political
fundraiser in history as he pulls the convention strings in Los
Angeles. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COOL-TOWN _ PALO ALTO, Calif. _ A recent tour of Cool Town, as
Hewlett-Packard labs here are known, highlighted some of the
high-tech gadgets that will be
</P>
<P>
   appearing in our lives soon. (Geewax, Cox News Service). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, Business, Technology.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPES _ BOONVILLE, N.C. _ In the four decades he's grown
tobacco, Frank Hopson never worried about the rising and setting of
the sun. ``Tobacco's a weed,'' and will grow just about anywhere,
he always figured. But now one of a fast growing number of North
Carolina farmers growing grapes to supply area vineyards,
57-year-old Hopson has learned to pay attention to sunshine and
other considerations critical to growing sweet, firm grapes. The
payoff? A crop that agricultural experts say won't replace North
Carolina's embattled, nearly billion-dollar-a-year crop, but one
that is acre for acre as profitable as tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Burritt with photos, possible list of number of commercial
vineyards in other Southern states. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN-TOBACCO _ LEXINGTON, Ky. _ Southern tobacco farmers are
nervous. Growers in Kentucky, North Carolina, Georgia, Tennessee
and South Carolina farm 90 percent of the domestic crop. But a $145
billion anti-tobacco verdict in Florida has many wondering whether
this is the straw that's broken Joe Camel's back. Will they turn to
catfish farms and grape vineyards or car sales? We check and see.
Pegged to meeting of big tobacco on Aug. 14. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PYRAMID-$ADV13 _ MOSCOW _ Looking like something straight
from the X-Files, the cosmic gray three-story pyramid appears
suddenly around a bend off
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's northbound highway. Lines outside it attest to its
reputation of a Mecca of the paranormal. According to its builder,
a new celebrity among Russian faith-healers and astrologists, the
pyramid can bring peace and harmony to the world, can prolong life
and heal disease. All you have to do, he says, is believe. And
thousands of Russians, bored or disenchanted with traditional
religions, do. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., Aug. 9, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-CRIME-$ADV13 _ SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Long admired as
one of Latin America's most peaceful, prosperous and stable
countries, Costa Rica has hit a
</P>
<P>
   bad patch recently with a crime wave that is threatening its
reputation and the peace of mind of its
</P>
<P>
   residents. The murder of two young American women tourists in
March captured international headlines, while a top Costa Rican
policeman recently complained
</P>
<P>
   that he doesn't have the resources to fight the growing problem.
We profile the problem and the country. (Williams, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-CHILDSEX-$ADV13 _ SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Apparently
the country has a booming sex-tourism trade, and children as young
as 12 and 13 have been selling themselves as prostitutes.
(Williams, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., Aug. 9, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DEMOCRACY-$ADV13 _ QIUBAN VILLAGE, China _ Just about
every single one of this watermelon-growing village's 444 eligible
voters turned out to cast a ballot for the village chief. They had
a choice between a mini-bus driver, a shop owner and a fellow
farmer. That the election took place in China is a sign to some -
especially those at the Carter Center, who are working with China
on standardizing village elections _ that this communist country is
on a slow but steady course towards democracy. To others, village
elections are but a cynical gambit by the central leadership to
maintain control over the massive rural
</P>
<P>
   population. (Chao, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move by Wed., Aug. 9, on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ When UPS formed an insurance company in Bermuda in 1983 to
be owned by employees, there was no indication the participants had
any idea they had just set in motion a series of events that would
culminate 16 years later in a punishing U.S. Tax Court ruling that
found UPS had committed a ``sham transaction.'' As a result, the
company may now be forced to pay the IRS one of the largest bills
in tax history - up to $2.3 billion in back taxes, interest and
penalties. UPS has appealed the ruling and the 11th Circuit
considers it next month. (Hirschman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SALES-SLUMPS _Sales slumps happen to even the best sales workers
_ even in good economic times. We'll look at strategies to weather
sales slumps. (Mallory, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MALL-OF-GEORGIA _ ATLANTA _ Mall of Georgia opened with great
fanfare a year ago promising to be the mall of all malls. A year
later, it's still searching for its last anchor and competing in
area that choaking with retail venues. Has it lived up to its
promises. What challenges does it face today? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PHONES _ ATLANTA _Local telephone service, the rather boring
plain jane element in communications compared to go-go cell phones
and red-hot long distance services, has suddenly become a new
battleground. Many players are emerging to take on BellSouth, none
more eager than the cable giant,
</P>
<P>
   MediaOne, backed by its tentative parent, AT&AMP;T. Yes, AT&AMP;T, old
Ma Bell who used to be everybody's phone company. The move by the
cable company into phones, oddly enough, is being helped along by
BellSouth, mostly in obedience to federal legislation. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN _ LUFKIN, Texas _ Before I made that dash
from the air-conditioned office to the air-conditioned car, I
checked my finances. I had 65 cents to my name. I could buy a cold
drink to sip on the way home, or be 65 cents ahead tomorrow. I
decided I needed the change more than the soda. As I pulled out of
the newspaper parking lot, cranked up the AC and headed to the
intersection, I saw her, looking like a frightened rabbit. (Ernest
Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News) MOVED
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Undermined by votes in the Knesset and betrayed
by a one-time coalition partner in filling the nation's figurehead
presidency, Prime Minister Ehud Barak has been left holding an
empty political bag. The question now is whether Barak, after a
series of political defections, can cobble together a functioning
coalition before the Knesset, on a three-month recess, reconvenes
in October and makes a final decision on its preliminary vote to
call early elections. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ ``Is America ready for a Jewish vice
president, only a heartbeat away from the presidency?'' The answer
needs to be a typical Jewish one, a return question: ``Why not?''
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service
in the Washington bureau.) MOVES THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN - THE BALLPARK IN ARLINGTON _ This is the house
that George W. Bush helped build. Politics aside, it's such an
improvement over its ugly predecessor as to not be in the same
ballpark, so to speak. Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel. MOVED Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   CLIMBING _ It's hard to explain. Those who know don't have to
say a thing. They know, and that's enough. But occasionally
somebody asks, or the meter hits full and the feelings from on top
have nowhere to go but out.
</P>
<P>
   So they touch their fingertips together to form a peak and
whisper, ``Fourteener,'' a mantra of endless meaning and
possibility. (Grand junction)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MIDWAY _ MIDWAY ATOLL _ It hardly seems possible that the
three tiny islands that comprise this atoll, lily pads floating
peacefully in the remote North Pacific, could harbor as much
history and hope as they do. But Midway looms large in American
military and natural history. And Cartersville entrepreneur Mark
Thompson, in a unique public-private partnership with the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service, is working to assure its future by operating
a low-impact eco-resort way out here in mid ocean, 1,200 miles west
of Honolulu. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE: WITH PHOTO gallery (facing half-pages on centerspread)
of Dave Tulis' awesome pictures.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIDWAYBIO _ At-a-glance bio box on Mark Thompson, Atlantan who
forged a one-of-a-kind agreement with U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service to operate a eco-resort on Midway Atoll. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDWAY-IFYOUGO _ Details on planning a trip to Midway Atoll.
(Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: The Midway package is the CoxNet Travel page centerpiece
for the current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JACKDANIEL _ Brief on the new 16,000-square-foot Visitor
Center at the Jack Daniel Distillery in Lynchburg, Tenn. The
facility houses more than 30 exhibits and displays about the
Tennessee whiskey and the life and times of Mr. Jasper Newton
``Jack'' Daniel, who would've celebrated his 150th birthday this
year. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet BACK TO SCHOOL page This layout is now
available.)
