<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   RECORDER _The trend of going from analog recording _ tape, vinyl
records, etc. _ to digital _ optical discs, computer chips, etc. _
continues with the introduction of the TeraOptix CD Video Recorder.
The unit looks and works a lot like a conventional video recorder,
but instead of recording on tape the TeraOptix machine records on
CD-R or CD-RW blank discs. The recordings are digital and can be
replayed on compatible DVD players, CD players and computers.
(Cummings, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week. This layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0812: ALL ABOUT EVA -- Back when romance novelist
Eva Rutland used a typewriter, she'd sometimes discover that it had
run out of paper. It wasn't that her concentration was so rapt _ or
that her story was so steamy. Eva Rutland is blind. She may not be
a household name like Barbara Cartland. But this 83-year-old
granddaughter of a former slave is one of the most prolific
romantic authors working today. (Brock, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4-column color photo photo of
author.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BIOGRAPHY BOX -- Personal information about author Eva
Rutland. Art includes a 6-pica color photo of a book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW PHAROAH-- Thirteen hundred years before Christ, the
Egyptian pharoah Akhenaten preached that there were not dozens of
gods, but only one, and his name was Aten, the god of the sun.
Akhenaten received the due that comes to nearly everyone ahead of
his time _ he was cast aside and almost certainly murdered..
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of a
book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW BEN -- Twelve years ago, Doris Lessing wrote a
grisly little horror tale called ``The Fifth Child,'' which
recounted the story of a monstrous child born into a middle-class
London family. When the sequel to that book, ``Ben, in the World,''
opens, Ben is 18 and on his own, roaming the streets of London. He
now looks like a yeti or caveman and still has fits of brutal
anger. Still, this Ben is more sinned against than sinning.
(Kakutani, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes a 6-pica color
photo of a book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW WARNER -- St. Louis Rams quarterback Kurt Warner's
new autobiography goes well past Hollywood-scripted tripe often
passed off as ``Field of Dreams'' material. This reads, and feels,
more real. (Kakutani, N.Y. Times News Service) Art includes a
6-pica color photo of a book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-JAZZ _ Review of Gene Santoro's biography ``Myself When I
Am Real: The Life and Music of Charles Mingus.'' (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-ROSENBAUM _ Review of Ron Rosenbaum's essays ``The Secret
Parts of Fortune: Three Decades of Intense Investigations and Edgy
Enthusiasms.'' (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   KENNY-ROGERS _ In the '70s and '80s, Kenny Rogers was one of
America's hottest recording artists. But by the '90s, he virtually
disappeared from music charts, written off by Nashville as a
has-been. But Rogers has had the last laugh. Last month, he earned
a platinum album and a No. 1 record with a comeback few artists
could imagine. And he did it without the support of a major label.
Kenny, who lives in Alpharetta, opens up his home to the AJC and
talks about his life and career. A profile. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FALLTV _ The fall season starts late this year (in October,
after the Summer Olympics) but the promotions are unavoidable for
Bette Midler's new sitcom and others. TV critic Phil Kloer gives a
quick overview of what's coming, what the trends are, and what's
good. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
