<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SECURITY _ The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's
information systems are ``riddled with security weaknesses'' that
has made it vulnerable to Internet hackers, says a new report from
the U.S. General Accounting Office. Most of the serious problems
were spotted by the agency's own inspector general three years ago.
(Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA-FLAG _ NCAA says it will not cancel or move any of the
announced NCAA sports events because of the SCLC's protest.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Also moving ins Sports (s) category
</P>
<P>
   CLONE _ Send in the clones. The only privately owned cloned
animal in the country (maybe the world) is celebrating its first
birthday. And owner/rancher/jester Ralph Fisher of La Grange is
hosting a birthday party with 300 guests on Sat. Aug. 12 for
``Second Chance,'' the clone of Fisher's favorite old dead Brahman
Bull, ``Chance.'' It's all so eerie. Second Chance acts and looks
just like Chance, even down to finding the one perfect little nap
spot on a 50-acre spread. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman) WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-POLICY _ Smokey Bear's done his job. Perhaps too well in
the tinder-dry West. The U.S. Forest Service mascot who cheers the
notion of preventing forest fires succeeded in instilling fear of
fire into generations of Americans. But he may also have cast a
stigma on a land management tool that maybe could have diminished
the fuels - overgrown brush and trees that have grown unchecked for
decades - that have fed this summer's burns. ``We have been in the
mode to suppress,'' said Martha Ketelle, supervisor of the White
River National Forest. ``We have seen a buildup of fuels on most
national forests as a result of the policy.'' (Grand Junction Daily
Sentinel)
</P>
<P>
   TIREDEATHS _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Ten people were killed in tire
blowout accidents in Palm Beach County in 1999 and 2000, and three
of the fatalities can be linked to Firestone tires, according to
the medical examiner's office. In two other accidents in which
three people were killed, the type of tire is unknown and could
have been Firestones. The number of people killed in tire blowout
crashes in the county is ``not that staggering,'' said forensics
supervisor Bill Pellan. What is unusual is that three of the 46
deaths linked to Firestone tires nationwide occurred here, he said.
(McGinness, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-DISEASE _ JERUSALEM _ The cliche is that diseases don't
know borders. As a result, medicine is one of the prime areas of
cooperation between Arabs and Jews. A Palm Beach, Fla. infectious
disease specialist Sandford Kuvin has been exploiting that fact to
try to stamp out a widespread, and often fatal, parasitic disease,
Leishmaniasis. At the Jerusalem-based Kuvin Centre for the Study of
Infectious and Tropical Diseases, several Arab students work under
Israeli professors in researching the disease throughout Israel and
the West Bank. The students are among the Palestinians first
home-grown class of doctors. The center, recognized by the United
Nations, has projects from Israel to Tunisia and has been able to
navigate around the region's politics. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: MOVED on the NYT wire in (I) International and (l)
Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ ``Unless we take action now, our
nation may confront a situation similar to the Great Depression _
and maybe even worse.'' The presidential candidate who made this
frightening prediction is lying low. His political party, however,
currently has a high profile. It is being torn apart from within.
It turns out that Ross Perot's leadership was not needed to save
America from another Great Depression. But Perot may be needed to
keep his Reform Party from crumbling to pieces. (Rowland Nethaway
is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ ATLANTA _ As a born and
bred Southsider I can't help but get a chuckle out of the Great
Pink Flamingo Controversy north of here. In case you haven't been
following major news events lately, here's the story. Doug and
Ellen Henry bought a home in what I take to be a subdivision.
Hoping to spruce up their front yard, which likely had been left
bare of trees by greedy developers, they paid $15 each for a pair
of pink flamingos. They described the colorful birds as ``lawn
decoration.'' Their neighbors, certainly not Southern-born, thought
the colorful birds were tacky eyesores. (Jim Minter is a former
editor of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Texas _ When Al Gore introduced his new
running mate Tuesday _ Joseph Lieberman, America's first Jewish
vice-presidential candidate _ the mood in Nashville was jubilant.
The theme of the party: ``Isn't it great that we live in America,
where such a thing can happen?'' Meanwhile, in the months and weeks
leading up to the election, as the two major parties moved
inexorably to the nomination of yet another daring combination of
Four White Guys, I've found myself asking a different question:
``This is America! Why can't we get some semblance of diversity on
the ticket?''(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Foreign policy issues rarely decide elections.
Although they can be a factor in whether a candidate ``appears
presidential,'' most voters look elsewhere in choosing whom to
support. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in the
Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
