<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-FILES _ Back to school means the end of campouts and lazy
mornings. It also signals the end of juvenile ennui as parents
breathe a collective sigh of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pavlov's dog, these students will salivate at the feel of
clean, crisp notebooks under their tanned palms and
chlorine-wrinkled fingers and become intoxicated by the aroma of
newly sharpened pencils. But back to school also signals back to
routines and pressures and late-night wails of ``Mom, I need four
empty juice cans in the morning and a diorama of the Alamo on
Tuesday.'' On this last free, albeit frantic, Saturday, let the
Greig Files entertain and inform you. (Greig, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN OUTDOOR PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Texas paper is producing a special section dedicated to life
outdoors in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Mike Leggett wrote the stories and took photographs
for the package.
</P>
<P>
   Stories also will move in the Sports category.
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-LEGGETT _ I miss bullfrogs and I wish they'd come back.
From where, I don't know. I just know they're gone and with them
one of the few nighttime activities in a country kid's life that
was both fun and legal. There was no limit. You could hunt at
night. Ammunition was free if you caught them by hand. What a
world. (Leggett, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-PUBLIC _ Texas has permits. Texas has draw hunts. And
Texas has open areas, all for public hunters who might not have
their own place leased every fall. One things the Parks and
Wildlife Commission has done in recent years is expand the public
hunting program, both through extra opportunity on state land and
through cooperative efforts with private landowners. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-PARKS _ Whether it's the sight of a jaguarundi at
Bentsen-Rio Grande Valley State Park or a faint ochre shaman
drawing on a cave wall at Seminole Canyon, Texas state parks offer
unique opportunities for visitors. You can camp, hike, fish and
even hunt in Texas parks. And even though some of the best ones are
well-known throughout the state, there are others that have their
own special charm and are just waiting to be discovered by the
masses. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-GEAR _ It would be interesting to be a billionaire for a
day, just to see how long I could shop for new stuff without
getting tired. I expect the World Bank might have to be called in
to assess the damage, though, because there's if there's anything
better than buying new gear for hunting season, it's buying new
gear and not having to worry about how much it costs or if there's
a warehouse that can hold it. (Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-POINT _ Shorty Powers is no shrinking violet. In fact,
you'd better WANT him to have your phone number, because if he
thinks you can help him get disabled individuals outdoors, he's
going to call. And call again. The Dallas resident, himself a
paraplegic in a wheelchair, was the founder of POINT, Paraplegics
On Independent Nature Trips. Through hard work and sheer force of
will, Powers has pushed the cause to the forefront in Texas. He's
been able to involve Texas parks and Wildlife and other
organizations in offering outdoor opportunities of every kind.
(Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TX-LICEN _ The first license I ever bought cost a quarter and I
didn't even need it unless I was going to hunt deer. Squirrels and
birds were free and the two deer tags _ bucks only _ were just a
vanity thing, since there aren't that many in the river bottoms
where we grew up. Times have changed since then. The license costs
more, of course, even though it's still fairly cheap. On the
license now there are five deer tags, four turkey tags, a redfish
tag, your federal Harvest Information Program data and a partridge
in a pear tree. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-DOVES _ Our shooting ability aside, dove season is always
good in Texas. The number of birds in any given field may vary, but
hunter success does very little, according to Jay Roberson, dove
program leader for Texas Parks and Wildlife. Texas hunters numbered
about 390,000 last year and spent an average of 1.3 days each in
the field. They killed about 11 birds per person, not bad in a
sport where the national average is about one dove per every five
shells. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-RECIPES _ I hate to hear anyone say that wild game,
especially doves, tastes gamy and they don't like it. Dove breasts,
grilled or fried, is one of God's chosen favorites. The only thing
you have to do is cook it. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-MEASURES _ Successful shotgun shooting is so simple. But
if that's the case, then why don't more people do it well? Because
they make some simple mistakes. According to one successful shooter
and teacher, there are three fairly easy problems to identify, even
if it's not always easy to do away with them. ``The very first
thing, the most common thing people do is they stop the gun when
the trigger is pulled,'' said Leon Measures. The Coldspring
resident has developed a basic shooting course called ``Shoot Where
You Look.'' He uses air rifles and repetition to teach better
shooting. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-WOMEN _ Hunting and fishing are wonderful ways to spend
time outdoors. The biggest problem, it seems, is getting started.
People who get the chance to go when they're young, tend to stick
with it. However, it's much harder to recruit adults into the
outdoor world. The folks at Texas Parks and Wildlife learned that
long ago and besides having programs directed at youngsters the
agency has set its sights on women with a program called ``Becoming
an Outdoors Woman.'' (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUTBIRDS _ Birding is an inexpensive, simple and exciting way
to increase your time outdoors. It can turn a park into an oasis or
mean four dull hours in a deer stand pass faster than they ever
have. There are no seasons other than the ones imposed by the birds
themselves. It works everywhere, from your backyard to wilderness
areas. And if you're a beginner, you probably are farther along
than you might think. ``When I first started, I was amazed at how
many birds I already knew,'' said John Szypula, executive director
of the Audubon Society in Austin. ``I knew blue jays and cardinals
and chickadees. And most people already know quite a bit about it.
Once they get started, their interest really perks up.'' (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-SEASON _ Throw in feral hogs and pigeons and Texas hunting
is a year-round sport. Still, most of us tend to think of seasons s
starting with dove season in late summer and ending with turkey
season in spring. For formal hunting periods, that's a long time,
slightly more than eight months altogether. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-YOUTH _ Tradition is the foundation upon which hunting is
built. Hunting leases, guns and even secret places to hunt have
been passed down from one generation to the next, providing a
continuity that's rare in any other sport. But the changing face of
America _ single-parent families, urbanization, time demands from
work and other leisure activities _ have cut into the tradition of
youngsters following parents and grandparents into the field.
(Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TXOUT-WHITE-WING _ White-winged doves are not the bird of peace.
Once thought to be a bird limited by weather and constitution to
the Lower Rio Grande Valley, the whitewing has exhibited a unique
ability to find suitable living conditions almost anywhere. They
may be pushing out other species as they move, too. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   END OF AUSTIN PACKAGE
</P>
<P>
   FISHING-DRUGFREE _ The crowd was awed as 7-year-old Travis Dwire
proudly displayed the carp on the fishing line. After gently
returning the carp to the water, Travis flashed a smile and
remembered the biggest fish he ever caught. ``It was a really heavy
16-inch bass and I reeled it in all by myself!'' Travis and his
sisters Casey and Lindsay were among 175 children and parents who
were kept occupied with earthworms, rods and bobbers at Hooked on
Fishing, Not Drugs 2000. For the second summer, the Ohio Division
of Wildlife and Five Rivers MetroParks teamed up to offer a free
nine-week program that educates youngsters about the dangers of
drugs while they are kept busy enjoying nature. (Dayton Daily
News). 18. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ ATLANTA _ There are very few things
in this line of work more rewarding than actually being able to
help somebody. I hand out advice in this space every week and
almost never know whether it did anyone any good. (Warner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DUNGEONS-DRAGONS _ Wizards of the Coast released on Thursday the
first new edition of Dungeons and Dragons in 10 years and
apparently it's flying off the shelves in Atlanta. A quick story to
explain the new release (and the game) and to explore that it's hot
and why. (Head, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 8.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-HARRYPOTTER _ Some say they teach the golden rule.
Others say they encourage faith in the occult. One Atlanta talk
show hosts says they overemphasize revenge. And other parents have
used then as an avenue to introduce their children to Christian
apologist C.S. Lewis's Narnia chronicles. We look at Harry Potter
and friends from the F&AMP;V perspective. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SAPP _ Warren Sapp went silent. Honest. Sapp was talking
away, answering question after question, talking about how he loves
Miami - ``the fans, the sun, the women ... greatest city in the
world'' - when a reporter managed to plug the Hoover Dam of NFL
mouths with a mere two syllables. Todd Wade. (Palm Post Beach
Post). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-HERSCHEL _ SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Report on Herschel Walker's
enshrinement ceremony at the College Football Hall of Fame in South
Bend, Ind. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BOXING
</P>
<P>
   BOX-HOLYFIELD-ADVANCE _ As he approaches his 38th birthday,
Evander Holyfield is constantly faced with this question - how much
longer does he intend to fight? Holyfield wants to become the
undisputed heavyweight champion for the fourth time and he takes
the next step toward that goal Saturday as he faces John Ruiz for
the vacant WBC title. If he defeats Ruiz as expected, he could put
himself in position for another shot at the undisputed title. But
that fight might not occur until next year when he's approaching
39. (Tierney, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO RACING
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-POLE _ WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Report on the run for the
pole at Watkins Glen. ( Levine, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
