</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTUMN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUTUMN IN NEW YORK': MAY-DECEMBER ROMANCE, OR SIMPLY HOT AND
COLD? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it were 1940, ``Autumn in New York,'' a flagrantly
old-fashioned, triple-hankie tear-jerker that might have starred
Bette Davis and Cary Grant, would probably be lauded as a serious,
high-minded romance, the quintessence of ennobling adult
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But time has played nasty tricks on a genre that aims straight
for the tear ducts. Nowadays when audiences sense that a movie as
shameless as ``Autumn in New York'' intends to ennoble them with
tears and redemption, only the most die-hard sentimentalists will
fail to smell a rat.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably one reason ``Autumn in New York'' opened Friday
without advance press screenings and despite the public expression
of disappointment by its two stars, Richard Gere and Winona Ryder,
over the studio's marketing decision.
</P>
<P>
   Gere plays Will Keane, a superstar New York chef and legendary
womanizer. Ryder is Charlotte Fielding, the ailing, doe-eyed young
designer of kooky hats who reforms him. Shortly after their affair
begins, Charlotte informs Will that she is suffering from an
extremely rare and probably terminal heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about medical anomalies! In the classic triple-hankie
tradition, Charlotte is the picture of sparkling vitality and fun
until she has sudden fainting spells (always at crucial dramatic
moments and at picturesque locations like the ice rink at
Rockefeller Center).
</P>
<P>
   She also has an improbably stiff upper lip. Although there's a
small chance her life could be saved through a risky operation (she
has less than a year to live), she refuses to have it, because she
doesn't want to entertain false hope.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made of the fact that Will is more than twice
Charlotte's age. He's (gasp!) 48 to her 22, something that is
repeatedly pounded home by Will's bartender John (Anthony
LaPaglia). One of the movie's two official scolds, John warns Will
that if he goes on like this, he might end up, God forbid, dying in
his own arms.
</P>
<P>
   John's dire warnings are raspingly seconded by Charlotte's
crusty old grandmother and official guardian, Dolly (Elaine
Stritch). Both of Charlotte's parents died in a mysterious accident
many years earlier. Way, way back in the 1960s, we learn, Will
actually dated Charlotte's mother. But such is the movie's prim
sense of propriety that the screenplay goes out of its way to let
us know that Will never actually had sex with the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Will was supposedly a true child of the '60s whose favorite
singer was (you'll never guess!) Stephen Stills. When the name is
dropped, Charlotte draws a blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn in New York'' once and for all certifies Gere as a
romantic ``older man'' in the mode of the 1950s and '60s Cary
Grant. In fact, the two have much in common. Both exude an
unflappable suavity under which percolates a hidden, enigmatic
sexuality. But unlike Grant's typical romantic heroes, who were
vaguely upper-class and vaguely British, Gere's Will has the
slightly roguish air of the self-made newly rich man up from the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   With her high-strung energy and saucer-eyed precocity, Ryder's
Charlotte is upper-middle-class all the way. The chemistry between
these two is less than scintillating. But in their best moments
together, Gere sheds his wariness to express a sad world-weary
tenderness, while Ryder's slightly shrill, pouty bravado melts, and
her frightened doe eyes appear caught in metaphysical headlights.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie, directed by Joan Chen, exhibits a loving eye for
New York exteriors, it's undone by its own rigidly old-fashioned
conventions. Allison Burnett's screenplay does a creditable job of
filling out the characters (Charlotte's a blunt truth-teller and
Will a sneaky and evasive liar), and depicting their love affair,
which Will blithely sabotages more than once.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's tentative psychological realism clashes lethally
with its soft-focused medical vagueness and refusal to confront the
physical realities of illness. Today we know too much about the
body to accept the notion embraced by ``Autumn in New York'' that
dying makes you more beautiful by giving you a heavenly glow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Autumn in New York'' is rated PG-13 (parents strongly
cautioned). It has sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AUTUMN IN NEW YORK'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Joan Chen; written by Allison Burnett; director of
photography, Changwei Gu; edited by Ruby Yang; music by Gabriel
Yared; production designer, Mark Friedberg; produced by Amy
Robinson, Gary Lucchesi and Tom Rosenberg; released by
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures. Running time: 105 minutes. This film
is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   With: Richard Gere (Will), Winona Ryder (Charlotte), Anthony
LaPaglia (John), Elaine Stritch (Dolly), Vera Farmiga (Lisa) and
Sherry Stringfield (Sarah).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
