<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9138 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FIRE-POLICY0812-COX     08-11 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE-POLICY0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Multiple factors contribute to record fire season
 &HT;    By Marija B. Vader
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIFLE, Colo. _ Smokey Bear's done his job.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps too well in the tinder-dry West.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service mascot who cheers the notion of
preventing forest fires has instilled fear of fire into generations
of Americans. But he may also have cast a stigma on a land
management tool that maybe could have diminished the fuels _
overgrown brush and trees that have grown unchecked for decades _
that have fed this summer's burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in the mode to suppress,'' said Martha Ketelle,
supervisor of the White River National Forest. ``We have seen a
buildup of fuels on most national forests as a result of the
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Add drought, dry lightning and people moving to the forests, and
the result is an unprecedented fire season in the American West. So
far, more than 64,000 individual fires have torched 4.3 million
acres.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fires have caused heartache for many Americans,
overshadowing the good fires, especially those deliberately set by
land managers, can bring to the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never our intent to suppress all fires,'' said Dan
Hormaechea, a planner with the White River National Forest. ``That
became convoluted at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer's fires have led some to question fire management
policies of federal agencies such as the U.S. Forest Service and
Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on conditions, officials spark what they call
``prescribed burns,'' or controlled fires, to eliminate overgrowth
of trees and brush and to replenish animal habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Before a controlled burn can be set, officials have to work
through a bureaucratic maze of public hearings and environmental
studies. Once that's done, they have to wait for the perfect
conditions _ the right relative humidity, fuel moisture content and
winds _ before they can light the match.
</P>
<P>
   The process can easily become bogged down, sometimes taking
years to resolve, said Faye Christiansen of the Eastern Idaho
Interagency Fire Management Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part is, by the time you get through the environmental
assessment and the different hoops, you've got another year or two
of fuel buildup,'' said Christiansen. ``It just takes a long time
to get things processed.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects of such delays can be seen in the vicinity of Vail,
where mountain pine bark beetle, mistletoe and disease have killed
thousands of trees. They are ripe for lightning-struck fires, but
environmentalists and others block their removal by opposing
logging and controlled burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people claim that's part of nature _ the cycle Mother
Nature takes,'' Hormaechea said. ``That's all well and fine, I
guess.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the process, fuels mount.
</P>
<P>
   Cheatgrass, an insidious culprit in fast-spreading wildfires,
covers the West. Other fuels, like pinon juniper, pine and aspen
trees, continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on conditions, when wildfires move through an area,
they're likely to travel faster through tall brush and trees,
hopping from treetop to treetop with the winds.
</P>
<P>
   And the farther the fire is from the ground, the more difficult
it is to control and contain, said Robert Storch, supervisor of the
Grand Mesa, Uncompahgre and Gunnison national forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the tree canopy touching one another, it's easy
for the fire to run along the tops of the trees,'' Storch said. ``A
broken pattern will break the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a critical situation right now,'' he said. ``For
western Colorado, this is the worst I've seen it in nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   Controlled burns earn a bad reputation when firefighters lose
control, such as what happened in May at Los Alamos, N.M.,
Hormaechea said.
</P>
<P>
   At Los Alamos, U.S. Park Service officials at Bandelier National
Monument started a fire to clear brush, but 50-mph winds quickly
blew it out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The fire forced 25,000 people to flee, burned 47,560 acres and
left more than 200 families homeless.
</P>
<P>
   One month later, the fire was extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have an event like Los Alamos, people always question
fire management,'' Hormaechea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't see the red flags, they didn't heed the
warnings,'' Hormaechea said of park service officials. ``You always
have to err on the safe side.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 2.3-million-acre White River National Forest, fire
management plans for specific areas are incorporated into the new
forest plan set to be adopted in six months, Hormaechea said.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas may include controlled burns, some do not, he added,
but protecting life and property is ``always a given.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we have a prescription that says otherwise, we put them
out,'' Storch said of the GMUG forests.
</P>
<P>
   The forest service is now taking inventory of fuels and
vegetation in the GMUG. With that, the prescription rule will be
incorporated into the new GMUG forest plan now under development,
Storch said.
</P>
<P>
   Storch and his staff analyze aerial photos to determine current
vegetation compared with trees and shrubs of the late 1930s and
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding vegetation conditions have changed dramatically,
especially with our shrub types,'' Storch said. ``The canopy cover
has increased tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire suppression has become a science, Hormaechea said, far more
sophisticated than when Indians roamed the plains.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been dramatic. Between 1919 and 1929, an
average of 29 million acres burned each year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the average has been 3.6 million acres per
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the longer history, fire played a much larger role than it
does now,'' Hormaechea said.
</P>
<P>
   Christiansen agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fire used to do its own thing,'' she said. ``Massive forests
could burn, but there was no population there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few thousand people, but not millions,'' Christiansen
said.
</P>
<P>
   People want to suppress fires now because the forest has become
much more populated than in the early 1900s, Christiansen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the vegetation right up close to their home so
people can't see in,'' Christiansen said. ``People want to get away
from the city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably partially our Smokey Bear's fault that people
have a real fear of many kinds of fire,'' Hormaechea said. ``But
that may not be legitimate.''
</P>
<P>
   When done properly at the right time of year, controlled burns
are effective, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A summer like this, there needs to be a fear of fire,''
Hormaechea said. ``It's so dry, whether it's human or
lightning-caused, you've got to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncontrollable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
