<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FRANCE CONCORDES TO REMAIN GROUNDED 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's transportation minister reiterated Friday that
Air France's five remaining Concordes would stay grounded for the
time being because of continuing uncertainty about why the
supersonic jet caught fire last month and crashed north of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Jean-Claude Gayssot, issued a statement after
meeting with investigators looking into the cause of the crash and
said they had informed him that at this point in the inquiry they
believe that `'the initial cause of the accident is the destruction
of the internal forward tire of the main left wheel carriage.'' The
tire's destruction, he said, produced ``catastrophic consequences
in a very brief period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister's statement came one day after investigators from
the Bureau of Accident Investigations confirmed that a 16-inch
strip of metal found on the runway after the crash had punctured
one of the jet's tires, turning chunks of rubber into fast-flying
projectiles that caused a major fuel leak and fire to occur before
the plane even left the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the beginning, French investigators have been
working on the broad assumption that at least one tire burst,
triggering a chain of events that included damage to the plane's
structure, a fire and engine failure that led to the plane's crash
on July 25 shortly after takeoff, and the deaths of 113 people.
</P>
<P>
   But Gayssot said Friday that investigators still did not know
the sequence of those events, how they might have been connected or
how they might ultimately have caused the fire.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways has continued flying its seven Concordes, and
Gayssot said he would begin talking to British aviation authorities
about joint measures to be taken in light of the investigation's
preliminary results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1823EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
