<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9142 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV13-     08-11 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOING GRASS ONE BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13.)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you a poor fool who mows the lawn on a hill so steep you
have to pull the mower back up on a rope? And then your back goes
out and you have to be hauled off on a stretcher?
</P>
<P>
   That hill needs a ground cover.
</P>
<P>
   The same applies if you are bashing into your trees with that
mower. Stop, unless you want to kill them. Plant a ground cover
from the tree's trunk clear to its drip line. Or even farther, if
you would like a sustainable, low-maintenance landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you a lot of horticultural heresy,'' Jim
Glover said, brandishing a pot of golden creeping Jenny (Lysimachia
nummularia Aurea), a sun lover that can form a carpet of little
round, golden leaves in areas too wet for a lawn. ``Rip up your
lawns! Forget about flowers! You can get as big a bang for your
buck with foliage _ for nine months of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   I've been happily brainwashed by Glover and his brother, Rob,
who started Glover Perennial Growers three years ago out in
Mattituck, N.Y., where you can still sniff the salt breezes over
the potato fields. Rob runs the business end of things, and Jim
heads the propagation in 32 greenhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Their 3-year-old wholesale business is thriving because a
plant-hungry public wants new perennials and alternatives to grass.
Not only is grass often unsuited to wet or shady areas, but it
needs to be doused with chemicals to stay lush and green, unlike
many ground covers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '80s, you had to push new stuff,'' Jim Glover said.
``Now, people say: `New? Oh, give me new!'''
</P>
<P>
   Some are new cultivars of old favorites like Ajuga, or
bugleweed, which is usually associated with spoon-shaped purplish
leaves and little blue flowers that bloom from May through June.
But now, even the classic types of Ajuga have interesting
variations: Gaiety's purple leaves are highly glossed and crinkled;
Jungle Beauty has highly textured, mahogany-purple leaves, and its
blue flowers are 10 inches tall; Chocolate Chip has cute, smaller
leaves that form a dense cover; and there's a real oddball named
Mini Crispa Red, which has crispy wrinkled bronze leaves that curl
inward to form little buns. It's not a spreader, like some Ajugas,
and rock gardeners can't get enough of this weirdo.
</P>
<P>
   Glover also grows unusual perennials like golden box-leaf
honeysuckle (Lonicera nitida Baggesen's Gold), a shrubby spreading
evergreen that grows to 3 feet, with tiny, brilliant yellow,
fern-shaped leaves. Its foliage turns red in winter, but it doesn't
like full sun, so Glover suggests using it to highlight a bed of
purple-leaf Ajuga.
</P>
<P>
   The Glovers' greenhouses look like quilts of many colors and
textures: burgundy, chartreuse, blue green, grass green, tawny and
gold; soft mats of tiny rounded leaves, leathery, crinkled ones,
billowy grasses that wave in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads me to the versatile Carex family, with roughly 2,000
species of sedge. Somewhere in that range is a plant that can
tolerate almost any condition. Ice Dance, for instance, which has
leathery 12-inch green leaves with creamy white margins, loves the
sun and forms such a dense cover you'll never see a weed. The
Beatles is a green mop top that loves wet conditions. So does
Bowles Golden, a large clump-forming sedge that grows 18 to 30
inches tall; its glowing yellow foliage lights up dark spaces, and
it's perfect for the mucky edge of a pond. Carex flacca, an
intensely blue sedge that grows 6 to 12 inches tall, tolerates salt
and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Glover also recommends an unusual Japanese forest grass
(Hakoneckloa macra Aureola) with bamboo-like weeping foliage. The
leaves are yellow with a green stripe and turn intense pink-red in
the fall, lighting up the area beneath a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Some ground covers are being rediscovered, like lily of the
valley and Kenilworth ivy (Cymbalaria muralis), a Victorian creeper
with tiny lavender viola-like flowers that loves to grow on shady
stone walls.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a sucker for creepers that grow in and around stepping
stones and in the cracks of old brick terraces, and Glover is
experimenting with a number of marginally hardy types like Cotula
squalida Platts Black, or New Zealand Brass Buttons, which has soft
deeply dissected black leaves with a touch of green. It has little
yellow buttonlike flowers in summer and tolerates light foot
traffic. If you live in Zone 7 (zero degrees) or higher, try it
among your stepping stones.
</P>
<P>
   Mazus reptans is another good one for the walkway, especially if
the soil is moist. It forms a 2-inch carpet of bright green with
little blue or white flowers, and it's tough enough to thrive under
the weight of Morgan, the Glovers' hefty Labrador, who likes to nap
on its cool cushion. Another stepping-stone cover that takes light
foot traffic is dwarf shamrock, Oxalis magellanica Nelson, which
has little white double flowers.
</P>
<P>
   West Coast strawberries are taking hold on the East Coast,
because they thrive in sandy soil and form a dense cover that
prevents erosion. The red stems are beautiful, but the berries are
kind of dry, so if you want to graze on your ground cover, grow an
old favorite like Fort Laramie, Ozark Beauty or Quinault.
</P>
<P>
   There's also an evergreen creeping raspberry called Rubus
calycinoides, with tough leaves that turn red in the fall and
winter. It bears orange raspberries, full size and sweet, in
midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Since Glover Perennials is a wholesaler, you can't drive up its
sandy lane to buy plants, but they are sold in fine garden centers
in New York and Connecticut. Many other growers are propagating
these same varieties, so ask for them at your local nursery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-OFFICIAL-REPLACE     08-11 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-OFFICIAL-REPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE ON TO REPLACE U.N. REFUGEES COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The highest-ranking U.N. official responsible
for refugees plans to retire at the end of the year, and a race is
on to find a replacement within the next month or two.
</P>
<P>
   Several candidates seem willing to take on the job, even though
it is being redefined by an era of civil wars whose combatants have
often turned their guns on aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 30 million people driven from their homes and
needing help in Europe, Africa and Asia, the job of the U.N. high
commissioner for refugees has become one of the world's most
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a decade _ through conflicts from Bosnia to Congo to
East Timor _ the position has been held by Sadako Ogata of Japan,
who studied at Georgetown and Berkeley and was dean of foreign
studies at Sophia University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   During her tenure, Ogata said in a recent interview, she has
been forced to be fund-raiser, logistics expert, security provider
and administrator of a large bureaucracy, all the while trying to
pursue and protect her primary role of refugee advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Geneva, she has perennially been on the move from
crisis to crisis. Often she has had to defend her agency against
critics who say that it moves too slowly, as in the Kosovo crisis,
or that it fails to stop combatants from supplying themselves in
refugee camps, as in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan will choose Ogata's replacement
after he consults with various governments. The General Assembly
will then consider his choice. U.N. officials and diplomats say
Annan hoped to have a candidate by early October but was still
seeking nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no formal, public list of candidates,
diplomats say that nearly half a dozen people are considered
serious contenders. American diplomats say they have not decided
which candidate to support.
</P>
<P>
   An early nominee was Crown Prince Hassan of Jordan, brother of
the late King Hussein and a close informal adviser to Ogata.
</P>
<P>
   Two possible candidates from within the U.N. system are Sergio
Vieira de Mello, the organization's coordinator of humanitarian
affairs and now administrator of East Timor, and Bernard Kouchner,
the U.N. administrator of Kosovo and founder of Doctors Without
Borders.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans see Foreign Minister Knut Vollebaek of Norway as a
strong nominee. In the last year, Vollebaek has played a role in
monitoring the conflict in Chechnya on behalf of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe. He has also tried to broker
peace talks between the government of Sri Lanka and Tamil rebels
waging war in the country's northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Axworthy, who is expected to step down soon as Canada's
foreign minister, is a possible dark-horse candidate. Axworthy has
given relief issues a high priority in Canadian foreign policy and
was very active in international campaigns to ban land mines and
establish an international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate, Maahti Atisaari, a former president of
Finland, was a leading contender until he withdrew from the race
early this summer. Atisaari has told officials that he prefers to
remain in Finland and serve the United Nations on shorter special
assignments from there. But some diplomats say he might be
persuaded to reconsider.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
