</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9147 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DNC-ONLINE-LADN &LR;      08-11 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-ONLINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET ACCESS RIGHT UP CONVENTION'S ALLEY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This story is being transmitted to both lifestyle and
entertainment wires.) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an era that celebrates technology, political conventions have
proven no more immune than any other part of society in being
impacted by the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It's just taken a little longer for the impacts to be noticed,
because the 2000 Republican and Democratic conventions are the
first to be conducted at a time when more than half of all American
households have Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Democratic convention, for instance, only drew a
handful of Web sites, most of them add-ons to established Old Media
operations such as The New York Times and ABC News, said Luis
Vizcaino, spokesman for the Democratic National Convention
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They usually involved one or two reporters in the back of each
room with a laptop,'' Vizcaino said.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 2000 Democratic National Convention will be a
state-of-the-art convention suitable for the 21st century,'' said
Vizcaino. Every Democratic delegate will have his or her own Web
page, scheduling and messaging services, to keep track of events
and gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of Internet sites set up shop last week in the GOP
convention's ``Internet Alley'' portion of one of four media tents
in Philadelphia. And in the Democratic Convention's Internet Alley,
about 150 organizations are expected to set up booths, Vizcaino
said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-month-old Staples Center _ already something of a
technological marvel with its two TV production studios, 12,000
built-in phone lines, fiber-optics and other infrastructure _ has
been beefed up even further since Democratic Convention organizers
took over the facility June 9, said Staples Center director of
communications Michael Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more phone lines, 300 miles of TV cable, rooms for the
wireless transmission connections for roving reporters and special
air- conditioning units to cool TV equipment have all been added,
while more than 4,000 seats are being removed and more than 40
luxury skybox suites radically renovated to accommodate each
network's broadcasting needs, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest of Internet sites in Philadelphia were still
the Web operations for TV and cable operations such as MSNBC and
ABC News, even though both had significant separate areas elsewhere
in the media tents for their broadcast headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted to send a message to the new guys,'' joked
Mike Cornfield, a George Washington University professor of
political management and director of the Democracy Online Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struck by the amount of original content on these sites,''
said Phil Agre, associate professor of information studies at the
University of California, Los Angeles, and operator of a major
politically-minded mailing list called the Red Rock Eater News
Service. ``You (usually) need an audience to (be able to afford to)
produce original content. Maybe they're not getting paid.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornfield gave the partnership of ABCNews.com, the Washington
Post and Congressional Quarterly high marks for their combined Net
coverage of the GOP proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean they had much to cover in a GOP convention so
tightly scripted that the schedule literally put aside two minutes
for a ``spontaneous demonstration'' of crowd support.
</P>
<P>
   The news-free situation was worsened for the dot-com crowd by a
Bush campaign decision to do virtually nothing that catered to the
Internet's particular needs, Cornfield said.
</P>
<P>
   During the GOP convention, a number of sites tried techie tricks
and gimmicks to attract attention, such as Insight.com, which
outfitted its reporters in Borg-like fashion, with a headset that
included a tiny eyepiece to view video, video camera, a
wrist-mounted keyboard and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Bush Campaign decision not to do much with the Net
during the convention has disappointed them at the least and may
have hurt them,'' Cornfield said. ``I'm sure they're all hoping
Gore decides to be more aggressive at the Staples Center.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because big events such as the conventions are an
opportunity for a new medium to make a splash, if everyone
cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk for a candidate with online is you never know what
will happen to your message. You can't control it,'' Cornfield
said.
</P>
<P>
   Already under way, according to Agre, is an ``underground war of
e-mails,'' as partisans on both sides duke it out on
opposition-research sites such as www.bushcheney.net, the
Democrats' quickly launched spotlight on the voting records of the
GOP nominees, and www.goreline.come, the Republicans' equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   But where those sites make it clear who's behind them, Cornfield
said, other, more vicious, and perhaps less accurate, sites won't
be this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Just as so-called independent expenditure groups are expected to
finance a series of single-issue attack ads in various battleground
states independent of the two campaigns, so too can attack Web
sites be expected to crop up with innocuous-sounding groups paying
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this intensified underground warfare going on,'' said
Agre. ``The grassroots groups such as Free Republic (a Fresno-based
conservative site at www.freerepublic.com) have already played a
huge role in these semi-, pseudo-, quasi-scandal stories that have
been kept alive. They create a sort of echo chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is not only trailing in the polls but has long
proclaimed his efforts to help fund the Internet in its early
years, is probably more likely to go Net in a big way at his
convention and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's apparently behind, so he has to take some risks,''
Cornfield said.
</P>
<P>
   There will not only be an Internet Alley at the Los Angeles
convention, but a ``Democracy Row'' of booths will be set up in the
convention center's West Hall, located maybe 100 yards from the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cornfield also credited the so-called Shadow Convention with
doing a good job using the Internet to get people involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Shadow Convention, which will start at 6 p.m. today at
Patriotic Hall several blocks south of the Staples Center, is
focused on three issues, said organizer and columnist Arianna
Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty in a time of prosperity,'' the failings of the drug
war, and the corrosive effect of money on the political process,
Huffington said.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidential contender John McCain gave a rousing speech
at the Philadelphia convention on money in politics; Russ Feingold
of Wisconsin, will speak in the Los Angeles version, Huffington
said. Other speakers include rapper Chuck D, U.S. Sen. Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota and ``Politically Incorrect'' host Bill
Maher.
</P>
<P>
   Their speeches and other work can be seen at
www.shadowconventions.com, Huffington said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
