</P>
<P>
   Just as so-called independent expenditure groups are expected to
finance a series of single-issue attack ads in various battleground
states independent of the two campaigns, so too can attack Web
sites be expected to crop up with innocuous-sounding groups paying
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this intensified underground warfare going on,'' said
Agre. ``The grassroots groups such as Free Republic (a Fresno-based
conservative site at www.freerepublic.com) have already played a
huge role in these semi-, pseudo-, quasi-scandal stories that have
been kept alive. They create a sort of echo chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is not only trailing in the polls but has long
proclaimed his efforts to help fund the Internet in its early
years, is probably more likely to go Net in a big way at his
convention and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's apparently behind, so he has to take some risks,''
Cornfield said.
</P>
<P>
   There will not only be an Internet Alley at the Los Angeles
convention, but a ``Democracy Row'' of booths will be set up in the
convention center's West Hall, located maybe 100 yards from the
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cornfield also credited the so-called Shadow Convention with
doing a good job using the Internet to get people involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Shadow Convention, which will start at 6 p.m. today at
Patriotic Hall several blocks south of the Staples Center, is
focused on three issues, said organizer and columnist Arianna
Huffington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty in a time of prosperity,'' the failings of the drug
war, and the corrosive effect of money on the political process,
Huffington said.
</P>
<P>
   Former presidential contender John McCain gave a rousing speech
at the Philadelphia convention on money in politics; Russ Feingold
of Wisconsin, will speak in the Los Angeles version, Huffington
said. Other speakers include rapper Chuck D, U.S. Sen. Paul
Wellstone of Minnesota and ``Politically Incorrect'' host Bill
Maher.
</P>
<P>
   Their speeches and other work can be seen at
www.shadowconventions.com, Huffington said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
