A9152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TXOUT-PARKS0812-COX     08-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-PARKS0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park it at any of these great places
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Whether it's the sight of a jaguarundi at
Bentsen-Rio Grande Valley State Park or a faint ochre shaman
drawing on a cave wall at Seminole Canyon, Texas state parks offer
unique opportunities for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   You can camp, hike, fish and even hunt in Texas parks. And even
though some of the best ones are well-known throughout the state,
there are others that have their own special charm and are just
waiting to be discovered by the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Personal prejudice about the best places to visit for fall park
activities is allowed, and so the American-Statesman turned to
Brent Leisure of the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department Public
Lands Division for his top 10 list of favorites. They include:
</P>
<P>
   Daingerfield State Park: This East Texas park has 551 acres that
feature a lake, fall colors in the oak, sweetgum and maples and the
chance to get away from it all when the weather is at its best in
Texas. Locals know it, but it's often overlooked by travelers. Call
(903) 645-2921 for information.
</P>
<P>
   Caddo Lake State Park: Located near Karnack and obviously on the
lake, this is another fall treasure. It offers huge cypress trees,
hunting and fishing and history in nearby Jefferson and Marshall.
``Both those parks have camping and cabins,'' Leisure said. ``They
don't get the attention that some others do.'' Call (903) 679-3351.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Maples State Natural Area: Vanderpool in the Hill Country.
As the name implies, this is one park that foliage freaks pay
attention to when the weather begins to cool down. Big-tooth maples
put on a show every fall, and visitors come from all over to see
them. There is camping, but it can get crowded. Fishing is
available as well as hiking through the park. Call (830) 966-3413.
</P>
<P>
   Palo Duro Canyon State Park: This gem is located near Canyon in
the Texas Panhandle and offers a close-up view of the famous
canyon. The park is composed of more than 16,000 acres and is open
for camping, hiking, bicycling and horseback riding. ``It's a very
pretty park with a lot more fall color than people realize,''
Leisure said. ``That canyon is such a neat place.'' Call (806)
488-2227.
</P>
<P>
   Bastrop State Park: This one is nearby and fall is the perfect
time to visit, Leisure said. ``The weather is great, plus you have
some fall foliage and the pines. It really has a little bit of
everything. You can camp, play golf and we've just added 1,000
acres of undeveloped land,'' he said. Fishing and hiking are
available. Call (512) 321-2101.
</P>
<P>
   Pedernales Falls State Park: ``You have to include that one,''
Leisure said. The park encompasses more than 5,000 acres and is
great for fall camping and hiking activities. Call (830) 868-7304.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Mountains State Park: ``That's always in my top five,''
Leisure said. ``You get a lot of color in the fall, plus it's a
good place to go to see lots of birds.'' You can camp or stay at
Indian Lodge, plus enjoy the history of the local area, including
Fort Davis. The McDonald observatory is nearby for nighttime
activities. Call (915) 426-3337.
</P>
<P>
   Palmetto State Park: If you drive through Luling from time to
time, you might have seen this small park on the outskirts of town.
Most people drive right on by, though, which is bad for them, but
good for a visitor looking for a hidden gem. ``That's a neat little
park that definitely has unique characteristics, ecologically and
culturally,'' Leisure said. ``And it's really underutilized.'' Call
(830) 672-3266.
</P>
<P>
   Enchanted Rock State Natural Area: Any regular park goer has
likely stopped and climbed to the top of the granite monolith from
which the park derives its name. If you haven't, then you've missed
something. ``It's great at any time of the year, but it's really
nice in the fall,'' Leisure said. ``The weather is nice, and there
is some nice color there.'' There are hiking trails around the
park, as well. The park is located between Fredericksburg and
Llano. Call (915) 247-3903.
</P>
<P>
   Cleburne State Park: Leisure thinks this is an underutilized
park, as well, despite its proximity to the Dallas-Fort Worth
Metroplex. ``It's a neat park with a lot to offer,'' he said.
Fishing, hiking and bicycling are among the top attractions. Call
(817) 645-4215.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations are required for camping in state parks. Call (512)
389-8900.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
