<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      08-11 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Aug. 12 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   EGYPTAIR-CRASH (Washington) _ The National Transportation Safety
Board Friday strongly indicated that Egyptair 990 crashed last Oct.
31 because of a deliberate act by the relief co-pilot, releasing
nearly 1,700 pages of documents, as the chairman of the board
declared that there were ``no unresolved safety issues'' that would
require a hearing. But American experts representing Egyptair,
including a former chairman of the Safety Board, said that the
documents contained extensive evidence that argued against the
crash as being a deliberate act. The plane went down about 60 miles
from Nantucket on a flight from Kennedy airport to Cairo, killing
all 217 people aboard. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-STAMPS-STATES (Undated) _ In California, New York, and 27
other states, people applying for food stamps are asked if they own
a burial plot. Nebraska and Nevada want to know if applicants have
sold their blood, and for how much. Hawaii demands garage sale
receipts, South Dakota wants documentation of past bingo winnings,
and Minnesota, on page 20 of a 36-page eligibility application,
asks if anyone in the household gets money from a paper route. Food
stamp applications in most states have become so onerous that they
are deterring needy people from applying for the subsidies, the
most comprehensive analysis of the applications has found. Many of
the inquiries about income and assets have no connection to legal
requirements for food stamps but are either aggressive responses to
federal mandates to deter fraud or part of recent state and local
efforts to cut welfare costs by eliminating recipients. Federal
officials say that the report, sponsored by America's Second
Harvest, the nation's largest food bank network, adds to worries
that such stringency is one reason that millions of people who are
eligible for the benefits, and need them, are not getting them. By
Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ASSESS (Washington) _ The five-party system of
Democrats, Republicans, Greens and two Reform parties is something
new in American politics and right now it's helping Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas in important ways. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (Editors, this story originally budgeted as
REFORM-PARTY-ASSESS.)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-DIAMONDS (Yellowknife, Northwest Territories) _ By 2005,
the Northwest Territories is expected to produce as much as 15
percent of the world's diamonds and Canada will then join the ranks
of the world's top five diamond producers. With this future on the
horizon, officials are taking the lead now to protect the future
image of diamonds by suppressing the trafficking in uncut stones
that helps to fund guerrilla armies in Sierra Leone and Angola. By
James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   WEST-FIRES (Undated) _ With the worst wildfires in a generation
still burning out of control across a dozen Western states, a
fierce debate, tinged with politics, is also under way over who is
to blame. Fire experts had warned for years that a buildup of
combustible material in Western forests had reached vast and
dangerous proportions. But federal agencies did not address the
problem in earnest until 1995, and even since, conservative critics
including the Republican governor of Montana said angrily Friday,
the administration did not move with appropriate dispatch. By
Douglas Jehl.
</P>
</TEXT>
