<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SAFRICA-WACKENHUT-NYT     08-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-WACKENHUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. FIRM WINS $245-MILLION CONTRACT TO BUILD AND RUN PRISON IN
SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA, South Africa _ Wackenhut Corrections Corp., a world
leader in private prison construction and management and a frequent
target of industry critics, contracted on Friday to build and
operate a 3,024-bed maximum-security penitentiary in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The prison, expected to be ready in about 18 months, is the
first such venture in Africa for the company, which is based in
Florida and operates correctional facilities across the United
States as well as in Britain, Australia, New Zealand and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-contract, which is valued by the South African
government at about $245 million including the $45-million expense
of the prison construction, was signed on Friday morning during a
90-minute ceremony here in the capital. The cost of construction is
to be financed by a consortium of South African banks.
</P>
<P>
   With South Africa's jails and prisons desperately overcrowded
and the government struggling to find the money to build new ones,
Wackenhut hopes the new prison, to be located in the northern town
of Louis Trichardt, is only the beginning of a long and lucrative
relationship with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of South Africa share that hope, and for them, more
is at stake than simply the success of a single prison. Beset not
only by high crime rates, but also by other social ills that
require substantial funding and attention, the government is
grappling with how to pay for more houses, schools, hospitals and
prisons. Wackenhut, which saves governments money by running
prisons more efficiently than they can, is seen in South Africa as
a promising solution.
</P>
<P>
   So three years ago, the South African government began an
experiment in privatization, soliciting bids to build and manage
four prisons here. Wackenhut and its local partners, incorporated
as South African Custodial Services, bid for the right to build
three prisons and won contracts for two, including the planned
prison at Louis Trichardt.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Wackenhut to operate at least one of them, South
Africa is turning to a company that made itself a common name in
the private prison-industry and not always for good reason. Over
the years, and even in recent months, the company has been
criticized for how some of its facilities in the United States have
been run.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Texas reclaimed control of a Wackenhut-run prison
in Austin after a dozen former employees were indicted late last
year on charges of sexually assaulting and harassing inmates. And
earlier this year, authorities in Louisiana transferred the entire
population of a juvenile prison run by Wackenhut after federal
investigators alleged that inmates were beaten and deprived of
adequate food and clothes.
</P>
<P>
   South African officials say the safeguards they have
incorporated into the contract will ensure that the new prisons are
run properly.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's prison system is built to house about 100,000
inmates, but the network of facilities around the country presently
incarcerates more than 170,000, and escapes are common.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
