<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ORLECK-HNS &LR;      08-11 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORLECK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORLECK &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    WWII DESTROYER COMES HOME
 &HT;    By RICHARD STEWART 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    ORANGE, Texas _ As Don Greer stood on the pitching deck of the
<TEXT>
little fishing boat watching a Ukrainian seagoing tug pull the old,
rusting warship out of the Gulf of Mexico into the safety of the
Sabine River Waterway, the years melted away.
<P>
   He was no longer a retiree living in Florida and the ship was no
longer an over-age and obsolete Turkish destroyer. Suddenly it was
1952. He was an 18-year-old sailor and the ship was the proud USS
Orleck, the gray ghost of the Korean coast.
</P>
<P>
   He'd come 850 miles for the reunion. The ship had come 7,500
miles. They had both journeyed almost 47 years since he'd last seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worth it just for this,'' Greer beamed, looking over the
vessel that had carried him through two typhoons. He recalled the
day a North Korean shell came crashing through the radar pod where
he worked, missing him by a few feet.
</P>
<P>
   He also remembered the night he watched as the ship steamed
2,000 yards offshore _ ``too close in for a destroyer, really'' _
and blasted away at a coastal railway train with its five-inch
guns. ``It must have been an ammunition train,'' he said, ``because
it sure went up in a blaze of glory.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a huge salmon going up river to its birthplace, the Orleck
returned Friday to the waterway where it was born. But unlike a
salmon, the ship hasn't come home to die. It's come home to be born
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Orleck, the last of more than 90 destroyers built in this
southeast Texas petrochemical city during World War II, has
returned to be renovated and converted into a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
   Built at Consolidated Steel Corp.'s Orange shipyard, the
Orleck &UR;  &LR; was launched on May 12, 1945. &UR;  &LR; It is 390 feet long, 40 feet
wide and has a displacement of 2,250 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Designed as a fast, aircraft carrier escort ship, the Orleck was
meant to last just 10 or 12 years. Friday it looked almost as if it
could fight another war.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's got a lot of rust on her,'' Greer said. ``She needs a
bath.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take her to Hong Kong to see Garbage Scow Mary,''
he chuckled. He said thatduring the Korean conflict a woman with
that name would bring crews to repaint the sides of American ships
in exchange for the ship's garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she often tilted over 35 degrees during big storms
and room was tight for her 300-man crew, the Orleck was a happy and
proud ship, Greer said. ``It was a great life for a single man,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Greer didn't want to be single. He left the Navy to get
married and made a career of the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ship was launched too late to see duty in World War
II, the Orleck was in service in the U.S. Navy for more than 37
years and spent 16 more years in the Turkish Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was named for Lt. Joseph Orleck, the son of Russian
immigrants and commander of the USS Nauset, who went down with his
ship in 1943 when it was hit with bombs and struck a mine during
the amphibious invasion of Salerno, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   During the Korean War, the Orleck was known as a ``train
buster'' after twice hurling shells inland to destroy enemy supply
trains. Greer still proudly keeps a certificate he has for being
aboard when the ship blew up two such trains.
</P>
<P>
   Later the destroyer &UR;  &LR; was to make several tours off Vietnam,
earning the honor of ``top gun'' and credited with firing more
shells into Vietnam than any other American destroyer.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Orleck was transferred to the Turkish Navy,
where it was renamed the Yucetepe. Its final war patrols were made
during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Depwe, who heads up a local group raising money to restore
the old ship, said his group has long wanted to bring back one of
the warships built in Orange.
</P>
<P>
   When they heard about the Orleck last year, it was in a shipyard
in Izmir, Turkey, and was scheduled to be taken apart for scrap.
Depwe and some others made a quick trip to Turkey and met with
officials there to see if they could get the ship.
</P>
<P>
   What really did the job, he said, was giving a Turkish admiral a
badge and proclaiming him an honorary Texas Ranger. ``Just like
Walker, Texas Ranger!'' the beaming admiral said. The admiral
helped Depwe make plans to tow the ship to Orange.
</P>
<P>
   The ship will be berthed first in a downtown city park on the
Sabine River. During formal ceremonies at 5 p.m. Saturday, it will
be transferred to the restoration group.
</P>
<P>
   Greer was joined Friday by several other former Orleck crewmen
who came to see the arrival of their old ship. Former crewmen will
be allowed the visit it, but it may be several months before the
vessel is restored enough for public tours.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, after $3 million to $5 million in restoration, the
entire vessel will be open for tours, and there are plans for
battle re-enactments. A special park on the riverfront is being
created for the ship's permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
