<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-SAPP0812-COX     08-11 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAPP0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Sapp vs. Wade rivalry
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Warren Sapp went silent.
</P>
<P>
   Honest. Sapp was talking away, answering question after
question, talking about how he loves Miami _ ``the fans, the sun,
the women . . . greatest city in the world'' _ when a reporter
managed to plug the Hoover Dam of NFL mouths with a mere two
syllables.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Wade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next question,'' Sapp said icily.
</P>
<P>
   The next question came, and the Tampa Bay Buccaneers defensive
tackle cheerfully answered it. Well, as cheerfully as one can
expect after a 15-13 loss to the Miami Dolphins, pre-season or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep score, don't they?'' Sapp said.
</P>
<P>
   Then someone asked Sapp what he thought of Wade, a Dolphins
rookie offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp stared ahead blankly, scratching his chest with his right
hand. The question was rephrased. The catatonic look continued.
Another question was asked. More scratching and staring.
</P>
<P>
   End of interview.
</P>
<P>
   Start of a rivalry?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, we've got to begin somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what would happen if you managed to get Florida and
Florida State on the same field in August.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't have to be an exhibition game. Heck, it wouldn't
even have to be a game.
</P>
<P>
   If the Seminoles and Gators got together in a Publix parking lot
to stare at each other for three hours, people would show up to
watch. The fans would spend the days leading up the game debating
the relative eyelid strength of the quarterbacks. They would spend
days afterward calling talk radio shows to recount the clutch
blinks; to complain the referees and announcers clearly were alumni
of the other school and to look forward to the regular-season
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But put the Dolphins and Bucs together on an August night and
what do you get?
</P>
<P>
   Excitement. Anticipation. Fervent debate. . . . No, wait. That
was for the CBS postgame interview with Colleen, the South Florida
native booted off the ``Survivor'' island.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dolphins and Bucs get together for an exhibition game _
and Thursday night was the 15th time it happened _ it isn't exactly
a passionate affair. Or at least it hasn't been for 20 years, since
the Dolphins temporarily canceled the exhibition meetings despite a
string of four sellouts because, as then-owner Joe Robbie said, the
Bucs were treating each game ``as if it were a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note: This clearly violates NFL regulations which state that
both teams shall strives to make exhibition games as lifeless as
possible.)
</P>
<P>
   But, guess what, this non-rivalry may have found its version of
Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp vs. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, when the Dolphins and Bucs practiced
against each other in Orlando two weeks ago, Sapp turned a routine
pass-blocking drill into a chance to practice his celebration dance
steps. Wade didn't appreciate this. And he let Sapp know _
something his teammates later told him was a no-no.
</P>
<P>
   This week, fans rallied to Wade's defense, calling talk radio
shows to say they appreciated him standing up to Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   So the stage was set. Bucs kicker Martin Gramatica lined up for
the opening kickoff, stood with his arm raised . . . and heard a
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Delay of game. On an opening kickoff. Such is the story of this
non-rivalry. Full of false starts.
</P>
<P>
   Once the game started, Sapp had his moments. He tripped running
back Lamar Smith to stop one drive inside the 10. He knocked Damon
Huard to the ground. He celebrated by bobbing his head. And
talking.
</P>
<P>
   Wade also had his moments, opening a couple huge holes for Smith
to run through. Afterward, though, neither player wanted to discuss
the other.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be a rematch. These two teams will meet again
Dec. 10 at Pro Player (This Space For Sale!) Stadium. It already is
sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for both teams,'' Bucs General Manager Rich McKay
said Thursday night. ``But as long as they're not in our division,
I don't think there ever will be a true rivalry. And I don't see
that happening in realignment.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that there seemed to be a bit more of a
buzz in South Florida this week than before some of the previous
August meetings _ and that maybe that could carry into the December
_ McKay smiled slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it wasn't just because of Todd Wade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, Sapp sat in front of his locker. Silent.
</P>
<P>
   It's not much, but it's a start.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
