NYT-08-11-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TXOUT-LEGGETT0812-COX     08-11 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-LEGGETT0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ears everywhere miss the sound of a bullfrog opera
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I miss bullfrogs and I wish they'd come back.
</P>
<P>
   From where, I don't exactly know. I just know they're not as
plentiful and with them went one of the few nighttime activities in
a country kid's life that was both fun and legal.
</P>
<P>
   There was no limit. You could hunt at night. Ammunition was free
if you caught them by hand. What a world.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's drought that has killed off many of the frogs.
Others blame ozone depletion, highway paving, global warming or
pesticides. Their absence signals an impending ecological disaster,
they say. Whatever killed off the frogs or displaced them did a
pretty effective job in some parts of the country, taking with it
one of the world's great ``I am here'' vocal declarations.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have I lain under a blanket on the ground,
worried that a water moccasin would crawl in there with me, and
quaked at the mixed men's chorus of big bullfrogs and territorial
alligators? These were not some pretend frogs in a beer commercial,
but the real thing, basso profundo and proud of it. It sent shivers
up my spine even on a hot summer night.
</P>
<P>
   I've had the quiet pleasure on trips with my dad of gigging them
by the light of a two-cell flashlight. We would have the sweet,
succulent legs for breakfast the next morning. I was always
fascinated with the fact that they jumped around in the pan when
you cooked them.
</P>
<P>
   And I've known the terror of riding a customized, frog-fishing
johnboat to the bottom of the Sabine River on an ill-fated Explorer
Scout float trip. Two guys snuck some whiskey onto the trip and a
friend, whose dad owned the boat and was hosting the trip, got
drunk and sank the boat with me and his younger brother in the
front end.
</P>
<P>
   We drifted apart after that, and he died in a car wreck. My last
memory of him is his staggering into the light of the campfire,
wet, letting the alcohol dare him to talk tough to his father, who
chastised him for endangering other people and promptly knocked him
cold in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   The one frog we caught that night got away later when somebody
opened the storage compartment under the front seat where live
frogs were kept until time to clean them. No frog legs for
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Now most frog legs we eat come from somewhere else, like
Indonesia, where they are farmed for food. Domestic frogs are just
too hard or too expensive to mess with.
</P>
<P>
   Houses in East Texas always had a fishing pole tree, a China
berry or willow maybe, against which all the cane poles would be
stacked. You could go there and pick one out before you went to
fish for bream or catfish. Lots of them had frog gigs there, too.
They were sold in most hardware stories, but if you had one on your
scavenger hunt list today you'd be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need frog gigs if you don't have frogs. But where did
they go?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have that question all the time,'' said John Herron, who
heads the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department's Wildlife Diversity
program. ``There's not question they are not as common as they once
were. We know they go through cycles, but we don't know why. We
can't say if it's a long-term decline or what the cause might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Texans have several species of frogs from which to choose when
they can find them, Herron said, all of them in the genus Rana.
``The bullfrog is mainly an animal of the eastern United States,
west to the Rocky Mountains,'' he said. ``We also have the leopard
frog, the bronze frog and the pig frog, as well as the Rio Grande
leopard frog in southern Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to catching and eating, though, they all are
lumped together as bullfrogs. That's not quite fair to the real
dudes. ``There's no doubt that the bullfrog is at the top of the
frog food chain,'' Herron said. ``They'll eat anything they can get
in their mouths, including other frogs.''
</P>
<P>
   The first one I ever caught, with my dad standing at my shoulder
and telling me what to do, was a big bullfrog that hit a Heddon
Crippled Minnow topwater plug. He put up a pretty good fight, too,
before we put him on the chain stringer and scheduled him for
supper. I've caught them by hand and shot them with .22s in South
Texas hunting lease tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But now they're gone for the most part. You still see one here
and there and sometimes, on nice summer nights, I'll hear one or
two big dudes crank up and announce their presence to the world.
I've never had a place to take my kids frog gigging and actually
find any, which is a shame.
</P>
<P>
   They've never gotten to see spider eyes shining on the bank or a
small alligator sink beneath the moss or fight off a water snake
that was trying to climb into the boat. The frogs were the catalyst
for all those experiences, the foundation of an adult life of
hunting and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   A lot's missing without them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
