<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9187 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV13-     08-11 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-ART-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE SHELF: SPEAKING OF SUCCESS, IN A WOMAN'S VOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 Alecia Swasy, assistant managing editor for business at The St.
Petersburg Times, is the author of ``Soap Opera: The Inside Story
of Procter &AMP; Gamble.''  
 By ALECIA SWASY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside our newsroom in St. Petersburg, Fla., is a filing-cabinet
drawer emblazoned with a yellow smiley face. We call it the Happy
Drawer _ home to the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not where we keep the Belvedere vodka. We're talking
chocolate. Hershey's Kisses, Snickers bars and Reese's peanut
butter cups.
</P>
<P>
   When the chocolate stash runs low, people get cranky. No small
problem, considering that there is a correlation between chocolate
served and articles produced. The average 1,000-word article might
require a handful of Kisses, while a 300-page nonfiction book might
mean 27{ pounds of peanut M &AMP; M's.
</P>
<P>
   So what a treat to come across the management tricks of fellow
chocolate aficionado Ellen Gordon, the chief executive of Tootsie
Roll Industries. At 68, Gordon presides over production of 49.5
million Tootsie Rolls and 16 million lollipops a day, generating a
net profit margin of 17 percent, far ahead of her competitors at
Hershey. She merits a place among the profiles of ``Why the Best
Man for the Job Is a Woman'' (Harper Business, $24), by Esther
Wachs Book, a former reporter at Forbes magazine who knows how to
put a human face on a business story.
</P>
<P>
   My eyes tend to cross at most management texts, but this one is
different. It's not a generalized, predictable tome on how and why
women should become leaders. Book's book is like a series of comfy
chats inside a corporate suite. We hear the voices of the women who
have broken into the boys' club.
</P>
<P>
   It's lonely there, and the statistics are truly pathetic. In
1999, women held just 12 percent of the senior posts in Fortune 500
companies. And women chief executives are as scarce as pandas. But
in broader terms, women still represent power and money _ they
control 85 percent of all personal and household spending.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles offer plenty of lessons. For starters, these women
never forget their roots.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Carsey, who developed ``The Cosby Show'' and ``Roseanne,''
then pitched them to the networks, is the daughter of a shipyard
worker and a homemaker from Quincy, Mass. A self-described nerd,
Carsey endured the gray, slushy winters by watching television.
Clearly, she understands the untapped market of female viewers.
``Roseanne,'' for instance, portrayed the absurdity of everyday
life for working moms.
</P>
<P>
   Carsey's shows became huge hits: her production company is worth
an estimated $1.2 billion and she is now a partner with Oprah
Winfrey in Oxygen Media, whose chief executive is Geraldine
Laybourne, a former chairwoman of the Nickelodeon cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these successful women knew hard and dirty work in
their childhood. Rebecca Mark slopped hogs in Missouri; she is now
chief executive of Azurix, a global water supplier started by
Enron. Her Escada blazer and Ebel watch belie her modest farm
roots, but the work ethic has remained. After her hotel was bombed
during a visit to Bombay, she worked by candlelight to develop a
new power plant for the city of Dabhoi. But that probably wasn't as
tough as raising her twins while earning her Harvard M.B.A. with
distinction. Just reading about her workweek made me want to take a
nap.
</P>
<P>
   All of these women also demonstrate the importance of
establishing confidence at an early age. Researchers have found
that self-esteem for many girls plummets at about the age of 13.
One survey cited in the book found that 60 percent of girls are
happy in elementary school, but that drops to 29 percent in high
school. Boys maintained a higher level of self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Sports were important confidence-builders for many of the women,
including Meg Whitman, chief executive of eBay, who was a swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Along with self-confidence, of course, comes the courage to take
chances. Carsey, for instance, quit a comfortable job at the
networks, took out a second mortgage and started her company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the women lead by example and know how to balance work
and family. They go to school plays and don't miss birthday
parties. That sends a clear message to their colleagues: ``I trust
you to get the work done. You don't have to account for every
minute of your time.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has a couple of flaws. First, the editors could have
shown us some mercy by deleting every other use of the word
``paradigm.'' A far greater problem is the excessive fawning over
unsympathetic characters like Darla D. Moore. The book chronicles
Moore's time at Chemical Bank, where the bankruptcy and
reorganization unit she ran earned millions a year before she
joined her husband, Richard E. Rainwater, the billionaire investor,
as president of his investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   In her Upper East Side Manhattan condo, the book says, she
displays a floor-to-ceiling oil painting of herself, decked in
burgundy taffeta. And the book acknowledges her reputation as a
manager who motivates by fear. One of her mantras to employees:
``So, what are you wasting your time on today?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But for my money, the single fat paragraph given to Moore's and
Rainwater's woes in the Columbia/HCA Healthcare scandal falls
short. The two were slow to catch on to Richard L. Scott's
management problems at the chain, which Rainwater founded with
Scott. Eventually, Moore pushed for Scott's ouster, but it took a
federal investigation into allegations of Medicare fraud to get her
attention. Columbia paid hefty penalties in settling the case, and
shareholders saw their investment dwindle. But, hey, Moore wants to
be a role model for young M.B.A.'s attending the Darla Moore School
of Business, a result of her $25 million contribution to the
University of South Carolina. This might not be someone I want my
nieces to admire.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the good stuff _ chocolate. Gordon's family has
controlled Tootsie Roll for 65-plus years. Her grandfather had sold
paper to the company and noticed that management was late in paying
its bills. Enter Grandma, who saved a bit of her teacher's pay to
buy up Tootsie Roll stock. Other relatives did likewise, and the
family bought a controlling interest after the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Her father took young Ellen along with him to work, and she
wrote a high school essay on how she wanted to become a
businesswoman, a laughable notion in that era.
</P>
<P>
   After college, she and her husband took over the company. She
watched General Motors and other American manufacturers lag behind
foreign competitors because they failed to invest in new
technology. So she invested in high-speed machines and listened to
employee feedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a manager, you really don't know all the answers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At meetings, many people may drop by to offer their points of
view. ``That's why my chairs have wheels on them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The company doesn't even track turnover; most employees have
been there for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing 70, Gordon still gets calls from headhunters with job
offers; she rebuffs them. She has no plans to retire but hopes to
pass on the Tootsie Roll business someday to one of her daughters
or a top manager. ``I love the game,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Must be all that chocolate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
