<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BOY-CRITIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBASSADOR SAYS DAUGHTER DIDN'T USE OFFENDING PHRASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RYDE, England _ In the dog days of August, what media types here
call the silly season, it is manna from heaven, an
honest-to-goodness diplomatic scandal, a cultural war pitting a
trash-talking American teenager against all that is good about
British chivalry.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-person account on the perils of dating in London,
Mary-Catherine Lader, the 15-year-old daughter of the US ambassador
to Britain, wrote in the society magazine Tatler:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the English countryside, the Scottish Highlands, the
sheep in Wales, and above all else, living in London. But when I
started going out here, I found that British boys really suck.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to laud the social skills and looks of American boys
while disparaging English boys as scrawny, pale, and awkward, and
it immediately became front-page news. Virtually every newspaper,
radio, and TV station in Britain, including the staid BBC, picked
up the story.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the tabloids denounced the ambassador's daughter as
a spoiled, whiny American princess who couldn't get a boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Burrows, a columnist for the Mirror, suggested that Lader
should ``pack up her Prada bag, go back to the land of Jerry
Springer, and get it on with all the obese cretins and racist
red-necks.''
</P>
<P>
   The story was picked up and ran all around the world, but few
journalists bothered to call the US embassy, and none waited until
the Laders, who are out of the country on vacation, could be
reached. Had they, they would have learned that US Ambassador
Philip Lader is considering suing Tatler magazine because he and
his daughter claim the magazine made up the most controversial line
in the piece, in which she allegedly wrote that ``British boys
really suck.''
</P>
<P>
   The line appeared in headlines throughout Britain, and was
seized upon by most commentators as evidence that Miss Lader was
too ignorant and immature to get an English boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   While there was probably enough criticism of English boys in the
article to trigger some stories, it was that incendiary line that
has captured the imagination, and indignation, of many.
</P>
<P>
   Lader and his family were still out of the country Friday, but
Lader released a letter in which he said it was an editor at Tatler
who first suggested the offending line. Lader said his daughter
refused, but the editor unilaterally inserted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the article appeared, not only was that phrase included,
but it was highlighted in large, red typeface,'' Lader wrote to
Tatler editor Geordie Greig. Lader said the editors ``promised to
send her the final edit of her article before publication. This was
never received, and she never signed any release.''
</P>
<P>
   The line, he concluded, ``was not in her submitted draft and
actually was suggested by an adult editor. This has caused
considerable embarrassment to my daughter and our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatler fired back Friday, as Greig insisted Miss Lader
authorized the wording and signed off on the final draft.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever's telling the truth, what began as a story about an
undiplomatic diplomat's daughter was evolving into an indictment of
the British press, often criticized for printing rumors, unverified
information and, if Lader's allegations are true, fabrications.
</P>
<P>
   At the US embassy, embassy spokeswoman Carol Lynn MacCurdy said
The Globe, Newsweek, ABC News, and NBC News, and the Reuters wire
service were the only media organizations that waited for the
Laders' response before going with the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, at least no one in the British press, bothered to call
and get our side. They just ran with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph devoted more than half a page to the affair,
running three stories, plus an editorial pondering whether the
15-year-old's verbal attack had affected the ``special
relationship'' between Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Telegraph stories, the reporter sought comments
from English teenagers who, with nothing to back their assertions,
suggested that Lader's broadside was the result of her having just
been dumped by an English boy.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Miss Lader of embracing stereotypes of English men as
tongue-tied fops, many hurled stereotypes back at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``As she is an ambassador for American girls, I would like to
say that they are all presumptuous, offensive and very
irritating,'' teenager George Kemp wrote in the Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
   MacCurdy said some American newspapers did no better than their
British counterparts. She said the Washington Post, the
Philadelphia Enquirer, and the Houston Chronicle ran items about
the Tatler piece without calling the embassy for comment.
</P>
<P>
   When Miss Lader returns to the prestigious St. Paul's school
next month, she will no doubt be asked to explain lines such as,
``I'm not sure it's actually possible to become friends with a
British teenage guy. His idea is to to ask two questions. . .and
then feel entitled to stick his tongue down your throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how many of those lines may have been embellished by
Tatler's editors remained unclear. MacCurdy said when the Laders
return, they will go over the article ``line by line.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Isle of Wight Friday, young English people were mostly
amused by the scandal. Naomi Mead, 16, said some of Lader's
criticisms of English boys are valid, but ``you can't generalize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say all English boys are like that, nor should you
say all American boys are one way or the other,'' said Mead,
displaying a sense of fairness that was hard to find in the British
media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
