<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ACCEPTS BACKING OF UAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Pa. _ Al Gore's labor pains abated somewhat Friday,
as an effusively thankful vice president accepted the long-awaited
endorsement of a powerful union, the United Auto Workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful to you more than I can say in words,'' Gore told
a crowd of boisterous UAW members at a rally at Willow Run airport
near Detroit, where a red carpet had been rolled out to greet the
Democratic presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means the world to me. I respect you, I appreciate what
you have done, and I thank you for your help.''
</P>
<P>
   UAW President Stephen Yokich _ who once accused Gore of
``holding hands with the profiteers of the world'' for backing a
free trade agreement with China _ offered his full support for the
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be our candidate,'' Yokich told the vice
president, who pumped his fists exuberantly in the air as Yokich
reported the unanimous UAW board vote to endorse Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a clear choice. I don't think Bush, Juniorhad a
chance,'' Yokich said. ``You name it, he's against what we believe
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he and his running-mate, Connecticut Senator Joseph I.
Lieberman, would not only ``defend the right to organize, we're
going to strengthen it.'' Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew who does not
work from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday, skipped the labor
event so he could be back in Washington to observe the Jewish
sabbath with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president acknowledged his support of free-trade
agreements _ pacts organized labor has opposed _ but said ``we have
to use trade to lift up labor and environmental standards around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign staff were obviously relieved to get the
endorsement, especially before the Democratic National Convention
begins in Los Angeles on Monday. Membership in the 700,000-strong
union is big in Illinois, Ohio and Michigan, a senior Gore campaign
advisor noted, giving Gore a needed boost in those delegate-rich
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a long process, they made their decision, and I beleive
it was the right one,'' said Gore campaign manager Donna Brazile.
``This campaign has the support of working families,'' she said,
echoing the campaign's pre-convention theme.
</P>
<P>
   For an incumbent vice president and Democratic party nominee,
Gore has had a comparatively tough time nailing down support from
from some sectors of organized labor. While the Democratic nominee
last October won the backing of the AFL-CIO, he only this week got
the endorsement of the UAW after persistent lobbying by the Gore
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some UAW members said they were still annoyed with Gore for his
support for international trade agreements the workers said could
cost American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It was best that the union held back its support as long as it
did, said member Dan Shepherd, 52. ``If you get into a commitment
too early, then you run the risk of giving the union a black eye if
the guy turns out wrong,'' Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW had flirted with the idea of backing consumer advocate
Ralph Nader for president. Nader has been winning about four to
five percent of voter support in opinion polls _ limited support
but perhaps enough to tip the balance from Gore to Bush in some key
states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore staff met with UAW members at the union leadership's
request, the Gore senior aide said, and garnered the endorsement by
winning over the rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president still hasn't gotten the official approval of
the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, whose president, James
Hoffa Jr., was honored at a reception at the Republican National
Convention earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa is, a delegate-at-large at the Democratic convention next
week, but the union is still not likely to issue an endorsement _
if they even decide to endorse at all _ until after Labor Day, said
Teamsters spokesman Bret Caldwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoffa's always been a Democrat, but he's an uncommitted
delegate,'' Caldwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The union is conducting a ``scientific poll'' of its members
this month, and will take its cue from the results, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Hoffa have not met personally since late April,
Caldwell said. But Gore and Teamsters staff have been in contact at
least once a week, he and Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor has been miffed at Gore for his ardent support
for free-trade pacts such as the North American Free Trade
Agreement and the China trade agreement. Union leaders argue that
expanding free trade will undermine American workers and benefit
operations in foreign nations were wages are low and environmental
standards are lax.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans have also backed the trade bills, and Democrats
hope that union leaders will ultimately realize they are better
off, overall, with Gore than with his opponent, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've noticed what everyone else has noticed, which is this
playful repartee between unions and Nader,'' said Representative
Jose Serrano, Democrat of New York, who is a longtime labor
advocate. ``I can't see how they could go anywhere else'' but to
the Democrats, who have been ``nice to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If at this point, labor doesn't realize that the Democrats are
their friends, then the problem is bigger than this election,''
Serrano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
