<SLUG> BC-TV-BULL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMART MONEY'S ON TNT'S NEW WALL STREET DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The newest theory in TV programming is that, if America can
embrace innumerable ensemble dramas about doctors, lawyers and
cops, it can handle an ensemble drama about investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   We may not know an IPO from a hole in our pocket, but producer
Michael Chernuchin believes we still can care about well-dressed,
well-educated, well-heeled plutocrats whose sole purpose is to make
money.
</P>
<P>
   No patching leaky aortas here. No defending the common man. It's
survival of the fattest cat, and if someone happens to have a
conscience, well, even Wall Street has to pay lip service to
equal-opportunity strictures.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin's ``Bull,'' premiering Tuesday night on TNT, does
likewise, with a Caucasian cast punctuated by one person of color.
Maybe that's just art imitating life. As one stiff-collared
boardroom bully says in the premiere episode, there is a glass
ceiling for minorities on Wall Street, because rich white people
spending billions in the rarefied air of high finance might not
want to be sitting across the table from, ahem, persons not like
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bold assertion that could be uttered about many other
industries, TV included. In any event, it leaves Malik Yoba (``New
York Undercover'') the sole minority member of an impressive cast.
And even his character, Harvard-educated Corey Granville, doesn't
seem to realize he's an outsider. The son of academicians,
Granville is a member of the black elite, unaccustomed to bigotry
and racially motivated limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as he recognizes and accepts it, all will be well,''
says Robert ``The Kaiser'' Roberts, head of the investment banking
firm where Granville has sold $10 million worth of Brazilian bonds
the firm has been trying to unload for six months.
</P>
<P>
   What Roberts doesn't know is that Granville is part of a
renegade group planning to bolt the firm and open their own shop.
And the leader of the pack is Roberts' own grandson Robert III,
better known as Ditto.
</P>
<P>
   This is the premise of ``Bull'': young people on Wall Street
getting rich, doing it their way, maybe even thumbing their noses
at the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin, executive producer of ``Law &AMP; Order'' for more than
half of its 10 seasons, says he got the idea for ``Bull'' when he
was working as a lawyer in New York City. He was sitting with three
friends, all of them investment bankers, all of them about 25 years
old, and they invited him to join them at Pebble Beach. They had
leased a private plane and were flying across the country for a
round of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin's idea didn't fly for about 10 years. But now, with
the majority of Americans owning shares in publicly held companies,
the concept is hotter than Microsoft stock used to be. Besides
``Bull,'' the prime-time pipeline this fall includes Darren Star's
``The $treet,'' airing on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an opening 10 minutes of Wall Street jargon that will
confuse anyone who wasn't born with a silver certificate in his
mouth, this ``Bull'' is worth riding. With the remarkable Stanley
Tucci appearing as a recurring slimeball, and Donald Moffat as the
Kaiser, ``Bull'' shapes up as the smartest thing TNT has done in a
while.
</P>
<P>
   The cable channel calls the show its first original series,
which isn't exactly true. It aired ``Crusade,'' the sequel to
``Babylon 5.'' But who's counting? ``Bull'' has an interesting
look, not unlike ``The West Wing,'' and an attractive cast, led by
George Newbern as the eccentric Ditto and Christopher Wiehl as the
fresh-faced underdog, Carson Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   Chernuchin's first script, while a little heavy on insider
patois, is reminiscent of ``L.A. Law'' in its heyday. Each
character gets good lines, not just setups for the marquee players
to hit out of the park. It's the mark of a good ensemble show, and
in a new season that's looking meager for the commercial networks,
Chernuchin and TNT may have hit the bullseye.
</P>
<P>
   BULL
</P>
<P>
   WHAT: One-hour drama series about a breakaway Wall Street
investment-banking firm
</P>
<P>
   CAST: George Newbern, Malik Yoba, Donald Moffat, Elisabeth Rohm,
Ian Kahn, Alicia Coppola and Christopher Wiehl
</P>
<P>
   WHEN: Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE: TNT cable
</P>
<P>
   RATING: TV-14
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
