<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-EXITSOURCE-SERVICES-B     08-11 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXITSOURCE-SERVICES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY BRINGING WIRELESS DATA TO TRAVELERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: eXitSource is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even ennui, it now seems, moves at Internet speed.
</P>
<P>
   Take the wireless Net, for example. In the barely eight months
since cellphones connected to the Internet hit the mass market, the
general sentiment has rapidly gone from ``Isn't that amazing?'' to
``What a stupid user interface!''
</P>
<P>
   The promise of using your cellphone to surf the Web has crashed
into the reality of tiny screens and the hassle of using a
telephone keypad. That has quickly led cellphone companies and
wireless content providers to conclude that what people want from
their phone is not the whole Net but specific information tailored
for quick access and manageable display.
</P>
<P>
   A good example of the trend is a newly launched service from an
Atlanta-area company called eXitSource that provides information
about restaurants, lodging and hospitals at 20,000 US Interstate
highway exits.
</P>
<P>
   While the information could theoretically be obtained from a Web
site such as MapQuest over the phone, eXitSource has worked over
its database to make data available with as few as four keystrokes.
</P>
<P>
   By entering a state and choosing from a list of Interstates,
wireless users can get a list of restaurants, gas stations, motels
and hospitals arranged by exit, and find out what is available at
each exit for the next 25 or 50 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, the service has become available in the last two weeks
as a featured link on Net phones from Verizon Wireless and Nextel,
and another national carrier is expected to sign on for the service
as soon as next week, Peterson said. It can also be reached from
any wireless Net phone by someone willing to enter the Internet
address of 216.205.12.122.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the application that fuels the market for
wireless Net phones,'' said eXitSource president Ron Peterson.
``This is what takes you from `nice to have' to `need to have.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Market research firm DataQuest has estimated that the US will
have 12.6 million wireless data users by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   However, many industry officials and analysts contend it is
still not clear whether current wireless Net offerings and promised
enhancements are compelling enough to achieve some of the rosier
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, wireless Net access could turn out to be something
millions of Americans do sign up for _ but actually use only a few
times a week or month, which would limit both how much they would
be willing to pay for it and how much wireless content providers
can reasonably hope to make from the services.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lowenstein, a senior wireless analyst with The Yankee Group
in Boston, said, ``There's really nothing that has hit big in the
US. I think we are still in a great experimentation phase. Nobody
really knows exactly what content people want to get access to, so
right now we are in a big market-test phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, some wireless officials acknowledge that what entices
people to pay an extra $10 or $15 a month to get Net access from
their phone is not what they expected last year when services were
first launched allowing people to get news headlines, weather
forecasts and stock quotes from their cellphone screen.
</P>
<P>
   While ``mobile financial services'' such as obtaining stock
quotes or even trading stocks with a phone are by many accounts the
most popular of the services offered, Lowenstein said most studies
find no more than one in four wireless Net subscribers use them
frequently.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Maggio, president of NetMorf, a Boston company that
tailors Internet content for display over a phone, said, ``The
mobile consumer is vastly different from Web users.
</P>
<P>
   ``While typical online Web users require lots of rich content,
mobile users need precisely the right information delivered at a
time when every minute counts,'' Maggio said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, what eXitSource can offer over a wireless phone is
pretty thin, and not much more informative than the simple signs
you would see right before the off-ramp.
</P>
<P>
   It can tell you there is a hospital near a given exit off the
interstate, for example, but it does not give the name of the
hospital, how far away it is or any directions. ``We wanted to come
out quickly with a 1.0 version,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein said eXitSource is on the right track by offering
information that requires ``as little data entry as possible to
get.'' But he said, ``You still have to enter a lot of information.
That's OK if you're a passenger, but if you're a solo driver it
brings up some (safety) concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Peterson said, eXitSource hopes to make money by
charging food or hotel chains to include better information, such
as directions and whether a given McDonald's or Burger King has a
playground or a gas station has a car wash.
</P>
<P>
   Cellphone owners using eXitSource to get information might be
able to learn the names of four restaurants or three gas stations
near an exit, but would only get complete directions and richer
information about those whose owners had paid eXitSource to have
the extra data listed.
</P>
<P>
   Already the service includes a link to many hotel and motel
listings allowing people, once they have located lodgings near an
exit, to make a voice call instantly to the reservation desk.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also working with California-based speech
technology giant Nuance to develop a system with which people could
use their voice instead of pressing keys on the phone to request
information about services at each exit.
</P>
<P>
   Six-year-old eXitSource, formerly known as Interstate America,
sends a crew of 40 people out to continually survey every exit on
the 45,000-mile Interstate system. Its financial backers include
Zenrin, a leading Japanese developer of geographical information,
and buyers of its data include Rand McNally and General Motors'
Onstar in-vehicle data service.
</P>
<P>
   Well before launching the wireless service, eXitSource has been
making money developing specialized directories for trucking
companies, tour-bus operators and recreational vehicle owner
associations.
</P>
<P>
   Based on measurements of parking lot sizes made by satellite
positioning devices, these directories include listings of
restaurants with lots big enough to park a truck or camper, as well
as sites that have facilities at which to empty an RV toilet.
</P>
<P>
   eXitSource researchers visit every business or service within a
half-mile of each exit and re-survey sites at least annually to
keep up with changes, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   New cellular systems are being developed that can determine
where a cellphone user is, either by triangulating their distance
from cellphone towers or using the Pentagon's satellite positioning
system.
</P>
<P>
   With such a system, eXitSource could effectively ``push''
information to subscribers about services available at the next 10
exits in the direction in which they are travelling. But Peterson
said he thinks it could be 18 months before such location systems
are functional.
</P>
<P>
   While Peterson is confident that traveling consumers will find
eXitSource's database helpful, he acknowledged: ``We have to figure
out how to make money at this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
