<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9199 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TXOUT-WOMEN0812-COX     08-11 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-WOMEN0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women reeling in the outdoors life
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hunting and fishing are wonderful ways to spend
time outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem, it seems, is getting started. People who
get the chance to go when they're young tend to stick with it.
However, it's much harder to recruit adults into the outdoors
world.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department learned
that long ago. Besides having programs directed at youngsters, the
agency has set its sights on women with a program called ``Becoming
an Outdoor Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1993, more than 4,000 women have come
through its seminar program, many of whom have gone on to join
other organizations and try advanced skills activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ideal model that creates a system to keep them moving
through the various programs, one-day seminars, weekend events and
local events that are more advanced,'' said Steve Hall, education
coordinator for Texas Parks and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The women who have come to the program, which was pioneered in
Wisconsin but has grown intensely in Texas, are looking to learn
traditional skills, too. ``Shotgun shooting and fly-fishing are the
two most popular events among all the seminars,'' Hall said.
Canoeing is another popular activity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the five weekend events held each year, there are various
education modules from which to choose for each afternoon and
morning session. The basic classes have been the best, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are advertising workshops that are fairly broad, but they
are about one-third shooting, one-third fishing and one-third other
activities,'' Hall said. Some women come back to subsequent weekend
events to study other courses, as well as enjoy the campfire
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   TPWD has expanded the outdoor women's program. There are now 12
chapters around the state, including Austin, through which women
can take part in outdoors field activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's neat is that we can get a one-day introduction to many
of the teaching modules,'' Hall said. ``We can go around and
present these programs, and that recruits them to the weekend
seminars or the TOWN (Texas Outdoor Women's Network) chapters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall admits that just offering some seminars for women won't
bridge the gap that's created when those individuals haven't been
exposed to the outdoors as children. As a result, Parks and
Wildlife is looking at methods for expanding women's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two ways of doing that, starting with a program called
`Wonders of the Outdoor World' or `WOW.' That will be family events
in a camplike setting,'' Hallo said. Getting families involved will
help women be involved, as well as expose youngsters to the
outdoors at an age when the lessons can stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing we're looking at is CEO,'' Hall said. That
stands for `Corporate Executives in the Outdoors,' a program that
will allow companies to deal with leisure activities and stress
management through outdoor programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
