<HEADER>
A9202 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-RAZOR-SCOOTERS-$ADV13     08-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAZOR-SCOOTERS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING FOR THE METHOD BEHIND SCOOTER MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By JOHN LELAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The maitre d' at Coup, a swanky New American
restaurant in the East Village, smiled as he fingered the coat
check ticket. Coup is a place of daring high-modern style, and one
can only imagine what finery has passed through its coat room. Yet
even so, this article cut a figure: sleek of line, cutting-edge in
design, of the moment and yet blue-collar practical. ``I'm so glad
you had this ticket,'' the maitre d' smiled, ``to distinguish it
from all the others back there.'' He handed over my scooter, and I
rode off into the night.
</P>
<P>
   For one week, the idea was to travel everywhere on these two
resin wheels, testing whether these fashionable new scooters were a
viable alternative to cabs and hoofing. Since arriving from Hong
Kong at Christmas, the chrome Razor scooters, which go for about
$100 a pop, have been selling out at both Toys ``R'' Us and the
Sharper Image, appealing equally to superannuated kids and to the
regular kind. With a handful of other manufacturers and
distributors jumping on the Razor wagon, the devices have become a
new form of transit for New York's urban masses.
</P>
<P>
   But on to the road test. As a mode of transportation, sadly, the
scooter proved the stiletto heel of the two-wheeled set: great to
look at, lousy for carrying laundry to the dry cleaner. Scootering
is work, especially at rush hour. The small wheels bog down on the
city's rough surfaces, and the base rides so low that any size bump
becomes a potential obstacle. By the time I reached the office my
first morning, after a 40-block ride, I was drenched in
perspiration, my knee was bruised from a near tumble, and my hands
ached as if I'd been working a jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   These things I learned: cracks and seams in the sidewalk are not
the scooterist's friend; a polite ``excuse me'' cuts you only so
much slack; and the scooterist's code is a subtle one. One
afternoon, as I passed a fellow rider somewhat my junior _ say, by
about 30 years _ I threw him a fraternal salute. The boy stared
back blankly and whizzed by. This, I figured, is the code of the
road, at least when some crazy adult lets go of his handgrip,
posing a threat to self and all around.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as I glided around town, weaving perilously among the
scaffolds, I felt part of a new urban tribe, joined by our
insouciant disregard for the slow pace of pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pavement-bound, they mostly didn't get it.
Construction guys asked for a lift; others shot dirty looks,
rightly fearing for their ankles. When I did impress a couple of
gym bunnies on Eighth Avenue with my lapidary roll, they simply
parked themselves in my path, astounded that they had just read ``a
whole article'' about these gizmos in a men's fashion magazine.
Fine. Now get out of my way.
</P>
<P>
   I also learned that, contrary to what you might think, it is
actually the stationary leg, not the pushing one, that gets the
more rigorous workout: or rather, the gluteal muscles attached to
that leg. If you aren't careful to switch legs from time to time,
you might find that your seated position begins to lean to the left
or right, poor form in most any occupation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, once you get the hang of it, there is real
fetishistic satisfaction in unfolding the finely machined frame _
every bar and bolt sliding silently into place _ and of breaking it
down again before entering the Met or your local noodle house. For
those of us who have never had call to assemble a high-powered
weapon in a James Bond movie, this seems the next best thing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, steady rains and the scooter-related return of an
old repetitive strain injury cut my experiment short. It was a
relief to rejoin the slow-moving ranks of the asphalt-bound.
</P>
<P>
   As a trend, scootermania properly belongs in the category of
irrational mob behavior, like soccer rioting or capri pants: one
person starts shouting something, an alpha male does this or that,
and before you know it, everybody is on scooters. I was ready to
get off the razor's edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
