<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9203 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-LOOKER-B     08-11 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-LOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKER HOPES HE'LL CATCH ON WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM KALEC  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The dream started with a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired wide receiver Dane Looker practiced with the
Patriots for the first time Tuesday, approximately three years
removed from a conversation that forever changed his life.
</P>
<P>
   Ater completing his second season at Division 2 Western
Washington University _ not as football player but as a shooting
guard averaging 14 points per game _ a former high school teammate
asked Looker a simple question.
</P>
<P>
   The answer has led him to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``My buddy Brock Huard, who is a quarterback with the Seahawks
right now, he (said), `Why not try and play football at the
University of Washington?' I played high school ball with Brock and
junior high school ball with Brock so it was kind of an ongoing
story.''
</P>
<P>
   One that Looker felt had reached its completion when he accepted
Huard's challenge and walked on. He made the Huskies team, but
Looker never expected to make a real impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main goal when I got to Washington was to make it on the
field once during my career,'' Looker said. ``I didn't have any
intentions of starting, so it was my dream to start. The coach
didn't give me any assurance about anything there.''
</P>
<P>
   The same holds true in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Patriots gave up a 2002 sixth-round draft choice
for Looker, he is joining a deep and somewhat established corps of
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn isn't going anywhere. Veterans Vincent Brisby, Troy
Brown, and Tony Simmons are virtual locks to make the final cut.
Plus, Looker is battling Matt Bumgardner, Shockmain Davis, Tony
Gaiter, and Sean Morey for a spot on the 53-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Looker caught 72 Huard passes for more than 700 yards
and five touchdowns. As a senior, his numbers dropped considerably
because Huard's replacement, Marques Tuiasosopo, was primarily a
running quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   So after an established two-year collegiate career, Looker
received his degree and was ready to move on to a life without
football. But his agent got on the phone and called all 31 NFL
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after I caught the 72 balls I never thought that I had a
shot at the NFL,'' Looker said. ``I thought you had to have a
four-year career for the NFL to look at you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have very much interest from any teams, to be honest
with you. My agent called around and St. Louis was the only one to
take the bait.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' free agent catch of the day hauled in three receptions
in his first professional appearance to lead all receivers. For his
efforts, Looker was given his first taste of what life can be like
in the NFL _ he was traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know they traded free agents,'' Looker said with
a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Looker has relished the opportunity to work with some of the
game's best. So far, Looker has run plays with Super Bowl MVP Kurt
Warner and Drew Bledsoe, and in practice, he's being chased by one
of the league's top safeties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyer (Milloy) is a legend where I grew up (near Tacoma),''
Looker said. ``I went to high school about five minutes from where
he lived. I remember growing up hearing about Lawyer Milloy and, of
course, I watched him at the University of Washington. He is a
great athlete and a legend in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional star-gazing, Looker is aware there is
still business to take care of and he's committed to giving it his
best shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I have an opportunity,'' Looker said. ``Nothing is
guaranteed, we have some great receivers here, but I have the
opportunity to make the roster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
