<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9204 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV1     08-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: U.S. REMAINS DESTINATION OF CHOICE FOR INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States has been living through
extraordinary economic times for so long now that fresh milestones
sometimes pass with a yawn. With growth rates over 5 percent,
subdued inflation, low unemployment, high productivity and strong
corporate profits _ all with the expansion already a decade old _
it is hard to surprise people with good news.
</P>
<P>
   But here is another sweet nugget to chew on: The unusually large
gap between the performance of the U.S. economy of those of its
main peers, Europe and Japan, is proving more sustainable than many
economists expected. And the strong dollar that helped make it all
possible continues to defy gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Months after the sharp correction in the Nasdaq began last
April, the dollar has not only failed to plunge against the yen and
the euro as was once widely expected, but it has actually retouched
its record highs against the euro and held steady against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, stock market nervousness aside, foreigners have arguably
never had as much faith in the future of the U.S. economy as they
do today. The dollar's value is determined, in the simplest sense,
by the confidence that the world has in the United States. And
nothing that is happening here has persuaded foreigners that they
would do better to put their money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The old economic laws suggest that this cannot go on
indefinitely. In a sense, the United States has been living on
borrowed money, running the largest trade and current account
deficits in its history. That makes it more vulnerable to the whims
of foreign trading partners. Fortunately, they seem to be as
smitten by America's technology revolution as Americans are.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not flinching,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief economist
at Deutsche Bank Securities in New York. ``In terms of the new
economy, Europe is still somewhat behind and Japan is seriously
behind, and they cannot afford not to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most popular script for a so-called hard landing of
the U.S. economy begins with a stock market correction, followed by
a plunge in the supercharged dollar, reflecting the world's lowered
hopes for growth and profits here.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States' major trading peers _ Europe, Japan,
Canada and Mexico _ stopped recycling the dollars they earn by
selling goods here into productive investments here, the dollar
would quickly lose its strength. That would make imports more
expensive, contribute to inflation, cause the Fed to raise interest
rates and further undermine the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers has been sufficiently
concerned about such an outcome for the past year that he traveled
the globe urging the country's economic peers to prod their
economies to grow faster so that the world could ``balance up,''
not ``balance down.'' Europe has been growing only half as fast as
the United States, and Japan's economy is flat, worsening the
already severe U.S. trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Hard landing could still happen if the stock market takes
another dive. But the 30 percent correction in the Nasdaq was no
minor blip, and it only slightly unnerved dollar investors, who
have since sent the U.S. currency higher.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why is speculative. But the consensus is that foreign
investors view America's technology prowess as far more resilient
than a stock market bubble. And they are willing to keep investing
in what is essentially a seller's market _ the high dollar making
assets here very expensive.
</P>
<P>
   One way that shows up is through mergers and acquisitions of
American companies by foreigners, which have quickened this year
from the already extraordinary rate of 1998 and 1999. Through early
August, foreign companies had announced 1,202 deals to buy U.S.
companies, with the purchases valued at $266 billion. For all of
1999, there were 1,701 deals valued at $305 billion.
</P>
<P>
   If that enthusiasm continues, it is not inconceivable that the
record current account deficit could continue to expand without
jeopardizing the dollar and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rudi Dornbusch, an economics professor at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, says the United States, with its younger
population, has long had lower savings rates and higher investment
rates than Europe and Japan. That was true even when Japan seemed
to be years ahead in manufacturing efficiency. But it is still true
today, when both Japan and Europe lag far behind in technological
innovation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who were worried about our deficit were wrong because
they underestimated the appeal of our new economy,'' Dornbusch
said. ``It's as though there's both an oil and a gold rush, and
it's all happening here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
