u l BC-TXOUT-PUBLIC0812-COX     08-11 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-PUBLIC0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opportunities abound for all Texas hunters
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas has permits. Texas has draw hunts. And
Texas has open areas, all for public hunters who might not have
their own place leased every fall.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department Commission has
done in recent years is expand the public hunting program, through
extra opportunity on state land and through cooperative efforts
with private landowners.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation for the successes on private land was in the
public dove hunting program. The department provided the initial
seed money to lease land near urban areas for hunting, and since
that time hunters have paid the way through purchases of the annual
$40 public hunting permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 130 units in 48,000 acres this year, and 23 units will
offer species other than doves, such as squirrel, rabbits,
pheasants and quail,'' said Herb Kothmann, public hunting
coordinator for Texas Parks and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The department also has released its 2000-2001 Public Hunting
Lands booklet, which includes applications for drawings on state
parks and wildlife management areas. In addition, hunters can pick
up information about the special drawings that include the Texas
Grand Slam and the Texas Whitetail Bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Special permit hunts cover everything from alligators to
white-tailed deer. The annual booklet explains how to apply, who
may apply and also gives dates and times for the various hunts. The
number of entrants and successful hunters from the previous year
are included so that hunters can assess their chances for success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Applications are already coming in,'' Kothmann said.
``Unfortunately, we continue to have people who apply for more than
one hunt in their draw category. They disqualify themselves and
everybody on their cards when they do that. They need to read the
instructions carefully on how to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be more than 6,000 openings on state parks and
wildlife management areas this year.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the department has had tremendous success with the Big
Time Texas Hunts. That program started with the Texas Grand Slam,
all expenses-paid trophy hunting trips for whitetail and mule deer,
proghorn and desert bighorn sheep. There will be one winner this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The department then added the Texas Exotic Safari, which is
based on the department's Mason Mountain Wildlife Management Area.
That hunt is for two exotics from among waterbuck, gemsbok, oryx,
kudu, able and impala. Taxidermy, food and lodging and guides are
included. Two winners will be chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Other hunts added last year featured the Texas Whitetail
Bonanza, trophy deer hunts of three to five days on some of Texas'
top hunting ranches. Twenty hunters will be selected from among the
entrants for the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Waterfowl Adventure will allow a winner and three
guests to travel around the state for a series of hunts for geese
and ducks, including mallards in East Texas and geese in the
Panhandle. Each trip includes guides, food and lodging.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is the Texas Big Time Bird hunt. One winner gets
four hunts for quail, pheasant, doves and spring turkeys. Three
guests will be included on the two-day quail hunt, pheasant hunt
and two afternoons of dove hunting. One guest is allowed on the
two-day turkey hunt. Food, lodging and guides are included.
</P>
<P>
   Individuals may buy $10 entries for a chance to win any of the
Big Time Texas Hunts. You can enter all or just one and buy as many
tickets as you wish.
</P>
<P>
   For information on public hunting programs, visit the TPWD Web
site at: www.tpwd.state.tx.us. Or call (800) 792-1112, ext. 4505,
or (512) 389-4505 for information or to request an application
booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
