r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-11 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; JUSTICE IS AN EXPENSIVE BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeannie Sack &LR; , who's in Chicago, forwards some shopping
information from the Chicago Tribune, which was reporting on the
case of Circuit Judge  &UR; George J.W. Smith &LR; , who is alleged to have
bought his judicial appointment.
</P>
<P>
   When he was interviewed by the FBI, said the Trib, ``Smith
denied paying for his judicial position but said he had heard
rumors that others had paid money for their judicial appointments.
He indicated to the FBI that the rumored cost for a judicial
appointment was $30,000 for Democrats and $50,000 for
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - &UR; Katie Couric &LR; , 48, is having a romance with TV producer Tom
Werner _ whose Carsey-Werner company was responsible for ``The
Cosby Show,'' ``3rd Rock From the Sun'' and other series _ reports
the New York Daily News. Werner lives mainly in Los Angeles, &LR;  but
has been traveling east often to see Couric, whose husband died two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   - MSNBC says  &UR; Angelina Jolie &LR;  has told reporters in Europe,
where she is promoting ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' that she and her
husband,  &UR; Billy Bob Thornton &LR; , are planning to have their Oscars
welded together.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bo Derek &LR;  told the New York Post's  &UR; Cindy Adams &LR;  why she has
decided to come out with a line of expensive pet beauty products.
``For 20 years, I'd been asked to use, try, plug every cosmetic
line there was. Finally, I was asked to do a skin-care line. As I
worked on that, my dogs began to concern me. They'd sometimes smell
badly. Like, after we'd play or if it was hot and they'd perspire,
they weren't so fragrant. They swim with me. They're in the house
with me. I wondered what to do. ... So I came up with shampoos,
conditioners, fragrances, air fresheners, silk pomades.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Al Franken &LR; 's ``Why Not Me?'' a book published last year in
which he wins a presidential election on a campaign of reducing ATM
fees, names Sen.  &UR; Joseph Lieberman &LR;  as his running mate. In the
book, Franken serves for four months, then pardons himself for
crimes in office, &LR;  and quits; Lieberman becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STREETS OF THE CITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Bruce Townley &LR;  saw a man walking what looked like a
21/2-foot-long water monitor lizard on a leash last week, near the
intersection of Sutter and Sansome in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   - When  &UR; Robert Kunze &LR;  helped a blind man cross the intersection
of Fillmore and Sacramento last week, the man laughingly told him,
``Don't worry. The people around here don't want to get their cars
all sticky.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SKIP TO THE LOO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Top-of-the-line restaurants in New York have top-of-the-line
bathrooms, reports the New York Times, which describes a number of
specific innovations:
</P>
<P>
   - At Bar 89 in SoHo, transparent glass doors on the stalls
become opaque when the occupant turns the lock.
</P>
<P>
   - Fun, a restaurant in Manhattan's Chinatown, has two small
video monitors, one in the men's room and one in the ladies', that
allows &LR;  users of the sink to see users of the sink in the other
room.
</P>
<P>
   - At Brasserie, a cast-resin trough in the wall serves both rest
rooms. A sign above the trough in the men's room reads
``WASHISTOPURGEISTODENYISTOWASHIS.''
</P>
<P>
   Designer  &UR; Liz Diller &LR;  explained, ``It has to do with different
aspects of cleaning oneself. And the relationship between sin and
dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. New York magazine reports that  &UR; Al Gore &LR; 's motorcade was
whizzing through Manhattan recently, &LR;  when the candidate got
hungry. The motorcade stopped at the Mercer Kitchen, an extremely
chic place, and an aide was sent in to ask for a simple lunch _
tuna salad and something chocolate for dessert _ that could be
brought out to Gore, who was waiting in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The manager said the chef does not make tuna salad, and gave the
aide a few suggestions for other places.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - ``I don't know why Walter Mondale and I and Michael Dukakis
and Jimmy Carter are all singled out as four kind of duds in
American politics, except that we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; George McGovern  &LR; in  &UR; Brad Koplinski &LR; 's book ``Hats in the
Ring: Conversations With Presidential Candidates'' (Presidential
Publishing; $19.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
