<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-GUIDE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELCOME TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
  It's not `Survivor' island,  
but it still takes some skill 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles is a vast metropolis whose many sights and wonders
simply cannot be seen in a mere five summer days without the
benefit of a little planning and a good respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Factor in the media saturation and the vast number of parties,
protests and speeches going on during the Democratic National
Convention and delegates will be hard-pressed to come away from
their stay feeling like they really experienced L.A.
</P>
<P>
   That's why we'd like to offer our Ultimate Delegates Guide To
Los Angeles, an ``ideal'' scenario on how to enjoy your stay in the
nation's smoggiest _ check that _ make that second smoggiest city.
See, everything looks brighter already.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free to imitate this itinerary, although, as our lawyers
urged us to point out, we're not responsible for anyone who
actually runs into O.J. Simpson in their travels.
</P>
<P>
   TODAY
</P>
<P>
   _3 p.m. Check into Westin Bonaventure. As you ride the glass
elevator with four reporters, be prepared to answer the same three
questions:
</P>
<P>
   1) Can Gore win?
</P>
<P>
   2) Any idea where the really good strip clubs are?
</P>
<P>
   3) Who will be the last castaway remaining on ``Surivivor''?
</P>
<P>
   This is a good time to work up you're best ``no comment'' or
launch into an answer so longwinded the reporters will go pester
somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   _3:45 p.m. As you emerge from hotel lobby onto downtown streets
be ready to dodge protesters rallying against the Gap and Banana
Republic and their alleged sweatshop practices. Make sure to untuck
your charcoal pique polo shirt so as to cover the Banana Republic
label on your Smithfield chinos.
</P>
<P>
   _5:30 p.m. Go to Shutters for wine tasting held by Napa County
congressman Mike Thompson. A little advice: Immediately hit the bar
in order to beat Ted Kennedy to the punch (so to speak).
</P>
<P>
   _ 8 p.m. Head to the People For the American Way dinner at
Beverly Hilton to chow down, but be prepared to duck if a fight
breaks out between Vice presidential pick and self-proclaimed
``culture warrior'' Sen. Joseph Lieberman and liberal producer and
free-speech advocate Norman Lear after Lieberman keeps harping on
how terrible ``Maude'' was. Luckily, Carol O'Connor will be there
to tell both of them to ``stifle it.''
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY
</P>
<P>
   _ 9 a.m. While breakfasting in the hotel restaurant beware of
reporters and Internet geeks who attempt to extrapolate your
preference for decaffeinated coffee into a treatise about how the
Democratic party is not as energetic and fun-loving as it once was.
With any luck Carol O'Connor will be there to tell the pests to
``stifle it.''
</P>
<P>
   _Noon: Go to California Gov. Gray Davis's luncheon at Union
Station but don't get on any trains or subways. You could end up at
Universal's CityWalk or even Santa Clarita for the rest of the day
_ or even the rest of your stay in town. _6 p.m. Ignore the boring
convention speeches by going to a reception hosted by Recording
Industry Association of America honoring Maryland congressman
Stenny Hoyer and his efforts to shut down Napster and keep music
``outrageously overpriced.''
</P>
<P>
   _10 p.m. _ At the ``Soul Train'' party at Paramount Studios be
prepared to call it a night after Sen. Barbara Boxer makes like
``Seinfeld's'' Elaine when ``Love Rollercoaster'' comes on.
</P>
<P>
   _11 p.m. _ As you return to hotel to watch a taped broadcast of
Clintons speaking on ``prosperity and progress'' be sure to gaze
out window at National Homeless Convention at Dome Village.
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   _10 a.m. to 2 p.m. _ It's time to enjoy something of the city's
diverse culture. For a mere $500, take an organized bus trip to the
Hsi Lai Buddhist temple in Hacienda Heights. Be content in your
newfound faith and knowing _ as an accompanying brochure notes _
that ``this is NOT a Democratic National Committee fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   _5 p.m _. Enjoy yourself at happy hour with Irish delegates at
Jonathan Club. Carrol O'Connor is the designated driver.
</P>
<P>
   _8 p.m. _ Next up is Congresswoman Loretta Sanchez's planned
party for the Hispanic Coalition at the Playboy Mansion. But
beaware that the event, which has already run into image problems,
could run into more. There are rumors that George !ita!P. _ Bush
(the ``Ricky Martin of the GOP'' and nephew to George !ital!W _ and
grandson of George !ital!H. _) might crash the soiree and start
monopolizing the babes.
</P>
<P>
   _9:30 p.m. _ Then it's time to skip over to the Universal
Amphitheatre for the Hispanic Talent Showcase at Universal
Amphitheatre. This is as good as time as any to find yourself stuck
behind a slow-speed police chase on the Hollywood Freeway. Just sit
back an marvel at how all those TV copters manage not to smash into
each other. By the time you arrive, though, the concert's over so
you decide to return to Hef's and the event that's being delicately
described as the ``Gorgy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Midnight: _ About this time the president and Senator Kennedy
show up (even if the party gets canceled, they'll show up), and you
decide that maybe a good night sleep would be better than getting
caught up in Bill and Ted's Excellent Adventure. Than again maybe
you don't.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   _9 a.m. _ Begin your day at the House of Blues where United Auto
Workers host party honoring Michigan congressman John Dingell.
Anyone driving an American-made car to the event gets a dollar off
the valet parking!
</P>
<P>
   _11 a.m. _ Then pop down to Disneyland and get lost in
Fantasyland, which, afterall, isn't much different than a political
convention.
</P>
<P>
   _6 p.m. _ As Karenna Gore Schiff and Joe ``Let's Put `Friends'
In Movie Theaters'' Lieberman make nominating speeches for Gore,
duck out early to watch ``Survivor'' in your hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY
</P>
<P>
   _8 a.m. _ Waking up hung over and still bitter that right-winger
Rudy remains alive on ``Survivor,'' take your frustrations out by
heckling protesters on the street.
</P>
<P>
   _10 a.m. _ With Clinton, Kennedy, Hef and George P. Bush on the
loose, you realize you haven't found a date to Barbra Streisand's
concert tonight. Left with the unhappy prospect of actually having
to, gulp, actually go to the convention for the afternoon, you opt
instead to go back to your room and take a nap.
</P>
<P>
   _5 p.m. _ Refreshed, you give it one last try at Young
Democrats' happy hour at McCormick &AMP; Schmick's and get lucky. Now
you hope all those contributions (we mean donations, we mean ...
oh, whatever) _ and newfound Buddhist faith _ will put you on the
guest list for Babs' post-convention show at the Shrine.
</P>
<P>
   _6:30 p.m. _ As the vice president rambles on about ``Al Gore's
Vision For the Future,'' point out the pretty balloons overhead to
your date and remind her that Barbra will be on soon.
</P>
<P>
   _8 p.m. _ As you arrive at the Shrine you may think it's a a bit
gauche for the doorman to be holding out a bag asking for your
jewelry, but remember, you can always buy another Rolex and won't
be able to hear Streisand again until her !ital!next _ farewell
tour.
</P>
<P>
   _10 p.m. _ Babs caps the evening with ``Happy Days Are Here
Again.'' (You wonder if ``Send in the Clowns'' wouldn't have been
better?) Walking out, you wipe away a tear as your five day stay in
L.A. comes to an end. Then, of course, you can't get a cab. So you
walk back to your hotel. As L.A.'s finest round up the last
protesters, you find yourself humming ``The Way You Were.'' The
convention has already become misty, water-colored memories for
you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
