<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT &LR;      08-11 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON'S MANAGERS SLOG THROUGH 12-HOUR DAYS _ AND WIRES _ TO COPE
WITH STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leslie Macpherson fumbled with her tool belt as she
walked into the room crammed with wires. She had never seen so many
in her life. Blue ones, white ones. Wires as thin as toothpicks,
wires as thick as thumbs. Thousands of them.
</P>
<P>
   In her management job with Verizon Communications, the country's
largest local telephone company, Macpherson kept track of utilities
regulations imposed by state agencies. She wore a suit and sat at a
desk. She met with government officials. She wrote reports. She did
not carry around pliers or orange telephone handsets.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Verizon's unionized employees began their
strike on Sunday. Macpherson is now temporarily a technician, and a
technician must know her wires. In this Verizon office in midtown
Manhattan, the wires are housed in metal frames the size of small
sailboats. After several days on the job, Macpherson now knows how
to lay a wire to help set up a dial tone for a new customer. A dial
tone. The fundamental product created and sold by Verizon and its
260,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's fed from the switch,'' she said, waving toward
a bundle of wires. ``I think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are cables,'' she said, pointing to a thick gray sheath.
``They go underground to the cosmic frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Cosmic frame?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me about the cosmic frame,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Macpherson is one of about 30,000 managers who have been filling
in for more than 86,000 unionized workers at Verizon offices from
Maine to Virginia, pinch-hitting on union jobs that range from
answering 411 calls to fixing aerial cables.
</P>
<P>
   And after several days of the work, many of them said that while
they were not siding with the unions, they had a new appreciation
for the work of its members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of respect for the people who do it,
having done it myself,'' said Diana Barnes, who was transferred
from the department that places advertising for Verizon to work as
a directory assistance operator. ``So some good comes out of bad,
if management appreciates the workers more.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Macpherson and Barnes were sent from Verizon's New York
headquarters to work at the company's largest directory assistance
center in the city, on 38th Street between Second and Third Avenues
in Manhattan. An informal, school's-out atmosphere had descended on
the place. Offices usually bustling with a dozen people were
staffed by one or two managers. Fill-in workers sauntered in
wearing jeans and sneakers. Supervisors who usually sat at desks
ran around the hallways with tools, doing double duty as bosses and
the bossed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, union workers, represented by the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers, have been less than thrilled with managers filling their
jobs. The police have received reports of egg throwing and
vandalism. On a recent afternoon, several people in a picket line
outside the 38th Street building yelled at a woman walking in
through the front doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, don't go in there,'' shouted Arthur Treisman, a telephone
operator waving a union placard. ``Don't go in there! Scab!''
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Garrido, a technician picketing along side Treisman, said
he felt insulted that managers were working union jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think none of them are qualified to do what we do,'' Garrido
said. ``Most of them were educated in college, but they're not
technically inclined.''
</P>
<P>
   While union shifts are usually eight hours, most managers have
been working 12-hour days to compensate for being short staffed.
After 13 days, if the strike lasts that long, they are to get a
one-day break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, the work out of this office is tremendous, and
we do the best we can with what we have,'' said Deborah Torruellas,
who supervised Macpherson and other frame technicians. ``Over the
long term, one would see a negative change, because the people here
are working 12 hours a day, seven days a week, and it just won't
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Torruellas has been with the company for 22 years, working her
way up through half a dozen departments to become a manager. When
her department's 38 frame technicians went on strike, she was
forced to train eight managers from other parts of the company to
do the jobs of the striking frame technicians. The recruits had to
learn in hours what it sometimes took months to master, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike has also meant that Torruellas had to strap on a tool
belt and work on the frames herself, something she had not done
regularly for a decade. ``At least I'm off my desk and on the
floor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jobs that needed filling were operator positions.
Three floors above Torruellas, about 30 people sat in gray cubicles
wearing headsets. The calls for directory assistance came in one
after another, an endless stream of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Shapiro was trying to type the word Coronet into his
computer. A caller wanted the number of the movie theater by that
name. Shapiro tapped out the letters slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spell it for me,'' he told his caller. ``I'm a manager here. I
don't have typing skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro usually manages computer programmers in the White
Plains, N.Y., office who are developing Verizon's e-commerce
systems. In his operator's cubicle he sat for 12 hours with only
three breaks _ 30 minutes for lunch and two 15-minute periods. He
had taken his shoes off. On his desk sat an apple, a cookie and a
bottle of water.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro, who also worked as an operator during the last strike,
which lasted for two days in August 1998, has been averaging 900
calls per 12-hour shift. (A trained directory assistance operator
takes more than 1,000 calls in an eight-hour shift.) During a
recent five-minute period, callers asked Shapiro for the numbers of
a pizzeria, a doughnut shop, a pharmacy, United Pacel Service and a
jeweler in Manhattan named Gumuchjian Fils.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really gives you an appreciation of the work that the union
folks do,''he said. ``It's invaluable.''
</P>
<P>
   Three floors below, Macpherson pulled out her pliers and stared
at the wires snaking over the metal girders. So many wires. During
the last strike, at least, she had been able to hit the road for
two days as a delivery driver. But it could be worse, she said,
shaking her head as she thought about the managers who had to work
as operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm OK with this,'' she said. ``I'm not complaining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
