<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final Four will remain in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ NCAA Final Four basketball tournaments will be played
in Atlanta despite calls from civil rights activists that they be
moved because the Confederate emblem is part of the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-member executive committee of university presidents,
meeting in Indianapolis, said they would continue to monitor the
situation and did not rule out the possibility of revisiting the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Christian Leadership Conference's president, Martin
Luther King III, has requested that the men's basketball Final Four
in 2002 and 2007 and the women's basketball Final Four in 2003 be
taken out of the Georgia Dome if the state does not remove the
Confederate emblem from its flag.
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact of the three events is estimated to be more
than $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This a matter of considerable concern to this committee and
this organization,'' said NCAA Executive Committee Chairman Charles
Wethington, who is president of the University of Kentucky. ``Our
paramount concern is for the welfare of student-athletes who are
asked to travel to specific locales to participate in NCAA
championships. So we will continue to watch these issues closely.''
</P>
<P>
   The flag question is to go before the Georgia Legislature when
it next meets in January. Meanwhile, there is nothing the city can
do about it, said Gary Stokan, president of the Atlanta Sports
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Stokan called Tom Jernstadt, executive vice
president of the NCAA, to explain Atlanta's position. ``He
understood where we were coming from and just asked us to keep him
up to date,'' said Stokan. ``(Atlanta) won the bid based on all our
qualifications. This is just something we'll have to deal with in
the legislative process.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes has said that barring the Final Four tournament
``would not be productive to the ongoing debate about Georgia's
flag.''
</P>
<P>
   But Julian Bond, the NAACP's national board chairman, was not
happy about the NCAA's decision. ``The Confederate swastika is an
abomination and incites hatred, and we think it ought not to be
displayed at any public event,'' he said. The executive committee
also voted to keep the first and second rounds of the men's
basketball tournament in Greenville, S.C., in 2002. The NAACP and
the National Association of Basketball Coaches called for that
tournament to be moved because the Confederate flag, while no
longer flying over the South Carolina Capitol, is still displayed
on the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
