A9247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TXOUT-BIRDS0812-COX     08-11 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-BIRDS0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feast for the eyes
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Birding is an inexpensive, simple and exciting
way to increase your time outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   It can turn a park into an oasis or make four dull hours in a
deer stand pass faster than they ever have.
</P>
<P>
   There are no seasons other than the ones imposed by the birds
themselves. Bird-watching works everywhere, from your back yard to
wilderness areas. And if you're a beginner, you probably are
further along than you might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started, I was amazed at how many birds I already
knew,'' said John Szypula, executive director of the Audubon
Society in Austin. ``I knew blue jays and cardinals and chickadees.
And most people already know quite a bit about it. Once they get
started, their interest really perks up.''
</P>
<P>
   Audubon is the big bird of resource and bird conservation
organizations, with established chapters in Travis County, Bastrop,
Bexar County and Waco. Those local chapters provide the perfect
setting for new birders who want to get started or serious folks
who want to interact with other longtime bird watchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of just taking that first step,'' Szypula said.
``Once you get started, you can find a place to go and people who
are willing to help.'' Audubon maintains a Web site with space
dedicated to Texas birds. It gives birders a place to ask for help
or just find out which birds are being seen where in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texbirds is a good place for serious birders and you can get
information on trends, sightings and it's a good place to go
because there are people there who can help you,'' Szypula said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is the place for birding, boasting more species (more than
600) than any other state. ``It's the birdiest state and the best
place to get started,'' Szypula said. ``Right now is a great time,
too, because you've got fall migrations starting. The sheer numbers
and diversity of bird life in Texas is wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Szypula offered these tips for getting started in birding in
Texas:
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a good field guide, especially one that's more local than
not. It will help you find birds that you're more likely to see in
your area,'' he said. Audubon publishes field guides, as does the
American Bird Conservancy. There also are Texas bird guides that
can be purchased in local book stores.
</P>
<P>
   A mentor can help with getting into the sport and with learning
how to identify birds, or even setting up feeding stations around
your house. Joining a local chapter is a good way to find mentoring
help.
</P>
<P>
   Binoculars help. They don't have to be super expensive, since
you're working at close ranges, but they can help in identifying
birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about birding is that you can start in your own
back yard,'' Szypula said, ``and you'll see all sorts of stuff.
Then you can work to more serious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Audubon offers help for youngsters who want to get started
birding, with more than 4,000 Central Texas youngsters already
involved in its Junior Audubon program. Information is available
at: http://www.audubon.org/chapter/tx/tx/jr/. Information for
adults can be found at http://www.audubon.org/chapter/tx/tx/ or by
calling (512) 306-0225.
</P>
<P>
   The Audubon information Web site for birds and sightings is
http://www.audubon.org/chapter/tx/tx/birds.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
