<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-DOVES0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A love for doves
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Your shooting ability aside, dove season is
always good in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The number of birds in any given field might vary, but overall
hunting success varies very little, according to Jay Roberson, dove
program leader for the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   Texas hunters numbered about 390,000 last year, and each spent
an average of 1.3 days in the field. They killed about 11 birds per
person, not bad in a sport in which the national average is about
one dove per every five shells.
</P>
<P>
   But the size of the bag is only a portion of the attraction of
dove hunting in Texas. There's the sport, of course, and the
fellowship of being outdoors with other hunters. Then you have the
privilege of eating the doves you kill.
</P>
<P>
   However, the biggest attraction of dove hunting might be the
fact that the Sept. 1 opening day each year means the long, hot
summer of waiting is over. We can finally take the guns out of the
closet, dust off the old game bag and warm up the retriever.
Hunting season is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting success to jump up this year over last year,''
Roberson said. Much of that success could be attributed to rain, or
the lack of it. ``Water holes will be important because of the
drought,'' he said. ``And the places that have been able to
irrigate or have gotten enough rain for crops to grow will attract
even more birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Doves are one game bird that must find water every day. They
will descend in great numbers on very small watering holes when
there's nothing else available. Afternoon hunts, especially, are
good around water holes and even better during years when there
hasn't been much rain.
</P>
<P>
   August storms could fill tanks and put enough water in cattle
tracks to spread doves out over large areas, but if the rains don't
come, be sure to have a water hole on your list of hunting spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dove hunting is just lke the real estate business: location,
location, location,'' Roberson said. ``The guys who scout and are
fortunate enough to have leases in areas with good water and food
supplies will have the most doves and the best hunting. You like to
have both of those close to roosting and resting areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson did point out that dove populations throughout the
central section of the country have been in a slight decline since
1966, though the problem has been less noticeable in Texas. There
is enough concern that federal officials have put states on notice
that unless the trend reverses itself, there could be shorter
seasons or smaller bags in the future.
</P>
<P>
   TPWD biologists have begun looking at ways to determine just how
real the problem is and whether it represents a decline in numbers
or a shift in geography for doves. ``We're gearing up to do some
studies on what's happening in Texas,'' Roberson said.
</P>
<P>
   The department will study whether the long-term routes it uses
for its spring call counts could have lost enough habitat to have
shifted nesting doves into other areas. Satellite imagery is one
way in which the problem could be studied, Roberson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem is real, but I'm not comfortable at this
time in saying what it is,'' he said. Changes in agricultural usage
could be having an impact on doves, as could urbanization of
certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   All of which doesn't mean much when shooting time rolls around.
You're either in the doves or you aren't. If you are, then the
trick is to hit the ones you shoot at.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a couple of tips:
</P>
<P>
   1) Use quality shells. Try 7 1/2s with at least an ounce of
shot, for instance, instead of cheaper shells that might be the
special of the season. You'll get better performance, more shot in
the air and kill more birds.
</P>
<P>
   2) Adjust your choke to the conditions. Afternoon water hole
shooting can easily accommodate improved or even skeet chokes. For
pass shooting and windy conditions, you'll probably want to use
modified for longer shots.
</P>
<P>
   3) Pick one shot you're comfortable with and try to use it as
much as possible. You might not fire the gun as much, but your
percentages will go up.
</P>
<P>
   4) Shoot your shotgun ahead of time. You need to know if it's
shooting high or low, left or right and you need to get your eye
and shoulder into condition for lots of shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
