u s BC-TXOUT-LICENSE0812-COX     08-11 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-LICENSE0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's good to be an outdoors know-it-all
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The first license I ever bought cost a quarter,
and I didn't even need it unless I was going to hunt deer.
</P>
<P>
   Squirrels and birds were free and the two deer tags _ bucks only
_ were just a vanity thing, since there aren't that many in the
river bottoms where we grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed since then. The license costs more, of
course, even though it's still fairly cheap. On the license now
there are five deer tags, four turkey tags, a redfish tag, your
federal Harvest Information Program data and a partridge in a pear
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Life's more complicated, and so is the Texas hunting and fishing
license. The standard license now costs $19 for hunting or fishing.
Residents can buy a combination license for $32. The best buy,
though, is the $49 Super Combo license, which includes licenses and
all stamps except for the federal migratory game bird stamp.
</P>
<P>
   This year's license list also includes a $25 Senior Super Combo
for residents 65 and older. Seniors also can buy the $6 special
resident license for hunting or fishing. That same license is
available for residents 17 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   Licenses are required of any individual who hunts any animal or
bird in the state. That would include frogs, for instance, as well
as feral animals such as pigs.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Parks and Wildlife Department publishes an annual
hunting booklet that details license fees and requirements, as well
as county-by-county regulations for hunting seasons and bag limits.
It's a good thing to study the booklet, especially for the counties
in which you hunt and for general regulations that might affect
you.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few things you'll find in the book:
</P>
<P>
   One fully feathered wing must be retained on all migratory game
birds except doves until the bird has reached its final
destination. All birds imported from Mexico must have a wing
attached.
</P>
<P>
   Deer tags must remain with the carcass, not the head. If you
take the head to a taxidermist, leave tags and permits with the
meat. The head should have a wildlife resource document, noting the
hunter, license number, ranch, who receives it and other
information. A sample document is available in the back of the
annual booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics showing how to properly measure a fish or a crab, as
well as diagrams for puncturing the air bladder on a saltwater fish
so that it can be released alive.
</P>
<P>
   Identification tips for yellow, white, striped and hybrid
striped bass. You look at the tongue, and the booklet tells you how
to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TXOUT-MEASURES0812-CO     08-11 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-MEASURES0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Techniques that will trigger a good shot
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Successful shotgun shooting is so simple.
</P>
<P>
   But if that's the case, why don't more people do it well?
Because they make some simple mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   According to one successful shooter and teacher, there are three
fairly easy problems to identify, even if it's not always easy to
do away with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first thing, the most common thing people do is they
stop the gun when the trigger is pulled,'' said Leon Measures, who
has developed a basic shooting course called ``Shoot Where You
Look.'' He uses air rifles and repetition to teach better shooting.
</P>
<P>
   However, no shooting course, no finely tuned shotgun and no
fancy clothes can make a load of shot intersect with a flying
target if the gun isn't moving before and after the trigger is
pulled. Mind overcomes muscle, in a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes back to the first gun you ever shot, which was
probably a BB gun,'' Measures said. ``Somebody taught you from the
beginning that you have to put your head down on the stock, close
one eye, line up the front and rear sights and hold that barrel
still if you want to hit anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that that first BB gun or .22 rifle came with a bunch
of bullets probably means those shooting steps have moved past
instruction and become instinct, Measures said. ``I have to teach
you to unlearn that instinctive movement and creat a habit of not
stopping the gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Measures has drills to do just that, and he teaches those in his
course. Almost any shooter, though, can work on the problem if he
knows he has it and if he does it in the proper way. All of which
brings us to the second problem: lack of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, when dove season starts, haven't had that gun out
of the closet since the last shot they fired last year,'' Measures
said. ``There's not much way they're going to hit anything with it.
You wouldn't think of just going out and running a marathon without
practicing, but people try to do that with a shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Repetition doesn't necessarily equal practice, though. Shooting
thousands of rounds at live or clay targets without the proper form
and motion can mean you're doing nothing more than locking in bad
habits. Good instruction from the beginning helps teach the right
foot placement, how to mount the shotgun and keep the gun moving.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Measures wants shooters to point, not aim. The shotgun
should follow the eye, not the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking at the front bead on a shotgun, if you can
see that clearly, you cannot see the target and you won't hit what
you're shooting at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Measures doesn't worry about dominant eye or whether a shooter
is left- or right-handed. The key is building a repetitive motion
that allows the gun and eye to function within a field that helps
the shot intercept the target.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
