<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-POINT0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powers: `I did it to create some opportunities'
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Shorty Powers is no shrinking violet.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you'd better WANT him to have your phone number,
because if he thinks you can help him get disabled individuals
outdoors, he's going to call. And call again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas resident, himself a paraplegic in a wheelchair,
founded POINT, Paraplegics On Independent Nature Trips. Through
hard work and sheer force of will, Powers has pushed the cause to
the forefront in Texas. He's been able to involve the Texas Parks
and Wildlife Department and other organizations in offering outdoor
opportunities of every kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it to create some opportunities for physically
challenged people that they might not have otherwise,'' Powers
said. ``They might not have uncles or dads to hunt and fish and can
take them.''
</P>
<P>
   With POINT involved, Powers said, those with physical challenges
know there will be other individuals who understand their special
needs or the obstacles they might face in getting into a boat or a
deer stand. ``They know things are going to be set up for them,''
he said. ``It's a better environment and a chance to be around
people they know.''
</P>
<P>
   POINT has been around for more than 20 years, but Powers still
hasn't reached the plateau he would like to. ``We still don't have
a place we can call our own,'' he said. ``We'd like to have it for
a whole season and bring people in to hunt. We need a place to hunt
ducks and deer that's centrally located.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization has been able to secure one such location in
East Texas, on Caddo Lake near Marshall. It's small, though, and
doesn't allow the numbers of people Powers would like.
</P>
<P>
   Powers already does fishing and hunting activities for children
and adults, as well as other outdoors activities. There are
chapters in Houston, Austin and Dallas. ``We obviously are looking
at San Antonio and Corpus Christi,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   For information about POINT and its activities, contact Powers
at (214) 827-7404. In Austin, call Chuck Dahkle, (512) 793-3120 or
Mike Haynes, (512) 867-5141.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
