<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ``KILL THE UMP!'' JUST DOESN'T CUT IT
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   If you ask me (and even if you
don't), the main thing wrong with major league baseball today is
not exorbitant salaries, greedy owners or the fact that you can't
afford to bring your family to a game without taking out a second
mortgage on your house.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The main thing wrong with baseball is hecklers. There just don't
seem to be any good ones around anymore. When I say ``hecklers,'' I
am not referring to the drunken thugs in the bleachers who throw
batteries, bullets and golf balls at opposing players.
</P>
<P>
   That is not heckling; that is assault. Good hecklers hurl words,
not deadly missiles. A good heckle is caustic and pointed, but not
so mean that the player is likely to leap into the stands or throw
a ball at your head. A good heckle should get a laugh from the fans
sitting near you; it should not make them run for cover.
</P>
<P>
   A good heckle should be creative and show a little imagination.
Yelling ``kill the umpire'' is neither and, considering how twitchy
everybody is about gun violence these days, it may even get you
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Some heckles are so bad they actually make you feel sorry for
the ballplayer, even a ballplayer you would otherwise dislike. I
was at a Tampa Bay Devil Rays/Baltimore Orioles game a few weeks
ago. We were seated in right field, behind ``controversial''
Baltimore slugger Albert Belle. (When sportswriters use the word
``controversial,'' that means there is unanimity of opinion that
the player is a jerk.) When he first broke into the major leagues
and before he became ``controversial,'' Belle went by his given
name, Joey. The fans next to us thought it would be incredibly
clever to chant ``Jo-ey, Jo-ey'' at Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Not just once, but for the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   This got old after about the third ``Jo-ey,'' so we moved to a
different part of the stadium where the most vocal heckling came
from a woman who was snoring with a book on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be this way. There is now a Web site,
www.heckledepot.com, where fans can stock up on dozens of clever
(and not so clever) heckles to hurl at players, umpires, managers
and other fans the next time they go to the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of umpires, heckles are usually variations on three
themes: The ump is blind, the ump is on the take and/or the ump is
grossly overweight.
</P>
<P>
   Some possibilities include:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``When your dog barks twice, it's a strike!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hey, ump! The manager called! Your uniform is ready!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hey, ump! Move around! You're killin' the grass!''
</P>
<P>
   Heckles directed at pitchers usually focus on a lack of control,
a lack of speed and/or a tendency to give up a lot of long home
runs. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What the matter? You need a running start?''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``There's a fight at the bat rack.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``With this guy pitching, the ground crew will have to drag
the warning track after the fifth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitters probably absorb the most heckles, especially when
they're in a slump and are psychologically fragile. Lack of power,
low batting average and unenthusiastic running are common themes:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You couldn't hit sand if you fell off a camel!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You've had fewer hits than Vanilla Ice!''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Run! What are you doin'? Draggin' a piano?''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are your miscellaneous heckles, directed at whomever
happens to be handy:
</P>
<P>
   To a vendor: ``Watch out! He's sellin' corked hot dogs!''
</P>
<P>
   To other fans: ``If you throw all your peanuts at me, what are
you going to feed your mother?''
</P>
<P>
   To an ugly player: ``Did your mother feed you with a
slingshot?''
</P>
<P>
   Heckling is an integral part of baseball, like spitting and
crotch-scratching. Let's keep the tradition alive.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
