u p BC-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-11 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PONDERING THE IMPACT OF BUCHANAN AND NADER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The five-party system of Democrats, Republicans,
Greens and two Reform parties is something new in American
politics, and right now it is helping Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
in important ways.
</P>
<P>
   The fracture in the Reform Party has dampened whatever slim
hopes the ex-Republican Pat Buchanan had for weakening Bush from
his right. And the energetic campaign by the Green Party's Ralph
Nader, at least for the moment, is helping Bush maintain his lead
over Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the election is not right now, and the fluctuations
in the polls reinforce the impression that it is far from the minds
of most Americans, even those who state a preference. And Buchanan
and Nader have a potential for hurting Bush, too _ Buchanan with
social conservatives and Nader with diehard campaign reform voters,
the old John McCain crowd. But not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last fall, when Buchanan's romancing of the Reform
Party seemed to threaten Bush? Well, his need to reinvent himself
as an authentic Reform Party man distanced him from his core
anti-abortion, anti-homosexual, anti-immigrant base. And even
though Buchanan tried to return to his first love Thursday with a
statement of social value principles, Bush has used the last 10
months to fill the conservatives' dance card, and stir their dreams
of Supreme Court justices who will reverse Roe v. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   The impending weeks or months of dispute over who gets the
Reform Party's $12.6 million in federal funds _ even if Buchanan
ultimately prevails over his rival, John Hagelin _ mean that he
will be handicapped in using the money strategically. Lots of
important television time, after all, has already been bought.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Nader, ranging between 5 and 9 points in national
polls and thus plainly able to tip some battleground states like
Michigan, Washington Wisconsin and maybe California to Bush by
draining support from Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Nader and his backers say that is not their purpose.
And Gore and his backers say that won't be his effect, eventually.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore folks are whistling past the graveyard. The threat
to Gore is the real meaning of the Nader campaign. Right now there
is no question that two-thirds or more of Nader's backers, in state
after state, are coming out of the vice president's potential
voters. And some Gore backers outside his campaign itself admit the
problem. Robert F. Kennedy, Jr., for example, wrote in an Op-Ed
piece in Thursday's New York Times that ``A vote for Mr. Nader is a
vote for Mr. Bush and environmentalists who join his personal
crusade risk marginalizing the conservation movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader takes on that argument on two fronts. First, he says he is
running to win, which is about as realistic as General Motors'
defense of the Corvair when Nader attacked it as unsafe in 1965.
Second, he says that while Gore might be a teeny bit better than
Bush on the environment and a couple of other things, the
differences are too small to matter.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars of third parties argue that such candidacies always
fade. John Anderson went from 15 percent to 6 percent in 1980.
Henry Wallace declined similarly in 1948. And even Ross Perot, the
eccentric billionaire who founded the Reform Party in 1992, dropped
from about a third of the vote in polls to 19 percent on election
days, and after spending $56 million.
</P>
<P>
   John Bibby, a retired political scientist at the University of
Wisconsin-Milwaukee and a student of third parties, said: ``Nader
looks like he could do respectably now. My guess is his vote would
go down as you get closer to the election. The closer the election,
the more significant is the wasted vote argument.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``When it comes down to it, you want your vote to be
meaningful.'' A Gore strategist agreed. He said: ``I don't see
Nader being like Perot in being able to communicate. He won't spend
$56 million.'' And he argued, ``As people get to know Gore better,
I think it's going to make it a lot easier to see him as someone
who fights for people and will be on their side.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Republican strategist was unconvinced, arguing that Nader
would hold on to enough support to be a factor. ``He has a
long-standing reputation among a core group of voters he doesn't
need ads to purchase,'' the strategist said.'' He added that
because of his consumer record, Nader ``gets a little bit of an
earned media ride, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, and Buchanan, too, also argue that their differences from
the Republicans and Democrats are enabling them to make voters out
of non-voters. Nader sometimes argues that even if Gore loses, the
Green Party's missionary efforts will help elect more Democrats to
the House, and make Rep. Dick Gephardt speaker.
</P>
<P>
   That's what third party candidates always say. Curtis Gans, head
of the Committee for the Study of the American Electorate and a
student of voter turnout, said he saw only ``a slight chance that
Nader will stir some increase among young people,'' and no
indication that he was bringing in other potential voters.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Patterson, head of a Harvard study of ``the Vanishing
Voter'' that uses weekly polling to learn what is behind low
participation, said he saw no evidence that either Nader or
Buchanan ``really seems to be popping'' and exciting voters.
</P>
<P>
   There is another target for Nader _ the Perot voter who reacted
in 1992 to Perot's criticism of the way campaign cash and lobbying
fees dictate results in Washington. This week Nader started showing
a television commercial (with an authentic old politics touch, his
staff refused to say where the modest purchase of advertising time
was taking place or how much was spent). It parodied recent ads for
Mastercard with lines like ``Grilled tenderloin for fund-raiser:
$1,000 a plate'' and ``Finding out the truth: priceless.''
</P>
<P>
   But clever as that ad is, the Nader campaign says it plans to
spend no more than $5 million on commercials for the entire 2000
campaign. While ads for which little time was bought, like the
Willie Horton ad to promote Bush's father in 1988, have sometimes
become effective by being shown often on news programs, there is no
indication that will happen with Nader's commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The only real money available for the outsider candidates is the
$12.6 million for the Reform Party. Even if Buchanan gets it, the
Bush campaign dismisses him as meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman, said ``The sun has set on Pat
Buchanan's candidacy and will not rise again. Pat Buchanan is old
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Federal Election Commission can speed up its
normal pace and get a check in the mail before the 2004 campaign,
Buchanan could be at least an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Maisel, co-author with Bibby of the 1998 book ``Two
Parties or More,'' said he thought if Buchanan spent his money
wisely, in a few small states with big anti-abortion movements, he
might still matter. The Colby College professor of government said
Nader might fade faster. He said, ``I think there is more
ideological zealotry on the part of the anti-abortion people than
there is on the part of labor and the environmentalists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 1956EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
