<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) DLC
SPELLS SUCCESS FOR CENTRIST DEMOCRATS  
 By CARL HULSE  
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   WASHINGTON _ Evidently a J.D.,
Ph.D or M.B.A. is no longer the ticket to political success in the
Democratic party _ candidates should instead have DLC after their
names.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newly anointed vice presidential candidate Joe Lieberman is the
current chairman of the Democratic Leadership Council, the centrist
political coalition that also counts President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore among its prominent members.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore and Lieberman are elected, it would extend DLC dominance
over the White House to 12 years, quite an achievement for a group
formed in the mid-1980s to give Southern Democrats a voice to
counter what they saw as the increasingly liberal posture of the
national party.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gore, a founding member, the roll call of DLC political
figures includes the late Lawton Chiles of Florida, Louisiana Sen.
John Breaux, Florida Sen. Bob Graham, former Sen. Sam Nunn of
Georgia, Virginia Sen. Chuck Robb and dozens of other House members
and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly have created the formula that helps win
elections,'' said Matthew Frankel, a spokesman for the group. ``The
DLC is an important breeding ground for the new Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the old Democratic party that worried its Southern
members more than a decade ago. They felt politically exposed as
their region became more suburban and Republican while the national
Democratic leadership became more allied with labor, minority
groups and other activists typical of big-city politics. Some
Democrats bolted to the GOP but others stayed and created the DLC.
</P>
<P>
   The group stressed welfare reform, more responsible fiscal
policy, tougher anti-crime laws, stronger defense and other
positions not typically associated with Democrats. It found an
audience and launched Clinton to the White House. In fact, some
analysts equate the compassionate conservatism message of Texas
Gov. George W. Bush with a GOP version of the DLC.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is evidence of the appeal the group has for
politicians outside the South. DLC members say the centrist senator
could make an impact in the region if voters look beyond the fact
that he is from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are trying to get that word out. ``He's just a
Northern Sam Nunn,'' Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes told a rally in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER SIDE OF REFORM
</P>
<P>
   Welfare reform may have been a winning political message for the
DLC, but it is driving up the number of low-income parents without
health insurance in Southern states, according to a new report from
a consumer group.
</P>
<P>
   Families USA blamed the push to reduce the welfare rolls for
jumps in the uninsured in Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, North
Carolina and Tennessee among other states. The group said that
low-income adults moved into the labor market by welfare cutbacks
often lose their Medicaid coverage but end up in low-wage jobs that
don't provide health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of thousands of low-wage working parents are cast
adrift without health care when they do the right thing and find
jobs,'' said Ron Pollack, executive director of the liberal group.
He wants the government to expand Medicaid access to working
families.
</P>
<P>
   SEA TO SHINING SEA
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fritz Hollings of South Carolina is known for making waves
with his independent streak, but he may have hit a new highwater
mark.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has signed into law Hollings' Oceans Acts of
2000, which creates a new commission to undertake a comprehensive
evaluation of the nation's hodgepodge of coastal and ocean
policies. Its findings could lead to an overhaul of fishery
management and environmental regulations much like the work of a
similar panel 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings said the 16-member commission, which will include
oceanographers, policymakers, industry representatives and
conservationists, should ``help us develop consistent national
policies that reflect our country's evolving national relationship
with our oceans and coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA GOES HOLLYWOOD
</P>
<P>
   Southern California already has the Rose Bowl parade, but Los
Angelenos should brace for the Mardi Gras parade planned for the
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana Sen. John Breaux is the host of a mega-event to be
held Tuesday night on the backlot of Paramount Studios. The
corporate-sponsored party will feature such entertainers as Rockin'
Dopsie Jr. and the Zydeco Twisters and the Storyville Stompers from
New Orleans. Even laid-back LA might find it hard to resist that
sort of bayou boogie.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief of the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
