<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-JAPAN-RATES-ART-NYT &LR;      08-11 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-RATES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFYING THE GOVERNMENT, BANK OF JAPAN RAISES INTEREST RATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Forcefully asserting its view that Japan's economy is
now growing firmly after years of false starts, the central bank
raised interest rates Friday for the first time in a decade,
defying strong pressure from government officials to keep borrowing
costs close to zero.
</P>
<P>
   In what was described as a difficult all-day meeting, the Bank
of Japan's nine-member board voted to abandon the zero-interest
policy it had adopted in February 1999 as an emergency measure to
keep the economy from slipping further into recession.
</P>
<P>
   While the move by the Bank of Japan had been widely expected, it
nonetheless sent a powerful message about the central bank's view
that the Japanese economy, the world's second-largest, has now
achieved enough momentum to keep expanding. The move also
represented an unprecedented display of independence by the central
bank, which had been given more autonomy under a change in the law
a few years ago but until Friday had never exercised it.
</P>
<P>
   The central bank said it would steer a benchmark rate known as
the overnight call rate _ the interest rate banks charge each other
_ to 0.25 percent from virtually zero.
</P>
<P>
   The official discount rate, which is the largely symbolic rate
on loans the central bank charges to private banks, was left
unchanged at 0.5 percent, a record low.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the first time since 1990 that the central bank had
raised rates, which it had lowered repeatedly in response to
Japan's seesaw pattern of recession and feeble recovery that
characterized much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``At present, Japan's economy is showing clearer signs of
recovery, and this gradual upturn, led mainly by business fixed
investment, is likely to continue,'' the central bank said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the benchmark rate will lead to higher borrowing
costs for consumers and businesses. Even so, the benchmark rate
remains extraordinarily low in this country. The comparable rate in
the United States is 6.5 percent and in Europe it is 4.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the rate increase came after the close of
the financial markets. The benchmark Nikkei index of 225 stocks was
up 141.85 points, or .89 percent, to 16,117.50. The yen was little
changed against the dollar. The markets were not expected to react
much when they reopened on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the central bank's decision drew sharp criticism from
government officials, political leaders and many economists who
have argued that Japan's economy is still too delicate to sustain
an increase in interest rates, no matter how small. Many critics of
the increase view it more as a statement of independence on the
part of the central bank than sound economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Bank of Japan has probably moved too soon in light
of the economic situation,'' said Robert Alan Feldman, chief
economist for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in Tokyo. ``The onus is on
them to demonstrate their decision was correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Bevacqua, senior economist for Commerz Securities in
Tokyo, said the rate increase was ``a brave move but not
necessarily one that the economy justifies.''
</P>
<P>
   While Japan's economy grew 2.5 percent in the first three months
of 2000 and the government projects economic growth this fiscal
year will be 1 percent, double the rate of a year earlier, Bevacqua
said Japan's growth was peaking and would slow.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which early this week denounced any rate
increase as premature, asked the central bank at its meeting Friday
to postpone a decision on rates until next month, when
second-quarter gross domestic product figures will be available,
allowing a better assessment of the country's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
   But the board immediately rejected the request by a majority
vote, the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the meeting, Masaru Hayami, the
central bank's governor, stressed that the zero-rate policy had
been an extraordinary measure meant to ward off deflation _ a
dangerous downward spiral of prices and incomes that can lead to a
full-scale depression. But Hayami said such a policy had to end at
some point and that the deflation threat had passed.
</P>
<P>
   Hayami has long stated the need to raise interest rates, arguing
that the zero-rate policy essentially encourages nearly free
borrowing that keeps money-losing businesses from making painful
cutbacks. It also hurts the incomes of Japan's growing population
of retirees whose savings are barely earning interest.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Hayami had conducted a public relations
campaign of sorts, proclaiming the necessity of raising rates. Many
analysts said he had gone too far to turn back. One central bank
board member who attended Friday's meeting said that Hayami had
convinced most board members that it was their duty to vote for the
rate increase, as a measure not only of their independence but
their legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``All economic data, ranging from corporate investment to jobs
and spending, have gotten better in August and July,'' Hayami said.
``Board members took these data as proof that deflation fears have
dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   At its board meeting last month, the central bank had been
widely expected to lift the zero-rate policy, but the collapse of a
highly indebted retailer, the Sogo Co., sent shudders through the
financial system and the bank decided to maintain the policy while
it monitored the impact of Sogo's failure.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the immediate impact of the rate increase was
likely to be a tightening of credit available to small and
medium-sized businesses, which would increase bankruptcies and
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly vulnerable are the real estate, construction and
retail sectors, which are the most heavily indebted. Higher
interest rates will also make it more costly for the government to
borrow money to feed the extensive spending projects that have
helped keep Japan's economy from faltering even further over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The rate increase puts Japanese banks in a particularly
difficult position. The banks, which have received massive
government aid because of hundreds of billions of dollars worth of
unpaid loans on their books, have promised that they would make
more loans to small and medium-sized businesses. But they will be
hard pressed to keep those promises while raising their loan rates.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the rate increase was mixed in the Japanese business
community. Takashi Imai, chairman of Nippon Steel Corp., told the
Kyodo news service that he found it difficult to understand the
central bank's decision. ``Given personal consumption and prices,
it can hardly be said we have come to a point where we can be
certain that concern for deflation is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yotaro Kobayashi, chairman of the Fuji Xerox Co., welcomed
the rate increase, saying: ``The Japanese economy is now in a very
good shape. The decision is confirmation that concerns about
deflation are gone and that the economic recovery is getting on the
right track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
