<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYFRIEND-THREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS TESTS FOR THREATENING BOYFRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A judge has ordered that Vincent J. Froio Jr. -- whose
arrest last weekend for allegedly breaking into his ex-girlfriend's
apartment, ransacking it, and threatening to kill her was detailed
in The Boston Globe -- be held in custody at a New Hampshire
psychiatric facility until Monday, when he will be transferred to
Bridgewater (Mass.) State Hospital for a 30-day evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mark Summerville ordered the transfer after determining
that the psychiatric facility where Froio was admitted earlier this
week, Elliot Hospital in Manchester, N.H., did not provide adequate
security.
</P>
<P>
   Once Froio's evaluation is complete, his case will be referred
for further review to Summerville, who will then determine whether
to jail him pending trial, or to release him with electronic
monitoring or other security measures.
</P>
<P>
   The move represented a dramatic shift by the judge who last week
had set Froio free on $30,000 bail without electronic monitoring
but with the requirment that he seek treatment in a psychiatric
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Froio, 33, a lawyer with the law firm of Foley, Hoag &AMP; Eliot,
was arrested at about 4:30 a.m. last Saturday after police found
him sitting shirtless and blood-splattered on the front steps of
the trashed apartment of his ex-girlfriend, Angelique Uhlmann.
</P>
<P>
   A former competitive bodybuilder, Froio allegedly broke into the
apartment after smashing the door off its hinges, destroyed much of
Uhlmann's property, and smeared blood throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers who arrived at the apartment said the scene was
so disturbing that they believed they had encountered a homicide,
possibly involving mutilation.
</P>
<P>
   Froio was bleeding from a nearly severed finger when he was
discovered by police. Froio's lawyer, Desmond Fitzgerald, said
Froio cut his finger when he fell while walking to Uhlmann's house
and may have gone to her apartment ``for assistance with his
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Uhlmann, a fourth-year medical student at Tufts, is studying to
be a surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday Froio, apppeared in Boston Municipal Court, where
prosecutors asked Summerville to hold him without bail, arguing
that he was too dangerous to release. Summerville instead set bail
at $30,000, rejecting prosecutors's requests that Froio be tethered
to an electronic bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   Froio made bail and was freed later that day after promising to
check himself into a New Hampshire psychiatric hospital. Because of
a problem finding a bed, he was not admitted to a hospital until
nearly 27 hours after leaving jail.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after learning about Froio's delay in being
admitted, Summerville ordered that his defense attorney provide
additional information about the psychiatric facility where Froio
was admitted.
</P>
<P>
   And, after reviewing that information, Summerville ordered that
Froio be transferred Monday to Bridgewater for a ``competency and
criminal responsibility'' evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly feel better than I did after Monday's result,''
said Uhlmann, who is in hiding. ``Of course my ultimate wish would
be that he was behind bars until the trial, because only that would
give me complete safety. But at least it gives me some comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
