<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9263 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-FOOD-STAMPS-STATES-AR     08-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STAMPS-STATES-ART-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW BURIAL PLOTS AND BINGO CONNECT WITH FOOD STAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Calif., Del., Ind., Minn., Neb., Nev., Ohio, S.D.,
Tenn., Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In California, New York and many other states, people applying
for food stamps are asked if they own a burial plot. Nebraska and
Nevada want to know if applicants have sold their blood, and for
how much. Hawaii demands garage-sale receipts, South Dakota wants
documentation of bingo winnings, and Minnesota, on page 20 of a
36-page eligibility application, asks if anyone in the household
earns money from a paper route.
</P>
<P>
   Food-stamp applications in most states have become so onerous
that they are deterring needy people from applying for the
subsidies, a comprehensive analysis by a national network of food
banks and advocacy groups has found.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the inquiries about income and assets have no connection
to legal requirements for food stamps but are either aggressive
responses to federal mandates to deter fraud or part of recent
state and local efforts to cut welfare costs by eliminating
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   State administrators contend that they are simply complying with
federal pressure to be tight-fisted with taxpayers' money and
properly enforcing the tougher rules passed by Congress in the 1996
welfare overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   But federal officials say that the report, conducted by
America's Second Harvest, the nation's largest food-bank network,
adds to their worries that such stringency may be one reason that
12 million people who need the benefits, and are eligible, are not
getting them.
</P>
<P>
   Food-stamp use is plummeting at a faster rate than can be
explained by economic growth. Since 1996 the number of people using
food stamps has declined to 17.2 million people from 23 million,
though a growing bipartisan consensus now holds that food stamps,
like Medicaid, are supports needed to keep low-wage parents
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes in this program we have not looked at the big
picture,'' Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said in an interview
about the survey, which will be released on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my goal to keep hungry people out of the program _
that's a disgrace,'' Glickman said. ``But it's also my job to keep
fraud down. It's tricky to balance those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, he added, ``is actually helpful. We are going to
continue to work with the states to make sure that the income
limits aren't ridiculous,'' and that anti-fraud techniques are not
``outside the bounds of what we ought to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the new sleuthing methods for countering fraud are
parking-lot espionage in Tennessee, computerized credit checks in
Delaware and Texas, and calls to employers and landlords in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want you to have nothing,'' a disabled woman of 56,
who asked that her name not be used, whispered as she peered at the
question about a burial space in the shabby waiting room of a
food-stamp office in the Harlem area of New York. ``It's none of
their business. You want to tell the truth, but they make it so if
you tell the truth, it don't help.''
</P>
<P>
   When the comment was repeated to the sponsors of the study,
which examined application forms from all 50 states and a sampling
from the United States' 3,143 counties, they said it underlined the
unfairness of such questions, though they are not illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's afraid she'll go hungry if she's honest,'' Deborah Leff,
president of America's Second Harvest, said of the woman's concern.
``Isn't that a mess?''
</P>
<P>
   Though the federal government finances and oversees the
food-stamp program, states administer it, with wide variations. The
shortest application, in Florida, is only a page, but most are more
than 10 pages, and all warn that misleading answers are punishable
by a stiff fine and up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the study found, many questions are unintelligible to the
average applicant, and some are mind-boggling even to the
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you or anyone in your household fleeing from New Jersey?''
Ohio's eight-page application asks. Researchers nicknamed the query
the Soprano Clause, after the television drama about a Mafia
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in Cleveland,'' said Sharon Davis, 39, a single mother
of three who was laid off last month from her job as a machine
operator and had spent most of the afternoon applying for food
stamps. ``Why would they ask if you're from New Jersey?''
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, state administrators contend that all the
questions _ including that one _ reflect local efforts to comply
with a stream of federal dictates, including periodic crackdowns on
fraud, stiff penalties on states that overpay even by $5, and new
rules in the 1996 federal welfare legislation.
</P>
<P>
   To explain the so-called Soprano Clause, for example, Ohio
food-stamp administrators pointed to a provision by Congress in the
1996 legislation. It excludes from the food-stamp program any
fugitive from prosecution of a felony, which in New Jersey is
called a ``high misdemeanor.'' To be on the safe side, said Jon
Allen, a spokesman for the Ohio Department of Job and Family
Services, Ohio added an extra question just to cover New Jersey's
terminology.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, Nebraska, which was fined $1 million for
food-stamp errors in a 1998 federal audit, asks about money from
blood-plasma donations and counts it against a family's food
allotment _ which food-bank analysts say is simply wrong _ because
in 1986 an obscure federal policy memorandum defined such money as
earned income.
</P>
<P>
   As for burial plots, some state administrators justify
questioning elderly applicants about them because a federal
provision notes that only one grave per customer can be discounted
when calculating a household's assets. To be eligible for food
stamps at all, a household cannot have assets of over $2,000, or
$3,000 for senior citizens, including checking and savings accounts
and the value of any car above $4,650.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that some people seeking food stamps have
been turned away or cut off in a push to divert them from welfare _
sometimes illegally, as a federal court found in New York City last
year. Many other people either do not know they are eligible or are
discouraged by the requirements, especially in states that
shortened eligibility to three months instead of a year, which is
allowed by federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Applications take an average of five hours and two visits,
Agriculture Department figures show, and the benefit, only $73 a
month per person on average, can be as low as $10. Ninety percent
of households getting food stamps have income under the poverty
line, or $14,150 for a family of three. Three-quarters have no
countable assets.
</P>
<P>
   Though many longer applications include questions relating to
cash assistance and medical benefits, a recent study in Western and
Southern states found that 78 percent of those seeking food stamps
were not told when they qualified for the other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials are now urging outreach
efforts, and this year for the first time they are offering modest
rewards to states that increase participation. But state
administrators see a certain hypocrisy in the new thrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only message we have heard for years is accuracy; your
error rate is what matters,'' Ann Sessoms, Minnesota's welfare
reform manager, said. ``If you miss a plasma donation, if you miss
a paper route, the state is held liable.''
</P>
<P>
   Only last September the Agriculture Department's quality-control
arm praised the Tennessee Department of Human Services' ``Project
Parking Lot,'' in which Nashville investigators patrol for cars
whose blue-book value exceeds the $4,650 limit. They feed the
license-plate numbers into a computer listing people on the benefit
rolls, and have cut off $3 million to $4 million in benefits as a
result, according to Larry Evitts, the director of investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's crazy,'' said Stephanie Manning, who oversees a
Nashville food pantry that limits aid to three boxes of groceries
every six months. ``You can't eat your car,''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Harris, administrator of food stamps in Nebraska, said that
the dollar limit on cars, raised by only $150 since it was set by
Congress 20 years ago, shows how states get stuck enforcing
obsolete regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's happened to the price of cars,'' Harris said.
``It's like, come on, people!''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest enforcement trend, some states either require
electronic fingerprinting of food-stamp recipients or are planning
it. Texas has contracted with computer information brokers who
provide, among other tidbits, a listing of 10 neighbors who could
be asked about an applicant's circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware pays $2 or $3 an inquiry for credit-card histories on
applicants whose answers seem suspicious to a caseworker. Though
privacy laws make it illegal to use credit information in a
criminal case, William Garfinkel, director of audit at the Delaware
Department of Health and Social Services, said that nothing barred
using it to determine government benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They count everything,'' Anna Santana, a divorced bookkeeper
in Lincoln, Neb., said, citing a $25 gift certificate from her
church for her three children's Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   Before she qualified for food stamps, she added, there were
times when she fed the children first and ate only if they left
something. But her older daughter, then 5, caught on.
</P>
<P>
   ``She started cutting back on what she was eating,'' Santana
recalled. ```I'm not hungry, Mommy, you need to eat, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said some state actions seemed overzealous,
congressional mandates notwithstanding. ``The irony here is that we
don't ask farmers to do anything like we do our food-stamp
recipients,'' Glickman added, referring to federal farm subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   A few states stand out in the study as exceptions. Indiana, for
example, has a two-page application that does not ask about burial
plots, bingo or blood products. Federal audits last year found
fewer mistakes in its calculations of benefits than they did in
California, which squeezes 120 questions onto 21 pages. Indeed, the
study found that there was no correlation at all between the length
of a state's application and the accuracy of its payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some states have shown a lot of good judgment and simplicity
in complying with the requirements,'' Glickman said. ``Other states
have gone down a much more complicated route. Our job is to try to
help all the states run a simpler system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
