<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9268 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SUNBIZ-BRIEFS-2TAKES-     08-11 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNBIZ-BRIEFS-2TAKES-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the GOP Convention, Carmakers Toot Horns
</P>
<P>
   It was the battle of the cars at the Republican National
Convention, between GM and DaimlerChrysler. On Sunday night, GM,
which gave $1 million to the convention's host committee, held a
party for 2,000 people. It featured Hank Williams Jr. and a replica
of the Batmobile. DaimlerChrysler, which had given the host
committee $250,000, held a reception honoring Rep. J.C. Watts of
Oklahoma that featured the Temptations and a gold Phaeton, a
futuristic concept car.
</P>
<P>
   The carmakers have a tradition of treating the conventions as
marketing opportunities. GM plans equally lavish events at the
Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles, but with the United
Automobile Workers as a Democrat-friendly partner.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes Raises Some Capital
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, who has spent nearly $70 million on two bids for
the Republican presidential nomination, now spends much of his time
running Forbes magazine. But not all of it.
</P>
<P>
   He was at his party's convention to _ what else? _ promote his
tax policies and raise money for other candidates. With his old
buddies Jack Kemp, who has become something of a venture
capitalist, and Lawrence Kudlow, the Wall Street economist, he
talked up their new venture, the Club for Growth, at a breakfast
meeting. Joining the club requires a political donation, which the
group will use for Republicans sharing Forbes' supply-side economic
views. ``I'm trying to help get kindred souls elected,'' Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Hats Enter the Ring
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Mattel decided to promote the new Barbie by
announcing that she would run for the presidency. But at the
Republican convention, GetSetClub.com, a Web-based doll maker in
Philadelphia, ambushed her by showcasing its own candidate,
Vanessa, an African-American doll said to have a college degree and
a history of struggles and successes. According to GetSetClub, she
is running as a candidate of the Surprise Party.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, Mattel struck back by stuffing little Barbie
doll delegates into the Republicans' welcome bags. Mattel hasn't
decided whether there will be a showdown at the Democratic
convention in Los Angeles, and it is leaning against having Barbie
accept Vanessa's challenge to debate. ``Barbie is really busy
serving as a delegate at the convention,'' said Julia Jensen, a
spokeswoman at Mattel and Barbie's campaign manager. ``She doesn't
have time to accept the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Other Tigers on a Celtic Course
</P>
<P>
   With the spotlight on the PGA tour and Tiger Woods all summer,
other, less-known golf tournaments have been largely overlooked.
But the Stone of Accord Tournament last month at the Old Head
course in Kinsale, Ireland, was also a display of American golfing
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   First Ralph Crowley, chief executive of Polar Beverages, a
soft-drink company in Worcester, Mass., shot a hole in one. Using a
6-iron, Crowley got what was not only his first hole in one, but
the first ever on the 180-yard 16th hole of the course, which
opened in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Dan Hoffstad, another member of Crowley's group,
finished the round with a 72, just one stroke over the course
record, held by Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley, with a 12 handicap, said he was happy about his game,
but added that his wife, Joan, defeats him regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Water, Water Everywhere, And That Means Funds, Too  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Internet funds hemorrhaging cash and wireless funds
careening after an earnings warning from Nokia, America needs a
cool new mutual fund sector. How about water? It's eternal. It's
cool. And this most basic of life's necessities even has its own
mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the initial returns of the $4.5 million Water
Fund have been slightly soggy. Since its introduction last Oct. 28,
the fund has gained just over 2 percent, compared with the 8.2
percent return of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is managed by Avalon Trust Co., a Santa Fe, N.M.,
investment concern that specializes in socially conscious
investing. Despite the slow start, Owen M. Quattlebaum, the fund's
manager, predicts that opportunities for water investments will not
dry up anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has elements of a scarce commodity,'' he said. ``More
people appear to be looking to use it in areas where the supply is
not growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Quattlebaum said the bulk of his portfolio was devoted to
playing mergers and acquisitions in domestic water utilities and to
buying companies developing water filtration technologies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Estate Tax's Pulse
</P>
<P>
   The possible death of the death tax, to borrow from Mark Twain,
has been greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``repeal'' of the levy, known in less partisan terms
as the estate tax, has been passed by both houses of Congress,
Republican leaders have yet to send the bill to President Clinton,
who vows a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republican leaders appear to have decided that there
are more votes in attacking Democrats for preserving the so-called
marriage tax _ the president recently vetoed a remedy of it _ than
in seeking tax relief for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Republican bill _ or a less ambitious Democratic
alternative _ became law, it would not mean that the government
would stop taxing estates, at least not anytime soon. For one
thing, the levy would phase out over a decade, not disappearing
until 2010. At that point, to minimize revenue loss, the Treasury
would start collecting tax on a buildup of capital gains that it
now disregards _ the amount by which a stock, for example, has
appreciated before an heir receives it.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, estates bigger than $675,000 are hit with taxes
progressing from 37 percent to 55 percent; the threshold is to rise
to $1 million in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   With so much uncertainty over the tax, planners are giving
general advice to remain financially flexible. They also remind
clients that they may need more, not less, professional counseling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be frozen into thinking that, `Oh boy! This might go
away,''' David Megaw, second vice president at Lincoln Financial
Advisors in Hartford, said of the tax issues. ``You'll probably be
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Context for Spending
</P>
<P>
   Consumers follow the three S's _ spend, save and share _ in that
order, emphasizing the first, says Nathan Dungan, vice president of
stewardship and brand development at Lutheran Brotherhood, a
financial services group in Minneapolis. Americans ``are caught in
a web of hypnotic consumption,'' he said. ``We're at an all-time
low in savings and there's little energy invested in sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   To reverse the order, Dungan offers seven tips for financial
planning:
</P>
<P>
   _ Think it through before you act.
</P>
<P>
   _ Evaluate spending to determine if it reflects what you value.
</P>
<P>
   _ Budget with values in mind.
</P>
<P>
   _ Protect income for your family.
</P>
<P>
   _ Save for goals like a child's education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give to a cause that counts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teach the next generation about financial values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
