<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanks to TPWD, the season is young
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Tradition is the foundation upon which hunting
is built.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting leases, guns and even secret places to hunt have been
passed down from one generation to the next, providing a continuity
that's rare in any other sport.
</P>
<P>
   But the changing face of America _ single-parent families,
urbanization, time demands from work and other leisure activities _
have cut into the tradition of youngsters following parents and
grandparents into the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Parks and Wildlife Department has been working to
reverse the downward trend by offering special youth hunting days
and supporting youth hunting activities in concert with other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there will be a special statewide youth-only season
for whitetails, turkey and quail on Oct. 28-29. Only youngsters 16
and younger may hunt during the special weekend. Check your local
county listings for bag and possession limits.
</P>
<P>
   The department also is sponsoring youth-only hunts for waterfowl
in the three duck zones in Texas: Oct. 14-15 in the High Plains
Mallard Management Unit, Oct. 21-22 in the North Zone and Oct.
21-22 or Dec. 2-3 in the South Zone. Federal rules allow youngsters
17 and younger to hunt waterfowl on the special days.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and Wildlife also has special youth-only hunts on some of
its public hunting areas. Youngsters must have a valid hunting
license and a special hunting permit, as well as be accompanied by
a licensed adult. There are hunts for alligators, deer and
javelinas this year.
</P>
<P>
   For information on public hunting opportunities for youths,
contact the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department at (512) 389-4505.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Texas Youth Hunting Association, sponsored by
the Texas Wildlife Association, provides a series of structured
hunts for youths throughout the year. For information, contact
Jerry Warden at (210) 930-2177.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
