<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas' smorgasbord is open year-round
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Throw in feral hogs and pigeons, and Texas
hunting is a year-round sport.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of us tend to think of seasons as starting with dove
hunting in late summer and ending with turkey hunting in spring.
For formal hunting periods, that's a long time, slightly more than
eight months altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is opportunity personified, really, since the number of
species and the length of seasons is unique to our state. Few
others can boast both species of deer, antelope, exotics, ducks and
geese, quail and doves, turkeys, woodcock, snipe, sandhill cranes,
javelinas and squirrels, to name more than a few. And those aren't
all the animals available.
</P>
<P>
   Things start with dove season, which opens Sept. 1 in the North
and Central zones of Texas. The South Zone season for doves will
open Sept. 22. North Zone hunters have through Oct. 30 to chase
doves. The Central Zone will close Oct. 17 and the South on Nov. 5.
The South and Central zones each have a shorter late season that
opens Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Other season openings and closures include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Special teal only: Sept. 15-30.
</P>
<P>
   _ Special white-winged dove area: Sept. 2-3, 9-10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Woodcock: Dec. 18-Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ White-tailed deer: Statewide, Nov. 4-Jan. 7; South Zone, Nov.
11-Jan. 21; special late season for spikes and does, Jan. 22-Feb.
4. Statewide archery, Sept. 30-Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mule deer: Panhandle, Nov. 18-Dec. 3; Trans-Pecos, Nov.
25-Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   _ Turkey: same as deer season in fall. Spring: North Zone, April
7-May 13; South Zone, March 31-May 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ Squirrel: Most counties have no closed season. East Texas,
Oct. 1-Feb. 4 and May 1-31.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ducks: North Zone, Oct. 28-29, Nov. 11-Jan. 21; South Zone,
Oct. 28-Nov. 26 and Dec. 8-Jan. 21; High Plains Mallard Management
Unit, Oct. 21-23 and Nov. 11-Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ Geese: Western Zone: Oct. 28-Feb. 11; Conservation season Feb.
12-April 1. Eastern Zone, Oct. 28-Jan. 21; Conservation season,
Jan. 22-April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters always should check local county listings for specific
regulations on bag limits and such things as doe days and special
rules on deer and turkeys. All the information is available from
the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department through its annual hunting
booklet or at www.tpwd.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
