u l BC-TXOUT-WHITE-WING0812     08-11 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-WHITE-WING0812 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White-winged doves are piling up frequent-flyer miles
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ White-winged doves are not the bird of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Once thought to be a bird limited by weather and constitution to
the Lower Rio Grande Valley, the whitewing has exhibited a unique
ability to find suitable living conditions almost anywhere. The
doves might be pushing out other species as they move, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all over Texas, other states, too,'' said Gary
Waggerman, the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department's whitewing
program director. ``We had one at a feeder in Newfoundland about a
month ago and in the winter of 1999 we had reports of birds at
feeders in Nebraska and Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're moving everything else out. In my opinion, they do,''
Waggerman said. ``We're trying to get a study going to look at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the good things, of course, about whitewings and their
current territorial expansion is that Texas dove hunters should
benefit. ``I think everybody's going to just about have to have a
whitewing stamp this year,'' Waggerman said. ``The only exception
would be in deep East Texas, and there are even some over there.''
</P>
<P>
   White-winged doves once lived almost exclusively in deep South
Texas and Mexico along the Rio Grande. They found nesting
conditions in the citrus groves of the valley to their liking.
However, following the 1983 freeze that killed most fruit trees,
the birds began to change their habits.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, Waggerman pointed out, there were more
whitewings living in San Antonio than in the Valley. They have only
continued to increase in numbers, as well as move northward into
cities such as Austin and Waco. ``We counted 799,000 in the city of
Austin this year,'' Waggerman said. ``We counted 507,000 in the Rio
Grande Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Waggerman thinks that San Antonio could boast a population in
excess of one million birds. And the doves are beginning to expand
outside the city limits, where more than 100,000 were counted in
one area.
</P>
<P>
   Waggerman pointed to another intruder showing up around Central
Texas, the Eurasian collared dove. The non-native dove was first
seen in Texas in 1997, but has rapidly established itself in every
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been seen in Van Horn and Dalhart,'' Waggerman said.
``Hunters should know that they are not a protected species at all,
just like a pigeon. You see them around grain elevators a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents in Austin and San Antonio are accustomed to seeing
whitewings at their back-yard feeders, where they seem to be more
aggressive about staking out territory than mourning doves. As they
expand outside city limits, the birds are more available to
hunters, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Hunting white-winged doves is no different than hunting mourning
doves, though they might not be seen in the same areas. Whitewings
show up in feeding areas such as grain fields and often can be shot
when they're passing from feeding to watering areas. They are
larger than mourning doves and have a distinctive white wing patch
visible in flight.
</P>
<P>
   The limit is 15 birds per day outside the special white-winged
dove area in South Texas. In the special zone, the limit is 10
doves per day with no more than five mourning doves and two
white-tipped doves. Hunters who take white-winged doves must
possess the $7 whitewing stamp, which can be purchased along with
the regular Texas hunting license.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9278 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-TEACHING-SOFTWARE     08-11 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TEACHING-SOFTWARE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: their work.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These multimedia simulations differ radically from current
online offerings. ``When you look at online courses now, what do
you see?'' Schank said. ``Text online with a quiz. We're not taking
a lecture and putting it on screen. We're restructuring these
courses into goal-based scenarios that will get kids excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Schank says that such courses will render traditional classes _
and many professors _ obsolete. ``The idea of one professor for one
class is ancient,'' he said. ``New technology is going to give
every student access to the best professors in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But many academics dismiss Schank's prediction that traditional
teaching methods will soon become obsolete and question software
learning's pedagogic value. ``Education depends on relationships
between people,'' said David Noble, a history professor at York
University in Toronto and a critic of online learning.
``Interactive is not the same as interpersonal. What Schank doesn't
recognize is that teaching is not just about relaying knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Others warn against accepting radical new technology without
pause. ``The American university system is a highly functional
institution,'' said Phil Agre, an associate professor of
information studies at UCLA. ``The danger is that we will apply
overly simplistic ideas about technology and tear apart the
institution before we really know what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another assessment of the value of Schank's work is offered by
Prof. Howard Nusbaum, chairman of the psychology department at the
University of Chicago. ``Schank's idea in principal is a very sound
one,'' Professor Nusbaum said. ``But in the case of software
learning, its success or failure will depend on implementation more
than theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the country's top universities are experimenting with
ways to implement new technology-based teaching methods. Seymour
Papert, a professor and researcher at the Massachusetts Institute
of Technology's Media Laboratory, was among the first to advocate
computers as teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is changing so fast that the concept of schools
teaching people what they need to know is no longer viable,''
Papert said. ``We're moving into a time when people need to know
how to learn things they weren't taught in school. Second, we now
have the technology to let kids learn better. This will not just
allow them to learn the same things better; it will teach kids to
learn radical new things at all ages.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel Resnick, another professor at MIT's Media Laboratory,
said: ``Computers offer kids multiple ways to learn, where in the
past there was only one way. Ultimately, you want kids to have a
tool chest of different options they can bring to bear when solving
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But new technology also threatens to exacerbate current
inequities. Resnick worries that the so-called digital divide will
not be one of access to computers but a ``fluency gap'' between
those able to use them for learning and those who merely use them
to play games.
</P>
<P>
   Schank does not think his programs will be a victim of the
digital divide. He believes that poorer schools are likely to
benefit first from his programs. Top high schools ``don't want this
_ their kids get into Harvard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But poorer schools,'' he continued, ``aren't going to turn
down a college level software course that's endorsed by
Columbia.''.
</P>
<P>
   Schank pointed to the example of the Daniel Jenkins Academy, a
public high school in Polk County, Fla., a poor district that will
switch to online teaching this fall. Students will gather in
classrooms where they will take Web-based classes on computers.
They will be taught remotely by teachers working from their homes.
Schank suggested that once disadvantaged students began
outperforming those from better schools, many of the long-held
assumptions about teaching will go the way of the slide rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole country of people who agree on education, and
they're all wrong,'' he said with characteristic bluntness.
``School just isn't that relevant anymore. We'll make it relevant.
We're trying to overthrow the system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
