<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mmm, mmm ...dove breasts (with gravy, of course)
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I hate to hear anyone say that wild game,
especially doves, tastes gamy and they don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Dove breasts, grilled or fried, are one of God's chosen
favorites. The only thing you have to do is cook them.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two simple recipes that both start with filleted
breasts. Just run a sharp knife down either side of the breastbone
and turn it out along the rib cage. You'll have two nice fillets
from each bird.
</P>
<P>
   To grill them, use two fillets, wrapped in a piece of bacon and
held together by toothpicks. Purists place a slice of jalapeno
between the two breast fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Soak them in zesty Italian dressing for at least an hour, or
overnight if you can. Grill until the bacon begins to crisp and the
fillets are slightly firm to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   This can work as appetizers or a main course, and it will work
with wine or beer.
</P>
<P>
   Frying starts with the same breast fillets, soaked in milk or
butter milk for an hour. Dredge in seasoned flour and fry in a
quarter inch of oil in a cast iron skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Gravy is required.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
