A9280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TXOUT-TEAL0812-COX     08-11 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXOUT-TEAL0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Teal deal
 &HT;    By Mike Legget
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Teal don't play favorites.
</P>
<P>
   They'll make a fool of the guy with a $10,000 engraved 12 gauge,
just as easily as a poor boy with a single-shot .410. It doesn't
matter. But they'll always be there for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   If you want fast, they've got it. If you want plenty, teal are
your boys. If geography is important to you, teal are all over the
map.
</P>
<P>
   The special early teal season that Texans enjoy every September
is a wonderful opportunity to get in some early shooting at one of
nature's sportiest targets. This year's season runs Sept. 15-30,
with a daily bag limit of four birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a truckload of them this year,'' said
Vernon Bevill, migratory wildlife and wetland ecology program
director for the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department. ``We had the
biggest breeding population on record this year for bluewings, 7.4
million birds.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of teal that will migrate down through the Central
and Mississippi flyways and on into Mexico will probably be double
that number, Bevill said. Blue-winged teal travel south quite
early, and the special season is scheduled to allow hunters a
chance at the birds before they move through. Hunters will see a
few greenwings, but the majority of the bag will be bluewings.
</P>
<P>
   Texas hunters bag some 70,000 to 80,000 bluewings every year,
Bevill said. Nationwide, the numbers approach 1 million teal.
``There are actually more greenwings in the harvest each year, even
though there are only about one-third as many greenwings and
bluewings,'' Bevill said.
</P>
<P>
   The early teal season has a number of things going for it, not
the least of which is the accommodating nature of the birds. ``Teal
are easy to decoy,'' Bevill said. ``All you need is half a dozen
decoys, and you don't have to call them very much. If they can see
the decoys, they'll usually come in for a look.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-bird limit is reachable, even on days when not many
birds are flying. Bevill said Central Texas hunters can have
success on small lakes and tanks, especially if there are enough
hunters to cover several lakes in one area. ``That way you can keep
the birds moving from one lake to another and usually have enough
to shoot,'' he said. ``They are using lots of stock tanks all over
Texas, especially during the regular season. There are all kinds of
ducks on those tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought that has plagued much of the state has positive and
negative impacts on duck hunting, especially teal, Bevill said.
Coastal hunters with water likely will see quality hunting
throughout the season. Areas with food supplies also will be able
to attract enough teal for hunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Panhandle has gotten a lot of water this year, and they
should have a great season,'' Bevill said. ``The later season we're
having this year could help because it will encourage people to
pump water during the season that will hold teal and also stay in
the ground long enough to help during the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in so-so hunting years, the early teal season remains a
good opportunity for hunters. ``Just go,'' Bevill said. ``It's an
opportunity that's underutilized for the most part. Only about 30
percent of the regular duck hunters hunt teal.''
</P>
<P>
   Equipment for hunting teal is simple; a few decoys and a
camouflage shirt work fine. You don't even need waders, but they
might help keep away some of the mosquitoes and fire ants. A head
net is a good way to fight mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Shotguns can be whatever you're comfortable with. Twelve and 20
gauges work equally well, and you can even get bismuth shot for
.410s if you're feeling tough. All shot must be steel or some other
approved non-toxic load.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
