<SLUG> BC-THONG-POPULARITY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR WOMEN GREAT AND SMALL, BRIEFS CAN'T GET MUCH BRIEFER
</HEADLINE>
 - ART-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 8 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release on Sunday, Aug. 13.) 
 By   NANCY HAAS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a recent Friday lunch hour in Kmart's underwear department in
Flushing Meadows, N.Y., in Queens County, it was obvious where the
action was. The aisles of billowy white panties were deserted. The
racks of hip-hugger briefs stood virtually untouched. But a
half-dozen women _ from chubby teen-agers in capri pants to
middle-aged moms pushing full carts of housewares _ were bravely
shopping where few women had, until recently, shopped before: the
thong section.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm liking this one,'' said Maria Mantalusa, 46, a nurse from
Kew Gardens, who was shopping with her niece Kim, 25. She held up a
baby blue thong with white stripes _ probably no more than three
square inches of fabric all told _ against her generous curvy hips.
The younger woman, whose array of thongs on little white plastic
hangers already weighed down her index finger, nodded
enthusiastically and said, ``You can't ever have enough of those.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it only three years ago that Monica Lewinsky shocked the
nation by flashing her thong at the president? Or just a few
seasons ago that the randy roommates on ``Friends'' traded
reproving quips about thongs, comparing them to dental floss? Could
that be the thumping bass of Sisqo's ``Thong Song'' _ a
chart-topper since March _ piped through the sound system at the
local mall?
</P>
<P>
   Once the sole province of pubescent underwear models and Rio de
Janeiro beach bunnies, thongs, it seems, have made it into the
mainstream. Sisqo's racy video aside, the thong is going from a
flag of sexual provocation to a common item in the lingerie drawer
of even modest women.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria's Secret sold nearly 20 million thongs in 1999. Thongs
and their even briefer counterpart, the G-string, now account for
40 percent of the underpants sold by the chain. Five years ago, it
was only 10 percent. Even at Macy's, where the average shopper is
older _ in her 30's and 40's _ thongs make up 20 percent of the
total sales for women's underpants, said Carolyn Moss, director of
ready-to-wear. That is a 100-percent rise in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds unbelievable, but thongs have become the core
of our business,'' said Monica Mitro, a spokeswoman for Victoria's
Secret. ``And it cuts across ages and body types.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular style is a ``dressy'' black satiny polyester,
Mitro said, but the second favorite is white cotton. Victoria's
Secret is increasingly offering thongs in casual everyday styles,
like polka dots and lily pad green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it was the bolder girls who wore thongs,'' Mitro said.
``Now, that's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem surprising that a style so revealing _ and according
to some, so uncomfortable _ would catch on in a population that on
average has never been older or fatter. Bathing suit manufacturers
attempted to import thong bikinis from Brazil a few years ago, but
the trend fell flat. Women felt a thong was too revealing to wear
in public. Yet, they began taking to them in private, wearing them
under clothes, lured by their practicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways you can trace the culture through its taste in
women's undergarments,'' the fashion historian Valerie Steele said.
``What is sexy or practical changes in pretty dramatic ways as the
mores change.'' Just as confining panty girdles expressed the
repression of the 1950s and navel-baring bikini briefs seemed to
epitomize the newfound sexual freedom of the 1960s and 70s, the
dawn of the 21st century, when sex is numbingly omnipresent, is a
time when underwear is threatening to disappear entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, as Steele notes, is that society's attitude toward
underwear has come full circle. Until the 1860's, well-bred women
didn't wear underpants at all, opting instead for slips and
corsets. ``To wear underwear was scandalous _ only courtesans wore
bloomers,'' she said. ``It was considered a sign of looseness.''
</P>
<P>
   Only with the introduction of the hoop skirt were underpants
invented, as a necessity due to the skirt's precarious construction
(after, say, a slip on the ice, the stiff hoop could send a
Victorian lady's skirt sailing over her head). ``Now, after nearly
150 years of fetishizing underwear,'' Steele said, ``fashion seems
to be dictating that it be invisible again.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0335 </DOCNO>
