<SLUG> BC-GA-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REQUEST TO NCAA THROWS LIMELIGHT ON EFFORT TO CHANGE GEORGIA'S
FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A quiet effort to negotiate a new state flag for
Georgia that eliminates its Confederate symbol has suddenly become
very public, after a leading civil rights organization asked the
National Collegiate Athletic Association to move its planned
basketball championships from Atlanta if the flag is not changed.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Thursday, the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, which was founded by the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr., asked the NCAA to move the 2002 and 2007 Men's Final Four and
the 2003 Women's Final Four from Atlanta if the flag is not
redesigned by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA executive committee met Friday in Indianapolis and took
no action on the request, but issued a statement criticizing any
official symbol that ``conveys discrimination and racism,'' and
urging more discussion of the issue. Charles Wethington, president
of the University of Kentucky and chairman of the committee, said
the organization would watch the issue closely because it is
concerned about the welfare of student athletes who travel to
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the Georgia flag consists of the Confederate flag
, placed there by the state Legislature in 1956, two years after
school segregation was ruled illegal by the Supreme Court. Many
historians believe the flag was changed as an act of defiance
against federal civil rights legislation, and the city of Atlanta
refuses to fly it on official buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Christian Leadership Conference's request, signed
by its president, Martin Luther King III, surprised several black
elected officials who said they hoped to change the flag's design
in the next session of the Georgia Legislature, which begins in
January. Many who want a new flag are hoping to change the minds of
opponents without the kind of boycott that polarized a similar
recent debate in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped to have more dialogue than action at this time,''
said Calvin Smyre, chairman of the Democratic caucus of the Georgia
House of Representatives and a prominent black legislator. ``At the
appropriate time, external pressure may be the right course of
action, but right now we need to have some internal political
dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Smyre, a life member of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, said he was not criticizing the organization, but was
surprised by its action.
</P>
<P>
   Many white state legislators, both Democratic and Republican,
and particularly from rural areas, have said they fear that if they
agree to change the flag, they will be turned out of office. Even
Gov. Roy Barnes said recently that the state is not ready for a new
flag yet, and has not publicly advocated a new one.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of a new flag say that the time for change may
come soon after a new Legislature is elected in November, because
it will be two years before another election, by which time voter
anger may have faded. As a result, talk of a boycott has been muted
in the hope that white legislators would not feel pressured. An
boycott of South Carolina by the NAACP angered many lawmakers, but
ultimately the Legislature there voted to remove the Confederate
flag from the statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   King did not return phone calls Friday. In his letter to the
NCAA, he said that the boycott of South Carolina was a ``key factor
for change,'' and noted that his organization had canceled its
convention there last year. Without being specific, he said his
organization has now initiated a campaign to remove the Confederate
symbol from the Georgia flag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
