<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9288 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CANADA-DIAMONDS-ART-6     08-11 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DIAMONDS-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA TRIES TO MAKE CLEAR THAT ITS DIAMONDS ARE DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YELLOWKNIFE, Northwest Territories _ Sidewalk pennants that
proclaim Yellowknife the ``Diamond Capital of North America'' help
explain why Canadians are working to ensure that their baubles are
not confused with the ``blood diamonds'' of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clean, upfront business,'' Stephen Kakfwi, the
provincial premier, said in an interview, throwing diplomatic
subtleties to the Arctic winds. ``You don't have to go through the
jungles of Angola or Sierra Leone, dealing with guerrillas and
dictators.''
</P>
<P>
   In the largest industrial project above North America's tree
line, Ekati Mine opened almost 200 miles northeast of here two
years ago and now produces about $1.3 million worth of diamonds a
day, or 5 percent of the world production. When two other mines
start producing nearby, by 2005, the Northwest Territories is
expected to produce as much as 15 percent of the world's diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The only large producer in the Americas, Canada will then join
the ranks of the world's top diamond producers, which include
Botswana, Russia, South Africa and Angola. With this future
glittering on the horizon, like a mineral aurora borealis, Canadian
officials are acting to protect the future image of diamonds, in
contrast to the trafficking in uncut stones that helps to pay for
guerrilla armies in Sierra Leone and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do otherwise would be to court commercial catastrophe,''
Canada's ambassador to the United Nations, Robert Fowler, told the
World Diamond Congress, an industry group, in a speech in Belgium
last month. ``In Canada in the 1970s, we watched our fur industry
_the business upon which our country was founded _destroyed by a
small number of very shrill and very effective animal rights
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Indian families have yet to recover income lost when
consumer resistance to fur coats wiped out in a few years a
tradition of commercial trapping that dated back to the 1700s, and
a potential consumer backlash against diamonds strikes fear in the
Northwest Territories, a vast wilderness larger than Texas and
California combined, but with a population of only 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kakfwi, the premier, who is a member of the Dene tribe,
estimated that the portion of his people making a living from
trapping has plunged, to five percent today, from 65 percent a
quarter century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Irving, the territorial director of diamond projects,
said, ``We have been through it with fur, and we don't want to go
through it with diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ``If the issues with conflict diamonds don't get
solved, the consumer is not going to be able to differentiate
between the different kinds of diamonds, and is going to be against
diamonds, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police are developing a technology
that would ``fingerprint'' diamonds, identifying them by trace
impurities that could be tracked to known mines.
</P>
<P>
   To promote Canada's Arctic diamonds, the Territorial government
now provides certificates to show that the diamonds were mined and
cut in the Northwest Territories. One cutting and polishing company
working here, Sirius Diamonds, now etches with a laser a tiny polar
bear on each diamond. Other Canadian cutters use as their brands a
maple leaf and a snow goose.
</P>
<P>
   And Canadians are actively involved in the crackdown on diamonds
from war-torn areas. Fowler chairs a U.N. committee that is
investigating violations of an embargo on the purchase of diamonds
from Angolan rebels. Ralph Hazleton, a Canadian diamond expert,
recently testified at the United Nations about Liberia and Burkina
Faso buying diamonds from Sierra Leone guerrillas in violation of a
second embargo.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to images of war associated with West African
diamonds, Irving said that Canadian marketers want to associate
Arctic diamonds ``with images of the north _ ice, clean, pristine,
crystal clear.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To provide jobs, the Territorial government has insisted that
diamond mines market at least 10 percent of their raw diamonds
locally.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Sirius and two other cutting and polishing
companies have opened here, with the cutting skills largely coming
from Antwerp, Belgium. In future years, billions of dollars of
diamond mining investments are expected. Today, mining projects are
underway for only 12 out of the Territory's estimated 325
kimberlite pipes, the funnel shaped veins of diamond-bearing rock
associated with ancient volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   From London, DeBeers Consolidated Mines, the company that
controls about two thirds of the world trade in uncut diamonds, is
suddenly focusing its investing telescope on this laid back
frontier town of 18,000 people. Since late June, DeBeers has
invested in one company prospecting for diamonds in the Northwest
Territories, and has begun a hostile takeover bid for a second
company that is about four years from production.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be an international diamond center, a place where
Israelis, where people from New York will come to secure their
diamonds,'' said Kakfwi. That will be a stretch for a territory
whose sole air links are daily flights to Edmonton, Alberta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
