<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL PRICES FALLING? DON'T COUNT ON IT, SAYS A WALL ST. EXPERT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a sharp run-up, which helped put gasoline back onto front
pages in the spring after a long absence, oil prices have subsided
and politicians rail no longer about supposed industry gouging.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem unshaken in thinking oil prices can only slide
further, following the pattern traced after the 1973-74 Arab
embargo, the 1979-82 period that included revolution in Iran, and
the 1991 Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles T. Maxwell, regarded as the dean of Wall Street's
oil analysts, contends that things are different now. Maxwell, with
Weeden &AMP; Co., made the case on Thursday for his against-the-grain
view. Here are excerpts from the conversation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You're predicting that oil will average $24 a barrel through
2003 in contrast to a Wall Street consensus that it will return to
$18 to $20 within the next year or two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Excess world capacity, what could quickly be brought
into production, has ranged between about 7 and 10 percent over the
last 50 years. It reached 18 percent in 1986, when prices
collapsed. Today it's around 5 percent, and we need 2 to 2{ percent
as a cushion against emergency, such as weather or strikes. So we
are as tight now as I have seen in my 44 years studying the
industry. It's not political maneuvering by OPEC _ the oil
physically isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is this a result of reduced supply or higher demand?
</P>
<P>
   A. Both. Low prices until recently not only created
disincentives to invest, but they've also limited the capital
available to invest because earnings collapsed. And then demand
rebounded in the Far East and Europe, and we've got unprecedented
prosperity in America.
</P>
<P>
   Q. But profits are now pretty robust, right?
</P>
<P>
   A. It takes as much as four years from the time a major
development project gets approved to the time when oil begins to
flow. Besides, national oil companies in Venezuela and elsewhere
must compete for budget money, and the Exxon Mobils of the world
are sensitive to stockholder values and their own options. Every
dollar they put into buying back shares because they're cheap is a
dollar that doesn't go into the drill bit.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the tight market what caused the price of gasoline to jump
recently, to as much as $2.50 a gallon in the Midwest?
</P>
<P>
   A. It may have been a modest contributor, but what happened
there was basically an environmental issue _ making reformulated
gasoline. They brought supplies from other areas, and the problem
quickly dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Q. So will the government investigation prove to be fruitless? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No investigation we've had yet has found a conspiracy of the
oil companies. I'm not going to say there weren't individual
operators or terminals that were gouging. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. If profits are good and you think oil will stay above $20,
why are most industry stocks, except for the oil-field service and
exploration companies, in the dumps? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Investors have ``learned'' from experience that a high price
elicits an investment cycle, which creates an expanded supply,
which drops the price quickly and leaves them hanging. And while I
think the process this time will be gradual, irregular and
stretched out, the business is regarded as more cyclical than 20
years ago, when people saw growth in it.
</P>
<P>
   As the price of oil holds in the mid-20s, I expect people to
realize what good value these stocks are. The stocks have suffered
from being ``old economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Hasn't Chevron, for one, been bragging about becoming a
high-tech company? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Let's be serious. They're going to do a little Internet
purchasing, but I think it's laughable. When Internet P/Es get low
enough, they won't even mention it again.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will the industry continue to consolidate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The game's not over. Chevron probably won't merge, but Texaco
is likely, with Royal Dutch the most logical candidate. Conoco,
Amerada Hess and Phillips would be perfect for takeover. Phillips,
which doubled reserves when it bought ARCO's Alaskan assets, is
most appealing, selling for 9 times earnings, compared with 15{ for
its peers.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do oil companies stand to gain if George W. Bush and Dick
Cheney, both of whom worked in the industry, win in November?
</P>
<P>
   A. When push comes to shove, the parties would make geopolitical
decisions about such things as imports and subsidies pretty much
the same way. But Bush's would be a looser environmental policy, on
offshore drilling, say, than Gore's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How did Cheney do as chairman of Halliburton, whose stock has
a P/E of 65 and has jumped 30 percent this year? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I wouldn't call him a brilliant businessman, but he did a
workmanlike job organizing the company, putting a face on it and
winning business. He certainly met the expectations of the people
who put him in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
