<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-ADVANCE     08-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-ADVANCE0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Resilient Holyfield says he's `driven by love'
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Be they matters of the heart or of the fist, Evander
Holyfield gets knocked down, picks himself up and bulls in for
more.
</P>
<P>
   An admitted two-time loser at marriage, he vows to exchange vows
again someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, I make it difficult on myself. I just need to
be a little patient, give it a little more time,'' Holyfield, who
acknowledges his hasty decision to wed for the second time led to
divorce this year, said recently in training camp before arriving
in a city known for its ubiquitous wedding chapels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I'm going to have a (third) wife. I will not quit
till I hit a home run. I will never give up until somebody runs
around the bases with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who normally accepts questions head-on, is coy about
any current relationship. He has turned gun-shy since his marital
split was played out in the media and disclosures that he has borne
out-of-wedlock children, staining an otherwise saintly reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But he volunteered his dream to say ``I do'' once again and even
discussed adding to his brood after marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be responsible for someone, and someone to be
responsible for me,'' Holyfield said. ``I want to take care of
someone, and want someone to take care of me.''
</P>
<P>
   He grinned. ``I'm driven by love.''
</P>
<P>
   The only ring, presumably, on Holyfield's mind today is the
large, square one in which he will work against John Ruiz. Only a
four-time fight loser (he admits but to two, with the others blamed
on the judges) in 16 remarkable years of dueling for dollars,
Atlanta's indomitable boxer and incurable romantic is back for his
first bout in nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The setting, appropriately, is a re-creation of the world's
capital of romance _ the Paris Hotel and Casino, complete with
soaring faux Eiffel Tower. The fighters will dance about the ring
in a ballroom with 9,000 seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonjour, monsieur,'' Holyfield said, tapping his limited
retention of the language from a French high school class.
``Comment t'allez vous?''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, in fact, is doing quite well. Oblivious to the
possibility that his next bout could be his last, he exudes
confidence that the three major heavyweight belts will return to
his closet.
</P>
<P>
   Only the WBA's is for the taking tonight. Lennox Lewis has the
others. With so many cross-currents flowing through the heavyweight
division, keeping logical opponents apart, there is no telling when
_ or if, even _ Holyfield will get a chance to gather them all up.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, two months from his 38th birthday, Holyfield insists he
will hang around as long as it takes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue,'' he said, ``until I'm the undisputed
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Reclaiming the WBA wing of the heavyweight class would make
Holyfield a champ for the fourth time. From one angle, it can be
viewed as a dubious honor because it means he has been deposed on
three occasions. Unbeatable fighters, by definition, are champions
but once.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's situation certifies his peerless resilience. ``A
setback,'' said his manager, Jim Thomas, ``is nothing but an
opportunity for a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield was not always one to eagerly dust himself off and
return to battle. He recalled his first taste of defeat at age 11
as if it were asparagus. One Cecil Collins was Holyfield's first
foe to punch back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, he hit me,'' little Evander whined in his corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to boxing,'' said the coach, patting him on his
scrawny chest.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield charged out and tackled Collins, resulting in
disqualification. He ran home, embarrassed, and announced his
retirement. This time, only his mother heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't quit,'' she scolded. ``Go back in there.''
</P>
<P>
   At a subsequent tournament, Holyfield crossed his fingers and
hoped Collins had not entered. No such luck. Before their rematch,
Holyfield cried and prayed aloud for divine assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, he's calling Jesus,'' a friend said that day. ``He must be
scared.''
</P>
<P>
   As a pro, he has uttered the R-word to the world in the
aftermath of a loss but would unretire after the self-inflicted
shame wore off. When Riddick Bowe beat him in 1992, his first
defeat in eight years, a painful flashback to Cecil Collins ensued.
Holyfield wanted to quit and hide.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he knows to let the hurt wear off and carry on. And, John
Ruiz and the conflicted gods of boxing willing, he intends to do so
until the three organizations concur in their choice of champion.
</P>
<P>
   And then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done. Everybody will say, 'You can't go.' (Promoters) are
going to throw all this money in my face. And I can say, 'It's not
about the money.' ``
</P>
<P>
   For Holyfield, even with his fists, it's a matter of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
