<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9293 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WEST-FIRES-920(2TAKES     08-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-FIRES-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POLITICS OF TIMBER ENGULFS WESTERN BLAZES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., N.M., Idaho)   By DOUGLAS JEHL with ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With wildfires still burning out of control across
a dozen Western states in what may be the worst fire season in a
generation, a fierce debate in timber politics has begun to rage
over who may be to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Fire experts have warned for years that combustible material had
accumulated in Western forests to dangerous levels. But federal
agencies did not begin to address the problem until a policy shift
in 1995, and conservative critics _ including the Republican
governor of Montana _ were arguing Friday that, even afterward, the
administration did not move fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton administration didn't cause these fires, but their
policies have left the Forest Service underfunded and underprepared
for this crisis,'' Gov. Marc Racicot said in an interview. ``I
don't think it's a conspiracy, but it's a philosophy they have that
leads to explosive fires that destroy everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the attack, which was echoed by representatives
of the timber industry, was a contention that the priority given to
environmental concerns within the administration had prevented
officials from confronting the fire threat as might have been most
appropriate, through emergency logging measures.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and their allies were quick to rebut
the criticism, suggesting that the critics were speaking mostly out
of self-interest and arguing that the Forest Service and other
agencies had acted responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a campaign year, and these charges are politically
motivated,'' Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said in a telephone
interview from Colorado. Babbitt conceded that ``some bottlenecks''
had slowed efforts to move ahead with forest thinning programs and
other fire-prevention measures, but he said the delays did not
reflect any lack of administration will.
</P>
<P>
   Independent fire experts in the West have said that the blazes
appear to be following no particular pattern, burning with roughly
equal fury in areas that had been logged in the past and those
where development had been prohibited. But some said there were
indications that the recent use of fire-prevention measures had
given some areas an additional margin of protection.
</P>
<P>
   The finger-pointing hinted at some of the emotions being laid
bare in a summer in which fires had already burned more than 4
million acres of the West, or an area larger than Connecticut. At
least 25,000 firefighters are battling the blazes across the
region, with reinforcements that include contingents from Australia
and New Zealand, as well as from the Army and Marines, which
together have dispatched three battalions.
</P>
<P>
   In Boise, Idaho, the National Interagency Fire Center said
Friday that the number of large fires burning in the West had been
reduced to 60 from 65.
</P>
<P>
   But with the hot, dry weather that has fueled the blazes showing
no sign of abating, most experts say that some blazes will continue
until the first snows, in what is now widely expected to become the
worst fire season in at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.4 million-acre toll for the season so far is already
nearly double the average from the last 10 years, and it well
outstrips notorious fire years like 1988, when a large portion of
Yellowstone National Park burned.
</P>
<P>
   With this year's fire control costs already above half a billion
dollars, and with the Republicans looking for potent issues to help
them win the White House, the political debate may well get even
hotter.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday, Racicot of Montana said he had
warned officials from the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land
Management since 1992 about the dangers of increased timber
buildup. He said he had written unsuccessfully as recently as
January to the Forest Service chief, Mike Dombeck, to request that
more timber operations be authorized in Montana's national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Racicot said he blamed those he called strong environmentalists
within the administration, portraying them as opposed to timber
cutting under any circumstances, including thinning, that might
have reduced the severity and extent of the fires. ``Ultimately,
the White House is responsible, just as I am responsible for what
happens to our state forests here in Montana,'' said Racicot, who
is regarded as a close ally of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Among others who spoke scathingly about what they called the
administration's mistakes was Michael Klein, the chief spokesman
for the American Forest and Paper Association, an industry group
with close ties to the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all comes down to not really understanding that to save a
forest, you have to cut a tree,'' Klein said in a telephone
interview from the group's headquarters in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, timber harvests on national forests have fallen from
12 billion board feet per year to less than 3 billion, in large
part to address environmental concerns, such as threats to
endangered species like the spotted owl. That trend, Klein said,
was a sign that ``this administration is in the hands of a radical,
environmental fringe wants to tie the hands of the federal land
managers by removing tools from their toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   But environmental activists who were quick to defend the
administration said they believed that this year's fires had little
to do with any shift in logging practices. ``This is more a
phenomenon of the weather than any forest management policy,'' Bob
Ekey, regional director of the Wilderness Society, said in a
telephone interview from Bozeman, Mont.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the broadest sense, all fire experts agree, the main reasons
for the current, fire-prone state of Western forests must be traced
back much further, to the kinds of practices that have prevalent
over the last 100 years. Through nearly all of that period, most
fires were suppressed as a matter of federal policy and selective
logging of large trees was widely permitted, creating the
conditions that have left most of today's woodlands choked with
trees and brush.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 20th century, when fires tended to be small and
frequent, trees like Ponderosa pines grew in densities of as few as
20 to 50 trees an acre. Now, in much of the West, the same variety
of trees tend to be much smaller but are found in densities that
can range from 300 to 900 trees an acre, creating conditions ideal
for intense, fast-growing fires.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after a review conducted after the 1994 fire season,
the administration formally embraced a fire policy for wild land,
which identified thinning, preventive fires and other steps as key
tools to be used toward the goal of trying to assist forests in
returning to their natural, less-dense state.
</P>
<P>
   But progress has been slow, in part because of legal challenges
and other opposition from environmental groups like the Forest
Guardians of Santa Fe, N.M. Such groups object to practices that
they would construe as allowing commercial logging in the national
forests.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the Forest Service and the Bureau of Land Management
seem to prefer preventive fires over cutting in their efforts to
thin forests. But public confidence in the man-made fires was dealt
a heavy blow in May, when one such fire set near Los Alamos, N.M.,
swept out of control and damaged hundreds of homes.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing Friday that the administration had failed to take the
fire danger seriously enough, some critics pointed to a memorandum
written in January by Lester Rosenkrance, who was then director of
the Bureau of Land Management's firefighting arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should calamity strike, in the form of being unprepared for a
severe fire season that results in injuries or deaths among the
fire personnel, the agencies will be held accountable,''
Rosenkrance wrote in the memo, which was addressed to Tom Fry, the
agency's director.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenkrance complained that inadequate funding of the agency's
fire presuppression budget requests was leading to insufficient
training of federal firefighters and reduced training for local
government firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is doubt in my mind that we are placing the public and
property at greater risk as our ability to respond quickly and
aggressively to wild land fires decreases,'' Rosenkrance wrote. But
senior bureau officials not only ignored his warnings, said
Rosenkrance, they asked him to transfer to another job. After more
than 30 years with the agency, he chose to retire instead.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Interior Department, which oversees the land
management bureau, declined Friday to discuss the issues
surrounding Rosenkrance's retirement. But they said there was no
danger that the agency would short of money needed for fire
suppression, in part because Congress had already authorized
emergency funding and was likely to provide more after the summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``One lesson from this summer is that we've got to ask Congress
for 100 percent funding of our requests,'' Babbitt said. ``But we
can draw on open-ended funding during the fire season. Money is not
an issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
