<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS TAKE A CUE FROM REPUBLICAN CONVENTION, BUT STRESS
DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to figuring out the dos and don'ts of
running a convention, the Democrats seem to have picked up a few
pointers from the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, when the Republicans were paying tribute to their
three living former presidents, Ford, Reagan and Bush, with brief
videos, Vice President Al Gore was watching intently from a beach
house along the North Carolina coast.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by the films, Gore got on the phone the next morning to
the sole living former Democratic president, Jimmy Carter, and
asked him to come to the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles next week.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who has had strained relations with President Clinton
and who spent the 1996 Democratic convention vacationing in
Montana, had been wavering about attending this year's event. But
when Gore called, he said yes. (An aide to Carter said the former
president had a good relationship with Gore.)
</P>
<P>
   And so on Monday night, the Democrats, too, will pay video
tribute to their last former president, while Carter looks on. (He
will not address the convention, his aide said.)
</P>
<P>
   Carter's tribute is not the only way the Democrats have designed
their convention to be like, or unlike, the Republican gala in
Philadelphia last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans ran a ``cotton candy convention'' without much
discussion of specific issues, the Democrats say. So their
convention will be loaded with policy discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, they will hold carefully staged panels featuring
people Gore has met during the campaign _ some of them just happen
to be Democratic delegates _ talking about the big issues, like
health care, crime and the economy. To provide a little Hollywood
flavor, the actor Jimmy Smits will help lead a session on health
care with Sen. John D. Rockefeller 4th.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore campaign has been reacting to everything Gov. Bush
has done since the beginning of the campaign,'' said Dan Bartlett,
a spokesman for Bush. ``It's not surprising they might be following
our lead on the convention as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But in another marked contrast to the Republican program,
congressional Democrats will have prominent roles in their
convention. In Philadelphia, the Republicans gave few prime-time
speaking slots to their congressional leaders, saying they were
trying to leave the limelight to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats contend the Bush campaign was trying to distance
itself from an unpopular Republican congressional majority. Not so
with Gore and the congressional Democrats, they say.
</P>
<P>
   And to prove it, they have laced their night sessions with
speeches by congressional Democrats. On Monday, all six of the
Democratic women in the Senate will speak, along with the president
and Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is running for senator from New
York. On Tuesday, the Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle of South
Dakota, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts will address
the convention, followed by the keynote speaker, Rep. Harold E.
Ford Jr. of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, women members of the House, Speaker Dick Gephardt
of Missouri and Sens. Rockefeller of West Virginia and Charles
Schumer of New York will all have prominent speaking roles. And on
Thursday night, Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa will speak before Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut is nominated as the party's
candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we trying to do things differently? Absolutely.'' said
Jennifer Backus, a spokeswoman for the Democratic National
Committee. ``This makes an understated political point: Unlike the
Republicans, everyone in our party is running on the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett replied, ``If they want to wheel out Washington-based
politicians to display as their face at the convention, that's fine
with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
