<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-POLE0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Showers wash out attempts to qualify
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ A series of showers washed out qualifying
Friday for the Global Crossing at the Glen Winston Cup race at
Watkins Glen International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   After a 75-minute practice this morning, the Cup cars will
attempt at 10 to set the field for Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   Rain hit the track Friday 15 minutes into the scheduled 2
1/2-hour practice session on the 2.45-mile road course that began
at 10:30 a.m. The rain finally stopped and the track was dry at
3:45 p.m. But track officials had to accommodate Cup practice and a
32-lap modified race before dark, so they moved qualifying to
today.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear brought its rain tires to the track, but no Cup teams
were eager to bolt them on. Defending champion Jeff Gordon said the
track would have to be in a state of ``perfect wetness'' for the
tires to be beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Benson, driver of the No. 10 Pontiac, probably best
summed up the sentiment in the garage: ``If it's raining, I think
the fans will have a great race to watch. In fact, I think I will
be sitting in the stands with them. Only a few guys have had a
chance to race in the rain, and I'm not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   MCREYNOLDS TO THE BOOTH
</P>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds' year-end departure as crew chief for Mike
Skinner's No. 31 Chevrolet has led to speculation that Skinner also
will be leaving, but team owner Richard Childress denies it.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds resigned his job with Childress this week to join FOX
television as an analyst on racing telecasts next season. He'll
team with Darrell Waltrip, who will be retiring after 29 years as a
driver. McReynolds will stay with Skinner the remainder of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skinner is going to be in that car for two more years,''
Childress said Friday. ``We had a meeting with our team. The team
said they want him, and he says he wants to stay. I've got a
contract for two more years with him. Everybody is happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting offers, and when he starts getting offers, I get
other drivers coming to me. It opens a chain. Everybody is trying
to make something out of something that isn't there. Mike Skinner
will be in the 31 car next year.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds said he still has hopes of being a team owner some
day, but he couldn't pass up the opportunity to make as much money
as he does in racing and still have a little more time for his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this 20 years,'' McReynolds said. ``My kids
are 11, 9 and 2. Linda and I have been married almost 17 years. If
I can give some more time to them and make as good a living as I'm
making now, still be in the sport, still do something I enjoy
doing, it's basically a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. LOVES BODINE
</P>
<P>
   Todd Bodine's team picked up a big-hearted sponsorship Friday.
The ``I Love New York'' logo, which features a heart, will be on
Bodine's No. 34 Chevrolet for Sunday's race and as an associate
sponsor on his No. 66 car in the Busch series the remainder of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Governor Mary O. Donohue made the announcement as Bodine
participated in a late-afternoon practice. He is a native of
Chemung, N.Y. The new money topped an already significant weekend
for Todd and his brother, Geoffrey. ``We're getting inducted into
the sports hall of fame in our hometown,'' Todd said, ``and that's
going to be really neat.''
</P>
<P>
   RACE INFO
</P>
<P>
   What: Global Crossing at the Glen.
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 12:30 p.m. Sunday; Watkins Glen (N.Y.)
International.
</P>
<P>
   TV: ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion: Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
