<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ELFERS-FASHION-PROFIL     08-11 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELFERS-FASHION-PROFILE-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOSENING UP AT LORD &AMP; TAYLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although dressed in a flowing, almost-formal black pants outfit
by Yeohlee, Jane T. Elfers, the 39-year-old merchant promoted
recently to be president of Lord &AMP; Taylor, says she is instituting
a new more relaxed dress code for executives _ and that she is
leading by example. ``See?'' she said, jovially pointing to her
feet, which were stuffed into a pair of pointed black pumps. ``No
hose.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfers took the helm of Lord &AMP; Taylor, a division of May
Department Stores, in June, facing a tide of disappointing sales.
Still, she has made it clear that she plans no sharp shift in
strategy for this venerable retailer. Her incremental loosening of
the dress code is a sign of her approach: an oh-so-gentle movement
of the stores to a younger, funkier market, she has demonstrated,
will be the hallmark of her tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are going to see a lot of new, young and exciting
designers,'' she said, ``but I think loyal customers will still be
very comfortable with us.''
</P>
<P>
   By consensus, Elfers treads a delicate path. On one hand, much
of Lord &AMP; Taylor's charm comes from being among the last of the
grand-dame Fifth Avenue stores to maintain its old-world ambience:
the dressing rooms are clean and spacious, the staff is shockingly
courteous and the merchandise is capaciously spaced.
</P>
<P>
   But its genteel atmosphere has also been a weakness in the
increasingly competitive and vamped-up retail world. In the women's
sportswear department, for example, the background music is more
likely to be easy listening (think Chris Cross), where at
Bloomingdale's, shoppers might be blasted with 'N Sync. Such
ambiance has helped give Lord &AMP; Taylor a reputation in the industry
and among some shoppers for being out of touch with what is young
and hip _ a potentially deadly faux pas in the retail world.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking clout with the profitable juniors market, the chain's 79
stores have seen sales per square foot decline from $237 in 1997 to
$218 last year, as much of the rest of retailing was seeing a
spectacular boom. Total sales have also suffered as the chain has
relied heavily on markdowns to entice shoppers. ``They've trained
their customers to play the coupon game,'' said Candace Corlett, a
partner at WSL Strategic Retail, a consulting firm based in New
York. ``You can see new-season merchandise and know that you will
get it on sale with a coupon within the season. It is a
self-defeating strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure for Lord &AMP; Taylor to right itself has been compounded
this year as May, which has been a smooth operator of chains
including Foley's and Filene's, has stumbled. While Federated
Department Stores, a big rival, has delivered strong sales
increases, May's growth has been so disappointing that, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial, stock analysts' consensus estimate
for annual earnings has continued to drop.
</P>
<P>
   But Lord &AMP; Taylor, which has been around for 174 years, has a
loyal customer base that might be alienated by too much updating.
``If you look at the demographics of Lord &AMP; Taylor, they are
older,'' said Shari Schwartzman Eberts, a stock analyst at J.P.
Morgan Securities. ``Of all the formats, they need to be the purest
to the tradition of the brand name,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If gradual change is the best path, the genial Elfers appears
well suited for the job, by both temperament and training. Elfers
grew up in Ho-Ho-Kus, N.J., and inherited her interest in the trade
from her father, Thomas H. Taylor, who was a marketing executive at
Sears. She graduated from Bucknell University in 1983 with a
business degree and joined Lord &AMP; Taylor in 1989 as a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 11 years, Elfers rose within the organization,
which has a reputation for rewarding efficacy rather than
revolutionary thinking. Her latest post was executive vice
president with responsibility for dresses, suits, sportswear, coats
and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Elfers is one of the youngest top executives in the
business; many of the stock analysts who follow May were unfamiliar
with her record. She says Lord &AMP; Taylor's problem is not so much
that it attracts older customers, but that it is perceived that
way. ``The younger customer is in the store,'' Elfers said. ``My
job is to position Lord &AMP; Taylor's image to make it more obvious
that she is here'' _ without, of course, forgetting about its more
traditional customers.
</P>
<P>
   A new campaign will begin soon, focusing on direct mail
advertisements with modern, colorful presentations of more
fashionable merchandise. For newspapers, the chain will keep its
distinctive, classic pen-and-ink ads of women with tiny upswooped
noses.
</P>
<P>
   All of that is not to say that Elfers is just starting a public
relations campaign. She is changing the merchandise mix to appeal
to a trendier customer. This spring, she introduced Betsey Johnson,
a wild woman of fashion known for pushing the more outlandish
colors and styles. She also added young contemporary collections by
French Connection and Nine West Sportswear, as well as more
offerings from the suddenly hot designer copycat genius, ABS by
Allen B. Schwartz. In lingerie, amid the staid Maidenform bras and
panties, there are now Lilly of France changeable bra straps in
animal print and hot magenta. Coming soon to the shoe department
will be teen-friendly Skechers.
</P>
<P>
   But such tweaking may not be enough in a roughly competitive,
fast-cycling fashion environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Wal-Mart and H &AMP; M are setting the shopping culture,''
pondered Corlett, herself a loyal shopper, ``is there still a place
for Lord &AMP; Taylor? I hope so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
