<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-INTERNET-$ADV1     08-11 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INTERNET-$ADV13-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE FUNDS, BUILT TO ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 (Editors: in references to Folio((fn)), please change double
parentheses to single brackets)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN and DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Michael Nadel is just getting started as an investor,
he says the mutual fund industry has already lost him as a
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Nadel, 26, a Washington lawyer, says he grew frustrated a few
months ago when he could not determine what was causing the sharp
decline in the value of his shares of an Internet stock fund.
Because most mutual funds disclose their complete holdings only
twice a year and with a significant time lag, he said, ``I don't
know what they own or how they make decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking that he could generate better returns by calling his
own shots, Nadel shifted a retirement savings account to
Folio((fn)), an Internet-based start-up that lets investors build
their own baskets of stocks and trade them as often as they like,
for a monthly fee of $29.95. ``I have no desire to be in a managed
fund any more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nadel is an early convert to a new breed of investment services
that are using Web technology to create alternatives to mutual
funds and traditional brokerage accounts. Since Folio((fn))
introduced basket investing for individual customers in May, a raft
of upstarts have appeared, promoting similar products they
variously call folios, e-baskets or personal funds. As they race to
harness the Internet's power to sell investment advice and
flexible, low-cost products, they threaten to siphon off some of
the $7 trillion that is now in mutual funds and the trillions more
parked in brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Each start-up is trying to carve out its own slice of the
spectrum between actively managed mutual funds and online brokerage
accounts. Some, like Folio((fn)) and Unx.com, will let customers
choose preselected baskets of stocks or build their own. Others,
like NetFolio and Smartleaf, plan to advise investors on how to use
baskets of individual stocks to manage their taxes, trading costs
and investment risks. Yet another venture, Personal Fund, which is
backed by the financial journalist Andrew Tobias, is selling
software to brokerage firms and financial planners that would help
them manage these baskets.
</P>
<P>
   All these young companies share an underlying belief that the
Internet provides a way for investors to combine the simplicity of
mutual funds with the greater control of owning stocks through a
brokerage account _ and that they can make money by exploiting that
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' executives argue that mutual fund shareholders
pay too much in taxes and fees to managers who exert complete
control, disclose too little about what they are doing and
routinely underperform the overall market. Online brokerage
accounts, on the other hand, leave investors to navigate a sea of
choices without much guidance, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of potential in the idea,'' said John
Rekenthaler, director of research at Morningstar Inc.
``Diversification with more customization, more ability to control
one's tax bill and potentially lower costs _ that's an attractive
combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not for everybody,'' he continued. ``It's a minority
audience that's going to want to make their own decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why start-ups like NetFolio and Smartleaf are
emphasizing the value of the advice they offer and are leaving it
to others to buy the stocks to place in the baskets. James J.
Atkinson, a fund executive, says this sort of unbundling of
investment ideas _ from the packages they come wrapped in _ reminds
him of the controversy that is roiling the recorded-music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, who heads the domestic mutual fund operations of
Investec Asset Management, says the Internet is opening financial
services to an early-stage ``disruptive technology'' like the one
that spawned Napster, the service that lets people swap music files
over the Internet instead of buying compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fund industry is no longer the way to get packaging and
convenience, they will lose the ability to control pricing of their
intellectual content,'' just like recording companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts say these personalized funds are more likely to
draw money away from mutual funds than from brokerage accounts. But
it is the brokerage firms that have begun to respond with plans for
baskets of their own. Meanwhile, executives of the two biggest
mutual fund companies, Fidelity Investments and the Vanguard Group,
say they do not see the new products as much of a threat to their
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors have already shown an appetite for new twists
on the decades-old format of mutual funds. In the last two years,
companies have rolled out dozens of products that look like mutual
funds but trade all day like stocks, including several from Merrill
Lynch called Holdrs. In the first six months of the year, assets in
all of these exchange-traded funds grew almost 50 percent, to $52.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the established financial companies are not waiting to
see if personalized funds will catch on. Etrade, the second-largest
Internet brokerage firm in trading volume, recently bought one of
the upstarts, the Electronic Investing Corp. of San Francisco.
Before year-end, Etrade plans to offer the ability to create and
manage baskets of stocks _ either directly to its customers or
through affiliated financial advisers. Etrade has not said how it
will price the products.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, the leading online brokerage firm, is developing
a similar service and may introduce it as soon as early next year.
But as the operator of the largest mutual fund supermarket, Schwab
has more at stake than most brokerage firms: about 30 percent of
its customers' assets are in mutual funds, which pay service fees
to Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Hubbard, a Schwab spokesman, said that fact would not
stop Schwab from offering baskets if the company's executives
decided to proceed. ``We don't believe these products represent a
direct challenge to mutual funds or to our relationships with
mutual fund companies,'' Hubbard said. ``The real issue is whether
there is enough investor interest.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James P. O'Shaughnessy, a money manager who sold his mutual fund
business this year to get into the business of advising investors
on setting up their own baskets of stocks, has no qualms about
butting heads with the fund industry. Visitors to his NetFolio Web
site are greeted with the headline: ``Goodbye mutual funds. Hello
NetFolio.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Shaughnessy, who has built a following among individual
investors who think there are ways to consistently outperform the
market, said: ``I've always thought that mutual funds were the
investment of choice for the masses. But I think the enabling
technologies of the Internet are going to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   For as little as $200 a year, NetFolio will advise investors on
buying one of more than 100 ``e-baskets'' of 5 to 40 stocks to fit
their investing goals and appetite for risk. The customers will be
able to make changes in the baskets or create their own from
scratch. The stocks will be held in brokerage accounts at Bear
Stearns, said O'Shaughnessy, whose desk in NetFolio's temporary
offices in midtown Manhattan is a folding table. Bear Stearns,
which has invested $1 million in O'Shaughnessy's company, plans to
offer NetFolio's service to its wealthy brokerage clients, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The folio approach has already caught on with some hedge fund
managers and investment advisers, said Matthew Ridenour, chief
executive of Unx.com, an online brokerage firm based in Burbank,
Calif., that specializes in such investing for the institutional
market.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, professional and individual investors alike have
sought ways to diversify efficiently by investing in groups of
stocks, through actively managed mutual funds, index funds, hedge
funds or other packages of securities. Ridenour predicted that as
much as $2 trillion could move from these existing funds into the
new breed of basket over the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Unx.com, which has assets of about $250 million, plans to
develop an offering for individual investors. ``My argument,''
Ridenour said, ``is that no one ever needs a mutual fund again.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Wallman, a former member of the Securities and Exchange
Commission who founded Folio((fn)), is trying to make a competitive
issue of the fees, expenses and taxes rung up by mutual fund
investors. Wallman says folios allow investors to better manage
their tax bill because they can sell losing positions to offset
profits on winners. Mutual fund investors are not able to manage
their taxes in that way, because fund managers decide when to
distribute gains.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in the typical mutual fund pay about 1.35 percent of
assets annually in management fees _ about $500 on the median
investment of $38,000. Many funds also charge sales fees when you
buy into, or sell out of the funds, some as high as 5.5 percent. If
that fee is paid up front, it reduces the amount that an investor
puts into the account _ a significant factor in certain
tax-deferred retirement accounts, like IRAs, in which the fee cuts
into annual contribution limit.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, paying a flat fee to set up a personalized
fund can also cost less than buying the same stocks through a
discount broker at $10 to $30 a trade.
</P>
<P>
   The new investment vehicles have attracted the support _ and
participation _ of some big-name financial experts. Steve Ross, a
professor of finance at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
is an adviser to Smartleaf, a start-up that wants to use the
Internet to deliver advice to individual investors on managing
trading costs, taxes and risk.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias, the Personal Fund co-founder who for years has been
warning investors through his books and columns about the hidden
costs of mutual funds, said he would be endorsing the concept as a
low-cost alternative to mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stuns me how many folks currently pay a sales fee to buy a
high-expense mutual fund over which they have no tax control,'' he
said. ``We can help them see how much better they could be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Sharkansky, the chief executive of Personal Fund, said
that mutual funds would be around for a while, but that, ``over
time, the mutual fund structure will be displaced by
mass-customized personal accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharkansky says companies that do not offer customized funds in
some form will risk losing investors like himself. Four years ago,
he was the kind of customer whom most brokers dream about: he had
been the president and the biggest shareholder of Prospero Systems,
an Internet communications company that was acquired for $3
million, and he wanted to invest his share of the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the costs of actively managed mutual funds, and
after a big brokerage firm quoted him commission rates as high as 2
percent, Sharkansky decided to pick his own stocks, using an online
broker. But in short order, he said, he became frustrated with this
stock-by-stock approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owning individual stocks is pretty appealing, but it's too
much damn work to have to pick them one at a time,'' he said. ``I
really wanted a more convenient solution which would help me get
reasonable diversification and also appropriate tax strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   When he could not find online tools for building a more coherent
investment strategy, he said, he decided to create his own. ``Just
as Pierre Omidyar invented eBay so his girlfriend would have a
place to buy Pez dispensers, I invented Personal Fund in order to
satisfy my own needs,'' Sharkansky said, referring to one of the
resounding success stories of electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Fund is preparing to offer free access to the
portfolio-planning and tax-management tools on its Web site,
www.personalfund.com, while it tries to strike deals to sell its
basket-management software to brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   Sharkansky cites his wife, Irene Song Sharkansky, as an ideal
prospect. A lawyer and a former employee of General Electric, she
owns ``a fair amount'' of shares in GE, one of the most widely held
stocks in the world. ``Now, when she buys a mutual fund in her
401(k) at work, what is she buying?'' he asked. ``More GE, which
she doesn't need.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is a problem that even the most cost-efficient index funds,
like Vanguard's 500 Index, cannot conquer. By definition, funds
that are intended to match the major stock-market indexes own
shares in the biggest American companies. Occasionally, they also
surprise their shareholders with taxable gains, because they must
sell shares of companies that are deleted from indexes and buy
shares of their replacements.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the person who wants to buy big stocks and big stocks
only, Vanguard 500 is a good choice,'' said O'Shaughnessy, the
former money manager, who spelled out his quantitative approach to
investing in ``What Works on Wall Street'' (McGraw-Hill, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our proposition,'' he said, ``is that most people don't want
to buy just big stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   All this talk about a brave new investing world does not seem to
be rattling executives of the biggest mutual fund companies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Pozen, a vice chairman of Fidelity Investments, said
he thought the products would run into regulatory hurdles. Doing so
could slow their development and drive up their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Purveyors of the new products assert that they are not subject
to the Investment Company . Act of 1940, which governs mutual
funds. ``These are people who are trying to make believe that
they're not mutual funds, but they're coming very close to the
line, and I would say they're actually crossing the line,'' Pozen
said. ``I think that issue will be litigated, and properly so.''
</P>
<P>
   John Brennan, chief executive of Vanguard Group and chairman of
the mutual fund industry trade group, the Investment Co. Institute,
was more dismissive. ``I think it's likely to be a niche product at
best,'' he said. ``It's hard for me to see the competitive
advantage in them.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Vanguard executives, including
Brennan, have spoken out against a new twist on mutual funds. In an
interview in the February issue of Money magazine, George U.
Sauter, head of Vanguard's indexing division, criticized
exchange-traded funds. But by May, after several competitors had
introduced them, Vanguard announced that it would also hop into
that arena.
</P>
<P>
   If the mutual fund giants doubt the viability of folios, there
are believers on the outskirts of the industry. Among them is
Atkinson of Investec, a London firm that manages $27 billion
worldwide. Investec's limited presence in the United States has
driven Atkinson to devise out-of-the-ordinary products _ including
a mutual fund that tracks an index created by the editors of Wired
magazine, as well as the first wireless mutual fund _ to attract
investors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, Investec is considering offering individual
baskets of stocks ``as some kind of complementary products to our
funds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``While it may cannibalize the fund business,'' he added,
``we're more interested in serving our investors' needs.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TherE are still plenty of skeptics who say they have seen
threats to the mutual fund industry come and go, but the whiff of
potential for the new personal funds seems to have many nostrils
flaring.
</P>
<P>
   A recent check of available Internet domain names that
incorporate the word ``folio'' revealed that dozens had already
been taken. Among them were Schwabfolios.com and
Vanguardfolios.com, though they were not registered by Schwab or
Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Those and other domains with the word ``folio'' were registered
by Peter Moran, the chief marketing executive for Turner Funds,
which manages $10 billion, after he read an article in the July 31
issue of Barron's that mentioned Folio((fn)).
</P>
<P>
   Moran said he had intended to reserve only one generic domain
name, managedfolios.com, and had registered the other names
unintentionally while experimenting at Register.com, a Web site
that charges $35 to reserve an Internet address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell mutual funds through Schwab _ obviously that's a faux
pas,'' he said, adding that he planned to cancel his transactions
for the Schwab and Vanguard domains. But he has been following the
development of Folio((fn)) and NetFolios for some time and wanted
to find his own way to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more of a California gold rush _ jump on your horse and
throw your stake in the ground,'' Moran said. But he is planning to
keep managedfolios.com, in case the concept takes off, he said,
adding, ``It might be the best $35 I ever spent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
