<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9323 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-ROSENBAUM13-COX     08-11 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROSENBAUM13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rosenbaum recaps eclectic inquiries
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 13.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The documentary filmmaker Erroll Morris calls Ron Rosenbaum
``one of the great masters of the metaphysical detective story,''
which certainly sounds more highfalutin on a dust jacket than
``really smart journalist.'' Rosenbaum describes what he does as
``journalism that asks the questions literature asks.''
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, there is no easy slot for Rosenbaum, a
pathologically curious and eclectic writer, a sifter of cultural
meaning. Catch him on one of his goofier assignments, and he's
whipping through a deadpan deconstruction of Mr. Whipple of Charmin
toilet paper fame, and getting off on a tangent about how the white
fluffy stuff is manufactured. History buffs who read his brilliant
1998 book ``Explaining Hitler,'' however, found a dense but
compelling amalgam of history, travelogue, psychological profiling
and philosophical meditation on the nature of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Remember all the hoo-ha about George Bush belonging to Skull and
Bones, the secret Yale society? Rosenbaum was unearthing all their
secret rituals back in 1976, years before it became fodder for
``Doonesbury.'' He also hung with ``phone phreaks,'' early '70s
kids who had figured out how to rip off Ma Bell big time, the
spiritual forefathers of today's computer hackers. ``Computer
freaking may be the wave of the future,'' he wrote in 1971, at a
time when practically no one envisioned what computers would
someday become.
</P>
<P>
   The geeky phone phreaks and the secretive Yalies are among those
covered in the 56 pieces (articles, essays, musings) collected in
``The Secret Parts of Fortune'' (the title is an obscure line from
``Hamlet''). It's a massive compendium of Rosenbaum's best work
from the early '70s, when he wrote for Esquire and The Village
Voice, through the '90s, when he's been a columnist for The New
York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, there is nothing as dated as the journalism of 20 to
30 years ago, which is why it's better to think of Rosenbaum's work
as metaphysical detective stories. He does the legwork, but more
important, he does the brain work. A literature student at Yale
before postmodernism took over the academy, he learned the art of
``close reading,'' of examining poetry for ambiguity and nuance.
Later, he applied those literary tools to ``trial transcripts,
autopsy reports, congressional-hearing records,'' in search of
``the shadow of some submerged truth that belies the surface
intention of the words.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Catcher in the Driveway,'' for example, Rosenbaum shows
off his legwork/brain work double play when he tracks J.D.
Salinger, the notoriously reclusive author of ``The Catcher in the
Rye,'' to his home in rural New Hampshire. Rosenbaum is by no means
the first nor last to try to sniff out Salinger; there is an entire
underground of Holden Caulfield obsessives who have made the
pilgrimage, and we meet some of them on Rosenbaum's journey.
</P>
<P>
   But as he ponders whether to violate the ``No Trespassing''
sign, Rosenbaum digresses into an explanation of the Zen koan
``What is the sound of one hand clapping?'' which Salinger used as
the epigraph to his ``Nine Stories.'' The answer to the riddle is
that it is awareness of the absence of sound, of silence, the
silence in which Salinger has submerged himself for decades.
Rosenbaum then jumps from the silence of the author to the silence
of God; it's amazing Salinger wasn't disturbed by the whirrings of
Rosenbaum's mind as he stood outside Salinger's house.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fox Mulder, he wants to believe. He listens, long past the
point where any normal person would run away screaming, to people
who have it All Figured Out: the JFK conspiracy theorists, the
researchers (some legit, some bogus) who search for the Meaning of
It All in Elvis, Hitler, Watergate or the Dead Sea Scrolls. He
sifts their ravings and reads their reports, these modern-day
Ancient Mariners, as he calls them, for kernels of truth, or at
least meaning. Skeptical but rarely cynical, he finds that even
cranks sometimes have something to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer is a television critic for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ON THE WEB: For an excerpt and an interview with the author:
ajc.com/(at)issue/books
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Parts of Fortune: Three Decades of Intense
</P>
<P>
   Investigations
</P>
<P>
   and Edgy Enthusiasms.
</P>
<P>
   By Ron Rosenbaum. Random House. $27.95. 799 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: 30 years on the offbeat beat.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
