<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9324 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-FALLTV13-COX     08-11 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLTV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall TV _ and other risky Bettes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 13.
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   She's practically the 17th ``Survivor,'' the 11th member of the
``Big Brother'' cast. If you've seen a moment of either show, you
know from the relentless promos that Bette Midler has a sitcom
coming on CBS this fall.
</P>
<P>
   And even by the beyond-Barnum parameters of TV hucksterism, CBS'
touting of ``Bette'' has been as outsize as Midler's own persona.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, viewers watching ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' on
ABC hear the drumbeat for Geena Davis' new sitcom, while Fox folks
are wondering what the deal is with the futuristic ``Dark Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately (or fortunately, in many cases), you'll have to
wait until October to see most of these. With the Summer Olympics
running until Oct. 1 on NBC, the official start of the fall 2000
season is the first week of October.
</P>
<P>
   What's coming among the 31 new series? You'll notice a lot more
African-Americans, the result of the NAACP rubbing the networks'
noses in their too-white schedules (but still a near-shutout of
Latinos). A smattering of star power: Midler, Davis, Tony Award
winner Gabriel Byrne, Yasmine Bleeth (hey, she's a star to a
certain section of the audience).
</P>
<P>
   There are shows that try to break the rhythms of traditional
network categories, mixing drama, comedy and a twist: NBC's ``Ed,''
CBS' ``That's Life,'' WB's ``Gilmore Girls'' and Fox's ``Boston
Public'' (the last from David E. Kelley, about high school
teachers).
</P>
<P>
   And as is the case every season, there are a few shows with
enormous promise, scattered among the six networks' schedules like
rubies in a cow pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the pilots have been sent to TV critics and ad buyers
yet _ some have not even been shot _ but of what's in circulation,
three stand out:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gideon's Crossing'' (10 p.m. Wednesdays on ABC) _ Andre
Braugher, the late great Frank Pembleton of ``Homicide,'' returns
to series TV as Dr. Ben Gideon. In the pilot, he reluctantly treats
a repulsively slick financier. Braugher and the writing are nothing
less than brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dark Angel'' (9 p.m. Tuesdays on Fox) _ In a
post-apocalyptic, semi-fascist America, a genetically enhanced
young warrior-woman (Jessica Alba) searches for her hidden past and
aids a cyber-journalist freedom fighter. Oh man, not another one of
those. The two-hour pilot, co-created by ``Titanic's'' James
Cameron, rocks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ed'' (8 p.m. Sundays on NBC) _ After losing his job, a
lawyer (Thomas Cavanaugh) returns to his small town of
Stuckeyville, buys a bowling alley and tries to woo his high school
crush. A sweet, offbeat hour that floats along on its own
wavelength.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bad news: Don't bet a dime on any of these shows
succeeding in the ratings. ``Gideon'' is too dark and off-putting
(Dr. Feelgood he ain't), ``Angel'' will crease your brain trying to
follow its convoluted story and ``Ed'' will battle tough
competition (``Touched by an Angel,'' ``The Simpsons'').
</P>
<P>
   A fall TV season is about the most ruthless Darwinian system
ever devised, and recent history is littered with great shows that
couldn't get the necessary audience. (Requiescat, ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' ``My So-Called Life,'' ``Now and Again.'')
</P>
<P>
   Also looking good enough, if not memorable:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bette'' (8 p.m. Wednesdays on CBS) has the brand name, the
marketing muscle and an A for effort; it just needs to settle down
and not be so frantic. Midler, very game, plays a version of
herself.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Geena Davis Show'' (9:30 p.m. Tuesdays on ABC) finds the
Oscar winner as a single career gal engaged to a widower (Peter
Horton) with two kids. It, too, is trying too hard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gilmore Girls'' (8 p.m. Thursdays on WB) is a very agreeable
mother-daughter show; like ``Ed,'' it has a tenderness you don't
usually see on TV. Also, like ``Ed,'' it'll soon be toast.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Fugitive'' (8 p.m. Fridays on CBS) is a ready-made
franchise and is pumped up more like the movie than the old David
Janssen series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The $treet'' (9 p.m. Wednesdays on Fox) gives us predatory
Wall Street slimebags; the fun is figuring out which one you loathe
the most.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Welcome to New York'' (8:30 p.m. Wednesdays on CBS) comes
from David Letterman's production company and is about a TV
weatherman from Indiana. But the guy isn't close to Letterman. Go
figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nikki'' (9:30 p.m. Sundays on WB) has Nikki Cox shedding her
bimbo image and pairing up with likable newcomer Nick von Esmarch
in a romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's NBC. Aside from ``Ed,'' you can turn to the
Peacock for your turkeys this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``DAG,'' the new sitcom starring David Allan Grier, is, uh,
watchable. But ``Cursed'' (which gets the post-``Friends'' Thursday
slot) and ``Tucker'' are like Satan's yardstick, the device by
which truly awful television is measured. The aforementioned Bleeth
show on NBC is called ``Titans'' because ``Rich, Messed-Up People
Having Sex'' wouldn't fit in TV grids.
</P>
<P>
   And the pilot for ``The Michael Richards Show'' has been
scrapped and is being redone from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Come fall, there will be much, much more. Consider yourself
warned.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
