<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-KENNY-ROGERS13-COX     08-11 2196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNY-ROGERS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At 61, Kenny Rogers is the oldest in CMA history to be up for
contemporary award
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting on the sofa in his Alpharetta mansion, country superstar
Kenny Rogers is surrounded by the kind of tokens of success that
would make any 61-year-old grateful for a winning ride.
</P>
<P>
   His massive living room looks designer perfect, as if poised for
the next gawking tour of homes _ black lacquer furniture,
cream-and-taupe upholstery, family photos grouped in silver frames.
On the wall are dozens of autographed photos: Kenny with a former
president (George Bush). Kenny with Lionel Richie. Kenny with Dolly
Parton. A massive, floor-to-ceiling cabinet, encased in
look-but-don't-touch glass, holds the awards _ two gold gramophones
for his Grammy wins, three shelves of crystal American Music
Awards, a slew of engraved statuettes signifying he was the
People's Choice for such 1970s hits as ``The Gambler,'' ``Coward of
the County'' and ``Lucille.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore that this is the home of someone who has
made it, the framed sheet music to ``We Are the World'' _
autographed by everyone from Michael Jackson to Cyndi Lauper _ is
carefully encased behind a frame over the fireplace (the music was
given to artists, such as Rogers, who participated in the monster
fund-raiser, the first of a long string of '80s ``cause''
projects).
</P>
<P>
   But this morning, as the sun comes up over the trimmed golf
course that slopes down from Rogers' back yard, the singer isn't
getting ready to tee off, catalog his awards or inspect his stock
portfolios online. In fact, taking it easy is the last thing on
Kenny Rogers' mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I really wanted?'' he says, his thick hand
casually tugging on his famous white beard. ``I didn't want to die
somewhere without having had a hit since 1985. I didn't want to go
out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Four decades into a recording career, Rogers isn't going out at
all.
</P>
<P>
   On this hot August morning, 300 miles away in Nashville, young
country starlet Lee Ann Womack is reciting the names of the most
recent Country Music Association award nominees for TV cameras.
Sandwiched in between such 20-something acts as Faith Hill and Brad
Paisley is Rogers, whose song ``Buy Me a Rose'' has been nominated
for single of the year.
</P>
<P>
   What Womack doesn't say is how utterly unlikely this moment is.
</P>
<P>
   Casually munching on a sausage bagel (``Oops,'' he says, at a
tray table in the kitchen. ``You caught me eating my McDonald's''),
Rogers seems remarkably nonplussed calm to have just become one of
the oldest artists in the history of the CMA awards to be nominated
for a major, contemporary trophy. While most of his peers wish for
one last gasp of notoriety _ perhaps a plaque in the Hall of Fame
or at least an episode on A&AMP;E's ``Biography'' _ Rogers has bucked
the system to become a player in the music business.
</P>
<P>
   His latest album, ``She Rides Wild Horses,'' was recently
certified platinum. The hit single ``Buy Me a Rose'' shot up
country charts _ past acts more than half his age _ to hit the No.
1 spot. His current single, ``He Will, She Knows,'' is also
climbing Billboard charts with a bullet. While many of his
contemporaries have retired to group-tour dinner theaters in
Branson, Mo., Rogers is in the middle of a cross-country tour of
major venues, including the Fox Theatre on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   What are the odds of a grandfatherly singer having such a career
resurgence?
</P>
<P>
   ``A million to one,'' says Phyllis Stark, editor of the country
charts for Billboard magazine. ``He was fighting a bias at country
radio against older artists, and against his own image. For years,
he was sort of perceived as someone that would appear on your
father's country station. The younger, hipper, hot country stations
weren't about to play Kenny Rogers, even to say his name.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers discovered that truth the hard way, more than a decade
ago, via an incident in an Athens grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother-in-law was in line buying groceries, and I was there
on the cover of People magazine. The fellow (at the cash register)
didn't know who she was, and he said, `If I see this guy on the
front of one more magazine, I'm gonna throw up.' At that point I
said, `Stop. Back up. I don't want to do anything else.' That's the
moment when the grass roots come up and tell you what's going on.
And they were sick of Kenny Rogers.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Michael Jackson and his glove or Madonna and her bustier,
the silver-haired crooner realized his smooth, master-of-ceremonies
style had become a caricature of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   At that same time, the city that Rogers had ruled for more than
a decade was going through a fairly radical makeover. By the early
1990s, Nashville stars were no longer middle-aged, pop-oriented
acts turning out such crossover tunes as Rogers' zillion-selling,
pillow-talk hit ``Lady.'' They were young, brash and wearing cowboy
hats. As artists such as Garth Brooks began dominating country
charts, Rogers retreated to his Athens, Ga. farm (where he was
living with fourth wife Marianne) to contemplate his future.
</P>
<P>
   He studied photography. He played golf. He immersed himself in
business ventures, such as his fast-food chain of chicken
restaurants, Kenny Rogers' Roasters. His marriage fell apart. Then
the tabloids got wind of a sexual harassment lawsuit filed by three
women who claimed Rogers engaged them in kinky phone sex. Suddenly,
the publicity machine that had made him a star was eating him
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe that people who are truly successful
create their own demise,'' he says today, reflecting on a darker
period in his life. ``I think you get to the point in your life
where you say, `You know what? Success is not as important as my
life.' And when you are that successful, you have no life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers made a different kind of life for himself _ which
included meeting and marrying Valdosta native Wanda Miller, 32, and
auctioning off his palatial Athens estate (to two men who later
backed out of the agreement) _ and moved to the landscaped suburbs
of north Atlanta. He started making music again, only to discover
he was out of step with the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a new record out, and was going to radio stations to get
audience reaction. But here's what I realized,'' he says, flashing
back three years. ``Everyone wanted to interview me. They were
totally in awe of what I had accomplished, and they'd talk about
how good I had been for country music. But they could care less
about what I was doing now. They'd put on my new song, turn it
down, talk over it. No one would listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mitchell, program director of Atlanta country station
Y-106.7, recalls the post-Garth days when Rogers couldn't get
noticed: ``He hadn't had a hit record on the radio in years. And he
wasn't even getting much airplay of the songs he had had on the
radio in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching his singles drop off music charts as fast as they
were released, Rogers came to a startling conclusion: ``All of the
people who were in radio when I had my success were gone. That was
a sad realization. ...I knew that if I was ever going to make it, I
had to reinvent myself.''
</P>
<P>
   So Rogers opened his own record label, Dreamcatcher
Entertainment, with just one artist: himself. He then spent months
looking for new songs, eventually turning to old friend Don
Schlitz, the man who wrote Rogers' signature piece, ``The
Gambler.'' Schlitz had penned a sweet tune about a little boy
playing baseball called ``The Greatest,'' the kind of meandering
story song Rogers has always delivered so well.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying only an acoustic guitar, Rogers began playing the tune
on the air at country radio stations. His timing was impeccable: It
was spring 1999 _ the beginning of baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had this theory that if you tear yourself down,
people always build you up,'' he says. ``So on the air, I would
say, `I don't know whether people out there would care to hear this
song,' and inevitably the phones would light up.''
</P>
<P>
   Billboard's Stark says the grass-roots demand for ``The
Greatest'' was ``astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That record came completely out of left field, and he worked
it like you wouldn't believe,'' she says. ``Kenny did a smart
thing. He didn't lower himself by calling stations that weren't
playing the record and beg for airplay. He's beyond that. He called
stations that were already playing it and thanked them.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for ``The Greatest'' was unlike anything Nashville
has seen in years. As soon as Rogers would perform the song in
studios of large and small radio stations, listeners would call to
request the tune. He opened ballgames, did interviews with
small-town papers, and generally made the public remember that he
was, well, a really nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some million-selling pop artists, who tend to wander
through their accomplishments like jaded royalty, Rogers exudes an
uncanny sense of how to navigate today's music business. He
analyzes it like a card dealer at a game, raising his fingers in
front of his face to draw an imaginary rectangle, calling country
radio ``a box.'' Pointing to the left, he cites the careers of
pop-leaning artists such as Shania Twain and Garth Brooks. Moving
his hand to the right, he talks about steel guitars, banjo and
songs about drinkin' and cheatin'.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was crossing over between pop and country decades
before today's hot acts ever held a microphone, Rogers believes he
has found himself somewhere in the middle of the pop vs. twang
debate. A new album, set for release in October, sounds decidedly
more country than many of today's rock-influenced Nashville hits,
with guest vocals by such traditionalists as Diamond Rio and
Paisley. ``Buy Me a Rose,'' the song that earned a CMA nomination,
features the pure mountain vocals of fiddle queen Alison Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I've included the country community with me on there,''
he says. ``For a while we thought we might go down the Americana
road. And if I have two or three hits off this record, I can do
anything I want. I can move the (country) box. But you've got to be
really careful when you pull power plays. Like, I think Garth
Brooks made a tragic mistake on (the way he handled the career of
his alter ego, rocker Chris Gaines). Musically, it was better than
anything I've ever heard him do. ... But that is one of the
tragedies. It's like the more you see somebody, as a rule, the less
you like them. He's doing exactly what he should do right now _
taking a couple of years off and getting out of the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' 10-year disappearing act may be the best career move he
has ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allen, executive director of the Nashville-based Country
Radio Broadcasters Association, says it's rare for an artist to
have not just one comeback, but two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anybody else who has come back as often as he
has. Remember, when he was with the First Edition, he was playing
rock. Then he paused, and came back in country. Now he's taken
another pause, and he's back again. I really think he is one of the
smartest people when it comes to the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking out a wide picture window at the sunlight bouncing off
his swimming pool, Rogers doesn't look like a man who is planning
to pause ever again. With 19 million-selling albums, he doesn't
need the money. His trophy cases barely hold room for another
award. His look _ the silver-tinged hair, neatly trimmed beard and
round cheeks _ is much like it was in his '80s heyday, though the
famously crinkly eyes appear to have been tucked and he's mixed a
little light red into his trademark gray locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody got on this new, young country thing, but what I
kept saying is, `Hey, guys, all you're doing is building
obsolescence.' You can be new but once, and only young for a while.
Look, we're not athletes. We shouldn't have to retire at 25 or
30.... You really need three things in life to be happy: You need
someone to love. Something to do. And something to look forward
to.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Rogers is looking forward to tomorrow. And the day
after that. Throughout his career, he never drank or smoked, and
credits his clean health habits for the energy he feels today.
However, longevity is on his mind. He chats about spending an
entire day at the doctor's to keep a close check on his heart. He
travels only on the weekends, avoids the Nashville party scene and
gets up with the sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a contemporary hit record changes everything. It
changes the audience's perception of me and, more importantly, it
changes my perception of myself,'' he says. ``When I walk on the
stage, I am no longer someone doing hits from the '80s. I am a
factor in the music business. And there is nothing worse than being
a nonfactor. ... As you get older, you stop striving for success
and start striving for significance. I think that's kind of where I
am. This is not about money, it's about a place in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
