<HEADER>
A9327 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DUNGEONS-DRAGONS12-CO     08-11 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNGEONS-DRAGONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Role-playing fans snap up copies of new handbook
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dungeons &AMP; Dragons, the ``mother of all role-playing games,''
has produced its first offspring in more than a decade. There's a
new player's handbook for the game in which participants act out
adventures filled with monsters and magic, wizards and warring
tribes. In the second day of sales Friday, metro Atlanta dealers
reported that D&AMP;D devotees had snapped up virtually every copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phenomenal, just phenomenal,'' said Kirk Stephens, owner of
the War Room, a 4,000-square-foot game, model and book store in
Norcross, Ga. ``Sales have been going crazy. We got 50 in
yesterday, and they're just about all spoken for. I'm getting 20
more today, and expect they'll be gone over the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the same story at Titan Comics in Tucker. ``We ordered
three (12-book) cases and have gone through two cases and have only
four books left in the last case,'' said Roger Davis, who works in
the store. ``It's been pretty brisk, like the Christmas season.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Johnson, a 13-year veteran of playing D&AMP;D, walked in less
than five minutes after Titan Comics opened for business Friday. He
headed straight for the new handbook, which is the third version of
the rules since the game came out 26 years ago. Johnson, a
23-year-old employee of a technology company who lives in the
Northlake area, said the friends with whom he regularly plays D&AMP;D
also are eager to see what has changed in this complicated game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping they've cleared up some of the rules problems that
they've had,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis says D&AMP;D creators have removed some of the arcane rules.
``There are things like mathematical calculations for the strength
of armor that have been taken out.''
</P>
<P>
   The new handbook won't appease critics who accuse D&AMP;D of
inciting teen violence. The game still calls for players to immerse
themselves in an imaginary world in which survival depends on
vanquishing foes, with weapons ranging from magic spells to bloody
swordplay.
</P>
<P>
   While Seattle-based Wizards of the Coast, which created and
markets the game, said the new handbook is more inviting for novice
players, Davis said the game remains beyond most young children.
</P>
<P>
   ``People under 12 don't have a chance,'' he said. ``It's played
by people 16 and over mostly. It's not for young kids. That's what
Pokemon is for.''
</P>
<P>
   John Head writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
