A9329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-BEEF-NYT &LR;      08-11 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-BEEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TEMPORARILY HALTS TRADE IN ARGENTINE BEEF 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ The United States and Argentina have
temporarily halted trade in Argentine beef because of concerns of a
possible outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease here.
</P>
<P>
   In statements Friday, the two governments called the step
precautionary and said the disease did not pose a long-term threat
to the growing trade in one of Argentina's most popular exports.
Nevertheless, the halt in shipments is more bad news for President
Fernando de la Rua in his lagging efforts to pry Argentina out of a
two-year recession.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's quota of beef sales to the United States is 20,000
tons a year and it is lobbying hard to increase the quota. The
United States refused fresh Argentine beef until 1997, when the
Agriculture Department lifted a ban linked to recurrent outbreaks
of foot-and-mouth disease in the early part of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine beef has become a gastronomic fashion in much of the
United States. Fed on grass rather than corn and allowed to roam on
the pampas, Argentine cattle produce beef that is lean and tasty,
if slightly chewy.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a week ago, Argentine officials found antibodies for
foot-and-mouth disease in 10 head of cattle smuggled from
neighboring Paraguay. Foot-and-mouth, rarely suffered by humans
although they can be carriers, is a virus characterized by fever,
weight loss and mouth blisters. As a precaution, the Argentine
government ordered the slaughter of 3,000 head of cattle in
northern Formosa, Corrientes and Entre Rios Provinces and suspended
most exports of fresh beef, not only to the United States, but also
to Canada, Venezuela, Central America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the cattle with the antibodies were not
actually sick.
</P>
<P>
   After Argentina took action, the U.S. Department of Agriculture
put a ``temporary hold'' on fresh, chilled or frozen Argentine
beef. Cooked and canned beef imports will still be allowed in.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Antonio Berhongaray said Friday that his
government took Washington's action in stride. ``There is no
inclination on the part of the United States to prohibit the import
of Argentine beef,'' Berhongaray said. ``This was a move that was
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement Friday, the American Embassy praised
Argentina for taking prompt action. ``As soon as this situation is
resolved,'' the statement read, ``exports of fresh beef will be
able to resume.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fourth largest beef exporter, Argentina expected to sell
350,000 tons of beef products abroad this year. Three months ago,
international monitors declared Argentine beef free of
foot-and-mouth disease, a finding that officials had hoped would
help them increase exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina made the decision to cease meat exports until the
sanitary situation is resolved,'' the Argentine Agriculture
Department said in a statement that predicted a resolution of the
problem in a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
