<HEADER>
A9330 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-MIDWAYBIO13-COX     08-11 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDWAYBIO13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mark Thompson at a glance
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 13.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Early years: Graduated from Atlanta's Northside High School.
Though enrolled in Andrew College in Cuthbert, Ga., he volunteered
for the Army when his birth date was chosen No. 1 in the draft
lottery. He made a snap decision to sign up to become a helicopter
pilot when he saw a poster listing the requirements at the
recruitment office. Served as an Army warrant officer 1970-72.
After his honorable discharge, started his first business operating
parachute centers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Professional: President of Phoenix Air, which provides
electronic warfare training services to the Air Force, Navy, NATO
and allied governments; and Midway Phoenix Corp., which operates
the Midway Atoll with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Resides: Primary residence in Cartersville. Also owns a
vacation home in Destin, Fla., and a cabin in the Alaska wilderness
outside Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  All in the family: Thompson is the divorced dad of a daughter,
18, and son, 17. His older brother, Dent Thompson, is vice
president of the Cartersville firms, where Mark Thompson's
British-born fiance, Jackie Sawyer, also works. His late father,
Romulus ``Tommy'' Thompson, a founder of the Atlanta architecture
firm Thompson, Hancock, Witte &AMP; Associates, designed his sons'
Cartersville headquarters as well as the Clipper House, Midway's
French restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pedal to the metal: The Midway Islands stock-car racing team
competes in ARCA (Automobile Racing Club of America) series events.
Thompson himself won the Easy Care Certified 100 at Charlotte Motor
Speedway and Media One 200 at Michigan International Speedway, both
in 1997. But he has not raced competitively since a near-fatal 1998
wreck at Atlanta International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  His go-for-it philosophy: ``I never picked a job or project
that I didn't find fun, because at the end of the day, when the
lights go out, they go out and anything you've left undone along
the way will always be undone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
