<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9332 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-JACKDANIEL13-C     08-11 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-JACKDANIEL13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    See the history, lore behind Jack Daniel's
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 13.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you don't know Jack, check out the new 16,000-square-foot
Jack Daniel Distillery Visitor Center in the tiny burg of
Lynchburg, in south central Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance, say howdy and ``Happy 150th Birthday'' to
Jasper Newton ``Jack'' Daniel, specifically, a 1,800-pound marble
sculpture of the pioneering distiller. The life-size statue _ all
of 5-foot-2 _ was moved to the visitors center after having stood
guard at Cave Spring since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 people are expected this year to take one of
the free daily guided tours. The tours show each step of the
process by which Jack Daniel's Tennessee Whiskey has been made
since 1866, making it the oldest registered distillery in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor center houses more than 30 exhibits and displays
about Daniel and his whiskey and includes a video presentation.
You'll learn such facts as: When Jack was 13, he and his cousin
Button drove wagonloads of whiskey down to Alabama where they sold
it to Civil War soldiers. And he steadfastly refused to grind more
than 99 pounds of corn a day to keep the government from stationing
a ``revenuer'' at the distillery.
</P>
<P>
   You'll know Jack, but you won't sample his whiskey (unless you
buy a commemorative decanter for $37.98). Moore County remains dry.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Visitor center is open daily from 10 a.m. to 5:30
p.m. except Thanksgiving Day, Christmas Eve, Christmas Day, New
Year's Eve and New Year's Day. Upcoming events: Jack Daniel's
Birthday Party and antique car show Sept. 2 and Jack Daniel's BBQ
on Oct. 28. 931-759-6180; www.jackdaniels.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
