NYT-08-11-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-MIDWAY13-COX     08-11 2977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MIDWAY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midway Atoll: At peace in the Pacific
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDWAY ATOLL _ As viewed out the window of our plane banking
toward the runway, these three North Pacific lily pads hardly seem
big enough to harbor all the history, nature and hope that have
survived here. But Midway Atoll looms large in American military
and natural history, and the native Atlantan piloting our
Gulfstream G-I, Mark Thompson, has invested millions to ensure its
future, so others can appreciate it _ and never forget.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Thompson and his newly incorporated Carters-
</P>
<P>
   ville-based firm, Midway Phoenix Corp., entered into a
one-of-a-kind cooperative agreement with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service to operate the atoll when the Midway Naval Air Facility
closed. At no cost to the American government or taxpayers,
Thompson's company maintains the imposing infrastructure for what
is now the Midway Atoll National Wildlife Refuge in exchange for
being allowed to run a low-impact eco-resort on the largest and
only inhabited of the three isles. The Fish and Wildlife Service
focuses on animal and habitat conservation and education.
</P>
<P>
   Visitation is limited to 100 at a time on the atoll, nesting
ground of nearly 1 million Laysan albatrosses (the world's largest
colony of ``gooney birds''), 14 other species of migratory
seabirds, the endangered Hawaiian monk seal and plenty more marine
life. Tourists sleep in handsomely updated 1950s officers quarters
on Sand Island, 2 1/2 miles long and 1 1/2 miles wide, and dine in
the old galley or a chic new beachside French restaurant tended by
a Paris chef. They pass their days viewing the wildlife, searching
out military memorials and artifacts or enjoying typical resort
diversions: fishing, scuba diving, swimming, sunbathing, bicycling
or plain goofing off. It's the first time the public has had a
chance to experience Midway in more than five decades.
</P>
<P>
   From our bird's-eye vantage point, the atoll appears the
definition of pacific: at peace. West of Honolulu by 1,200 miles,
2,600 miles east of Tokyo, 140 miles east of the international date
line, in a time zone virtually its own, it floats tranquilly, its
turquoise lagoon a jewel set against the vast, deep, dark blue
ocean. A bridal veil of white surf defines the 6-mile-diameter
coral reef, formed millions of years ago on the slopes of a
volcano, and sugar-white beaches outline the three islands within
it.
</P>
<P>
   Sand Island's 7,940-foot runway (as well as the one no longer in
use and quickly returning to nature on neighboring Eastern Island)
was integral in the heroic 1942 battle considered the World War II
turning point in the Pacific theater. It was also key in the
transfer of Midway's custody from the Navy to the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service. Without a private-sector partner versed in
running an airport, which Midway Phoenix's sister corporation does
in Cartersville, Fish and Wildlife probably would have been forced
to operate the refuge as a remote field camp with minimal or no
public access.
</P>
<P>
   That would've been fine for the gooneys and other fauna. But
Fish and Wildlife's Pacific Islands operations manager Robert Smith
says it would have been ``a tragedy'' for any American interested
in the legendary battle. Here, the patriotic can see firsthand
where outmanned U.S. forces ambushed the Japanese fleet, inflicting
heavy losses, including 3,500 soldiers, 300 planes and four
aircraft carriers.
</P>
<P>
   It's that potent combination of blood and beauty that captured
the imagination of Thompson, 49, when he began landing at Midway,
to refuel and occasionally bunk overnight, beginning in the
mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   An Army helicopter pilot in the Vietnam era, Thompson has
charted an intriguing professional course since his 1972 honorable
discharge. He went from running a parachute jump business to flying
freight, to working as an Alaska bush pilot, to starting a new, and
ultimately ultra-successful, aviation company to haul explosives as
a Department of Defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility and contacts that his firm, Phoenix Air Group,
gained internationally on those dangerous missions paved the way, a
dozen years ago, for its transition into a new role as a provider
of electronic warfare training to a host of U.S. and international
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's firm, named after the mythic bird that symbolizes
Atlanta's rise from the ashes, became a regular in the remote
Pacific. And Phoenix's success brought him riches to afford his own
stock-car racing team and countless other pricey toys, as well as a
quiet confidence to itch for even bigger challenges.
</P>
<P>
   That itch got a good scratching in the early '90s, when he
landed at Midway and heard the first rumblings of the Department of
Defense's plan to close the base, one in a series of post-Cold War
cuts. Not only would the airfield be closed, Thompson was told,
most everything would be demolished and the island returned to
nature _ all that history mothballed, buried or hauled away.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, whose sly sense of humor and insouciant flyboy
demeanor somewhat obscure a lavalike intensity, couldn't believe
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pearl Harbor gtest naval defeat. Yet Midway, which was the
greatest naval victory in American history, was going to be
abandoned,'' he says, his disbelief still as hot as embers. ``The
fact is, at Midway, lots and lots of Americans died so that people
today can sit at home and watch CNN on their color TVs and have
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to come off like a ``flag waver,'' Thompson pauses
and measures his words. ``I think this is _ and I don't want to
sound strange here _ hallowed ground. And yet they were going to
close it. It was like, `See ya.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Midway, the old veteran, had found a new defender.
</P>
<P>
   `No place like this'
</P>
<P>
   In the galley, holding a food tray with enough mileage on it to
be a Korean War relic, I met Norm Isaacs, host of ESPN's ``Inside
Big Game Fishing.'' We had just arrived. He, having taped fin
features around Midway for three weeks, was heading back to Hawaii
on the regular Aloha Airlines flight that night.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to have hooked a fresh ear, Capt. Norm boasted of catching
(and releasing) three marlin in the neighborhood of 500 pounds _
each _ offshore. ``It's not like if you don't get a marlin, you
don't get anything,'' he added. ``You can get your arms pulled off
by big wahoo or yellowfin tuna or. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   But Norm had something more than fish tales to share. Smiling
serenely, like a sun-baked Yoda, he said sagely, ``You won't want
to leave. There is no place like this anywhere. You have to be here
to fully understand it. By the time you leave, you'll know.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't sure what ol' Norm meant, and wondered if he'd been
bobbing on boats for a few too many days, but I was curious to find
out.
</P>
<P>
   In the initial impression at least, Midway doesn't look all that
cosmic _ it's more lost-in-the-'50s Mayberry than mystical
Marrakech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Town Center'' is a walking-distance circle of winding roads
dotted with white-painted, cinder-block former officers' homes
fronted by low fences and banana plants, hibiscus and other
flowering shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   Also here are the guest quarters, where we were whisked from the
airport _ well, as much as a loaded-down golf cart can whisk. The
rooms' glossy white-painted cinder-block walls, spotless gray
carpeting and slow-moving ceiling fans convey ``cool,'' and they
are as nice, if more austere than, those at a good chain hotel.
Despite the makeover, the three-story former officers quarters are
still called Bravo and Charlie, typical of the way the island is
being modernized while maintaining the thread of the past.
</P>
<P>
   As all-American as Midway's '40s- and '50s-built structures make
it appear, its ethnic flavor sneaks up on you. As was the case when
the Navy ran the atoll, the workers, who keep the power running and
water treated and all the other services going required in any
small town, are mostly foreign nationals. Along with 30 Americans,
there are 120 workers who hail from Thailand, Sri Lanka and the
Philippines. Their retreating presence _ a smile and a nod or wave,
but rarely any words _ is most clearly felt at the cafeteria line,
where a flavorful pork adobo might be warming beside the
standard-issue fries or spaghetti and meat sauce. In this galley,
Aunt Bee more likely would be whipping up some green curry and rice
than a blueberry pie _ or maybe both.
</P>
<P>
   That was just one small way that Midway veered from
expectations. As I explored Sand Island, my whole sense of
perspective got off kilter.
</P>
<P>
   First, there was the bigger-than-life scale of the military
infrastructure _ the massive pipelines at the fueling dock, the
water tower and tanks capable of storing 17 million gallons.
</P>
<P>
   But empty streets and the occasional driveway leading to nowhere
also made me cognizant of open fields where once there were
workplaces and homes for military personnel and their families _
4,000 residents during the Vietnam-era peak. For instance, all that
remains of the George Cannon School _ named for the hero who
refused to leave Midway's command post despite being mortally
wounded in shelling from Japanese ships returning from Pearl Harbor
_ is the marble marker out front. The school was one of more than
100 buildings razed during the Base Realignment and Closure
procedure that was part of the atoll's transfer to the Interior
Department (which runs Fish and Wildlife).
</P>
<P>
   In handing over the ``key to Midway'' (appropriately, in the
shape of a Laysan albatross), Navy Secretary John Dalton proclaimed
that the government was ``trading guns for goonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, plenty of a military nature remains, some of it off
unpaved paths that cut through thickets of ironwood trees. The
wandering guest can find a tiny graveyard for military doctors,
rusted weapons arsenals hiding under mounded soil, even the
battle-scarred command center where Cannon perished, becoming the
first Marine Medal of Honor recipient from the Pacific theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you find unexploded ordnance, please don't bring it into my
office,'' ranger Jennifer Schramm warned us during orientation,
garnering a laugh but not kidding. ``Mark it on your map and show
us.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where I went with my map, I was struck by how huge
little Sand Island seemed. The quietude had something to do with
it, as did the wide, long beaches, where I was more likely to
encounter a Hawaiian monk seal taking a siesta than a sunning
tourist. But at some point it finally dawned on me that the sense
of vastness I was feeling had more to do with the endless Pacific
than our wee place in it.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never felt so much like a speck in my life. Not that I was
complaining, cooled as I was by subtropical easterly winds by day,
watching billions and billions of stars and silver-edged clouds
float across the sky at night, all the while inhaling deeply the
cleanest air I've ever breathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you sit by the beach at night, you can't help but be awed
by the whole universe,'' said Pete Hansen, a California State
University professor emeritus. He visited in July as part of a
National Science Foundation-funded course that he hopes will be the
first step toward establishing a permanent teaching center on
Midway.
</P>
<P>
   Miracles of nature are almost commonplace here, and visitors
have the rare opportunity to witness some from an intimate
distance.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if most of the seabirds don't seem particularly
alarmed when humans are nearby, it's because they have important
business to conduct. They are pelagic _ of the ocean _ and they
need terra firma only to perpetuate their species. ``The only thing
they haven't figured out how to do on water is lay their eggs and
nest,'' explains Fish and Wildlife Pacific chief Smith. ``These
birds are hard-wired to return to Midway to reproduce and bring up
their young.''
</P>
<P>
   An astounding 2 million birds visit the atoll yearly. Alas, we
managed to miss the star attraction, the nearly half-million pairs
of Laysan albatrosses _ representing 70 percent of the breeding
population worldwide _ that nest here November to May. The goonies,
graceful in air with a nearly 6 1/2-foot wingspan, clumsy on the
ground, have the absolute run of the place _ nesting almost
everywhere and clacking, lowing and clambering about deep into the
night.
</P>
<P>
   But we were more than taken by the fairy terns, snow-white
creatures that swoop down and flutter right in front of visitors'
faces _ blurring the line between watcher and watchee. These
seabirds don't bother building a nest; they lay a single speckled
egg directly on a branch or other surface. Perhaps because of that
precarious arrangement, the parents serve up meals of freshly
snagged whole fish or squid. Under the eaves of the French
restaurant, the Clipper House, I saw one chick very slowly choke
down a guppy that was almost as big as he was.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't my most unforgettable nature moment.
</P>
<P>
   It came one afternoon on a fishing boat, heading out to go
snorkeling. As soon as we got far enough from the marina to
accelerate, we were out of nowhere joined by a school of 20
Hawaiian spinner dolphins that cavorted beside and in front of the
vessel like a class of kindergartners at White Water. Overhead,
perhaps sensing a fish snack in their future, a flock of sooty
terns had taken flight. I couldn't stop staring at their white
underwings, which looked solid aqua from the reflection of the
water _ which itself, of course, takes its color from the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Words barely do this scene justice _ you really needed to be
there.
</P>
<P>
   I was starting to see what Capt. Norm was talking about. I was
starting to sound like him, too.
</P>
<P>
   Man with a vision
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Mark Thompson heard that Midway stood a real chance
of being closed, he began brainstorming ways to make it
self-sustaining. He figured selling fuel to military aircraft and
ships would be a steady revenue stream. He thought he could strike
a deal with Boeing, which had a vested interest in keeping Midway's
airport open _ to meet a federal regulation in case of an emergency
involving one of its extended-range twin-engine 777 jets crossing
the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism, the third moneymaking idea he arrived at, was way
outside his usual realm, but he was excited by the idea of
Americans getting to experience the beauty and emotion of a place
so long off-limits.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Air's board didn'tHe hung tough, and his advisers,
recognizing how strongly he felt, ultimately deferred to his
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a bit of a bumpy flight since Thompson founded Midway
Phoenix, signed the 20-year agreement with Fish and Wildlife and
set out to save the little atoll that casts a giant shadow.
</P>
<P>
   It costs $4 million a year to keep Midway running, and Thompson
figured at best he could break even. The one thing he hadn't
counted on was how tough it would be to get tourists to make the
pilgrimage. Until recently, he was paying Aloha $64,000 a week for
twice-a-week charter service from Honolulu, and admitted that only
a handful of flights weren't money losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up in the morning and Midway cost you another $8,000
or $10,000 last night,'' he complained when we visited last summer.
``It's a substantial hit. It's not like I'm Ted Turner. I'm
light-years away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, while the partnership with Fish and Wildlife
has basically been solid, there have been some tensions in trying
to balance the rules of wildlife protection and the rights of the
paying customer. Thompson cracked sarcastically that Fish and
Wildlife's initial orientation sessions were so hard-line that it
was if guests were being welcomed to Alcatraz, not Midway.
</P>
<P>
   The ironwood trees, which provide shade and a windbreak but are
invasive nonnatives, became a particularly contentious matter. Fish
and Wildlife removed a forest's worth from uninhabited Eastern
Island, believing it to be impenetrable for goonies and other
long-wingspan birds in search of nesting habitat. That was fine
with Thompson, but he objected when trees were poisoned on Sand
Island, especially some on the south shore, where more than a few
veterans enjoyed sitting on a bench, looking out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't,'' Thompson recalls, ``impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But those differences have been ironed out, and there is
improved communication between the private and public partners.
There are several other developments over the past year that have
Thompson more optimistic about Midway.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Aloha replaced the charters from Honolulu with
regular scheduled weekly flights on 737s, lowering ticket prices
and Midway Phoenix's expense. Coverage in travel magazines,
including a piece by Paul Theroux in the July/August issue of
Islands, has helped fill more of those seats. There was even a
celebrity sighting at Midway recently: Barbra Streisand and hubby
James Brolin. Increased military refuels and overnight stays, as
well as the prospect of establishing the collegiate learning center
here, bode well, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always viewed Mark as somewhat of a visionary,'' says
Smith, one of Fish and Wildlife's main negotiators in forging the
partnership with Thompson's company. ``Midway probably pushes the
envelope of anyone's vision. It's an enormously complicated
situation and an unprofitable one. But I think it's Mark's way of
giving something back.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of sentiment is a mite mushy for the gung-ho Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a private citizen, keeping an island open for the American
public is insanity,'' he says, before adding drolly, ``but
everyone's got to have a hobby. Ted Turner raises buffalo; I ended
up with an island.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
