<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9334 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS13-COX     08-11 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Books make a connection that can't be found elsewhere
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 13.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a time when you're online or out of line, no one has much
good to say about the simple book. Oh, people still buy them and
quite a lot of them. But we'll soon be able to download books like
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Books, after all, are only vessels of information, and that now
can be conveyed electronically. And so there are people gathering
under the elms, waiting rather impatiently to give the book an
indecent burial.
</P>
<P>
   The time might one day come. But before it does, someone should
aver that books were never worth much if they were only
transmitters of ``information.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, they are the expression of a mind.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, while reorganizing the landfill I call my study,
I came upon a yellow pocket-size spiral notebook. I hadn't seen it
since I was in elementary school, but I recognized it at once. In
it, from cover to cover, I had entered words I did not know _
useful everyday words such as ``inveigh'' and gaily unvarnished
words such as ``gimcrackery.'' I wrote the word, the definition
and, in some instances, the sentence in which I'd encountered it.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, for some reason, that many of those words were
furnished by the novels of Jack London. He was not Henry James, but
there it was _ testimony to one mind not fully able to engage
another.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows why things lie in a back corner of the memory,
collecting dust, while more urgent matters _ a meeting, a new
organizational chart _ evaporate like dew drops? Who knows how
ideas leap from the pages of a book, disembodied like ghosts, and
take shape in other minds?
</P>
<P>
   Altering the world in significant ways
</P>
<P>
   Words are only the beginning. Hard or simple, they are both the
kernel and husk, the grain from which ideas sprout. There are no
ideas without words, but it is the ideas that germinate,
challenging and sometimes changing our understanding of the world
and even of ourselves. And the conveyor of ideas has been, for half
a millennium, the book _ taken for granted, under threat of
extinction, unappreciated these days even in its last refuge, the
public library.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is everyone's choice as the engine of change, but
more often than not it has been books and ideas that have altered
the world in significant ways. Examples abound. To name only three,
obvious to anyone who's dabbled in the humanities: Freud's ``The
Interpretation of Dreams,'' Charles Darwin's ``The Origin of
Species'' and the Declaration of Independence, drafted by Thomas
Jefferson and edited much to Jefferson's displeasure by John Adams.
(Writers and editors are ever at odds, even in rebellion against
authority.)
</P>
<P>
   In our own time, examples are more numerous than we realize.
Modern feminism did not originate with Betty Friedan's ``The
Feminine Mystique,'' published in 1963, but it achieved through
Friedan's book a rejuvenated spirit.
</P>
<P>
   It could almost be said that what we call the environmental
movement did begin with a single book: Rachel Carson's ``Silent
Spring.'' Originally published as a series of articles in The New
Yorker, it created a firestorm that has long since been forgotten.
Carson was a biologist with the soul of a poet. She had written
elegantly about sea life, but was a stranger to the thunderings of
oil men and lumber men and the harrumphing of politicians who did
their bidding. And, of course, she was a woman _ it was 1962, after
all _ and what would a woman know of things inextricably tied to
business and governmental policy? (``The little lady,'' she was
more than once referred to.)
</P>
<P>
   At roughly the same time, Michael Harrington's book ``The Other
America'' was making us aware of poverty even before President
Lyndon Johnson waged war on it. Indeed, the war on poverty had much
of its impetus in Harrington's book. Contrariwise, another book,
``The Unheavenly City,'' by sociologist Edward C. Banfield,
disputed the arguments for the Great Society and provided the
groundwork for the conservatism to come.
</P>
<P>
   Helping us to look inside ourselves
</P>
<P>
   In every decade, a small handful of books set new terms for
public debate, even if they do not alter the landscape. Recall the
chord that Allan Bloom's ``The Closing of the American Mind''
struck in the '80s, remaining atop the best-seller list for the
better part of a year. No one, least of all its publisher, had any
such expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Books reinforce or revise our understanding of what is just and
unjust, of what purposes are served or not served by our social
institutions. And then there are other books that read us more than
we read them, and, in so doing, help us know better who we are.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, preparing for a week at the beach, I conducted my
annual ritual of packing into a bag more books than will get read.
No room could be found for Bloom or Freud, and I don't believe I
even own a copy of ``The Feminine Mystique.'' But along with that
little yellow notebook I came upon a slender edition of Anne Morrow
Lindbergh's ``Gift From the Sea,'' published almost a decade before
anyone had ever heard of Betty Friedan.
</P>
<P>
   Slight in appearance, almost too poetic to be taken seriously,
it is a ``woman's book.'' My older sister told me it had been a
favorite of our mother's, something I had not known. Maybe I should
read it, I told myself, but I never did. Thumbing through it now,
the beneficiary not just of an education she never had but of more
years than were given her, I find not even a single unfamiliar
word. I find instead many familiar ones gracefully arranged.
</P>
<P>
   Their simplicity is deceiving, of course. But they were the
pellucid means by which one mind once engaged another, in ways I
can only guess at, and would now engage mine. In such a way do we
better know not just ourselves but others, too.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
