<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-EGYPTAIR-DOCUMENTS-BO     08-11 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-DOCUMENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTAIR DOCUMENTS REVEAL MORE ABOUT CO-PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The co-pilot of EgyptAir Flight 990, who US investigators have
alleged may have deliberately crashed the Cairo-bound jet last year
killing everyone on board, was investigated for allegedly exposing
himself in a New York hotel, according to documents released
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   That revelation was contained in FBI interviews that are part of
more than 1,600 pages of investigative work by the National
Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   The documents exacerbated the ill-will between the United States
and Egyptian officials, who find it inconcievable that co-pilot
Gamil El Batouty would take his own life and those of 216 others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careful examination of the FBI interviews indicates
(Batouty's) behavior in a New York hotel is largely
unsubstantiated,'' said Shaker Kelada, vice president of safety for
EgyptAir and a member of the Egyptian investigative team that
worked with NTSB investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempts to focus on this are a smokescreen _ designed to
divert attention from the fact there is no credible evidence
anywhere to indicate he intentionally dove the aircraft into the
ocean,'' Kelada said.
</P>
<P>
   But NTSB Chairman Jim Hall, in an unsual news conference before
releasing the documents, said, ``Our investigators have determined
that the interview may be relevant to our investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB normally releases a packet of documents when it holds a
public hearing into a crash. However, Hall said that the NTSB staff
``had recommended that a hearing not be held on this crash because
they believe there are no unresolved safety issues that require
such a forum.''
</P>
<P>
   NTSB officials have said there was no mechanical, weather or
air-traffic issue to explain the plane's rapid descent from
cruising at an altitude of 33,000 feet and that the only
explanation is the descent was a deliberate action by a crew
member. The plane crashed in the waters off the coast of Nantucket,
Mass. last Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Former NTSB board member Carl Vogt, a Washington lawyer who is
working for the Egyptian government, said he could not recall
another major crash where a public hearing was not held.
</P>
<P>
   EgyptAir, which is owned by the Egyptian government, issued a
statement saying the Boeing 767 may have crashed because of a
failure of components in the airplane's elevator control system.
The elevator, flaps at the back of the horizontal stabilizer, are
moved to change an airplane's pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Documents released Friday also included an Arabic transcript,
and an English translation, of the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   Those who support conflicting versions of how the plane crashed
are using the document to support their version of events.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript, Batouty, a member of the relief crew
who had not been scheduled to fly the plane until much later in the
trip, enters the cockpit shortly after takeoff saying he cannot
sleep and takes the first officer's seat.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, at 1:48 a.m., Capt. Ahmed El Habashy, says,
``Excuse me, Jimmy, while I take a quick trip to the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the sound of an electric seat motor operating and
the sound of the cockpit door being operated. A split second later,
Batouty responds, ``Go ahead please'' and, Habashy continues,
``Before it gets crowded. While they are eating and I'll be back to
you.'' Then there is another sound resembling the cockpit door
being operated.
</P>
<P>
   The transcript indicates the sound of a ``thunk'' and a
``clink'' followed by a cryptic utterance of three syllables with
the accent on the second syllable.
</P>
<P>
   Then, an unusual footnote adds to the mystery: ``The five Arabic
speaking members of the group concur that they do not recognize
this as an Arabic word, words, or phrase,'' the transcript states.
``Four Arabic speaking group members believe that they heard the
words similar to `control it.' One English-speaking member believes
that he heard a word similar to `hydraulic.' The five other members
believe the word(s) were unintelligible.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine seconds later Batouty whispers ``Tawkalt,'' or, ``I rely on
God,'' a phrase he repeats 10 more times in the next 89 seconds,
before the plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:49 and 44.98 seconds the auto-pilot is disconnected and at
1:49 and 48.42 seconds, Batouty says for the second time, ``I rely
on God.'' Then there are a series of thumps heard and then four
tones similar to the Master Caution aural beeper, as Batouty keeps
repeating, ``I rely on God.''
</P>
<P>
   At 1:50.06 Habashy is heard saying, ``What's happening? What's
happening?'' Batouty says, ``I rely on God.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 22 seconds, Habashy repeats the question, saying,
``What's happening Gamil? What's happening?'' He then says, ``What
is this? What is this? Did you shut the engines?''
</P>
<P>
   At 1:50.29 Batouty responds, ``It's shut.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, over five seconds, Habashy says, ``Pull. Pull with me.
Pull with me. Pull with me.'' Two seconds later, the tape ends.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of the voices revealed that ``the speaker of
`tawkalt' and `it's shut' was expressing no more than a first stage
of stress, while the speaker of `pull with me' was expressing a
higher stage of stress in response to the emergency nature of the
situation,'' one NTSB dcoument states.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the plane entered a steeper diver reaching nearly
supersonic speed, Batouty continued to utter ``tawkalt'' in a
passive voice. ``Speech duration often becomes shorter with
increasing psychological stress. However, the speaker of the phrase
`tawkalt' did not appear to display a significant shortening in the
speech duration,'' a NTSB report states.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB offered no analysis with the documents.
</P>
<P>
   But Egyptian sources said Batouty's actions as the plane began
its dive are reasonable, like slowing the engines to try and keep
airspeed down.
</P>
<P>
   If he had been trying to crash the plane, ``he would have locked
the cockpit door, given full power and rolled it over.''
</P>
<P>
   To restart the engines they would have to be shut down and
relit, which is why Habashy was saying ``shut the engines,''
Egyptian soruces believe.
</P>
<P>
   The plane did pull out of its dive and climb before plunging
into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The docket indicates that the aircraft recovered from a sharp
descent during the final movement of the flight, indicative of the
crew's attempt to save the aircraft,'' said Vogt.
</P>
<P>
   That the elevators were split _ Habashy's was trying to give the
plane lift, while Batouty's was pointing the plane down _ does not
indicate a struggle for control of the airplane, but rather could
have resulted from shock waves affecting the surface of the plane
as it reached supersonic speed.
</P>
</TEXT>
