<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9342 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-BROAD-965(2TAKES)     08-11 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-BROAD-965(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING HEAVEN AND EARTH FOR THE CITY OF ANGELS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He helped lead the charge to lure the Democratic
National Convention. He helped finish the fund-raising for a grand
new concert hall. He helped recruit the new school superintendent.
He founded one art museum and has plans to vastly expand another,
and to revive a historically anemic downtown. He's the mayor's best
friend, and helped bankroll campaigns to elect a new school board
and pass a new city charter. And, oh, did we mention, he's the
richest man in town, worth more than $5 billion?
</P>
<P>
   Almost every sphere of civic life in Los Angeles these days
bears the fingerprints of one soft-spoken, silver-haired
67-year-old man: Eli Broad, chairman and chief executive of Sun
America Inc., the financial services and investment giant that for
most of the 1990s was the fastest-growing company on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx-born son of Lithuanian Jewish immigrants who began his
career at 21 as the youngest certified public accountant in
Michigan history, then developed a home-building empire that
stretched from Detroit to Los Angeles, Broad has in the last few
years become his adopted city's ultimate go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Democrats arrive next week, Broad (rhymes with road) will
be front and center to welcome them, though perhaps not as front
and center as he wished. He did not get either the speaking slot at
the convention or the skybox at the Staples Center that he had
asked for. (He will have to share one of three skyboxes with the
local host committee, of which he is a co-chairman and to which he
gave $1 million while helping raise several times that.)
</P>
<P>
   But Broad, and his supporters and critics alike, are quick to
agree that he has flourished in Los Angeles as he could have in few
other cities, if any, where tradition, schools, clubs and old-boy
networks matter more and moxie and money matter less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple,'' Broad said as the afternoon sun filtered
over a broad swath of Beverly Hills outside his office window.
``It's a meritocracy. You can come here without the right family
background, which I don't have, the right religion, the right
political affiliation, and if you're willing to reach out and
really work and spend your time, energy and sometimes your money,
you're accepted. That's not true of most other cities in the world
or North America.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's one of the reasons I love the city, because it's
allowed me to do all this.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Commerce Secretary Mickey Kantor, who has known him since
they worked on Alan Cranston's campaign for the U.S. Senate more
than 30 years ago, said Broad ``is making a herculean effort to
fill a vacuum'' in Los Angeles' civic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he does something, he does it all out,'' Kantor said.
``Most of the time he succeeds. Sometimes he does not. But the fact
is that some people, whether they are threatened by it or resent
it, are irritated by anyone who pushes that hard and demands
action. He does not sit around and suffer inaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard J. Riordan, a Republican businessman who has
recruited Broad, a lifelong Democrat, to help in innumerable civic
causes, finds a more mischievous way to describe his friend's
bluntness: ``Eli knows nothing about foreplay.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention is a case in point. Broad was among a handful of
people who wanted the chance to show off the city's recovery from
the fires, earthquake, riots and recession of the early 1990s, and
was one of the original co-chairmen of the local host committee,
which pledged to finance the convention by raising more than $35
million and to use city money only for municipal services like
transportation and security.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles got the convention, but ever since has had trouble
raising the promised money. And Broad has complained publicly and
privately that at least one of his fellow co-chairmen, the record
and movie mogul David Geffen, failed to put up any of his own. Andy
Spahn, Geffen's chief political aide, said Geffen had made clear
from the beginning that he would help bring the convention to Los
Angeles but intended to direct his fund-raising and contribution
efforts to the actual electing of Democrats, beginning with Vice
President Al Gore. ``This is a case of no good deed going
unpunished,'' Spahn said.
</P>
<P>
   But bad blood and embarrassing headlines have lingered for
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened?'' Broad said of the controversy. ``I'll tell
you what happened. I got all the press, that's what happened. And
why did I get all the press? I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Every city has a cadre of civic leaders who support the elected
government, raise money for cultural institutions and charitable
causes, and offer private advice to public figures. In the 1950s
and '60s, Los Angeles itself had the Committee of 25, a shadowy
conclave of businessmen who helped pick candidates for appointment
or election to public office and generally set the tone in the city
until the Watts riots set off changes in the municipal power
structure.
</P>
<P>
   But with a shift in the region's economy from large, home-grown
industries like aerospace to multimedia conglomerates, with a wave
of mergers and acquisitions that have left downtown Los Angeles
lacking a headquarters of a single Fortune 500 company, and with
his own considerable ambition, Broad has emerged as a virtual
committee of one, or, as he puts it, a venture philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   That has not always endeared him to some officials and fellow
billionaires here, who complain _ invariably under cloak of
anonymity _ that he is too quick to claim credit, too willing to
hog the spotlight, too wrapped up in his own pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a big ego,'' Broad said matter-of-factly in a recent
interview in his 38th-floor headquarters in a Century City office
tower. ``I like to be thought of well.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Broad is also something of a rarity in an age of handlers
and spin doctors, consultants and retainers. He returns his own
phone calls, often flies commercial and still shows up at the kinds
of business breakfasts and chicken dinners that most moguls eschew.
A few years ago, he used his American Express card to buy a Roy
Lichtenstein at Sotheby's for $2.5 million, because he had
calculated the interest he could earn by delaying the payment for a
month. (He also got 2.5 million frequent-flier miles, most of which
he gave away to a local arts college for student travel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, people are visionaries or doers, but not both,'' said
Riordan, who regularly vacations with Broad on cruises and bike and
ski trips. ``He is both a visionary and an incredible doer, who
gets onto something like a pit bull and won't let go until he gets
it done. To a point that drives you nuts sometimes. On vacation,
you want to avoid him. He spent our last vacation, in Sun Valley,
on four major topics of what the city needed to do. I just wanted
to run the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked a couple of years ago what Broad wanted, one leading
Angeleno, a respected graybeard among the city's power players,
said, ``I think he wants to be the single most influential private
citizen in Los Angeles,'' adding with a chuckle, ``And he's got the
money to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad has not managed to get everything he wants _ his bid to
draw a National League Football team to a revamped Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum failed last year, as did his rivals' _ but it is
not for lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   Associates say that working for him is like working for a
jackhammer, that he is fair but relentless, keeping four aides busy
in his outer office alone. Golf and other leisure activities hold
not the slightest allure; he keeps his perpetual tan by holding
long business meetings or reading papers outdoors. His speech, in
the flat accent of Michigan, is economical, tending to omit
prepositions and definite articles, so that he says, ``I was born
New York City.'' Even his passion, collecting modern art, is a
business, with a curator and a lending foundation.
</P>
<P>
   His impatience is also legendary. A few years ago, irked that
the world-famous architect Frank Gehry was taking too long to
finish his new house in the Brentwood section, Broad hired another
architect, with the result that Gehry disowned the house. (That
feud threatened to derail Broad's later efforts to raise money to
finish the Disney Concert Hall in downtown Los Angeles, which Gehry
also designed, but things were smoothed over.) Just now, on the
site of two former houses in Malibu, Broad is building a
4,000-square-foot beach house designed by Richard Meier, who
designed the new Getty Center here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a white Richard Meier house,'' Broad said, ``and I think
white Richard Meier houses look great in beach areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad's current projects, both just beginning, are an expansion
of the Los Angeles County Museum of Art, on whose board he serves,
with a new wing and pedestrian arcade (an effort to which he will
presumably give millions of dollars), and a public-private
undertaking to revive Grand Avenue, the downtown street that is
already home to the Los Angeles Music Center and the Museum of
Contemporary Art (which Broad helped found 20 years ago) and that
will soon see the completion of the Disney hall and a new cathedral
for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles. Just talking
about downtown gets him so excited that he pulls out a pad and
starts sketching his vision of a new park, pedestrian-friendly
sidewalks, restaurants and so on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't own anything downtown,'' Broad said. ``All downtown
does is cost me a lot of money. But every great metropolitan area
needs a core. This city doesn't have any real core. It doesn't have
a place where people from different communities can come for free
concerts.''
</P>
<P>
   Some elected officials have complained that Broad involves
himself in matters, like selecting a new school superintendent,
that are none of his business. But he professes pride in such
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I think I'm doing what's right,'' he said, ``I think at the
end of the day people will appreciate it and I'll feel good about
it. And along the way I'm not looking for votes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
