<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9344 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-L.A.-MILKEN-PALS-$ADV     08-11 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-MILKEN-PALS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREXEL ALUMNI MOVE ONWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with LOS-ANGELES-FINANCE)  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 13)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Drexel Burnham Lambert filed for bankruptcy in 1990, it was
the end of an era in Los Angeles. No other Wall Street firm
commanded the attention that Drexel's high-yield bond operation
there did as it transformed not only the way that corporate America
financed acquisitions but the character of the city as well.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, many of those who worked at Drexel's offices in
Beverly Hills wondered whether they would ever work in such a heady
environment again. As things turned out, Drexel alumni are all over
_ working on Wall Street, running their own investment firms, even
comfortably retired, managing the millions of dollars they were
paid more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Milken, who masterminded the junk-bond unit, has
continued to make headlines even after he pleaded guilty in 1990 to
violating securities laws and served time in prison. Now Milken, as
a financier-turned-philanthropist, is the chairman of the Milken
Institute, which is involved in charities and institutions that
finance prostate cancer research and education. He is also the
chairman of Knowledge Universe, which invests in Internet concerns;
he was a co-founder of the company in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Winnick, a former senior vice president, has also received
much attention lately. He left Drexel in 1985, before it crashed,
to start what later became Pacific Capital Group, an investment
firm in Beverly Hills. More recently, he helped found Global
Crossing, an cable telecommunications concern that went public in
1998 and now has an eye-popping market capitalization of $23
billion, making Winnick a multibillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Off Santa Monica Boulevard in Century City, about a mile from
Global's headquarters, are the offices of Apollo Management. Apollo
was formed by a group of former Drexel executives, and several are
still there. John Kissick, Drexel's former head of corporate
finance on the West Coast _ and the man who took over as head of
the junk-bond department after Milken left _ is now a senior
partner at Apollo. So is Antony Ressler, a senior vice president at
Drexel who briefly managed the syndication desk, and Leon D. Black,
who works at Apollo Advisors in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lorraine Spurge, who preceded Ressler at the syndicate desk, is
now a Los Angeles-based adviser for a handful of investment firms
and a consultant for, among others, the music producer Quincy
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Moelis, a managing director, left Drexel in 1990, taking
nine associates with him down the street to Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, where he is head of corporate finance. Donaldson's Los
Angeles office has succeeded Drexel as the most prominent Wall
Street firm in the city today.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Milken's colleagues ended up in Southern California.
Peter Ackerman was Milken's right-hand man, heading the structured
finance unit and helping with the recapitalization of Mellon Bank,
among other companies. He is now an executive at Rockport Capital,
an investment firm based in Washington, making private investments.
He is also co-author of a yet-to-be published book called ``A Force
More Powerful: A Century of Nonviolent Conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street executives said Warren Trepp, Milken's chief bond
trader, moved to Lake Tahoe at some point and manages his own
capital now. Trepp could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   And Dennis B. Levine, the Drexel banker who pleaded guilty to
insider trading and started the firm's fall, is now president of
the Adasar Group, financial advisers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There were, of course, many executives who did not work at
Drexel but used its financial muscle and played a part in making it
an important player in the 1980s. One of the best-known was Thomas
Spiegel, the security-conscious former chief executive of Columbia
Savings &AMP; Loan Association, which was a big buyer of Drexel-backed
junk bonds. He caught the latest business wave and went to work for
MP3.com, the San Diego-based Internet music site, in business
development. Spiegel recently left MP3, but remains a consultant,
the company said. Spiegel did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
