<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-POLITICAL-MOVIES-LADN     08-11 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-MOVIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURE BEATS WACHING CONVENTIONS ON TV
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients on or after Aug. 14,2000) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the spectre of all local television programming being
ruined by boring convention or redundant civil unrest coverage this
week, concerned citizens might understandably wonder why
entertainment has to suffer when politics comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not necessarily the case. While our town _ more
specifically, Hollywood _ is not exactly known for making the kind
of trenchant political movies you'll find in the cinemas of, say,
Britain or Italy or Argentina, a solid body of astute work about
the American democratic process has developed over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   And our electoral system being what it is, many of these films
are pretty darn amusing. Here, then, is a list of 10 great
political films that you might want to rent in lieu of watching
this week's parade of empty speeches, prefab patriotism and broken
windows:
</P>
<P>
   ``All the King's Men'' _ This 1949, multiple Oscar-winner (best
picture, actor, supporting actress for Mercedes McCambridge)
remains American cinema's most perceptive look at populist
demagoguery. Adapted from Robert Penn Warren's Pulitzer Prize
novel, this thinly veiled critique of Louisiana despot Huey Long's
rise and reign benefits from Broderick Crawford's overwhelming lead
performance and a sophisticated insight into the mechanics of power
politics that Hollywood hasn't matched in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being There'' _ A superbly pitched satire that gently but with
utter ruthlessness skewers the Media Age dumbing down of our
national debate. Peter Sellers is the mildly retarded gardener
Chance who, upon the death of his guardian, leaves home for the
first time in his life. Knowing nothing but how to care for plants
and what he's seen on television, Chance proves the perfect
pablum-spouting politician for an electorate threatened by real
issues and drugged by vague platitudes. If Sellers, who died a year
after this 1979 release, were still with us, he could fit right in
at both parties' sappy symbolism conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Roberts'' _ Tim Robbins' self-starring, 1992 comedy about
a right- wing ideologue running for the Senate under folksy
camouflage suffers a bit from its own lefty smugness. Still, it's a
marvelously scathing look at the partisan monster behind the
presentable mask, and a timely caution against taking glib
catchphrases like compassionate conservatism at face value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulworth'' _ It's hard to tell where fiction ends and reality
begins in Warren Beatty's hallucinatory, 1998 cry for a free and
meaningful contemporary politics. As the corrupted title senator
whose crisis of conscience goes hand-in-hand with a truth-telling
nervous breakdown, Beatty cuts a marvelously poignant ridiculous
figure. When he considered actually running for the Democratic
nomination last year, the poignance was noticeably missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Candidate'' _ This 1972 Robert Redford vehicle was a good
20 years ahead of its time, predicting as it did how telegenic
blandness would triumph over philosophical commitment by the 1990s.
Amusingly, the film's director, Michael Ritchie, attended Al Gore's
alma mater, Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave'' _ In a year when two fortunate sons of old political
families are trying to convince us they're champions of the average
guy, Ivan Reitman's 1993 fantasy about an everyday schlub's
successful misadventures as a presidential surrogate is a welcome
tonic. It's ham-prone Kevin Kline's best and subtlest film
performance, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gabriel Over the White House'' _ Political looniness is hardly
a new phenomenon in America, as this utterly nutsoid, 1933 flight
of fascistic fancy demonstrates. Walter Huston is impressively
versatile as a corrupt, venal pol who, having recently been elected
to the highest office in the land, has a divine vision that turns
him into a zealous reformer _ who ain't shy about straightening
crooked America out at gunpoint. Alarmingly, the filmmakers seem to
condone his scorched earth approach to societal renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medium Cool'' Worried about potential violence between
demonstrators and police at this year's Democratic convention? Take
comfort in the fact that it couldn't be any worse than the
cataclysm that exploded around the party's Chicago conclave in
1968. Noted cinematographer Haskell Wexler was there, directing
this story about a cynical TV news cameraman's redemption odyssey,
and he got more than he bargained for when Vietnam protesters and
Mayor Daley's finest tore the city apart before his unblinking
lenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'' _ While Frank Capra's work has
always been marred by sentimental hokiness, you'd be downright
un-American if you didn't leave this 1939 movie with misty-eyed
pride in our imperfect but wonderful form of government. Only Jimmy
Stewart could persuasively pull off the role of the naive young
senator whose inextinguishable decency survives assaults from all
quarters of the capital and even inspires the scoundrels there to
change their unscrupulous ways. Did I mention that Frank Capra's
movies never remotely resembled reality either?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wag the Dog'' _ Y'know, we're really gonna miss Bill Clinton.
No matter how untrustworthy, craven and downright dishonest our
next president will inevitably prove to be, it's hard to imagine
either contender inspiring a black comedy as entertaining as this
1997 tale of White House sexual misconduct, media subterfuge and
distracting military adventurism. And I do mean inspiring:
Remember, this movie was made before anyone had even heard of
Monica Lewinsky. A president who can generate so much entertainment
simply by being himself will be one hard act to follow.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
