<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LA-RIORDAN-ART-NYT     08-11 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-RIORDAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIORDAN'S LAST TERM: LOS ANGELES MAYOR, STILL RESTLESS, AWAITS
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Photo NYT25  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Richard J. Riordan is not central casting's idea
of a big city mayor. He has no ``How'm I doin'?''  &UR; chutzpah &LR; , no
big stick. He is no speechmaker and is terrible on television. Even
some of his allies refer to him with a mix of affection and
exasperation as ``Mayor Magoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The other day, at a ceremony related to the opening of the
Democratic National Convention, which he worked so hard to lure
here, Riordan, a Republican, actually said: ``I just want to say
those three magic words: Welcome to the City of Angels.'' He once
introduced the actress Tyne Daly as ``Tiny.''
</P>
<P>
   But for seven years, Riordan, a multimillionaire businessman and
lawyer who works for $1 a year, has presided over this city's
recovery from riots, fires, earthquake and the worst recession in
50 years with implausible success. With pots of his own money and
the help of wealthy friends, he financed successful campaigns to
limit the terms of local politicians, pass a new city charter to
restructure government and elect a new majority on the school board
to deal with the beleaguered schools, all in a city where his
official powers are weak and political involvement low.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does this `I'm just a country lawyer' thing and very slick
guys in blue suits screw up because they mistake that facade,''
said a former chief of staff, Robin Kramer. ``Because there's a
very capable, highly intelligent and very practical guy behind
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For about two minutes on the convention podium on Monday,
Riordan will stand in a national spotlight as he welcomes
Democrats. When he set out to bring the convention to town more
than two years ago, Riordan had no idea that delegates would arrive
in the midst of the worst police corruption scandal in decades and
amid fears of disruptive street protests. But he was philosophical
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a father putting on a wedding for his oldest
daughter, and being driven nuts,'' Riordan said in an interview in
the City Hall conference room, surrounded by autographed
photographs of President Clinton and photos of the restless,
70-year-old mayor biking and jogging. ``And then at the last minute
everything comes together and you have a great time. But, really,
this has not been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a typical understatement. For months, convention
planning had been plagued by money-raising troubles, infighting
and, for a time, Riordan's inattention. But last winter, Riordan
began making phone calls to raise some $5 million to cover
convention costs and spent at least 10 percent of his time on
planning. In the end, President Clinton's top fund-raiser, Terry
McAuliffe, had to step in to raise the rest of the needed money.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Riordan has had to contend with the worst
police corruption scandal in decades, in which rogue officers have
been accused of fabricating testimony and, in at least one
instance, handcuffing and shooting an unarmed man, then implicating
him and watching him go to prison paralyzed from the waist down.
The U &UR; .S.  &LR; Justice Department, which was already investigating
patterns of police misconduct here, has threatened a federal civil
rights lawsuit if the city does not accept a binding agreement to
make long-promised changes in officer training.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year of his second term, even some longtime
supporters say Riordan seems adrift. Senior aides have left, and he
barely speaks to the man who was once his most trusted confidant,
William M. Wardlaw, a Democratic lawyer. Riordan has not forgiven
Wardlaw for backing the city attorney, James K. Hahn, a Democrat,
for mayor next year. Riordan, who built an unusual coalition of
white suburban homeowners and inner-city Hispanics in the wake of
the 1992 riots, favors a fellow Republican businessman, Steve
Soboroff.
</P>
<P>
   But Riordan insists he is busier than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say, and I really believe this, that if you start
thinking about a legacy, then it takes your eye off the ball,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, who was born in New York City came to politics by a
nontraditional route. After graduating from Princeton, and ranking
first in his class at the University of Michigan Law School, he
made a fortune in the leveraged buyout business in the 1980s. He
has a longstanding interest in education, and his private
foundation has given away $30 million over 20 years in support of
education. Riordan said he would like nothing better when he leaves
office than to finance and become the principal of a new charter
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an odd combination, because he's such a restless guy,
with a short attention span and his mind always seems to be jumping
to the next thing,'' said Patt Morrison, a columnist for The Los
Angeles Times and one of the members of the mayor's book club _ a
group that includes the actor Alan Alda and the sociologist James
Q. Wilson _ which gathers in the 40,000 volume library at his home
in Brentwood to tackle authors from Stendhal to Raymond Chandler.
``And yet he takes on a great deal of serious reading.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Riordan's biggest failure has been his inability to get
along with the 15-member City Council, all but three of whom are
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more words than reality,'' he said. ``Some of the
liberals who would like to be friendly with me are afraid, afraid
they'd be thrown out of the liberal cult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
