</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLAPSE OF CAMP DAVID TALKS DOES NOT APPEAR TO HAVE KILLED PEACE
PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Less than three weeks after the Camp David push for
a final Middle East peace settlement ended without agreement,
perhaps the most promising development, by the reckoning of many on
both sides, is what has not happened.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dire warnings of bloodshed were the talks to collapse,
there has been almost no violence. Apart from minor clashes,
Israelis and Palestinians have gone peacefully about their lives.
Coordination between Israeli army and police commanders and the
security chiefs for Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority,
unthinkable only a few years ago, has helped to keep things
tranquil. In fact, the Palestinian security forces have won high
praise from Israeli military commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the warnings that the Arab world would unite to
stiffen Arafat's resolve not to budge on his claim to Jerusalem.
Instead, a whirlwind tour of his traditional backers among Arabs
and Europeans has left Arafat with almost unanimous advice to keep
talking.
</P>
<P>
   When Arafat set out on his tour, the assumption was that he was
hoping for a common front in backing his refusal to compromise at
Camp David. But as his itinerary has lengthened, some diplomats
have come to suspect that the Palestinian leader is taking
soundings on whether the Palestinians' traditional backers,
especially Arab countries, might accept a compromise over
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's going to back off, and I don't say that he will, he's
going to need cover,'' one Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat traveled Friday to Moscow, one of more than a dozen
capitals on his itinerary, and encountered also there a reluctance
to see the peace process founder over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   According to news agency reports from Moscow, the Russian
president, Vladimir Putin, urged further negotiations with Israel,
and advised Arafat not to take ``unilateral decisions,'' the code
for Arafat's threat to declare a Palestinian state on Sept. 13 on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it extremely important to continue the negotiations,
and to reach a peace agreement,'' Igor Ivanov, the Russian foreign
minister, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important were upbeat comments from Arafat. ``We must
complete this peace process, no matter what difficulties we
encounter on our way, for the sake of our children, the children of
our children, for our future,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Egypt, where Arafat met with President Hosni Mubarak on
Wednesday, there were also signs of flexibility. Mubarak's chief
political adviser, Osama Baz, suggested a readiness for compromise
when he said on Thursday that Egypt would not dictate to the
Palestinians on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our role is not to deliver the Palestinians, and not to exert
pressure on them,'' Baz said. ``On the other hand, our role is not
to tell them to harden and not accept what is offered. Our role is
to encourage.''
</P>
<P>
   From Moscow, Arafat flew to Finland, and then to Norway, where
he was to meet with Shimon Peres, the Israeli who shared the Nobel
Peace Prize with Arafat and the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin for their roles in forging the 1993 Oslo agreement that
launched the Israelis and Palestinians on a process toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Oslo said Arafat had arrived later than expected,
forcing the cancellation of a formal dinner and putting the talks
with Peres in question.
</P>
<P>
   Although he now holds a relatively junior Cabinet post, minister
for regional cooperation, and was unexpectedly defeated in a
contest for the Israeli presidency last week, the 77-year-old Peres
had arrived in Oslo saying he hoped to discuss possible future
courses for a Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials continued to sound optimistic. Shlomo Ben-Ami,
Israel's new foreign minister, said in Barcelona that negotiations
with the Palestinians were continuing with the purpose of closing
``everything that needs to be closed'' and setting up a ``short and
decisive summit.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief U.S. mediator in the Middle East, Dennis Ross, was due
in the region next week for a round of meetings.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there were also voices of discord. In talks with
Iran's leaders in Tehran on Thursday, Arafat was told to hold firm
on Jerusalem. The visit assumed special significance because Iran
is the current chairman of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference, a grouping of about 50 Muslim states.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Muslim can allow holy Jerusalem to remain under occupation,
and the Organization of the Islamic Conference will never let any
deal be made over Jerusalem,'' the Iranian foreign minister, Kamal
Karrazi, told Arafat, according to news agency reports.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Saudi Arabia suggested that the Saudis, who claim a
special authority on matters like Jerusalem because of their
guardianship of the two holiest sites in Islam, Mecca and Medina,
have also opposed any compromise on Jerusalem. But several Arab
states in the Persian Gulf, under pressure from the United States,
have shied away from any all-or-nothing statements on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats believe Arafat may find new negotiations hard to
resist even without an Israeli compromise on East Jerusalem. In
this view, Arafat, who is 71 years old, may find it difficult to
slam the door conclusively on proposals put forward by President
Clinton that would give the Palestinians, apart from Jerusalem, a
settlement that only a few years ago would have seemed chimerical _
including Palestinian sovereignty over much of the West Bank,
Israeli acceptance of Palestinian statehood, and a Western aid fund
that could run into billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Even the proposals for Jerusalem could be hard to reject if
Arafat were to conclude that a majority of Palestinians, and
traditional backers like Russia and Egypt, would back, or at least
not oppose, their acceptance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0388 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ANGLICAN-BISHOP-ART-7     08-11 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGLICAN-BISHOP-ART-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSIONARY TO ENGLAND: A PAKISTANI-BORN BISHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, England _ For centuries the Church of England's
cathedral here has greeted pilgrims as the next-to-last stop on the
road to Canterbury. Signs inside still bid travelers welcome,
indicating the route's enduring popularity.
</P>
<P>
   But these days some wonder whether Rochester's bishop might one
day go to Canterbury himself _ not as a pilgrim but as successor to
the incumbent archbishop, whose retirement may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would make him the Church of England's spiritual
leader, first among equals among bishops of Anglican churches
worldwide, among them the Episcopal Church in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a historic transition, because Rochester's prelate,
Bishop Michael Nazir-Ali, is a native of Pakistan. At 50 he already
has the distinction of being the only non-Caucasian in the Church
of England to head a diocese.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four decades, Christianity has grown rapidly in
Africa and Asia, and with it the influence of African and Asian
prelates. But if Europeans and Americans are to grasp the
significance of the trend, it may have to be personalized through
people like Nazir-Ali.
</P>
<P>
   And there are several like him. There is the Rev. Setri Nyomi,
the Ghanaian who is the top official of the World Alliance of
Reformed Churches, which includes the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.).
There is Nyomi's counterpart at the Lutheran World Federation, the
Rev. Ishmael Noko, a Zimbabwean.
</P>
<P>
   And there is Cardinal Francis Arinze, a Nigerian who heads the
Vatican's interfaith council. Within the Roman Catholic Church,
whose African membership has more than doubled since 1975, the
cardinal is considered to be among Pope John Paul II's possible
successors.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in his study, the Cambridge-educated Nazir-Ali
discussed his rise to influence. ``I've never actually applied for
anything,'' he said. ``I've always been told to do it. I never
thought I would have a ministry outside Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice is heard well beyond Rochester, which lies east of
London. The Guardian, a leading British newspaper, recently
published an article he wrote calling attention to the persecution
of Christians in some Islamic nations. In it he cited verses in the
Koran supporting religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Christian convert, the bishop has Shiite Muslim
relatives. He speaks Arabic, Persian and Urdu, and is often invited
to speak in British mosques.
</P>
<P>
   Nazir-Ali has been an increasingly visible presence among
Anglican prelates since 1986, when Robert Runcie, then the
archbishop of Canterbury, invited him to help plan the 1988 Lambeth
Conference, the once-a-decade meeting of Anglican prelates
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   When the bishops met again in 1998, three years after he was
named to head the Rochester diocese, Nazir-Ali presided over a
conference committee concerned with Christian-Muslim relations and
spoke about Islam in the world. ``It was a very learned talk,''
said Bishop Henry N. Parsley of Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Parsley invited Nazir-Ali to lecture and preach to
Alabama Episcopalians. ``People in Montgomery and Birmingham were
delighted,'' Parsley said. But asked about his colleague's
ecclesiastical future, he said, ``Who knows, when you're talking
about the next archbishop of Canterbury or the next pope?''
</P>
<P>
   Nazir-Ali has heard the speculation and, not surprisingly, is
circumspect. ``I carry on with what I'm doing in the way I regard
as best,'' he said. Rochester and Canterbury, neighboring dioceses,
share major social work projects.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of Canterbury stands at the core of the British
establishment, by protocol outranking even the prime minister. To
live up to the job description, a prelate must function as local
bishop, leader of a diverse and often divided national church, and
head of a global religious association. Commenting on the
responsibilities, the bishop said, ``Nobody in their right mind
would seek such a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Others mentioned as candidates include Bishop Richard Charters
of London, who is considered close to the royal family, and
Archbishop Rowan Williams of Wales, who is admired as a theologian.
</P>
<P>
   The successor to the incumbent, Archbishop George Carey, will be
chosen by members of a royal commission as well as the prime
minister and Queen Elizabeth II. The decision may be years off.
Arch Carey, who was chosen in 1991, can remain in office until he
turns 70, in 2006. But he could step down sooner.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Canterbury's Christian significance dates to 597, when a
missionary monk named Augustine arrived to evangelize the
Anglo-Saxons. One of his colleagues ventured west to the Medway
River, becoming Rochester's first bishop.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese is economically varied, incorporating London's
eastern flanks, agricultural areas and new towns. Dickens grew up
within its boundaries. Now it contains an emerging religious
diversity, with Mormons, New Age spiritualists and others, part of
a wide challenge confronting the Church of England, whose problems
might have daunted even Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   Church attendance has fallen. Anglican leaders speak of a
society awash with ``pick and mix'' spirituality, in which people
choose beliefs and practices to suit their private needs.
</P>
<P>
   To examine the church's place in this, Nazir-Ali headed a
committee that published ``The Search for Faith'' (Church House
Publishing, 1996). The book examined the history of ideas
underlying contemporary thinking and suggested that the church find
new ways to communicate the Gospel to a postmodern culture.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop has also been quoted as saying that the British might
benefit from receiving missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Britain is a missionary situation,'' he said. ``There's no
question about that. It's a lack of even basic knowledge of the
Bible in the population. I was preaching at a Charles Dickens
international conference, and I was saying Dickens was immersed in
the Bible. But now when students study Dickens in university, they
have to be taught the Bible to understand Dickens.''
</P>
<P>
   The church, he said, ``needs help, in the sense of inspiration,
enthusiasm, new eyes to see its mission.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also need self-confidence. At times members of the clergy
inviting him to speak have urged him to avoid saying anything that
might upset people. But he still feels, as he put it, that ``the
world is willing to give us a hearing, as long as we're willing to
say something.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows reactions can be hostile. Earlier this year the bishop,
who is married and has two grown sons, touched off a furor by
writing that the church should continue to teach ``that having
children and their nurture is a basic good of marriage and not an
optional extra.''
</P>
<P>
   One critic, representing an organization for ``nonparents,''
called his message ``too offensive for words.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were pleased. ``That Michael would say that warmed my
heart,'' said Bishop Munawar K. Rumalshah, the head of a London
missionary society and a friend of Nazir-Ali for over 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nazir-Ali's becoming archbishop, his old friend said, would have
a big impact throughout the Anglican Communion _ would prove ``that
there is no black and white in Jesus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
