<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN SELECTION HINDERS DEMOCRATS' EFFORTS TO REGAIN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ However much the selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman
has helped the presidential prospects of Vice President Al Gore, it
has dimmed the Democrats' flickering hopes of regaining the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Those hopes shot up when Georgia's former Democratic governor,
Zell Miller, was named to replace Sen. Paul Coverdell, a
Republican, who died last month. Miller is generally conceded to be
a sure winner in November. That meant the Senate had 54 Republicans
and 46 Democrats, so the minority had to gain five seats for a
clear majority, or just four if Gore won and his vice president
could cast a tie-breaking vote.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lieberman is elected vice president, his replacement
under Connecticut law would be an appointee of Gov. John Rowland, a
Republican who would not pick a Democrat. And the Democrats would
need, elsewhere, to win five more seats than they lost, giving them
50. (Lieberman could break a tie, so the Democrats would control
the Senate.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Gore-Lieberman ticket loses but Lieberman, as expected,
wins re-election to the Senate, the Democrats would still need to
win, elsewhere, five more seats than they lost, for a total of 51.
If they only had 50, Dick Cheney, as vice president, would break a
tie against them.
</P>
<P>
   So the Democratic goal is back to a net gain of five seats. Even
the minority leader, Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, calls that
goal, with characteristic understatement, ``tough.'' For a gain of
that size, Democrats would need to get a victory by their only
embattled incumbent, Charles Robb of Virginia; take four out of
five open seats (in Nebraska, Nevada, New Jersey, New York and
Florida), and then defeat five out of the nine more or less
vulnerable Republicans, in Delaware, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri,
Montana, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Washington and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle called those gains ``doable.'' Dave Hansen, political
director of the National Republican Senatorial Committee, said they
were far-fetched. He added that the choice of Lieberman had
``negated Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Republicans have taunted Lieberman to withdraw to
show his confidence in a Gore victory. But he is not taking the
bait.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, interviewed Tuesday on CNN's ``Larry King Live,''
said: ``I have the intention of continuing to be a candidate for
re-election to the Senate. The people in Connecticut have asked me
to do that. The law allows it. It is a very complicated process in
Connecticut. If I withdrew from the election, a very small group of
people would choose the nominee. And I don't know if that is fair
to the people of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said there ``could be a special election next year,'' so
the loss of a seat would be only temporary. But, in fact,
Connecticut law would have Rowland's appointee serve until the
election of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle had been given the same misinformation about Connecticut
law. He got it from Gore himself. Daschle had spoken publicly about
his hope that Gore would not choose a senator from a state with a
Republican governor. But on Monday afternoon, Daschle said in an
interview that Gore had told him that very day that Connecticut law
called for a special election early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle offered a different view on Thursday. He said what he
now knew about the law ``makes our situation a little more
complicated.'' He said, ``Connecticut is a very Democratic state,
and I'm sure when the election is held we'll retain it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign did not respond when asked how Gore happened
to misinform Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen of the Republican Senatorial Committee conceded that the
choice of Lieberman helped Democratic Senate candidates in Florida
and New York. In 1996, Jews cast 10 percent of the vote in New York
and 6 percent in Florida. But Hansen said, ``We're going to win New
York'' anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
