<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-PROSPERITY-ART-8     08-11 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PROSPERITY-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ON ECONOMY IS WONDERFUL, BUT IT ISN'T HELPING GORE YET
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With less than three months until Election Day,
Vice President Al Gore faces a crucial and perplexing question: Why
does his presidential campaign not seem to be benefiting from an
economy that is as good as it gets?
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the Democratic National Convention next week in Los
Angeles, Gore can point to an array of indicators that would seem
to work powerfully to the advantage of the incumbent party in the
White House, especially when today's economic conditions are
compared with those that the Clinton administration inherited 7 1/2
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is down to levels not seen in a generation. Incomes
and homeownership are up. Budget deficits have given way to huge
surpluses, and the stock market has generated staggering wealth.
</P>
<P>
   It may be too early to count the economy out as a big factor in
Gore's favor. But so far, prosperity's glow has done little for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has he trailed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas in nearly
every national poll for months, but his efforts to portray himself
as a superior steward of the economy have fallen flat.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times/CBS News poll last month found that 75 percent
of voters believed Gore was likely to keep the economy strong if he
was elected president, compared with 71 percent for Bush, a
statistical dead heat. Asked which candidate would do a better job
of managing the economy, respondents in a Business Week/Harris Poll
last month favored Bush by 51 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, the economy is not cutting for Gore as much as
I would like,'' said Al From, president of the Democratic
Leadership Council, an organization of centrist Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts and officials of both parties said Gore might
have hurt himself to a degree by failing to stick to a simple,
consistent message about the economy, especially during the spring,
when he veered into issues like the Elian Gonzalez case. And they
said Bush had artfully tried to shift the debate from who gets
credit for prosperity to what should be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the real difficulty for Gore might be that times
had been good for so long that voters took prosperity for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's biggest problem on the economy is that this recovery
has been going on much longer than any previous recovery,'' said
Robert Reich, who served as labor secretary in President Clinton's
first term. ``It's become almost background noise, and people
assume the good economy will just keep on rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do voters show little willingness to grant credit to
Gore, analysts said, but the electorate does not see either
candidate as having much control over an economy that seems
increasingly driven by technological advances, globalization and
other forces beyond the control of any administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the economy we're in now, the public doesn't buy the idea
that the economy is good because of the Clinton-Gore
administration, and they'd be just as disinclined to credit the
Republican Congress,'' said Mickey Edwards, a former Republican
congressman from Oklahoma who is now a professor at Harvard's John
F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experience suggests that when Election Day rolls around,
a fat and happy electorate is likely to think hard before throwing
an incumbent party out of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts _ as well as Gore's aides _ point to the last time
a sitting vice president ran for president with a strong economy at
his back _ in 1988, when Bush's father faced Gov. Michael Dukakis
of Massachusetts. For most of the summer, Bush was behind despite
nearly six years of steady economic expansion and an unemployment
rate that had been halved, to 5.4 percent, since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll in June 1988 showed Dukakis ahead of Bush by 52
percent to 38 percent, and when asked which candidate would do a
better job keeping the country prosperous, voters ranked the
candidates evenly at around 40 percent. But by November, Bush had a
52-35 advantage on economic management in the Gallup poll, and he
went on to win the election comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   ``History says that people's perceptions of a sitting vice
president's capability with regard to the economy can change,''
said Andrew Kohut, a pollster who is director of the Pew Research
Center for People and the Press. Mark Fabiani, Gore's deputy
campaign manager for communications, said most voters have not yet
focused on the election, and that when they do, they will conclude
that Gore has supported and shaped the policies that have brought
the economy to where it is and that his approach is more prudent
than his rival's.
</P>
<P>
   And he said Gore would seek to link Bush's economic plans to
those of his father, who presided over a recession that contributed
to his loss in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the end will focus on the economy as the most
important issue, and in the end will focus on whether we're on the
right economic track and whether they are better off than they were
four or eight years ago,'' Fabiani said. ``The answers to those
questions are good for Gore and bad for Bush.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If anything, Gore is stressing the economy more as the campaign
progresses, using a message that has two distinct components.
</P>
<P>
   One is unabashedly populist, and is aimed in part at the party's
liberal base and at people who do not feel they have fully
benefited from the economic boom. It is built around the assertion
_ challenged by Republicans _ that Bush's economic platform amounts
to tax cuts for the wealthy, an overhaul of Social Security that
would leave the retirement security of working people at risk and
deference to powerful special interests like oil and pharmaceutical
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a promise to continue the policies of fiscal
responsibility that helped bring about budget surpluses and reduced
interest rates. This portion of his message is intended to stress
continuity with one of the most successful elements of Clinton's
record and to appeal to moderate swing voters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
