u s BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT &LR;      08-11 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTIN USES HIS SHORT GAME TO CUT RIVALS DOWN TO SIZE
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BLANC, Mich. _ After starting the day in first place,
Woody Austin played well enough to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 5-under 67 and hoping to end a five-year victory
drought, Austin entered the weekend with a two-stroke lead after
Friday's second round of the Buick Open. He was 14 under for the
tournament (63-67, 130), two strokes ahead of Rocco Mediate (12
under), who shot a 64, and four strokes ahead of Hal Sutton (10
under, 67-67), who was in third place.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the enormous crowd that followed Tiger Woods around
Warwick Hills Golf &AMP; Country Club saw him struggle to his second
consecutive 70, leaving him 4-under, 10 strokes behind Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, of course, still believed he could win. But Austin still
believed in himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very important for me to play aggressive and not be
happy where I was,'' said Austin, who started the day with a
two-stroke lead after blistering the course with an opening-round
63. ``My wedge game has been absolutely perfect this week. Every
chance I got with a wedge, I hit a really good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin did not putt as well as he did Thursday, needing 29 putts
Friday compared with just 21 putts in the first round. But Austin's
ball striking remained excellent, in a round that included six
birdies and just one bogey. Instead of looking uncomfortable with
the lead, Austin looked confident.
</P>
<P>
   As for Woods, it was clear that he was not as sharp as he
intends to be for next week's PGA Championship. Woods drove the
ball fairly well, but his approach shots lacked their usual
accuracy. For Woods, the goal is to peak next week. But on a course
where birdies have been plentiful, Woods still had time to get
himself in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it before,'' Woods said of his ability to come back,
before he headed to the practice range. ``I'm hitting the ball
well, just not as well as I'd like to.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for Austin to play any better. His only
victory on the PGA Tour came at the 1995 Buick Open. Currently
108th on the tour money list, Austin could use a title, or at least
a strong finish, to help restore his confidence. After 36 holes,
and with his best chance to win in a long time, Austin was eager to
see how he would react this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will probably be shaking in my shoes when I tee it up
tomorrow,'' Austin said. ``But if you're nervous and you're playing
well, it's easier to overcome. If you're nervous and you're playing
like a dog, you're going to play like a dog. I think I will be
fine.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
