<HEADER>
A9367 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLAN     08-11 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY LOOKING FOR A BREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Kansas City defender Nick Garcia was
complimentary of the Los Angeles Galaxy's 5-1 victory over the
Wizards last week at Arrowhead Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a great game plan. They executed very well in the
final third,'' said Garcia, a Rookie of the Year candidate. ``In
midfield, they dominated us. All the credit goes to them for
getting five goals on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something that coming into the season I would not
have expected anyone to do. We are definitely looking to go into
Los Angeles and trying to get our three points back.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (13-6-5, 44 points), which once held a nine-point
cushion over its Western Division rivals, could watch its lead drop
to a single point with a month remaining if the Galaxy (11-7-7, 40
points) can beat the Wizards at the Rose Bowl tonight. Game time is
7 p.m. with a concert by Los Tigres del Norte following. Admission
to the concert is free with paid admission to the game.
</P>
<P>
   For Wizards coach Bob Gansler, tonight's task is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that we couldn't hold serve last week,'' he
said, sounding like a tennis player. ``But if someone breaks you,
you just have to break them right back.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid isn't concerned with a letdown. If the
Galaxy stumbles tonight, last week's big win is a wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to feel good about that game because we've got a
bigger one in front of us now,'' said Schmid. ``Our veterans know
what is at stake. If we don't take care of them at home, then we've
done nothing with this home-and-home series.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Wizards, Galaxy striker Luis Hernandez, who
scored a goal and notched two assists in last week's victory, is
unavailable because of World Cup qualifying commitments with
Mexico. However, Garcia admitted that Hernandez, along with
midfield general Mauricio Cienfuegos, make the Galaxy a dangerous
team heading into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watched some of the goals they scored on us at practice
this week,'' said Garcia. ``Those two are definitely in sync. He
and Cienfuegos are much better oriented with each other. You can't
give them much space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-11 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DOGGED BY QUESTIONS ABOUT PLAYBOY MANSION FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Pa. _ Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joseph
Lieberman came to this small factory town outside Philadelphia
Friday to praise working women. They visited Little Souls, a
company owned by women that makes handcrafted dolls, where they
called for equal pay and expanded day care benefits. Both paid
elaborate homage to their own wives, daughters and mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my sister and I were growing up,'' Gore told a small
audience made up mostly of women, ``there was never any doubt in
our minds that men and women were equal, if not more so.''
</P>
<P>
   Unmentioned, though, was the one topic that had their audience
buzzing Friday morning: aggressive efforts by Gore and the
Democratic National Committee to scuttle a Democratic
congresswoman's fund-raiser next Tuesday at the Playboy Mansion in
Los Angeles. Several women here described the site as the sleazy
epitome of a society that treats women not as equals but as sex
symbols to be exploited and degraded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not the right image,'' said Mary Beth Pratt, 57,
chief marketing officer of a Philadelphia law firm.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the Gore campaign had hoped to highlight proposals
for helping working women, it instead found itself facing questions
about values, its tolerance for sexually explicit publications and
campaign contributions from Playboy executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure do enjoy that Playboy money,'' Jim Nicholson,
Republican National Committee chairman, said, all too happy to
portray Gore and his campaign aides as morally selective for
accepting contributions from Playboy executives even as they
criticized a Democratic congresswoman, Loretta Sanchez, for
planning a fund-raising event at the Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now Sanchez has resisted pressure from Gore's
emissaries to move the event, which was planned to raise money for
Hispanic voter registration efforts. But Friday morning, in an
appearance on NBC's ``Today'' show, she said that she was now open
to finding another location, so long as it has the ``kind of
cachet'' offered by the Playboy mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never been about the Playboy mansion,'' Sanchez said, one
day after her speaking role at next week's Democratic convention
was canceled by Joe Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. ``It's been about putting on a good event and raising
money.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, an executive with Playboy Enterprises who spoke
on condition of anonymity confirmed that Sanchez had decided to
move the event, and two managers at a blues club run by B.B. King
in Universal City, Calif., said that Democratic Party officials had
approached them about holding the event there. But they said no
final decision had been reached.
</P>
<P>
   In a Fox television interview Friday, Gore said that he
supported Andrew's action, and during the appearance here at Little
Souls, Lieberman pointedly emphasized that a Gore-Lieberman White
House would work to help families teach strong moral values to
their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work _ Al, Tipper, Hadassah and I _ to help renew the
moral center, the moral health of this nation, to support the
mothers and fathers who are trying so hard to raise their kids,
give them good values, give them discipline in the face of so many
competing forces,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the audience that Tipper Gore _ ``long before it was
easy to do so'' _ embarked on a campaign against explicit song
lyrics ``to try and help Americans to raise PG kids _ as she said _
in an X-rated society.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's efforts to put the Playboy matter behind him were
complicated by his refusal thus far to return a $1,000 campaign
contribution from Hugh Hefner, Playboy's founder, and a $500
contribution from his daughter, Christie Hefner, the chief
executive of Playboy Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apples and oranges,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's campaign press
secretary, when asked the difference between holding a fund-raiser
at the mansion and accepting campaign contributions from Playboy
executives. The Hefners' contributions, he said, represented only a
tiny fraction of the money raised by the Gore campaign, while the
fund-raiser is a major event for some 600 guests.
</P>
<P>
   Heather L. Parker, a 31-year-old elementary school teacher who
works summers at Little Souls, failed to see a distinction. By
taking money from the Hefners, she said, Gore has endorsed an
enterprise based on the exploitation of women.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't be taking their money,'' she said. ``He should be
separating himself completely from them. It doesn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rosenzweig, executive vice president of Playboy
Enterprises, defended the company in an interview, saying that
Playboy is as ``American as apple pie'' and asserting that Gore and
other party leaders were ``following political correctness right
out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very disappointed in the party,'' he added. ``I would
never have expected this from a party that we have supported
financially and editorially through the pages of the magazine for
many years. It's very saddening to us to see this. We wonder what
pressure groups in the party are exerting this pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   According to campaign records, Playboy executives have made
several contributions to Democratic candidates. Rosenzweig
contributed $500 to the Clinton/Gore campaign in 1996, and another
$500 to the 1998 Senate campaign of Geraldine Ferraro. Helen
Isaacson, a senior vice president for Playboy, donated $500 to Bill
Bradley's campaign this year. In 1996, Christie Hefner donated $250
to John Dingell, a veteran Democratic congressman from Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's sudden focus on Playboy, of all things, was only
one of the factors that diverted attention from Gore's intended
message Friday. On Thursday, Clinton apologized once again for his
affair with a White House intern. Clinton also said that Gore
should not be blamed for Clinton's moral failings.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in the Fox interview Friday whether he agreed that he
should not be blamed for Clinton's affair, Gore simply praised
Clinton for his remarks while predicting that voters would make
decisions based on the future.
</P>
<P>
   In between questions about Playboy and Clinton, Gore gamely
pressed on Friday with his campaign message, asserting that George
W. Bush's proposed $1.6-billion tax cut is, at its core, a huge
gift to the nation's wealthiest families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to these facts,'' he told an audience of about 150
crowded into a musty warehouse loft here. ``Under the Bush-Cheney
plan, for every 10 dollars of tax relief that would go to the
richest 1 percent, middle-class families would get a dime, and the
poorest families would get a penny.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, his proposal to cut taxes by $500 billion
is ``targeted'' toward single mothers struggling to pay for day
care, toward couples trying to finance their children's college,
toward families trying to provide long-term care for sick or
elderly relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day Gore traveled to Detroit to formally accept the
endorsement of the United Auto Workers and then to New York City
for a fund-raising dinner that raised $500,000 for the Democratic
Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
