<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HOPE THEY'LL HAVE THE ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ There are no questions about handicapped-parking
placards. No questions about quarterbacks who haven't taken a
meaningful snap. No questions about waves of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A season like UCLA's in 1999, in which the Bruins collapsed to
4-7 after back-to-back 10-win seasons, is one they're happy to have
behind them. Nobody more so than UCLA coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, his father died, his son-in-law was diagnosed with a
brain tumor that proved to be benign, his youngest daughter was
married and he was dealing with the fallout from the parking scam.
Then star quarterback recruit J.P Losman quit during fall camp, the
early games turned into a quarterback tryout, and injury after
injury were followed by loss after loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just tears you up,'' Toledo said of his fourth season as
head coach. ``When it was over, I was ready for it to end''
</P>
<P>
   The unranked Bruins begin practice today in preparation for the
season opener against No. 3-ranked Alabama on Sept. 2 at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But already Toledo's having a better year. This summer, he
enjoyed a trouble-free vacation playing golf around Southern
California and fishing for salmon in Alaska. And probably thinking
about some of these questions, ones that will determine if this
season is just as pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   __ QB or not QB? Whoever wins the job _ Cory Paus or Ryan McCann
_ the Bruins need much better play at the position than last year.
They don't need Cade McNown, just someone who doesn't make mistakes
and can execute routine plays consistently so the Bruins can put
the ball in the hands of playmakers like DeShaun Foster, Freddie
Mitchell, Brian Poli-Dixon and a trio of talented tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   __ Can't they have Kansas State's schedule? The Bruins will know
where they stand _ on both feet, they hope _ by the end of
September. After the opening-day test against Alabama, they face
No. 6 Michigan two weeks later, again at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In between could be a dangerous game against Fresno State.
Finally, on Sept. 23, they play their conference opener at Oregon,
which has a 14-game home winning streak. A 3-1 start and the last
two games of the season _ at Washington and home to USC _ might
mean something; a 1-3 start and it could be `99 all over again.
</P>
<P>
   __ Will free safety cost dearly? Traditionally the marquee
defensive position at UCLA _ Kenny Easley, Eric Turner, Don Rogers,
and Shaun Williams were all first-round draft picks _ it has been
makeshift since Williams left three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, former walk-on Joey Strycula filled the position
admirably when nobody else claimed it. This year, with talented
sophomore Lovell Houston out for the season with shoulder surgery,
little-used, fifth-year senior Jason Zdenek gets the first crack at
the job that could eventually go to true freshman Ben Emanuel.
</P>
<P>
   __ The O (no!) Line again? The offensive line was a complete
disaster in `99 _ decimated by injuries, inexperience and poor
play. The Bruins allowed 35 sacks, including six against USC, when
they lined up with the No. 4 center and one healthy reserve. Paus
was a victim of the pounding, suffering a separated shoulder and a
broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the running game totaled only 1,191 yards rushing
and 2.9 yards per carry _ the Bruins' worst output since 1963. So,
it's not necessarily good news that everyone is back.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Brian Polak, who has started 23 consecutive games,
and junior center Troy Danoff, who was the best lineman until a
season-ending knee injury, are solid. The key might be the progress
of three former Parade All-Americans _ sophomore tackles Bryce
Bolander and Mike Saffer, and freshman Shane Lehman, who is pushing
senior Oscar Cabrera at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   __ Say what? The Bruins, so help them Edgerrin James, swear the
defense will carry them early in the season. And when's the last
time anyone's said that around Westwood? The Bruins have allowed
more than 28 points per game three of the past four years and
haven't led the conference in scoring defense since 1987. Yet, with
Bob Field back as defensive coordinator, they'll have the same man
in charge after having three different coordinators the past three
seasons. Also, the only projected starters who don't have a full
season in the lineup are freshman tackle Rodney Leisle and senior
safety Jason Zdenek.
</P>
<P>
   __ Star-crossed or star power? Defensive end Kenyon Coleman and
tailback DeShaun Foster are considered future first-round NFL
picks. Linebacker Robert Thomas and defensive tackle Ken Kocher
could be.
</P>
<P>
   All four have shown flashes of greatness the past two seasons,
but only Coleman has so much as made second-team All-Pacific-10. If
these four have breakout years, so will the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   __ Will there be a rush to judgment? UCLA allowed seven running
backs to rush for 100 yards or more last season and lost six of
those games. In the other loss, Stanford didn't have to run; it
passed for 465 yards. Defensive ends Rusty Williams and Coleman,
and 300-pound tackles Leisle and Kocher will find out against
Alabama and Michigan if this year is going to be different.
</P>
<P>
   __ Can they stay healthy? The Bruins, through injuries and
suspensions over the handicapped-parking scandal, used 45 different
starters last season. Toledo said the most he'd ever used at UCLA
was 31. While the Bruins can't expect a repeat, they aren't deep at
receiver, and Foster _ the focal point of the offense _ has missed
considerable time the past two seasons with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   __ Secondary concerns a primary problem? This unit is much like
the quarterback position: The Bruins don't need to be spectacular,
just solid. The past two seasons, the secondary has had two
problems _ it couldn't cover and couldn't tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Jason Bell, often the victim of his own
aggressiveness two years ago, is back for his fifth year after a
heel injury cost him last season. Ricky Manning, who succeeded and
failed spectacularly last season, will start at the other corner.
Marques Anderson, who was suspended from school last fall, returns
with 15 additional pounds of muscle and a new position (strong
safety).
</P>
<P>
   If this unit isn't better, Alabama's Freddie Milions might
litter the Rose Bowl field with jockstraps next month.
</P>
<P>
   __ Big plays or bust? With playmakers like Foster, Mitchell and
Poli-Dixon, the surest sign that offensive coordinator Al Borges'
offense is back will be the big play. In 1998, when the offense
nearly carried the Bruins to the national title, they scored 25
touchdowns of more than 15 yards. Last year they managed just
seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
