<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIREDEATHS0812-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Story contains statistics and recall info only.
 &HT;    By Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ From 1992-98, tire blowouts were a
``related factor'' in 118,764 crashes nationwide, according to the
NHTSA. But that does not mean the defective tires were the primary
cause of the crashes, according to National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration spokeswoman, Liz Neblett.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville-based company Bridgestone/Firestone on Wednesday
recalled 6.5 million all-terrain tires. Motorists with certain
15-inch radial ATX, Radial ATX II and Wilderness AT tires should go
to a licensed Firestone dealer to get their tires replaced at no
cost. But be prepared to wait because the replacements are out of
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The only Wilderness AT tires being recalled are those marked
with the Department of Transportation code beginning with VD. This
indicates that the tire was made at a plant in Decatur, Ill. The
code is usually found on the tire's inside sidewall, meaning you
must crawl under your car to find the code.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone ATX, ATX II and Wilderness tires have been used as
original equipment on the Ford Explorer, the industry's top-selling
SUV, since 1991. The tires also are factory-installed on General
Motors, Toyota, Nissan and Subaru SUVs and pickups.
</P>
<P>
   NHTSA is not expected to complete its investigation for another
couple of months. Motorists can report problems with their tires by
calling the agency at (800) 424-9393.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
