<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NJ-URBAN-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A RESCUE PLAN FOR CAMDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 12:
</P>
<P>
   When bankrupt cities are taken over, it is usually by
state-appointed control boards that dictate fiscal policy until the
cities return to solvency. The board that Gov. Christie Whitman of
New Jersey has proposed for the dysfunctional city of Camden may be
tough by New Jersey's standards but no tougher than the control
boards that revived the prospects of municipalities like New York
City, Chelsea, Mass., and, most recently, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Camden's difficulty in governing itself was underscored last
week when the City Council asked the state to assist in running the
city attorney's office, which has been incapacitated by scandal.
Instead of digging in their heels, state legislators who represent
Camden should embrace the Whitman plan and improve on it.
</P>
<P>
   Camden's troubles began in the 1970s, when middle-class flight
and job loss combined with corruption to undermine civic stability.
Three of the last five mayors have faced federal charges and have
presided over a government that has consistently failed to provide
even the most basic city services. In recent years Camden residents
have complained about undrinkable tap water, raw sewage in the
streets, abandoned buildings and open-air drug bazaars, all threats
to public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Whitman takeover plan argue that the state is
partly to blame, given that Camden has been under state supervision
through an existing finance board that can question or veto
decisions made by the city government. This arrangement has been
ineffective, partly because the board is precluded from taking
affirmative steps to deal with Camden's most pressing problems. As
it stands today, the state is paying 70 percent of Camden's
expenses and says it has spent $2 billion there over the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman administration wants to ratchet up the state's
authority through a chief management officer who would have broad
powers during a period of civic ``rehabilitation.'' The manager
could break contracts, ignore Civil Service rules in hiring and
firing, issue or revoke licenses and direct all appointments and
spending decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is vague on how long the takeover would remain in
effect and what it should accomplish. But this can be clarified in
the Legislature, which should identify the circumstances under
which the takeover would be lifted and power returned to local
officials. This plan, however, should not become a license for
permanently suspending democratically elected leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
