<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's Central Bank Ends Policy of Zero Interest Rates
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan ended its policy of zero interest rates on
Friday, defying government calls for a delay in a rate increase in
what has been the biggest public fight over Japanese economic
policy this century. After 17 months of near-zero rates, the
central bank raised its target for overnight lending to 0.25
percent _ the first rate increase in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. to Buy Chris-Craft for $3.5 Billion
</P>
<P>
   News Corp. has agreed to acquire Chris Craft Industries, the
television station company, for $85 a share or a total of $3.5
billion, a person close to the discussions said Friday night.
Earlier Friday, Viacom pulled out of merger talks with Chris-Craft.
Such a merger would put tremendous control of television stations
into the hands of Rupert Murdoch, chairman of the News Corp.
Chris-Craft, which is controlled by Herbert J. Siegel, owns 10 TV
stations, while News Corp. owns 22.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Climbs Above 11,000 Again
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose as blue-chip companies surged on encouraging
economic data. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 119.04
points, or 1.09 percent, to 11,027.80, crossing the 11,000
threshold for the first time since April. Broader stock indicators
were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was up
11.59 points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,471.84, and the Nasdaq composite
index was up 29.48 points, or 0.8 percent, to 3,789.47, having
recovered from a loss of 60 points earlier in the session.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone Struggles to Keep Up
</P>
<P>
   As confused consumers kept phones ringing off the hooks at
dealers across the country, Firestone struggled to cope with the
demand for replacement tires unleashed by its recall of 6.5 million
tires for sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Reports Suggest No Rate Change
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales rose in July at the fastest pace in five months,
while prices paid to manufacturers, farmers and other producers
were little changed, two reports showed. Sales, led by gains at
auto dealers, department stores and building supply outlets, rose
0.7 percent in July after a revised 0.4 percent June increase, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   Jury Rules Disney Stole an Idea
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney stole ideas for a sports complex from two
businessmen and should pay $240 million in damages, a jury ruled.
Nicholas Stracick, Edward Russell and their company, All Pro Sports
Camps, accused Disney of fraud, theft of trade secrets, breaking an
implied contract and breaching a confidential relationship. The
six-member jury accepted all the claims except fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Barclays Agrees to Buy Woolwich
</P>
<P>
   Barclays, Britain's third-largest bank, agreed to acquire
Woolwich, a British mortgage lender and former building society,
for (PS)5.4 billion, or $8.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut in South African Deal
</P>
<P>
   Wackenhut Corrections signed a 25-year contract, valued at $245
million, to build and operate a 3,024-bed maximum-security
penitentiary in South Africa. The prison, expected to be ready in
about 18 months, is the first such venture in Africa for the
company, which is based in Florida and operates correctional sites
in the United States, Britain, Australia, New Zealand and the
Caribbean.
</P>
</TEXT>
