<HEADLINE>
LAZIO DISPUTES MRS. CLINTON'S CLAIMS ON ROLE IN ADMINISTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's assertion that she played a quiet but
major role in several policy and legislative efforts by the Clinton
administration cannot be trusted and stems from a bid to
``reinvent'' herself for voters, Rep. Rick Lazio said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is this is just another attempt to reinvent Hillary
Clinton and that is why the people of New York have such a problem
with credibility when it comes to the Clinton campaign,'' Lazio,
who is running against Clinton for a U.S. Senate seat from New
York, said in an interview Friday after returning from a
cross-country fund-raising tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``She either was not forthcoming and not sincere when she said
she had nothing to do with these things all these years,'' Lazio
said, ``or she is communicating a very different approach to things
now.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article published Friday in The New York Times, Clinton
said that, contrary to what she and the White House previously had
said, she played an active role in proposing, lobbying and writing
legislation after her failure to overhaul health care in 1994.
Clinton said she cloaked her role and learned to be more subtle in
dealing with legislators on Capitol Hill after her blueprint for a
national universal health care program was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he had voted for several of the bills that Clinton
now says she engineered or pushed. The legislation he supported
included bills to create the Corporation . for National Service, a
domestic version of the Peace Corps, and the Children's Health
Insurance Program, which provides $24 billion over five years to
states to insure children.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio said he was unaware of any role Clinton played in any
legislation. Democrats and some Republicans in Congress supported
Clinton's version of events, but a few Republicans say she is
taking too much credit for legislation they in fact sponsored.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spoke by phone after returning from a 14-city trip this
week, his first such cross-country tour. It included stops in
Cincinnati, Las Vegas; the Los Angeles area; Salt Lake City;
Portland, Ore.; Jackson, Wyo.; and, Friday, Bloomington, Minn.
Aides said he raised more than $1 million at fund-raisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
