<HEADER>
A9385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-CAR-SALES-70     08-11 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAR-SALES-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERAL MOTORS PROPOSES AN ONLINE SITE FOR CAR SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the biggest concession by an automaker that the Internet is
transforming its business, General Motors has proposed a joint
venture with its dealers to establish a Web site offering cars made
by other manufacturers as well as its own.
</P>
<P>
   GM already has an elaborate site, called gmbuypower.com, that
refers potential customers to its dealers. But a vast majority of
online car shoppers have chosen sites offering all makes of cars,
like Autobytel.com and Microsoft's CarPoint. Moreover, an
increasing number of car buyers are using Internet services that
post no-haggle prices, rather than require the customer to
negotiate with a dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The details of GM's new service depend on talks with its
dealers, who have generally recoiled from posting their prices
publicly. But most likely it will let customers order cars at a set
price, much as they can buy books from Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter this week to its dealers, Bill Lovejoy, GM group
vice president for sales, said the company was looking to fight off
the growing influence of the Web startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we _ General Motors and its dealer partners _ use the
Internet to take on those intermediaries whose mission is to come
between us?'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that if GM and its dealers decided to go forward,
they would probably want to buy an existing auto sales site rather
than build a new one. Given the fall in stock market prices, even
the leader, Autobytel, has a market value of $100 million, pocket
change for GM.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors said it would consider an acquisition, but that
it had not made a decision.
</P>
<P>
   GM and its dealers are increasingly worried that the new sites
may wrest customer relationships away from them. That is crucial
because dealers profit more from selling financing, insurance and
service than from the cars themselves. And the Web sites all want
to offer those services, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dealers have a love-hate relationship with the Internet,''
said Chris Denove, a partner at J.D. Power &AMP; Associates, an
automotive marketing and research firm in Detroit. ``They are
getting incremental business in the short run, but they fear that
it will ultimately do to them what it has done to other middlemen
like stock brokers and travel agents.''
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power estimates that more than half of all car buyers use
the Internet to shop for cars _ looking up dealer invoice prices,
for example. This year, it estimates, 4 percent of cars will be
purchased online, up from 2.7 percent last year and 1.1 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the car-shopping sites get fees from dealers for
sending them customers. A few buy cars from the dealers and sell
them at a markup.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said GM's new plan could remedy some of the problems
that have hurt its site in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers prefer to use the sites that sell all makes and
models because they think they can get a better deal,'' Denove
said. But he added that the plan requires an accord between GM and
the dealers giving the manufacturer a role in selling cars,
something that has caused explosive discord in the past. Earlier
this year, GM withdrew a plan to buy up 10 percent of its
dealerships so it could sell cars directly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At least some GM dealers familiar with its plan, however,
praised it for including them in a way that GM's previous efforts
have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the majority of dealers will put their arms around
this because they know the Internet is here to stay,'' said Gene
Meyers, who owns Chevrolet dealerships in Paramus and Hawthorne,
N.J. ``This should be a joint venture. They have the clicks, and we
have the bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller dealers, which are still more reliant on personal
relationships, have been more resistant to the carmakers' Internet
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The company hopes to reach an accord with dealers in the next
few months. And even before that it will start a test in one market
of a key aspect of the proposed new company: an Internet site where
customers can see the entire inventory of GM vehicles for sale in a
region and true selling prices for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move fast,'' said Mark T. Hogan, president of the
company's electronic commerce unit, e-GM. ``The Internet is about
launch and learn.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Several other car makers have run tests to experiment with
posted car prices, but none have offered a plan as elaborate as
GM's. Ford has purchased a partial stake in CarPoint, but that site
is not favoring Fords over other cars. Rather, Ford plans to use
Microsoft technology in a new site.
</P>
<P>
   GM's proposal is complex. For one thing, manufacturers rarely
try to sell competitors' products. But the Internet has made for
some strange bedfellows. American Airlines controls Travelocity, a
site selling tickets for all carriers. And Bertelsmann has agreed
to buy CDNow, a site that sells music of all labels. As GM
envisions it, the new site would not use the GM name and would
offer information on all car models from neutral third-party
sources. Customers who decided to purchase a GM car would find more
detailed information and be able to complete the purchase online.
Those who wanted to buy a Ford, for example, would probably be
referred to the Ford site, or to a participating Ford dealer. (Many
larger GM dealers own franchises to sell other makes, and they
could get referrals from the new site for those cars.)
</P>
<P>
   Another potentially more contentions issue is GM's plan for the
new site to display the dealers' actual prices and inventory, as
some sites already do. Dealers have been concerned about such
systems, hoping to prevent online price wars.
</P>
<P>
   But some dealers familiar with GM's proposal say they are not
likely to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, the Internet hasn't compressed
prices,'' said Jerry Seiner, the owner of 10 GM dealerships in Salt
Lake City. ``We make so little money from new cars, there isn't
much more you can cut.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
