<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MAGGIOLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER MAGGIOLO, 92, FEDERAL LABOR MEDIATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.Y.)   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Andrew Maggiolo, a top trouble-shooter for the Federal
Mediation and Conciliation Service in the 1950s and '60s, died Aug.
7 in Arlington, Va. He was 92 and lived in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   His career as a labor-management negotiator started in 1933
when, as a freshly minted lawyer in private practice, he was asked
to mediate a protracted strike in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distrust, enmities, and failure of the parties to try to
understand each other's problems,'' Maggiolo recalled later,
``persuaded me that this was a challenging field to which I could
and should make a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Over nearly four decades, that contribution helped end
stalemates or avert walkouts in labor disputes that had national
repercussions. He helped settle a nationwide telephone strike in
1957 and a shutdown of the steel industry in 1959. A lasting
contribution was a national master agreement he mediated in 1964
for the trucking industry and the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   His efforts also kept New Yorkers supplied with milk and
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Since mediators have no enforcement power, Maggiolo relied on
persuasion, perseverance and mutual trust. As his reputation grew,
management and labor both came to rely on his counsel.
</P>
<P>
   His Washington executor, Hugh Beins, said Maggiolo, as a Roman
Catholic, was guided by the teachings of the church as they applied
to his field. He attributed his professional success to the
principles set forth in papal encyclicals as far back as Rerum
Novarum of 1891, in which Pope Leo XIII stated that workers had a
moral right to a living wage and to a voice in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Bronx, Walter Maggiolo graduated from Holy Cross
College in 1930 with a degree in philosophy. He received his law
degree at Harvard University in 1933 and went into private practice
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He began his public service as a trial lawyer for the New York
State Labor Relations Board in 1939 and was named a commissioner of
what was then the U.S. Conciliation Service in 1943. After working
in the New England and New York branch offices, he went to the
national headquarters in Washington as general counsel in 1952.
From 1957 until he retired in 1972 he was the agency's director of
mediation.
</P>
<P>
   Maggiolo wrote many articles and a book, ``Techniques of
Mediation in Labor Disputes'' (1973). He lectured at various
colleges and was an adjunct professor of labor law at Georgetown
University Law Center for more than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
