<HEADER>
A9392 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-1185(2     08-11 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-CRASH-1185(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR SUICIDE THEORY IN EGYPTAIR CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reinforcing suspicions that a suicidal co-pilot was
responsible for the crash of EgyptAir Flight 990 last fall, the
United States' top air-safety investigator said Friday that there
were no safety issues in the crash that would require a public
hearing to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, the official, James E. Hall, the
chairman of the National Transportation Safety Board, released
1,700 pages of documents, including FBI reports showing that the
co-pilot had been accused of a variety of sexual improprieties at a
New York hotel during visits there in the year before the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Hall drew no conclusion from the reports and said the board had
not yet analyzed the information it had gathered.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of the crash, which killed 217 people when the
Cairo-bound Boeing 767 went down in the Atlantic Ocean off
Nantucket, Mass., last October, almost immediately became an
international problem for the United States. When some
investigators indicated early in the board's 10-month investigation
that it suspected a co-pilot had deliberately crashed the plane,
Egyptian officials reacted with outrage and demanded a broader
investigation of the airplane's flight-control systems.
</P>
<P>
   They strongly denied suggestions that the co-pilot, Gameel
el-Batouty, grabbed the controls and put the plane into a steep
dive.
</P>
<P>
   That the matter remains sensitive was evident in the fact that
safety-board officials stressed that they still had reached no
final conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly on Friday, Hall said there were ``no unresolved safety
issues'' that would require a formal public hearing, which is
usually held after a major crash. A final report is months away.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall also said, without elaboration, that the board thought
the FBI witness reports were relevant and should be included. The
files show that the co-pilot, Batouty, was the subject of numerous
complaints at the Pennsylvania Hotel in New York, where EgyptAir
crews stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Several women who worked at the hotel told security officers
that Batouty repeatedly propositioned them sexually. In another
incident, two teen-age girls accused Batouty of following them and
exposing himself through a window.
</P>
<P>
   Several people interviewed by the FBI described him as a moody
loner. One said he saw Batouty drunk on several occasions and
thought of him as ``a tragedy waiting to happen.'' One said that
Batouty was ``a religious person who was like a kid in a candy
store when in New York City,'' because he was unaccustomed to
seeing women dressed in relatively revealing clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The files show that EgyptAir was notified of the complaints by
the hotel, and that Batouty consistently denied the accusations,
saying the hotel was harassing him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. experts representing EgyptAir, including a former chairman
of the Safety Board, said the documents contained extensive
evidence that argued against the crash being a murder-suicide.
Other portions of the FBI files back up the assertion of relatives
and friends who have defended Batouty. Several people interviewed
on the West Coast, where he also traveled for EgyptAir, described
him as pleasant and sociable, considerate of others and looking
forward to retirement so he could spend more time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The docket released Friday also included the transcript of the
cockpit voice recorder from the plane, which, as previously
reported, showed that Batouty had repeatedly uttered a religious
phrase in the moments before the crash. The common Arabic phrase
``Tawakalt Ala Allah,'' translated as ``I rely on God,'' could be
heard 11 times in the last minute-and-a-half of the tape.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the board releases only a transcript, not a copy of the
tape itself, but one person who has heard the tape described the
phrase being repeated ``like a mantra'' in an obsessive way.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Adel Fouad, an Egyptian psychiatric
consultant to the Egyptian Civil Aviation Authority, in a letter
submitted to the Safety Board and released Friday with its reports,
said that the phrase reflected an Islamic belief that humans are
supported and controlled by God, and that it ``is used only when
one embarks on a good action and not a bad one.''
</P>
<P>
   The board said in a footnote disclaimer that Fouad's statement
was not developed using board procedures and that his views were
``not necessarily''' those of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating the significance of the phrase to the
investigation, a committee of experts analyzed all of the
utterances for their acoustic qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Language and behavior experts say that people under stress talk
faster. The analysis found that the first utterance was the
longest, 1.02 seconds. But the phrases did not become progressively
more panicked as the plane's fatal dive continued, varying from .73
to .87 second each, which the committee called ``relatively
regular.''
</P>
<P>
   The transcript catches the crew carping about the airline and
about one another.
</P>
<P>
   Batouty seemed to be in a mood to throw his weight around.
Shortly after takeoff, he used his seniority to oust the junior
co-pilot, Adel Anwar, scheduled to be on duty for that part of the
trip. Anwar, 36, expressed surprise that Batouty was not resting in
the rear, a typical routine for a relief co-pilot early in the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you something,'' Batouty said. ``I'm not going to
sleep at all. I might come back and sit for two hours, and then
...'' Anwar indicated that he himself was well rested and happy to
stay in his regular seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean you're not going to get up?'' Batouty said. ``You
will get up ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have told me,'' Anwar protested. ``You should have
told me this, Captain Gameel.''
</P>
<P>
   Anwar later complains to the captain about Batouty: ``He does
whatever he pleases. Some days he doesn't work at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash was in international waters, and the plane, a Boeing
767, was registered in Egypt, which by treaty would put the
Egyptian government in charge of the investigation. But Egypt
delegated the job to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Safety Board will not establish a probable cause of the
crash for months, and after that the Egyptian government will have
60 days to review the report before it is made public. But in
another indication of the board's thinking, the crash has resulted
in just one formal recommendation thus far: that video cameras
should be in the cockpits of commercial airliners, joining the
microphones that have been standard for decades.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear again Friday that the Egyptian side was
uncomfortable with the results of the investigation to date.
</P>
<P>
   An Egyptian investigator, Capt. Mohsen el-Missiry, of the
Ministry of Civil Aviation, said pointedly, ``Additional work
remains to be done, particularly in assessing the design of the
Boeing 767 elevator control system.''
</P>
<P>
   The board's position is that it will listen to arguments from
participants about what should happen next, but that, for now at
least, it believes that it has completed all the necessary
investigative work, leaving it ready to turn to analysis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, at one point an Egyptian reporter asked
Hall why the sexual allegations were relevant to the cause of the
crash, and then began discussing President Clinton's sexual
activities in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Hall replied, ``We are very aware of the important
responsibility that we have to the victims'' to perform a thorough,
fair investigation, and added, ``The statements you refer to are a
very small portion of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was clearly being careful. He responded to the question
about why there would be no public hearing on the crash by reading
from a prepared statement. He said the board's staff had
``recommended that a hearing not be held on this crash because they
believe there are no unresolved safety issues that require such a
forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his assertion Friday that the board had made no
conclusions on the crash squared with his statement on Nov. 15 that
the board was considering turning the case over to the FBI because
it might be a crime, he simply referred the questioner to a
statement posted on the Safety Board's Web site. (The statement, on
Nov. 19, said that after consultation with the FBI and the
Egyptians, the board concluded that more work had to be done.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many staff investigators are persuaded that the crash
was a suicide and are eager to move on to other mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials said Friday that they would let the documents
they had released speak for themselves. But those documents formed
a sort of Rorschach test, with experts hired by the Egyptian side
drawing contradictory conclusions from the material, which, like
much evidence in crash reports, was ambiguous in places.
</P>
<P>
   For example, EgyptAir believes Batouty was never alone in the
cockpit; Safety Board investigators believe he was.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve minutes before the end of the recording, the cockpit tape
captures three syllables.
</P>
<P>
   The five Arabic-speaking people who helped prepare the
transcript agree that it was not an Arabic word; four of them
believe they heard words similar to ``control it.'' One
English-speaking member of the committee thought it might be
``hydraulic.'' Five others say it is unintelligible.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said writing a transcript of a half-hour tape, complete
with analysis of cockpit sounds, usually takes 16 hours, but this
one took 130.
</P>
<P>
   The former Safety Board chairman, Carl Vogt, a lawyer here who
now represents the Egyptians, pointed out that according to data
released Friday, the tail elevators, the devices that change the
plane's pitch, never moved to the maximum extent they are able to,
indicating that the dive was not deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   And, he noted, the flight data recorder captures someone in the
cockpit cutting engine power. ``When the nose of your airplane goes
down, to maintain constant air speed and not accelerate, you always
pull off power,'' said Vogt. ``That to me is compelling evidence
against any intent to do anything but preserve the airplane and fly
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some government investigators, though, say they do not
understand why someone _ presumably Batouty _ turned off both
engines as the plane screamed toward the water, approaching the
speed of sound.
</P>
<P>
   But Vogt made another point that other pilots have also raised,
that diving is not the fastest or surest way to crash a plane.
``You'd turn the thing over, and apply power to make it go
faster,'' he said. ``This flight crew maintained wings level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
