<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS' NEW DEAL IS MOST UNUSUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Roger Clemens will sign an unusual multiyear
contract extension that obligates him to play two years for the New
York Yankees, for $30.9 million, and perhaps allows both sides to
address peripheral issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very excited to lock up one of the greatest pitchers in
baseball history,'' said Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will receive a $5 million signing bonus, to be paid over
the next two years, and a salary of $7.8 million in 2001 and in
2002. There is a third-year option for $10.3 million, with a twist.
Clemens has the right to accept the option and play for the
Yankees. Or he can reject the option and still collect $10.3
million. The Yankees hold a $7.2 million option for a fourth year
that contains no guaranteed money.
</P>
<P>
   In the months that followed the Yankees' acquisition of Clemens
in the spring of 1999, his agents and the Yankees reached an
understanding on a two-year deal worth between $28 million and $30
million, according to several baseball officials. The two sides
negotiated the final terms of the contract in the last three weeks,
and the Yankees announced Clemens' contract as a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   With this structure, the annual average value of Clemens' deal
is $10.3 million, and the Yankees _ always aware of the perception
that they are contributing to baseball's salary escalation _ can
say they are giving Clemens a deal worth much less than the $15
million-a-year deal signed by Kevin Brown with the Los Angeles
Dodgers two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing stopping Clemens from playing two more years,
however, moving to within range of 300 victories _ he currently has
256 _ and then declining to play for the Yankees in 2003, and
earning the $10.3 million anyway. He could then seek a new contract
for 2003, with the Yankees or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   If Clemens were to play for the Yankees in 2003 under his new
contract, he would effectively be playing for no monetary
compensation, because he is guaranteed to make $30.9 million
whether he plays two or three years with the Yankees; he would
merely be playing to ensure his ties to the Yankee franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point it looks like it's the final stop,'' Clemens
said Friday night. ``It's great to know I can stay with a great
team.'' Clemens, who would have been eligible to be a free agent
after this season, said the new contract has a limited no-trade
clause, but said he wasn't sure of the details.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, 38, sometimes labored in his first season with the
Yankees, going 14-10 with a 4.60 earned run average in the regular
season, but finished the year by winning the clinching game of the
World Series. He started slowly again this year, and was placed on
the disabled list June 10 with a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   But since he came back July 2, Clemens has been dominant,
winning all five of his decisions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
