A9398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-11 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   POLAND: WALESA CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   Lech Walesa, who fought Communist rule for two decades before
its fall in 1989, was cleared of collaborating with the
Communist-era secret police and will be allowed to run for the
presidency, which he lost in 1995. He was forced to defend his
reputation in a special screening court, which dismissed
suggestions in old police files that he spied on fellow dissidents.
Walesa, the founder of Solidarity, was scrutinized under a 1998 law
that requires candidates to declare whether they cooperated with
the Communist secret services. There is no penalty for admitting
collaboration, but anyone found to have lied is banned from public
office for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: ANTI-RIGHTIST TASK FORCE
</P>
<P>
   A working group representing the German government and the 16
states gathered for the first meeting to discuss banning the
far-right National Democratic Party. The group, which is expected
to present its conclusions by mid-October, will consider the
judicial aspects of a ban and collect evidence of
anti-constitutional activities by the party. It will also consider
bans of Germany's other right-wing parties.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: ISLAMIC PROPONENT SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   An arrest warrant was issued for Fetullah Gulen, the leader of
an Islamic group that is seen by military leaders as a threat to
Turkey's secular government and by his admirers as a
nation-building tool. The charges have not yet been specified, but
a prosecutor has accused Gulen of plotting to establish an Islamic
government, which could carry the death penalty. Gulen, 61, is in
the United States for medical treatment, but his associates say he
would be willing to return to Turkey to face formal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: WHALE HUNT GOES FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring international criticism, Japan said its whaling ships
have so far caught and killed one sperm whale and four Bryde
whales, which many countries consider endangered species. Japan
plans to catch 50 Bryde whales, 10 sperm whales and 160 minke
whales this season. The United States has threatened to impose
sanctions against Japan, which insists its whale hunts are for
scientific research although the whale meat is sold in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: APPEAL FOR LAWYER
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 villagers have petitioned their provincial
government to free a lawyer jailed for helping them fight high
taxes and brutal officials, the Hong Kong-based Information Center
for Human Rights and Democracy said. The residents of eight poor
villages demanded that the Shaanxi Province high court overturn a
five-year jail sentence handed down to Ma Wenlin last year after he
went to Beijing to file an appeal with the central government.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: WARNING TO JAPAN
</P>
<P>
   China warned Japan that a decision by top officials to visit a
shrine honoring Japan's war dead, including several war criminals,
demonstrates a callous disregard for the victims of Japanese
militarism. Japanese cabinet members have said they will visit
Tokyo's Yasukuni Shrine on the anniversary of the end of World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: HELP FOR AMERASIAN SCHOOL
</P>
<P>
   The government said it will provide about $2 million to a school
for Amerasian children on the island of Okinawa, where U.S.
military bases are located. The cash-strapped school, started five
years ago by parents, provides a nurturing environment for pupils
who are typically the children of Japanese women and American
servicemen and often suffer discrimination in Japanese public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   CONGO: REBEL ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   A rebel leader in northwest Congo said his forces sank two
government gunboats on the Ubangi River, killing 800 soldiers. The
government of President Laurent Kabila denied the assertion by the
rebel leader, Jean-Pierre Bemba. But the government also said it
would halt an offensive against Bemba that began last month. If
Bemba's claims are true, it would mark one of the largest losses of
life in the two-year civil war. A cease-fire was signed last year
among all warring factions, though battles have continued.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: RESTRAINTS ON MISSING EX-MINISTER
</P>
<P>
   A district judge ordered the former minister of tourism to
remain in the country as prosecutors investigate him for charges of
embezzling $45 million in government funds. The order came three
days after prosecutors were unable to locate Oscar Espinosa
Villareal, who is widely believed to have fled. Espinosa resigned
from the Tourism Ministry this week after prosecutors said they
could not press charges against a member of the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: BABY-THEFT ARREST
</P>
<P>
   Santiago Omar Riveros, a retired general, was arrested to
testify on suspicions that he was involved in a conspiracy to seize
the babies of dissidents who gave birth while they were held
prisoner during the 1976-83 military dictatorship and give the
children to the families of military personnel. He was the 10th
senior officer arrested in the last two years in connection with
the plan. Gen. Riveros denied he was involved.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: LINK TO SYRIA
</P>
<P>
   Iraq resumed a rail service to Syria, 19 years after rail
connections between the two countries were cut, the official Iraqi
News Agency said. Relations between Iraq and Syria have improved in
recent months after two decades of tension. Syria backed Iran in
the 1980-88 Iraq-Iran war and was a member of a military coalition
that drove Iraqi forces from Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
