<SLUG> BC-DEM-CLINTON-1075(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GORE BALANCING ACT: EMBRACING CLINTON WHILE STANDING ON HIS
OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE with MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ For months now, Al Gore has been searching
for the proper degree of separation from Bill Clinton. He has used
measured words and occasional policy differences both to try to
distance himself from the president and demonstrate that he is his
own man, worthy of the presidency in his own right.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he has hoped to benefit from his participation
in the administration that has presided over the longest economic
expansion in history.
</P>
<P>
   But in an ultimate irony for Gore, it seems he may have to rely
on that very same president he is distancing himself from in order
to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is planning a multi-stage separation process
over the next few days, although there are still internal debates
over some of the details and how explicitly Clinton should allude
to his personal behavior and impeachment when he addresses the
convention on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   That process may have begun prematurely with Clinton's comments
Thursday, when he said in a lengthy public confessional that voters
should not hold Gore accountable for Clinton's sins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, no fair-minded person would blame him for the mistakes
I've made,'' Clinton said in an interview with a pastor in
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore advisers have been frustrated over the months with
some of Clinton's moves, designed to be ``helpful'' but often
upstaging Gore, they said Friday that Clinton's most recent
comments could help the vice president _ because they expected the
light to shine brightly on Clinton at this point anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known for the last four months that the first few days
of the ramp-up into our convention was in large measure going to be
about Bill Clinton and the last eight years,'' said a top Gore
adviser. ``To do it any other way would be frankly ungracious and
not politically smart.''
</P>
<P>
   But such is the entangled relationship between the president and
vice president _ and such is the admiration for Clinton's political
skills _ that questions were raised about whether the White House
and the Gore campaign had actually planned Clinton's remarks as a
way for Clinton to give Gore some breathing space, even if they
dredged up the unpleasantness that led to the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Both camps said no. Joe Lockhart, the president's spokesman,
said that Clinton arranged the interview with his pastor and did
not clear it with the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore adviser said the same thing. ``I have no idea whether
Clinton's remarks were spontaneous or pre-meditated,'' he said.
``But they were not coordinated.''
</P>
<P>
   But much of the distancing dance that will take place in the
next few days has been. In fact, the two camps have choreographed
an entire ``transition'' process over the next week that may occur
naturally as the country begins to focus on the election, but is
designed nonetheless to help dissipate the Clinton cloud that hangs
over Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has given Clinton the starring prime-time role at the
convention on Monday. Both sides are envisioning not only a
celebration of Clinton's glory years but a clear signal that his
problems are of his own making and should not be used against Gore.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat close to Clinton said that the president used his
confessional interview on Thursday as a kind of rehearsal for the
convention speech. ``He's trying out the show in New Haven before
he gets to Broadway,'' this Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign says Clinton will not be so explicit. In any
case, Gore advisers are focused on other things. ``Clinton has
great job performance ratings and terrible personal ratings,'' one
said. ``The whole trick here is to try to be associated with the
job performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Tuesday, the Gore campaign and White House
officials have arranged for a symbolic ``passing of the torch''
from Clinton to Gore, to take place in Michigan. Their wives are
expected to attend the event as well, in an attempt to cement the
idea that the Clintons are basically getting off the bus now
(although Hillary Clinton is seeking a Senate seat in New York and
Clinton seems chronically unable to yield the stage).
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton Question has been swirling around the Gore candidacy
for months, and Gore has dealt with it in various ways. He began
his campaign in June 1999 with his strongest comments to date about
Clinton's affair, but he seemed genuinely surprised along the
campaign trail to be asked about the president. Finally, though, he
figured out a fairly formulaic answer, which he has more or less
followed for several months.
</P>
<P>
   He told audiences that his relationship with Clinton consisted
of four parts. As he put it in January to New Hampshire Public
Radio: `'First of all, we're friends, and that friendship is
genuine. Secondly, I have been critical of the personal mistake
that the president made, which I've been asked about from time to
time in this campaign. Third, I have fought alongside the president
for this strong economy and for the other improvements that we've
seen during the Clinton/Gore administration. And fourth, I have to
win this race on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   `'Now,'' he continued, `'depending upon the question that's
asked or the perspective of the questioner, they may focus on one
of those four aspects of the relationship and not really hear the
complexity of it with all four, and if they hear only that I'm
running on my own, they may say, `Oh, he's distancing himself.' If
they hear I fought with President Clinton for a strong economy,
they may say, `Oh, he's embracing President Clinton.' Well, all of
those things are true, but it's not true that I'm either distancing
myself from him or that I am trying to run as a derivative
candidate. So it's a complex relationship, just as most human
relationships are.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday, in an interview with Fox News, Gore sounded kind of
ho-hum about Clinton's confessional comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate what the president said,'' Gore said. ``He's said
it before. I think that he also went on to say that this election,
as all elections, is about the future and not the past and I very
much agree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore advisers acknowledge that this is an important week for
the Clinton/Gore relationship. And they acknowledge that Gore's
selection of a running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut,
who was the first Democratic senator to openly chastise Clinton for
his behavior, was part of the larger process of trying to inoculate
himself from Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton, who arrived in Los Angeles Friday for
Gore's nominating convention, is charting his own course in how a
president ought to hand off the baton. He has already broken with
the tradition of past presidents who arrived just as the
conventions for their vice presidents were set to begin.
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Angeles International Airport, a reporter shouted to
Clinton that his vice president was concerned that the president
was overshadowing him. Clinton tilted his head back, laughed and
said: ``I've never heard him say that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is attending several galas in his honor, but aides said
the president would spend much of his time polishing his hand-off
speech. Clinton intends to give a valedictory address that is
shorter than former President Reagan's 53-minute speech in New
Orleans but just as focused on making the case for 12 years of
one-party rule. As is the custom, the White House has shared early
drafts of the speech with Gore. White House officials have told the
Gore campaign there will be no surprises when the president steps
to the podium, but at this point, it is not clear whether Clinton
will reiterate his thoughts from Thursday as he tries to make the
case for Gore's election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, he's given this speech 100 times,'' said an
administration official. ``He'll say this is a big election. He'll
say there are big important differences between the parties and
that the Democrats are the only ones who want you to know what
those differences are.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the White House would coordinate its scheduling
and strategy with the Gore campaign even more than it is currently
doing. But he said the president would continue to have his own
agenda, from forging next year's budget to conducting foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
   One administration official said, ``Conventions have a certain
rhythm and they build to the presidential nominee's speech. I'm
sure the president will get an enthusiastic response on Monday, but
the reality is that by Thursday, Gore's moment will have arrived
and the president's remarks will have been forgotten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CHENEY-1035(2TAKES)-N     08-11 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-1035(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY'S DALLAS COMPANY GIVING HIM $20 MILLION RETIREMENT PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y., Ga.)   (Exclusive)  
 The following article is based on reporting by Lowell Bergman,
Floyd Norris and Diana B. Henriques and was written by
Henriques.   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The energy services company that Dick Cheney served for much of
the last five years as chairman and chief executive has agreed to
give Cheney, the Republican vice-presidential candidate, a
retirement package worth an estimated $20 million, according to
people who have reviewed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The board of the Halliburton Co., which is based in Dallas,
approved the arrangements on July 20, five days before Gov. George
W. Bush announced his selection of Cheney as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The board's vote allowed Cheney to avoid a potentially costly
aspect of his employment contract, which said he would forfeit some
of his compensation if he retired before age 62 without the board's
permission. This provision, known as golden handcuffs, is routinely
included in executives' contracts to give them incentives to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who spent much of his life as a public official and
federal employee, became a wealthy man in his years with
Halliburton. He has been paid at least $12.5 million by Halliburton
since he joined the company in 1995 and has received stock and
options worth nearly $39 million at its current stock price.
</P>
<P>
   By permitting Cheney, 59, to treat his departure as early
retirement, the directors allowed him to keep $10 million worth of
stock and options he would have forfeited had he simply resigned,
the company's public filings show. It was not clear whether the $10
million was part of the retirement package or in addition to it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those briefed on the company's plan said the board was
told the package totaled about $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   While not extraordinarily large by current corporate standards,
Cheney's retirement package solidifies and expands his personal
stake in the oil industry in general, and Halliburton in
particular, while he is on the campaign trail confronting energy
policy issues that will affect Halliburton's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Vande Beek, Cheney's spokesman, said details of the package
were being worked out. Cheney, he said, will remain an employee of
Halliburton until Aug. 16 with the title ``chairman in
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of Halliburton stock is substantially higher than it
was when Cheney took over, but his tenure was not an unqualified
success. The Halliburton board annually sets financial goals for
the company with the understanding that executive bonuses will be
withheld if the targets are not met. The company failed to meet
those targets in both 1998 and 1999, although the board decided to
pay Cheney and other executives bonuses anyway in 1998 because they
had engineered a major merger with Dresser Industries, another oil
services company.
</P>
<P>
   That Cheney bonus came to $1.15 million, nearly as much as his
$1.18 million salary for the year. In 1999, however, the bonus was
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said in interviews that he will sell off his
Halliburton stock if the Republican ticket prevails in the fall. It
is not yet clear how Cheney might handle his stock options, a major
part of his wealth, which, if retained, would give him a stake in
the company's performance for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The options give him the right to buy shares at a set price for
up to 10 years. Some of Cheney's options, however, cannot be
exercised before next January, unless the board waives restrictions
on them. Other options give Cheney the chance to buy Halliburton
stock at more than its current market price of $51 a share,
worthless now but potentially valuable if he can hold them until
the company's stock rises.
</P>
<P>
   A company representative, Wendy Hall, declined to discuss
Cheney's retirement. Hall said the company allowed some executives
to retire with full benefits after age 55 and that details of
Cheney's arrangement would be made public next week.
</P>
<P>
   According to one board member, the package approved for Cheney
was not discounted to reflect either his age or his short tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the contract calls for'' is what was approved for
Cheney, said W.R. Howell, a Halliburton director and former
chairman and chief executive of J.C. Penney Co. ``He's entitled to
full retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell added, ``There was nothing done at the board level of an
exceptional nature for Dick Cheney. The press release indicated
that Dick Cheney is retiring, and that's what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   According to reports filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Cheney is covered by two retirement plans at
Halliburton, a profit-sharing plan and a second plan, intended to
provide a minimum pension if the profit-sharing funds are
inadequate. The company has not disclosed how much Cheney stands to
receive from those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton's financial statements do not describe its early
retirement program, but such arrangements typically involve a
substantial reduction in the pension benefits the employee
receives.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, a number of corporate boards have granted
departing chief executives pension benefits for which they did not
qualify under strict terms of their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney joined the company's board on Aug. 10, 1995, and became
chief executive on Oct. 1, 1995. While details of the retirement
plans affecting Cheney are not clear from the company's public
filings, many such plans require an employee to have at least five
years of service to receive any benefits, a milestone Cheney did
not pass until Aug. 10 at the earliest, assuming his board service
is counted.
</P>
<P>
   Under his leadership, the company has won two important
international contracts, one with Petroleos Brasileiros, or
Petrobras, the Brazilian oil giant, the other a Defense Department
contract for the reconstruction of war-damaged Kosovo. Also on his
watch, to save money, the company laid off thousands of employees
and reduced retirees' medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's decision not to sell his stock until after the election
drew some criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a built-in conflict of interest throughout the
campaign,'' said Chuck Lewis of the Center for Public Integrity in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, rejected that
view. ``America is best served when good people from the private
sector are willing to return to the public sector,'' Fleischer
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many good people like former Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin who have done so. Surely we want to encourage their
return,'' Fleischer added.
</P>
<P>
   The Halliburton board was well within its legal powers in
granting Cheney full retirement benefits earlier than the date
specified in his contract, said John C. Coffee Jr., a securities
law professor at Columbia Law School and an expert on corporate
governance practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of such `golden handcuffs' is to keep an
attractive executive from taking a competitive job in business,''
Coffee said. ``I don't think you need to extend that concept to
keep someone from becoming pope, vice president or chief justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision is certainly a significant one for Cheney's own
financial security, since his tenure at Halliburton came after he
had spent most of his career in government service as a congressman
from Wyoming and as secretary of defense _ without amassing
significant wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he is wealthy. He exercised options on 100,000
shares and sold the stock at the end of May, earning a profit of $3
million. The other options and restricted stock he was given are
worth $35.7 million at current prices.
</P>
<P>
   History offers few examples of how other candidates in Cheney's
circumstances handled the effect of a campaign on their personal
financial interests.
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates on a presidential ticket, even those with
business experience, actually entered the race from state or local
political office, said Judge Leslie H. Southwick, author of the
book ``Presidential Also-Rans and Running Mates, 1788-1980.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far less common for a full-time corporate manager to step
directly from the executive suite onto the campaign trail, where
campaign issues can affect his personal fortune.
</P>
<P>
   There have been exceptions, of course. For example, Wendell
Willkie was president of Commonwealth and Southern, a large utility
holding company, when he made his bid for the presidency in 1940 at
a time when utilities were vehemently opposing New Deal projects
like the Tennessee Valley Authority, Southwick noted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Ross Perot sought the presidency on the Reform Party
ticket while overseeing Perot Systems, a computer systems company.
But the company was not publicly traded then. Jimmy Carter
campaigned for the White House in 1976 while helping run his
family's struggling peanut business in Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
