u f BC-FIRESTONE-TIRE-RECALL     08-11 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRESTONE SCRAMBLES TO MEET DEMAND FOR REPLACEMENT TIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As confused consumers kept phones ringing off the hooks Friday
at dealerships across the country, Bridgestone/Firestone struggled
to cope with the demand for replacement tires unleashed by its
recall of 6.5 million tires for sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it planned to double its production of tires in
the United States and to step up its imports from other plants run
by Bridgestone, its Japanese parent. The domestic increases will
not include a plant in Decatur, Ill., to which Firestone has traced
a disproportionate number of the tire failures that led to the
recall, the second biggest in its 100-year history.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, dealers were still impatiently waiting for Firestone
to give them a definite timetable for when replacement tires will
roll in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers are calling from the time we open until the time we
close, and we don't expect the calls to slow down before next
week,'' said Scott McClain, a sales manager at S&AMP;S Tire, which runs
22 retail stores in Kentucky and also serves as wholesaler to other
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The recall includes all of Firestone's ATX and ATX II tires for
15-inch wheels, as well as Wilderness tires of the same size with a
Department of Transportation 10-digit designation starting with the
letters VD; these latter tires are the ones made at the Decatur
plant. Because most of the reported incidents involve motorists
driving in hot-weather regions _ and because supplies of
replacement tires are short _ the recall is being conducted in
phases, starting in the Sun Belt states.
</P>
<P>
   The recall, a response to reports of 46 deaths in accidents and
hundreds of tire failures, has been extended to Canada and Mexico.
Most tires being recalled were supplied as original equipment on
Ford Explorers, the most popular sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   McClain said he spent two days this week walking through an S&AMP;S
retail outlet, checking tire pressure on customers' Ford Explorers.
Some were as high as 45 pounds per square inch _ an overinflation
level that could itself cause a tire to eventually burst _ and some
as low as 20 PSI. ``No tire is safe if you are running it
underinflated at 100 miles an hour,'' he said. Many dealers said
their customers were expressing wariness about all Firestone tires,
not just those being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Although Firestone is giving California, Arizona and other
hot-weather states first priority for replacement tires, dealers in
other states are unwilling to make their own customers wait. On
Wednesday, when Firestone announced the recall, S&AMP;S had 3,500
Wilderness tires _ not counting any being recalled _ in stock. It
has already used them up, and is almost out of similar tires from
other manufacturers as well. The company has ordered 2,500 more
SUV-compatible tires from Goodyear, Michelin and other Firestone
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Wright Tire, a large independent dealership in Anoka, Minn.,
that derives about 95 percent of its sales from Firestone tires, is
getting more breathing room. The owner, Thomas Wright, said he got
as many as 300 calls a day on Wednesday and Thursday, but that the
volume had tapered off by Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But in his view, customer panic is misplaced. ``Probably 80
percent of the Firestone tires we've sold have gone on SUVs, many
of them on Ford Explorers, and we've never had one reported
problem,'' he said. ``If you keep the tire properly inflated, it
runs just fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
