<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FROM THE PAPER OF FRIDAY, AUGUST 11 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GORE-BIO-HOUSERACE-NYT (moved on Thursday, August 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
10, about Al Gore's earliest political campaign gave a misspelled
name at several points for the newspaper on which he worked before
deciding to seek office. It is The Tennessean, in Nashville, not
Tennesseean.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GORE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, August 9) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
9, about a campaign trip by Al Gore and Joseph Lieberman referred
incorrectly in some copies to the office Gore held in 1989. He was
a senator, not a representative.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BRITAIN-QUEEN-MOTHER-NYT (moved on Friday, August 4) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 4,
about the 100th birthday of Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother
misspelled the surname of a woman from St. Louis who was visiting
London and praised the celebrations. She is Connie Nisinger, not
Missinger.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCHWAB-EDUC-NYT (moved on Monday, August 7) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 7,
about efforts by the financier Charles Schwab to champion the term
``learning difference'' over ``learning disability'' referred
incorrectly to his actions and those of his Schwab Foundation for
Learning. While Schwab has pledged substantial financial support to
an organization that uses the term ``learning difference,'' he is
not spending the equivalent of hundreds of millions of dollars on
such a campaign. His foundation, with an endowment of $280 million,
embraces both terms.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UNION-ADS-NYT (moved on Thursday, August 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
10, about the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees' establishment of an independent group to underwrite
election-related activities misstated the name of the group at one
point in some copies. It is American Family Voices, not American
Family Values.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-BURNHILL-NYT (moved on Tuesday, August 8) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An obituary of Dr. Michael Burnhill sent by the New York Times
News Service on Tuesday, August 8, omitted a survivor. She is his
mother, Lillian Birnberg of Cocoanut Creek, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT (moved on Thursday, August 10) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on, August 10, about
the planned retirement of William C. Steere Jr., chief executive of
Pfizer, misstated the increases in the company's sales and stock
price during his leadership. Sales have doubled since 1992, not
nearly tripled; the shares have increased more than 400 percent in
the last five years, not 500 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2210EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
