<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GERMANY'S IMMIGRATION DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 12:
</P>
<P>
   A bomb apparently targeted at foreigners went off at a
Duesseldorf train station recently, injuring nine immigrants, six
of them Jews, as they returned home from a German-language class. A
few days later, with great fanfare, a 25-year-old Indonesian
software specialist became the first recipient of a new visa
Germany plans to give to foreigners with computer skills. The
juxtaposition underscored one of the main challenges facing German
society and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's government _ the
nation's need to be more welcoming to immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The Duesseldorf bombing, along with a rash of other attacks on
foreigners, has provoked much soul-searching. Foreign Minister
Joschka Fischer of the Green Party urged Germans to speak out
against skinhead and neo-Nazi violence, lest the perpetrators
believe they are acting on behalf of a silent majority.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the moral imperative, an attitudinal change toward
immigration has become a matter of economic necessity. Where
Germany once grudgingly allowed in millions of guest workers,
mostly Turks, to do menial jobs, the nation's high-technology
industries must now rely on skilled foreigners in order to remain
competitive in the world market. The Federation of German Employers
says that the nation lacks as many as 1.5 million skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Schroeder pushed through a reform of citizenship laws
that had enshrined the principle that immigrants in Germany, as
well as their descendants, should forever remain foreigners. Now
the children of guest workers born on German soil may acquire
German citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's Social Democratic Party paid a heavy price for
championing this sensible reform, dampening its enthusiasm to take
further pro-immigration stands. But the political atmosphere is
changing. The growing sense of shame at the rash of attacks on
foreigners coincides with a realization that Germany will become
increasingly reliant on immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   There is a common misperception that Germany is a nation
overcrowded by immigrants. According to a government report, the
net population gain due to immigration last year was 202,000. But
because of the country's low birth rate, even if that number were
maintained every year, Germany would still lose 15 percent of its
population by 2050. Germany's social insurance programs face an
ever-shrinking pool of workers subsidizing retirees' benefits. It
should be clear to all Germans that immigration is vital to the
nation's health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
