<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STATION-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CORP. SAID TO AGREE TO BUY CHRIS-CRAFT TV
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y., Calif., Ore., Minn., Ariz., Fla., Utah, Texas,
Md.)  By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   News Corp., which owns the Fox television network, has agreed to
acquire Chris-Craft Industries, the TV-station company, for $3.5
billion, a person close to the discussions said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chris-Craft, which is controlled by Herbert J. Siegel, 72, owns
10 television stations, while the News Corp., controlled by Rupert
Murdoch, owns 22 stations.
</P>
<P>
   The News Corp. is expected to pay $85 a share, a 21 percent
premium to the price of Chris-Craft stock this week.
</P>
<P>
   Viacom abruptly announced Friday that merger talks with
Chris-Craft had broken down, sending shares of Chris-Craft
plummeting to $62, down $8. Then, after the market closed,
Chris-Craft said it was in talks with another major media company.
</P>
<P>
   The competition to acquire television-station companies has been
intense. Viacom, which owns television stations and is also
part-owner of UPN, has been negotiating on and off for several
years to acquire the Chris-Craft stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked the assets, but only at a price,'' Sumner Redstone,
the chairman of Viacom, said Friday night. ``The price wasn't
right, and we decided to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a merger would put tremendous control of television
stations into Murdoch's hands. For one thing, the News Corp.,
already owns WNYW, Channel 5, in New York. The purchase of
Chris-Craft would bring him WWOR-TV, Channel 9, a UPN affiliate.
That raises the issue of whether Murdoch would shut UPN out of the
New York market. The News Corp. would also own two stations in Los
Angeles, as well as in Phoenix and Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, the Federal Communications Commission did not
permit the ownership of two stations in a single market. The FCC
still limits station groups to ownership of stations that cover no
more than 35 percent of the nation's households.
</P>
<P>
   Under rules adopted in August 1999, the FCC allows dual
ownership in cities where there are a sufficient number of ``media
voices,'' which include all radio and television stations, large
daily newspapers and cable systems. Specifically, a city must have
at least eight independently owned television stations for a single
company to own two. And a company cannot own more than one of the
four top-rated stations in any market.
</P>
<P>
   Should the deal go through, it would also give the News Corp.
control of BHC Communications, of which Chris-Craft owns 80
percent. BHC operates very-high-frequency and ultra-high-frequency
TV stations. It has a market value of $3.18 billion. There are 4.5
million shares outstanding. BHC in turn owns 58 percent of United
Television.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Chris-Craft tried to sell Viacom all its stations and
its half-interest in UPN. But Viacom thought the price was too
high. Viacom walked away from the deal and told Chris-Craft that it
would exercise a clause that allowed it either to buy Chris-Craft's
half-interest in UPN or sell its own half-interest to Chris-Craft.
Chris-Craft was then forced to sell its half-interest to Viacom.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, there was a second round of negotiations on the
stations, and Viacom walked away again, thinking the price too
high.
</P>
<P>
   Chris-Craft owns 10 stations: WWOR in Secaucus, N.J.; KCOP, Los
Angeles; KPTV, Portland, Ore.; KBHK, San Francisco; KMSP,
Minneapolis-St. Paul; KUTP, Phoenix; WRBW, Orlando, Fla.; WUTB,
Baltimore; KTVX, Salt Lake City, and KMOL, San Antonio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
