<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DUSTY BAKER, THE GIANTS AND DIGNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the midst of preparing for the opening game in a
series against the New York Mets _ tickets to get, coaches to
coordinate for a meeting _ Dusty Baker paused Friday at Shea
Stadium to contemplate a question about his second passion, music.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants' 51-year-old manager was asked to
consider a hypothetical scenario: He was exiled to a deserted
island and could only take five compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take Tupac, the double set. I'd take George Clinton; I'd
bring John Lee Hooker; I'd bring Santana, and I'd have to bring
something by George Howard,'' he said. ``Sometimes you need to be
up, sometimes you need to be angry. Sometimes you need to be
mellow, sometimes you need to enjoy. Sometimes you just need to be
entertained.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Baker summed up his strength as a manager and laid
out the reasons he has been able to stay in one place for seven
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Baker became the Giants manager in 1993. Only Minnesota's Tom
Kelly, Atlanta's Bobby Cox and Montreal's Felipe Alou have been at
their current jobs longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple times I knew I was on the hot seat, but
seems like my teams would always win when I was on the hot seat,''
Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   What is the source of his longevity?
</P>
<P>
   Baker cited God, but conceded a variety of extenuating factors.
Baker, who was born in the Southern California city of Riverside,
has settled into the Bay Area. ``I live in the community, and I'm
big in the community, too,'' he said. ``You have more people who
know you personally. That puts pressure on the organization not to
get rid of you quicker, too. If you're not big in the community and
you don't have any community people saying, `Hey don't do this,
don't do that,' people have freer rein to do what they want to do,
and nothing's said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps that San Francisco is a more liberated town,'' Baker
continued. ``The mayor is African-American, you have black civic
leaders, a powerful black clergy that's also big in the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, under Baker, are a hard-nosed team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teams have always played hard,'' he said. ``My teams are
always in the thick of it. Whether we won it or not, we were
usually pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain spirit Baker brings to the game. Players feel
it; most of them like it. Darryl Hamilton played for Baker in 1997
and 1998. ``You knew that he was the guy in charge,'' Hamilton said
of Baker. ``Then again, you didn't. He kind of came to you like
another player. All the guys who played for him respected him
because of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still thinks he can hit,'' Hamilton said. ``He'd always be
talking to the hitters about hitting. I'd be like, `Dusty, come on,
man, you can't hit anymore.' He'd grab a bat and go out and hit.
Most managers aren't like that. They're not as easy to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Baker has an unyielding bottom line that you
cross at your peril. He uses it to distinguish between outer and
inner dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the outer dignity is stuff like our parents had to
learn that we didn't have to do.'' he said. ``You've got a wife,
kids, responsibility. So you take certain things for now, in order
to survive. ``But when it gets too personal, at that point, damn
the job, damn everybody because now you have penetrated my inner
core, my inner dignity, which no man has the right to intrude
upon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are treading perilously close to Baker's inner
dignity. Baker, one of only six managers to be voted Manager of the
Year twice _ in 1993 and '97 _ is a hot commodity. The Giants seem
to be playing loose and easy with Baker. They have a new stadium
and a solid team. Life is good. Maybe the franchise has deluded
itself _ as franchises often do _ into thinking the front office is
the source of the team's success and that it can get just about any
skipper to direct the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is not making his status an issue. That's an offshoot from
something else his father taught him. ``You've got to pick your
battles,'' he said. ``Sometimes you've got to say, `I'll take it
now, but I'm going to get you later.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the best-case scenario, Baker would lead San Francisco to the
World Series, then ride off, perhaps with his music to that
deserted island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm trying not to distract my team,'' Baker said.
``I told the team: `Who knows where anybody's going to be next
year, or tomorrow, for that matter? Tomorrow is not promised to
anybody. Let's go out, work hard, play hard, have a good time and
make this the most memorable year of your career. Let's go out and
make this a miracle year.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
