u s BC-OLY-SWIM-NYT &LR;      08-11 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTROKE FAVORITE QUALIFIES FOR SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Oleg Krayzelburg had one piece of advice for his
son, Lenny, before the U.S. Olympic trials: ``Break world
records.''
</P>
<P>
   They were an immigrant's expectations. Oleg and Yelena
Krayzelburg brought their two children to Los Angeles from the
former Soviet Union in 1989, seeking harbor from anti-Semitism and
from the possibility that their son would be conscripted into a
protracted war when he turned 18. Lenny Krayzelburg had been an
age-group champion in Odessa in what is now Ukraine. A born
backstroker, his coach had told him. For his father, those words
were as indelible as a stamp on a passport.
</P>
<P>
   ``His expectations are pretty high,'' Lenny said with a laugh
late Friday morning, seven hours before he was to swim the final of
the 100-meter backstroke. ``Sometimes he has higher expectations
than what is possible. But I know how to handle it. As long as I
win, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night he did just that. Krayzelburg, 24, did not break
his own world record of 53.60 seconds, but he won the 100
backstroke in 53.84. Neil Walker, who missed the 1996 Olympic team
by a hundredth of a second, qualified Friday night in second place
in 53.85. Krayzelburg also holds the world record in the 200-meter
backstroke of 1 minute 55.87 seconds, and with a leg on the medley
relay, he could establish himself as the dominant American swimmer
of the 2000 Summer Games next month in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to send a message to the Australians that we're
ready to go,'' Krayzelburg said.
</P>
<P>
   In other events, the ebullient Barbara ``B.J.'' Bedford, 27, of
Etna, N.H., won the women's 100-meter backstroke in 1:01.85,
qualifying for her first Olympic team at what are her fourth
trials. Extremely nervous before the race, she vomited and then
placed a call to the Olympic training center in Colorado Springs,
Colo., to speak to a sports psychologist. Elated upon winning, she
hugged everyone within reach on the pool deck. Four years ago,
Bedford had shaved her head for what became a disappointing meet.
Friday night she did not even have to shave time from her career
best of 1:01.11 to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am overwhelmed, excited and effervescent,'' Bedford said.
Previously, she said the monkey on her back had become an
orangutan. ``This is an unbelievable feeling. I don't think I'll be
able to describe it for at least three or four years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 200-meter freestyle, Josh Davis of San Antonio made
an attempt to break the world record of 1:45.51 held by Australia's
teen sensation, Ian Thorpe. Davis could not hold his early pace,
but he still finished first in 1:47.26, breaking a 12-year-old U.S.
record held by Matt Biondi.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Thompson, who won the women's 100-meter butterfly on
Thursday, withdrew from the 200 freestyle Friday as planned to
concentrate on the 100 freestyle. Dara Torres, who finished second
in the 100 butterfly after a seven-year layoff, dropped out of the
200 freestyle semifinals Friday night after suffering uterine
cramping during the preliminary round Friday morning. She is still
scheduled to compete in the 50 and 100 freestyles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dara has a history of severe uterine cramping during long
races such as this one,'' Glen Luepnitz, her nutritionist, said in
a statement. ``The cramping can be debilitating. Any type of
intense activity can bring this about. Her blood pressure drops,
she gets the cold shakes. It can come on during the warm-down. We
just keep her very warm until the cramping subsides.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's 100-backstroke, Krayzelburg consummated a career
that began when his father urged him to enter an army-sponsored
sports club in Odessa at kindergarten age. By age 9, he and 44
other swimmers were together from 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. each day at a
sports school, being taught in the pool and the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   When his family immigrated to West Hollywood, Calif., on March
14, 1989, it seemed that his promising career might evaporate. At
13, Krayzelburg had little facility for English and no facility for
swimming in his neighborhood. ``I want you to keep swimming,'' his
father told him. But where? The school he attended, Fairfax High
School, did not even have a swim team. For a year, he took a
50-minute bus ride each way to train at Santa Monica City College.
</P>
<P>
   The long commute and lack of proper training left him
disheartened. He wanted to quit, but his father would not let him.
``You put in so many years in Russia,'' Oleg Krayzelburg told his
son. Lenny began training closer to home at the Westside Jewish
Community Center in Los Angeles. The pool was only 25 yards in
length, half the size of an Olympic pool. Still, the center was
close to home and offered him a job working as a lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, he enrolled at Santa Monica City College in
1993 and set a national junior college record in the 200-yard
backstroke. Southern Cal then offered a scholarship, and its coach,
Mark Schubert, told Krayzelburg, ``If you are willing to work, you
can be the best backstroker in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I needed to hear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg, who has a finance degree, became an U.S. citizen in
1995, and a year later he finished sixth in the 200-meter
backstroke at the 1996 Olympic trials. He has since become the
world's dominant backstroker. That was particularly evident
Thursday night. Wearing neither a high-tech bodysuit nor even a
swim cap, he cruised through the 100-meter semifinals, coming
within seven hundredths of a second of his record of 53.60.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, in a cap and a hydrodynamic suit that extended to
his knees, Krayzelburg touched the wall in 25.6 seconds after 50
meters, second to Walker, but surged into the lead into the
homestretch. He appeared to be on world-record pace but he seemed
to tire at the end, perhaps under the expectation of a record.
Still, he won. Oleg Krayzelburg, a hospital chef, and Yelena, a
bookkeeper, were in the stands watching. This is why they had come
to the United States, to see their son become a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, I never imagined standing here today,''
Lenny Krayzelburg said. ``This is very special. I've been fortunate
to get some opportunities and to take advantage of them with great
people who were willing to help me be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
