<HEADLINE>
INFLUENTIAL ENTREPRENEURS STRESS L.A.'S IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eli Broad, the co-chairman of L.A. Convention
2000, and other influential entrepreneurs spoke Friday of the
challenges Los Angeles faces in continuing the current economic
expansion to a host of prominent business and entertainment
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge we face is to make K-12 education more
challenging to our students,'' Broad told an audience at an
economic round table held at the county library. ``Our biggest
challenge and vulnerability is education.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was bolstered by Amgen Corp. Chairman Gordon Binder;
Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills; Henry Cisneros; Sky Dayton,
founder of Earthlink; Alfred E. Mann, chairman of MiniMed; and
Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of Los Angeles in the future is going to depend on
education,'' Riordan said. ``Unless this revolution succeeds in our
schools, Los Angeles is not going to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have these great universities, but we have to better
prepare the students moving up,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Broad also outlined a number of downtown projects, including the
Walt Disney Concert Hall under construction, and plans to enhance
sidewalks to make it more pedestrian friendly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vibrant downtown would be a place to bring all our
communities together,'' Broad said. ``All great cities have dynamic
centers.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, also co-founder of Santa Monica-based eCompanies,
highlighted technology as an industry that will continue the
region's economic expansion because of the diversity of people and
industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles is a perfect cross-section of the world,'' Dayton
said. ``When we started Earthlink, we had people coming out of
entertainment and defense. JPL was a source for engineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that could happen anywhere else. Los Angeles is
an amazing crossroads of industry, entertainment, manufacturing and
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, founder and chairman of American CityVista,
spotlighted why the image of Los Angeles to the rest of the country
doesn't match the reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that happen here are high profile: the Lakers
celebration, fires and the Northridge Earthquake,'' he said.
``Despite whatever negative press that comes out of L.A., people
and businesses are still attracted to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad agreed that Los Angeles faces image problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``For as many of the old economy companies that have left,
including Douglass Aircraft and Home Savings, they have been
replaced by many companies that aren't as well known,'' he said.
``That's part of the reason for our image problems.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
