<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRACELET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SISTERS DEVISE LATES FASHION RAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAM PARK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE _ Growing up in Mexico City, Gina Eckstein and Ivette
Helfend started their entrepreneurship early. The sisters, born 11
months apart, persuaded their mother to buy them chocolate, then
promptly sold it - at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Their business acumen has improved. Now they've taken a $2,000
investment and turned it into a business they expect to gross
$200,000 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Linx composable bracelets was born in September 1999, when
Helfend was on a cruise to Italy. There she saw bracelets that
could be assembled from links of stainless steel decorated with
18-karat gold letters, semi-precious stones and various ornaments
and symbols.
</P>
<P>
   She called her sister from Italy and said ``You have to trust
me. You have to go into this with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Helfend said she spent half her vacation arranging to import and
distribute the bracelet components and nearly missed her boat
several times.
</P>
<P>
   The bracelets can be customized to spell the names or initials
of loved ones, carry a message or just be decorative. They can be
``stacked'' or combined for effect, and because they can have any
number of links and are stretchy, they fit any wrist - from very
large to tiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I think this is so successful is that
people can create their own,'' Eckstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they get the instant gratification of having it done on
the spot,'' Helfend said.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities such as Heather Locklear, Jennie Garth and Tracy
Austin are wearing Linx, the sisters said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once one celebrity starts wearing it, it just grows and
grows,'' Eckstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Linx components are sold at retail, mainly by phone order
through their Northridge office, at charity shows and at home
parties. One of the sisters' projects is to create an online order
form for their Web site, linxbracelets.com. For now, the Web site
acts as a showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $30 to $400 for a bracelet.
</P>
<P>
   With five children under the age of 3 between them, Helfend and
Eckstein see Linx as an opportunity for other full-time moms to
make money and socialize at the same time. Some 20 representatives
around the country have come on board.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Bloxberg sells Linx at shows and parties through her home
business, Family Ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was selling `mommy' jewelry, so this tied in perfectly with
my line,'' Bloxberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Moms love anything to do with their children, so they love to
customize bracelets with their children's names or initials, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bloxberg said she is happy with the results of home jewelry
parties, and the bracelets have been a big hit at shows.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Bloxberg had a booth at the national Haddasah Jewish
women's convention, attended by about 3,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did tremendous. I believe we were their No. 1 vendor,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eckstein and Helfend arrange their business around the
children's schedules. The sisters work on Linx after they put their
children to bed - sometimes staying up through the wee hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our only quiet time. I think it's worth it because we
like to be productive in a business sense,'' Eckstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do it on your own time. It's pleasurable, social,
successful,'' Eckstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters have developed a good relationship with their
Italian suppliers, and now they are part of the design team.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have a basketball, because in Italy, they don't play
basketball. Same thing with golf: It's not as hot there,'' Eckstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters also sell premade bracelets, rings and necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   They like to be in business, particularly with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any excuse to be together,'' Helfend said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very lucky,'' they said in unison.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
