<SLUG> BC-CT-LIEBERMAN-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN COMMITS TO PLAN TO STAY IN SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Joseph Lieberman, the U.S. senator who on
Monday became Al Gore's vice presidential running mate, has
confirmed his initial preference to continue his Senate re-election
campaign, his spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stay in the Senate race was made carefully,
after discussions with Gore and other Democratic leaders in
Washington and Connecticut, said Dan Gerstein, Lieberman's press
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Lieberman and our campaign staff canvassed the
Democratic leadership in the state,'' Gerstein said, ``and the
clear message back was that it was not only acceptable but the
appropriate and necessary thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision is significant because it means that a
Gore-Lieberman victory in November would allow the Connecticut
governor, John Rowland, a Republican, to appoint someone from his
own party to fill Lieberman's vacated Senate seat. Such a move
would undermine the Democrats' drive to retake control of the
Senate, where they are now a 54-46 minority.
</P>
<P>
   While virtually all Democratic Party leaders have publicly
voiced support for Lieberman's staying in the Senate campaign,
Scott McLean, a political science professor at Quinnipiac
University in Hamden, said some party members were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to some Democrats who question the decision
insofar that it signals Lieberman isn't fully confident with the
ticket,'' McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, there is still time _ until Oct. 27 _ for
Lieberman to change his mind, drop out of the Senate race and give
another Democrat the opportunity of winning it. Political experts
said any of several other Democrats ready to fill the vacancy would
probably easily beat Lieberman's little-known Republican opponent,
Phil Giordano, the mayor of Waterbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some other Democrats have lamented that if Lieberman leaves,
it would still be easy to win against Phil Giordano,'' McLean said.
``Whoever they went for, they would easily beat Giordano.''
</P>
<P>
   But by committing himself to the Senate, at least for now,
Lieberman, the popular two-term senator, chose the more cautious of
two political paths, and the same one previously taken by two
prominent Texas Democrats. Lyndon B. Johnson, in 1960, and Lloyd
Bentsen, in 1988, also ran simultaneously for vice president and
senator.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman had decided to pull out of the Senate race,
figuring that another Democrat would win it anyway, he would face
the specter of being out of elective office, should he and Gore
lose the presidential election. Staying in the Senate race, where
Lieberman is the overwhelming favorite, virtually guarantees that
this will not happen.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, should Gore win the White House, Lieberman
would have to sacrifice his valuable Senate seat to a Republican
chosen by Rowland. That person would serve until 2002, when the
next statewide elections are held.
</P>
<P>
   Edward L. Marcus, Connecticut's Democratic Party chairman, said
Lieberman's choice was in the best interests of the party. Without
Lieberman on the Senate ballot, Marcus said, state Democrats would
have to hastily nominate another candidate at a convention, instead
of taking the time to hold a primary.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal, Connecticut's popular attorney general, was
widely regarded as the Democrats' leading prospect to replace
Lieberman. But on Friday he called Lieberman's refusal to abandon
his Senate campaign ``absolutely the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Lieberman has been so extraordinarily effective and
distinguished in the Senate that I would hate to lose him if the
Gore ticket is not successful,'' Blumenthal said Friday. ``There is
no other way to guarantee that he would be there if he's not vice
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his own ambitions to work in Washington, Blumenthal
said, ``There will be an opportunity in 2002, if not earlier, to be
a candidate for Senate, and I would be very interested in being a
candidate.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since Monday, when Gore chose Lieberman, the junior senator from
New Haven, to be his running mate, there has been near-constant
debate about whether Lieberman should give up the Senate and put
all his efforts into his vice presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   A public-opinion poll taken of 502 state residents this week by
the University of Connecticut found that 54 percent believed that
Lieberman should not run for both offices, while 37 percent said
they would not mind if he did.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Republicans have begun portraying Lieberman's vow to
stay in the Senate race as proof that Democrats do not believe they
can beat their Republican rival, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a signal nationally that he believes Gore's chances
of winning are not good,'' Robert Ward, the minority leader in the
state House, told The Associated Press. Gerstein of the Lieberman
campaign denied any hedging on Lieberman's part. ``This is in no
way a sign of a lack of confidence in the Gore ticket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland seemed in no hurry to consider the replacement question.
Dean Pagani, Rowland's press secretary, said Friday that the
governor would not contemplate whom he might appoint to replace
Lieberman until after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has said he's not going to spend any time
thinking about that because he's going to be campaigning for
Governor Bush,'' Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Lieberman does stay with his Senate campaign to the very
end, no one expects Giordano to be Rowland's appointee, said
Douglas Schwartz, director of polling at Quinnipiac University and
McLean, the Quinnipiac professor.
</P>
<P>
   With no experience at orchestrating a high-profile political
campaign, Giordano, 37, is regarded by many people in both parties
as unpolished and not particularly ready for prime time. He has
already made several faux pas, including this characterization of
Lieberman, quoted in The New Haven Register: ``I think he's a very
moral man,'' Giordano said. ``I think he's very Christian.''
Lieberman is an Orthodox Jew.
</P>
<P>
   If Rowland is given a chance to appoint a U.S. senator, he may
well choose his lieutenant governor, Jodi Rell, said Schwartz of
Quinnipiac University. ``She's a high-ranking Republican who is
popular and gets along with Democrats,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
