<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAVORITES WINNING BUT WORKING UP A SWEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Lindsay Davenport admits to being in
a funk, Serena Williams said she's winning but not playing well,
and Martina Hingis says she goes through times she can't do
anything right.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a post-Wimbledon funk, the summertime blues or proof
the women's tennis tour is deep, but seeded players aren't having
it easy in the estyle.com Classic.
</P>
<P>
   They're winning, but they have to work for it. This week,
top-seeded Hingis dropped the first set to Chandra Rubin before
recovering. No. 2 Davenport fell apart in a second-set tiebreaker
against Anne-Gaelle Sidot before recovering. No. 5 Williams breezed
against No. 4 Conchita Martinez before falling apart in the second
set. Then she, too, recovered.
</P>
<P>
   So did No. 8 Sandrine Testud against Dominique Van Roost,
although she couldn't overcome Davenport on Friday night. But
Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario lost to Amy Frazier, and the world's
top-ranked doubles team of Lisa Raymond and Rennae Stubbs lost
Friday to Lisa Arendt/Manon Bollegraf.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis said the best way to combat a slump is to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep winning, you think it's going to be good for the
next tournament and the next tournament,'' she said. ``Consistency
is what it's all about.
</P>
<P>
   And many here are showing just enough to stay alive. It could
make for a very interesting U.S. Open in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Arbitration update: Arbitration for Raymond's bid to be
instated onto the Olympic team will happen the week of Aug. 20-26,
the week before the U.S. Open. Raymond's attorney, Greg Becker,
said the details will be finalized Monday. Raymond, the world's
top-ranked doubles player who filed a grievance with the U.S.
Tennis Association after being left off the Olympic team, competes
in New Haven, Conn., that week.
</P>
<P>
   Becker expressed disappointment the hearing won't be sooner but
said, ``Lisa's looking forward to her day in court. She knows she
has been cheated. She's disappointed and frustrated and she's not
going to roll over.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States Olympic Committee also has filed
for arbitration, since it's the USOC's code of conduct that Becker
alleges the USTA didn't follow when it selected the Olympic team.
Becker said the USOC will remain ``extremely neutral.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
