<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STAY HOT AS PIAZZA AND ALFONZO BOTH HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Gardner uncorked a fastball that tailed inside
on Mike Piazza, and immediately, Gardner knew. Everyone knew.
Gardner slammed his hand against his right leg, glanced toward left
field and then looked away. But Piazza's massive drive in the
fourth inning stayed in the air so long that Gardner peeked one
more time, watched the two-run homer land in the picnic area and
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Piazza was nearing second base and Snap's ``I Got
The Power'' was blaring on a soggy night at Shea Stadium. The New
York Mets definitely had the power Friday night, for Edgardo
Alfonzo also pounded a two-run homer to the almost identical spot
two innings later. Those blasts and helped the Mets rumble to a 4-1
victory over the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   So the Mets kept on churning. They have won 14 of their last 17
games, they stay hot on the trail of the first-place Atlanta Braves
and they have padded their lead in the wild-card skirmish. On a
night where Glendon Rusch was more gritty than good, the Mets were
satisfied with his five tedious innings as he allowed only one run
and then let the bullpen finish stifling the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Three relievers nabbed the last 12 outs and helped the Mets
begin avenging a four-game sweep against San Francisco from early
May. The Mets are a different team now, an improved team, and they
have not lost more than three in a row since that sweep. Their
starters have been superb, their bullpen has been stable and Piazza
is playing like a most valuable player, which the fans chanted over
and over Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's been most valuable, most spectacular and most
dependable,'' said Manager Bobby Valentine. ``He's been the most of
a lot of things this year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dusty Baker and Valentine shook hands behind the batting cage
before the game, which was just as curious as when Valentine and
President Fred Wilpon did the same. Baker and Valentine are
managers who do not like each other, and Wilpon is one of the men
who has adamantly refused to give Valentine or General Manager
Steve Phillips contract extensions. But Baker had to watch Piazza
and Alfonzo go deep, which made Valentine smile, and Wilpon must
wonder about his decisions and how they might impact the Mets in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Mets are naturally focused on today. Gardner faced
only nine batters through the first three innings and was
incredibly economical, throwing only three balls. Darryl Hamilton,
who was starting a game in left field for the first time since
Sept. 20, 1993, had a leadoff double in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After Gardner retired Derek Bell and Edgardo Alfonzo, Piazza
strolled to the plate, and there was a buzz at Shea. Piazza had two
homers in 15 lifetime at bats against Gardner and, when Gardner
tried to sneak a 1-0 fastball in on the hands, Piazza quickly
turned on it and hammered it. Piazza is 8-for-20 with two homers
and 12 runs batted in over the last five games. Before Piazza's
31st homer, the Giants loaded the bases against Rusch in the second
and did not score. The third was even stickier for Rusch. After
Russ Davis' one-out single, Rusch pumped a 1-2 fastball by Barry
Bonds on the inside corner for the second out. Bonds felt the pitch
was too inside to be a strike and he mentioned this to plate umpire
Charlie Williams. But Rusch kept firing inside pitches because
Williams had a wide strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   After Rusch walked Jeff Kent, Ellis Burks hit a broken-bat
roller to third. Robin Ventura charged in, scooped up the ball and
tried in vain to tag Davis as he chugged past him.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch was in another bases-loaded bind, but he tossed a 1-2
fastball to Rich Aurilia that sneaked into Williams' expansive
zone. Aurilia was looking to third base for signs when he saw the
animated Williams punching his fist in the air to indicate strike
three.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants finally nicked Rusch for a run in the fifth, but
Rusch retired Aurilia with his 103rd pitch to strand his seventh
and eighth runners. Valentine pinch-hit for Rusch in the bottom of
the fifth, removing him before the Giants could do any serious
damage. Then Alfonzo duplicated Piazza with a two-run shot, Gardner
hopped off the mound in distress a second time and the Mets were
glad to be home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
