<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR, SAME WOES AT KICKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ As week one draws to a close, USC's quest for a
kicker is looking remarkably familiar, despite an all-out attempt
over the summer to find a new candidate to revive its dreadful
kicking game.
</P>
<P>
   Junior David Newbury has emerged with a slight lead over senior
David Bell and freshman John Wall of Birmingham High, which is
ironic because there was some discussion of redshirting Newbury
following his disastrous spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newbury probably has a little leg up,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also said he won't hold Newbury's spring against him,
although it was a major reason the Trojans signed Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wiped that out,'' Hackett said. ``All that matters is if the
ball goes through (the goal post).''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has been for Newbury, who has reverted to a kicking
style he used before he came to USC last year. Former special-teams
coach Shawn Slocum made Newbury change his form last season and
Newbury struggled by making only 11 of 20 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But new special-teams coach Dan Ferrigno has allowed Newbury to
use his old style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I never really got comfortable,'' Newbury said. ``I
never got in a routine. Coach Ferrigno gave me some freedom. Now
I'm in a rhythm and my consistency is better. I knew I was going to
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury said that although he is being pushed by Bell and Wall,
he should be the favorite to be the Trojans' kicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really felt they wanted David (Bell) to start last
year, they just wanted the best man,'' he said. ``And John's going
t great kicker, but he's a little overwhelmed by it all right now.
I know what it was like for me my first year.''
</P>
<P>
   Newbury also vowed that special teams will not be USC's downfall
for a second straight season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can promise that special teams will not be the cause for us
losing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kelly improved: Wide receiver Kareem Kelly (strained knee
ligament) felt much better after therapy Friday afternoon and said
he will practice today and participate in the team scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels real good. Hopefully, when I wake up I'll be 100
percent,'' Kelly said. ``For me, it's big (to play today) because
I've been out for so long. I've got to get out here and have my
mind in a game atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rideaux's ahead: In the battle for right cornerback, Darrell
Rideaux holds a slight edge over junior college transfer Chris
Cash, but the position remains wide open. Both will play.
</P>
<P>
   __ Another mover: Junior Faasea Mailo appears no worse than even
with freshman Jacob Rogers for the starting right tackle spot.
Rogers originally won the position in spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, freshman wide receiver Keary Colbert made a strong
claim to be the No. 3 wide receiver. Sophomore wide receiver Steve
Stevenson remains out with a sore hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   __ Pad stars: Hackett said strong safety Matt Grootegoed,
linebacker Zeke Moreno, offensive guard Zach Wilson and Mailo have
been among the most impressive players since the Trojans started
practicing in pads Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   __ Minor injuries: Strong safety Troy Polamalu suffered what
might be a mild concussion and did not practice Friday. He also
suffered a concussion last season. Linebacker Markus Steele has
been bothered by a sore hamstring but is expected to play in
today's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   __ Two-sport player: Tight end Gregg Guenther (6-foot-8, 245
pounds) of Taft said he also intends to play basketball. Guenther,
who was projected to grow into a tackle, appears so lean and quick
that he will probably spend his career as a tight end.
</P>
</TEXT>
