<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON NOT CHANGING STYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson hears what
most of Los Angeles is saying. He should have bunted in this
scenario, hit-and-run in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson usually turns a deaf ear to such criticism, but he
admits to experiencing a great deal of frustration of late.
Especially in the last two weeks, when the Dodgers went 5-7 against
Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Milwaukee and the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   However, even under the intense scrutiny which suggests
Johnson's job is in jeopardy, the man with 14 years of managerial
experience at the major-league level isn't about to turn into
something he's not. The Dodgers are built as a powerful,
run-producing team, and that's how he'll manage them.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, to reinvent the wheel isn't going to win you
any more games,'' Johnson said. ``You manage the team that you
have. You don't manage every team the same way. In Cincinnati, we
stole every bag we could steal. We were a running team, we played
good defense and we hacked. If it was 3-0, I had them swinging and
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a little more information than the people (those who
are criticizing Johnson) trying to play the game, and a little more
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   And a better winning percentage than any active manager. Johnson
has a .564 winning percentage, has won a World Series, five
division titles and qualified for the playoffs once as a wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's strategy late in games has come under fire, the latest
incident occurring Wednesday when he didn't bunt Todd Hundley with
runners on first and second and none out in the ninth in a tie game
the Dodgers eventually lost. Of course, down by a run in the 10th
inning, they had first and third with none out and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 13 years of managing, I'll tell you this,'' Johnson said.
``With guys that are run-producers, maybe I have bunted once. And
I've won my share of ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite being under contract next season and guaranteed $1.5
million, Johnson's tenure as Dodgers manager is tied almost
exclusively to the final 49 games of the season, a stretch which
began with Friday's game in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers fail to make the playoffs, Johnson's time with
the team is likely over. Though sources said it would be possible
for Johnson to remain if the Dodgers don't make the playoffs,
several sources said it would be an unlikely scenario and would
only occur under extreme circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   During the All-Star break, general manager Kevin Malone was
critical of the way the Dodgers played, stating they needed to do
more of the little things _ bunt, hit-and-run and move runners
over.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers managing general partner and CEO Bob Daly went to San
Diego in early July to tell Johnson the team needed to play with
more fire, and Daly also said he expected more from a team that,
after trade-deadline acquisitions, has a payroll of $98 million.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers began their six-game road trip 59-54, three
games over .500 in the second half of the season and 5 games behind
San Francisco in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating when you don't execute,'' Johnson said.
``It's frustrating from a managerial standpoint. Do I have to
change my whole managerial philosophy, change my approach? Do I
have to change things for guys that are in the league six, seven
years?
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain situations in ballgames, when you have to put the ball
in play, guys are paid to do it. That's why they're making the big
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Daly informed the club he will pay the $71,000
in fines stemming from the May 16 fight at Wrigley Field. Sixteen
players, three coaches and bullpen catcher Travis Barbary were
fined. . . . Right-hander Mike Fetters said the cut on the middle
finger of his pitching hand has healed enough and he's available to
pitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
