<SLUG> BC-RUN-WELTKLASSE-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELIGHTFUL OUTCOMES FOR GREENE AND JONES 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZURICH, Switzerland _ Back on foreign yet familiar ground,
Maurice Greene and Marion Jones continued doing what they have done
for much of the last three seasons: Winning and waving to the
crowd. But the U.S. stars' victories Friday night at the
Weltklasse, the world's most prestigious and lucrative one-day
track-and-field meet, were hardly business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Greene had not raced since straining his hamstring and ruining
his chances for an Olympic sprint double during the 200-meter final
at the U.S. track-and-field trials in Sacramento, Calif., on July
23.
</P>
<P>
   What was supposed to be a race for the ages between Greene and
Michael Johnson, the world record-holder in the 200, became an
anticlimactic dud when both failed to finish the race because of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it was my birthday, it was a very sad night,''
said Greene, who turned 26 on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   But while Johnson has yet to return to competition, Greene made
it clear Friday night that he is now healthy and still the favorite
in the 100 at the Sydney Olympics next month. He handled a fine
field with confidence and controlled power to win in a time of 9.94
seconds that was all the more impressive considering that Greene
was running into a slight head wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm baaaaack,'' sang Greene, who said he felt no pain during
the race. ``I wish I could have run a lot faster than I did.
Unfortunately I wasn't able to, but I believe I ran a very good
race tonight. I feel a little sluggish from being off, but this is
the start of coming off my injury and I plan on getting better each
and every race from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones certainly plans to improve on Friday night's sprint
performance, as well. She has not lost a 100-meter race since 1997,
but she came perilously close here. After false-starting, she got
off to a sluggish start and then had to chase down fellow American
Inger Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a two-time world champion in the 100, would end up
winning by one-hundredth of a second in 10.95 seconds, a time that
was mediocre by her high standards and well off the 10.78 she ran
last week in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the false start, I had to sit in the blocks,'' Jones
said. ``But I'm not going to make excuses. Inger ran a very good
race and today was her chance. It doesn't get much worse than that
for me. Technically, it was very poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Other star sprinters might have headed back to the hotel and
spent the rest of the evening stewing, but Jones, whose ambition is
to win five Olympic gold medals next month, still had another
event. And so she walked off the track and onto the infield and
proceeded to win the long jump, traditionally her weakest event,
over the strongest field yet assembled this season. She won with a
jump of 22 feet 7 inches on her fifth of six attempts.
</P>
<P>
   That was only less than a half-inch farther than Iva Prandzheva
of Bulgaria could fly on this balmy summer evening in Switzerland.
Jones' other victims included Fiona May of Italy, the former
Olympic champion Heike Drechsler of Germany, and the reigning world
champion Niurka Montalvo of Spain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The only major Olympic threat missing from the meet was the
Russian Tatiana Kotova, who won the long jump in the first three
legs of the Golden League against relatively weak fields but was
missing Friday night because of minor injuries that she sustained
in a recent car accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Marion to come out and beat this field is good for her
confidence,'' said Jones' coach, Trevor Graham. ``The things I've
been telling her about the long jump are finally sinking in. We had
some problems with the takeoff, and the speed on the runway is not
there yet like we want it. So we've tried to focus on that, and
when she gets the rhythm down on the runway, I think we're going to
be way over 7 meters, and that's the key to get ready for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicham el-Guerrouj of Morocco certainly looked ready Friday
night. The world's premier men's middle-distance runner recorded
the third-fastest time in history in the 1,500, winning in three
minutes 27.21 seconds. Noah Ngeny of Kenya, considered the only man
with a reasonable chance of beating el-Guerrouj in Sydney, was
second in a Kenyan national record of 3:28.12.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively small margin of victory, el-Guerrouj was
in control of this race down the stretch and now has run all three
of the fastest times in the event, including the world record of
3:26.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriela Szabo, the diminutive Romanian with the daunting kick,
was also back in fine form after a rare loss last week in a
1,500-meter race in London. Her winning time in the women's 3,000,
a non-Olympic distance, was the best of the year: 8:26.35 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia O'Sullivan of Ireland was second in 8:27.58. Regina
Jacobs, who won both the 5,000 and the 1,500 at the Olympic trials,
finished 14th in 8:50.12, which should make it easier for the
American to decide which race to run in Sydney (the 1,500 would now
seem the logical option).
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included the American champion Angelo Taylor in
the men's 400 hurdles, the American record-holder Gail Devers in
the women's 100 hurdles in a meet record of 12.39 seconds and Danny
Ecker of Germany in the men's pole vault with a leap of 19 feet 2
inches. Sergei Bubka, the world record-holder and six-time world
champion who is attempting to make one more run at an Olympic gold
medal at age 36, cleared 18 feet but failed three times at 18-7.
</P>
<P>
   Haile Gebrselassie, the remarkable Ethiopian distance runner,
did not fail in what could have been his final major race at 5,000
meters. But he did not dominate either, barely holding off a late
charge by Kenya's Paul Tergat to win in 12:57.95. Gebrselassie is
unbeaten outdoors since 1996 and is the world record-holder in the
5,000 and 10,000, but he plans to run only the 10,000 in Sydney
before switching to the marathon and half-marathon. Friday night's
race was his last before the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting harder and harder to win, but it's normal for an
older runner,'' Gebrselassie said.
</P>
</TEXT>
