<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Buchanan taps woman as VP pick
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JOHN C. HENRY
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Pat Buchanan won the Reform Party
presidential nomination Friday and named Ezola Foster, a
conservative Los Angeles educator who grew up in Houston, as his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Buchanan, a disaffected Republican, was
assured after he handily defeated John Hagelin in a mail-in
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan received 49,529 votes to Hagelin's 28,539 votes in the
primary balloting, according to Reform Party officials. A little
less than 10 percent of the 887,925 ballots mailed out were
returned. Hagelin won only three states, Colorado, North Carolina
and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   The Buchanan nomination was sealed by his supporters late Friday
in a proclamation from the convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will decide our party's nominee,'' National Chairman Gerry
Moan told delegates at a convention controlled by Buchanan allies.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of the delegates under Buchanan's control, he
easily won the two-thirds vote needed to override whatever the
primary results might have been.
</P>
<P>
   At a theater nearby, hundreds of longtime Perot loyalists
holding their own parallel, or rump, convention, dismissed the
primary results, voted to disqualify Buchanan and nominated Hagelin
to head their Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept with humility and with pride the mantle of H. Ross
Perot,'' Hagelin said as delegates cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The Perot faction was expected sometime today to formally
nominate a running mate for Hagelin, a physics professor at
Maharishi University. He has not announced his choice for running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   With both the Buchanan and the Hagelin-Perot factions claiming
legitimacy, the Federal Election Commission, and possibly federal
courts, will have to decide who will carry the party banner into
the fall elections.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, which would come within two weeks, would center on
which candidate is to receive $12.6 million in federal campaign
funds. The money is being made available under federal rules to the
Reform Party because Perot finished the 1996 race with almost 9
percent of the vote. Political parties whose candidates receive
more than 5 percent of the popular vote are eligible for federal
funding.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Buchanan introduced Foster as his running
mate, saying she is part of his pitch to reunify the sharply
divided party and to appeal to Republicans and Democrats unhappy
with their parties' presidential aspirants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care what party you came from, where you've been and
who you're running away from,'' Buchanan said. ``Come with us.
You're welcome in our party.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a political activist opposed to government aid for
illegal immigrants and sex education, was not as welcoming as
Buchanan. ``Well, of course, if you're too leftist, you many not
want to be with us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Described by Buchanan as a ``lifelong Christian'' and first
black woman on a ``major party ticket,'' Foster is a former
Democrat who turned Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, 62, lost twice in campaigns against Maxine Waters, who
at the time was a Democratic member of the California state
assembly. Waters currently is a member of the U.S. House.
</P>
<P>
   Foster was a supporter of California's Proposition 187, a ballot
measure in 1994 that sought to deny most forms of state aid to
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Maurice, La., Foster moved to Houston when she was 6 and
grew up in Houston's Third Ward. She graduated from Jack Yates High
School and received her undergraduate degree from Texas Southern
University in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Foster moved to California and taught for 33 years in
south-central Los Angeles. Her activist career began after the
Watts riots in 1965, when she began organizing parents and teachers
to keep an eye on how public money was spent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, she was arrested for trespassing, disturbing the peace
and resisting arrest while passing out flyers criticizing GOP
leaders for ``failure to protect family values'' in favor of
pornographers and homosexuals. The charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
