<HEADLINE>
HOTEL KEEPS DOORS OPEN DESPITE YEARS OF VIOLATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Ouellette lives in an illegal room in
Manhattan. His cell-like home of 8 feet by 13 feet has no window
for light and air, as required by New York City statute. Two other
rented rooms in the building are also windowless, and he disputes
the legality of three more.
</P>
<P>
   Missing windows are not the only problem. In fact, Ouellette
contends that the whole building is operating outside the law.
There is no certificate of occupancy, a required city document
authorizing the use of a building. And in June, a city buildings
inspector issued a ``hazardous violation'' citing the property as
an illegal single-room-occupancy hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire building is illegal,'' said Ouellette (pronounced
oh-LET), 38, who sells and services computers. ``I want it 100
percent compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a catch-22. The management says that compliance will
force his eviction.
</P>
<P>
   Among New York's 900,000 buildings, this one is not big, famous
or historically notable. It is far from the worst building on the
city's radar screen. But it shows how a troubled building can slip
through the regulatory cracks for decades. Tenant advocates say
that a bewildering morass of city codes, inspection practices and
enforcement policies too often perpetuate problems rather than
solve them.
</P>
<P>
   The building, at 77 East 125th St., has a convoluted history of
continued operation despite uncorrected violations and the lack of
a certificate. It dates to the 1870s, when it was built as a
three-family house. Decades ago _ no one seems to know exactly when
_ it was converted into a rooming house. Its 17 rooms rent for $125
to $150 a week, including utilities.
</P>
<P>
   For at least 36 years, city officials have known about its
improperly subdivided rooms. Inspectors issued a citation in 1964
and ordered the owner to correct the violation and to obtain a
certificate of occupancy. But apparently the city never enforced
the regulations, and a succession of landlords never complied.
</P>
<P>
   The city did close the building in 1995, but for hazardous
violations other than the illegal rooms without windows. At that
time, inspectors cited defective fire sprinklers, no gas, no water,
no heat and no lights in the halls and stairway.
</P>
<P>
   The building was declared ``dangerous to life and detrimental to
the health and safety of the occupants and others and unfit for
human habitation.'' The city issued a ``full vacate order,''
removed the tenants to temporary lodging and gated the entrance.
The owner was forbidden to reopen without a certificate of
occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring that order, the manager made repairs and the building
resumed operations in 1997, sans certificate. It has continued ever
since, even after inspectors returned to issue still more
citations.
</P>
<P>
   How could such a situation continue? Critics say that the city
issues myriad citations with little or no follow-up to force
compliance and collect fines. Budget cuts have reduced the
inspection staff by a third in the last decade, and tenant
advocates complain that city enforcement lawyers are also
shorthanded.
</P>
<P>
   With limited resources, city lawyers focus on ``comprehensive
cases,'' every year cracking down on a few hundred buildings with
the most flagrant violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it all the time,'' said Peggy Earisman, managing
attorney of the East Side SRO Law Project, a nonprofit group.
``There are violations that are open for years, with 400 violations
on some buildings. Surely if these laws have any meaning, their
purpose is to protect the health and safety of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Allied Building Inspectors Union Local 211,
Joseph M. Corso, said, ``We could have thousands of inspectors, but
if there's no follow-up litigation, it's useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Since reopening, 77 East 125th St. has assumed an upscale name,
the Renaissance Hostel. Advertisements in The Village Voice stress
its location between Madison and Park avenues and its renovated
rooms and international environment. But the ramshackle four-story
structure lacks some features considered common even before the
Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the first thing a visitor notices about the
building is the front-entrance doorknob. There isn't one. The
absence of a knob was duly noted by inspectors and cited as a
violation a year ago, so far to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground floor is a storefront padlocked in a police raid
last November. Until June, bright yellow and orange police posters
in the window proclaimed: ``Closed by court order. Criminal sale
and possession of marijuana.'' Now a new sign heralds a
soon-to-open clothes shop.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the entire building was overrun with illicit
drugs and prostitution, according to the current manager, Andrew
Haurylkiewicz (pronounced harry-KEV-ick).
</P>
<P>
   When he took over, Haurylkiewicz arranged major repairs of the
sprinkler, plumbing and heating systems and reopened the building.
But problems persisted, including the lack of a certificate and
other uncorrected violations. Several thousand dollars in past
fines were ignored. Also unpaid was a $61,000 city lien for the
cost of moving the tenants in 1995 and putting them up in hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by Ouellette, inspectors from the Department of Housing
Preservation and Development returned in recent months. They issued
new citations for the certificate of occupancy, illegal rooms, a
defective sprinkler, rusty fire escapes, loose chimney bricks and
the failure to post an inspection certificate near mailboxes. Not
only was there no posting; there were no mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   The case also drew a fresh Buildings Department review. In June
the department ordered the owner either to restore the original
three-family floor plan or to obtain a permit for a different use
that conforms to code. The windowless rooms would have to be
restored as alcoves to other rooms that have windows. At a hearing
on Aug. 3, the landlord did not show up and was declared in
default.
</P>
<P>
   The result of all this? The building's legal status is in
bureaucratic limbo, with the violations, fines and lien still
pending, yet the building continues to rent rooms by the week.
</P>
<P>
   The owner denies responsibility. ``We're hands off,'' said
Sharock Jacoby of Great Neck, president of Ashan Realty. It leases
the property to Haurylkiewicz's firm, Newkirk Realty, under a
contract obliging Newkirk to correct violations.
</P>
<P>
   Haurylkiewicz said he inherited the problems and was doing his
best to remedy them. But he said he was going broke from the
repairs and lawyers' fees, totaling $30,000 to date. He is also
being squeezed by a rent strike led by Ouellette, with 10 tenants
withholding $1,350 a week and the arrears approaching $30,000,
Haurylkiewicz said. ``I'm running out of money,'' he said. ``I'm
drowning.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because some city documents listed 18 dwellings in the building,
Haurylkiewicz said he had initially assumed they were legal. Now he
agrees that the windowless rooms violate the housing code, and he
vows to fix them. But he said that the renovations planned by his
architect would require Ouellette's removal so his room could be
opened to the adjoining room, which has a window.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the city housing agency said it was issuing an
order that two windowless rooms in the building, including
Ouellette's, be vacated by Monday for lack of ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Ouellette refuses to budge, asserting that since he has been
there longer, his neighbor is the one who should move out. Why does
Ouellette stay in his cramped space? ``My mission is to legalize
the building,'' he said. But Haurylkiewicz said that the real
attraction for Ouellette was living rent-free and avoiding electric
bills for all his computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Management's dispute with Ouellette runs deep. Both sides have
hurled bitter accusations of vandalism, harassment and assault.
There are court orders of protection and a mound of unresolved
litigation over rent, repairs and eviction.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth of the charges and outcome of the cases,
government records detail the building's legal woes. There are
unpaid fines for lack of heat last winter and for failing to post
boiler inspection certificates. Other violations over the years
included exposed electrical wires, a defective fire escape ladder,
broken plaster and water and sewage leaks. The rent roll, required
to be submitted annually, was filed only once before 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such problems, the city's housing and buildings agencies
said that conditions at the Renaissance were far from the worst.
(Both agencies inspect structures but for different rules.)
</P>
<P>
   A recent tour found the interior dingy and run-down. The wooden
stairs were uneven and springy. The apartment doors were unfinished
wood. Each floor had one common bathroom. Some had new tiling, but
there were also cracks in the walls. Water dripped from bulging
ceiling plaster and leaked around a toilet; each sink and vanity
teetered; medicine cabinet doors did not close, and sooty black
mold covered one patch of wall. The communal kitchen had no chair.
Plastic sheets covered much of the roof to keep out rain.
</P>
<P>
   Missing mail is a big complaint. ``Anything important I have
sent to my ex-wife's house,'' said one tenant, Murray Pessin.
Another issue is the lack of intercoms and buzzers. ``I can't hear
the doorbell downstairs,'' Pessin said, ``and even if I could, I
wouldn't know who it was for.''
</P>
<P>
   Another resident, Brett Faison, said he was hit by a chunk of
plaster. ``I told them two weeks prior it was about to fall, and it
did.'' Like Ouellette, he lives in a windowless room. ``It's a
little inhumane,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
