<SLUG> BC-GAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TO INVESTIGATE OVERNIGHT INCREASE OF GAS PRICES IN KC
AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Missouri's attorney
general said Friday he would launch an investigation into the
``suspicious'' overnight increase in gasoline prices in the Kansas
City area.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Area motorists on Friday found that prices at most gasoline
stations had risen by about 15 cents a gallon, to $1.44 at most
stations. Attorney General Jay Nixon said his investigators would
look at whether area retailers colluded in raising prices. No other
area is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen in this market is not normal market
activity,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which will cover the Missouri side of the
Kansas City area, will include the issuing of subpoenas to the
companies that own area stations. The investigation is expected to
take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It comes just days after the governor's task force on gasoline
prices, which was headed by Nixon, released a report finding that
oil producers and refineries profited from increases in gasoline
prices in May and June but that there was no illegal activity.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon, who is running for re-election, said that this week's
sudden and widespread increase by Kansas City area gasoline
stations raised the possibility that they somehow communicated with
one another to raise prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a deep and dire concern about the possibility of
collusion in this market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Area gasoline retailers said Friday that it was too early to
comment about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Debbi Graham, a spokeswoman for QuikTrip, the area's largest
seller of gasoline, said she couldn't comment because the company
was already being sued by the attorney general for allegedly
violating a Missouri law that prevents gasoline from being sold too
cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald J. Leone, executive vice president of the Missouri
Petroleum Marketers and Convenience Stores Association, said his
members had little control of prices at their stations and had not
increased profit margins as prices had increased in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my guys making the 300 percent profit,'' he said,
referring to the higher earnings being reported by major oil
companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said his group told the governor's task force that it could
expect continued volatility in gasoline prices because of supply
and demand.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, wholesale prices have increased more than 10 cents a
gallon over the last two weeks. Energy traders say refinery outages
and higher crude-oil prices are to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Right, a spokesman for AAA Auto Club of Missouri, said
prices promise to be volatile in the near future. They also have
gone up recently in St. Louis and on Friday were at the same level
as Kansas City prices. On Wednesday, some St. Louis stations raised
prices 10 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said St. Louis retailers wouldn't be included in the
investigation because the increase there wasn't as uniform and
widespread as in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one jumped off the meter,'' he said. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
