<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ROBB-KAN &LR;      08-11 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DETAILS EMERGE IN HART LITIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An ``allocation
agreement'' written by lawyers for the family of deceased wrestler
Owen Hart violated rules of professional conduct, say two legal
experts hired by the World Wrestling Federation, a defendant in the
family's wrongful-death lawsuit.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hart, 34, fell more than 70 feet to his death at Kemper Arena
last year when a stunt at a professional wrestling match went awry.
His widow, two children and parents are seeking millions of dollars
in damages from the WWF, the city of Kansas City and other
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The allocation agreement called for Hart's 10 siblings to share
in any damage award due Hart's parents if the siblings cooperated
with the plaintiffs. It also provided that siblings who cooperated
with the defendants would not share in any damage award.
</P>
<P>
   In affidavits filed in the case, one of the WWF's experts called
the allocation agreement an ``effort to suborn perjury.'' The other
said the agreement ``appears to offer an inducement to a witness
that is prohibited by law.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts, former University of Missouri-Kansas City law
professor James Jeans Sr. and University of Missouri-Columbia law
professor James R. Devine, were retained to provide opinions on the
ethics of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Their opinions contrast sharply with that of UMKC law professor
Francis M. Hanna, an expert retained by the family, who termed the
agreement ``ethically proper and acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanna said the document, which he called a ``family settlement
agreement,'' was improperly obtained by the defendants' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, should this document have been in the hands
of opposing counsel as a matter of legal ethics?'' Hanna said in an
interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The allocation agreement is at the core of a dispute between
Gary and Anita Robb, Kansas City lawyers who represent Hart's
widow, children and parents, and attorneys for the WWF and the
other defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs asked Hart's siblings to sign the agreement but
rescinded it after the defendants learned of its existence. The
defendants want to question potential witnesses about the document
to determine whether they were promised a financial stake in the
lawsuit's outcome in return for their favorable testimony.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary writ issued last week by the Missouri Court of
Appeals directed the agreement to be kept under seal and prohibited
the defendants' lawyers from asking witnesses about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that the Court of Appeals has seen all
these competing affidavits and testimony, and has ruled in our
favor on the preliminary rule in prohibition,'' Gary Robb stated
Friday in written responses to questions from /{The Kansas City
Star./}
</P>
<P>
   /{The Star/} obtained a copy of the agreement last month from an
open court file at the Court of Appeals. At the newspaper's
request, the court this week released most of the remainder of the
file, including the legal experts' affidavits.
</P>
<P>
   Under Missouri's wrongful-death statute, Hart's siblings can't
be parties to the case _ and share in any judgment _ as long as
Hart's spouse, children or parents survive him. Because the
siblings may be witnesses in the case, the defendants say the
agreement was an attempt to buy their favorable testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs have insisted the document was akin to a confidential
client retainer agreement and was a legally supportable effort to
secure unity among members of Hart's extended family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is legal and proper in every jurisdiction for elderly
parents to give their children an interest in their estate, as they
see fit,'' Anita Robb stated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs have said their intent was to prevent the WWF from
exploiting divisions in the extended Hart family _ some have ties
to the WWF _ and from reaching a ``quick and cheap settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs also say the WWF's attorneys improperly obtained the
agreement when a sibling with ties to the WWF faxed them a copy.
The Robbs say the WWF's lawyers were legally bound to return the
agreement and violated rules of professional conduct by failing to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs said they rescinded the agreement because they didn't
want it to become a ``red herring.'' Since then, they have battled
to keep the document under seal and to prevent the defendants from
questioning witnesses about it.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavits of Jeans and Devine were filed in late May, just
before trial Judge Douglas Long Jr. ordered the document unsealed
after a May 31 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court writ reversed Long's order, at least until it
heard further arguments on the issue. Additional arguments were
filed by the defendants on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In his affidavit, Jeans called the allocation agreement an
``effort to obstruct justice'' and said it was a ``clear
violation'' of the rule of professional conduct prohibiting a
lawyer from assisting a witness to testify falsely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The misstatements of law, the citation of a non-existent
statute, the invitation to exchange a portion of the verdict for
evidence to enhance that verdict, and the mandate to withhold
evidence under the threat of losing out on a piece of the pie
amounts to a pattern of egregious violations of ethical behavior
demanded of trial advocates,'' Jeans wrote of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Devine, in his affidavit, said the agreement ``gives the
appearance of paying the Hart Brothers and Sisters, who would
otherwise receive no portion of the proceeds under the law, a
benefit for keeping quiet or testifying favorably for the
plaintiffs....It appears to offer an inducement to a witness that
is prohibited by law.''
</P>
<P>
   Devine's and Jeans' affidavits differed sharply from the
affidavit of Hanna, who described the agreement as ethically
acceptable and confidential because it dealt with the
attorney-client relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna on Friday said that the WWF's attorneys were obligated,
once they obtained the document, to consult with opposing counsel
or the court on its disposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should have raised a red flag in any ethically sensitive
lawyer's mind that this agreement was confidential,'' Hanna said.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs, who signed the agreement, asked the Hart siblings to
sign it after accusing the WWF's counsel in Pittsburgh, Jerry
McDevitt, of going behind their backs and trying to persuade Hart's
parents to settle the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Robbs say one of the Hart siblings stole the agreement from
the parents and sent it to McDevitt. After McDevitt sought to
question Hart's mother about the agreement in a deposition, the
Robbs asked Long, the trial judge, to seal it. Long initially did
so but reconsidered after the May hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Because final briefs aren't due for another 60 days, the appeals
court isn't expected to rule for at least two more months.
( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000811.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-11 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      08-11 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAMING THE NET IS TOO EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Whatever caused Kansas City's sales tax
revenue shortfall over its last fiscal year, it's not likely the
e-tailers of the Internet contributed significantly the problem.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although most Internet transactions don't involve a sales tax,
the volume of Web-based retail sales hasn't reached anywhere near
the critical mass needed to drain substantial revenues from local
coffers. Those who track e-commerce closely estimate Internet
retail sales at 1 percent or less of total spending in the
industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   Another interesting retail number was put out a couple of years
ago by an economist for the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development, who noted that 70 percent of all retail sales were
generated by 30 percent of the population. Thus, it could be that
Kansas City isn't doing enough business with those hard-core
consumers who generate most of the retail sales volume.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever state and local government leaders gather these days, a
foremost topic of conversation is the need for legislation to
ensure that e-tailers are required to collect sales taxes just like
the retailers on Main Street, USA. It's not fair, most say, for
Internet merchants to get a free ride and thereby gain an unfair
competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   Without getting into the merits of this argument, what
grass-roots politicians should be probing are ways to finance
government without relying so heavily on sales taxes. The
record-breaking U.S. expansion of the '90s has created enough
prosperity to ameliorate a lot of natural resistance to rising
sales taxes. In the process, it's safe to say, local officials have
gotten spoiled, which is why sales tax increases seem to have
become the revenue enhancer of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Considered in this context, perhaps Kansas City's sales tax
revenue weakness is a matter of the law of diminishing returns
taking effect. Or perhaps it's a matter of Kansas City losing its
luster as a consumer destination. Or perhaps it's a combination of
both.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's metropolitan area is, after all, a highly
competitive consumer arena. Kansas City officials concerned about a
decline in sales tax revenue should compare their figures with
other jurisdictions. Overland Park is, of course, the standard by
which all others must be measured, because it's the acknowledged
shopping mecca.
</P>
<P>
   First, if overall areawide sales tax take is stable to up, that
would be the first sign of problems that can't be explained away by
Internet competition. If some jurisdictions are experiencing
healthy gains while others are stable to down, this would be a sign
of declining competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive decline might occur for many reasons, but the first
thing a jurisdiction with problems should check is how its sales
tax rate compares with similar tariffs of other governments.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the problem, many local governments probably have gone
about as far they can go using sales tax increases as the primary
answer to revenue enhancement needs. At some point consumer
resistance will mount to the point that more means less when it
comes to sales tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   This will be especially so if the Internet continues to be a
mostly tax-free zone. ( 30 )
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-11-00 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
