<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
Aug. 12. If you have any questions, please call Bruce Janssen on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   MARIANDAYS -- A look at the Marian Days event in Carthage, Mo.,
where more than 50,000 Vietnamese Catholics will gather this
weekend to celebrate their faith. The event is even more meaningful
this year, the 25th anniversary of the fall of Saigon and a Jubilee
year in the church. We look at how an entire group of people found
refugee in an unlikely place: the heart of the Protestant Bible
Belt. The story also will touch on how immigration is changing
traditional expressions of faith in the Ozarks. By Oscar Avila.
Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   PEACH -- Cheryl and Marion Wall always dreamed of owning an
orchard. So they left the big city and moved to some land just
beyond Cass County and planted 2,500 peach trees. This year, those
trees are finally bearing fruit, but Marion isn't there to help
with the harvest. He dropped dead April 1 of a heart attack at age
55. Now his 45-year-old wife and their 12-year-old son Curtis and a
13-year-old friend are harvesting all those peaches by themselves,
sweating a lot and learning as they go. They'll do it again when
apple season arrives. By Donald Bradley. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
